<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA JOINS TRADE GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Albania has become the 138th member of the World Trade
Organization, eight years after it applied to join. Mike Moore,
director of the Geneva-based global trade group, said the accession
of the formerly Communist-ruled country means the WTO can ``help
foster greater peace, stability and development in southeastern
Europe.'' Albania was one of the last redoubts of orthodox
Communism until 1992, when it was transformed by elections and
free-market economic changes. But Albania remains one of the
smallest and weakest countries in the region, hurt by years of
isolation and proximity to the armed conflicts in the Balkans. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   PHARMACEUTICALS ACQUISITION
</P>
<P>
   The Dublin-based drugmaker, the Elan Corp. acquired Dura
Pharmaceuticals, Inc. of San Diego, for $1.8 billion in stock,
paying 0.6715 of an Elan ADR for each Dura share. The purchase,
Elan's third acquisition this year, raises its North American sales
force to more than 1,000. Dura's antibiotics and its Spiros brand
of inhaler had sales of $301 million in 1999. The products will
broaden Elan's offerings, which are now focused on painkillers and
treatments for breast cancer and Alzheimer's disease. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   GE DEAL SEEN FOR SCOTTISH LIFE
</P>
<P>
   The financial services arm of the General Electric Co., GE
Capital, is close to announcing a deal worth (PS)1 billion, or
about $1.42 billion, for Scottish Life Assurance, the mutual
pension provider, people close to the situation said. Details of
the deal are likely to be announced late in the week. GE Capital
approached Edinburgh-based Scottish Life after it decided not to
pursue a bid for Scottish Provident, another Edinburgh mutual life
insurer that agreed last week to sell itself to Abbey National for
(PS)1.8 billion. Scottish Life, with assets of (PS)9.7 billion,
would give GE Capital a foothold in the British pension market. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT UP AT TARGET OF CEMENT TAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   A leading building materials manufacturer, Blue Circle PLC of
Britain, reported a 14 percent rise in profits for the first half
of the year, to (PS)125.8 million, or about $179 million, helped by
cost-cutting and a recovery in Asia. But the results were hurt by
the company's extensive spending to thwart a hostile takeover by a
French rival, Lafarge SA Blue Circle's chief executive, Rick
Haythornthwaite, had persuaded investors to reject Lafarge's
takeover offer in May, telling them that Blue Circle, which makes
about half the cement used in Britain, was better off independent. &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL INTERNET OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's largest Internet service provider, UOL Inc., plans an
initial public offering of shares on the Nasdaq by the end of the
year to finance regional expansion. The company, which is
controlled by the Abril and Folha media groups, still has to file
paperwork with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The company
has opened an international headquarters in Argentina, as well as
offices in most major Latin American countries, as part of a plan
to build a presence in the regional market. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE STAKE FOR SALE
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong conglomerate, Hutchison Whampoa, said it would
sell part of its 3.4 percent stake in Vodafone AirTouch, which it
acquired through the sale of Orange PLC to Mannesmann. of Germany
and Vodafone's subsequent takeover of the German telecommunications
conglomerate. Hutchison Whampoa said it would sell a $2.5 billion
three-year bond that would be convertible into Vodafone shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
