<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDER WANTED A FINAL SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 KICKER-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Rookie kicker Tim Seder said Monday that he would have liked to
have ``taken a whack'' at a game-winning field goal from 61 yards
on the Cowboys' final play of a 32-31 loss at Arizona on Sunday
night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If successful, the kick would have been the third-longest field
goal in NFL history behind only New Orleans' Tom Dempsey (1970) and
Denver's Jason Elam (1998), who share the record of 63 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to make a kick like that, everything has to go just
right,'' said Seder, who tried a 58-yarder in preseason that was
short. Earlier in that same Oakland game, he made a 47-yarder that
would have been good from 58 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Seder, who coached football, baseball and basketball at an Ohio
high school the past two years before making the Cowboys' roster,
was thinking like a coach Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But he never questioned coach Dave Campo's decision Sunday
night, saying, ``I don't think it was a bad call by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys faced their final fourth down Sunday night with 14
seconds remaining, no time outs remaining and the ball at the
Arizona 43. Randall Cunningham tried to dump a fourth-and-10 pass
off to Michael Wiley in the right flat, hoping that the rookie
could run to the down marker and scoot out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   This would have given Seder (5-foot-9, 180 pounds) a more
plausible shot at winning the game from 51 yards. He remains
perfect this season from 34, 38 and 44 yards.
</P>
<P>
   NFL kickers are getting stronger. Since 1991, four field goals
of 59 yards or more have been made, including Elam's record-tying
kick two years ago. The others were Buffalo's Steve Christie (59 in
'93) and Atlanta's Morten Andersen (60 in '91 and 59 in '95).
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kicker, you're always prepared to kick a field goal.
That's what a kicker wants to do,'' said Seder, who until nine days
ago hadn't kicked in a regular-season game since 1997 at Division
II Ashland (Ohio) University.  &LR; tagtop:Ray Buck (817) 390-7096
 &LR; tagbottom:rbuck &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
