<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN IS STILL NO. 1 FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
IRVING _ The Cowboys do not have a quarterback controversy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo thought he made that point clear before
backup Randall Cunningham took the field for injured starter Troy
Aikman against the Arizona Cardinals on Sunday. He reiterated that
point in the locker room after Cunningham's brilliant performance
in the Cowboys' 32-31 loss to the Cardinals. Cunningham, who
connected on his first 13 passes en route to completing 24 of 34
passes for 243 yards and three touchdowns, would go back to the
bench when Aikman was ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Trying again not to be misunderstood, Campo echoed those
sentiments at least three times Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it very clear that Troy is our starting
quarterback if he's ready to go,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   The first-year coach, who said he's ``still hurting real bad''
for his first victory, acknowledged staying up at night agonizing
over the Cowboys' poor play, but not about who is going to start at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall played well,'' Campo said. ``I feel comfortable that
we have a guy we can win games with. At the same time, Troy is our
starting quarterback. We have to get him in there as soon as we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   If Aikman, 33, has his way, he will be ready to go Monday when
Dallas (0-2) plays at Washington (1-1).
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was plagued by lingering headaches and nausea last week
after suffering a concussion against the Philadelphia Eagles on
Sept. 3. He was forced to sit out of the Cardinals game by Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But Aikman, who has suffered eight concussions in his NFL career
and one in college, said Monday he's approaching practice this week
like he will play against the Redskins. He said the headaches have
dissipated, and the only thing that would block his return would be
an adverse reaction to the workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go through a week of practice and see how things go,''
Aikman said. ``I plan on playing unless symptoms occur throughout
the week once I start working out.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman experienced recurring headaches after strenuous workouts
on his own last week. He said he will consult with Cowboys doctors
before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Campo and Jones are both on board with Aikman's plan to return.
They maintain that Aikman's health would be the only mitigating
concern with his return, not the spark that the scrambling
Cunningham seemingly brought to a Cowboys offense that was
punchless under Aikman in a 41-14 loss to Eagles a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman didn't complete a pass on five attempts and was sacked
four times before leaving the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will get both of them ready,'' Jones said. ``And we'll be
conferring with the doctors throughout the week. But the decision
will be based on how Troy's responding. Troy's health will be the
biggest consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said he would like to make a decision on his starter by
Thursday. He also said that a good performance by Cunningham
doesn't temper the fact that the Cowboys are still winless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be what the doctors say and what Troy says,''
Campo said. ``Health is the No. 1 issue on him. Obviously, I'm very
happy with what Randall did. But we didn't win the game. Let's not
forget, Troy Aikman won 90 games in the 1990's, the best of any
quarterback in one decade. Troy is our guy. He will go in and do a
great job.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Aikman, his job as a starter is to play when he's
healthy _ without regard to his backup having a hot hand. Aikman
has been the Cowboys' starter since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to get myself ready to play,'' Aikman said. ``When I
feel I can do that, I do that. I don't look at the surrounding
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 37, says his job is to play when Aikman's not
healthy. The former two-time league MVP understood that when he
signed with the Cowboys during the off-season. He has no problems
with his role now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to do whatever is called,'' Cunningham said. ``It's
that simple. I respect the Cowboys and I respect Troy. There is no
room for division on this team. I know what my role is. When they
say go, I go. When they say sit, I sit.''  &LR; subheds:Briefly Middle
linebacker Dat Nguyen suffered a sprained medial collateral
ligament in his left knee and will be out two to four weeks. Barron
Wortham will replace him in the starting lineup. Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones said he is disappointed with the Cowboys' 0-2 start,
but he isn't ready to abandon playoff hopes yet because of
league-wide parity. The Cowboys worked out defensive tackle Ron
Moore and safety Earl Wiley on Monday. Both are considered
practice-squad candidates.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
