A9671 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-DEFENSIVE-L     09-12 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-DEFENSIVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD SHOOTS BACK AS GORE TARGETS HOLLYWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The entertainment industry circled the wagons
Monday, defending itself against government claims that violent
material was being aggressively marketed to children in complete
disregard for its own ratings system.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, music and video gaming industries came under fire
from a 104-page Federal Trade Commission report released Monday
which claims that entertainment companies ``routinely target
children under 17 in their marketing of products their own ratings
systems deem inappropriate . . . due to violent content,'' said FTC
Chairman Robert Pitofsky.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate,
seized on the report to warn he would push for legislation if the
entertainment industry fails to improve on its own self-policing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America defiantly
proclaimed its commitment to artistic freedom while saying it
abides by a ratings system that tells parents what their kids are
buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an industry, we are not in the business of dictating
content to our artists,'' said Hilary Rosen, the RIAA's chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Video gamers congratulated themselves over the report's finding
that they had the most comprehensive regulatory system of the three
industries blasted in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The Interactive Digital Software Association said it recently
established an advertising review counsel to further enforce
anti-targeting guidelines established six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that any such practices exist and violate our
codes, we condemn them and six months ago took steps to prevent
recurrences in the future,'' said association President Doug
Lowenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Most Hollywood studios declined to comment on Monday's report,
saying they had not yet had time to review it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we are marketing our material appropriately, but we
are reviewing our marketing practices to ensure this is the case,''
said Ken Green, spokesman for The Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association of America withheld comment until
Wednesday, when its president, Jack Valenti, is scheduled to
testify at a Senate hearing on media violence.
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled to testify is Democratic vice presidential
candidate Sen. Joseph Liberman, D-Conn, a longtime critic of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning in Illinois, Gore threatened to punish
Hollywood if it did not ``clean up its act'' on marketing violence
to children.
</P>
<P>
   Later, on the ``Oprah'' television talk show, he said families
share a responsibility for what their kids see and hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to be done privately,'' Gore said. ``What
we're calling for in this case is industry self-restraint and
self-regulation. It's about parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called for the FTC study in June 1999, two
months after the school shooting in Littleton, Colo., in which
music and other media influences on the gunmen were called into
question.
</P>
<P>
   While the motion picture, recording and electronic gaming
industries do identify and label content not appropriate for
children, they routinely market those products to kids under 17,
the report concluded, calling these actions ``pervasive and
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC did not propose a regulatory or legislative remedy,
suggesting instead that these industries help increase parents'
understanding of ratings systems and press retailers to restrict
minors from buying inappropriate content.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said the industries should self-police
themselves with new or expanded codes that prohibit these marketing
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions, not censorship, was the appropriate response, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer Steve Allen, a crusader against sex and violence in
movies and on TV said government intervention is still a
possibility if the entertainment industry does not change these
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real danger is if you get the American television viewers
and parents angry enough you're going to get censorship,'' Allen,
78, said from his office in Van Nuys. ``So the offenders would be
well advised to say we've gone a little too far -- maybe we
shouldn't have shows that are this vulgar.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said it's his bet that Hollywood will not heed these
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics were likewise pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Hollywood going to clean up Hollywood? It's never going to
happen,'' said Allen Wildmon, spokesman for the American Family
Association. ``It's like the fox guarding the chicken house.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-regulatory programs of these industries, such as movie
ratings and content warnings on records and games, do little good
if individual companies in turn market the same products to teens,
as the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Recording industry officials said they market artists -- not
violence -- and that parents -- not the government -- have the
responsibility to safeguard their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission's own survey reports that a predominant 77
percent of parents are already aware of the current rating system
for music, and a similarly large majority are 'somewhat' or 'very
satisfied' with the current system of rating music,'' according to
the RIAA's Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
