<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      09-12 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    JUROR WANTS TO NULLIFY HER GUILT(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Patricia Wharton didn't realize she had the power to
set a guilty man free. It's what she wanted to do. It's what she
would have done if she'd known she could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have,'' she says. But, she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had proven its case. The evidence was there.
Still, Wharton and a few other jurors in the Maricopa County case
were convinced that defendant Steven Boyd should not go to prison.
They didn't believe justice was being served.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went back into the jury room, we thought we had no
choice but to follow the letter of the law,'' she says. ``So, we
found him guilty. It wasn't until afterward that we found out we
(beginitalic)did (enditalic)have a choice. Law or no law, we could
have found him not guilty. Now I feel terrible. I want every person
who's going on jury duty to know that they have this option.''
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``jury nullification.'' All it means is that a jury
can vote its conscience, no matter the law or the evidence. They
can do what they decide is right. In Arizona, like most other
states, jurors aren't told about this. If anything, they're
frightened by judges and prosecutors into thinking it's something
they can't do. That they must vote strictly according to guidelines
outlined by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's right,'' Wharton says. ``I believe jurors
should know they have this kind of power.''
</P>
<P>
   She felt strongly enough about it to write to me and forward a
copy to Gov. Jane Hull. In it, she describes how Steven Boyd was
arrested after being caught driving erratically. He said he had
been taking a sleep-enhancing supplement sold at health food stores
and was disoriented by its delayed effects. The supplement was
similar to one that nearly killed Phoenix Suns player Tom Gugliotta
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd claimed to have been an uninformed consumer who had a
seizure, like Gugliotta. Prosecutors believe Boyd knew exactly what
he was doing, however, and that he was an abuser, not a victim.
Either way, Boyd was driving impaired on a suspended license.
That'll get you jail time in Arizona, as Boyd will find out when
he's sentenced later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us on the jury thought that was wrong,'' Wharton says.
``Sometimes, a lawbreaker isn't necessarily a bad person, and
sending him to prison seems like a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's public defender, Gregory Navazo, agrees. He would have
liked to tell the jurors about the nullification option, but that's
not permitted in Arizona courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to dance around it,'' Navazo says. ``You can ask them
if they would think of themselves as criminals in similar
circumstances. You can ask them to do the right thing. But you
can't address nullification specifically.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been attempts to pass a law in Arizona requiring
judges to inform juries about nullification. None made it through
the Legislature, thanks to lobbying from prosecutors like Maricopa
County Attorney Rick Romley. Nullification wouldn't happen often,
no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   In a guest column he wrote once for (beginitalic)The Arizona
Republic(enditalic), however, Romley said instructing juries about
the option would allow objectivity to be replaced by ``sympathy,
prejudice and whim.''
</P>
<P>
   Or worse. At least as far as prosecutors are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   It would actually let jurors use their common sense.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
