<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9687 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     09-12 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EVEN A LUNATIC DESERVES RESPECT  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bobby Knight, now there's a sad story: Great
coach and molder of young men, brought down by a rude teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Why, oh why, has the Youth of Today not learned to be polite and
respectful and hold a civil tongue in its head?
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting that Knight's bosses at the Indiana University
ordered him to behave last May, put him on ``zero tolerance''
notice, and then tolerated at least four instances of
Knight-typical abusive and bullying behavior.
</P>
<P>
   At Indiana, they've raised the bar for zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a floating, flexible zero.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, maybe now Bobby will have time to join a
raging-lunatic support group.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's loss could be San Francisco's gain. Citizen Tom Krebs
suggests that Mayor Willie Brown hire Knight to serve as Muni coach
_ ``Teaching respect and courtesy to drivers and passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   If you take the job, Bobby, pack a lunch. And heat.
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE, give that company credit for not rushing out with a
warning on its faulty tires years ago and throwing the public into
a panic.
</P>
<P>
   Now the word is out, and Firestone tires are no longer selling
like hotcakes, but they are  &UR; riding  &LR; like hotcakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about renaming the company
Firestone-Bridgestone-Gravestone?'' suggests Leon Unruh.
</P>
<P>
   And Cuffs Corbett chimes in, ``Their new ad slogan could be a
slight modification of the old Revolutionary War flag _ ``No tread
on me.'' And they could change the company name to ``Liarstone.''
</P>
<P>
   SOME OF US quibble with terminology.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone refers to the problem as ``tread separation.'' But as
Christopher Lierle says, ``When a vital part splits off
permanently, causing wreckage and lawyers, who but Firestone and
San Jose Mayor Ron Gonzales would call it `separation'? Sounds more
like `tread divorce' to me.''
</P>
<P>
   I like the ``complaint'' part of the news accounts. The stories
refer to ``X number of complaints about Firestone tires, including
Y number of deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   If your wife and kids die in a flaming car wreck caused by
faulty tires, you hate to get shuttled off to the Complaint Dept.,
where you stand in line behind irate people with balky toasters.
</P>
<P>
   HE DIDN'T check to see if the limo had Firestones.
</P>
<P>
   But John Bejarano passed the roadside remains of a limousine
that had been burned to a crisp.
</P>
<P>
   John could still make out the license plate: COOKS 6.
</P>
<P>
   I ASKED for mini-gripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine,'' says Sheppard Levine, ``is columnists whose
familiarity (with the city) is so shallow they don't know the
difference between the streets and the Avenues, fer cryin' out
loud!''
</P>
<P>
   The good Sheppard is referring to a recent item here, a man
complaining of Golden Gate Bridge drivers who pay at the far left
toll booth then quickly cut across all the lanes to exit at 19th
St.
</P>
<P>
   Which would be quite a trick. It's 19th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I'm learning.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE WAY, how city-knowledgeable are the FasTrak people, who
set up the automatic-pay bridge toll system?
</P>
<P>
   Even though a lot of drivers do take that 19th Ave. exit, the
FasTrak lane is the far left. Maybe that's just the way the city
leans.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, you first-exit FasTrakers, on the daring
flying-crossover maneuver. All those other drivers aren't flipping
you off, they're saying, ``You're No. 1!''
</P>
<P>
   TOO HIP an event: A jazz concert /book-signing, tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Only in San Francisco, probably. ``Jazzography'' is the book,
and authors Mars Breslow and Dan Guaraldi will be signing their
volume of profiles of current San Francisco jazz greats.
</P>
<P>
   And some of those very same greats will be signing and jamming _
Larry Vuckovich, Noel Jewkes, Marcus Shelby, Vince Lateano ...
</P>
<P>
   At Whitehall-Jazz, Pier 33 on the Embarcadero.
</P>
<P>
   WE MARVELED, fans and writers alike, at how executive Carmen
Policy worked creative magic under the NFL salary cap to bring top
talent to the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Then Policy left for the Cleveland Browns, and now he has been
fined $500,000 by the NFL for rule-busting salary-cap shenanigans
during his 49ers days.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad Carmen and former 49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo are no
longer buddies. Carmen could have Eddie deliver the half-million to
NFL headquarters, in small bills in a briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   THE KIDS are swinging away, and I ask birthday dad Steve Didion
where he got the traditional U.S. Space Shuttle pinata.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Pinatas.com, &LR; '' he says. ``Seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe those folks already have this covered, but why do kids
get all the fun? How come there are no adult pinatas? Why can't we
swing bats at generic models like IRS auditor, boss or cell-phone
screamer? Or at specific models like Rush Limbaugh, the Prez, Jerry
Springer, even this columnist!
</P>
<P>
   For me, it would beat darts in the eyeballs. Reader Tom Krebs
(mentioned in first item) suggests somewhat kiddingly (I think),
``Get a bigger picture in your column. I'm having trouble with
these mini-darts.''
</P>
<P>
   That solves a mystery. I  &UR; wondered  &LR; who do that voodoo that he
do so well. And why my pimples kept popping themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
