<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LIMIT-NEWS-KAN &LR;      09-12 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMIT-NEWS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL APPEALS COURT OVERTURNS MISSOURI'S LIMITS ON POLITICAL
PARTY CONTRIBUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A federal appeals court handed Missouri's
major political parties a potent weapon Monday when it tossed out
the state's limits on what political parties can contribute to
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The 8th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in a 2-1 ruling, found
that limits on contributions by political parties violated the
parties' First Amendment rights to disseminate their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon immediately promised to
appeal the decision to the U.S. Supreme Court. He said he would
seek an order that would allow the state to enforce the limits
while the case is under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, a Democrat, said the decision showed ``a stunning lack of
understanding of what really happens in campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will allow contributors to circumvent the state's
limits on individual donations by giving hundreds of thousands of
dollars to the political parties, which can now forward the money
to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public understands that big money makes big corruption,''
Nixon said. ``This lets contributions through the back door so the
public cannot tell who is supporting these candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Missouri Republican Party, which brought the lawsuit
challenging the state's limits, called the ruling a victory for
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a powerful precedent that allows political parties to
continue to be a major factor in communicating ideas to the
public,'' said state GOP Chairman John Hancock. ``A party and its
candidates have the same interests in espousing principles and
values.''
</P>
<P>
   The state law adopted in 1994 had limited party committees to
maximum contributions of $11,175 in cash plus an equal amount of
in-kind support, such as shared office expenses or printing of
signs. Those amounts are roughly 10 times the maximum contribution
allowed from an individual, corporation or a political action
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The 8th Circuit in 1998 threw out the limits on individual
contributions. But the U.S. Supreme Court overruled that decision
last January when it ruled that the limits were a reasonable way to
halt the corrupting influence of money on political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, state law allows party committees to make unlimited
contributions to statewide candidates during general election
campaigns or uncontested primaries. During contested primary
campaigns, they are limited to a maximum of $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas also limits contributions to party committees. The
maximum ranges from $5,000 to $25,000, depending on the identity of
the giver and the type of party committee. Missouri allows
unlimited contributions to party committees.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's decision, written by Judge Morris Sheppard Arnold,
the court found that the First Amendment rights of political
parties to contribute money were weightier than the more general
rights of individuals to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold concluded that political parties are often
indistinguishable from their candidates. So limits on the party's
spending are tantamount to limits on a candidate's spending. Such
limits are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by Judge Pasco Bowman, who wrote the 8th Circuit's
1998 opinion that threw out the individual limits.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold wrote that candidates are their parties' standard-bearers
and they often appeal to party principle. Candidates and parties
influence each other so they present a united front until their
identities effectively merge, the opinion said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In large measure, the speech of (a party's) candidates is its
own speech...A principal way in which they express themselves is
through the speech of their candidates,'' Arnold wrote. ``In fact,
parties and their candidates are often virtual alter egos.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Gibson dissented, saying the Supreme Court's
decisions upholding limits on individual contributions should apply
to this case. He noted that a plurality of the Supreme Court in a
1996 case rejected the idea that political parties and their
candidates are identical.
</P>
<P>
   He also derided the majority decision's waffling on the
relationship between candidates and their parties. At one point,
the court noted that the two have ``observable differences'' and
the two do not always correspond to each other. Yet the majority
concluded that they are the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon this shifting foundation, the court constructs its entire
opinion,'' Gibson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said candidates are distinguishable from their parties.
They are the only part of the democratic system that is directly
accountable to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elected officials vote; parties don't,'' he said. ``That is
why the Supreme Court upheld the limits'' on contributions they
could accept.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, however, said parties put candidates in a powerful
context that the public understands. Therefore, parties should not
be limited in their support.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri law allows donors to make unlimited contributions to a
political party, but it limited how much each party committee could
give to candidates. Nixon said the ruling opens a gaping loophole
that will allow people who have made the maximum donation to funnel
additional contributions through the party.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock rejected Nixon's contention. He said the Republican
Party would never pass money from a donor to a candidate just
because a donor requested it. Large contributions to the party, he
said, are not a way to evade individual limits.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that, during several months when the courts had limits
on hold, the Democratic Party contributed more to its candidate for
governor than did the Republican Party. Republican Jim Talent
received at least $700,000 from party committees; Democrat Bob
Holden received $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The 8th Circuit decision also rejected the contention that party
contributions were corrupting. The court said the potential evasion
of individual limits did not justify limits on the parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scheme burdens the free speech rights of political
parties in order to control the activities of someone else,'' the
decision said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon called the decision a dramatic intrusion into the state's
electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law was upheld by the District Court and now, by a
one-judge majority, the court would allow political parties to
circumvent a law in effect since 1994,'' Nixon said. ``When
candidates for the top three races in the state are within one or
two points of each other, this could really matter...The judiciary
could be deciding these races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
