<HEADLINE>
UNION: BILLIONS IN FUNDS DIVERTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News staff writer Kathleen Sweeney contributed to this
story.) &HT;    By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County has diverted $3.4 billion in
surplus from employee retirement savings to pay its share of
retirement benefits, according to a claim filed by employee unions.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, which represent 90,000 employees, said Monday the
surplus should be spent on their benefits and using it violates a
1996 state Attorney General's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   If the county rejects the claim, which was filed last week, the
union intends to sue, said Santa Monica attorney Stephen Silver,
who filed the claim on behalf of the Coalition of County Unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Attorney General's opinion is pretty specific that the
money in question could only be used for the benefit of retirement
plan members, not to relieve the county of any obligation to make
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   County Chief Administrative Officer David Janssen admitted the
county has made employer contributions out of the pension surplus,
but he said the county disagrees with the Attorney General's
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the county entered into an agreement with LACERA that
allowed for excess earnings during a five-year period to be
credited to the county's contribution credit reserve fund to offset
the employer's normal contribution, which is about $250 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
