<SLUG> BC-LAND-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATION CALLS LAWSUIT FILED BY PARTNERS LAST WEEK A `NUISANCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A $120 million lawsuit filed in Jackson County Circuit Court
last week by business partners is a ``nuisance'' that will be
defended vigorously, Station Casinos Inc. says.
</P>
<P>
   Partners that co-own Station Casino Kansas City's 170-acre land
parcel sued the Nevada-based gaming firm late Friday afternoon for
more than $120 million in alleged damages, in part over the
Missouri Gaming Commission's decision last month to strip the firm
of its state casino license.
</P>
<P>
   The partners, all Mississippi or Nevada businesses, also alleged
that Station, as managing partner of their joint land venture,
entered into a ``secret lease'' that subleased part of that land to
a day-care center for employees' children for $1 a year for at
least 20 years. The plaintiffs said they learned of the sublease
only in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nuisance suit,'' a Station spokesman in Las Vegas
said in a prepared statement. ``It is simply an unfortunate case of
our partners attempting to take advantage of the sensationalized
atmosphere in Missouri affecting our company.''
</P>
<P>
   Jess H. Dickinson, a Gulfport, Miss., lawyer for the plaintiffs,
said Monday that the partners were upset that Station acted
unilaterally to sublease land and arranged a pending sale of the
casino without consulting them first.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't treat partners that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group in 1993 assembled the joint venture to buy land for a
casino site, and its members receive income from Station's
estimated $90,000 monthly rent payment.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, the plaintiffs alleged that Station's
controversy with the Gaming Commission, along with the other
allegations, amounted to breach of contract and breach of fiduciary
duty, and they seek to dissolve the partnership. They claim $20
million in actual damages and seek $100 million in punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaming Commission held a two-day inquiry in Kansas City last
month into events surrounding a former Station lawyer's guilty plea
in federal court earlier this year. Michael Lazaroff admitted to
multiple felonies, including misappropriation of law firm funds
that included a questionable $500,000 bonus payment from Station.
</P>
<P>
   When Station executives refused to honor the commission's
subpoenas and testify under oath last week, the commission voted
5-0 to revoke the company's state gaming licenses. The casinos
would remain open during Station's expected appeal of that action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what I heard and saw in Kansas City and based on
information we've gathered in our investigation, there is
substantial concern on our part that Station is going to lose their
(Missouri casino) license,'' Dickinson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the commission's consideration of Station's
proposed sale of its Kansas City and St. Charles casinos to an
insider group of executives is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in the lawsuit are First Holdings Co., and its sole
proprietor, C.D. Tyner; and Lenny Sawyer Consulting Inc., all of
Mississippi; Barrick Properties Inc. of Nevada; and the Kansas City
Stations Joint Venture, which includes Station Casinos Inc. as
general partner.
</P>
</TEXT>
