<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-PREDICT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS TRY TO FORESEE MARRIAGE BREAKDOWNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Think of it as a warning light on the dashboard of
love.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of university researchers announced Monday that they can
scientifically and mathematically predict how likely and how soon a
newly married couple will untie the knot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a snapshot of a marriage early in its life, and you
study that snapshot, and you figure out what are the patterns of
emotional expression and emotional regulation that occur,'' said
Robert Levenson, a psychology professor at the University of
California, Berkeley, who did the study with University of
Washington psychology professor John Gottman.
</P>
<P>
   Like an overheated sports car, couples who run hot, letting
their emotions flare during arguments, are likely to burn out
sooner, probably within the first seven years, the researchers
found in their 14-year study of 79 married couples from
Bloomington, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slow-burning couples -- for them the problems lie dormant
for many years until something comes up to stir the pot, like
having teen-age kids and their problems,'' Levenson said. This type
of marriage often ends during a midlife crisis, the researchers
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``These couples stifle things and do not raise issues with their
partner,'' Gottman said in a prepared statement. ``Their marriages
are a suppression of negative emotions and a lack of positive
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   The two scientists determined which couples were simmering,
boiling or just warm for each other, much the same way some cooks
monitor a roast turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1983, the two researchers, then colleagues at Indiana
University, strapped electrodes and heart monitors and other
devices to the couples and videotaped them arguing with each other.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers tracked the marriages of the 79 to see whether
and how soon they divorced. Gottman and Levenson and then came up
with a formula to predict whether and when couples would divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The complicated mathematical formula includes numbers of
thoughts of divorce, amount of perspiration measured by skin
conductivity levels, humor during the discussion, marriage length,
amount of anger and something called ``facial action units'' -- or
frowns, smiles and grimaces caught on tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be able to develop warning lights that tell us that
something is likely to break'' in a marriage, Levenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some local psychologists and marriage counselors were wary of
reducing human relationships to a math problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relationship. It's one's humanity. It's complex, but
not that kind of complex,'' said Alice Dollinger, an Encino couples
therapist for about 15 years. ``My experience says that the
overwhelming predictor of an unhealthy, unhappy marriage is a lack
of empathy,'' which is best measured by human interaction, not
mechanical monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Johnson, staff psychologist at California State University,
Northridge, and coordinator of the campus Dispute Resolution
Program, praised Gottman's earlier research, saying he uses it in
his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're under stress, it causes chemical changes,'' and
that's something that a researcher can monitor in a laboratory,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Rivera, 25, and his wife, Sandra, 21, said they see more
than chemistry in their two-year marriage and business partnership
running GQ Balloons in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they can predict something like that, because
even if somebody has a bad temper, it depends on whether they want
to work it out,'' said Sandra Rivera, who admitted that she is
``the loud one'' during arguments.
</P>
<P>
   But her husband, whom both acknowledged is ``the quiet one''
during disputes, sees things more simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like my relationship to last, like her parents','' he
said, pointing to his wife, who was holding the couple's
7-month-old son, Anthony IV. ``Their relationship lasted for 25
years.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
