<HEADLINE>
CANCER TREATMENT DRUGS TO BE EXEMPT FOR NOW FROM PAYMENT CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is holding back on plans
to cut Medicare reimbursements for drugs used for outpatient cancer
treatments. However, it will adjust payments on 32 other types of
drugs after an investigation found the government was paying too
much.
</P>
<P>
   Oncologists and many lawmakers, including several from Missouri,
balked when the Health Care Financing Administration announced
three months ago that it wanted to reduce reimbursement for
chemotherapy given at doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors acknowledged that the money they receive for the drugs
often exceeds prices they pay wholesalers, but they said that makes
up for getting too little for the time and expertise needed to
administer the drugs. They lobbied Congress to oppose the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the administrator of the Health Care Financing
Administration said in a letter to Congress that 14 drugs used in
cancer treatments and three used on hemophiliacs would be exempt
from Medicare payment changes set for Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of those 17 drugs will be studied further, and a
proposal will be made to accompany any reduction in reimbursements
with an increase in fees paid for giving those drugs, administrator
Nancy-Ann DeParle said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal would be to have more accurate pricing for both
chemotherapy drugs and chemotherapy administration in place at the
same time,'' DeParle wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican who sponsored a bill
to stall cuts in chemotherapy reimbursements pending a review, said
he welcomed DeParle's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Clinical Oncologists said in a statement
Monday it also was relieved by the announcement and intends to work
with the administration to update the fee schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said cutting reimbursement for cancer drugs would mean
they could no longer afford to administer them in their offices and
that patients would have to go to hospitals for treatment. About 90
percent of chemotherapy is done on an outpatient basis.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to cut payments stemmed from a study showing huge
markups in prices doctors billed Medicare for cancer drugs. They
made profits ranging from 11 percent to 900 percent, said Donna
Shalala, secretary of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said adjusting payments on 49 drugs eligible for
Medicare reimbursement, including the cancer drugs, would save
taxpayers $2.9 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 17 drugs for cancer and hemophilia patients will
not be reduced as planned, savings will still be significant by
adjusting payments on 32 other drugs, DeParle said. Those changes
constitute about 70 percent of the projected savings, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
