<HEADER>
A9700 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-SCHOLARSHIP-PROGRAM-S     09-12 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOLARSHIP-PROGRAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CAL GRANT GETS $1.2 BILLION EXPANSION  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   California's leaders took a bold step Monday, promising to pay
tuition at the state's public colleges and universities _ or nearly
$10,000 toward a private education _ for every low- and
middle-income student with good grades.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Los Angeles Monday, Governor Gray Davis
signed into law a massive expansion of the Cal Grant program,
committing at least $1.2 billion annually for every eligible
student starting in the 2001-2002 academic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is telling students that if you work hard and do
your part by studying hard, then we as leaders will do our part to
help you pay for it,'' said Davis spokeswoman Hilary McLean.
</P>
<P>
   The action comes at a time when the governor and legislators
armed with a bounty from the budget surplus are focusing on
improving education. But the Cal Grant plan makes financial need a
key requirement in awards, unlike other programs touted by Davis
and being adopted around the nation. Those largely benefit middle
class families, rely on grades and offer tax breaks and benefits
based on performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Davis has made improving education and expanding
access to quality education the number one priority of his
administration,'' McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1960 master plan, California promised the top 12.5
percent of graduating high school seniors seats in the University
of California system, while the top third would be guaranteed a
space in the California State University system.
</P>
<P>
   But the law signed into law Monday is the first time the state
has come up with the money to make college a reality for eligible
students who previously could not afford it.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the state set aside an established sum for the
grants, handing out awards to applicants according to a ranking of
need and grades. When the money ran out, eligible students were
left out.
</P>
<P>
   UC Berkeley freshman Charlene De Leon, 18, said the new
guarantee of money for college is vital for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry wasn't that I need to go to this particular college
or that college. I had to worry about how I was going to pay for
it,'' she said. ``Just getting in wouldn't be enough. I would not
be able to go to college without financial aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, which legislators called the most
significant increase in access to higher education since the GI
Bill, any student meeting the eligibility requirements will get a
grant.
</P>
<P>
   The new program is expected to reach 30 percent of the students
attending California high schools. When Davis took office last
year, there was enough Cal Grant money to reach only 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Students fitting income and asset requirements who earn at least
a 3.0 grade point average, or a ``B,'' will be eligible for grants
that cover tuition at the state's public institutions _ up to a
maximum of $1,428 for CSU and $3,249 for UC _ and about $9,700
toward a private university such as Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Eligible students earning a 2.0 average, or a ``C,'' will get a
grant of up to $1,551, which they can use to pay for textbooks and
other incidental costs at community colleges. Part-time students
enrolled at least half-time _ six credit units a semester _ will
also qualify for grants. Students have within a year of high school
graduation to apply, although Davis agreed to award 22,500 new Cal
Grant awards to adult students who have returned to or are newly
entering college. Cal Grants will also be extended to students who
complete community college within five years of high school
graduation and whose academic record allows them to transfer to
four-year universities.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are available to students whose families have no more
than $45,400 in assets. The annual income ceiling for eligibility
varies, from $23,500 for students who are independent to $74,100
for students from families of six or more. As family size drops, so
does the income ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco State University math professor Daniel Fendel said
the infusion of financial aid would allow students to worry less
about money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of students who have families and are working
long hours. Anything that will help them out is welcome. It really
is needed,'' he said. ``If they can cut down on their work hours a
bit and have more time for their classes it will make them better
students.''
</P>
<P>
   CSU spokesman Ken Swisher said Monday that the system's
Chancellor Charles Reed heralded the aid program as ``historic''
and a renewal of the California dream.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher said it will open the doors of higher education for many
more people, especially those who are first generation college
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many students who shrug their shoulders and say
it doesn't matter what I do in school, I won't be able to afford
college,'' Swisher said. ``It lets students know that if they want
to work hard, they can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis called the bill he signed Monday ``landmark,''
the Democratic governor initially opposed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   He backed a $71 million increase in money for the Cal Grant
program in his budget proposal _ which did not include the
educational guarantee _ far less than lawmakers had proposed. To
win Davis' support, the bill's champion, Senate President Pro Tem
John Burton, D-San Francisco, linked the Cal Grant to another
Davis-backed bill giving $1,000 merit scholarships to students who
score in the top 10 percent of their school on aptitude tests or in
the top 5 percent statewide.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis had vetoed one of the bills, the other would have died
with it. Burton also told Davis that because of unanimous GOP
support, the governor might risk an override if he vetoed the plan.
Burton and Davis negotiated during the summer and finally reached
an agreement in August that narrowed the scope and cost of the
program, while maintaining the guarantee of an education to needy
students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
