<HEADLINE>
VALDES' STOCK PLUMMETING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sometimes a player shuns a long-term deal because a
bigger contract awaits. Ismael Valdes took that gamble and, in
Vegas terminology, crapped out.
</P>
<P>
   He was once a highly sought-after commodity who turned down a
lucrative contract with the Los Angeles Dodgers. Now Valdes,
despite being 27, has seen his career teeter to where industry
officials believe he'll be fortunate to get anything more than a
one-year, incentive-laden contract next season as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   It's based on performance and reputation. Neither have been
strong, but the latter took another brutal hit Monday when he was
scratched hours before his scheduled start against the Arizona
Diamondbacks. The numbness he experienced in his right pinkie
finger has left Valdes' status as day to day, but with a contingent
of young pitchers now in the fold, it's uncertain when his next
start will be.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Eric Gagne, who got into town about 4 p.m. after
being recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque, started in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who is 0-3 with a 6.08 ERA with the Dodgers and 2-7 with
a 5.64 ERA overall, was examined by Arizona team physician Dr.
David Zeman. Dodgers trainer Stan Johnston said the numbness could
be an after-effect of Valdes being hit with a line drive last
Wednesday against Pittsburgh, but Valdes added he had no problems
throwing a bullpen session in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be pressure on the sensory nerve,'' Johnston said.
``Everything else is fine. Blood supply and other things you worry
about are fine. Right now it's being treated as a neuro problem.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's another problem for Valdes, whose stock in the
free-agent market has plummeted this season. Even though Valdes was
9-14 last year, his stock was high because of a 3.98 ERA. But
questions of his mental toughness were always an issue and Chicago
Cubs manager Don Baylor questioned it soon after the winter trade
had sent Valdes to the Cubs. Since then, Valdes has had trouble
with his shoulder, hamstring and blisters.
</P>
<P>
   In a nightmare season, Valdes also has a six-game suspension
pending. An appeal hearing date has not yet been set, but the
office of the commissioner is looking at either Friday or early
next week. Either way, it's going to be in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' Valdes said. ``I don't know what to tell
you. I'm telling you, I've never experienced that before. It's
crazy. It's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More callups: In addition to right-hander Eric Gagne, the
Dodgers also recalled left-hander Jeff Williams and infielder Hiram
Bocachica. The moves were made because Triple-A Albuquerque was
eliminated from the Pacific Coast League playoffs Sunday night in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will add three more players to the roster. Catcher
Angel Pena, once thought of as the future catcher of the Dodgers,
and right-handers Mike Judd and Al Reyes are expected to join the
club Thursday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Pena's addition is perplexing, especially since a sprained left
thumb kept him from catching lately. The Dodgers soured terribly on
Pena, 25, in the last two seasons to the extent they tried to trade
him throughout the season. The Dodgers also plan to offer Pena to
beef up trades during the offseason, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Outfielder Bruce Aven (strained oblique) could
return to action Thursday. . . . Tom Goodwin extended his hitting
streak to a season-high 12 games, two shy of tying his career best,
with a homer in the fifth inning.!dlim!!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
