<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GREER-TEX </SLUG>
 
BAD SEASON LEAVES GREER FOCUSED ON FUTURE (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
The hardest season of Rusty Greer's career is coming to a slow,
agonizing end. It has been a season of injuries, uncertainty about
his next contract and mounting losses for his team.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has tried to remain upbeat, but it has been difficult. Like
Rafael Palmeiro and other members of past division-winning teams,
he is used to winning, being in pennant races this time of the year
and looking forward to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been frustrating and hard and disappointing,'' Greer
said. ``There again, though, you learn about yourself and learn how
to deal with things and be better for it. It's easy to ride the
ship when it's smooth water. But when it gets rough, that's when
you really see what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, like just about everybody employed by the Rangers,
eagerly looks forward to the off-season to see what will happen,
both with the team and with
</P>
<P>
   his contract situation. It could be a critical time for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have an option on Greer's contract for next season
at $4.5 million, and there is little doubt they will pick up the
option. But he is unsigned beyond 2001. There have been sporadic
talks with management since spring training, but everything was
shut down when the club started to falter in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to sit down as soon as possible and try to get
something worked out so I could hopefully be here for my whole
career, or at least the near future,'' Greer said. ``I can sit here
and speculate what might happen, but the only people who really
know are the guys in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be general manager Doug Melvin, who wants to keep
Greer but said the time to talk is in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of our club; I don't think that has changed,''
Melvin said. ``I've always had that interest. But it's hard to
speculate until you see the numbers. I wanted to re-sign Aaron Sele
and Todd Zeile. But until you sit down and talk, you really don't
get a sense of where it's going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer said the contract has not been a distraction this season
but could be next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has affected me,'' Greer said. ``Certainly
you think about it because it's part of the job, and that's what
affects you both now and down the road. As far as on the field, I
hope it hasn't affected me at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to get something done before the beginning of
next season. If not, then, if you go into the season, it could be a
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   The distractions this year were from injuries. He had a strained
hamstring that put him on the disabled list in April. He used that
time to have ankle surgery. Then, while on a medical-rehabilitation
assignment in the minors, he hurt his shoulder, and his return was
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   He missed six weeks, didn't get back into the lineup until May
27 and found himself far behind everybody else. An admittedly slow
starter, Greer didn't find himself back at the top of his game
until after the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers are returning to normal, even if the six-week
absence will prevent him from reaching his customary 100 runs
scored and 100 runs batted in. He is hitting .302. His on-base
percentage is .379, and his slugging percentage is .463. Melvin
likes to add a player's on-base percentage and slugging percentage,
and deems anything over .800 as showing a productive season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a couple of nice streaks and swung the bat well,''
manager Johnny Oates said. ``All of us, as we get older, can't do
some things well as we used to, but there are some things we can do
better. He's still a guy you'd like to have up there with the game
on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer said: ``I feel very, very good. I think that my body has
responded well. Numbers-wise, with another 100 to 140 at-bats,
you'd see things right where they normally are. I've been happy
with the way things have gone. It's more of a relief in my mind
that everything is all right with the ankle where I don't have to
worry about it going into spring training next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer gives the Rangers some flexibility by being able to hit in
any of the top three spots in the lineup. Oates is even reviving
the notion of batting him leadoff if the Rangers are able to
acquire the big bat they eagerly seek in the middle of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusty's a guy, depending on the rest of the lineup, that could
hit first, second or third,'' Oates said. ``He could be a sixth
guy. There are so many roles he could fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer has never fretted where he bats. He would just like to
play on a winning team, he would like to do it injury-free and he
would like to do it for the Rangers beyond next season.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he could forget about what happened this year. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
