<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-12 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VULTURES SERENADE BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Above the west tunnel in Giants Stadium,
several dozen fans, many in Jets jerseys, were perched like
vultures, waiting for Bill Belichick to appear. And when the
Patriots coach did appear, the boos descended. Heavy, hearty boos.
Cruel boos. Among the serenade of those boos a heavy, hearty voice
could be heard above the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gutless pig,'' that heavy, hearty voice boomed.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the climate on Monday night when the Jets deflated the
Patriots, 20-19, in a dazzling renewal of their rivalry as
Belichick, who joined the Patriots as head coach instead of
fulfilling his Jets' contract as Bill Parcells's successor,
returned to Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When Belichick and Al Groh, who did succeed Parcells, were on
Parcells' staff, they would put together the defensive game plan
and then bring it to Parcells, who often would say with his
familiar sarcastic grin, ``What have you geniuses come up with this
week?''
</P>
<P>
   And for more than 50 minutes on Monday night, Belichick appeared
to be the genius. His defenses were stifling the Jets' offense. But
suddenly Vinny Testaverde, after throwing five passes to Richie
Anderson, found Wayne Chrebet for a 2-yard touchdown that pulled
the Jets to within 19-14.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Jets had the ball Testaverde completed two
quick passes for 78 yards _ 44 to Dedric Ward, then 28 to Chrebet
for the winning touchdown. On the Patriots sideline, Belichick's
shoulders slumped. On the Jets' sideline, Groh was the resident
genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't anything specific that woke up the offense, maybe
just a sense of urgency,'' Groh said later. ``It was do or die.''
</P>
<P>
   During the warm-up, Groh walked over to Belichick, shook hands
and chatted for maybe two minutes as they stood on the
red-white-and-blue National Football League shield at midfield. And
after the game, he had a quick conversation with Belichick on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just exchanged pleasantries before the game; we'd been
through a lot of battles together in this stadium,'' Groh said.
``After the game, I just wished him well. I knew he just wanted to
get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh and Belichick were on the same coaching staff for seven
seasons with the Giants, Browns, Patriots and Jets; they remain
friends. But Parcells was not at the game, having explained that
his presence would have been ``too much of a circus.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Jets, a real rivalry has been rare, if only because in
most of their 40 previous seasons the Jets (and their American
Football League ancestors, the Titans) were seldom good enough to
create a real rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   In the years leading up to and following their Super Bowl III
victory, the Jets briefly had a coast-to-coast rivalry with the
Oakland Raiders that flared in 1967 when Joe Namath had his
cheekbone shattered (and helmet knocked off) by defensive end Ike
Lassiter.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as Parcells joined the Jets after having taken the
1996 Patriots to the Super Bowl, the Jets-Patriots rivalry burst
into flames. It singed not only the souls of the fans along the
I-95 corridor but also the National Football League
schedule-makers.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth straight season, the Jets and Patriots were
playing in prime time, the third straight season on Monday night.
But the three other games had all been at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When Parcells returned to Foxboro on a Sunday night in the 1997
season, he was hooted by fans waving banners and wearing T-shirts
that implored ``Grill the Tuna.'' When he strode onto the field for
the warm-up, he was greeted with shouts of ``Show me the money,''
meaning his reported six-year $14.4 million Jets contract.
</P>
<P>
   That night the Jets would've won had John Hall made a 29-yard
field goal in the final seconds, but the Patriots blocked the low
kick, then won in overtime, 27-24.
</P>
<P>
   In that season's rematch, Parcells, ``looking for a spark,''
benched Neil O'Donnell at halftime, inserted Glenn Foley at
quarterback and the Jets rallied to win, 24-19.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the Jets swept both games. In the 1999 season opener
Testaverde would crumple to the artificial turf in Giants Stadium
with a torn left Achilles' tendon and the Patriots held on to win,
30-28. But the Jets won the Monday night rematch, 24-17, behind Ray
Lucas's two touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday night the vultures had the last laugh on Bill
Belichick. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
