<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-TEXAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS APPEAR HUNGRY AGAIN, NOT BLOATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ The mountains are still emerald green, the stream
that chatters through the Vail Valley is still icy cold and the air
is crisp and clean, but there's something distinctly different this
year about Stars training camp.
</P>
<P>
   No Cup hangover.
</P>
<P>
   Last September the Stars spent the first week of camp telling
everyone that asked that there would be no problem gearing up for
another run at the Stanley Cup, even though their glazed eyes told
a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Stars were just trying to convince themselves. In the
process, they even fooled head coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight allows Hitchcock to contemplate last September with a
sharper eye now, but he can still remember how surprised and
pleased he was with his team's performance here and in exhibition
games a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was confusion,'' Hitchcock said as he sat on a bench in the
afternoon sun in Vail Village on Monday, sipping a cup of coffee.
``I'd prepared myself for the worst, but we came into this training
camp, and man, we were flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told \Rgeneral manager\R Bob \RGainey\S\ just before the
start of the season, `Man, Bob, this is unbelievable. This team
hasn't missed a beat.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was Gainey, who has been there himself, who sounded the first
word of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget what he said,'' Hitchcock recalled. ``He
looked at me in that way he has and said, `We're in trouble.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What do you mean we're in trouble? We look great.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `We're running on last year's energy. We're not
running on this year's energy, and when the tank goes empty, Hitch,
we've really got our work cut out for us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for Hitchcock to believe, based on how his team
seemed to be responding in camp, but he knew that Gainey had played
on Stanley Cup winners. If anyone would know how difficult it is to
get energized for another run, it would be him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the best description for it I've ever heard,''
Hitchcock said. ``He said, `When the tank empties, it's going to be
like when you have a big turkey dinner at Thanksgiving, and you eat
until you're full, and then an hour later someone taps you on the
shoulder and tells you its time to eat again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take another bite. You're already stuffed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Stars found themselves a month into the season
last year. The sustained energy from winning the Stanley Cup in
Buffalo finally ran out. They couldn't take another bite.
</P>
<P>
   For the next month the Stars struggled to figure out whether
they really wanted to pay the price to get back into serious
contention for another run. It could have gone either way.
</P>
<P>
   You know the rest of the story.
</P>
<P>
   There's a big difference between winning the Cup and losing it
in six games, as the Stars did last June against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The hunger is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling around this team right now among the leaders is
the same feeling we had after the \Rconference championship\S loss
against Detroit \Rtwo years ago\S: Ticked off. Disappointed. Mad.
Focused. All of those things. In a lot of ways, the plate is
empty,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know other organizations would say, `Man, you got to the
finals, you did great.' Not this group. We have loftier goals than
that. And so there's this feeling that redemption is a big part of
what's going on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock can sense the difference in his veteran players,
people like Mike Modano, Brett Hull, Mike Keane, Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a methodical energy within the framework of the
leadership,'' Hitchcock said. ``They are very low-key serious.
They're leading the drills, they're leading the scrimmages. They're
not loose, they're focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand-in-hand with this refreshed determination to make a third
consecutive trip to the Stanley Cup Finals is a decision by
Hitchcock and Gainey that to stay the same is to risk stagnation.
Thus, they will make a minor alteration to their precious system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dramatic but it's funny how when you make one little
change in your system it affects a ton of things on the ice,''
Hitchcock said. ``We've decided to be more aggressive defensively,
putting more pressure on the puck, and we think that will lead to
more chances offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable on-ice manifestation of the team's new
pressure tactics will be a new emphasis on the fourth line.
</P>
<P>
   That means younger, faster, meaner, and did I say faster?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidence that we can play four lines significant
minutes and not affect things,'' Hitchcock said. ``It means
Modano's line will play 18-20 minutes instead of 25 minutes. It
means the fourth line won't play eight minutes, it'll have to play
12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we're going to have to play at a tempo that the other
team can't compete at. Our fourth line is going to have to be an
energy line. It's not going to a line of mixing and matching like
it has been in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Brenden Morrow, Roman Lyashenko and Jon Sim, with the
occasional dash of Blake Sloan or maybe rookie Ryan Christie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a team that's had two lines that check and
two lines that score,'' Hitchcock said. ``We want to have three
lines that score and one that checks.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more emphasis on offense ... what a concept.
</P>
<P>
   So the Stars are clear-eyed and focused. Cup hangover is long
gone. They open the exhibition season Thursday night in Denver and
play the Blues on Saturday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost hockey time in Texas, folks, and with the summer the
Rangers have had and the way the Cowboys have started, not a moment
too soon. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
