<HEADER>
A9716 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-KNIGHT-     09-12 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-KNIGHT-WRITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN: KNIGHT CAN HAVE JOB WITH MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 THRU-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If Mavericks owner Mark Cuban gets his way, Bobby
Knight won't be unemployed for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a huge fan, Bobby has a standing offer to join the Mavs as
a consultant,'' Cuban said Monday. ``I would offer him a job in a
heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight was fired Sunday from his longtime job as the Indiana
University men's basketball coach. Cuban, an IU graduate, is very
fond of Knight and even paid him a visit when the Mavericks played
the Indiana Pacers in Indianapolis in February.
</P>
<P>
   With Knight's legendary status in Indiana, many of his followers
are having difficulties coping with his dismissal. Cuban, who has
given generously to the IU program, admitted as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult in some respects, because I know how important
coaching is to him, and no one wants to be fired under those
circumstances,'' Cuban said. ``On the other hand, it's liberating.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if he takes another coaching job, my guess is he is going
to be incredibly motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cuban plans on hiring Knight, he might have to move quickly.
New Pacers coach Isiah Thomas said he wants Knight to be an
assistant on his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's welcome to sit on my bench at any time,'' Thomas told a
Detroit radio station. ``I would love for him to mentor me the way
Tex Winter has for Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genius that \RKnight\S has to give is strategically
unmatched. I would definitely offer him a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas played two years for Knight at Indiana before leaving for
the NBA in 1981 as a first-round draft pick of the Detroit Pistons.
Thomas guided the Hoosiers to the '81 NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Thomas and Knight's close player-coach relationship _
and the fact that Indianapolis is a stone's throw away from
Bloomington, Ind. _ Knight might be more inclined to work for the
Pacers than the Mavericks. But that won't stop Cuban from pursuing
a man who, despite the many controversies, would instantly push the
Mavericks into the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bobby is a great coach,'' Cuban said. ``From an NBA
perspective, his players always come well prepared to the league
and the coaching shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as whether he will coach again, I don't know. He may
decide his future lies in discovering new fishing spots around the
world.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
