<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRIBULATIONS AND TRIUMPHS IN SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 12:
</P>
<P>
   Baseball and football have yet to produce their main story lines
for 2000, and the summer Olympics that open this week in Australia
will generate many of the year's most memorable athletic images.
But for sports aficionados this past weekend provided plenty of
nourishment. The University of Indiana finally summoned the
gumption to fire Bob Knight as basketball coach, a gifted young
Russian tennis player gave the sleepy world of men's tennis a badly
needed jolt and Tiger Woods added another golf title to one of the
greatest championship years anyone has ever achieved in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of Knight was long overdue. His abusive treatment
of players, colleagues and officials was condoned by university
administrators because Knight brought the school three NCAA
championships and 11 Big Ten Conference titles in 29 years at
Indiana. His bullying behavior continued even after the university
set a ``zero tolerance'' policy for the coach last spring. Even so,
Myles Brand, the university president, managed to ignore the strict
code until a confrontation between Knight and a student last week
became a public issue. Knight's unruly partisans might ponder the
example of John Wooden, who won 10 NCAA titles at UCLA without
intimidating his players.
</P>
<P>
   After dominating men's tennis for a decade, and collecting a
record 13 Grand Slam titles, Pete Sampras may have met his
successor on Sunday in the U.S. Open. Marat Safin, a 20-year-old
Russian with an overpowering serve and laser-like ground strokes,
disposed of Sampras in three quick sets. His emergence may give the
men's game the kind of compelling new rivalry that women's tennis
enjoys with the wondrous Williams sisters, Venus and Serena, and
their top rivals.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tiger Woods, a year of unsurpassed excellence seemed
complete after he won the PGA tournament last month, giving him
three of golf's four major titles in 2000. But by triumphing in the
Canadian Open on Sunday, Woods brought his overall victory total
this year to nine and became only the second player to win the
U.S., British and Canadian Opens in the same year. Someone will
have to win a bucket of gold medals in Sydney to eclipse Woods as
athlete of the year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 0222EDT &QL; 
