   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-REPRODUCING-ROBOTS (Undated) _ Bees do it. Birds do it.
Bacteria do it. Robots can't. When computer scientists at Brandeis
University two weeks ago unveiled a robotic system that designs and
builds other robots, that set off speculation that
self-reproducing, evolving robots could someday explore the galaxy,
or push humans to extinction. But it looks like the hardest
obstacle in building an intelligent, evolving, self-reproducing
robot may turn out to be the self-reproducing part. By Kenneth
Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BUTTERFLIES (Undated) _ Over the past 20 years, biologists
have voiced increasing concern about the monarch butterfly's most
threatened and critical habitat, a single stretch of Mexican forest
to which hundreds of millions of these butterflies migrate from the
United States each year to spend the winter. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RARE-INSECTS (Edgartown, Mass.) _ Ask people on Martha's
Vineyard about insects and they are likely to talk about
mosquitoes, no-see-ums and green-headed flies, all of which can
make life miserable here. But the island's insect population
comprises far more than pests. Entomologists hope to use it to
re-establish rare and endangered insect populations wiped out
elsewhere in New England years ago. By Cornelia Dean.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIRES-NUKES (Undated) _ Fires in and around nuclear
facilities understandably make people nervous, and so this has been
an unnerving summer in the American West, where the wildfires that
ravaged millions of acres edged into several major complexes.
Scientists outside the Energy Department who reviewed the air
monitoring data from the fires at Los Alamos and Hanford agreed
that there did not seem to be any cause for alarm. But the risks of
radiation releases during and after wildfires at contaminated
nuclear sites are still not very well understood by scientists, let
alone the public. By Jon Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENETICS-SOCIETY (New York) _ Just before the Fourth of July
holiday, an international scientific consortium announced at a
White House celebration that it had largely deciphered the DNA
instructions encoded in the human chromosomes. Once the hoopla died
down, we who are involved in the work have turned to preparing a
scientific paper to be submitted later this year describing the
findings. But while scientific revolutions may start with dry,
objective data, but ultimate impact depends on human interpretation
in a societal context. So, I was glad to visit the Exit Art Gallery
in Soho for the opening of a different kind of genome annotation
project, a show entitled ``Paradise Now: Picturing the Genetic
Revolution'' by 39 artists probing the social meaning of genetics.
By Eric S. Lander.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUGS-CHILDREN (Undated) _ Starting this December, a new
Food and Drug Administration rule mandates that any new adult drug
that the FDA decides could be used by children with the same
disease must undergo pediatric study, and its manufacturers must
list doses for children on the label. We have a conversation with
Dr. Dianne Murphy, associate director of the FDA's Center for Drug
Evaluation and Research. By Alexis Jetter.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUGS-TESTS (Washington) _ In a hearing today, the FDA tries
to hammer out details of how ethically to test drugs on children.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undted) _ The Personal Health column: The
Sugar Association is trying to convince Americans that consuming
large quantities of sugar-sweetened soft drinks and snacks does not
harm one's nutritional status, body weight or long-term health. But
the research the association cites to support its contentions shows
how statistics can often be misleading if they present only part of
the story. Here is what you should know about the appalling
increase in sugar consumption by Americans _ especially children _
and the effects this increase is having on health. By Jane E.
Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCOOTER-SAFETY (Undated) _ Those shiny, foot-propelled
scooters are everywhere, but so are injuries, according to a report
issued last week by the Consumer Product Safety Commission. By
Linda Villarosa.
</P>
