<HEADLINE>
LUCIRA AIMING TO TRACE HOT PCS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When his laptop computer was stolen three years ago, Ravi
Hariprasad got so mad he started a company to do something about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hariprasad's Boston-based Lucira Technologies Inc. is about
to release a product it says will be able to trace hot PCs whenever
they are used to connect to the Internet. The company also claims
its software will upload lost data and render the remaining
material unusable _ a repossession service for the information age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision of where we're going is to give everyone some
really powerful protections they don't really have now,'' said
Hariprasad, 24, who dropped out of medical school at the University
of Pennsylvania to become Lucira's president. ``You've got car
security and house security. But people walk around with this
information on their laptops and are only starting to think about
what they've got there.''
</P>
<P>
   A competitor is Absolute Software Corp. in Vancouver, British
Columbia, which also provides software that traces the whereabouts
of its host computer. Lucira says it will compete on price, giving
away its software free to most consumers beginning in a month or
two and charging a fee, perhaps around $20, to activate it to find
a stolen machine.
</P>
<P>
   It also just hired as a privacy officer Keith Enright, known for
the privacylaw.net Web site he maintains. Enright's job will be to
ensure Lucira only tracks the whereabouts of laptops that have been
reported stolen. He said the whole business should improve data
confidentiality as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more consumer-level sales there are of laptops, the more
people are going to start relying on these devices for their
confidential medical and financial information,'' Enright said.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop safety has been a hot topic among computer-security
consultants for years, since the machines are often worth thousands
of dollars and are easily lifted _ in both senses of the word.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey taken by the FBI and the Computer Security
Institute, thefts of laptops accounted for losses of $13 million
among 150 companies surveyed in 1999. Claims by laptop owners
accounted for 88 percent of personal-computer claims of $1.9
million last year, according to Safeware Inc., a Columbus, Ohio,
insurance agency.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the claims related to accidents, the company said, but
theft accounted for about $550,000 of claims.
</P>
<P>
   Lucira's products are meant to do something about it. The
software doesn't take up much room _ about 100k of memory _ and is
installed on a computer's hard drive in a manner Lucira says is
impossible to detect without sophisticated snooping tools.
</P>
<P>
   The software is written so that whenever its host computer is
connected to the Internet, it downloads from Lucira a list of
computers considered stolen.
</P>
<P>
   If the laptop's own number is on the list, it then sends to
Lucira its present Internet-protocol address, or the route it is
using to connect to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Next, after the laptop is signed off, the software instructs the
laptop's modem to redial itself to Lucira directly, where the
company uses an advanced caller-ID system to pinpoint the phone
line being used to tap into the network. The software also turns
off the laptop's speaker during the call to make it hard to detect
the connection.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, these steps should all provide Lucira enough
information to help police find and retrieve the stolen machine.
Hariprasad also describes a feature that would eventually allow
users to retrieve files from their stolen machines _ or even to
destroy or encrypt files they consider confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't suck back your whole hard drive, but we could get
back a few files you specify,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has several millions of dollars in venture
funding. Hariprasad and four other cofounders still own a majority
stake. The company says it is in discussions with several big
hardware makers about incorporating its software in its designs.
</P>
<P>
   The company has ties to the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and plans to test the software soon on the school's
computers. A board member is Gerald Isaacson, MIT's data-security
manager.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ross Kerber is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at kerber(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
