<HEADLINE>
HOFFSTEIN HOLDS FAST AMID MARKET STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy whose stock is down 85 percent this year, and who
regularly gets calls from shareholders asking if his company is
going out of business, Gordon Hoffstein is remarkably calm and
confident.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that confidence may be born of experience. Hoffstein,
47, the chief executive of Be Free in Marlborough, Mass., has built
and sold two successful companies in the past. It also doesn't hurt
that he is sitting on nearly $170 million in cash, enough to last
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffstein insists he is confident for another reason:
because Be Free has a promising future that the stock market has
yet to recognize. Could he be right?
</P>
<P>
   Be Free specializes in affiliate marketing on the Internet. The
process works like this: if you're on a baseball site reading about
the Red Sox, you might find a link that takes you to the site of
Fogdog.com, a retailer selling Red Sox caps. Or if you're perusing
a site on fly fishing, you might see a link to an offer by L.L.
Bean for a fishing outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Be Free provides the connective tissue between the Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't hard to see why the stock is in the dumps. It closed
Monday at $5.25; in February it hit $56; it debuted last November
at $12. The market figures Internet retailing is like the Red Sox's
season, a lost cause. Internet advertising is even more unloved,
especially since virtually everyone now agrees that banner ads on
the Internet don't work.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffstein argues that investors are missing the point. Yes,
it's true banner ads don't work, he says, but for Be Free that is a
plus, not a minus. ``Companies still have to find customers,'' he
said in an interview last week. ``What are they going to do? Hire a
blimp? Scream in an open stadium?''
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer is: no, they will try affiliate marketing
instead. With Be Free's programs, retailers pay only when a
customer makes a purchase. In other words, they pay for
performance. Another set of Be Free clients, search engines such as
Lycos and Yahoo, pay for traffic that is driven to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   As ad budgets get squeezed, the hope is the online world will
turn to affiliate marketing _ and Be Free _ to make their dollars
go further.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Humphreys thinks investors are making a second mistake
about Be Free. ``I don't think this mode of interacting with
customers (e-commerce) is going away,'' said Humphreys, a partner
at Matrix Partners, a Waltham venture capital firm that owns a
stake in Be Free.
</P>
<P>
   Humphreys said that while some dot-coms may disappear, plenty of
dot-coms and established traditional players will continue to grow
their Internet businesses. Because Be Free has a number of
blue-chip clients _ AOL, E-Trade, Staples.com, Gap _ its business
will grow along with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company's fans point to another strength, Be Free's cash
pile. The company has the money to hang on and to make
acquisitions. Its chief rival, Linkshare, is a private company,
which in the current stock market would have trouble going public.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the possibility that Be Free itself will be
acquired. ``I would not be surprised if they were bought out by
someone looking to become a powerhouse in e-marketing,'' said Ethan
McAfee, an analyst at T. Rowe Price, and one of a number of
analysts who, unsolicited, brought up the buyout scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Hoffstein has a track record of selling companies. In
1996 he sold PCs Compleat, a computer retailer, for $134 million.
In 1990 he sold Microamerica, a computer distributor, for $96
million. In the pre-Internet era, $100 million was a lot of money.
Hoffstein's former venture partners, who are with him again this
time, can't say enough good things about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would back him any time I could,'' said Ted Dintersmith, a
partner with Charles River Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Hoffstein faces an uphill path. The stock market
remains hostile to e-commerce firms, especially those that lose
money. Analysts say Be Free won't be profitable before the end of
2001 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Another negative: while sales are growing, they are not
exploding. Be Free had revenue of just over $4 million in the
second quarter, a number that is not going to bowl anyone over.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hoffstein's confidence remains unshakeable. He concedes that
some Internet companies have business models that will never lead
to success. Be Free just doesn't happen to be one of them. ``We
have a model that is sustainable, we have good growth and we will
be highly profitable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Is that bravado justified? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
