<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY FUND DRAWS HOT DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Perhaps one of the best kept secrets in Boston venture capital
_ until recently _ has been Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking billion-dollar funds or megadeals. The
school's Community Technology Fund has been quietly plugging away
since 1975, when cofounder Matthew Burns squeezed $2 million from
BU's endowment to invest in such ventures as Amos Hostetter's
Continental Cablevision.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the fund is still modest at $55 million. But its profile
is rising, following a string of successful investments and
early-stage tech deals.
</P>
<P>
   From relative obscurity, CTF has recently jumped to one of the
20 most active backers of Boston-area start-ups, according to
rankings by PricewaterhouseCoopers. And the pace is still surging:
The group has done seven deals in the first three months of its
fiscal year, already eclipsing the five deals it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   CTF has participated in rounds for Digital Broadband
Communications, a high-speed Web access company; C-Port Corp., a
chip and software maker; and, last month, Coriolis Networks, a
fiber optics company, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Crawford, 40, is chief dealmaker. He's a UMass engineer
who joined the fund in 1994, having previously done telecom market
planning for Boston Edison. Before that, he was a venture
capitalist with 3i Corp., a British investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford says the group's assets are evenly split between
information technology companies and life sciences companies. But
his chief focus now is on the former. His target investment is
$500,000 to several million.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal expected announced Monday, CTF is in a later-stage,
pre-IPO round for Mapletree Networks, a Norwood maker of software
and hardware used in routing voice and data traffic, alongside
Hostetter's Broadband Ventures Fund.
</P>
<P>
   How does a little fund get in on hot deals? The university
connection is the key, people who've done business with the fund
say. Entrepreneurs and venture capital firms want access to BU's
top engineering and science professors. The school's Photonics
Center, a cutting-edge facility for the study and commercialization
of light-related technogy, is another big draw. But perhaps the
biggest allure is a pipeline to job-seeking students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a huge differentiator,'' says Sean Aruda,
MapleTree's chief executive. He made contact with CTF in an unusual
way: He got a cold call from the group. Plenty of venture
capitalists would be turned away without a personal introduction.
But recruiting, Aruda says, ``is the thing that keeps me awake at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of the 7,822 graduates of BU's various
schools graduated with degrees in science or technology areas. The
venture group is glad to help graduates land jobs with promising
companies. It's also in the business of helping professors license
technology and raise venture funding for ideas developed in the
school's labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real test,'' says Burns, 64, a formal Naval officer
and Harvard Business School grad who sits on many boards. ``After
six months or a year, can you take this out and raise money?''
</P>
<P>
   Most big schools with engineering and science departments have
licensing operations to help professors patent their inventions and
profit from them. The goal these days is to gain equity stakes in
companies built around those technologies to generate profits for
the university and the professors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the venture group's biggest successes is Sequenom, a
genomics company based in San Diego with Boston offices. CTF first
invested in the company in 1995, backing BU professor Charles
Cantor, a cofounder. CTF has reaped a return greater than 100
percent on its bet.
</P>
<P>
   The recent successes overshadow a biotech investing debacle that
took place in the 1980s and 1990s. The school had invested heavily
in money-losing Seragen Inc. under the watch of former president
John Silber and suffered huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   But CTF appears to have a sterling reputation. When it's not
making direct investments, the group is advising the university on
outside venture funds in which to invest endowment funds. BU has
invested more than $60 million of its $900 million endowment in
funds from Charles River and Commonwealth to Bessemer and Alta.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fitzgerald, a general partner with Commonwealth Capital
Ventures in Wellesley, says CTF was able to get in on its third
fund, a $170 million pot closed in June, because of a long
relationship with Crawford. He acknowledges that there's so much
money in the market, it's tough for small players like CTF.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the thing is grossly oversubscribed by big guys, they're
going to have a hard time getting in,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   CTF squeaked its way into a recent round with one of the
region's hottest fund-raisers, telecom player Quantum Bridge
Communications, partly thanks to the entrepreneurs' BU ties.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gwynne, a cofounder at Quantum Bridge, says investors and
customers were clamoring to get into the Andover start-up's $102.5
million round in the second quarter. CTF didn't get to put in
nearly what it wanted to, but $100,000 was a coveted foot in the
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense for us to spread our investors over multiple
sources,'' Gwynne says. And it didn't hurt that more than 20
Quantum Bridge employees hold BU degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clareon call
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An online payments system with BankBoston roots is on its way to
a second round of venture funding and a key relationship with Wall
Street's Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Clareon Corp., a Portland, Maine-based B2B payments company,
announced $30 million in second-round financing led by Technology
Crossover Ventures of Palo Alto. Morgan is also a large investor.
</P>
<P>
   Among the returning investors is BancBoston Ventures, which has
backed the deal since March, when Kate Barrand and six other
executives spun their start-up operation out of the bank with
former CEO Chad Gifford's blessing. Fleet is now the number three
investor in the company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
