<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRELAND SUPPORTS ITS TARNISHED SWIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Given how much of the last four years she has spent
with lawyers, it is hardly surprising that as her contemporaries
take part in the Olympic Games in Sydney, Michelle Smith de Bruin,
Ireland's most decorated swimmer, will begin law school here in the
city that James Joyce once said wouldn't know the truth if it bit
it in the arse.
</P>
<P>
   After all, for whatever is left of de Bruin's tarnished legacy,
she can thank the law. It was her lawsuits that put off the
inevitable: being seen as someone who used performance-enhancing
drugs, or at least someone who tried to mask the evidence. It was
her threatening legal action that led Ireland's swimming body to
back down and allow her to retain 26 individual Irish records,
despite her international reputation as a cheat.
</P>
<P>
   The law has allowed her to remain a champion, if only in name.
There are the three gold medals from Atlanta. The two golds at the
European Championships at Seville. And nearly every record in Irish
women's swimming. They all stand.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the law aside, there is the inescapable conclusion that
Michelle Smith de Bruin, Ireland's greatest champion, has been
judged by the great bulk of people of the world, including Ireland,
a cheat. She and her affable lawyer Peter Lennon can claim
innocence as long as the day is long. But they might as well be
whistling ``Dixie'' and claim it is ``A Soldier's Song,'' Ireland's
national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   To some, their protestations of innocence, their claims of a
conspiracy orchestrated by Americans and somehow assisted by
numerous other countries (several of which dislike if not hate the
United States) are an embarrassing reminder of an Ireland that was
poor, insecure, unsophisticated, and desperate to be accepted into
the big leagues of nations.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in Ireland today, a rich Ireland that for nearly a
decade has had the most robust economy in Europe and has had to
hire Spaniards and Italians to serve natives in their suddenly
cosmopolitan restaurants, there are many who still defend their
greatest, most infamous champion.
</P>
<P>
   David Dwyer, an architect who has helped reshape Dublin from the
Victorian backwater that Joyce once described into one of Europe's
most vibrant capitals, said de Bruin was unfairly singled out. He
believes that most of the world's best swimmers use
performance-enhancing drugs. De Bruin should be blamed only for
getting caught, Dwyer suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her performance was excellent,'' he said of the Olympics. ``If
she did it, it was understandable. She wasn't the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar sentiments have been voiced by those excusing the sticky
fingers of Charles J. Haughey, who in the 1980s and early 1990s was
Ireland's prime minister on three separate occasions, and who
managed to solicit at least $12 million from businessmen.
Prosecutors who are currently trying to put Haughey in jail, or at
least shine a relentless light on the relentless corruption in
Irish politics, believe Haughey took far more than that.
</P>
<P>
   But walk around Dublin, and you'll hear something like this from
Pat Kelly, a God-fearing cabbie: ``Our Michelle did nothing wrong,
except succeed. It's the same with your man Charlie. People in this
country don't like success.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly may use pronouns differently than you and I, but he had
one thing right. Some Irish have a peculiar attitude toward
success. They resent it. It's called begrudgery, and it is
considered a national affliction.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Pat Coogan, whose just-published book about the Irish
diaspora, ``Wherever Green is Worn,'' should be required reading
for anyone who had a great auntie from County Galway, once
observed, ``The one problem with the Irish is begrudgery.''
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to de Bruin and her lawyer, you would think it was
begrudgery that ensured her downfall. But getting to listen to de
Bruin isn't easy. An interview with the Globe last Friday was
canceled, apparently because of a Newsweek article that mentioned
her in the same sentence as disgraced Canadian sprinter Ben
Johnson. As Lennon explained, if there was any chance of that
perceived slight being overlooked, it was lost Friday afternoon
when the Evening Herald, a Dublin tabloid, ran a front-page splash
saying de Bruin had been tossed back in the fray of drug-taking.
The article, by a reporter in Dublin who rewrote wire copy, quoted
an American swimmer who mentioned de Bruin in passing, in response
to an Australian rival who had suggested he was using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle is not very happy with the media at this time,''
Lennon said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And yet Michelle Smith de Bruin is nothing if not a creation of
the media, especially in Ireland. Aside from Stephen Roche, who won
the Tour de France in 1987, and perhaps Sonia O'Sullivan, the Cork
woman who is one of the best middle-distance runners in the world,
no other Irish athlete accomplished anything on the international
stage remotely as impressive as de Bruin's three golds and a bronze
in Atlanta, followed in 1997 by two golds and two silvers at the
European Championships. The Irish media fell over themselves
lauding de Bruin's achievements, and the nation, which by the mid
1990s had become one of Europe's richest countries, enjoyed her
success vicariously.
</P>
<P>
   But if most Irish journalists prayed at the altar of St.
Michelle, there were a few who became the proverbial skunks at the
garden party. While their contemporaries reached for thesauruses
for superlatives to heap on de Bruin, Tom Humphries of the Irish
Times, Paul Kimmage of the Sunday Independent, and Eamon Dunphy, a
Sunday Independent columnist and host of Ireland's most popular
drive-time radio show, began to smell a rat _ a water rat, at that.
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy, Humphries, and Kimmage were disturbed that de Bruin's
husband, who was also her trainer, had been banned as a shot putter
for using steroids. The trio pointed out that de Bruin's remarkable
improvement at the relatively late age of 26 was unprecedented in
swimming. Humphries did the math and found that the average age of
the previous 10 gold medalists in the 400-meter freestyle was 16.9
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a nation as broadly ignorant of the science of swimming
as we Irish were could have swallowed it all without question,''
Humphries declared.
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy, a former professional soccer player, admits to admiring
many of de Bruin's qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's tough, smart, resourceful, and guilty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy accuses the national broadcaster, Radio Telefis Eireann,
as being the most egregious of mythmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``RTE drove the hype machine,'' said Dunphy. ``RTE never
mentioned in its coverage that her husband and trainer was a banned
athlete, that he had used the sort of performance-enhancing drugs
that she was suspected of using. They ran this crap about how Erik
de Bruin had miraculously transformed her into one of the greatest
swimmers of all time, but they somehow forgot to tell the Irish
people that Erik de Bruin was a cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of questioning de Bruin, many questioned the
integrity of Dunphy, Humphries, and Kimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mirror called me a rat,'' said Dunphy. ``Some of the other
papers called Tom and Paul worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The response of potential sponsors was more telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the sponsorship deals Michelle expected never
materialized,'' said Dunphy. ``Corporate Ireland never got behind
her. They, like us, smelled a rat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all came crashing down on Jan. 10, 1998, when Al and Kay Guy,
a couple who perform drug testing on Irish athletes, came to the de
Bruin home in Kilkenny. When the urine sample was tested, it was
found to contain enough whiskey to kill an elephant. In August
1998, swimming's world governing body imposed a four-year ban on de
Bruin for tampering with a urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   De Bruin appealed the finding to the Court of Arbitration for
Sport in Switzerland, whose findings included the fact that a
steroid, androstenedione, was found in three samples taken from de
Bruin between August 1997 and March 1998. The court also rejected
as unfounded de Bruin's claim that someone else had tampered with
her sample. The court said de Bruin ``was the only person who had
the motive and opportunity to manipulate the sample.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of Ireland's heroes died for their country, Humphries
says de Bruin lied for it. Humphries, who is in Sydney covering the
Games for the Irish Times, believes the de Bruin affair has
irrevocably tarnished sports in Ireland, and he is disturbed that a
generation or more of Irish girls will be trying to beat the
records of someone who used drugs to become the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no cleaner or dirtier than anyone else,'' Humphries
concluded. ``Our innocence has been stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   De Bruin is a late bloomer. In a sport dominated by teenagers,
she became a champion at 26. She will enter law school this month
as a 30-year-old. Her lawyer says she is appalled that the opening
of the Sydney Games has triggered so many negative references to
her case.
</P>
<P>
   Lennon says he and his client believe recent allegations that a
widespread use of drugs by American athletes was overlooked proves
there is a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come from a powerful country, you get a rap on the
knuckles,'' said Lennon. ``If you're like Michelle, and you come
from a small country like Ireland that is not supposed to win these
medals, they go after you with a vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she is innocent. Or perhaps she only believes she is
innocent. Or maybe, just maybe, being Irish, Michelle Smith de
Bruin knows that in Ireland, like South Boston, they will make you
and break you but never forsake you. They did it to Charles Stewart
Parnell, the 19th century home rule leader, throwing lime in his
face when he courted a married woman. They did it to the leaders of
the Easter Rising in 1916, spitting on them before the British
executed them.
</P>
<P>
   In Ireland, the begrudgers love to build you up to tear you
down, but in the end, they almost always come around.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, they almost always wait until you're dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
