<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-ART-     09-12 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 `MNF' ANALYSIS WAS LIGHT AS AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Plantagenet?
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence is one thing, but who knew that ``Monday Night
Football'' viewers would need Regis Philbin to watch a game?
</P>
<P>
   Where in the name of George Carlin did Dennis Miller dig up that
little kernel?
</P>
<P>
   For those not keeping track, the House of Plantagenet started
their rule of Britain in 1154 with Henry II and ended in 1400 with
Richard II. Their rule was characterized by internal feuding, like
the Hatfields and McCoys, and Miller was trying to make the simple
point that there was bad blood between the Jets and Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   In case that analogy didn't work, Miller threw out a shot at
popular rapper Eminem and his much-publicized divorce. Ppphheewww.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Miller knows that sort of stuff. He might want
to host a new game show, ``Guess What I'm Talking About.''
</P>
<P>
   And what was that followup joke in Miller's opening? You
remember the one about the game being decided by whoever had ``the
best Woody''? Get it? The Jets owner's name is Woody Johnson and
the Patriots have center Damien Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. People are talking about ``Monday Night Football''
again, and that is a good thing, at least according to Don
Ohlmeyer, the show's executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between Miller's jokes about Sigmund Freud and his
calling the referee Alfred Hitchcock, the first half ended, and
with the exception of an occasional observation by analyst Dan
Fouts, no one in the ABC booth told viewers just why the game was
pretty boring up till that point.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way. The halftime piece narrated by Chris Berman on
classic NFL hits, though probably seen thousands of times before,
was the most entertaining thing in the first 90 minutes of the
telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing the fellas in the booth could do about that _ except
maybe tell us why. Instead viewers received pieces of irrelevant
gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the fact that the Patriots had penetrated inside the
20-yard line four times in the first half and came away with only
field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts stepped up to the plate on several fairly obvious points.
Jets linebacker James Farrior blitzed in the second quarter and
hurdled Kevin Faulk to drill Drew Bledsoe in the back for a sack.
``You have to stay high when you are pass-blocking,'' said Fouts,
pointing out that Faulk tried to block Farrior below his knees.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, when Antonio Langham missed an
interception and allowed Wayne Chrebet to score what turned out to
be the winning touchdown, Fouts screamed, ``You gotta make that
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   That was as good as it got. When Miller talked about Adam
Vinatieri missing on his fifth field goal attempt, Fouts actually
said on national television: ``That's why they call the game
football, Dennis. You have to kick the ball through the uprights.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Jerry Glanville would come up with something that lame.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone focused on Miller, the real key is the other new
man in the booth, Fouts. Through three exhibitions and two
regular-season games, Fouts has been just all right. By all
accounts, he was one of the most respected players when he
quarterbacked the San Diego Chargers. He is also considered a great
guy.
</P>
<P>
   But this is football, and more than in any other sport, opinions
_ and strong ones at that, based on facts _ are what matter.
Ohlmeyer said he has talked with Fouts about being ``more
opinionated,'' but that has proven to be a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Even with facts, Fouts has been selective. During last week's
game between the Rams and Broncos, Fouts said that St. Louis
quarterback Kurt Warner had thrown five interceptions in the Red
Zone last year. But he neglected to mention that Warner threw only
13 interceptions altogether and had one of the lowest interception
percentages (2.6) in the league.
</P>
<P>
   And Fouts's opinions are questionable. In the fourth quarter
Monday night, the Patriots were driving once again into the Red
Zone. Fouts suggested that they should run the ball on third and 4
to get better position for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Patriots set up without a running back, and
passed to Faulk for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Ooops.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots scored a touchdown two plays later, so instead of
going up by 8 points, as Fouts figured they would if they ran the
ball, they went up 19-7.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything was bad. The camera attached to the referee's cap
was excellent, enabling viewers to see the game from field level.
Having Michael Douglas visit the booth was a good thing. Not giving
him a microphone was inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   And, for whatever it's worth, Damien Woody was taken out of the
game with an injury in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
