<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 10:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     09-12 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE BY THE SACKFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New England Patriots' offense is on
pace to give up 96 sacks this season. That's all you need to know
about it for now.
</P>
<P>
   Six sacks a week ago and a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Six sacks Monday night and a heartbreaking loss.
</P>
<P>
   Six sacks a game and you beat as many teams as the Patriots have
beaten so far this season. You beat none.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Patriots had no business being in position to
defeat Tampa Bay at the end of a six-sack debacle. But there they
were at the Buccaneers' 22-yard line with the clock running out and
a chance to steal a win they didn't deserve staring at them. They
didn't do it. Six sacks and endless pressure on Drew Bledsoe were
the reasons why.
</P>
<P>
   They controlled the tempo and the field for 57 1/2 of the 60
minutes they played against the New York Jets, but they couldn't
protect their quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the Patriots couldn't score in the Red Zone
and, in the end, as good as their defense supposedly is, it
couldn't do what Tampa Bay's did a week earlier either. It couldn't
hold its ground with the game on the line, and the Patriots'
offensive line couldn't hold its ground and so they lost again.
Lost a game they did deserve, 20-19, to fall to 0-2 with emphasis
on the word ``fall.''
</P>
<P>
   With 9:56 to play, the Patriots held a 19-7 lead despite having
driven inside the Jets' 20 six times. They had the lead and had
Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde baffled.
</P>
<P>
   But when it counted most, the Patriots collapsed on both sides
of the ball, which is what troubled teams do.
</P>
<P>
   With the game on the line, a defense that likes to call itself
great gave up back-to-back touchdown drives of 85 yards in 10 plays
and 72 yards in two plays. The Jets' offense walked over the backs
of New England's supposedly great defense with Testaverde finding
tiny Wayne Chrebet for touchdown passes of 2 and 28 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The last touchdown pass came one play after fellow receiver
Dedric Ward hauled in a 44-yard reception despite blanket coverage
by Ty Law, a catch former teammate Keyshawn Johnson would have been
proud to call his own.
</P>
<P>
   The defense the Patriots thought they could rely on had cracked
the way Tampa Bay's had not. When it counted most, the Buccaneers'
defense held a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   When it counted most, the Patriots' defense split open like an
over-ripe melon and it was suddenly 20-19 Jets with 1:55 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was ample time for New England to pull this game
out with a fifth Adam Vinatieri field goal, but the Patriots didn't
because they spent most of the time remaining pulling their
quarterback off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Incomplete pass under pressure on first down.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe knocked flat by rookies Shaun Ellis and John Abraham on
second down for a 6-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Incomplete under duress on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe knocked flat on fourth down by Abraham again after the
rookie blew past left tackle Bruce Armstrong and ran over the
Patriots' weary quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Six sacks, just like a week ago. Four sacks in the final two
drives of the day. Six times 16 equals 96. Six times 16 also equals
a disaster in the making.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of what happened are clear: When the Patriots needed
to answer on offense, they couldn't because their quarterback was
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   When they needed to answer on defense, they couldn't because
they couldn't put Testaverde on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Football is a simple game when played the way it is being played
by the Patriots. You keep your quarterback upright, you win. You
get him knocked flat six times, you don't.
</P>
<P>
   You can talk all day about time of possession and how at one
point the Patriots had an advantage of nearly 14 minutes in that
critical category.
</P>
<P>
   You can talk about how they dominated the Jets for much of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   You can talk about how they were still in position to beat the
Buccaneers and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   You can talk about how they are 0-2 by an average of just 3
points per loss.
</P>
<P>
   You can talk about a lot of things if you want, but that's all
it would be. Talk.
</P>
<P>
   So forget about the talk and talk about the facts. Simple,
mathematical facts.
</P>
<P>
   Six times 16 equals 96 and 96 sacks equals a disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
