<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9931 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     09-12 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE CHANGE IN FORMATION TURNED THE TIDE FOR JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This is a game neither team will forget
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets, looking hopelessly beaten for 45 minutes,
rallied for two fourth-quarter touchdowns by a guy who wasn't
supposed to play.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Chrebet made a series of incredible catches in the fourth
period, two for touchdowns, including the winner with 1:55 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Just 24 hours earlier, the Jets didn't think Chrebet was going
to be able to play. On Saturday, he injured a calf muscle in
practice without being hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't even practicing in pads,'' said Jets coach Al Groh.
``He went up to catch a pass and landed awkwardly and he came away
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, in the team hotel a few miles away from Giants
Stadium, Chrebet was icing his injured leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt that he will be able to play,'' Groh said at the time.
``It doesn't look good. But we really won't know until kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet played, but for the first 45 minutes of this strange
game, he looked out of it like the rest of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots led, 19-7, with less than 10 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of one drive in the second period, Bill Belichick's
brilliantly conceived game plan was being executed to
near-perfection by his team.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the fourth period, the Patriots had controlled the
ball for more than 28 minutes, 12 more than the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   In the second and third periods, the Jets had the ball in
Patriots territory for just five seconds. Not five plays. One play
for five seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' offense couldn't do a thing. Quarterback Vinny
Testaverde appeared confused by the Patriot secondary. He hurried
some throws and wasn't quite sure what to do with others.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense tried to contain the Jets' outstanding
runner, Curtis Martin, and force Testaverde to try to beat it
through the air.
</P>
<P>
   It worked well, but only for 50 minutes. Completely frustrated,
the Jets went from their regular offensive formations, into an
``empty nest'' formation, where the running back lines up on the
flank.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Jets came alive. Testaverde rediscovered Chrebet,
and the two made beautiful music.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the final minutes, they sliced the Patriots' spread-out
defense with beautiful throws and catches. And by being spread out
on defense, and forced to cover rather than charge, the Patriots
collapsed and lost a game they deserved to win.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did everything to win. They did not have a single
turnover. No fumbles. No interceptions, despite Drew Bledsoe
throwing 43 passes. They ran the ball surprisingly well, and
effectively, keeping the Jets honest. Through the first three
periods, the Patriots made almost all of the key third-down plays
on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense got Testaverde &AMP; Co. off the field in a
hurry. The Jets' defense couldn't do the same with Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   But then it all changed with the ``empty nest.'' It wasn't that
the Patriots' defense left receivers wide open, but rather that
Testaverde, who was wild with his pitches all night, made a number
of perfect throws, and Chrebet, with no sign of a limp or gimp, did
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   This is a game the Jets can build on the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   This is a game the Patriots hope they can rebound from, to get
ready for an undefeated Minnesota Viking team at Foxborough next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Will McDonough is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
mcdonough(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
