<SLUG> BC-TECH-TRANSMETA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSMETA HOLDS OUT ON BENCHMARKS FOR NEW CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SANTA CLARA, CALIF. _ There are lies, damn lies. And then
there are benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   This is a story about semiconductor benchmarks, those fickle
numbers that are supposed to tell us how computer chips stack up
against one another. Think of it as an Olympic decathlon in which
the contestants are Pentiums, Athlons, PowerPCs, Alphas, and
Celerons _ chips that crunch squillions of instructions and act as
the ``brains'' of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The newest athlete on the field is the Crusoe, a chip made by
Transmeta Corp. in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   What's so special about the Crusoe? Transmeta claims the chip
consumes far less power than its competitors, thereby conserving
precious battery life. Anyone whose laptop has run out of juice in
the middle of a task, with no power plug in sight, knows the value
of this.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this fall, consumers will start to see the Crusoe
processor in ultra-light laptops and other types of portable
computers made by Sony, Gateway, IBM, Fujitsu, NEC, and Hitachi.
</P>
<P>
   Sony next month will come out with a notebook computer with a
600-megahertz Crusoe processor. It will have roughly double the
battery life of Sony's previous model, which has a 400-megahertz
Pentium II processor made by Intel Corp. The new 2.2-pound Sony
VAIO PictureBook can run up to 5.5 hours on a standard lithium-ion
battery, as opposed to up to 2.5 hours on the older machine.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is what Sony, an investor in Transmeta, is
claiming. There is no reason to doubt Sony. It's just that few
outside of Transmeta's circle truly know how good the Crusoe is. To
wit, there exist no independent testing _ or benchmarking _
comparing the Crusoe to its rivals, particularly the Pentium made
by Intel, the heavyweight champion of the chip industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal that they haven't allowed us to evaluate any
units,'' said Kevin Krewell, senior analyst at MicroDesign
Resources in Sunnyvale, Calif. ``They make a lot of claims, but
there's no way we can verify those claims.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think Transmeta would be eager to show the world how
well the Crusoe performs in the industry's decathlon, so to speak.
But Transmeta has so far boycotted the event, arguing that current
benchmarks aren't suited to the Crusoe. Instead, it is quietly
lobbying independent testing labs to introduce new benchmarks that
will measure Crusoe's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, Crusoe is less power-hungry than other chips, and
the Pentium tends to perform slightly faster, even under
Transmeta's internal tests. It comes down to speed versus battery
life, and Transmeta officials argue that current benchmarks give
too much weight to speed and not enough to power usage.
</P>
<P>
   In a white paper on the topic, Daniel McKenna of Transmeta
writes that ``traditional benchmarks are inadequate to address the
requirements of the new mobile computing paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Intel also has something to say on this topic.
</P>
<P>
   George Alfs, Intel's programs manager, argues that benchmarks
shouldn't change just to show off a new chip design. They should
change only to reflect new ways people use their computers, such as
surfing the Internet or playing digital video discs, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benchmarks should reflect the work people do on their
computers,'' Alfs said. ``You don't want to change the benchmarks
just to make someone's hardware look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that so bad?
</P>
<P>
   No, says Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies Inc., a
technology consulting firm in Campbell, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens all the time in our industry,'' Bajarin said.
``When a new category comes along, the old rules often don't apply.
So it's up to the newcomer to try to introduce some new rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, independent chip testers such as MicroDesign
Resources and Ziff-Davis Laboratories will have to wait until the
fall to get their hands on the Crusoe to publish their own test
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benchmarking is an art to some extent,'' said Krewell, who
admits that Transmeta has little to lose by holding out. ``It can
be manipulated and misused. But at its best, it does give some
indication of relative performance. At least that's what we hope
for _ we hope for the best. And then it's up to customers to make
the right choice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
