<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-LUCENT-ART-BOS &LR;      09-12 1850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LUCENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 LUCENT WORKS TO JETTISON A TATTERED IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ANDOVER, Mass. _ Over the last year, as Lucent
Technologies stock has plunged roughly 50 percent, the
gallows-humor line has been that Lucent's famed red swirl logo
symbolized its lifeblood going down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   But the world's largest telecommunications company is fighting
its way back, jettisoning its slow-growing office network
installation business and taking other steps to sharpen its focus
on advanced communications gear, especially optical devices.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the company's more promising new initiatives is
taking shape here at its landmark Merrimack Valley plant, a 2
million-square-foot behemoth whose heritage dates back five decades
to its Western Electric days making phone switches.
</P>
<P>
   The North Andover plant is where Lucent is developing a new
product called the LambdaRouter, an all-optical switching device
that, in a single refrigerator-sized box, could move 10 times as
much traffic as now passes through the entire Internet, or 10.2
trillion bits of data per second.
</P>
<P>
   How big a market the product might find remains unclear. Even
some of Lucent's severest critics, though, acknowledge that the
Lambda project has the potential to revive Lucent's tattered image
as an innovator and market leader.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's woes, including projections of lower than expected
earnings this quarter, are of more than passing interest in
Massachusetts. The state has more than 9,000 Lucent employees, the
third-largest US cluster after New Jersey and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In the 3 1/2 years after it was spun off from AT&AMP;T, Lucent stock
soared 11-fold, giving the company ample currency to go on a buying
binge that included the acquisition of seven Bay State companies
since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Those include Excel Switching of Hyannis, Nexabit Networks of
Marlborough, Kenan Systems of Cambridge, and Spring Tide Networks
of Maynard, companies whose businesses span most of the range of
telecommunications boxes and software.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last year, while its $43 billion in revenues still
represented the largest share of the $200 billion global
communications-gear market, Lucent stock has been hammered amid
repeated warnings it would miss earnings forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent remains a leader in wireless equipment and many other
telecom categories. But it has been widely seen as lagging behind
Nortel Networks in catching the hot optical market, and behind
Cisco Systems and Juniper Networks in selling Internet routers,
while struggling to prevent a ``brain drain'' of talent from the
start-ups it has acquired.
</P>
<P>
   With the world's communications networks groaning under the load
of exploding Internet traffic, a major quest for the industry is
developing purely optical switches and routers that move data
streams without converting them into electricity, which can create
bottlenecks on Net superhighways.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent earlier this summer recorded its first revenue sales of
the Lambda device, to a phone carrier that declines to be
identified, and it has begun ramping up a 100-worker production
line at the 5,600-person North Andover factory to crank out the
machines.
</P>
<P>
   While Lucent for now can claim to be at the front of the pack,
it faces certain competition from other companies building
all-optical switches. Two of them, Nortel's Xros unit and Calient
Networks of Silicon Valley, plan to ship their products as early as
next year.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers say its rapid development of the Lambda
device from a brainstorm at Lucent's famed Bell Labs research
center into a revenue-generating product represents a success for
the company, perhaps as important for symbolism as for sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the few recent technology decisions that they did
make right,'' said Steve Saunders, editor of the online optical
networking newsletter LightReading, which has been withering in its
critical coverage of Lucent and has portrayed its top management as
bungling bullies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's Lucent getting ahead in a market early and playing to
the strengths of Bell Labs,'' Saunders said. ``The LambdaRouter is
definitely one of the few bright spots for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts and competitors are less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Clavenna, a leading optical industry consultant who
recently left Pioneer Consulting LLC in Cambridge to start his own
business called PointEast Research, said, ``The LambdaRouter is a
good product, and they deserve credit for commercializing it
quickly. But I see it having a fairly limited opportunity in the
market. It's not going to be a billion-dollar product line.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rick Thompson, director of product marketing with Sycamore
Networks in Chelmsford, a rapidly growing optical networking
start-up, sniffed: ``I really look at it as more of a science
project. There's not really much application for it in the network
in its current state.''
</P>
<P>
   The guts of the Lambda machine are two devices the size of a
postage stamp that each contain 256 mirrors. Each of the mirrors,
no bigger than the dot on top of this i, can redirect traffic from
one fiber-optic strand to another. Within a year, Lucent expects to
increase capacity to over 1,000 mirrors, something both Xros and
Calient promise to deliver as well.
</P>
<P>
   One huge advantage is that the device does not care whether
traffic headed from, say, Boston to London is coming in at 45
megabits or 40 gigabits per second; it simply switches it over to
the outbound fiber line by bouncing it off a little mirror aimed to
within thousandths of a degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a model of how we hope to get products to market
faster than we ever have,'' said Mike Kahl, a senior Lucent
production executive at Merrimack Valley. ``It's central to being
in the leadership role of optical. We expect this to be a real
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   One limitation is that, for the near term, the device will have
limited capability to manage traffic beyond redirecting it.
</P>
<P>
   It can be compared to a system for moving luggage through an
airport: It gets bags from one airplane to another in less than the
blink of an eye, without needing to run them through a sorting
room, but for now has virtually no way of checking to make sure the
bags are not damaged and no way of quickly verifying to an airline
manager that they made it to the right plane.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Sycamore's Thompson said ``we are not losing
sleep over this'' because his company remains convinced carriers
want switches that incorporate traffic-managing software, even if
traffic has to pass through an electrical router.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's Merrimack Valley plant produces virtually everything
used in a fiber-optic network except the fiber lines themselves,
including ``multiplexers'' that cram 80 wavelengths of light and
someday soon as many as 160 wavelengths on a fiber that once may
have carried only a single channel.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five months, according to Michael Jones, Lucent's
manufacturing vice president, the plant has tripled its ability to
produce the 10-gigabit modules where Nortel has a commanding lead.
It plans to double capacity again by the end of the year through
better organizing production schedules.
</P>
<P>
   But, he acknowledged, ``It's still not enough. It still (limits)
our ability to sell a lot of products. As much material as we can
find to bring here, we can find demand to ship against.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent executives note that, for all the inroads made by Nortel
and others, Lucent remains the only company that can boast it is
number one or number two in four main categories of optical
communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has already seen some dirty laundry from the North
Andover plant aired in a bitterly contested trade-secret lawsuit it
filed against 10 employees who defected to a new 2,500-person Cisco
optical factory being built in Salem, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, who have been assisted by Cisco in their
defense, charged Lucent with everything from gender discrimination
and tyrannical treatment of employees at North Andover to
widespread toleration of shoddy workmanship to hustle products out
the door. Lucent has denied all these charges.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to archrival Cisco Systems, which like Lucent has been
on a buying binge of promising start-ups in Massachusetts and
elsewhere, Lucent has been seen as doing a poor job of
incorporating talent into the company and staving off a ``brain
drain'' once entrepreneurs cash in their Lucent stock.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, for example, Lucent spent $900 million buying terabit
router maker Nexabit Networks of Marlborough last June, only to see
its founder leave within a year to open an optical-networking
start-up literally across the street from Nexabit, with several of
his former employees moving with him.
</P>
<P>
   Vast swaths of upper management at the former Cascade
Communications in Westford bailed out after Lucent bought Cascade
successor Ascend Communications for nearly $20 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cascade alumni have since founded or become senior executives at
several hot start-ups, including Sycamore Networks and Unisphere
Solutions in Chelmsford, Sonus Networks of Westford, and Equipe
Communications in Acton _ a talent pool that could have done
wonders for Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to work at Lucent?'' said one Cascade veteran who is
now a top executive of a start-up and asked not to be named,
reflecting widespread disenchantment with Lucent's corporate
culture.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs, however, that Lucent has begun tapping
entrepreneurial-minded executives at companies it has acquired to
take larger roles in turning around the organization. Both of its
top optical officials, for example, come from smaller start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Akers, founder and chief technical officer of Spring
Tide Networks, a network-management devices maker that Lucent
bought earlier this summer for $1.3 billion, will become chief
technical officer for Lucent's entire data networking division as
part of that deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the new job, Akers will oversee the lashing together of
products from the former Cascade and Nexabit as well as a
half-dozen other divisions making everything from digital
subscriber line gear to dial-up modems and converged switches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent has a tremendous amount of technology and a lot of
smart people, and they have a really good Internet-protocol
strategy,'' Akers said recently. ``I think we really just need to
get the message out about what we have. I think Lucent has pretty
much gotten a bad rap.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging it will be a shift moving from a 150-person
start-up, Akers said being able to put the famed Lucent brand and
logo on his Spring Tide devices ``is a large benefit to us'' in
gaining credibility in the market and sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to being an engineer,'' Akers said. ``You're
excited at seeing your product reach its full potential. That's
what we can do with Lucent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
