<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MFS-OUTLOOK-ART-BOS &LR;      09-12 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MFS-OUTLOOK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 TAKING STOCK AT TOP-10 MFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They were the new generation at the oldest mutual fund firm in
the business.
</P>
<P>
   It was the late 1980s and they were barely 30 years old _
hotshot stock analysts and fund managers at MFS Investment
Management. They spent their Friday evenings at a Back Bay watering
hole called Montana's, talking about the market, their company, and
how things would run if they were in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, they were in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a tremendous sense of possibility,'' says Kevin
Parke, one of the wunderkind crowd, now 40 and chief equity officer
at MFS.
</P>
<P>
   The boss, chief executive Jeff Shames, 45, recalls, ``We were
the kiddie corps.'' When he became equity chief at 32, he says, ``I
had never managed anyone in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he and his colleagues have managed to turn a historically
significant but slow-moving investment shop into a top-10 fund firm
that's quadrupled in size since 1995, to $160 billion. They have
ridden the growth-investing boom to the big time. Now they talk and
worry about the challenges of becoming a big company, about the
stock market _ and taking MFS public.
</P>
<P>
   MFS, with about $1.5 billion in annual revenue, is on track to
earn nearly $170 million this year. The Boston mutual fund group
accounts for nearly one-third of the earnings of its parent, Sun
Life Financial Services of Canada. And executives of both companies
are talking more about a public stock that reflects MFS's
significant value.
</P>
<P>
   Shames estimates that the company, one of the industry's fastest
growers since 1998, could be worth $5 billion to $7 billion in an
IPO. If the market put a more lavish premium on it, akin to recent
buyout prices for investment firms, the price could rise as high as
$9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Life, Canada's biggest life insurer, would make out
handsomely in such a deal. It bought MFS for a mere $55 million in
1982. And for the managers of MFS, who already own 22 percent of
the company, it would mean greater incentives to stay aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would ultimately like to have some piece of us go public,''
Shames says. ``We're active in that discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject is more front-and-center than ever before now that
Sun Life itself is a public company. It demutualized and sold
shares in October, and its stock has risen 139 percent, to $20.31.
Though the company's headquarters is in Toronto, the stock trades
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   That's not half bad for an insurance stock in a year that's
favored technology companies, analysts say. But the pressure will
now be on Sun Life to show investors it's reaping the full value of
MFS. The firm's private shares, held by its managers, have risen in
value fivefold in three years, Shames says, based on a formula of
asset growth, profits, and revenue.
</P>
<P>
   There's a potentially huge pot of gold awaiting the top managers
of MFS, a strange irony for a place that has long boasted more
about its culture than its compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for individual glory, go somewhere else,''
Shames says. ``If you want the biggest paycheck, go to Fidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that MFS doesn't like stars. It does, from John Ballen,
41, who succeeded Shames as president and runs the firm's popular
Emerging Growth fund, to Maura Shaughnessy, manager of one of the
best utility funds in the nation and of the Capital Opportunities,
another big seller.
</P>
<P>
   Two MFS stars quit last year, breaking a long tradition of
minuscule turnover. John Brennan and Chris Felipe, part of the
Montana's crew and what Shames calls the MFS ``youth movement'' of
1987, quit to start their own hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too early to tell what the impact is of losing
Felipe and Brennan,'' said Sarah Bush, mutual fund editor for
Morningstar Inc.'s adviser Web site. ``One of the reasons it seems
not to have hurt the shop is that they really do have a very deep
analyst bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation is part of the mantra at MFS. Fund managers' bonuses
depend in part on how helpful they are to analysts. In this
research-driven culture, Shames says, it's not enough to simply
post solid returns on your fund and hide in your office. Managers
and analysts are expected to take an active interest in all sectors
of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gets carried away with their own self worth,'' Shames
says. The firm enjoys a reputation across Boston and the industry
as a great place for investment pros to work. Shames seems to care
about that more than most CEOs: ``If it's not fun, the success part
isn't as worthwhile,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, there's nothing more fun than managing money.
``It's a blast every day, being a money manager,'' he says. Shames
and his colleagues want to hang on to their small-company culture.
And that's getting harder.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday meetings of the executive committee take not just a
couple of hours, but nearly all day. MFS is expanding its
international investment capabilities, whereas in the mid-1990s, it
hired an outside firm to run non-US funds. It wants to gain market
share outside its core growth area, especially in value funds. And
it's working to do more investing for institutions, such as pension
funds and corporate 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been out of the institutional business for 20 years,''
Shames says. Now the firm has 120 people working on the sector,
plus $30 billion of assets, up from $2 billion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Shames spends much of his time worrying about whether people are
happy at MFS, which now has 3,000 employees at 500 Boylston St. and
at Downtown Crossing, plus offices in London, Tokyo and Singapore.
It's about to open a Phoenix office for 900 new employees, because
space is so tight in Boston. And the quarterly employee meetings
with Shames that used to take place in a lunch room now are held a
block away, in an auditorium at the John Hancock Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the analyst at heart, Shames tries to see into the future
of MFS. He worries about the stock market falling after this long
bull run. And he mulls how to avoid the pitfalls of success. ``It's
great to be where we are,'' Shames says. ``The big thing is the
growth _ managing the growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
