<P>
   THE ALL-IN-ONE MARKET
</P>
<P>
   SELLING-ON-WEB-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW _ Companies have always
wrestled with two questions in tandem: what to sell and how to sell
it. The question of how to sell is a big one, because in choosing
one way, sellers almost always foreclose other possibilities. All
that has changed with the Internet, where business is increasingly
unconstrained by the laws and limitations of the physical world. A
report. By Paul Nunes, Diane Wilson and Ajit Kambil.
</P>
<P>
   EXPLODING THE SELF-SERVICE MYTH
</P>
<P>
   SELF-SERVICE-MYTH-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW _ Many companies view
the Internet as a self-service channel; they let customers help
themselves. But self-service can frustrate customers. A better
approach to e-commerce is ``coproduction.'' In this model, a
company uses technology to shoulder many of the tasks involved in
shopping and buying, relieving the burden on the customer. By
Youngme Moon and Frances X. Frei.
</P>
