<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0023 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-SELF-SERVICE-MYTH-HAR     09-12 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELF-SERVICE-MYTH-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLODING THE SELF-SERVICE MYTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Mon., Sept. 11, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from a recent issue of
HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of information on the
art and science of business and management. For information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or about The
Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING _
contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives
listed at the end of the text.) 
 By YOUNGME MOON and FRANCES X. FREI  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows that it usually costs companies less to conduct
business over the Web than through traditional channels. An online
banking transaction, for instance, costs just 2 cents, compared
with 36 cents for an ATM transaction and $1.15 for a
teller-assisted transaction. So it's not surprising that many
companies are desperately trying to attract consumers to the
Internet channel.
</P>
<P>
   What is surprising, however, is that most have had dismal
results. In retail brokerage, for instance, only 2 percent of
households trade online. And the figures for the airline industry
are even worse: Less than 0.1 percent of households purchase
tickets through airline Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Why are the numbers so low? In large part, it's because many
companies have bought into the myth that the Internet is a
self-service channel. They assume they should let their online
customers help themselves to whatever product or service they need
_ be it reserving their own airline tickets or configuring their
own automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that when a company does less, the customer ends
up doing more _ and most customers don't want to do more. In many
cases, self-service sites just leave customers frustrated and
annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when customers visit a typical airline Web site,
they are invariably confronted with a self-service search engine.
If they know exactly when and where they want to travel, the Web
site will generate a list of feasible flights. But if they want to
find the cheapest ticket and are flexible on the dates and
destinations, they have to conduct search after search, often
re-entering basic information such as seating preference and
billing address.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, customers who contact that same airline's call
center have a markedly different experience. They can give the
sales agent far less specific information, and the agent does the
unpleasant work of searching through the flight databases.
Customers only have to state their preferences once and then choose
between the best alternatives. Sales reps can even check for
upgrades or request special meals.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be surprising, then, that air travelers have been
slow to move to the Web for ticket purchases.
</P>
<P>
   A better approach to e-commerce is ``coproduction.'' In this
model, a company uses technology to shoulder many of the tasks
involved in shopping and buying, relieving the burden on the
customer.
</P>
<P>
   The coproduction model recognizes that although customers like
having choices, they don't want too many. They appreciate it when
companies offer prescreened alternatives geared to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Coproduction also recognizes that customers want to state their
preferences only once. Through coproduction, companies focus on
customer service, not self-service.
</P>
<P>
   Some of e-commerce's brightest stars are already using the
coproduction approach. Dell Computer, for example, performs a host
of back-end transactions that are invisible to customers _ such as
grouping its products by customer segments and displaying only
in-stock items. That way, customers can help themselves _ they can
configure their computers and check the status of orders but they
aren't overwhelmed with choices.
</P>
<P>
   Dell has also developed hundreds of custom Web pages for its
most valuable corporate customers. These pages display only those
computer configurations that have been preapproved by the
customer's company, and the prices reflect negotiated discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also provides detailed purchasing reports and customized
inventory analyses so managers can use the Web pages to enforce
product standards and increase productivity. Far from pursuing a
self-service strategy, as most people assume, Dell has in fact
shouldered as many of the customer's transaction-related functions
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   You can help your company adopt a coproduction strategy by
taking the following four steps:
</P>
<P>
   First, deconstruct the entire transaction process _ from the
identification of the customer need to order fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Second, distinguish between those functions that are currently
performed by your company and those performed by your customer.
</P>
<P>
   Third, pinpoint which of the customer functions you can take
responsibility for _ establishing the boundaries of your company's
reach into the transaction _ and assess the costs and benefits of
taking on each task.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, find ways to expand your reach beyond a single
transaction to create more value for the customer _ as Charles
Schwab does by issuing e-mail alerts to customers when their stocks
make big moves.
</P>
<P>
   The Web promises not only to reduce corporate transaction costs
but also to enhance customer convenience. To fulfill that promise,
though, companies need to move beyond the self-service myth.
</P>
<P>
   Making it easy and enjoyable for visitors to use your site
through a coproduction strategy will translate into more customers,
greater loyalty and higher profits.
</P>
<P>
   (Youngme Moon and Frances X. Frei are assistant professors at
Harvard Business School in Boston.)
</P>
<P>
