<HEADER>
A0098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0913-CO     09-12 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forever wrapped around Biddy's paw
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Last month the cat took sick. She's wel now,
but I'm scheduled for counseling. The vet recommended it.
</P>
<P>
   My feelings weren't hurt nor was I surprised that Doc had so
quickly diagnosed the secondary problem. After all, he'd done just
fine with the first. Biddy was suffering from a urinary tract
irritation. Antibiotics and a change
</P>
<P>
   of diet cleared that up.
</P>
<P>
   My ailment, on the other hand, is much more complicated. In
fact, I suspect the medication has not yet been discovered that
will prevent a 10-pound ball of fur from reducing an otherwise
stable adult to a babbling psychotic who jumps to every meow.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy's grab for power was not premeditated _ just timely. She
did what any pussycat with an ounce of gumption would do once the
signs were clear that her human was beginning to crumble before her
saucer-size blue eyes. She moved in, took over, and made changes.
Now, we do it all her way.
</P>
<P>
   The transition began a couple of months ago when Biddy
discovered she was capable of raising my anxiety level in direct
proportion to the intensity of her howls, including a few that
registered on the Siamese Richter scale in
</P>
<P>
   Baden-Baden.
</P>
<P>
   In June she had an upset tummy which meant a trip to the vet.
Little she hates worse than being folded into her cardboard cat
house, riding in the car, and odd animal noises _ unless, of
course, it's the clucking of her raccoon
</P>
<P>
   buddy who comes almost nightly to talk through my office screen.
</P>
<P>
   Doc checked her out and prescribed antibiotics and vitamins, and
while my plastic was being swiped through the money slot, the nurse
handed me three bottles and an eyedropper. ``Twice a day,'' she
directed, ``until they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentally, I canceled all plans for the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy recovered rapidly. A lot faster than I did from our
``chase and medicate'' scuffles. She won a few skirmishes, but the
ultimate victory was mine. The cat got well.
</P>
<P>
   In July, since it was obvious Biddy was not going to cooperate
by letting me scrub her teeth with the chicken-flavored toothpaste
Doc gave me, I took her in for a professional job. She came home
sparkling but wobbly, so I moved her quilt-lined basket and water
dish onto the porch, next to the swing where I was working. She got
such a kick out of it that she now demands we spend entire days out
here.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of August, after Biddy's urinary were diagnosed, my
symptoms became even more apparent. With medication and a change of
diet, Biddy was healing on schedule. Meanwhile, my condition was
rapidly deteriorating. That's when she took charge.
</P>
<P>
   Now, before first light, she screams me out of the hammock with
demands to be brushed, fed, and watered. Then she shrieks for an
``attagirl'' because she's been to the basement and used her
sandbox. She yowls at the pantry door for
</P>
<P>
   her Mason jar _ the one filled with catnip and reconstituting
mice.
</P>
<P>
   And so go the days and nights of Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of weeks, this fuzzy martinet has perfected a
variety of verbal directives that she expects to be obeyed _
immediately and absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   Although I have reminded her that I'm only a dumb people and
she'll have to be patient, she's relentless. Our once normal
person-cat relationship has been reduced to a quibbling series of
demands and threats (hers) and groveling (mine).
</P>
<P>
   Although I don't like the direction it has taken, I suspect my
training is almost complete. I'm conditioned to jump at every howl,
and able to detect displeasure in the subtle cant of a velvety
brown ear or the uneven slap of a tail. I've learned that
``Nyeoow!'' means ``at once'' and ``Yikk!'' translates to, ``What
makes you think I'm going to eat that?''
</P>
<P>
   Doc was right. Biddy is doing just fine. Now I'm the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
