<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nickel would be fitting tribute to Reagan's fiscal legacy
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the rare enough occasion that Sen. Phil Gramm is dead-solid
right on something, we should shout it out. Gramm wants a Ronald
Reagan coin.
</P>
<P>
   I say give it to him.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm was talking the other day about how U.S. coins are
``crummy.'' I don't see that. But he chairs the Senate committee in
charge of currency. He wants to design coins.
</P>
<P>
   Again, I can't see any reason for it. They're fine. But as a
constituent, let me say Gramm can do less damage to American
currency this way than, say, by finding new ways for mega-banks to
eat America.
</P>
<P>
   So let him design a coin. I propose a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I think there's anything wrong with today's nickel. Not
at all. Anyone who calls Jefferson's image crummy has picked a
fight with me.
</P>
<P>
   But we can have more than one nickel. We have more than one
dollar and half dollar.
</P>
<P>
   So we can have a Reagan nickel.
</P>
<P>
   What we need is something different, something that reflects
Reagan's contributions to currency.
</P>
<P>
   Principally, what he contributed to currency was debt. And it
was no small debt. It was billions and billions of dollars, much of
it borrowed to pay for a military build-up and tax cuts for the
very rich.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan was a president who spoke of less government and more
budget austerity, though he budgeted more on the military than it
could spend. To compensate, sometimes the Pentagon would spend a
corporal's week's salary on a toilet seat, or more on a hammer than
Dan Quayle could spend on a week of greens fees.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Reagan was tight with some forms of federal
spending. For instance, to save a few pennies and soothe moist
corporate brows, he killed tighter federal regulations on tires.
Those rules were set to take effect after a 1978 recall of 14
million Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Firestone has had to recall 14 million more
tires. Many people have died. So much for the assumption that a
penny saved is earned. Sometimes a penny saved is just a dumb
allocation of pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Reagan talked a good austerity game, his principal
contribution was showing how to borrow one's way to prosperity.
It's no sin. See it on late-night cable infomercials. In the
corporate world of the go-go '80s it became absolutely the thing.
It was leveraging.
</P>
<P>
   Another Reagan contribution was financial deregulation. It was
applauded frantically by savings and loans in 1982. By 1988 a host
of them had loaned out their last nickel and were frantic for
rescue. We found extra currency. We borrowed it.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but it was good debt. In the long run, debt was the best
friend of Reagan and worshipful conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Being no fans of social spending, they knew that as the debt
climbed, government would have to be downsized. Debt made it harder
to justify Rooseveltian impulses. Government as enemy? Truly it a
self-fulfilling condition. And it was Reagan's signature.
</P>
<P>
   Though hardly the inventor of borrow-spend economics, Reagan
took it to new levels. He set government on a course to borrow
trillions of dollars to pay for his prosperity, as he cursed big
spenders.
</P>
<P>
   He could do all this because it wouldn't be his problem. Someone
else would pay it all back.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a Reagan nickel would serve us well. It would remind
us of what we have and what we owe. Instead of ``five cents,'' the
2000 edition could say ``five trillion dollars owed.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be minted in fine balsa wood.
</P>
<P>
   Future generations could carry around those wooden nickels as a
reminder and a receipt. Having a wooden nickel with Reagan's
likeness might inspire Americans to beware of blue-sky fiscal
scams.
</P>
<P>
   I say, give that man a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is Opinion Page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
