<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEY-TALK0913-COX     09-12 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Being in debt is not always a bad thing
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Borrowing money is not always a grimy and unspeakable
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Financial experts acknowledge that some debts _ mortgages or
education loans among them _ are good ones. They help build your
future.
</P>
<P>
   Bad debts are the ones that make you feel good today but mess up
your life for months or years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is in learning to use the one in moderation and the
other not at all.
</P>
<P>
   For 25-year-old Laura Wynn, the dark side included 10 credit
cards and bills for gas, food, clothes and entertainment. There was
also a $1,500 ring, purchased by a long-gone boyfriend. She got to
keep the ring, but she also kept the credit card bill.
</P>
<P>
   Her recollection of that period illuminates an all-too-common
cycle for the unwary: ``I was not making any money at all, but I
was trying to live a nice lifestyle,'' she recalls now. ``I started
getting calls from creditors at home, then at work. I was afraid I
was not going to be able to get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the booming economy, some American families are getting
deep in the hole. Median family debt stood at $33,300 in 1998, up
sharply from $23,400 only three years earlier. That includes
mortgages, credit cards and other kinds of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Debt distress is on the increase, too. The chart shows the
growth in the percentage of families who are late paying their
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Another worrisome trend: In 1989, one of every 10 families
reported that payments gobbled up more than 40 percent of their
incomes. By 1998, one in eight families crossed that threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planners often define bad debt as short-term
obligations that last longer than the item you bought and that have
no financial payback.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card debts are the most common. An additional problem is
that the interest rates are punishing, often 18 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Good debt includes the loans that help build your financial
future. ``Most people cannot buy a home without going into debt,''
said William G. Hammond, a certified financial planner. ``That's
good debt because you're building your equity, your net worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Education loans generally count as good because they tend to
increase earning power.
</P>
<P>
   Small-business loans also are constructive, assuming the
business thrives. ``If you can borrow money at 8 percent and get a
15 or 20 percent return from a business, that's good debt,'' said
Hammond.
</P>
<P>
   The main question with good debt is, how much is enough? The
Financial Planning Association suggests that total debt, not
counting mortgages, should be no higher than 10 percent to 15
percent of take-home pay.
</P>
<P>
   There's a common sense element, too. ``An obligation makes sense
if it fits into your budget and you have clear plans for keeping up
the payments, even if a short-term disruption in income occurs,''
said Suzanne Boas, president of the Consumer Credit Counseling
Service of Greater Atlanta. ``It doesn't make sense if you're just
gambling on future success to repay the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why planners like Hammond advise against borrowing money
to play the booming, alluring stock market. ``It strikes me as
speculative,'' he said. ``That's people who are day-trading, not
long-term investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing to play the market is more common than you might
think. According to the Federal Reserve Board, about one family in
10 has refinanced a first mortgage and put at least a fraction of
the money into investments. In 1998, 3.2 percent of all family debt
was used for investments.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the goal is to shed expensive and
nonproductive debts as quickly as you can. Laura Wynn took four
years to wipe out more than $6,000 she had charged on her 10 credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to quit running up debts. Remember the First
Rule of Holes: When you're in one, stop digging. For many people,
that includes cutting up credit cards or at least locking them away
in some inaccessible place, such as a safe deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to lay out a written plan for paying off your
debts. Some people like to pay off the smallest accounts first, but
the best bet is to start with accounts that charge the highest
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Boas strongly recommends regular checkups on your progress.
``You need to keep working toward your goal and measuring your
successes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also recommends setting up some sort of celebration of your
successes.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers recommend using any savings you might have to pay
off high-interest debt. The rationale is that you'll do better in
the long run by eliminating 18 percent loans than by making a much
smaller rate on a savings account.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond disagrees. ``Should you pay debt or build a cash
reserve?'' he asks. ``The answer is that you need to do both. If
you have never gotten in the habit of saving money, you have to get
into the habit. Even if it takes longer to pay off those credit
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   However long it takes, the rewards are great. Wynn, once a
student at Georgia Perimeter College, had to get a job to pay her
debts. Now she is back in school, finishing a history degree at
Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   In her case, there's a bonus: If she goes for a master's degree,
she can now get a student loan. That puts her on the side of good
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
