<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS-LEE-CASE (San Francisco) _ Asian-American scientists
in the nation's weapons labs express relief at reports that
suspected spy Wen Ho Lee may be freed. But they also vent anger
over what they perceive as government mishandling of the case,
which they blame on racial discrimination. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (San Francisco) _ A special panel appointed
by Mayor Willie Brown says the city's minority contracting program
suffers from a ``perception of inappropriate influence'' and needs
some political separation from the mayoral-appointed commission
that administers it. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   SF-SCHOOLS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's board of education
may have to cut its spending by $9 million this year and $14
million next year to pay for teacher salary hikes. The proposed
cuts, which will be voted on Friday, would be achieved through
massive reductions in central office staff, deferred maintenance of
school buildings, reorganization of staff and decreases in
overtime. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-COURT (San Francisco) _ The first ripples of the U.S.
Supreme Court's new ruling on sentencing have washed away five
years of a Northern California man's 10-year marijuana sentence.
The high court's June 26 ruling required juries, rather than
judges, to decide facts that increase a sentence beyond the maximum
term for the crime itself. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
here decided that the ruling also requires a determination of the
amount of drugs involved in a crime. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   LEADED-GAS (San Francisco) ) Leaded gasoline, phased out over
past decades, will continue washing into the San Francisco Bay for
50 to 100 years, according to scientists at the University of
California at Santa Cruz. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TOYOTA-PRIUS (San Antonio) _ Unlike traditional gasoline
engine cars, the Toyota Prius gets better fuel economy in town
because at speeds less than 30 mph, it operates almost exclusively
on its 44-horsepower electric motor. At speeds above that, or when
it needs to recharge its batteries, the 70-horsepower, 1.5-liter
gasoline engine kicks in automatically. Even though it's a green
machine, this car has as much zip as any other compact sedan on the
road. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-OLDER-BUYERS (Undated) _ The general wisdom for years has
been that women and minorities pay more for new cars than other
consumers. But a new study by automotive marketing specialists at
Virginia Commonwealth University debunks that notion. Older people,
the study says, are the only paying more when it comes to car
shopping. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-GM-LESABRE (Undated) _ Now is as good a time as any to buy
a Buick, especially if you can afford the $31,000-plus price of the
2001 LeSabre Limited Sedan. Besides giving its occupants a fine
ride in stylish surroundings without gratuitous luxury trappings,
this car is downright fun to drive. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-PACKARD (San Francisco) _ Computer manufacturer
Hewlett-Packard, based in Palo Alto, Calif., says it is in
discussions to purchase the management and information technology
consulting unit of PricewaterhouseCoopers, the New York accounting
and consulting giant. By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-PRICES (San Francisco) _ Stock options, bonuses and initial
public offerings of high-tech company stocks have helped boost San
Francisco Bay Area home prices, according to an economic study by
the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco. By RICHARD PAOLI.
</P>
</TEXT>
