<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-PACKARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     H-P CONSIDERS BUYING PART OF ACCOUNTING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Computer and printer manufacturer
Hewlett-Packard Co. is in discussions to buy the management and
information technology consulting unit of PricewaterhouseCoopers,
the New York accounting and consulting giant.
</P>
<P>
   A statement released Monday by Hewlett-Packard said a cash and
stock deal for $17 billion to $18 billion is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   David Nester, a spokesman for PricewaterhouseCoopers, confirmed
the talks but declined to provide specifics. The management and
technology consulting firm has about 30,000 employees worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would give Palo Alto-based Hewlett-Packard a
weapon in the increasingly important fight for the consulting and
software business that hardware manufacturers have been entering in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   With IBM the market leader, this business is seen as one avenue
for long-term growth at a time when sales of computers and systems
are tapering off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the hardware business versus the software
business and the servicing portions of the business in the
information technology arena, the better long-term growth is in
software services,'' said Wendy I. Abramowitz, an analyst with
Argus Research in New York. ``That's where a lot of old-line
hardware companies are looking to expand their focus. As
Hewlett-Packard is thinking of doing this, it sounds reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if consummated, would be Hewlett-Packard's first major
acquisition since new chief executive Carly Fiorina joined the
company last year. The company said it has been strengthening its
professional services abilities to come up with ways to help
clients use technology more to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would free PricewaterhouseCoopers of a regulatory
entanglement that began earlier this year when the Securities and
Exchange Commission, concerned about the potential for conflicts of
interest, began cracking down on the close relationships between
accounting firms' auditing and consulting divisions.
</P>
<P>
   In June the SEC proposed a ban on companies' providing
consulting services on a client's computer systems while auditing
the same client.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
