<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-LEADED-GAS-HNS &LR;      09-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEADED-GAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SAYS LEADED GASOLINE STILL AFFLICTS SAN FRANCISCO BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Leaded gasoline, phased out over past decades,
will continue washing into the San Francisco Bay for 50 to 100
years, scientists at the University of California at Santa Cruz
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-knock tetraethyl lead that was added to gas-guzzling
cars of the 1960s polluted the air and eventually found its way
into the water supply. It is still found in the Sacramento and San
Joaquin rivers, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year study was published in Tuesday's issue of the
Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped putting lead into gasoline over a decade ago,''
said Russell Flegal, an author of the study and professor of
environmental toxicology at UC-Santa Cruz. ``Yet, our study
indicates it's going to be a very, very long time before the lead
gets flushed out of the Central Valley into the Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Lead, a naturally occurring element in trace amounts, can cause
severe health effects even at low concentrations. Nervous,
reproductive and blood-producing systems are particularly
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay contains less lead than drinking water, not enough to
threaten anyone's health, the scientists said. They do not believe
there is any harm in eating fish from the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The study attributes the stubborn presence of lead to the large
volume that fell as air pollution in California's Central Valley
and the San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers estimated that cars burning leaded gas emitted
33,000 tons of lead in the drainage basins of the San Joaquin and
Sacramento rivers in the 1960s and 1970s, when the federal
government started phasing out leaded gas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 80 percent of the lead in the northern and central
portions of the Bay comes from the combustion of leaded gas during
that time. About 20 percent comes from the effects of hydraulic
gold mining during the 19th-century Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern end of the Bay, about 90 percent comes from
leaded gas, and 10 percent comes from the gold mining.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the phase-out of leaded gas began, only a
relatively small amount was sold in California. The state stopped
selling the fuel in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   However, the decline of lead in the San Francisco estuary has
been remarkably slow, while lead levels have fallen in urban air,
on the surface of oceans, in polar ice and snow and even in human
blood, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, only 1 to 10 percent of the lead emitted to the river
basins during the late 1980s and early 1990s had moved from the
rivers to the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Once contaminants are in the Bay, they stay there for a long
time. Eventually, the lead sediments move very slowly over years
out the Golden Gate Bridge to the ocean, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the natural flow of fresh water from rivers to the
ocean during rainy seasons and snow melts helped to flush out the
contaminants, but over the past decades, the damming and diversion
of water by agriculture, cities and industries have reduced that
flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study shows there is a link between Bay circulation and
the ability of the Bay to clean itself,'' said geochemist Douglas
J. Steding, lead author and doctoral candidate in the Earth
Sciences Department at the University of California at Davis. ``The
only way that the Bay can clean itself is if clean sediments come
into the Bay from the rivers, and we've yet to see that in the case
of lead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
