<P>
   MILITARY-STRATEGY _ The Clinton administration's national
security strategy, bitterly scorned by GOP presidential candidate
George W. Bush and his running mate Dick Cheney, was in fact
designed by Cheney as defense secretary in 1992 and enjoys broad
bipartisan support. Photo. About 1,200
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-CRISIS _ Experts say the sudden specter of an energy
crisis lurks in the worldwide reliance on Middle East oil, raising
the likelihood that sharp price increases will spike America's
economic expansion and revive consumer nightmares of heating oil
and natural gas shortages this winter. Graphic. About 1,100
</P>
<P>
   DRUGFIRM-CAMPAIGN _ Pharmaceutical companies have been targeting
most of their campaign donations to the Republicans since 1994,
when President Clinton began pushing for universal health care. So
far this election cycle, drug companies have given about $7.5
million to GOP congressional candidates and about $2.6 million to
Democrats. Graphics. About 1,500
</P>
<P>
   SUBLIMINAL-ADS _ At least one person isn't surprised in the
least by a Republican TV commercial that appears to highlight the
word ``rats'' in a message attacking Al Gore's prescription drugs
plan: Wilson Bryan Key, the communications professor who in 1973
coined the term ``subliminal seduction'' and who now says the GOP
ad ``should be quite effective.'' About 600
</P>
