<SLUG> BC-AUTO-GM-LESABRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUICK TAKES A STAB AT BOOMERS WITH NEW LeSABRE  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now is as good a time as any to buy a Buick, especially if you
can afford the $31,000-plus price of the 2001 LeSabre Limited
Sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Wow! This is a really nice car.
</P>
<P>
   I've never really been into large, cushy cars, having long ago
associated most of them with older folks who put more emphasis on a
smooth, soft ride than on crisp performance or exciting
acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   But my tastes are changing, or else General Motors is starting
to make big, comfortable cars that appeal to me. I believe it's a
combination of the two, and that just like other aging baby
boomers, I'm getting to where I'm going to enjoy some of the finer
things in life.
</P>
<P>
   The LeSabre, though, doesn't force me to compromise, trading
performance for comfort. That's what's so marvelous about Buick's
best-selling car: It encompasses the best of both worlds. Besides
giving its occupants a fine ride in stylish surroundings without
gratuitous luxury trappings, it's downright fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the LeSabre was completely redesigned, coming on a
whole new chassis platform with performance refinements throughout.
Interior and exterior designs are new, although the exterior does
still look much like that of the previous LeSabre generation.
</P>
<P>
   That was clearly a concession to the car's existing owner body.
As Buick's best seller for at least the past decade, the full-size
LeSabre has one of the most loyal followings in the car industry.
</P>
<P>
   More than a million of these cars have been sold in the past 10
years, but the average age of buyers has been 66, something that
Buick and General Motors corporate marketing strategists know has
to change if the Buick brand is going to remain viable.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers, it seems, just haven't been jumping into Buicks
the way their parents did, and even now that boomers are aging,
many still seem to prefer the imports that sell for about the same
as the LeSabre _ such as the Toyota Camry, Lexus ES 300, Honda
Accord, Toyota Avalon and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Buick has high hopes that this new LeSabre will combine the best
of two centuries and two worlds: the attributes of the previous
LeSabre that attracted the post-60 crowd, and enough new and
slightly daring changes to endear this car to the now-graying kids
of current and past LeSabre owners.
</P>
<P>
   GM marketers probably would have let out a collective groan to
hear my significant other's initial assessment of the new LeSabre
as ``my parents' kind of car,'' but unfortunately, that's the
stigma the car has to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   It still is a big, comfortable family car that seats up to six
adults in relative comfort, cruises over bumps and potholes with
the grace one would expect of a Buick, and moves along at a crisp
rate of speed when the gas pedal is goosed.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some styling cues designed to appeal to the
younger set without turning off older folks who are considering
trading in their current LeSabres for a new one. Gone is the
boring, straight, '70s-era dashboard and instrument panel, replaced
by a curved dash and cockpit-style instrument cluster that are
clearly reminiscent of some other modern GM cars aimed at the baby
boomer such as the outstanding Oldsmobile Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   The designers dispensed with the gratuitous chrome exterior trim
that was as passe as disco dancing, replacing it with flush door
handles, body-color trim and curvaceous lines that make the LeSabre
a lot more stylish in an understated kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the car should continue to appeal to older consumers.
Buick says it couldn't afford to lose the current owners _ 53
percent of whom come back for another LeSabre when they need a new
car.
</P>
<P>
   The danger here was in making a new model so radically different
that current owners would be repulsed before a new crop of buyers
had been cultivated. Buick had been selling 150,000 of these cars a
year, making it the nation's best-selling full-size car, and it
would have been bad business to abandon those loyal buyers on the
gamble that a younger clientele would develop a taste for the
LeSabre.
</P>
<P>
   Ford made that mistake with its radical redesign of the midsize
Taurus in 1996; the once best-selling U.S. car has never regained
its former stature, and Ford has already redesigned it to tone down
its outrageous styling.
</P>
<P>
   So what would appeal to boomers in the LeSabre besides the
subtle but modern new styling? Among other things, Buick is banking
on the much-improved ride and handling, a Limited model with bucket
seats up front, sun roof, 12-disc CD changer, and such safety
features as active front head restraints, side air bags for the
front passengers, and four-wheel disc antilock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy just might work if Buick can persuade these
consumers that what they really need instead of that sport utility
vehicle they've been lusting over is a big, roomy and comfortable
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem standalone Buick dealers have with that
strategy is there is no big, fancy SUV in the showroom to lure
those customers. That will change next year, however, when Buick
introduces its first sport utility, the impressive all-new
Rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the new LeSabre comes in two styles: the base
Custom, with bench seating for six and prices starting about
$23,000, and the Limited, which comes with front bucket seats and a
rear bench, carries a base price of $27,885 (plus transportation),
and with bucket seats up front. I liked the console between the two
front seats in the Limited, something that older buyers may not
particularly appreciate, but young buyers will demand.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is GM's smooth 3.8-liter V-6, with 205 horsepower and
230 foot-pounds of torque. It is connected to a smooth-shifting
four-speed automatic transmission, and does an admirable job of
pushing the LeSabre along at highway speeds and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is firmer than before, and steering response is much
improved, making the LeSabre feel sportier and less like a big,
floaty boat. It's still no sports car, but boomers will appreciate
the handling improvements, and repeat buyers probably won't notice
that the ride isn't quite as soft as before.
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment on the Custom includes air conditioning,
AM/FM radio, power windows/mirrors/door locks, keyless remote
entry, tilt steering wheel, cruise control, map lights,
intermittent windshield wipers and a security system.
</P>
<P>
   Limited models come with dual-zone climate control,
air-filtration system, dark walnut trim, a driver-information
center, power front seats, a premium stereo system with cassette
deck, and 15-inch aluminum wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car came with the ``prestige option package'' ($615),
which added auto-dimming inside mirror with compass, upgraded audio
system with compact-disc and cassette decks, moisture-sensing
windshield wipers, traction control, universal garage-door opener
and power reclining front seats; Medici red leather/vinyl seats
($750); the ``driver's confidence package'' ($730) that included a
heads-up speedometer display and active brake control; the ``grand
touring package'' ($235), which added 3.05 axle ratio, touring
suspension, blackwall 16-inch tires, leather-wrapped steering wheel
and variable-assist power steering; and memory driver's seat and
outside mirrors ($145).
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker was $31,015, including $655 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is a respectable 19 miles per gallon in the city
and 30 on the highway, making the LeSabre an excellent touring car.
The tank holds 18.5 gallons of gasoline, and unleaded premium is
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
