<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-MINNIE-DRIVER-IN-BEAU     09-12 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINNIE-DRIVER-IN-BEAUTIFUL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOROUGHLY MOUSE-LESS MINNIE: MINNIE DRIVER ON LIFE, LOVE AND THE
MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color photo of Minnie Driver in a scene from
``Beautiful.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN 
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    Her name may be Minnie, but Minnie Driver is anything but
mouselike. Seemingly an island of togetherness in a sea of
Hollywood neurosis, she handles whatever comes her way, even if
it's a little ... well, weird.
 &HT;    Like the autograph hounds who accosted her recently in Los
Angeles, shouting ``We just love your work, Janeane!'''
 &HT;    Janeane?
 &HT;    ``People think I'm Janeane Garofalo a lot,'' Driver says with a
shrug. ``I don't know what it is. Maybe we're both quirky-looking
girls.''
 &HT;    Quirky enough that she apparently even looks like herself.
 &HT;    ``The other day, I got, `Oh, you look an awful lot like Minnie
Driver,''' she recalls. ``So in a most humorous way I said, `Oh,
thank you. I hear she's a great actress.'
 &HT;    ``The other person said, `Nah, I didn't like that last movie she
was in _ it was a piece of junk!'''
 &HT;    Driver sighs, and turns her attention to breakfast at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel, where the tall, thin actress with the
mass of dark curls has come to talk about her latest film,
``Beautiful,'' opening nationwide on Sept. 22.
 &HT;    In the film, directed by Sally Field, Driver _ whose looks are
often described as ``quirky'' or ``unconventional,'' though by the
standards of anywhere but Hollywood she's a knockout _ plays a
young woman who is obsessed with beauty pageants.
 &HT;    The 29-year-old actress plays the character starting at age 18.
 &HT;    ``Believe me, that was a rough one,'' she says, laughing. ``I
gave the cameraman some gauze to put over the lens.''
 &HT;    Driver isn't a pageant buff, and had to learn a lot about it in
a hurry.
 &HT;    ``Those girls who compete in these beauty shows have it rough,''
the actress says. ``The competition is cutthroat, and you have to
learn all the tricks.''
 &HT;    Those tricks can be astoundingly detailed, she adds.
 &HT;    ``It always helps if you spray your bum with water before
putting on tights, so your butt is lifted,'' she says. ``You also
need to grease your teeth with Vasoline for that perfect wide
smile.''
 &HT;    Field, who is making her feature debut as a director, obviously
knows the other side of the camera intimately: She's a two-time
Oscar-winning actress, and brought that to her work on
``Beautiful.''
 &HT;    ``Sally was an amazing director,'' Driver says. ``She knows
exactly what you need to be in the moment as an actress, because
she is one of the best actresses to ever grace the screen. I could
tell by just looking at Sally for a nanosecond if she was pleased
with what I was doing.''
 &HT;    The idea of Driver anxiously seeking reassurance may surprise
those who know her public persona as a poised, self-confident Brit
who navigates Hollywood with no anxieties and the stiffest of upper
lips.
 &HT;    ``For some reason people don't think I have a care in the world,
which is not true,'' Driver says. ``People think I lead some
charmed existence, and I can't believe it. My life is not perfect.
There's always something inside that's troubling.
 &HT;    ``I'm just like you,'' she continues. ``Everybody has got some
worries. But as young actresses, we're packaged to keep people
coming to movies. We're molded to make other people want to be like
us or be us. It's just the fantasy of Hollywood.''
 &HT;    The child of divorced parents, Driver grew up in London with her
mother, a model and writer. She also spent time with her father, a
financial adviser who lived in the Caribbean. It was while
attending boarding school that she first found herself onstage.
 &HT;    ``I always loved writing,'' she recalls. ``That was so much a
reason of why I acted. I started out writing, and I was so
encouraged to create and use my imagination. My English teachers at
school inspired me to be so creative and free.''
 &HT;    Driver's big break came with the charming English drama ``Circle
of Friends'' (1995), in which she played the overweight Benny
opposite a young, handsome Chris O'Donnell. Among her later credits
are ``Good Will Hunting'' (1997), ``Hard Rain'' (1998) and ``Grosse
Pointe Blank'' (1997). Her most recent outing was opposite David
Duchovny in ``Return to Me'' (1999).
 &HT;    She's usually cast as smart, intense women who defy convention _
which, according to those who work with her, is pretty much
typecasting.
 &HT;    ``If you need a dumb actress to play a dumb part, that's really,
really sad,'' Driver says. ``Just don't call me.''
 &HT;    On the set she's quick to offer her opinion, whether or not it's
been asked for.
 &HT;    ``That's definitely true,'' Driver says. ``I don't feel like
there is anything at all that can't be said on a set. I don't think
one needs to defend herself for making a movie better.
 &HT;    ``People should know what you think,'' the actress adds. ``I'm
not the type of person who allows herself to blow in the wind while
others wonder what I'm thinking. This way when I'm old, I will have
no regrets.''
 &HT;    That applies to her love life as well, which has featured
several of the most eligible young men in Hollywood, including Matt
Damon, John Cusack and, for the past two years, Josh Brolin. She's
been portrayed as unlucky in love, but she won't have any sympathy.
 &HT;    ``With love there are so many permutations of it,'' she muses.
``I don't think there is any equation out there that explains it.
It's varied and completely unpredictable. It's a force of nature.
 &HT;    ``I also believe in timing,'' she adds thoughtfully. ``I don't
believe in there being just one person out there who is perfect for
you. I think there might be many people, who you may have even been
with, but you simply were not ready. Or they were not ready to be
with you.
 &HT;    ``I think a lot of forces have to align for us to recognize love
and accept it into our lives.''
 &HT;    It's particularly hard if, as was the case with her breakup with
Damon, the whole country is watching it happen.
 &HT;    ``Fame is a big drag,'' Driver says with a sigh. ``It totally
goes with the territory. Every actor with a burgeoning career in
Hollywood should go read `Faust.' It's true. It's the most
brilliant parable _ there is a pact that is made. It's part of the
deal.
 &HT;    ``You can whine about it until you're blue in the face,'' she
says, ``but you keep showing up at the premieres and wearing the
nice dresses. The light bulbs pop in your face because you put
yourself in that position. At times you feel very lucky. At other
times the whole situations seems unfortunate, if all you want to do
is act and not deal with the hoopla.''
 &HT;    She may be candid in her opinions, but Driver makes clear that
she won't be sharing any details about her life with Brolin or
about her possible future mother-in-law, Barbra Streisand. Like
many of the actors she most admires, she wants to keep her private
life private.
 &HT;    ``How much do you really know about Harrison Ford? How much do
you know about Jodie Foster?'' she says. ``How much do you really
know about Meryl Streep or Robert De Niro? That gives me hope that
you can keep a tiny part of your life for yourself.
 &HT;    ``I know people are interested in my private life, which is
flattering,'' she says. ``But if I keep my mouth shut, five minutes
will go by and we will be on to the next thing.''
 &HT;    As to her future, Driver has some new areas of interest.
 &HT;    ``One day I would like to write a script,'' she says, ``or maybe
even direct. I just need to find the discipline I found in acting
with these forms.''
 &HT;    Until then, however, she plans to keep acting and try to keep a
level head _ if only to keep her fellow Brits satisfied.
 &HT;    ``Over there they accuse me of being lost to Hollywood,'' Driver
says, rolling her eyes. ``I recently did a talk show and people
realized, `Oh, she's the same old Minnie.'''
 &HT;    c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Beautiful,'' consult the
official Web site at www.beautifulthemovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
