<HEADER>
A0295 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GENE-HACKMAN-IN-UNDER     09-12 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-HACKMAN-IN-UNDER-SUSPICION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAY EMINENCES: GENE HACKMAN FENCES WITH MORGAN FREEMAN IN `UNDER
SUSPICION'
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color photo of Gene Hackman with Monica Bellucci in a
scene from ``Under Suspicion.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    Actors come and go in Hollywood.
 &HT;    Some burn brightly for a while and then fade away. Others never
quite make it, but survive on the fringes as supporting players.
It's the way of the world.
 &HT;    And then there are those rare few who defy the rules, who attain
a measure of stardom as character actors/leading men and stick
around seemingly forever. Gene Hackman is one such actor, and his
longevity in this eat-them-up-and-spit-them-out industry surprises
no one more than Hackman himself.
 &HT;    ``It especially crosses my mind when I have to go to see a film
I'm in,'' he says. ``I look at who that person is and I think, `My
God, why would anyone pay to see me?'
 &HT;    ``I also recognize the fact that I'm not objective at all about
my work, about watching my work,'' Hackman says. ``I can be very
objective about my work when I'm doing it, I think. At least I know
if it works or not when I'm doing it.
 &HT;    ``Once I get away from that and I'm looking at an image on the
screen, that's somebody else _ it's my great-grandfather.''
 &HT;    At 69, Hackman remains one of Hollywood's busiest and most
versatile actors. In the past couple of years alone, he has
appeared in the thriller ``Enemy of the People'' (1998), the
private-eye drama ``Twilight'' (1998) and the current football
comedy ``The Replacements,'' as well as ``Under Suspicion,'' set to
open in limited release on Sept. 22.
 &HT;    ``When I choose a film I don't choose it in terms of quality, I
choose it in terms of story,'' he says cryptically. ``There may be
a contradiction there.''
 &HT;    Hackman, sitting in a conference room at New York's Essex House,
smiles and shrugs.
 &HT;    ``If you have a strong enough sense of story about yourself and
your character, then the quality will take care of itself,'' he
says. ``Something will come out of that, because you've done it
strongly enough and honestly enough.''
 &HT;    There may be a contradiction there, too, but it helps explain
why Hackman committed to ``Under Suspicion.'' A remake of the
French drama ``Garde A'Vue,'' it casts Hackman as Henry Hearst, a
prominent tax attorney, and Morgan Freeman, Hackman's co-star in
``Unforgiven'' (1992), as Victor Benezet, captain of the police
department on the Caribbean island where both men live.
 &HT;    Benezet at first chats amiably about a high-profile murder case,
then zeros in on Hearst as the prime suspect. Over the course of a
single night the two men engage in a wily game of bluffs and
attacks, with Hearst's comely, much younger wife (Monica Pellucid)
and Benezet's overzealous underling (Thomas Jane) serving as vital
pawns.
 &HT;    ``I loved the origina French film,'' says Hackman, who joined
Freeman as co-executive producers of the remake. ``I saw it with my
daughter almost 17 years ago. It was not a success in the United
States, but it was a huge hit in France.
 &HT;    ``I liked the idea of playing (Hearst),'' the actor says. ``He's
different from other roles I've played. He's a very successful guy,
but you wouldn't necessarily want him as your best friend, because
of his vanity and whatever else. The hairpiece falling off and all
of that was fun to play.''
 &HT;    Hackman describes ``Under Suspicion'' as being about prejudice,
but not in the sense that Hearst is white and Benezet is black.
 &HT;    ``It has to do with prejudice in terms of one's perception of
who people are and how we make mistakes in terms of being too quick
to judge merely because of lifestyles and money,'' he says, rubbing
at his scruffy gray beard. ``I liked that idea.''
 &HT;    Hackman, however, did not particularly enjoy producing the film.
In general, he says, he finds that splitting his focus detracts
from his performance. Moreover, it took years to get ``Under
Suspicion'' off the ground.
 &HT;    ``I was so tired of being turned down by a variety of people,
both actors and producers,'' Hackman says with a pained grimace.
``I still believed in the film, but I didn't think I could go on
with it after so long. I gave it to Morgan, and it took him two
years to find money, and he had a production company in place. He
found the money to do it, and it's a very low-budget film.
 &HT;    ``Morgan is a pro,'' Hackman says warmly. ``He's always
prepared, always knows what he's doing, but not in a rigid way.
He's able to shift.''
 &HT;    Hackman, too, can shift, as he's proven through the years by
amassing such credits as ``Bonnie and Clyde'' (1967), ``The French
Connection'' (1971), ``Night Moves'' (1975), ``Superman'' (1978),
``The Firm'' (1993), ``Crimson Tide'' (1995) and ``The Birdcage''
(1996), as well as his more recent films.
 &HT;    A five-time Oscar nominee, Hackman took home statuettes as Best
Actor for ``The French Connection'' and Best Supporting Actor for
``Unforgiven,'' but considers ``Scarecrow'' (1973) and ``The
Conversation'' (1974) his most underrated films.
 &HT;    By now, one might think, acting comes easy for Hackman, but he
insists that such is not the case.
 &HT;    ``In a funny way, it's harder,'' he says. ``I realize how much
I've left out, things I wish I hadn't done. So I'm more tormented
by acting, but I still love it.
 &HT;    ``In some ways I'm too quick to a shorthand, and yet I probably
work harder now than I ever have on each film,'' he adds. ``That's
probably because I realize that there are only a limited number of
films I have left in me, and I want to make them the best I can.''
 &HT;    Hackman is currently shooting ``The Heist,'' a caper film
written and directed by playwright David Mamet, and then will move
on to a military drama entitled ``Behind Enemy Lines.'' Already in
the can and awaiting release is ``Breakers,'' a comedy with
Sigourney Weaver and Jennifer Love Hewitt as mother-and-daughter
grifters.
 &HT;    ``I play an 80-year-old billionaire tobacco tycoon,'' Hackman
says. ``I constantly have a cigarette in my mouth. I'm always
coughing and blowing off billows of smoke.
 &HT;    ``It was great fun,'' he says, chuckling. ``I probably went too
far with it.''
 &HT;    Actors who feel time slipping away often covet a ``King
Lear''-like part that will send them out on a high note. Hackman,
again going against the grain, feels no such compulsion.
 &HT;    ``My career is diverse enough that it would be fine if it
continued as it is now,'' says the actor, who lives in Santa Fe,
N.M., with his family and recently wrote his first novel, ``Wake of
the Perdido Star'' (Newmarket Press, 1999), with Daniel Lenihan.
``I like taking what's offered to me, as opposed to going out and
trying to develop something I think I'll be terrific in.
 &HT;    ``Many times you can find out what people think about you by
what's offered to you,'' he says. ``I'm being offered pretty much
the same kinds of roles I've always been offered, just with a
little more gray in them.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Under Suspicion,'' consult the
official Web site at www.undersuspicion.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
