<HEADER>
A0297 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-RAPPER-DR-DRE-STARBEA     09-12 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPPER-DR-DRE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. DRE: THE DOCTOR IS (WAY) OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of rapper Dr. Dre.) 
 By GARY GRAFF 
 c.2000 Gary Graff 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    He came. He saw. He conquered.
 &HT;    And, most important, Dr. Dre did not go ``Up in Smoke,'' as his
critics had warned he would, when he took his gangsta-rap tour of
that name on the road during the past summer.
 &HT;    In fact, Dre _ a gangsta-rap pioneer with the group N.W.A. and
the producer of multiplatinum artists such as Eminem and Snoop Dogg
_ found himself helming one of the year's box-office hits.
Ostensibly launched to promote Dre's second solo album, the
five-times-platinum ``Dr. Dre 2000,'' ``Up in Smoke'' played to
521,000 fans in racially mixed crowds and grossed more than $24
million during its 45-date run, making it one of the most
successful hip-hop tours ever.
 &HT;    There were also no major incidents of lawlessness or misconduct
at any of the shows, which also featured Eminem, Ice Cube and
Warren G, among others. Only a move by the Detroit city government
to ban the violent, sexually explicit videos used during Dre and
Snoop's sets _ a ban currently the subject of a civil-rights
lawsuit filed against the city by Dre _ marred the otherwise smooth
concert run.
 &HT;    And Dre doesn't mind basking in the satisfaction of having
proved the naysayers wrong while also providing a very in-your-face
reminder of hip-hop's appeal.
 &HT;    ``It's real simple _ the music is hot,'' says the 35-year-old
Dre, who was born Andre Young in Compton, Calif. ``And it's
interesting. The stuff we're doing right now is different than
anything anybody else is doing. And I think when it's good, no
matter who you are or where you're from or what color you are,
you're going to get into it.
 &HT;    ``Everybody enjoys this music, no matter what the critics are
saying or anything like that,'' he says. ``And it's getting bigger
and bigger every year. I think it's going to be even bigger than it
is right now _ I think, in the years to come, you're going to be
able to see hip-hop shows played in stadiums.''
 &HT;    The tour wasn't without its share of controversy, though the
concerts themselves weren't disrupted. Prior to the tour's mid-June
start, Eminem faced gun and assault charges in two separate
suburban Detroit municipalities. Free on bond, he's slated to go to
trial during the early fall. Meanwhile, his wife attempted suicide
while the tour was in Detroit, and the couple subsequently decided
to divorce.
 &HT;    As if that weren't enough, a member of Snoop Dogg's entourage
received a misdemeanor citation for possession of marijuana during
a routine border stop after the tour's first date in San Diego, and
Nate Dogg was arrested on charges of kidnapping, making terrorist
threats, domestic violence and arson. He's free on $1 million bail.
 &HT;    So the shadow of gangsta rap's violent reputation hung over the
tour like a cloud of the chronic smoke that's celebrated in many of
the performer's songs. But Dre says that the performances eclipsed
any side issues.
 &HT;    ``I wanted it to stay high-energy,'' he says. ``I wanted people
to not want to take their eyes off the stage because they might
miss something.''
 &HT;    Dre says the morale on the tour remained high, despite the
numerous distractions. Many of the acts record for his
Aftermath/Interscope label, he notes, and he's worked on all of
their albums, which made camaraderie easier to come by.
 &HT;    ``This was the perfect tour with the perfect people,'' he says,
``and everybody was family on this. Everybody was helping out with
each other's problems, even. It's just a lot of fun.''
 &HT;    Dre _ who has a criminal record of his own _ has also tried to
offer an offstage hand to Eminem, whose second album, ``The
Marshall Mathers LP,'' had a six-week run at No. 1 during the late
spring.
 &HT;    ``I've just told him about the things that I went through and
had to deal with,'' says Dre, who lives with his wife and six
children in California's San Fernando Valley. ``It's really not
worth it _ for the couple of minutes it took you to get in trouble,
you could spend the rest of your life trying to get out of it. It
took me years upon years to get out of the few incidents that I
had.
 &HT;    ``So I just tried to tell him, and he definitely understands,''
Dre says. ``I think he's on the right path now. We're in the
position right now where we can not only build for ourselves, but
build for generations to come. We're in a position to make a lot of
money and leave something here for our kids and their kids.
 &HT;    ``Why f--k it up over some nonsense?''
 &HT;    With ``Up in Smoke'' in the history books _ although a European
tour is possible, as is a live album or home video _ Dre is
focusing on making new music. He's working with a number of acts,
including younger rappers such as Xzibit and Hitman, as well as an
R&AMP;B singer dubbed Truth Hurts, all of whom are recording albums.
 &HT;    But the most exciting prospect, he says, is a reunion of N.W.A.,
the controversial rap group that broke up during the early 1990s
after three platinum albums. Most of the group got back together to
close the ``Up in Smoke'' shows, however, with Snoop Dogg standing
in for the late Eazy-E.
 &HT;    Dre says a new album is indeed in the offing. The group members
are working on new material on the road, and will bring in the
group's fifth member, DJ Yella, when the tour ends later this year.
And while past opponents may not be cheering N.W.A.'s return, Dre
figures that in a mainstream market that's embraced hip-hop as a
commercial force, it should be viewed as a major musical event.
 &HT;    ``There's a few things written,'' Dre says. ``We've all sat
around already and tried to draw up a few blueprints for songs. We
have some ideas _ I have a few ideas for tracks, Cube has a few
ideas for songs and we're just going to get in there and mix it up
and see what happens. We have an idea that we really want to work
with Rage Against the Machine on. We would love to tour with those
guys.
 &HT;    ``We're definitely going to keep our edge,'' Dre says. ``We're
definitely going to come out and say a few shocking things. We plan
to say a couple of things that'll make Eminem raise an eyebrow or
two. I think we can do it.''
 &HT;    The rapper/producer adds that the ``Up in Smoke'' tour has also
inspired him to make new music for himself. If all goes well, a
successor to ``Dr. Dre 2000'' ought to take less than the seven
years it took Dre to follow up his solo debut, ``The Chronic.''
 &HT;    ``Before I came out here on the road, I had in my mind I was
never going to do another solo album,'' he says. ``Now I'm thinking
about it. Being here has motivated me enough to make me want to go
back in the studio.''
 &HT;    But if he does come out with another Dre album, he promises it
will be markedly different than its predecessors.
 &HT;    ``I can't come back with `The Chronic 3' or something like
that,'' Dre says. ``It'll definitely be something totally
different. I have an idea what I want to do. It's going to be a
concept album _ I like to say the music will sound like a mixture
between Kraftwerk and George Clinton.
 &HT;    ``Now, that will be pretty wild.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Dr. Dre 2000,'' consult the
official Web site at www.dre2001.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
