<HEADER>
A0298 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-FALL-TELEVISION-PREVI     09-12 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-TELEVISION-PREVIEW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TUBULAR: A PREVIEW OF FALL'S TOP TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color photo of Geena Davis in a scene from ``The Geena
Davis Show.'') 
 By THE STAFF OF TV GUIDE CANADA 
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    Fall is upon us, and with it the arrival of the latest
television shows _ one or two, perhaps, destined for pop-cultural
immortality, another handful for a run of several years and the
rest for the dustheap of television history.
 &HT;    Here's our predictions, admittedly highly subjective, of which
might end up in which pile. 
 -0- 
 BETTE (CBS)  
 &HT;    Premise: The Divine Miss M takes her larger-than-life persona to
the small screen in a self-parodic orgy co-starring Kevin Dunn as
her husband Roy, Lindsay Lohan as their teen-age daughter and
Joanna Gleason as Midler's manager.
 &HT;    Assets: Midler herself, of course, and an outstanding supporting
cast.
 &HT;    Liabilities: Some worry that the diva act will get on some
viewers' nerves.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: An eagerly anticipated powerhouse that looks likely
to deliver on its promise. 
 -0- 
 BOSTON PUBLIC (Fox)  
 &HT;    Premise: At a suburban high school, teachers _ including Fyvush
Finkel of ``Picket Fences'' _ struggle to help shape the futures of
their pupils.
 &HT;    Assets: Producer David E. Kelley, who created ``Chicago Hope,''
``The Practice,'' ``Picket Fences'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' has an
impressive batting average.
 &HT;    Liabilities: Kelley also created last season's ``Snoops.''
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Kelley seems to be aiming for the earnest timber of
``The Practice'' instead of the kookiness of ``Ally'' or
``Snoops.'' Good choice. 
 -0- 
 DARK ANGEL (Fox)  
 &HT;    Premise: James Cameron's television original casts Jessica Alba
as a genetically enhanced fugitive in a dark, near-future America,
aided by idealistic journalist Logan Cale (Michael Weatherly) and
pursued by the mysterious Lydecker (John Savage).
 &HT;    Assets: Alba should become a major breakout star, along the
lines of Sarah Michelle Gellar and Katie Holmes. The show itself is
sharp and well-crafted.
 &HT;    Liabilities: ``Dark Angel'' is scheduled against ``Angel,''
which attracts the same audience, as well as ``Frasier,'' ``Dharma
&AMP; Greg'' and ``The Drew Carey Show.''
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Cameron knows science fiction _ he made ``Aliens''
(1986) and the ``Terminator'' movies _ but this is a dark, complex
story that may be a hard sell. 
 -0- 
 ED (NBC)  
 &HT;    Premise: Ed Stevens (Tom Cavanagh) loses his job and his wife on
the same day, and decides to move back to his hometown.
 &HT;    Assets: Ed has the small-town magic of ``Northern Exposure,''
while Cavanagh and Julie Bowen, as his high-school sweetheart, make
an engaging couple.
 &HT;    Liabilities: A lot is riding on the untested Cavanagh's
likability.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Viewers will take a while to discover ``Ed,'' as
they did with ``Providence.'' But, once they do, they'll fall for
its charms. 
 -0- 
 THE FUGITIVE (CBS)  
 &HT;    Premise: Dr. Richard Kimble (Tim Daly), the one-armed man, a
pursuing lawman (Mykelti Williamson) ... you know the drill.
 &HT;    Assets: A fantastic cast gives this remake a real edge.
 &HT;    Liabilities: Viewers may feel they've seen it all before.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Good television never goes out of style, and this
smart update will keep the premise fresh enough to win over
viewers. ``The Fugitive'' could be the crossover hit that CBS is
hoping for. 
 -0- 
 THE GEENA DAVIS SHOW (ABC)  
 &HT;    Premise: Teddie Cochran (Davis) is a single New Yorker who meets
the man of her dreams (Peter Horton) and ends up engaged and living
with him, his two kids and his stern housekeeper in _ gulp! _ the
suburbs.
 &HT;    Assets: Davis and Horton, still beloved by fans of
``thirtysomething,'' have great chemistry.
 &HT;    Liabilities: It's a little tough to embrace Davis in such a
sublimated role.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Similarities to ``Sex and the City'' don't work to
the show's advantage. The romance works, but laughs could be in
short supply. 
 -0- 
 GIDEON'S CROSSING (ABC)  
 &HT;    Premise: The saga of Ben Gideon (Andre Braugher), a doctor with
enormous talent, a massive ego and a knack for getting involved in
his patients' lives.
 &HT;    Assets: Braugher is the big draw here, and fans of ``Homicide''
are sure to tune in. A large, intelligently chosen ensemble cast is
another plus.
 &HT;    Liabilities: The brooding camerawork and quiet, slowly paced
dialogue may pall on clicker-happy viewers.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Dark, verbose and ultimately rather boring. Our
diagnosis? Lighten up... stat! 
 -0- 
 GROSSE POINTE (WB)  
 &HT;    Premise: A ``Larry Sanders''-esque backstage saga of the
production of a contrived teen show about privileged kids in a
snooty American town, from ``Beverly Hills 90210'' producer Darren
Star.
 &HT;    Assets: Lots of insider dirt on ''90210'' and ``Melrose Place,''
plus Star's willingness to exploit them.
 &HT;    Liabilities: The pilot allegedly angered Aaron Spelling, Tori
Spelling and Shannen Doherty so much that Spelling Sr. called Star
personally to demand changes. Star agreed _ and any caution could
doom ``Grosse Pointe.''
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Who better than Star to skewer the ridiculousness
of teen TV? But it may be hard to keep coming up with new angles. 
 -0- 
 MADIGAN MEN (ABC)  
 &HT;    Premise: Successful, newly divorced Ben Madigan (Gabriel Byrne)
struggles to raise his teen-age son (John Hensley) in New York.
Matters get complicated when his crusty Irish dad, Seamus (Roy
Dotrice), arrives looking for a place to stay.
 &HT;    Assets: The acting and writing are top notch, and Byrne is
highly likable in a low-key, Anthony Edwards kind of way.
 &HT;    Liabilities: The tone of the show is rather quiet, going for
amusing more than flat-out funny. That may change, however.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Critical reviews will be positive, but that rarely
jibes with viewer reaction. 
 -0- 
 THE MICHAEL RICHARDS SHOW (NBC)  
 &HT;    Premise: Bumbling private eye (Richards) tries to carve out a
career in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Assets: Richards is a genius when it comes to physical comedy.
 &HT;    Liabilities: While casting isn't yet complete, the lineup so far
_ including William Devane, Tim Meadows and Bill Cobbs _is
guy-heavy.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Seems like a good bet, if viewers will accept
Richards in a role other than Kramer. We're pretty sure that they
will. 
 -0- 
 NIGHT VISIONS (Fox)  
 &HT;    Premise: Like ``The Twilight Zone,'' this series will feature a
new, creepy story each week _ or, in this case, two per week _ with
marquee actors and directors. Among the stars scheduled to appear:
Gil Bellows, Brian Dennehy, Cary Elwes, Bridget Fonda, Bill Pullman
and Aidan Quinn.
 &HT;    Assets: It's been a while since we've seen an original,
big-budget anthology show like this.
 &HT;    Liabilities: Anthology shows are by definition inconsistent.
Still, this one should have a good batting average.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Good, old-fashioned, shiver-inducing fun that
should score with viewers. 
 -0- 
 TITANS (NBC)  
 &HT;    Premise: Superwealthy, bitter divorcees (Perry King and Victoria
Principal) battle for the affections of their children, including
their prodigal son (Casper Van Dien). Then mix in a sexy tramp
(Yasmine Bleeth), who's engaged to dad but recently slept with
junior. In other words, soapy.
 &HT;    Assets: Bleeth and Principal are ideally suited to insanely
over-the-top proceedings.
 &HT;    Liabilities: Van Dien is wooden, and the story line is awfully
silly.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: Soap bubbles will soon be washed up. 
 -0- 
 WELCOME TO NEW YORK (CBS)  
 &HT;    Premise: An Indiana weatherman (Jim Gaffigan) joins a New York
morning show run by a hotshot producer (Christine Baranski), and
culture clashes ensue.
 &HT;    Assets: A great cast _ not only the likable Gaffigan and the
rapier-sharp Baranski, but also Sara Gilbert and Rocky Carroll.
 &HT;    Liabilities: Gaffigan is talented, but he's a no-name who won't
help CBS hype the show.
 &HT;    Bottom Line: With ``Spin City'' deprived of Michael J. Fox,
``Welcome To New York: could become the next workplace-comedy hit. 
 -0- 
