<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EX-GAYS-BOS &LR;      09-12 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EX-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYS WHO TRIED STRAIGHT LIFE NOW SAY IT DIDN'T WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Pierpont had perfected his approach: He would stroll into a
Bible study class for gays and lesbians and proclaim that he was
one of them. Standing before the circle of strangers, he would tell
them that he too was gay and had been misunderstood by his
fundamentalist family.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he would tell them that he had found, in a combination of
religion and therapy, an escape from the shame he'd felt all his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell them they didn't need to be gay, that they needed to
change just like me,'' recalled Pierpont.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, his tactics became more subversive: He
spent large parts of the 1970s and 1980s walking into gay bars in
Seattle, Philadelphia, and Atlantic City with his team of
followers, always pointing to his own life story as proof that
homosexuality is a choice. Over time, he became one of the most
vocal spokesmen in the controversial ``gay conversion,'' or
``ex-gay,'' movement.
</P>
<P>
   Then Pierpont became a changed man once again.
</P>
<P>
   He now embraces the fact that he is gay: Eight years ago he
divorced his wife and, in 1998, he moved to Provincetown, Mass.,
where he lives with his partner, Nick Massoni. Every night, he
performs in a gay cabaret. Today, Pierpont has become an outspoken
voice in an emerging backlash against gay conversion therapy, a
backlash dubbed the ``ex-ex gay'' movement.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, The Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay
and lesbian political organization, released a 37-page report
outlining what it believed to be the dangers of homosexual
conversion therapy. Many gays, according to the report suffer
depression and anxiety after trying everything from exorcisms to
lipstick seminars to change. The report included 14 stories of
homosexuals _ pastors' sons, Jehovah's witnesses, and gay
conversion leaders _ who say trying to change one's sexual
orientation is painful and fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one knows just how many people proclaim to be ex-ex
gays, specialists say thousands of homosexuals who spent years
trying to overcome their sexual orientation are now openly saying
they never doused their desires for the same sex. In Washington and
California, ex-ex gays have created support groups and others have
taken their gripping testimonies to the Internet. Gay rights
specialists say ``ex-ex gays'' began ``coming out'' again after the
Christian right published ads in leading newspapers in 1998,
promoting gay conversion therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new phenomenon,'' said Wayne Besen, editor of the
report. ``Ex-ex gays feel more and more that it's their moral
obligation to tell their stories. They want to save people 10 and
20 years of pain and misery.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics like Alan Medinger, who founded a Christian ministry
in the Baltimore area that says it helps people overcome
homosexuality, argues that most people experience ``significant
change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said it was going to be easy. It's a long road. . . .
We are not saying that it works for everyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The gay conversion movement began around 1974 when a band of
religious figures came together in Anaheim, Calif. Many of them,
said Medinger, had overcome homosexuality and wanted to start an
international gay conversion ministry to help others.
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, religious figures and medical experts
worried that the movement was a fraud and preyed on vulnerable
people: In 1979, Gary Cooper and Michael Bussee, who helped launch
Exodus International, the main umbrella organization for ex-gay
groups around the world, left their wives for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were examples of two who were not truthful. We lost a lot
of them but now we are much more careful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those setbacks, the gay conversion movement began to
grow, as men and women from deeply religious homes came seeking to
transform themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an overwhelming sense of guilt, like homosexuality was a
sin,'' Medinger said. ``I would just go to church and just cry and
cry and cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement, he said, gave him what nothing else had: hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I told people Christ had changed me, the more I
believed it would be true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pierpont married and had a son, he couldn't squelch the
romantic desires he had for other men. At one point in his life, he
was so full of rage, fear, and self-hatred that he began to tremble
and break out into a sweat. Finally after years of trying, he
realized there was nothing he could do to change.
</P>
<P>
   But Medinger questions if so-called ``ex-ex gays'' like Pierpont
overstated their conversion to heterosexuality from the start.
Medinger said that 10 years after marrying his wife and having two
daughters, he realized he hadn't dealt with his homosexual past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking terrible risks. I was vice president of a good
company, but toward the end I was openly going to gay bars and
parks,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Medinger said the conversion movement believes homosexuality is
rooted in childhood, sparked by an absent father, overbearing
mother, or gender-identity problems. He now believes he reverted to
his past homosexuality after years of not dealing with the fact
that his depressed father was never around for him.
</P>
<P>
   But Medinger, who has been married for more than 40 years and
has a 24-year-old son, said his dramatic religious conversion came
one night as he sat weeping during a prayer meeting. Only then,
said Medinger, did he get involved in the ex-gay movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a remarkable healing and became head over heels in love
with my wife,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Medinger's belief that gay people can become straight
through Christian-based therapy goes against the recommendation of
mainstream experts. As the gay conversion movement was just
starting out, The American Psychiatric Association declared in 1974
that homosexuality was not a disease. Soon after, other
professional organizations like the American Psychological
Association declared that homosexuality could not, and should not,
be changed. Still the movement continued to grow. Two years ago,
conservative groups such as the Christian Coalition launched an ad
campaign promoting ex-gay therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Wulfensmith of Monrovia, Calif., said the lingering
stigma that comes with being homosexual is one reason some gays are
still joining conversion programs.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pierpont, she grew up in a strong fundamentalist family and
was also taught that homosexuality was sinful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, she entered into a reparative therapy program that
promised to change her sexual orientation. There, she lived in a
home with other people who were also desperately seeking to become
heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the program worried that this was my only
option,'' she said. ``But I was still depressed. I was even more
hopeless,'' said Wulfensmith, who after years of therapy accepted
her homosexuality. She now lives with her ``wife'' and two adopted
children.
</P>
<P>
   But Pierpont's acceptance of his sexual orientation came only
after he could no longer deny his romantic feelings for other men.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started to come to terms with my sexuality, my whole
marriage came under fire . . . I started telling friends and 100
percent of my friends stopped speaking to me,'' he said. ``I think
one reason the Christian friends didn't want to associate with me
is because I had been a leader in the movement, and all of a sudden
I pulled their foundation from under them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
