<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've all watched TV shows where a crime victim scrutinizes a
police lineup, hoping to pick out the perp among the motley crew.
But what do you call the window the accuser is looking through?
</P>
<P>
   As far as Barry Bragen was concerned, it was always a one-way
mirror: ``The observers are stationed on one side and watch the
observed through the glass, while the subjects see only their own
reflection.'' So he was surprised to find the same kind of barrier
described in last Sunday's Globe as a two-way mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my friend about it,'' he reports in an e-mail. ``She
is a clinical social worker, and knows about those things, and she
said that of course it was a two-way mirror! . . . I believe there
is general confusion on the subject,'' he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there would be if anyone stopped to think about it. I
picked up the Sept. 4 New Yorker, and there were police watching a
suspect ``through a one-way mirror.'' A Nexis search quickly
confirmed that both terms have been used freely for more than three
decades, and neither has a clear lead in the citation sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The mirror, either way, seems to have begun as one-way glass or
one-way window. The first Oxford English Dictionary quotation is
from Fitzgerald's ``The Last Tycoon,'' 1940: ``(My father's office
was) the first to have one-way glass in the big French windows.''
The mirror variations _ both one-way and two-way _ appear in the
mid-'60s, but the quote from 1967 suggests that the device is still
somewhat unfamiliar: ``They directed total concentration through
the sighting side of a two-way mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early '70s, they were everywhere: one-way mirrors to make
tollbooths appear empty, the better to snare scofflaws; two-way
mirrors, so employees said, to nab shoplifters in the Macy's and
Gimbel's dressing rooms. And nobody seems to have minded that
neither term, looked at closely, really makes sense. The mirrored
side of the glass is a one-way mirror on one side and a one-way
window on the other; only the glass itself is a two-way material.
If we had stuck with the early and accurate one-way window, we
wouldn't have to choose between competing terms today.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't that happen? My guess is that most people, introduced
to the notion of a mirror that's also a window, imagine themselves
as the watchees, not the watchers. Many of us have tried on clothes
at department stores, or worked out at gyms, but few have spied on
others doing it. It's that deceptive mirror, the mirror that isn't,
that plucks the strings of paranoia. And once you're speaking from
the mirrored side of the wall, one-way and two-way seem equally
plausible; you're trapped on the one-way side of a two-way window.
</P>
<P>
   Most reference books have ignored the question, but the
Webster's New World Dictionary of Media and Communications (1990)
says the glass through which you watch a focus group is a one-way
mirror. The brand-new fourth edition of the American Heritage
Dictionary also gives preference to one-way mirror, though it notes
that it is ``also called two-way mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   We the people may not agree; a rash of recent two-way mirrors in
connection with TV's ``Big Brother'' suggests that the show's
publicity machine may have chosen two-way to describe their
camera-permeable walls. That could tip the balance _ or not; we may
well go on using the terms interchangeably with as little fuss as
ever, each according to his or her taste. If Big Brother is
watching our language, he doesn't seem to care whether the glass is
one-way or two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ancient curse
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So just how bad was it, the nasty word George W. Bush used to
describe a New York Times reporter last week? NBC, the Associated
Press, and the Times itself called it an obscenity _ from a word
that meant ``inauspicious, ill-omened'' in Latin, but later took a
turn for the worse. The following day, Times columnist Maureen Dowd
reported that the newspaper's style czar had downgraded the word to
a vulgarity, on the grounds that it ``has nothing to do with sex.''
That might not be everyone's reasoning, but vulgar does seem more
appropriate: It derives from vulgus, ``the common people,'' and it
can mean ``common'' in either the neutral or the pejorative sense.
Common the epithet is, and common it has long been. Credit George
with a sense of history: Unlike the congressman who called Bill
Clinton a scumbag, or the senator who called his opponent a
putzhead, Bush used a good old English word for his nemesis _
though in the year 1400, it was spelled arce-hoole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Include a
hometown and phone number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
