<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. LAURA'S TV DEBUT TAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Laura Schlessinger, the most famous homophobe who's not a
blonde-haired rapper from Detroit, made her much-debated debut on
the television Monday morning, and she managed to get through the
whole hour without calling anyone a ``biological error'' or
referring to their lives as ``deviant.''
</P>
<P>
   For her first show, Schlessinger, who made her name doling out
bilious advice on her radio talk show, took on teens and drugs,
warning parents that their ``bubbly young teenager could turn into
a moody, hostile, brooding drug user right behind your very back.''
But she steered clear of her controversial opinions about lesbians
and gay men that made her the target of protests for much of the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that campaign has been galvanized at the stopdrlaura.com
web site, which bills itself as ``a coalition against hate,'' and
has organized ``National Days of Protest'' against Schlessinger's
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jimmy the Greek disparaged African Americans, he got
fired. When Dr. Laura Schlessinger calls gays and lesbians
`biological errors' and pedophiles, Paramount gives her a TV
show,'' it reads on the site's home page. ``While Ms. Schlessinger
is free to malign minorities, corporate America is not required
subsidize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fallout, several major advertisers, including AT&AMP;T,
Xerox and United Airlines, pulled their commercials from her show,
as did Proctor &AMP; Gamble, which stated, ``While she has every right
to assert her views on all subjects in the context of her show, we
have an equal right as an advertiser to place our commercials in
less polarizing environments.'' At least on her first show, the
usually outspoken Schlessinger never mentioned the lost advertisers
or anything else pertaining to the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Schlessinger's silence on the controversy should
surprise no one. Did anyone really expect her to leap out of the
box with a mouthful of anti-gay rhetoric on day one when she knew
everyone _ especially gay and lesbian activists _ would be watching
for exactly such a misstep? With a show that had some stations so
nervous they downplayed its premiere _ WCVB, Channel 5, in Boston
wouldn't even list ``Dr. Laura'' on its Web site, placing a
discreet ``TBD'' (to be determined) in listings for the show's 10
a.m. time slot _ Schlessinger surely wanted to calm the fears of
the suits at Paramount, which produces the show.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the rest of this week's shows seem fairly routine,
ranging from ``When is an affair an affair'' to ``Are you your
kid's parent?'' But make no mistake. This momentary curb of her
biased tongue should not be perceived as some dramatic epiphany
concerning the lesbian and gay community. Schlessinger, who takes
her ``Dr.'' title from a Columbia University doctorate in
physiology, hasn't softened her views one bit. Schlessinger is
offering any half-baked apologies to explain herself _ such as
Atlanta Braves meathead John Rocker attempted after he infamously
maligned most of humanity in a 1999 Sports Illustrated article _ or
claiming she will no longer condemn homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week on ``Larry King Live,'' Schlessinger, who
maintains her views on gays and lesbians are based on her
conservative Jewish beliefs, reiterated her stance and said that
any attempt to shut down her show is ``very un-American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of difference of opinion is now taken as some kind of
discriminatory hate-mongering. One is not allowed dissent; one will
be shut down,'' she told King. ``We had a McCarthy era, and it's
interesting that the same side which cried blood then, is sort of
standing by and clucking now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthyism indeed. What Schlessinger doesn't seem to get is
that then, as now, people were fighting against damaging labels
applied by those determined to force their version of the world
down everyone else's throats. She has painted herself as a victim
while ignoring how her inflammatory words could lead to the
victimization of lesbians and gay men.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as much as I despise Schlessinger's views, I've never
believed her show should be censored or kept off the air. Keeping
controversial views off the air sets too dangerous a precedent, one
that could double back on those trying to shut Schlessinger up.
Besides, I like knowing exactly who my enemies are, the better to
fight and oppose their bigotry and small-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   Given enough rope, bigots eventually hang themselves on their
own hatred. And despite the transparent kinder, gentler face
presented Monday morning, don't expect Dr. Laura to be any
different.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
