<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0361 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-MANAGING-MONEY-ART-BO     09-12 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGING-MONEY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WOMEN AS PURSE-STRING POWERHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the beginning, there was the Husband/CFO. As Everyfamily's
chief financial officer, he earned the money, paid the bills, and
doled out spending money as he saw fit. His stay-at-home wife's
financial role was generally limited to buying groceries, clipping
coupons, and paying the PTA dues. Her job was to know the price of
milk and eggs, not stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   What's since changed is almost everything about American
families and money. In the past 40 years, the number of working
women has roughly tripled. The number of female wage earners in the
United States overtook the number of male wage earners two decades
ago. Although the median income of women is still some 45 percent
that of men, the gap is closing: between 1990 and 1998, women's
median income rose 48 percent, while men's grew only 6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And so, meet the Wife/CFO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the case in the majority of marriages, but it's more
common than most people think,'' says Diane Rosen, a financial
planner. ``Roles have become more fuzzy. Husbands and wives today
each do what they do best, and they do what they like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For many wives this means being in charge of paying the family
bills, balancing the checkbook, investing the spare cash, and
planning the estate. In a 1996 survey by the National Opinion
Research Center, 28.2 percent of the married women polled said they
managed all their families' money except their husbands' personal
spending money, whereas the figure for husbands was only 8.6
percent. (The others had separate or pooled financial
arrangements.) Meanwhile, in a 1998-1999 survey by SRI Consulting,
40 percent of the families surveyed said that women handled the
finances. Small wonder that a gaggle of books advising such
``smart'' women are on the shelves (``Smart Women Finish Rich'')
and that brokerage houses such as American Express now market
specifically to them (``Smart Women. Smart Choices'').
</P>
<P>
   But Wife/CFOs are not all the same. They have different
backgrounds, different skills, different motives, and different
management styles. Consider. . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE VETERAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big deal? Lila Hurwitz has been a Wife/CFO since
she got married 48 years ago. ``I glance at the bills occasionally,
but that's all I do,'' says her husband, Arthur Hurwitz, a
74-year-old retired paint filler from Winthrop, Mass. ``I can't
remember the last time I wrote a check. I'd be financially lost
without my wife. May she live a long life.''
</P>
<P>
   Already has. Now 72, Lila Hurwitz wanted to be a writer when she
was a teenager. Her father, who was in the drapery business, had
other notions. He wanted her to help with the books. So she did,
and eventually she became a bookkeeper for other businesses,
finally retiring two years ago. She also tended to her family's
financial business along the way, while she and her husband raised
two children. Yes, she consults with him about the purchase of,
say, a new washer or dryer, but she's clearly the one who writes
the checks and keeps track of the cash flow. ``I've never met the
bank statement I couldn't reconcile,'' she declares proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Lila Hurwitz is conservative, practical, and precise. Bills are
always paid on time, investments are considered carefully (the
couple didn't didn't buy their own home until they were well into
their 50s), and debt is eschewed. ``I guess it's because I grew up
during the Depression,'' she says. ``I have an absolute horror of
debt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Midlife Learner &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Silver, a 52-year-old speech therapist, did what she
thought she was supposed to do when she was in her 20s: She got
married, became a mother, and let her husband handle the money. Why
not? He was, after all, a financial professional. ``I had my own
checkbook for `fun money' and the kids' birthday presents and
things like that,'' Silver recalls. ``But I really didn't know
where or in what our money was.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed dramatically in 1990 when Silver divorced. Suddenly
she was responsible for managing the money for herself and her
three children, ages 9, 12, and 15. ``I jumped in with both feet,''
she remembers. ``What astounded me was how easy it was, and how
capable I was of getting everything paid on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarried eight years ago, the Sharon, Mass. woman now has a
his/hers financial arrangement with her second husband, Jim
Schwartz, a locksmith who has three children of his own. But, by
her own reckoning, she is responsible for paying about 75 percent
of their joint bills, and carefully manages her own money. ``He's
an incredibly wonderful person,'' she says of Schwartz, ``but very
laid back about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver is determined that her only daughter, Debbie Silver, not
be a late financial bloomer like herself. And the 19-year-old
Northeastern University sophomore, who faithfully deposits the
paycheck from her summer job in her own bank account almost as soon
as she receives it, agrees. ``It's important to know how much money
you have, and how much you can spend, at all times,'' she says. ``I
want to be in control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Mother's Daughter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With seven jobs and five homes since graduating from college a
dozen years ago, 33-year-old Susan Brown mirrors a generation
that's willing to make changes. But one thing has remained the same
in her life: She's almost always been the person in charge of her
own money. She started at age 11, when she got her first job, doing
prep work in the family's restaurant at Nantasket Beach, just
outside Boston. ``I wasn't promoted to a fry cook until I was 13,''
she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother had been independent, too. ``My father died when I
was 4,'' says Brown, of Waltham, Mass. ``He ran the restaurant, and
my mother pretty much took it over. She always talked to my older
sister and me about the importance of money. She wanted us to
understand that it didn't grow on trees, and that it was important
not to spend beyond our means.'' Later, Brown helped keep the
restaurant's books.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Brown is clearly a Wife/CFO. ``Right before we got
married, I noticed that my husband had all his savings in a savings
account,'' she says of her husband, James Brown, who works in the
executive protection field. ``I asked him what kind of interest he
was getting. He didn't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Brown knows. She also knew, because she and her husband
are looking for a first house to buy, that she should move their
investments out of mutual finds and CDs and into more liquid money
market funds. ``Of course, I told Jim what I was doing,'' she says.
``He shrugged and said, `That's fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Pro &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quite frankly, 49-year-old Lynda Schuepp's got better things to
do than be a Wife/CFO. After all, she's a professional investor who
also manages her own real estate holdings and writes for an online
financial newsletter. And she holds a master's degree in finanace.
Paying the family bills? ``I hate it,'' she declares darkly. But
she does it. Regularly if reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   She's seated at her desk at one end of her rambling Victorian
home in Milton, Mass., and she'd like to have a word with the folks
at AT&AMP;T. ``You see this?'' she asks loudly, waving a piece of paper
in her hand. ``It's a bill for $2.80. They've been billing me for a
toll-free number I never even had. I've sent them $2.80 three
times! But I can't get rid of the thing. It just keeps going on and
on.'' She glowers.
</P>
<P>
   Schuepp spends much of her professional life gloamed onto a
computer screen, so it's not surprising that she pays most bills _
telephone, property taxes, church donations, you name it _ online.
She also does online research before suggesting possible family
investments to her husband, Paul Schuepp, a vice-president of sales
at Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Schuepp is clearly happy to remain on the sidelines while
his wife calls the financial signals. ``She knows numbers,'' he
says. ``I'm more of a technical person. I might glance at the bills
that look sort of interesting, but I don't really pay attention.
Why should I?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Natural &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Oshman was 13 years old when she opened her first checking
account. One of the first things she bought with her accumulating
funds was a pair of sweatpants. She still has them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, I wasn't very good at math,'' says the 35-year-old
internal staff recruiter, who lives in Somerville, Mass. with her
husband, Kenny Laxague, and their two small children. ``But if you
put a dollar sign next to a number, it intrigued me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oshman loves being the family CFO. She loves paying bills, loves
setting up IRAs, loves buying bonds. She literally lies awake at
night thinking about family finanaces, prides herself in careful
investment research, and is still mortified that last year she
invested modestly in a mutual fund that went south.
</P>
<P>
   Laxague, a graduate student at UMass-Boston who is training to
be a teacher, concurs that family money is always on his wife's
mind, which is fine with him, because it's seldom on his. Oshman,
meanwhile, thinks there's a reason for her preoccupation. ``My dad
was a filmmaker who had a wildly fluctuating income,'' she
explains. ``It was feast or famine, and I don't want that for my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Oshman knows without looking, at any given moment, the exact
balances of the family's two checking and two savings accounts.
When Laxague returns home from grocery shopping, she immediately
asks how much he spent rather than what he bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how much we have in the bank,'' Laxague says.
``All I know is that I'm given $150 a week for grocery money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Oshman corrects him quickly, ``it's $130.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
