<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S A BIG MAN _ THE ONLY MAN _ ON THIS CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Beginning this week, Beam-Column will move on Tuesdays and
Thursdays.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BEAM COLUMN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's like a drop of milk on a chocolate bar. He's like a
gastroenterologist at a Christian Science convention. He's like a
vegetarian at a steak house. (That's enough foolishness _ Ed.) He's
the only male student at Wellesley College.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Ross Franklin, he's 20 years old, he hails from
Yonkers, N.Y., and he's the first resident male student at
Wellesley in the last five years. Franklin took advantage of a
12-college exchange program to leave Norton's Wheaton College to
spend the year at Wellesley, with much encouragement from his
mother and grandmother, both alumnae. ``It played a huge, positive
role in their lives,'' Franklin tells me. ``I'm really happy to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley is one of only a handful of all women's colleges left
in the country; Smith, Mount Holyoke, Spelman, Bryn Mawr, and
Barnard are others. There are some men around; about half the
faculty is male, and maybe 15 or 20 fellows from MIT, Brandeis, and
Babson cross-register into Wellesley classes. But as Franklin and I
chow down at Tower Court dining hall, I remark that we seem to be
the only men in the cavernous refectory. ``Oh, yeah,'' he says.
``It's always like this.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's it like being the only man around? ``I'm kind of a
celebrity here,'' reports Franklin, who has already been
interviewed by the college TV station and drafted into the fall
theatrical for a rare male role. He's also hoping to run for
student government. ``I need to represent my gender,'' he deadpans.
</P>
<P>
   The teaching in his major subjects, biology and psychology, is
superb, and he reports that the natives are quite friendly. His one
complaint concerns the weight room. ``It's like a dungeon,'' he
says. ``I was shocked at the shape it's in.'' I tried to convince
him that turning out Olympic weightlifters has never been a top
priority at Hillary Clinton's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Life in guy paradise is not without its complications. The
teachers generally use only female pronouns when referring to
students. Franklin will be allowed to join the basketball team, but
he can't play in any games. His hallmates just voted to make all
bathrooms on his floor co-ed, so that removed one problem. But he
still hasn't decided whether to attend the Dyke Ball, or Instead
House's annual Naked Ball, when women have to donate $1 to charity
for every article of clothing they wear through the door.
</P>
<P>
   With appropriate delicacy, I inquire about his social life. He's
straight, he's available, and yes, he has dated some Wellesley
women. But for the time being, he seems content to hang with his
pals from Wheaton. Truth be told, he seems a tad intimidated by the
intellectual candlepower of Wellesley women. ``They're awfully
intelligent,'' he concedes _ but his mother and grandmother could
have told him that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ON THE COUCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do we want a president who's obsessive-compulsive, or one with
histrionic personality syndrome? Without apparent irony, Psychology
Today ran Al Gore's and George W. Bush's personality traits through
the American Psychiatric Society's ``Diagnostic and Statistical
Manual of Mental Disorders.'' John Berecz tells the magazine that
Gore, as an obsessive-compulsive, can ``compartmentalize things . .
. he might tell you with tears in his eyes about his sister dying
of lung cancer and then tell the tobacco growers, `I'm with you.'
'' He calls Bush's histrionic style ``emotionally alive,
emotionally available,'' like Ronald Reagan's. More useless
knowledge from Dacher Keltner, PhD: ``The asymmetrical upper lip
raise (Action Unit10; Levator labii superioris) or asymmetrical lip
corner tighten (Action Unit14; Buccinator) . . . typically
accompany Bush's smile, and account for the smirk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MY MISTAKE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I erred in my Aug. 30 column, when I relegated Jim Jeffords of
Vermont to the US House of Representatives. He has been a US
Senator for 12 years. Vermont's only representative is the
crazy-like-a-fox socialist poseur, Bernie Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
