<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CONCORD-REVIEW-ART-BO     09-12 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORD-REVIEW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PUBLISHER FIGHTS ELITISM IN ATTEMPT TO INSPIRE STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUDBURY, Mass. _ Maverick publisher that he is, Will Fitzhugh
has both fans and detractors of the radical work he does in his
little office above a consignment shop, down the road from the
historic Wayside Inn.
</P>
<P>
   There are the famous scholars who are agog over the journal he
prints, and then there are the universities who tell him to stay
far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps the countless notes of thanks from his authors,
attesting to all the ways he has enhanced their careers. He also
saves the letters from the 137 foundations who have rejected his
grant applications.
</P>
<P>
   All for something as dazzling, as upsetting _ or neither _ as
The Concord Review, a quarterly collection of history essays by
high school students judged by Fitzhugh to be exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   A junior from Nantucket explores the Panama Canal. A sophomore
from Minnesota delves into the G.I. Bill. A senior from Missouri
writes about the United States and Iran in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   One would expect the project to win wide, if not especially
passionate, support. It taps into old-fashioned American values
like respect for hard work. It provides teachers with an
alternative to stale text books.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzhugh envisions The Concord Review in classrooms and
libraries across the country, inspiring students to do original
work and to set their sights high.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with subscriptions at only 800 nationwide, The Concord
Review is clearly not popular with schools. It's doesn't earn even
a tenth of the money it would need to be self-supporting. It makes
some educators downright queasy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Stanford admissions office once wrote glowing
letters, a dean recently yanked the school's support. The director
of National History Day says The Concord Review is alienating to
the typical student.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Fitzhugh has found that his plain, uncomplicated idea to
recognize the best and the brightest is curiously out-of-step with
the times. Even as it attracts fervent admirers, it languishes just
on the brink of existence.
</P>
<P>
   After this former teacher, 64, has put 13 years of his life and
all of his own money into The Concord Review, he believes his
efforts may evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, he's tired, and wants to retire. He is also almost
entirely dependent on one private philanthropist. In a few years,
he worries, there may be no more Concord Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a failure, frankly,'' Fitzhugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the negative attention and the lack of attention, Fitzhugh
believes, can be blamed on anti-intellectualism among educators,
many of whom would rather reward mediocrity than insist upon top
work. In his opinion, they are dumbing down American education so
as not to offend or discourage anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents want good grades, kids don't want a lot of work, and
there's a tremendous pressure for teachers to be entertaining
rather than demanding,'' Fitzhugh said. ``I'm still puzzled by this
do-nothing-and-feel-good syndrome. It's like finding out that
hospitals are staffed by people who don't believe in health.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Gorn, executive director of National History Day, said she
doesn't see anything overtly bad or wrong with The Concord Review.
But it's not the way she would choose to build passion for
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reserved for students of upper-level abilities,'' Gorn
said. ``Other kids might feel a little bit turned off, or feel
uncomfortable, or like, `I can't do that.' It limits the kids and
the teachers who will participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzhugh's journey, his unexpected road to controversy, began in
1987, when he was teaching at Concord-Carlisle High School. He
dreamed up The Concord Review as a way to reward top work in the
social studies. It would also provide a model to teach and
encourage other young people.
</P>
<P>
   He quit his job to start the journal, which he published out of
his Sudbury home until this year. It is the only quarterly in the
world devoted to high school scholarship, Fitzhugh says.
</P>
<P>
   Finding worthy material turned out to be a breeze. Fitzhugh
publishes 44 essays a year, only about eight percent of the
submissions he receives, which come from students in private and
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting some important champions posed no trouble, either.
Supporters range from former Assistant Secretary of Education Diane
Ravitchto historian Arthur M. SchlesingerJr., who says there should
be a copy of The Concord Review in every high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more satisfying for kids at that age than to
see their stuff in print,'' said Schlesinger in a phone interview.
``It's also an incentive and a stimulus for excellence in other
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such lofty supporters, Fitzhugh says he's been charged
with elitism time and time again. It's a notion he finds odd and
disheartening. He is not rewarding students for innate
intelligence, but for intense effort, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this misleading idea that good work must come from
genetic smarts,'' Fitzhugh said. ``It gets kids off the hook. `I'm
not bright, I'm not going to worry about it.' Well, I'm trying to
tell these kids, `Look at the end notes, look at the bibliography.
(The authors) worked hard.'
</P>
<P>
   With all of the qualms, funding has been quite a battle. In
1991-1992, and again in 1995-1996, Fitzhugh suspended publication.
In recent years, he says, his survival has been almost entirely
dependent on John Abele, founder and chairman of the Boston
Scientific Corp. Abele, a convert to Fitzhugh's ideas, provides
$85,000 to $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a way to make The Concord Review more
self-sufficient, Fitzhugh launched the National Review Board. It's
a service, that, for a fee, aims to give high school students
informed, unbiased comments and ratings on their research papers _
comments they can then attach to their college applications.
</P>
<P>
   A number of schools have signed onto the idea, including
Harvard, Princeton and Yale. And last year, Robert M. Kinnally,
dean of admission and financial aid at Stanford, wrote an
enthusiastic letter endorsing both The Concord Review and the
National Writing Board.
</P>
<P>
   Then, this week, came a note from Kinnally, who is stepping down
from his position, withdrawing those endorsements and demanding
that Fitzhugh remove Stanford's name from any promotional
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnally offered no explanation. When a reporter sought comment
from Stanford, James M. Montoya, vice provost for student affairs,
provided a written reply: ``Given the high level of anxiety
associated with the college admission process, we felt such an
endorsement was not in the best interest of college applicants.''
</P>
<P>
   Other university officials have argued that the National Review
Board service, for which Fitzhugh charges $60, should be free.
Fitzhugh said he'd be happy to do that if he had any money; he
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's decision is another sign, Fitzhugh says, that his
efforts are misunderstood. His is cheered, though, by the students
who tell him how much help The Concord Review has been.
</P>
<P>
   James Egelhofer, 18, of Holyoke, said he was inspired by copies
of the journal he read in his school library. They motivated him to
choose an unusual topic, attitudes toward World War I at his own
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually everyone does an encyclopedia, famous person, `Why
George Washington is Great' kind of paper,'' said Egelhofer, who
graduated from the Williston Northampton School in Easthampton and
is going to Brown. ``The Concord Review was in the back of my mind
saying, `You don't have to do that. Use primary sources. Do
something no one has done before.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
More information on The Concord Review is available at www.tcr.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
