<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MEDSCHOOLS-RACE-ART-B     09-12 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDSCHOOLS-RACE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MEDICAL STUDENTS QUESTION AFFIRMATIVE ACTION CRITERIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the eyes of the Association of American Medical Colleges,
Grace Lopez is not a minority. Even though she is
Salvadoran-American and has the broad face and caramel-colored skin
of a Mayan, to most medical school administrators, she's
essentially white.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who grew up poor in Los Angeles, is one of thousands of
minority students who face a tougher time getting into medical
school because the association excludes them from affirmative
action programs that could boost their chances.
</P>
<P>
   Under the narrow, 25-year-old definition of ``under-represented
minority'' used by the group, students whose parents immigrated
from the Caribbean, Central and South America, or Africa don't
qualify for special aid, even though they often face social,
cultural and economic hurdles that are just as high as those faced
by more established minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there is an injustice,'' said Lopez, 26, who says she
got into Harvard Medical School without the aid of an affirmative
action program. ``You might have a Mexican-American who grew up
middle class and had more access to enrichment, and then someone
like me who overcame more challenges, but because I'm Salvadoran,
I'm not counted.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a controversial policy that has angered Asians, Latinos,
and Africans, all of whom say the policy is unfair and doesn't
reflect changes in immigration patterns. On the other side, some
white students say ethnicity shouldn't be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   In all the years that students have clamored for change, the
association has reviewed its policy annually, and has decided to
restrict affirmative action to four groups: African-Americans,
Native Americans, Mexican-Americans, and Puerto Ricans from the
mainland United States. Changing the policy now might open a
hard-to-resolve debate over which groups are most deserving,
association officials argue. But even they don't feel completely
comfortable with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were creating the under-represented groups today, would
they be different? I think it would be safe to say that it would
be,'' said Bob Beran, vice president for student affairs and
education services at the association, which sets standards for
admissions to US medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   Most US medical schools abide by the organization's policy,
under which they can choose an ``under-represented'' minority
student over a white student if their grades are equal.
``Under-represented'' means that the minority group produces a
lower percentage of the nation's doctors than its share of the
general population.
</P>
<P>
   But ``under-represented'' depends on how ethnic groups are
divided up. For instance, Asians get lumped into one category that
includes Pakistanis and Indians _ whose ranks include many doctors
_ along with Cambodians, Vietnamese, and Filipinos who produce few
doctors. Taken together, Asians aren't considered
under-represented.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the association's affirmative action stance is not
only unfair, but it hinders medical schools' ability to promote
diversity at a time when the schools themselves say they aren't
attracting enough minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, just 15 percent of the students who graduated from
medical school were members of ``under-represented'' minority
groups, though they made up 25 percent of the US population,
according to an association study released this week. The report
estimates that black, Native American, and Latino graduates of US
medical schools represent about 6 percent of practicing physicians
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the organization set its policy in the mid-1970s, there
weren't large numbers of Latinos entering the United States from
countries such as El Salvador and the Dominican Republic. Nor were
there large influxes from countries like Haiti and Jamaica, or
refugees coming in from Vietnam and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the association hasn't created special categories for
these relative newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about people in the US who have historically
been disadvantaged in academic settings, it shouldn't matter if
you're Dominican or Haitian or Mexican,'' said Raul Ruiz, a
fifth-year Harvard Medical School student, who is of Mexican
descent. ``We've all grown up with similar disadvantages.''
</P>
<P>
   Some medical schools strictly adhere to the guidelines; others
say they adjust their definition of ``minority'' by taking into
account changing demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Medical School, which prides itself on its minority
recruitment efforts, doesn't have many minorities outside of the
``under-represented minority'' category as defined by the AAMC.
</P>
<P>
   According to a school spokesman, about 25 percent of this year's
freshman class of 167 students is drawn from under-represented
minorities, including 16 African-Americans, 18 Mexican-Americans,
two Puerto Ricans from the mainland, and seven Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But there are only four other Latinos from all of Latin America,
four non-American blacks, and two people who classify themselves as
``other.'' Pulling up the overall minority numbers are 33
Asian/Pacific Islanders, allowing Harvard to boast that overall, 52
percent of the new class is minority, compared with the national
medical school average of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alvin Poussaint, associate dean of Harvard Medical School,
said he understands the thinking that went into the association's
policy. The four groups considered minorities historically have
been victims of discrimination in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But, if oppression at the hands of the US government is the
criteria, what about people from El Salvador, ask critics of the
policy. In the 1980s and early 1990s, the United States poured
millions in military aid to the government, fueling a war in which
100,000 people died and many more became refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't measure oppression,'' said Ruiz. ``Who is to say
that the post-traumatic stress disorder that a Salvadoran gets from
seeing his family massacred by the Salvadoran military, with
backing from the US, is any different than the Native American''
whose family has been relegated to a reservation?
</P>
<P>
   But, even among medical school administrators, the issue of
which minority has suffered most becomes personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they (Salvadorans) have suffered the way my
parents did, and their parents,'' said Dr. Roland T. Smoot,
assistant dean for student affairs at Johns Hopkins Medical School
in Baltimore. ``My foreparents were slaves. That didn't involve
them (Salvadorans). Although the US can never repay us, there
should be some advantages because of what went on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than get into such delicate issues, the association has
chosen to hold the line on its affirmative action policy, and some
schools such as Johns Hopkins say they are getting away from
admissions practices that take race into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Johns Hopkins offers scholarships based on financial need rather
than minority set-asides, and only selects a minority over a white
student if the two are otherwise equal candidates, Smoot said.
Finally, he added, Johns Hopkins makes little effort to learn
applicants' ethnic history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten blond-haired, blue-eyed candidates (who) check off
African-American,'' he said. ``We don't say a thing. We don't go
into what they check.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
