<HEADLINE>
NEW GLIMPSES OF BLACK LIFE IN THE OLD WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA CITY, Nev. _ The freshly paved parking lot behind the
Bucket of Blood Saloon is marked with footprints, literally and
figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the small lot is crowded with cars, circa 2000. But 125
years ago, it was packed with people looking to drink, to dine,
maybe even to dance. Back then, the recently excavated site was
home to a saloon that archeologists and historians hope will tell
them much about the life of blacks in the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Boston Saloon, the bar in the heart of Virginia
City's entertainment district was owned and run by a black man from
Massachusetts named William A. G. Brown. Searchers so far have
turned up little more information about the proprietor. But
together with a team of students and other volunteers, they have
dug up enough artifacts to reconstruct at least part of the world
that free blacks inhabited at the height of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we had hoped to find was a ghetto of sorts,
but neighborhoods were not segregated and were in fact fairly well
integrated,'' said Ron James, director of the Nevada State Historic
Preservation Office. ``Instead, we found this fellow William Brown
who realized a chance to exploit the opportunities in one of the
most international cities of its time, more so than Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the scores of boxes now stored in an archeology lab at the
University of Nevada, Reno, is an Old West tale waiting to be
interpreted, once the thousands of excavated items are cleaned and
categorized. Many are melted or misshapen _ victims, like the
saloon itself, of the Great Fire of 1875, started by a drunken
miner who kicked over a kerosene lamp in his home up the hill from
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes shards of glass and whole glass bottles,
some with the stamped labels still legible. ``Essence of Jamaica
Ginger,'' the Pepto Bismol of the 19th century, reads one. There
are red-clay tobacco pipes and a white-clay one with the bowl
elaborately carved in the image of a British queen. A detailed
ceramic container once held cherry toothpaste ``for beautifying and
preserving the teeth and gums.'' The dig even uncovered a full set
of porcelain dentures whose small size indicates they belonged to a
female patron of the Boston Saloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, we have found things you might expect from a
saloon in the Old West _ glass tumblers and shot glasses,'' said
Kelly Dixon, a doctoral candidate at the university who helped
oversee the excavation. ``But we also found delicate stemware:
champagne flutes, tiny cordial glasses, brandy snifters, the type
of glassware that makes me rethink my paradigm of the Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   With the asphalt on the parking lot barely dry, researchers have
just begun to piece together the past. They know about Brown from
historical records _ that he arrived in Virginia City in 1862;
worked as a boot black, or shoe polisher; saved his earnings; then
opened the Boston Saloon in 1864 and relocated it within two years.
They know that about 100 blacks lived on the mountain, which had
25,000 or so residents at its most populated time and is located
about 25 miles from Reno.
</P>
<P>
   But not until a few years ago did they learn for certain where
the saloon had stood for nine years, an almost unheard of time for
a business to last in the boom-and-bust West of the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular myth _ brought about by the decision to set
the 1960s TV show ``Bonanza'' in Virginia City _ it was no cow town
or even a cowboy town. Workers did not ride herd. Mostly, the white
residents worked in the segregated silver mines, coming to take
part and maybe make their riches on the Comstock Lode.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmopolitan Virginia City was a place to be. Stars of the day
played the town, which is situated between Salt Lake City and San
Francisco. Mark Twain got his start, and his adopted byline, at the
local newspaper. Some blacks prospered, too, owning several hair
salons and a boarding house, Dixon said. A black doctor examined
patients. And the Boston Saloon, also patronized by at least some
whites, was open to serve them, one of more than 100 saloons in
operation in the city's heyday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a series of things that make the site remarkable and
maybe unprecedented in the West,'' James said. ``There's the amount
of time in one location. There's the fire, which devastated the
central core of the community and shortly after which he sold the
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life rarely gets better than this in archeology,'' he added.
``This is descending into the way-cool zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The dig zone itself was actually quite small; the parking lot at
the corner of D and Union streets holds perhaps a dozen cars.
Still, at the height of tourist season, James and Dixon said, it
drew attention. People who went to the historic district to gamble,
shop, or say ``Howdy'' to the characters in period dress dropped by
to watch and to help over the five weeks of excavation.
</P>
<P>
   James and Dixon said the fire that had swept through downtown
turned out to be helpful, as did the continuous family ownership of
the saloon since 1931.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't burn was often preserved below the ash layer and
charred floorboards, including a gold $2.50 piece the size of a
dime, pieces of a gas lighting fixture, pressed-tin ceiling
fragments, keg taps made of a copper alloy, even intact rodent
skeletons. Sheep bones, Dixon said, help tell what was on the menu,
as does a Lea &AMP; Perrins steak sauce bottle. Tiny unearthed beads
indicate the presence of women in the saloon, which was probably a
family gathering place.
</P>
<P>
   What the archeologists did not uncover, or have not cleaned the
piecesenough to know, were artifacts that specifically point to the
presence of black patrons at Boston Saloon. Instead, they said, the
evidence examined so far indicates that blacks lived much like
whites, at least in the West of those days.
</P>
<P>
   But that alone speaks to how blacks made their own way in
freedom and offers contrasts with enslaved blacks and perhaps
similarities with other free blacks in the East. The best pieces
from the dig, the results of one of four saloon digs in Virginia
City in recent years, will be sent on tour, Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hoping that while we're cleaning this stuff up,
we'll realize, `Oh, this wasn't a wine bottle, it was
hair-straightening tonic,' '' she said as she pulled artifacts from
manila envelopes and plastic bags. ``Either way, we'll have a
clearer understanding of the American West if you were an
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're dealing with ethnic groups in the Old West,
sometimes documents are written with a racist slant,'' Dixon added.
``So archeology really represents the best medium to reconstruct
their everyday life. Whatever we end up with will be
illuminating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
