<HEADLINE>
INSIDER'S `SEARCH' FINDS AN AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MOONEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
IN SEARCH OF DEEP THROAT 
The Greatest Political Mystery of Our Time 
By Leonard Garment 
Basic Books, 280 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a quarter-century after a furtive, chain-smoking
phantom whispered Watergate tips to a little-known Washington Post
reporter, many have tried but none has succeeded in unmasking
``Deep Throat,'' Bob Woodward's famous anonymous source.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the attention Leonard Garment's book has received,
Deep Throat's identity is probably still among the best-kept
secrets of the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Garment, who served in Richard Nixon's White House _ ultimately
as counsel to the president _ deduces that John Sears, a canny
political operative who would later manage Ronald Reagan's
campaigns, is the whistleblower who helped topple a president.
</P>
<P>
   His arguments are not convincing, however. As he checks off the
long list of usual and not-so-usual suspects, Garment actually
makes better or equally strong cases for several other candidates,
but discards them for one reason or another. In this way, he may be
covered somewhat when Deep Throat confesses, or when he dies and is
revealed by Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   A sometime suspect himself, Garment disqualifies himself by
saying he was constitutionally incapable of such stealth and
secretiveness. We must take him at his word on that.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Sears and Woodward have both denied Garment's
identification; so has Woodward's partner in reporting Watergate
for the Post, Carl Bernstein. Sears even offered to take a
polygraph test and threatened to sue over the allegation that he
was Deep Throat. The sobriquet, borrowed from the title of a
pornographic film of the day, was used to refer to the key source
in Woodward and Bernstein's 1974 bestseller, ``All the President's
Men.''
</P>
<P>
   End of story? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Garment, his flimsy, headline-grabbing hook is
almost a trifling aside amid the broader themes of this book. There
isn't an ounce of body fat in his often clever prose _ which makes
``In Search of Deep Throat'' one snappy read from start to finish,
Garment's shortcomings as a gumshoe notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   You needn't be a Nixon or Watergate junkie to appreciate his
penetrating analysis of this momentous chapter in American history
and the players involved, Garment included. Part morality play,
part self-deprecating memoir, part political science tutorial, ``In
Search of Deep Throat'' achieves the seemingly impossible: offering
fresh insight into an old, picked-over piece of history.
</P>
<P>
   Garment catalogs and assesses the legacy of Watergate: the
Office of the Independent Counsel, new financial-reporting
requirements for high-level officials, the Office of Government
Ethics, the growth in public-interest organizations,
campaign-finance reform, and whistleblower-protection laws, and
``the rise to a more adversarial culture in journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Garment also displays a remarkable grasp of journalism, its
mechanics and limitations, and the role of the press in American
political discourse. To those who contend that official
investigations, not journalists, rolled over the rocks to reveal
the scurrying felons behind the Watergate coverup, Garment offers a
significant rebuttal. ``What a government organization
investigates, how wide it casts its net, what others will think of
the often-inconclusive information it turns up _ all these things
are mightily influenced, in the United States, by the climate of
knowledge and opinion among both the population as a whole and
interested elites,'' he writes. ``This climate, in turn, is shaped
in significant part by the press.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the story of the Watergate break-in at the Democratic
Party headquarters, and of subsequent attempts to conceal it and
other acts of political sabotage, Deep Throat steered the
Washington Post reporters and altered the climate, Garment asserts.
</P>
<P>
   The jazz saxophonist-turned-lawyer, however, is at his best
analyzing Nixon, who still fascinates him. Of his one-time law
partner, Garment writes: ``You can dig endlessly and profitably
into the details of his history; they are indeed illuminating. But
in the end you cannot explain him with any certainty. In
particular, the details do not fully explain why he lived his life,
personal and political, by giving so little of himself in such
small, separate packets to different people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Garment all but confesses that his search for Deep
Throat was more a vehicle to solve ``the larger puzzle of Richard
Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the end justifies his means, flaws and all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
