<HEADLINE>
BARENAKED LADIES DRESS UP FAMILIAR RECIPE IN `MAROON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hip as it is for the musical cognescenti to scoff at Barenaked
Ladies's relentlessly congenial and geekily ironic folk-pop, for my
money they can stay.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to suggest that the Canadian outfit's fifth album,
``Maroon'' marks any sort of musical evolution for the band or even
adds anything of note to the pop canon, although there is a measure
of newfound maturity in both the songwriting and the lyrical themes
of some of the album's 12 tracks. But what's good about ``Maroon''
is what has stayed the same: Barenaked Ladies fill a near-bare
niche for clever, well-crafted pop songs for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Barenaked Ladies' 1998 breakthrough album, ``Stunt,'' seamlessly
merged the band's relentless wise-guy humor with big production
values, and the result was a string of smash hit singles (``One
Week,'' ``It's All Been Done,'' ``Call and Answer'') and more than
4 million in sales. To enhance the odds of repeating that success,
the Ladies brought uber-producer Don Was (Rolling Stones, Bonnie
Raitt, Paul Westerberg, Iggy Pop) on board for ``Maroon,'' and the
result will no doubt be a string of smash hit singles and...you get
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the band dabbles in genres, from their trademark
jangly pop-rock (``Too Little Too Late,'' ``Never Do Anything,''
``Falling For the First Time'') and alt-country (``Go Home'') to
near-bossa nova (``Conventioneers'') and novelty ditty (``Tonight
Is the Night That I Fell Asleep At the Wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter is a strangely affecting song sung from the
post-humous perspective of the victim. It's skewed and ironic as
ever, but also strikes a deeper chord, as do the loungey
``Conventioneers'' _ a thumbnail sketch of a business-trip affair _
and ``Sell Sell Sell,'' a Hollywood morality tale set to
glockenspiel and timpani drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinch Me'' is the wisely-chosen first single, already all over
the radio. It's a jaunty, mid-tempo musing on sleepwalking through
life that questions the ultimate meaning of anything more complex
than running through the sprinklers. A big part of BNL's appeal is
their refusal to leave behind the goony, sensitive smart-aleck
within (approximate age: 17) that's convinced life _ heartbreak and
alienation and moral decay included _ is a joke. That proud
geekiness is still intact. But BNL's formerly rampant cultural
references have been replaced by _ egads _ a bit of heartfelt
revelation, and glibness is tempered by moments of wistfulness and
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maroon'' is fun-loving, yes, but deceptively so. This is ear
candy with a spine, a stronger one than one might expect from
Barenaked Ladies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
