<HEADLINE>
FREEWHEELING AND CAR HANDLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. There have been many articles recently about new car
technologies that will save fuel and reduce pollution, such as fuel
cells and freewheels. My question is: Will freewheels affect car
handling? Will it be more difficult to turn? &QL; 
J.C., Belmont, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I assume by ``freewheel'' you mean ``flywheel'' _ perhaps
it's an expression with which I'm unfamiliar (could this be?). A
flywheel is basically just a heavy wheel that can be used to
temporarily store energy in its rotation. The idea is a nice one
since very large amounts of energy can be stored in quite modest
flywheels. The tricky bit is that a flywheel doesn't just hold
energy, but it holds a more subtle quantity called ``angular
momentum'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   The angular momentum of a rotating object can be visualized as a
sort of resistance to having its axis of rotation changed. A
bicycle in motion tends not to fall over as this would mean
changing the axis about which the wheels turn. Rifles have spiral
grooves in the barrel to make the bullets spin as they fly _ it
makes them go straighter.
</P>
<P>
   The more angular momentum something has, the harder it is to
change its axis of rotation. For a flywheel, the angular momentum
is greater the faster it turns. This means that the more energy you
store in a flywheel, the more angular momentum it has, and the
harder it will get to turn.
</P>
<P>
   The catch with flywheels for cars then is that, when you've got
a lot of angular momentum stored up, you will find it hard to move
in ways that change the axis about which the flywheel rotates.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a flywheel, a car that's going fast may flip over
as it goes around a corner in order not to have the angular
momentum carried by its wheels change too quickly _ and that's for
wheels made of rubber and air. Concrete tires would never puncture
but they'd carry so much angular momentum that handling on curves
would be hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   Flywheels to store energy can be good ideas, but you have to be
careful with the application and think about how much angular
momentum you dump into them and how you want the vehicle that
carries them to behave on curves. For example, for trains that
pretty much go in straight lines, flywheels can be a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions to drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston
Globe, Health/Science Section, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107.
Please include your initials and hometown. Selected questions of
general interest will be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
