<HEADLINE>
UP, UP AND AWAY IN NEW MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to compete with New Mexico's natural beauty. But the
Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta does just that. During the
annual event, to be held this year Oct. 7-15, the deep blue skies
of Albuquerque are dotted with hundreds of hot-air balloons in so
many colors and patterns and shapes that all spectators can do is
say, ``Ooooh.'' Or maybe ``Ahhhh.'' Here are some facts and
figures:
</P>
<P>
   --The event draws nearly 20 percent of the total number of known
balloons worldwide, with about 900 at the fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   --There are more than 1 million spectator visits during the
fiesta. And there are no barriers: Spectators can walk right up to
the balloons and chat with the crews.
</P>
<P>
   --More than 25 million still photos are taken each year, which
is why the fiesta calls itself the world's most photographed event.
Vendors stroll the grounds selling film (all of it Kodak, which
sponsors the event).
</P>
<P>
   --Special events include mass ascensions and ``night glow''
displays in which the balloons, fired by propane, glow
majestically.
</P>
<P>
   --Balloon Fiesta Park covers more than 350 acres. Both admission
and parking prices are low. Costumed characters stroll around, and
booths sell everything from balloon-shaped hats to Native American
crafts to green chile burritos to buffalo burgers. Not bad for an
event that began 28 years ago in a shopping mall parking lot with
13 balloons.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on the fiesta, call 800-284-2282 or visit
www.balloonfiesta.com. For information on balloon rides during the
event, call 800-725-2477. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: Not only do this state and this province share a
border, their names begin with the same letter. What are they?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The little town of Halfway, Ore., has changed its name
to Half.com for a year in connection with a promotion by the Web
site of the same name. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``The worst thing any tourist can do is to be ignorant of
the local customs, politics and geography. . . . Imagine if you
were talking to a visiting tourist (who) had no idea who Bill
Clinton was. . . . You must read up on the country you are
(planning on) visiting'' _ from CoolTravelMail.com, via faithful
contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ala-kazam: If you stayed at the old Aladdin Hotel in Las Vegas
during its final days, as we did, you no doubt were less than
impressed. But that building has been imploded, and the only thing
the new Aladdin has in common with the old is the name. The new
building has 2,567 guest rooms, 130 shops, 21 restaurants, two
pools, and a European-style gaming club. It also has an appropriate
phone number: 877-333-WISH. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Restless on the road: Nearly half of all travelers suffer from
sleeplessness, says a survey by Hilton Hotels and the National
Sleep Foundation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who's confused? Diamonds and pearls brought into the United States
are duty-free if they're loose but can be taxed if they're part of
rings or pendants. Cameras made in India are duty free but those
from Japan are not. The rules change often, writes Travel Holiday,
so it's a good idea to check the Customs Department Web site at
www.customs.treas.gov. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scads of sand: Twenty-four percent of the earth's land is desert. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Minnesota and Manitoba. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Tidbits is compiled from wire-service reports, news
releases, books, magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of
the author's mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits,
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to
carpenter(at)globe.com. Include Include your name and community. &QL; 
 &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a Canadian reader's comment that the United States
should have a name for its citizens rather than ``Americans''
(perhaps ``Bob''), Alan Colosi of Boston writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese have a specific name for United States citizens:
`Beikokujin.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Beikoku' (equals) `The United States.' . . . (and) `jin'
(equals) `a person.' Therefore specific for a person of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other word. `Amerikajin' . . . means practically the same
thing. `America' as a designation for the United States is
relatively recent in the history of our country's power of
influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, someone does have a name for United States citizens
specifically. Call me `Beikokujin.' Or, call me `Bostonian.' Don't
call me `Bob.' That's a failed Microsoft operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the same subject, Neil F. Dunn of Danvers, Mass. writes,
``Mexicans call us `norteamericanos' (North Americans) even though
anyone from Canada down to and including Panama is a North
American, technically. Go figure.''
</P>
