   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory, U.S.
Government.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY _ As the computer age makes extensive medical records
more readily available, researchers at the CDC and other agencies
find themselves facing a new enemy - privacy advocates. Groups such
as the National Coalition for Patients' Rights and people such as
U.S. Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) argue that the more our lives are
computerized, the more our personal information is subject to
abuse. With HHS Secretary Donna Shalala poised to release medical
privacy regulations sometime in the next few weeks, here is a look
at the issue from the side of those battling disease and those
working to prevent Americans' entire lives from becoming public.
(Eversley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
