<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NBEDFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUBBER AND BEYOND, A LEGACY LIVES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. _ It's not difficult to find the physical
heritage of this city's glory days as the whaling capital of the
world. The mid-19th-century grand Federal-style mansions where
shipowners and captains lived line several New Bedford streets. And
the New Bedford Whaling Museum on Johnny Cake Hill shows off the
artifacts of the era immortalized in Herman Melville's novel
``Moby-Dick,'' including a half-scale replica of a typical whaling
ship and the skeleton of a 33-foot-long humpback whale.
</P>
<P>
   But a New Bedford experience doesn't have to concentrate
completely on artifacts or on bricks and mortar. Along Coggeshall
St., Acushnet Ave., County St., and others in tightknit New Bedford
neighborhoods, a visitor can see, taste, savor, and smell the
varied aromas of another legacy of the whaling era: a powerful
Portuguese presence in the city. An estimated 65 percent of New
Bedford's 100,000 residents are of Portuguese birth or descent,
probably the highest of any community in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the local Portuguese community, who continue a
lively cultural history in restaurants, bakeries, social clubs, and
cafes, has links not to mainland Portugal, but to the Azores, where
whaling was once as central to local life as it was to New
Bedford's. An autonomous territory of Portugal, the Azores are a
group of islands in the Atlantic a little more than halfway between
North America and Europe; its inhabitants speak Portuguese. ``The
Azores were the first place that whaling ships would stop after
leaving New Bedford,'' says whaling museum librarian Judith Downey.
``They'd get fresh water and pick up any additional crew they
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Azorean families were split between their home islands and
New Bedford, keeping in touch through letters and by exchanging
photographs. Currently on display through the end of September in
the Coachman's House on the grounds of the Rotch-Jones-Duff House
and Garden Museum (508-997-1401) at 396 County Road is an
exhibition entitled ``Azorean Connections: Photographic Images of
the Brothers Goulart.''
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the 20th century, Manuel Goulart emigrated to New
Bedford from Fayal in the Azores and became a professional
photographer. His brother, Jose, remained at home, but also took up
photography. The exhibition consists mainly of photographs taken in
the Azores by both brothers over half a century, and vividly evokes
a vanished way of life. Also on view with the photos is a companion
exhibit of more than 200 pieces of traditional Azorean and mainland
Portuguese ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   Sited on a hilltop looking down on New Bedford harbor, the
Rotch-Jones-Duff House and its beautiful grounds, a popular spot
for weddings, occupies an entire city block. It's typical of the
homes owned by the wealthy merchants and shipowners ironically
described in ``Moby Dick.'' ``All these brave houses and flowery
gardens came from the Atlantic, Pacific, and Indian oceans,''
Melville wrote. ``One and all, they were harpooned and dragged
hither from the bottom of the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaling was a traditional Azorean occupation and for centuries
the islanders hunted whales from shore in open boats. A sturdy but
graceful eight-man Azorean whaleboat is one of the permanent
exhibits in the New Bedford Whaling Museum
(508-997-0046/www.whalingmuseum.org). Expansion plans in progress
include adding a new gallery that will be devoted entirely to the
role of Azoreans in the city's whaling history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The connection between the Azores and New Bedford's whaling
and fishing industries is direct, extensive, and continuing, ''
says Arthur Motta, the city's tourism director. ``Whaling ships
also stopped at the Azores on their way back from the whaling
grounds and some Azorean sailors were so homesick that they jumped
ship,'' says Motta. ``But if they wanted to get paid for a three-
or four-year voyage, they had to go on to New Bedford. Most did and
a lot stayed'' in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese seafaring tradition remains strong.``New Bedford
has a fishing fleet of more than 225 vessels,'' Motta notes. ``Many
of them are owned and worked by Portuguese families.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to the whaling museum, and probably the most visited place
in New Bedford, is the Seamen's Bethel, the nondenominational
chapel directly across from it. Described in ``Moby Dick,'' the
bethel is known for its distinctive pulpit shaped like the bow of a
sailing ship. Marble tablets line the walls, moving memorials to
men who died _ typically after falling from a ship's rigging, being
eaten by sharks, drowning when a whale capsized their boat, or
succumbing to fever _ on 19th-century voyages to the far corners of
the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Tablets continue to be added to the bethel. Nowadays, the
tablets tell of local fishermen lost at sea. In contrast to the
Anglo-Saxon names of whalemen memorialized in Melville's day, New
Bedford fishermen remembered in the bethel now often have
Portuguese surnames such as Madeiros, DaSilva, Cardoso, or
Lopes.``We lost a fishing boat and its crew just last year,''
recalls Motta. ``It's a fact of life here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy merchants lived on the heights, but Portuguese
immigrants settled largely around the waterfront in the north and
south ends of the city and in neighboring Fairhaven, still an
active fishing port. Although Portugese social clubs, football (as
in soccer) teams, newspapers, TV programs, and churches abound in
the area, a more tangible way to join in the culture is through
food. There are restaurants, bakeries, and shops selling Portuguese
wines, sausages, and other national specialties that evoke the
authentics tastes and aromas of Portugal and the Azores.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect fancy surroundings. ``Portuguese restaurants
here don't pay much attention to decor,'' acknowledges Motta, ``but
they really concentrate on the food. When you eat in one, you sit
down with local people, truck drivers and fishermen, and it's a
nice experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical dishes, found on just about every restaurant menu,
include kale soup, grilled sardines, seafood casserole (paella),
grilled meat, and of course, linguica, chourico, and other spicy
Portuguese sausage. Portions are invariably massive and accompanied
by a large basket of crusty bread. As a rule, there is a good
selection of imported Portuguese wines and beers in even the
smallest and simplest restaurant. Entrees are usually in the $8 to
$15 range.
</P>
<P>
   New Bedford's best-known and probably most accessible Portuguese
restaurant is Antonio's (508-999-3636) at 267 Coggeshall St. _ it's
right off Route 195 and has a large parking lot. Also popular and
well-regarded are Vasco Da Gama (508-993-4340) at 86 Dartmouth
Street, and Villa Verde (508-993-8483) at 362 Main St., Fairhaven.
</P>
<P>
   However, the largest concentration of Portuguese restaurants is
along Acushnet Ave. It's a long and rather shabby street, but it's
filled with intriguing aromas. Among the spots local people speak
highly of are Cafe Mimo (508-996-9443) at 1528 Acushnet Ave., Cafe
Portugal (508-992-8216) at 1280 Acushnet Ave., and Cafe Funchal
(508-990-1886) at 1708 Acushnet Ave.
</P>
<P>
   The avenue also has a number of bakeries producing sinfully
tasty breads and pastries. These include: Lydia's Bakery
(508-992-1711) at 1656 Acushnet Ave., offering a variety of
country-style breads, pastries, and malassadas (fried and sugared
dough), and Economy Bakery (508-992-9138) at 1685 Acushnet Ave.,
noted for ``pops'' _ small handrolled Portugese rolls that are
great for making sandwiches and having with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Many of New Bedford's Portuguese restaurants essentially cater
to their immediate neighborhoods and can be hard to locate.
However, bakeries like the ones on Achushnet Ave. are easy to find
_ just follow your nose to the source of all those delicious smells
_ and be prepared to give in to temptation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
