<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-WHERE-     09-12 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-WHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THE COLORS CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do the fall colors occur?
</P>
<P>
   Don Smith, Connecticut's state forester, tells us that according
to Native American legend, ``Celestial hunters slew the Great Bear
autumn, and the spilled blood turned the leaves red. The yellow of
fall came from the fat splattering out of the kettle as the hunters
cooked their prize.''
</P>
<P>
   However, scientifically and simply put, trees do not begin
producing fall color, as many believe. Instead, according to the
Maine Forest Service, as the dominant summer green colors fade, the
fall colors that were there all along are unmasked, revealing the
autumn coloration of reds, oranges, and yellows.
</P>
<P>
   And for an even more scientific explanation, this is how Yankee
magazine describes the process: Leaves contain a green pigment
called chlorophyll, which uses the sun's energy to make sugars that
feed the plant. Chlorophyll breaks down in the process but is
continually replaced.
</P>
<P>
   In autumn, things slow down. The leaf is sealed off from the
moisture and nutrients, which eventually causes it to fall from the
tree.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of moisture and nutrients causes chlorophyll to be
replaced more slowly, allowing brown, yellow, and orange pigments
called carotenoids, which have been in the leaf all along, to
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Red and purple pigments called anthocyanins develop in the sap
in late summer. If the autumn weather is bright and cool, and the
nights chilly but not freezing, more anthocyanins are produced,
leading to more brilliant color.
</P>
<P>
   Smith offers this brief guide to leaf color: red only _ red oak,
white oak; yellow only _ quaking aspen, birch, hickory, Norway
maple, tulip tree; red or yellow _ cherry, red maple; brown or
yellow _ silver maple; bronze _ beech; bronze or red _ sugar maple
and scarlet oak; purple or red _ dogwood; purple, red, or yellow _
ash; purple, red, yellow, or orange _ sassafras and sumac.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more than 65 years, a great source of information on fall
foliage has been Yankee magazine, whose September and October
issues feature foliage ideas. Yankee's Web site,
www.NewEngland.com, has a Foliage Central page, and there's a new
book, ``Yankee's Ultimate Guide to Autumn in New England'' ($14.95
in bookstores or by calling 800-729-9265, ext. 220).
</P>
<P>
   Here are foliage hot-line numbers, Web sites, and where to look
for the color in each state, as provided by Yankee magazine and
other sources. Most of the numbers will be active by Wednesday and
updated at least once a week, offering current information on where
the best color can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Maine: 800-777-0317; www.state.me.us. End of September: extreme
north and northwest. First week in October: east and
central-western mountains. Mid-October: south and coastal.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire: 800-386-4664 and 800-258-3608; www.visitnh.gov.
Last week in September: far north. First week in October: north
central. Second week in October: south.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont: 802-828-3239 and 800-VERMONT; www.1-800-VERMONT.com.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts: 800-227-6277; www.massvacation.com/foliage.html.
Color changes west to east. Beginning of October: Berkshires.
Mid-October: Cape and Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island: 401-222-2601; www.visitrhodeisland.com. Color
starts late September and peaks mid-October, moving east.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut: 800-282-6863; www.ctbound.org. Color changes north
to south; it peaks Columbus Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foliologist'' Scotty Johnson: 800-214-8209.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast: For local foliage reports and frequently updated
regional foliage maps, visit www.weather.com.
</P>
<P>
   US Forest Service: national hot line 800-354-4595.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
