<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0402 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-BOS &LR;      09-12 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE PLANS NOW TO SEE NEW ENGLAND'S DAZZLING DISPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the outlook for New England's most colorful season?
``Terrific!''
</P>
<P>
   And that's not the opinion of one person. We talked to a
``foliologist,'' Maine's Leaf Lady, and a couple of forestry
specialists _ and each said the season is going to be ``terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   The foliage season is beginning now and will continue into
November. It starts in the northern reaches of New England and
Canada and slowly moves south. Without fail, there is usually peak
color in most parts of New England during the Columbus Day weekend,
and the week before and after.
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to panic, but for the best foliage viewing you
should do some planning. This is one of the most popular seasons to
hit the road, and that can mean lots of traffic, sold-out inns and
hotels, and waits at attractions and restaurants. So get out those
maps and pick a route or two. Best of all, choose a circular route
so you'll cover more territory and improve your chances of hitting
peak color somewhere along the way. Call ahead for accommodations.
The most popular foliage viewing routes will be crowded, so just
allow more time than usual and you'll have a great ride.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Benson, who has been named Leaf Lady by Maine's Governor
Angus King, is preparing her first report, to be released
Wednesday. It is a pattern other states will be following for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, the foliage season usually runs from the third week
in September through the second week in October, starting north and
moving south and starting at higher elevations and moving lower.
``There is almost always color somewhere in Vermont during that
period,'' says Brian Stone, chief of Forest Management in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Stone adds, ``Spring has been wet and cool, ideal conditions for
tree growth. Several sunny days in late June have brought the green
leaves to peak. Assuming the trend continues, the foliage should be
fully prepared to put on an outstanding show.'' However, Stone
points out that weather conditions from just prior to and until
leaf drop will be the most important factors in leaf color. Heavy
rainfall, high winds, and strong storms can affect the foliage.
Frost timing and cloudy days can also have an impact on the
strength of the colors.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Forest Service rangers also report ideal conditions in
Maine's 17 million acres of forestland. ``Adequate rainfall this
spring and summer is keeping the tree canopy healthy and fire
danger low,'' says Tom Doak, Maine state forester. ``If these
factors remain on course, we're looking at a great fall foliage
season.'' In addition, Clark Granger, a plant pathologist with the
Maine forest service, is seeing growth in the crowns of trees that
were damaged in the 1998 ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to color, ``New England is by far the leader. It's
the image people are looking for,'' says Scotty Johnson. He should
know: He's been following the changing of colors throughout the
country and Canada for some 41 years, making him the nation's only
``foliologist.'' He does this for Tauck World Discovery, a tour
company with a wide range of foliage trips.
</P>
<P>
   Twice weekly through foliage season, he issues reports on the
changing colors from the Ozarks east to New England and Canada
(yes, other areas do have foliage, maybe not as colorful as New
England, but still good) based on observations by Tauck tour
directors in the areas.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf peepers, though, want to know where to go and when. Stone
says most of Vermont's colors are provided by sugar and red maples.
Their reds, oranges, and yellows are always spectacular, and the
state is renowned for its foliage in part because of the landscape
setting in which it appears: mixed hardwood and softwood
interspersed with rustic farms and small villages, vistas of Lake
Champlain, or backdrops of the White, Green, and Adirondack
mountains. Even small amounts of color can create beautiful scenes
with these elements.
</P>
<P>
   The Leaf Lady salutes Maine for its mountains, lakes, oceanside,
and especially for Camden Hills State Park where the foliage views
from Mount Battie contrast with the blue of Penobscot Bay. ``It
doesn't get much better than that,'' she says, adding ``Where else
can you top off a day of foliage viewing with a lobster dinner by
the ocean?'' Another plus for Maine is its 17.5 million acres of
forests that hold some 50 species of trees, all of which knit a
beautiful mosaic of foliage color.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Connecticut. ``Connecticut's geography makes it
the perfect destination for lovers of fall foliage,'' says Don
Smith, Connecticut state forester. ``Just as northern New England's
fall foliage is winding down, Connecticut's colors are getting
ready for their big burst of color.'' He adds, ``Only a few regions
of the world have seasonal displays of color as spectacular as
Connecticut's.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth, though, is that no matter where you go in New England
you'll find some awe-inspiring scenes. New Hampshire's Kancamagus
Highway in the White Mountains is one of the most famous drives,
being one of the designated scenic byway loops in the country.
You'll travel some 33 miles through the White Mountain National
Forest, past waterfalls, mountain brooks, and hiking trails _ and
it's a great place to watch for moose. Another inspiring drive is
through the close-to-Boston Monadnock region with its classic New
England villages like Fitzwilliam and the most climbed mountain in
the nation, Mount Monadnock.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is famous for the Mohawk Trail, Route 2, from
Orange to Williamstown. While this is one of the busiest roads in
foliage season, it is also one of the easiest routes because it's a
straight shot from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Having driven for years from Orange to Boston, I can testify the
route is beautiful, even in the rain. It's also a road you don't
have to stick to; there is hidden beauty along many of the roads
that branch off it. And Bostonians don't even have to drive that
far. The Blue Hills, a 5,000-acre reservation just nine miles south
of the city, can be as colorful as any northern forest.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be heresy for a New Englander to say so, other
areas do have colorful autumns. There's now a greater awareness of
this than before. Johnson says when he started out in 1960 as a
bell captain at the Pines Hotel in Digby, Nova Scotia, the place
was all closed up by fall. Now Nova Scotia is promoting its fall
colors, and the hotel is open during foliage season.
</P>
<P>
   So if you can't make it to New England, check out Scotty's
forecast for other areas. Nova Scotia hits its peak in mid-October
because it is close to the Atlantic Ocean, which provides a
moderating influence on both temperature and color. Ontario,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Colorado, and Wisconsin are other areas
inundating us with reasons to visit during their colorful season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
