<HEADLINE>
FORGET ABOUT LARRY KING; SEND IN OSCAR THE GROUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ITALICS)An emergency meeting of the Commission on Presidential
Debates is called to order ...(UNITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: (banging gavel) Welcome. Let's recap where we are. Mr.
Bush has rejected a proposal to meet Mr. Gore for three prime-time
debates on all networks. Mr. Bush has suggested one prime-time
debate, plus joint appearances on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and
CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' And Mr. Gore has rejected that.
</P>
<P>
   So this morning, Mr. Cheney and Mr. Lieberman are here to try to
help us reach an agreement on where and when their running mates
will debate. Mr. Lieberman, I understand you have a proposal to
counter the counter-proposal?
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman: Al Gore _ the next president of the United States and
a man whom I am honored to call my friend! _ respectfully offers to
meet Mr. Bush anytime, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: (clearing throat) I see. By ``anywhere,'' I take it
that you still do not mean ``Meet the Press'' or ``Larry King
Live''?
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman: No, sir, although we do have the utmost admiration
for Tim Russert and Larry King, as well as all other members of the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: Uh-huh. Mr. Cheney?
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: George W. Bush _ the next president of the United States
and a man whom I am honored to call my friend! _ is of the opinion
that Mr. Russert is a major-league (bleep)hole.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: I see. And that's your official position?
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: (nodding head) Yes, it is. Big time. And we're not so
very fond of Larry King, either.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: (sighing) OK, let's see if we can't find some common
ground here.
</P>
<P>
   (ITALICS)Several hours pass.(UNITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: George W. Bush, who believes it is time to put
plain-spoken Americans in the White House, will agree to one
prime-time debate, plus an appearance on World Wrestling
Federation's ``Smackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman: Al Gore vehemently objects to the gratuitous violence
of ``Smackdown.'' We also respectfully urge Mr. Bush to put up or
shut up!
</P>
<P>
   (ITALICS)Several more hours pass.(UNITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: All right, then. We now have an agreement on one
prime-time network debate, which is pretty much where we began this
morning. Mr. Cheney, I think you're next.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: George W. Bush, who believes it is time to elect people
who say what they mean, will meet Mr. Gore's bid of one prime-time
network debate and raise him one cameo on ``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman: Of course, we believe very strongly in the role of
faith in public life. We'll meet your angel and raise you one PBS
forum, moderated by Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: Mr. Cheney?
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: George W. Bush, who also believes strongly in the role
of faith in public life, is of the opinion that Barney is a
major-league (bleep)hole. And Baby Bop's voice grates on our
nerves. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: (sighing) OK, so that's no to PBS and Barney and no to
the WWF and Smackdown, but yes to ``Touched.'' Anything else, Mr.
Cheney?
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: We can talk about educational TV. In the spirit of
compromise, Mr. Bush is willing to appear on one of those boring
cable TV shows about computers. We do so in honor of the man who
created the Internet, Al Gore. (Room erupts into shouting.)
</P>
<P>
   (ITALICS)Several more hours pass.(UNITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman: Listen, friend, if I hear you call one more person
``major-league'' anything, I'm going to reach across this table and
...
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: (striking gavel) All right, all right! Gentlemen,
please! (Sighing deeply) We now have one network debate, one cameo
on ``Touched by an Angel,'' one run-toward-the-surf scene each on
``Baywatch,'' one five-minute diatribe on ``ER'' about the rising
cost of prescription drugs, and one panel discussion with
Teletubbies, if -- per the GOP stipulation -- Tinky Winky agrees to
sit next to Mr. Gore. Have I left out anything?
</P>
<P>
   Cheney and Lieberman: (in unison) I thought I saw a puddy-cat. I
know I did, I know I did!
</P>
<P>
   Chairman: Oh, yes, that's right -- and one panel discussion on
the Cartoon Network, moderated by Tweety Bird. Th-th-that's all,
folks?
</P>
<P>
   Cheney (nodding) Oh, yeah. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
