<SLUG> BC-AUTO-TOYOTA-PRIUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONSUMERS ARE GREEN WITH ENVY OVER NEW TOYOTA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The world's first _ and so far most practical _
hybrid gasoline/electric vehicle has arrived at Toyota dealerships,
but don't count on taking one home anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Although dealerships across the nation have at least one of the
new Toyota Prius sedans each, they are for demonstration purposes
only, and would-be consumers must get on a waiting list to buy one,
dealers and Toyota officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got about 20 people who have put deposits down, and
we're looking at probably October before we deliver the first
one,'' said Roger Johnston, sales manager at Cavender Toyota in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   There is a huge amount of consumer interest, though, for this
all-new car that gets 52 miles per gallon in the city and 45 mpg on
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cars with traditional gasoline engines, the Prius gets
better fuel economy in town because at speeds less than 30 mph, it
operates almost exclusively on its 44-horsepower electric motor. At
speeds above that, or when it needs to recharge its batteries, the
70-horsepower, 1.5-liter gasoline engine kicks in automatically.
</P>
<P>
   At highway speeds, the gasoline engine is used for cruising, but
for passing or whenever an extra burst of power is needed, the
electric motor kicks in along with the gas one. And it is at that
point that the driver realizes that the greenest sedan on the
market makes no excuses, and there are no tradeoffs: This car has
as much zip as any other compact sedan on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really are no compromises when you buy a Prius,''
Johnston said. ``It seats five people, has plenty of power and
costs no more than many other cars in this size class. When people
come by to test-drive our Prius, the acceleration and the roominess
really surprise them.''
</P>
<P>
   The price is $20,000, the same that Honda charges for its
two-seat Insight hybrid that made its U.S. debut in February. But
unlike the Insight, the Prius has room enough for a whole family;
it even has a trunk that, despite carrying the car's
nickel-metal-hydride battery pack, has plenty of room for luggage.
</P>
<P>
   And there are no options; everything comes with the vehicle at
the base price, including automatic air-conditioning,
AM/FM/cassette stereo, power windows/mirrors/door locks with remote
control, antilock brakes and an eight-year/100,000-mile warranty on
the battery pack and hybrid drive system.
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable thing about the Prius is that even though it
has an electric motor, it never needs to be connected to an
external power source for recharging like traditional electric cars
do.
</P>
<P>
   The battery pack is recharged by the onboard gasoline engine
that runs both the drive wheels and a built-in generator. But there
is a second way the batteries are recharged: whenever the brakes
are applied, or the car is coasting, the drive wheels automatically
turn the electric motor, which goes into a reverse mode and becomes
a generator of electricity, rather than a consumer of it.
</P>
<P>
   That harnesses otherwise unused power, much the way that a
hydroelectric generating plant uses falling water to make
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Having an electric motor without having to use an external
recharger is what makes the Prius palatable to consumers. Electric
cars have never caught on with manufacturers or consumers because
of their limited range between charges.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Prius, air pollution is minimized in city driving _
where exhaust fumes are the worst _ because it reverts to
nonpolluting electric power in stop-and-go traffic. The Honda
hybrid doesn't do that _ it uses its gasoline engine all the time,
with the electric motor on hand for power boosting only.
</P>
<P>
   Styling is quite nice, too _ very similar to that of the Toyota
Echo and Ford Focus sedans.
</P>
<P>
   The Prius, which looks like a subcompact on the outside, has
more than 100 cubic feet of interior space and is almost as roomy
as the nation's best-selling car, the midsize Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota began selling the Prius in Japan in December 1997, and
has delivered more than 35,000 of them in that country so far.
</P>
<P>
   The car just went on sale this summer in the United States,
although the first deliveries aren't due until later this year.
There are a few leased vehicles out with consumers already,
however, in a special program that Toyota promoted on the Prius Web
site at www.toyota.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest in these cars is unbelievable,'' Toyota spokesman
Clyde Hopkins said from Dallas. ``Demand has far outstripped
supply, and we're looking at about a three-month wait from order to
delivery right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese Prius was designed for the roads there, and has a
58 horsepower, 1.0-liter engine. For the U.S. market, where highway
traffic runs at higher speeds, Toyota increased the power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Prius was introduced in Japan, consumer response has
been phenomenal,'' said Steve Sturm, Toyota's U.S. vice president
for marketing. ``We hope to generate this same level of interest
and excitement in America. Our goal is to sell or lease an initial
volume of 1,000 a month. We anticipate that the highest sales
volumes will primarily be in congested urban areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The smoothness of the hybrid drive system is a big selling
point, Johnston said. ``It's very quiet, and the shift between
electric and gasoline power is automatic and not even noticeable.
The biggest thing to get used to is not hearing the engine when you
start up.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ignition key was turned to ``Start,'' a video screen on
the dash showed ``Ready,'' but there usually was no noise of an
engine starting because the gasoline engine doesn't come on right
away.
</P>
<P>
   Driving away from a parking space or a traffic signal, the
vehicle felt like an electric golf cart, although much more
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions were when the gasoline engine was needed right away
because battery power was low, or the air-conditioner was running
full blast.
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioning can pull the battery charge down very fast, so
the car automatically starts the gasoline engine to get the
electric generator operating.
</P>
<P>
   Americans who buy the Prius may qualify for a tax deduction of
up to $2,000 for purchasing a ``qualified clean-fuel vehicle,''
Toyota says.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance will be minimal, Toyota says. The all-aluminum
gasoline engine is limited to a maximum of 4,500 rpm, which will
give it a super long life (most engines reach the so-called red
line at 6,000-7,000 rpm).
</P>
<P>
   The electric motor is a permanent-magnet type with internal
components that do not wear out. It creates a whopping 258
foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   The body and interior of the Prius were styled at Toyota's Calty
Design Research studio in Southern California, and combine short
front and rear overhangs with a large, upright, and tall cabin for
exceptional roominess. It even accommodates very tall people
because of the high roof.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, the nation's oldest and largest environmental
organization, has honored the Prius with its ``excellence in
environmental engineering'' award for 2000, the first year that the
group has given out the award recognizing new products that make a
substantial contribution to improving the environment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
