u a BC-SCI-PLASTIC-BOS &LR;      09-12 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLASTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PLASTIC SURGEONS SHOULD JUST SAY `NO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who watched singer Michael Jackson's nose change from
dark-skinned and normal-sized to pale and pointy _ not to say
otherworldly _ may have pondered the question:
</P>
<P>
   When should a plastic surgeon say no to a client?
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons themselves argue about it all the time. A favorite
subject for debate is New York socialite Jocelyne Wildenstein, who
has posed proudly for magazine spreads to show off the look she
achieved through multiple surgeries, a look that critics have
described as somewhere between cat and Klingon.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Americans turn to tummy tucks, chemical peels and other
cosmetic surgeries in record numbers, the debate has become much
more than a parlor game. Now, as 230,000 people a year undergo
liposuction alone, the courts may soon weigh in on when enough is
enough.
</P>
<P>
   This summer a New York judge ruled that a 53-year-old New York
woman, identified in court papers only as Mrs. Lynn G., could sue
her surgeon, contending he should have known she had a psychiatric
condition that gave her a distorted image of her own body. As a
result, she claims, she was incapable of giving informed consent to
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   By her own count, Lynn G. has had liposuction on her chin,
stomach, knees and thighs; several eyelid lifts; eyebrow tattoos,
injections of fat to remove wrinkles; a tummy tuck; a nose job; and
other surgeries over 29 years. For the last seven, the man behind
the scalpel was Norman Hugo, a former chief of plastic surgery at
Columbia Presbyterian Hospital in New York City and past president
of the American Society of Plastic Surgeons, whom she sued over
scarring from the procedures.
</P>
<P>
   While most surgeons scoffed at the lawsuit, it got their
attention _ especially after it ran in The New York Observer, which
chronicles the antics of wealthy Manhattanites. It spurred much
wringing of hands over whether plastic surgeons would someday be
forced to get a psychiatrist's clearance for every patient.
</P>
<P>
   But some called it a much-needed wakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused physicians to take a second look,'' said Dr. Paula
Moynahan, who practices on Fifth Avenue and in Waterbury, Conn. She
went so far as to fire off a press release calling on her
colleagues to be more scrupulous about turning clients away if they
ask for surgery that seems wrong for them or if they seem to want
it for the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some doctors believe that up to 25 percent of the
patients who come to them requesting plastic surgery should be
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Gorney, a Napa, California, plastic surgeon who has
recently become medical director for a medical malpractice insurer,
said he rejected ``one in five, maybe one in four'' of the would-be
patients who came for consultations at his practice. Moynahan said
she
</P>
<P>
   turns away 15 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gorney refused to talk about Lynn G.'s doctor, Hugo, whom he
called a good friend, but he said that certain patients should
prompt ``an automatic refusal.''
</P>
<P>
   For example?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he said, ``if she looks like she's taking three G's while
sitting still'' because her skin is pulled back so tightly from
multiple facelifts. Or if her earlobes are pulled low from having
loose jowl skin sutured to them one too many times. Or if she has
``that stare-y look, the look of eternal surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Another red flag, he said, is sheer quantity of previous
surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's had a rhinoplasty (nose job), a face lift, Botox,
lipo, a boob job _ forget it. This patient is a plastoholic!''
</P>
<P>
   That's an overreaction, said Dr. Daniel C. Morello, president of
the American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery, another
professional group. Plastic surgery thrives on ``repeat business,''
he said, and it's impossible to make a blanket statement about how
much is too much.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who claims to turn away one in five patients, he said, is
exaggerating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking maybe 10 patients a year'' who should be
rejected for plastic surgery, he said. ``You have to be very alert
to pick out those 10. Do we miss one sometimes? Yes, we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Morello, who practices in New York's Westchester County, and
uses the online handle ``nipntuck,'' declined to comment on
Moynahan's press release chiding plastic surgeons. However, he
remarked, ``Anyone who puts out a press release is probably looking
for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Morello said, concerns about unnecessary surgery or
inappropriate surgery are very real, and recent events have
prompted a talk on the matter to be scheduled for the society's
annual conference in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of drawing the line on excessive plastic surgery is
exacerbated by two trends:
</P>
<P>
   The patient-empowerment movement, which includes both bonafide
education of the public about their choices and increasing
advertisement for cosmetic procedures, has spawned a population of
cosmetic surgery consumers with increasingly specific _ and
sometimes odd _ demands.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost-cutting and paperwork of managed care may have
spawned a population of doctors willing to comply with any demand
as long as the customer pays in cash. Cosmetic surgery, with its
up-front payments, soaring popularity and no insurance-company
involvement, is increasingly attractive to frustrated doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result, the number of cosmetic procedures have
skyrocketed over the last decade. Breast augmentation operations
alone have increased by 413 percent since 1992, according to the
American Society of Plastic Surgeons, while liposution is up 389
percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic surgeons' also worry that dermatologists and others they
view as less qualified are crowding onto their lucrative turf: In a
recent advertising campaign, they urged consumers to choose
board-certified plastic surgeons only. But they also worry that
their field may draw surgeons with questionable ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastic surgery has now become the last refuge of the
freebooter or the pirate,'' said Gorney, the California plastic
surgeon who is now medical director of The Doctors Company.
</P>
<P>
   But a more subtle problem is that the very idea of cosmetic
surgery makes it difficult for doctors to deny their patients'
wishes. In fact, many patients are surprised to learn that surgeons
can turn them away.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic surgery markets itself in the language of
self-actualization: A woman who enlarges her breasts or
liposuctions her thighs isn't pandering to society's notions of
beauty; she's taking charge, getting what she wants and enhancing
her self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   After tallying up data that showed 26 percent more women had
liposuction, breast augmentation and eyelid lifts in 1998 than in
1999, the American Society of Plastic Surgeons issued this upbeat
message:
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking as good as you feel is a continuing trend among
women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We enhance people's self esteem by changing their body
image,'' explained Moynahan, who also has a skin care spa and
salon.
</P>
<P>
   However, Moynahan, Morello and Gorney all said that many
patients come in with life problems that surgery can't change.
Those are the ones to watch out for: the woman who wants larger
breasts because her husband is cheating on her. Or someone who
seems unable to realistically assess how they look and may be
suffering from a condition called body dysmorphic disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Moynahan said she referred one would-be client to an ocular
plastic surgeon for reconstructive surgery because she'd had too
many eyelid lifts. The woman refused and wanted still more cosmetic
surgery, telling Moynahan, ``I have maintentnace and fine tuning
done every couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   But where to draw the line, when the profession constantly touts
statistics about how better-looking people get better jobs, higher
salaries and more personal happiness?
</P>
<P>
   Gorney said an example of surgery for the right reasons is a
woman who meets a nice man, but is embarrassed to get intimate
because of her small breasts. But others might suggest different
solutions, like psychological counseling, or, say, a heart-to-heart
talk with her would-be lover.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors cited problems with patients who want to look like
a celebrity. Dr. William Adams said young men have come to his
Boston office asking to look like Ringo Starr, Lee Majors and even
Cher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do an operation that I don't feel aesthetically
comfortable with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the American Society of Plastic Surgeons' code of ethics
forbids surgery ``that is not calculated to improve or benefit the
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, though, it's still a matter of taste. The woman
dubbed ``the Bride of Wildenstein'' by the New York Post says she
is pleased with the surgery that has made her nearly
unrecognizable. Her doctor, Richard Coburn, does not do interviews,
but his peers are reluctant to condemn him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's happy, and Dr. Coburn is happy, then mazel tov,''
Moynahan said. ``I don't think she has a good result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
