<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-VENTS-BOS &LR;      09-12 1635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE MOUNTS THAT LIFE MAY HAVE BEGUN IN A SCALDING SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For humans, it's about as hellish an environment as the
imagination could ever conjure: Bone-crushing pressure, water hot
enough to melt a lead pipe, and fire (red-hot molten rock) and
brimstone (the ancient name for sulfur) spewing up constantly from
below.
</P>
<P>
   But these violent and unearthly places, known as hydrothermal
vents, may have a surprisingly nurturing side: New evidence,
including a recent report in the journal Science, is lending
support to a controversial theory that these vents at the bottom of
the world's oceans may have been the cradle in which life began.
</P>
<P>
   It now seems more likely than ever that the spark of life was
first lit in the vicinity of such an inferno in the ocean's abyss
around 3.5 billion years ago, and it was from there that the first
cells began their long evolutionary trek toward the phenomenal
variety of living creatures we see today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions are just right for the formation of organic
compounds, for (heat-loving) microorganisms to develop, and for a
food-chain web to emerge.'' said Everett Shock, a planetary
scientist at Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   That's a dramatic shift from the original idea of life's
beginning espoused by Charles Darwin in 1871 _ and long supported
by the majority of scientists studying life's origins. Darwin
argued that the likeliest place for the beginning of life was in
some ``warm little pond,'' at the boundary between land and ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when oceanographer John B. Corliss first proposed the
thermal vents idea two decades ago, the idea was considered so
outlandish that he couldn't even get his papers published in the
scientific journals. But, he said last week, ``I have always known
that it was just a matter of time until the evidence would be as
overwhelming to others as it was to me 15 or 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the warm little pond seems a more credible place
for the incubator of life than a place with conditions so extreme
that it would instantly parboil the life out of the vast majority
of the world's living things. But the story is more complicated
than that description suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long been puzzled by the earliest stages of
life's evolution, in which raw chemicals served up by the cooling,
newly-formed Earth somehow combined and contorted to become the
exquisitely complex collection of molecules and membranes that made
up the first living cells. The probabilities involved, some have
said, seem as unlikely as throwing a bunch of metal fragments into
the air and having them assemble themselves into a 747 jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments in the laboratory have shown that some of the basic
chemical building blocks of life could, in fact, be created under
the conditions that might have existed in a warm little pond in the
planet's earliest days. But it is still a long way from those
building blocks to the complexity of even the simplest amoeba.
</P>
<P>
   Even if some of the basic chemicals of life could form in such a
pond, said George Cody of the Carnegie Institution in Washington,
lead author of the recent Science paper, ``it seems like you would
have just this dead soup. How would you get it going, how would you
prime it'' to produce living, evolving organisms?
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, at the seemingly hostile hydrothermal vents, it
turned out, the conditions might be much more favorable for the
creation of life's complexity. Such vents are actually very
energetic chemical reactors, as Corliss first deduced. Some of
these reactions would take place in the superheated water coming
from the vents, he figured, but most would take place in the cooler
water seeping out nearby, already partly cooled by contact with
seawater.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, several others, including Washington University's
Shock, biochemist Harold Morowitz of George Mason University and
German scientist Gunter Wachtershauser, have published numerous
papers describing the life-giving potential of the vents in
ever-greater detail.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's hard to blame Darwin for overlooking
hydrothermal vents. They weren't even discovered until a 1977
expedition to the seafloor off the Galapagos islands, led by
Corliss and using the Alvin submersible from the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution. Corliss had deduced the existence of
these sea floor vents from indirect evidence.
</P>
<P>
   At some hydrothermal vents seawater that seeped down into the
seafloor and came into contact with red-hot molten rock comes
spewing back out, heated to temperatures as high as 660 degrees
Fahrenheit and loaded with dissolved minerals that precipitate out
immediately on contact with the cold surrounding water, producing
the visible plumes called ``black smokers''. At the Galapagos vent
that was first discovered, though, the water was cooled below the
surface and came out at a modest 68 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   But what was completely unexpected was the rich variety of life
that surrounded and was sustained by the vents. This life, it
turned out, was sustained by the energy contained in chemical
compounds in the rich, hot water. It was the first time any form of
life had been discovered that was not ultimately supported by the
energy of sunlight. Because such environments are likely to be
found on many other planets, some scientists think the discovery
instantly raised the odds that life could have emerged on other
worlds as well.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the astonishing discovery of a whole ecosystem of
living things _ including strange varieties of crabs and clams and
exotic blood-red tube worms _ Corliss began thinking about the
possibility that this environment could have been the site of
life's origin. His first public talk about the new theory was given
in 1981, but the idea remained far outside the scientific
mainstream for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``People laughed at Corliss when he first mentioned it,'' said
Morowitz, a biochemist at George Mason University in Virginia.
``I'm the first to have taken him seriously . . . Now it's coming
into the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   In those early years, Corliss struggled even to get his
unorthodox suggestion into print; a major paper detailing the
concept was rejected by the the editor of the journal Nature in
1988, apparently without even the normal formality of a peer
review. But soon after that, papers by other authors began to take
up the theory and carry it forward.
</P>
<P>
   Morowitz advanced the idea by making detailed calculations about
the chemical chain of events needed to make life possible. That
work, and Morowitz's realization of the crucial role that may have
been played by organic chemical reactions taking place at high
temperatures and pressures, led to the laboratory research at
Carnegie Institution by Cody and a team of researchers, detailed in
the recent Science paper.
</P>
<P>
   The chemistry of such reactions under conditions present in
hydrothermal vents turns out to be an area that has been little
studied, partly because it requires unusually difficult and
expensive laboratory procedures and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But in the experiment at Carnegie, an important fact emerged:
every key chemical reaction upon which the basic biochemistry of
life depends can indeed be produced in the conditions of the
deep-sea vents. The last such reaction that had not been
demonstrated under these conditions, the synthesis of an iron
compound called pyruvate that is crucial to many biological
reactions, was demonstrated in their experiment.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't prove that life began in the vents, but it
certainly helps to show that it is possible. By contrast, very few
of these crucial chemical products are known to be produced under
the relatively benign conditions of the ocean surface or of
Darwin's warm little pond.
</P>
<P>
   As Morowitz describes it, the competing theories were based on
where the energy came from to spark life on Earth: Did it come from
the heat and light coming down from the sun _ from the heavens _ or
from chemical energy percolating up from the hot depths of the
Earth _ from hell? ``Everyone heavily favored the `heaven'
concept'' at first, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But German scientist Wachtershauser started to turn the
intellectual tide with a series of papers in the 1980s describing
the biochemical steps that could have led to the origins of life
under hydrothermal vent conditions. Others have argued that the
asteroids that pummeled the Earth during its first few hundred
million years would have made the depths a much safer place for
life to arise.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the biggest reasons for the turnaround in thinking
came from the work of Carl Woese, a University of Illinois
microbiologist who has analyzed in detail the family tree of life,
using the latest techniques of genetic analysis. His work has shown
convincingly that microorganisms that are adapted to extreme high
temperatures, called hyperthermophiles, are the most ancient forms
of life on this planet, and thus likely to resemble the earliest
ancestors of all life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first step in turning around this fairly dogmatic
attitude that life began at `room temperature','' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lovley, chairman of the microbiology department at the
University of Massachusetts, Amherst, produced yet another line of
evidence in support of the idea. He has published results of
laboratory experiments showing that microbes found deep underground
today all seem to use a chemical process involving iron to
metabolize their food, as would be expected under the deep-ocean
origins theory.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lovley said, the idea that started out as heresy 20 years
ago has become ``very well accepted. . . You'll see it in the
textbooks now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
