<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ Al Gore and George W. Bush tangle
over a Republican TV ad that flashes the word ``rats'' on the
screen for a fraction of a second during a 30-second spot
criticizing Gore's proposal on prescription drug coverage. The
candidates comment as Bush presses his health care initiatives with
voters in Florida and Gore and his running mate Joe Lieberman push
their education initiatives by campaigning on school buses in
southern Ohio. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Washington) _ The Federal Election Commission is
expected to decide whether Pat Buchanan or John Hagelin should
receive the $12.6 million due the Reform Party nominee. Last week,
FEC staffers recommended that the commission vote in favor of
Buchanan. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-READINESS (Washington) _ Weighing in on what has become
a major campaign issue, a frontline Air Force general says the
military readiness of his crews and equipment is on the mend after
several years of decline. The picture of the U.S. military painted
by Gen. Gregory Martin, commander of Air Force units in Europe, is
considerably less bleak than that of Republicans George W. Bush and
Dick Cheney. By ERIC ROSENBERG. Story will also be filed in the
POLITICAL NEWS (``p) category.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Thank you, Gloria Steinem. The
feminist pioneer who helped women move into the economic, political
and legal mainstream of our male-dominated culture has done it
again. Once dead set against marriage, calling it a form of
imprisonment, Steinem has gotten married herself now that she is a
senior citizen. She is demonstrating that age need not be a barrier
to wedded bliss, a psychological breakthrough as important in its
way as the independence she has always preached. By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
