A0418 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     09-12 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS SHOULD THINK TWICE ABOUT IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iowa hopes to bolster its declining workforce by enticing
immigrants to the land of tall corn and nervous pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily an agricultural state, Iowa is 96 percent white and
the average farmer is 58 years old. Iowa ranks third in the nation
in the percentage of seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Iowa retains every single one of its graduating high-school
students between now and 2005, we'll have a decrease of 3 percent
of the available work force,'' said Indianola mayor Jerry Kelley,
one of many civic leaders who favors immigrant recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Iowa is an unusual one for immigrants, who are
more used to being shunned by communities than welcomed. It also
raises the possibility that other states suffering from declining
population will seek them out, creating a competition for their
services.
</P>
<P>
   As immigrants find themselves more in demand, they will have to
be more discriminating, if that is the word, as to where they
settle down. While Iowa may seem like a nice place to live, with
its green fields of corn and white farmhouses, a closer inspection
of the state may make one think twice about relocating there.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Iowa is the No. 1 beef and pork producing state in
America, which puts it at the top of the hit list for PETA and
other organizations that believe the human diet should consist
entirely of organically grown celery. It is hard to enjoy a
medium-rare cheeseburger while some animal-rights nut is whacking
you over the head with a placard.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is also the No. 1 producer of corn, the No. 1 producer of
soybeans, the No. 1 producer of grain and the home of Quaker Oats,
the world's largest cereal company. Clearly, Iowa is overly fixated
on this ``No. 1'' thing and most likely has some issues related to
sharing that can only be worked out over years of counseling, most
likely at taxpayer expense.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is the birthplace of Grant Wood, the artist responsible for
``American Gothic.'' Look at the painting and ask yourself: Are
those the kind of people I want as neighbors? And what's the deal
with the pitchfork?
</P>
<P>
   According to Ripley's Believe It Or Not, Burlington's Snake
Alley is the most crooked street in America. This is not something
Burlington or any other city should be proud of. If they had any
sense, they'd dig it up, straighten it out and maybe line it with a
couple of Wal-Marts or maybe a Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne was born in Winterset. Only his name wasn't John
Wayne, it was Marion Robert Morrison. Any state where they name
their male children ``Marion'' is a state that I would have to
think twice about moving to.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of celebrities, guess who owned a farm in Eldon, Iowa,
before their marriage broke up? Tom and Roseanne Arnold. I'll take
the ``American Gothic'' couple as neighbors, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   Winnebagos are made in Winnebago County, Iowa. I don't bring
this up for any special reason; I just thought it might be
something you'd like to know.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is the only state name that begins with two vowels. This is
a pathetic observation and is just another example of how the
people of Iowa have way too much time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the movie ``Field of Dreams'' was filmed in Dyersville.
It was a corny movie (literally), but it did have a good line that
immigrants may want to consider before relocating:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this heaven?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
