<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SAYS TECH STOCKS DRIVE BAY AREA'S REAL ESTATE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The wealth generated by technology company
stocks has a direct connection to rising home prices here, the
Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco said.
</P>
<P>
   While this is not exactly news to real estate agents and many
home buyers in the region, ``it has given us confirmation of what
we were hearing,'' said John Krainer, an economist at the Fed and
author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a factor in real estate for more than a year
now,'' said Alain Pinel, regional vice president for Coldwell
Banker Residential Real Estate. ``Venture capital for these new
high-tech companies is generating the money through stock options,
up-front bonuses used to hire employees and IPOs.'' IPOs are
initial public offerings of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Pinel said housing prices jumped 40 to 45 percent in the past
year in the nine-county San Francisco Bay Area. San Francisco and
neighboring areas boast some of the nation's highest real estate
prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
