<HEADER>
A0437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-AUSSIE-TALK-HNS &LR;      09-12 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSSIE-TALK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEY, MATE. SPEECH IS GOLDEN IN THE LAND DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Greetings from Australia, where pubs are
``hotels,'' enthusiastic drinkers are ``tossers,'' the home team's
basketball men are ``boomers'' and its field hockey women are
``hockeyroos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Land Down Under is awash in euphemisms, quaint expressions
and messages that are downright inscrutable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please remove boot and bonnet'' exhorted one sign in the
Homebush Bay section of Sydney, where many of the Olympic venues
are located.
</P>
<P>
   Take off your shoes and hat? In America, no shoes, no shirt
means no service.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pyrmont Bridge Hotel, which is to say a pub, a sign
informed patrons ``Whilst the hotel is open 24 hours, alcohol is
not served between 7 and 9 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Go home, sleep it off and come back, it seems to be suggesting.
</P>
<P>
   For those not cut out to be parents, a photo studio downtown
might be the solution. It offered ``Kids shot here _ $25.'' That's
about U.S. $14. Heck of a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hotels full of tossers, Australia has a major
jones for gambling. City streets are chock full of ``pokie
parlors,'' the term for slot machines. Off-track betting on horse
racing is also prevalent. But in New South Wales, where Sydney is
located, gambling on the Olympic Games is not permitted. Just in
case you were thinking about putting down a few quid on the modern
pentathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of gambling, I went for a little gambol upon arriving in
Sydney, through Oxford Street. Victoria Bitter is the early leader
in the clubhouse for best draft beer in Oz.
</P>
<P>
   The adult bookstores on Oxford, of which there are many, are
either located upstairs or downstairs, never street level. There's
symbolism there, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers buzzing around town in clean little white sedans
all appear to be wearing their seat belts. Cab drivers do not,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Darling Harbour, indeed a darling harbor, is a gathering place
for visitors and locals alike as they stroll the waterside
promenade.
</P>
<P>
   While I was draining a Victoria Bitter, or VB for brevity's
sake, two sheilas (Australia's enduring term for young women)
joined me at my table and reported that Friday's rehearsal for the
Opening Ceremonies had not gone well.
</P>
<P>
   The word they used rhymed with spit. I'm sure there's a
euphemism for that, too. I'll find it. It's early.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0125 </DOCNO>
