A0457 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      09-12 0301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEACHER PAY HIKES FORCE SCHOOLS TO CUT BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's public school system is
considering cutting its budget by $23 million over the next two
years to pay for higher teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education proposal calls for cutting its
administrative staff, deferring maintenance of buildings and
reducing overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of money, but it's for the right reasons and it
moves us in the direction of spending money efficiently,''
Superintendent Arlene Ackerman said Monday. ``These are hard
decisions. But we have made a statement that it's important to pay
our teachers and staff competitive salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   In late August, the San Francisco Unified School District
announced raises of 5 percent to 20 percent for nearly 6,000
teachers and classroom aides. The salary increases will cost the
district $39.5 million this year and $44 million the next school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the district will receive more money this school year
from the state, deep cuts are necessary to make up for the salary
increases, Ackerman said. The administration wants to reduce
spending by $9 million this year and $14 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Unified, with 65,000 students, is California's
fifth-largest district. Audits have criticized the school district
for poor accounting records, a lack of oversight and personnel
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman, who quit as superintendent in Washington, D.C., to
take over the San Francisco system this summer, has reshuffled the
administration here, removing the district's chief financial and
reassigning 25 teachers and principals who worked in the
administrative office to schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
