<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FUEL (London) _ Truckers protesting against high fuel
prices blockaded highways across Western Europe on Tuesday, with
Britain poised to invoke emergency powers to prevent rising panic
by drivers from turning into a national crisis. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   EU-AUSTRIA (Paris) _ The European Union may lift sanctions on
Austria on Tuesday, although France wants some kind of monitoring
of Austria to continue. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   AUSCHWITZ-SYNAGOGUE (Oswiecim, Poland) _ A synagogue near
Auschwitz has opened for the first time since World War II. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-AIDS (Dateline to come) _ Caribbean countries have
adopted a plan to fight AIDS. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-PROTESTS (Melbourne) _ In scene reminiscent of the
violent protests at the World Trade Organization summit meeting in
Seattle last November, thousands of protesters have tried to
sabotage a meeting here of the World Economic Forum, clashing with
riot police and blocking the site of the conference. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ANNAN (United Nations) _ On the opening of the U.N. General
Assembly session, where Secretary-General Kofi Annan defended the
United Nation's role in globalization. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ALBRIGHT (United Nations) _ On Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's annual meeting with women foreign ministers. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CLINTON (Washington) _ Congressional leaders meet with
Clinton over legislative agenda. By Lizetter Alvarez and Marc
Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   SUBSIDIZED-RENT (Washington) _ HUD will increase the payments to
landlords for subsidized rental housing for low-income families. By
Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest New York
Times/CBS News poll on the presidential campaign. By Richard L.
Berke. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum, Ohio) _ Al Gore talks about education. By
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Shorts from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLACK-HOLES (Undated) _ Astronomers have discovered a new
class of black holes with a mass in between that of stellar black
holes and the supermassive black holes at the center of galaxies.
They are not sure how these medium size black holes are formed. By
Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-AUTOS (Seoul) _ In the wake of the financial crisis that
shook the South Korean economy almost three years ago, foreign
manufacturers _ Renault, Ford Motor and General Motors among them _
are snapping up factories and whole car companies, making direct
investments in a nation that has long turned its nose up at their
products. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate Commerce Committee was
scheduled Tuesday to hold hearings on the Bridgestone/Firestone
tire recall. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,4.
</P>
<P>
   DRESDNER-WASSERSTEIN (Undated) _ On reports that Dresdner Bank
AG, Germany's third-largest bank, is in talks to buy the U.S.
investment bank Wasserstein Perella Co. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-AIRLINES (Undated) _ American Airlines is reshuffling
its schedule and use of its Chicago and Fort Worth hubs to better
serve travelers following the delays and other problems suffered by
the industry this summer. Donald Carty, the company's chief
executive, also comments on the merger talks between its European
partner, British Airways, and KLM. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-SERVER (Undated) _ Hewlett-Packard, taken to task by
investors for coming up short against Sun Microsystems in the
server market, announces a new server line and brings Carly Fiorina
to New York to explain how H-P is reinventing itself. By Barnaby J.
Feder.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ The London Stock Exchange has
abandoned its merger plan with Frankfurt, at least temporarily, in
order to defend itself against a hostile bid from OM Gruppen, the
operator of the Stockholm stock exchange. By Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
<P>
   NOMURA-MILLENNIUM-DOME (London) _ Nomura Securities, which in
recent years has been on a buying spree for particular British
institutions _ chains of pubs and betting shops _ has drawn the
line at the Millennium Dome, the Labor government's celebration of
national pride. Nomura says it is withdrawing its bid because it
was not given enough financial information. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FARROS-BOSS (Undated) _ Royal Farros, chairman and ceo of
I-Print, an online printing service
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-VOLUNTEERS (Undated) _ For all the frenzied
fund-raising by both Democrats and Republicans this year,
candidates for offices from the the White House to the local school
board know that one thing is even more important than money:
volunteers. And while these unpaid armies are made up mostly of
students and retired people, it is business professionals who
exhibit the qualities that political candidates value the most:
nuts-and-bolts organizational skills, management savvy and
Rolodexes crammed with contacts. To campaign managers, these
executives are gold because they can get things done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties'' and Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings.''
