   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Wednesday, Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-GRAMMY-AWARDS (Undated) _ When the first Latin Grammy
Awards are broadcast Wednesday night, the show will mark the first
time a major U.S. television network has agreed to devote two
prime-time hours to multilingual programming _ the talk will be
mostly in English and Spanish, the singing in Spanish and
Portuguese. By Mireya Navarro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on television. By Bill
Carter and Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-INDIA-FILMS (Lenk, Switzerland) _ Many of the 800 to 900
films produced each year by the Indian movie industry, which is
sometimes called Bollywood, feature spectacularly scenic
backgrounds that are filmed in faraway locations, typically
Switzerland. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   FAMOUS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Almost Famous'': Cameron Crowe,
writer/director; with Patrick Fugit, Billy Crudup, Frances
McDormand, Kate hudson, Jason Lee, Anna Paquin, Fairuza Balk,
Philip Seymour Hoffman. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   PARAGRAPH-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ To the growing body of
precious cinematic literature that documents for posterity the
hideous barbarity of Nazism may now be added ``Paragraph 175,''
which relates the horror of the Nazi purge of homosexuals from the
life of Germany and the aftereffects that scar and roil these men
as the 21st century begins. Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   LOST-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Lost,'' by Lucy Wadham (Carroll &AMP;
Graf). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
