column: The 2000 Summer Games are about to start, but where are all
the people? Sydney isn't exactly bustling with the opening
ceremonies set for Friday night. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Sports of The Times column on
Andrew Gaze, and the cycle of a career that has included a Final
Four run at Seton Hall, five appearances on the Aussie Olympic team
and now, the honor of carrying the Australian flag at the game's
opening ceremonies. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-DISPUTE (Sydney) _ Three days of meetings have proven
that the IOC is under seige as never before. The Australian
govternment defied it by keeping out an Uzbeki boxing official;
Indonesia criticized it for lobbying for the release of a detained
crony of ex-dictator Suharto so that he can attend the Games; its
much touted EPO test has come under fire as ineffective and not
applied to enough athletes, and its being mocked in the local
papers. Its response: to act as if nothing were happening. By Jere
Longman.
</P>
