<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GAME-EVE2-LADN &LR;      09-12 0230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAME-EVE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOUT EVE 2
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After dodging a nasty mitochondrial infection in her first
adventure, stylish detective Aya Brea is back for more mayhem and
menace in Parasite Eve 2, a gorgeously wrought PlayStation
adventure videogame hitting store shelves this week.
</P>
<P>
   The original Parasite Eve was much lauded for its cinematic look
and noirlike sensibilities as players tried to stop the spread of a
horrific killer creature that infected people's cells.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Brea has left the NYPD and come to Los Angeles as part of a
special FBI task force fighting the Neo Mitochondrion Creatures (if
you skipped biology that week in high school, mitochondria are the
little energy factories in every cell; scientists have theorized
they once were separate creatures that merged in symbiotic
relationship with human ancestors).
</P>
<P>
   The only knock on the original Parasite Eve was that the fun
ended too quickly, after about only 30 hours of gameplay.
SquareSoft, best known for its Final Fantasy role-playing games,
seems to have taken care of that concern with a two-disc sequel big
enough for all of the gamemaker's great cinematic cut scenes, along
with a nifty new battle system that's more realistic. You might say
this game has an infectious quality to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
