<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CURRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CURRY NOT FOUND IN POWDER FORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDIA-BOOK-REVIEW) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the dishes of other countries become part of
American cooking vernacular, so do the ingredients that define
them. Curry leaves, which are used in Indian, Sri Lankan and
Malaysian cooking, are beginning to appear in mainstream cookbooks
just as Mexican cilantro and Southeast Asian kaffir lime leaves did
a while ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Indian cooking, mustard seeds and dried red chilies are
familiar enough, but curry leaves have no familiar reference; they
are not related to curry powder. Once tasted, you realize they have
no substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Curry leaves are sold on their thin stems. The leaves look like
bay, the fronds like ferns. Small, soft and waxy, the curry leaf
has a powerful toasty aroma, layered with green pepper and citrus.
It is not a fleeting aroma but one that is deep and heady, and
pronounced in every dish it touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are absolutely one of the best things,'' said Madhur
Jaffrey, author of ``Madhur Jaffrey's World Vegetarian'' (Clarkson
Potter, $40). ``I keep hoping it will be the next lemon grass of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   She gives curry leaves to chefs, and when she has guests, she
said, ``I put it on their napkin, a whole spray of it, so they can
crush it and smell it and see just how wonderful its aroma can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaffrey uses them not just in Indian dishes but western ones,
too. For pasta, she seasons a tomato sauce with mustard seeds, red
chili and curry leaves. When stir-frying shrimp, she adds curry
leaves to the oil.
</P>
<P>
   This is an easy herb to incorporate, potent but not too
assertive. I inserted them in slices in fingerling potatoes, as I
would bay leaves, before tossing the potatoes in peanut oil and
braising them with a few cloves of garlic. For soup, I combined
curry leaves with a few slow-roasted tomatoes and onions, a little
water and a pinch of cumin.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves, which offer a touch of bitterness once cooked,
helped balance the tomatoes' sweetness. They were also delicious
sprinkled on roasted eggplant, which was soft and caramely and
needed a powerful herb (which is why eggplant is so often paired
with rosemary or thyme).
</P>
<P>
   With dishes that have a sauce or a broth, the leaves should be
added whole to allow their flavor to seep out slowly. When
sauteing, they are best added to the oil as it heats so that the
flavor is infused in it and then the whole dish.
</P>
<P>
   Curry leaves are usually sold in plastic packages and will keep
in the refrigerator for a week. In tropical regions of India, the
curry plant is grown in backyards and in pots inside homes so, like
the laurel tree in many French homes, it is always at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Though dried curry leaves are easier to find than fresh, as
Jaffrey said, they ``give so little aroma that it's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh curry leaves are available at Indian markets. A package of
four to five stems is $1.49 at Kalustyan's, 123 Lexington Avenue
(28th Street); (212) 685-3451. Curry plants for growing indoors
start at $6 plus shipping from P.C. Link Corp., (212) 221-7040;
www.bhatia-nurseries.com.
</P>
<P>
   CARROT AND WATERCRESS SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Sophie Grigson's Herbs'' (BBC Consumer
Publishing, 1999) &QL; 
Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, peeled and grated
</P>
<P>
   1 large handful watercress, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch sea salt; more to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   20 curry leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   Lime juice, to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium heatproof bowl, combine carrots, watercress and
salt.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small saute pan, heat oil over medium heat. Add curry
leaves and mustard seeds. As soon as mustard seeds begin to pop,
take pan off heat and add cumin seeds. Return pan to heat, cover
and let seeds pop for about 10 seconds more. Remove from heat and
pour mixture over carrots and watercress. Toss to mix. Add about 1
tablespoon lime juice. Toss again. Taste and adjust seasoning,
adding more salt, oil and lime juice as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
