<HEADLINE>
YOUNG CHARMS THE GREEK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neil Young brought his A game but his B list of material to the
Greek Theatre Monday night, romping through an agreeable set of
what could be called his minor classics. Casual fans might have
left scratching their heads, but the faithful _ who seemed on hand
in strong numbers _ were pleased to revisit this segment of Young's
staggeringly rich catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the '70s composition ``Winterlong,'' he described it
as ``not quite a hit, it sounds like something else, but you just
gotta like it.'' That was the night in a nutshell. Figuring that
fans had heard ``Down by the River,'' ``After the Gold Rush,''
``Cinnamon Girl'' and similar chestnuts quite enough thank you at
this point, Young played lesser celebrated but nevertheless strong
tunes like ``Motorcycle Mama,'' ``Everybody Knows This Is
Nowhere,'' ``Walk On'' and the unreleased ``Bad Fog of
Loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Young fronted a solid ensemble of pro session musicians like
drummer Jim Keltner and bassist ``Duck'' Dunn. That his wife, Pegi,
and sister Astrid contributed backup vocals helped give the show a
more modest, homey feel in the Greek's spacious environs. The
singer and guitarist wasn't going for an electric, intense
performance as he has in recent years; this show was more
reflective and found Young in a jovial, nostalgic mood: He joked
about remembering how scared he was when he first played the Greek
a few decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   He mixed his vast repertoire from the '70s with numbers from two
more recent albums _ 1992's gentle, country-tinged ``Harvest Moon''
and this year's folky ``Silver and Gold'' (itself a collection of
tunes Young had written in years past). Nothing from his wilderness
years of the '80s made its way into the set, nor did any songs from
his harder-rocking comeback disks of the '90s, but the blend of
selected songs resulted in a pretty seamless vibe throughout the
course of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Guitar solos were kept to manageable lengths _ except, of
course, for ``Cowgirl in the Sand,'' which, along with
``Powderfinger,'' was one of the rare inclusions of his best- known
material. Young also drew the faithful to their feet with inspired
versions of ``Words (Between the Lines)'' (the evening's most
impassioned performance) and ``Tonight's the Night,'' a song about
the toll of drug addiction that's still eerie after all these
years: Moaning and wailing through the song, Young still seems to
be communing with long-departed friend Bill Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie Hynde and the Pretenders opened the evening with a
solid, professional set that tacitly acknowledged that the band
peaked with 1983's ``Learning to Crawl,'' a depressing but
realistic assessment. Hynde closed her show with another Young drug
song, ``Needle and the Damage Done'' _ sample lyric: ``I hit the
city and I lost my band/I watched the needle take another band'' _
a sad, sobering tribute to her own group's a rocky, tragic
history. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
--Neil Young and The Pretenders &QL; 
--Where: The Greek Theatre, 2700 N. Vermont Ave., Los Angeles. &QL; 
--When: 7:30 p.m. Thursday. &QL; 
--Tickets: $33 to $128. (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
