<SLUG> BC-OBIT-QUINN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM W. QUINN, GENERAL AND FORMER INTELLIGENCE OFFICER, DIES AT
92 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Calif. Ariz., France, Germany)   By   JOHN FILES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lt. Gen. William W. Quinn, an intelligence officer
during World War II and an infantry commander in the Korean
conflict, died here Monday at Walter Reed Army Hospital. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 30 years in the military, Quinn's career included a
variety of senior posts.
</P>
<P>
   As an intelligence officer in World War II, he gathered
information and helped coordinate the allied invasion of Southern
France in August 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, during the Battle of the Bulge, Quinn
anticipated a German attack on the 7th Infantry in Northern France.
On New Year's Eve, the offensive materialized. For more than 20
days, the Germans pounded the Americans, but they held firm.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded the Distinguished Service Medal for his
intelligence assessment that provided a crucial warning of the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he was named chief of operations of the
organization that became the Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``His preparations,'' George J. Tenet, the director of central
intelligence, said on Tuesday, ``ensured that the country
maintained some vital intelligence resources when chilled relations
with the Soviet Union expanded into a Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   As commanding officer of the 17th Infantry, 7th Infantry
Division in Korea in 1951, Quinn led his regiment _ known as the
Buffaloes _ against the communist forces, serving as a spearhead of
the 7th Infantry. The name became popular with his troops, and it
stuck.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as chief of information for the Department of the
Army from 1959 to 1961, before joining the Defense Intelligence
Agency, where he rose to deputy director. In 1964, he became the
commanding general of the Seventy Infantry in Germany. He retired
from the Army in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The general graduated from the National War College, the
Infantry School and the Command and General Staff College. In
addition to the Distinguished Service Medal, he received the Silver
Star, the Bronze Star, the Legion of Merit and a Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   William Wilson Quinn was born in Crisfield, Md., on Nov. 1,
1907. He graduated from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point in
1933.
</P>
<P>
   The general is survived by his wife, the former Bette Williams
of Arlington, Va., whom he married in 1939; two daughters, the
writer Sally Quinn, of Washington, and Donna Quinn Robbins of
Oakland, Calif.; a son, William W. Jr., of Phoenix; and four
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
