<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WRIGHT-FLYER13-COX     09-12 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-FLYER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GETTING WRIGHT FLYER OFF THE GROUND STILL HARD 100 YEARS LATER
 &HT;    750&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By TIMOTHY R. GAFFNEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A good measure of what the Wright brothers
accomplished with the world's first powered flight is how difficult
it's proving to duplicate their feat a century later.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of aviation organizations and government agencies
will spend more than a million dollars, use NASA research
facilities, and tap the talents of historians and engineers in an
effort to build and fly a replica of the Wright Flyer on Dec. 17,
2003, the 100th anniversary of powered flight.
</P>
<P>
   The project will be led by Ken Hyde of Warrenton, Va., a retired
airline pilot and aircraft mechanic who for the past several years
has been studying and trying to duplicate the Wright brothers'
kites, gliders, and powered airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde was selected for the project by the Oshkosh, Wis.-based
Experimental Aircraft Association (EAA), which has an agreement
with the National Park Service to plan the first flight centennial
celebration at the Wright Brothers National Memorial at Kitty Hawk,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   EAA President Tom Poberezny and Hyde detailed the group's
``Countdown to Kitty Hawk'' plans Tuesday morning at a news
conference at the National Air and Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The event included representatives of the National Park Service;
Inventing Flight, the organization planning Dayton, Ohio's flight
centennial celebrations; the First Flight Centennial Foundation, a
North Carolina group that has financed flight centennial projects,
and the air and space museum, which plans to open a new facility in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   The event was staged directly under the original Wright Flyer,
which hangs on display in the museum's main gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the airplane that started it all,'' Poberezny said,
gesturing at the historic airplanes, rockets and space capsules
that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Doll, park service superintendent of the memorial, said the
flight will be the ``pinnacle event'' of the 2003 celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Park Service feels that the EAA's recreation of
the first flight is a perfect way to bring this moment of history
alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The EAA was founded in 1953 to support people who build and
restore aircraft at home. It claims 170,000 members and has several
chapters in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   Poberezny said EAA members share the same passion for flight
that inspired the Wrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wright brothers were truly the first aircraft
home-builders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The EAA plans call for finishing the flyer in early 2003 and
taking it on a tour before the flight. Stops planned to date
include EAA's Sun and Fun air show in Lakeland, Fla., in April;
Dayton's air show and main flight centennial celebration in July,
and EAA's fly-in convention and air show in Oshkosh at the end of
July .
</P>
<P>
   Poberezny said plans also include recreating the Wright
brothers' camp at Kitty Hawk, and filming a series of documentaries
to tell the story of how they invented the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Poberezny said the EAA picked Hyde to build the flyer because of
his passion for authenticity. Hyde, who is also an aircraft
restorer, co-founded the Wright Experience in 1998 in an attempt to
learn how Orville and Wilbur Wright, and their machinist Charles
Taylor, designed and built their flying machines.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how they did it has been somewhat of an aviation mystery
because Wilbur Wright died suddenly of typhoid fever in 1912,
before he and Orville documented their work. Orville was unable to
finish the task without his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Working with several universities and the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration, Hyde's group has pored over the Wrights'
letters and notes and attempted to ``reverse engineer'' some
artifacts, such as parts of the engines that Taylor made in the
Wrights' Dayton bicycle shops.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the experience has been ``very humbling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read that they built the (1903) engine in three months,
it just blows me away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's goal is to make 1903 flyer as authentic as possible.
</P>
<P>
   It's a daunting challenge. Besides leaving incomplete records,
the Wrights employed tools, methods and materials that have long
since fallen out of use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest challenge is the fabric,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wrights used a tightly woven form of muslin, called ``Pride
of the West,'' that was used to make ladies' undergarments at the
turn of the century. Hyde said the fabric apparently is no longer
made, and he may have to appeal to the textile industry for help.
</P>
<P>
   Poberezny said the EAA expects to spend $1.5 million just
getting the flyer built and planning ``the core'' of the flight
centennial activities.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Equally challenging will be figuring out how the Wrights were
able, even briefly, to control the primitive, unstable flyer in the
air. The Wrights made hundreds of flights on a glider in 1902
before building their powered flyer.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who plans to fly the machine himself, said he hopes to
test it in a huge wind tunnel at NASA's Langley Research Center to
learn how it handles, possibly even flying it inside the tunnel for
training.
</P>
<P>
   Another Wright Flyer researcher said the original flyer's
instability and poor controls make a successful flight doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, our wind tunnel tests have shown that it is
an extremely unstable device,'' Jack Cherne, chairman of the
American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics' Wright Flyer
Project, said from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The AIAA's Los Angeles section has spent years testing Wright
Flyer models in wind tunnels and analyzing the data to learn just
how the flyer flew. The project drew international attention last
year when it tested a full-scale model in a cavernous wind tunnel
at NASA's Ames Research Center in California.
</P>
<P>
   Cherne said his group has used the data to make a flight
simulator program that runs on a desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our people began to get a feel for how to fly it after
about 20 tries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the project was to modify the original Wright design
just enough to make it safe to fly, then build a second aircraft
and fly it at the flight centennial event.
</P>
<P>
   Cherne, however, said the park service had told his group that
it would not permit any re-enactment flights at the memorial on the
anniversary date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached the National Park Service and they said they
would not allow any flyer on that day because they did not want an
accident to mar the event,'' Cherne said.
</P>
<P>
   Doll said the AIAA never formally asked to make the flight, and
she said worries about an accident weren't a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision (to approve the EAA's plan) was based on
historical accuracy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   AIAA's Wright Flyer Project: wrightflyer.com
</P>
<P>
   Experimental Aircraft Association: eaa.org
</P>
<P>
   First Flight Centennial Foundation: firstflightcentennial.org
</P>
<P>
   Inventing Flight: inventingflight.com
</P>
<P>
   The Wright Experience: www.wrightexperience.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
