A0644 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     09-12 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALVESTON CAN FINALLY TALK ABOUT STORM THAT ALTERED ITS FATE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last weekend, Galveston officially acknowledged the storm of
1900 that wrecked the community and killed more than 6,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
   There were wreaths, statues and marching bands. People
remembered; some cried.
</P>
<P>
   For a hundred years, the most famous island city of Texas has
been quiet about the storm. People knew of it, but the city never
really memorialized it _ made it a visible part of the past.
</P>
<P>
   As one local historian said, ``It's hard to promote a city as a
resort when people know they could be blown away at a moment's
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was more to it. Some say the people in Galveston were
simply too busy restoring the city to ever commemorate the storm.
They were on their knees bailing water or preoccupied carrying off
the dead. In the end, they just didn't want to talk about it. The
pain was too deep, too personal.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are those who believe that the most persistent
pain Galveston endured was constantly looking across the bay at the
incessant growth and prosperity of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While Galveston was rebuilding, it was watching its reputation
as the ``Queen City of Texas'' wash slowly away.
</P>
<P>
   Before the storm, Galveston was the state's darling city.
Fourteen direct steamship lines to Europe steamed out of Galveston.
Another three went to Cuba, one to Mexico and two served Japan and
the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston's port was ranked second in the United States in
cotton exports, third in wheat, sixth in cattle, seventh in corn
and 13th in flour. It had one of the largest flour mills in the
state and the only cotton bagging mill south of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   That was the business side.
</P>
<P>
   On the seedier side, the end of town where all the sailors and
stevedores took their pleasures, there were more saloons (489) than
any city of comparable size and more than in any other Gulf port,
including New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The city had 50 houses of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston was an eclectic city. The population was primarily of
European extraction, with 40 percent linked to England, Germany,
Ireland or France.
</P>
<P>
   But 20 percent were African-American, and they had an active
middle class with strong representation among the professional and
skilled labor forces.
</P>
<P>
   Italians, Eastern Europeans and a small number of Hispanics made
up the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston had electric streetcars, electric lights, local and
long-distance telephone service, two domestic telegraph companies.
The city had three big concert halls and 20 hotels with 200
ocean-facing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The city was second in the nation in millionaires per capita.
</P>
<P>
   The storm took all that away.
</P>
<P>
   But Galveston suffered its largest commercial setback when
Spindletop blew open the Texas oil business near Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Houston became the petroleum center of the country.
Gulf, Texaco and Humble set up their offices there.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years later, the Houston Ship Channel was dredged,
and Galveston no longer had the busiest deep-water port in the
state. Railroads were carrying goods throughout the nation, and
Houston had become a rail center. The railroad, as much as the
storm, shoved Galveston out of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galveston never was destined to be a huge city _ storm or
not,'' Elizabeth Turner told the Houston Chronicle. Turner, an
author of a Galveston history and associate professor of history at
the University of Houston-Downtown, said Galveston faced physical
limitations from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is just a sandbar,'' she said. ``For a city to grow,
it needs space. Galveston just didn't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 100 years later, Galveston can sit in the sunshine and
watch Houston highways become steaming parking lots. It can watch
an ugly haze cover the city almost daily. It can read about the
big-city crime rate and the rising cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston can be happy with itself again. It can speak of the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
