<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0657 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SUBLIMINAL-ADS-NNS &LR;      09-12 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBLIMINAL-ADS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATS IN GOP AD? AUTHOR OF 1973'S `SUBLIMINAL SEDUCTION' ISN'T
SURPRISED 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Sept. 12, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) The Democrats call it ``disappointing.'' To the
Republicans it's ``bizarre.'' The advertising firm insists it's a
coincidence. But it is there, in bright, capital letters, the word
``RATS'' in a GOP television spot attacking Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And Wilson Bryan Key is sitting at his ranch outside Reno, Nev.,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's delightful,'' Key says of the ad. ``I'm just
surprised it's so crude. Obviously, an amateur did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1973, Key, then a communications professor at University
of Western Ontario, brought a sinister phrase to the forefront of
the lexicon: ``Subliminal Seduction.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the title of the book in which he claimed that
advertisers were using ``embedded images,'' such as sexual figures
and suggestive words, to affect viewers on an unconscious level.
</P>
<P>
   The public was terrified yet fascinated that advertisers could
reach into unknowing minds. Key hit the lecture circuit in 1975 and
has yet to retire _ although he has slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did 97 lectures one year,'' says Key, now 75. ``I almost
died of jet lag.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years he wrote four more books: ``Media
Sexploitation,'' ``The Age of Manipulation,'' ``Subliminal
Adventures in Erotic Art'' and ``The Clam Plate Orgy.''
</P>
<P>
   The books have sold more than 8.5 million copies in six
languages, Key says, adding that ``Media Sexploitation'' is
currently being reissued for the third time in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, Key has noticed plenty of subliminal messages in
advertising. ``Absolutely. It's pretty insidious stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   As for this RATS spot, ``It should be quite effective,'' he
says. ``If you were Republican, pairing up `rats' with
`bureaucrats' fits into your cultural background.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Key has had his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Greenwald, a psychology professor at University of
Washington-Seattle, says his research shows that ``briefly flashed
visual images'' have an effect on the viewer, but only for ``a
second or so'' after shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be an effect of the kind that could influence
voting, or I wouldn't expect it to,'' Greenwald says, adding that
Key ``hasn't done any scientific research that establishes any
proof'' that subliminal persuasion exists.
</P>
<P>
   A paper published in the September 1999 Journal of Advertising
is inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   In it, three marketing professors studied 56 college students
who each viewed two ads with embedded images and two without. The
conclusion: Subliminal perception ``may influence feelings,'' and
the researchers ``encourage further discussion of that idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Key isn't swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an enormous amount of data'' backing up his premise,
he says, ``way over 500 published academic research pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   In his view, the problem remains that people can't bring
themselves to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terribly upsetting, the intensity and power that media
has over our lives,'' Key says. ``People don't want to deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But they should, he adds, especially because digital technology
is making manipulation of images ``so simple to do. It's unlikely
they'll ever be caught. In the old days, it was done by artists by
hand and not at all hard to detect.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he is fascinated that the word RATS was spotted in
the Republican ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the Democrats planted it there,'' he quips. ``The whole
thing is a house of mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Key just finished work on a one-hour program for the British
Broadcasting Corp., one of a 13-part series on conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife also keep up with their five grown daughters,
``scattered all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's writing another book _ a novel, his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love story,'' he says. ``I got bored with subliminal
seduction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
