<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FRYING-EATING-WELL-NY     09-12 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRYING-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIED VEGGIES? SOMETHING'S IN THE OVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The all-fat-is-bad theory of eating has gone the way
of the grapefruit diet, but the calories-do-count theory is still
with us. And that leaves fried foods where they have always been,
generally out of reach for those who would prefer not to gain
weight. Still, the results of perfect deep frying are hard to
resist: Most people prefer a plateful of French fries to boiled
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Some time ago, I figured out how to get that irresistible flavor
of French fries without actually frying potatoes. Roasting them at
a high temperature in a light coating of oil provides much of the
same crispness and crunch with far less grease. Not to mention far
less mess.
</P>
<P>
   This summer I decided to put other vegetables to the
``oven-fried'' test: Zucchini, green tomatoes and eggplants.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike potatoes, those vegetables are filled with water, so
roasting them at high heat simply softens them. They need a coating
to provide crispness, something that will actually toast and turn
brown.
</P>
<P>
   Flour, bread crumbs, egg whites all work wonders in oven-frying
vegetables. Just as they do in deep frying, the bread and flour
have properties that can be toasted and browned. The egg whites,
like whole eggs, help the coating stick to the food.
</P>
<P>
   For sliced eggplant, egg whites and bread crumbs were all that
were needed to provide a crunchy coating. But I enhanced the flavor
with thin slices of melted Parmigiano-Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   Green tomatoes, the juiciest of the vegetables, needed a
relatively thick coating to seal in the liquid and allow the
coating to brown. Adding a little garlic and cayenne to the batter
makes them even better. I also tried laying a leaf of basil on each
slice of tomato before cooking them, and it was a delicious touch,
although I doubt any Southerner would ever entertain such a radical
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini can be oven-fried in the same kind of batter.
</P>
<P>
   All these ``fried'' vegetables taste great just as they are, hot
out of the oven. But the zucchini and tomatoes are excellent with a
yogurt sauce, curried or dill, while the eggplant could be put
between good Italian bread to make a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Oven-frying beets and sweet potatoes is easiest of all, using
the same technique as with white potatoes because all three do not
have much moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the beets and sweet potatoes and cut into slices less than
an eighth of an inch thick. Season them with salt. Spray a nonstick
pan with cooking spray, arrange the slices on the pan and spray
them with pan spray. Roast on the top shelf of a preheated
450-degree oven for 15 to 20 minutes, turning once. They will be
crisp but tender, and you will want to eat them like potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   So go right ahead.
</P>
<P>
   `OVEN-FRIED' EGGPLANT
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Pan spray
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-large eggplant
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fine dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 slices Parmigiano-Reggiano.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Spray a large baking sheet with
pan spray.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut eggplant crosswise into \-inch-thick slices. Beat egg
whites in shallow bowl. Place flour in second shallow dish and
season with salt and pepper to taste. Dip slices first into egg
whites, then in flour, then in egg whites and finally in bread
crumbs. Arrange slices on prepared baking sheet and spray with pan
spray. Roast on top shelf of oven about 15 minutes. Turn once and
top with very thin slices of Parmigiano-Reggiano and return to oven
for a minute or two until cheese melts and bubbles. Yield: 2 to 3
servings.
</P>
<P>
   `OVEN-FRIED' ZUCCHINI
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pan spray.
</P>
<P>
   2 medium to large zucchini
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a bowl, mix flour with 1 cup water, the oil and salt to
taste. Let stand 20 minutes. 2. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Pan
spray a nonstick baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   3. Slice zucchini [ inch thick. Beat egg whites until soft peaks
form, then fold into batter. Dip each zucchini slice in batter and
place on prepared pan. Roast on top shelf of oven about 10 minutes,
until slices are browned on the bottoms, then turn and roast
another few minutes. Yield: 3 to 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   `FRIED' GREEN TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour plus extra for coating tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pan spray
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   6 medium-large green tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Crushed garlic to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Mix flour with 1 cup water, oil and salt and pepper to taste
in a shallow bowl and allow to sit for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Spray 2 baking sheets with pan
spray. Beat egg whites until soft peaks form and fold into the
flour mixture. Have more flour mixed with lots of salt ready in a
second dish.
</P>
<P>
   3. Slice top and bottom off tomatoes and cut each into
inch-thick slices. Sprinkle with garlic and cayenne. Dip slices in
flour, then in batter. Place on baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   4. Roast on top shelf of oven until bottoms are browned, about
10 minutes. Spray tops with pan spray and turn over. Return to oven
and continue roasting another 5 minutes, until crumbs brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
