<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CUSTOMS-CONFUSION-     09-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CUSTOMS-CONFUSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REST FOR AN OUTLAW IN NAME ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Johnny Santiago, an actor and an owner of Torch, a
restaurant on the Lower East Side, has been a wanted man for most
of his adult life. His outlaw career began in January 1994, just
before his 24th birthday, when he made the mistake of taking a
vacation in Italy and returning to Kennedy Airport with a passport
bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   As he recalls it, he and his luggage were soon surrounded by
eight Customs Service officers and two dogs. ``They took me to a
detention room,'' he said. ``I kept asking why I was there, and all
they'd say was, `Something's come up.' I asked to make a phone
call, and they said no.'' They searched his bags and his shoes.
Finally, after an hour and a half, an agent from the Customs
Service told him that there was a warrant for his arrest dating
from 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I was really confused,'' Santiago said. ``What happened in
1990? I was in college then. Did I get drunk one night and do
something? I couldn't think of anything except some unpaid parking
tickets. Was this part of the Giuliani crackdown? I told them about
the tickets, but they said that wasn't it. Finally an agent told me
the warrant was for robbery and possession of stolen goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that he knew he hadn't committed those crimes.
The bad news was that someone from the New York Police Department
was coming to the airport to take him to Rikers Island. ``I
couldn't believe it,'' he said. ``I sat there thinking, `What a way
to end the vacation.'''
</P>
<P>
   But then, as his third hour in detention was beginning, Santiago
got a mysterious reprieve. ``The Customs detective came back and
told me the warrant had been rescinded,'' he said. Still confused
but in no mood to linger, he went home and forgot about it, until
the next overseas trip, later that year, which ended once again
with an interrogation at Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   This time he was handcuffed. ``I tried telling them the warrant
had been rescinded, but it was still there in the computer,'' he
said. ``The agent looked it up and said to me, `Apparently you've
been busy lately.''' There were now additional charges: assault,
resisting arrest and jumping bail.
</P>
<P>
   After questioning him further and taking his fingerprints, the
Customs agents finally recognized his true crime: having the same
name and birthday as another man who was wanted for crimes in the
Bronx. You might think a computer would be capable of
distinguishing the two men, especially since they have different
birthplaces (Puerto Rico for the Bronx fugitive, Brooklyn for the
Manhattan restaurateur).
</P>
<P>
   But the problem seems beyond the scope of modern computer
technology; or, more precisely, the bureaucrats who program those
computers. While the wanted man apparently wanders free, the other
John Santiago has been detained half a dozen times at local
airports, most recently in July. ``The Customs Service now has a
special file in their computer on me,'' he said, ``but it still
takes an hour or two for me to explain everything and get the
agents to look up the file.''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest fear is being stopped outside the airport. ``I'm
afraid to take a long car trip,'' he said. ``I've already had some
close calls in New York. I was stopped for speeding once, but the
cop gave me a warning and didn't run the license through the
computer. Another time they ran the computer check and saw the
warrant, but I managed to persuade the cop I wasn't the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another close call occurred several years ago, shortly after he
got a driver's license with a new address in the Village. ``An NYPD
detective knocked on the door of my apartment at 11:30 at night,''
Santiago said. ``He showed me a picture of a guy named John
Santiago and a warrant for him listing my address. The computer
must have attached it because of my license. I was petrified. I was
standing there in my underwear figuring that I'd be arrested if I
told him my name. I just said I'd never seen the guy in the
picture, and the detective went away.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago tried to clear things up at the source of the warrant,
state Supreme Court in the Bronx. ``They ran a fingerprint check on
me and gave me a printout saying I wasn't the guy they wanted,'' he
said. ``But the document looks like something I could have made up
at home. I asked for a letter with a court seal on it, but the
judge refused. I said to him, `Look, if I get pulled over for
speeding some Friday afternoon, I could spend a weekend in jail.'
His response was, `Well, you shouldn't be speeding.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
