<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: New restaurant escalates Lufkin
controversy
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ We have a new restaurant _ this in a town that
uses the term loosely. McDonald's, for instance, is considered a
drive-in restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But Marbles, the new place, is a fine dining, uptown-style
establishment that just happens to be located in a downtown
basement.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the best basement Lufkin has to offer _ in the old
Perry Building, our would-be high-rise that never completely got
off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Perry Building is all of four stories plus a penthouse of
executive offices, which is pretty much our skyline hereabouts,
along with the water tower.
</P>
<P>
   The building's foundation had been constructed to support a
structure of some 10 stories. The idea was that it would be added
onto and ``grow with Lufkin.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a direct quote from the special edition of the Lufkin
Daily News, August of 1950, celebrating the grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that Lufkin hasn't grown _ but it grew out, not up.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown business went south, to the new malls that were
developed beginning in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Perry Building was headquarters for the chain of Perry Bros.
five and dime stores, which started here in my little hometown and
in latter times was second in number of stores only to Woolworth.
</P>
<P>
   Woolworth and Perry's had this much in common as well _ they
both shut down about the same time in the late '90s, commercial
casualties of the giant discount chains.
</P>
<P>
   Fair's fair. They in their day had put the mom-and-pop shops out
of business. What goes around comes around, and somebody goes bust.
</P>
<P>
   The basement of the Perry Building had housed Perry's Cafeteria,
as fancy as any East Texas eating place you could imagine, and
still well remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies a local controversy. Some remember that the Perry
Building had an escalator to and from the cafeteria, the only
escalator in Lufkin's history. Others remember no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   The subject has been much debated of late in the local
newspaper. As you can see, we're hard up for controversies. Hard to
imagine an adventure series, ``Indiana Jones and the Lost Escalator
of Lufkin.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm of the escalator persuasion, though I have to
admit that on visiting Marbles I could find no evidence that such
ever existed.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, any number of partitions have been added in various
stages of remodeling. Best, perhaps, that we leave it to future
archaeologists to decide the issue.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be the first to tell you that Marbles is a wonderful place
to eat. But I also have to tell you I'm a bit prejudiced.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Cates and Lesley Cross are the owners and chefs. Dean is
Roy Cates' son. I've known Roy since way back when he was called
Dinky Cates. To this day we're in the same Sunday school class.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, according to Dinky's boy Dean, the name Marbles
comes from the marble architecture throughout much of the building,
and also that Perry's five and dime was where Dean bought his first
sack of marbles as a kid. His daddy had bought his first sack of
marbles there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``And also maybe I've lost my marbles opening such a place,''
Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   Not really. No reason to think Lufkin can't support a fine
restaurant, even if it doesn't have a drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
