<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SCIENTISTS-LEE-CASE-H     09-12 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENTISTS-LEE-CASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ASIAN-AMERICANS UPSET OVER LEE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Asian-American scientists in the nation's
weapons labs expressed anger over what they perceive as government
mishandling of the case involving accused spy Wen Ho Lee, who on
Tuesday was awaiting a plea agreement that could set him free.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was worked out nine months after Lee was arrested. Lee
has professed his innocence and he has been characterized by
colleagues and Asian-American organizations as a scapegoat for
security and management shortcomings at the nation's weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the American justice system works, but unfortunately
it only worked after enough people complained about it,'' said Joel
Wong, an engineer and 16-year employee of the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory in Livermore, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, a lot of mainstream Americans don't think we
(Asian-Americans) belong to this country. They think our loyalty
will always (be) to the old country, which is bunk,'' Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hong Kong, Wong is now an American citizen and assistant
head of the hazards control department at Lawrence Livermore.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, a former employee of the Los Alamos National Laboratory
in New Mexico, remained in confinement as lawyers and federal
prosecutors worked out details of a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese-born scientist was fired from Los Alamos in 1999
and later was charged with downloading nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the plea deal, Lee would agree to plead
guilty to the crime of downloading restricted material to an
unsecured computer, one of 59 counts he had faced, and be sentenced
to the nine months he has already served in solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   The case has made Asian-Americans working in the laboratories
``extra careful of what we're doing and made us extra careful to
ensure our rights have not been infringed,'' said Manvendra Dubey,
an atmospheric scientist and chemist who heads the Los Alamos
laboratory's Asian-American Diversity Working Group.
</P>
<P>
   Dubey expressed concern about ``questionable'' investigative
tactics the FBI used in the Lee case. Dubey, however, acknowledged
that Lee would admit some guilt in the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's accepted his responsibility and we should move on,''
Dubey added. ``America is a melting pot of diverse individuals, and
let's all work together to make it a successful melting pot.''
</P>
<P>
   At Livermore, spokeswoman Susan Houghton said: ``We're not
really commenting on this (case) to anyone because it really
doesn't involve our lab.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Houghton said, Livermore has tried to help its
employees learn from its sister lab's experience: ``We spent a
morning training managers and employees to be sensitive to cultural
differences, (to) what is appropriate and what isn't appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor L. Ling-chi Wang, director of the Asian-American
Studies program at the University of California at Berkeley, said
the Lee case is ``a very important milestone in the annals of the
Chinese-American struggle for civil rights in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could point to several previous cases where
Chinese-Americans were treated so badly, and there was very little
resistance coming out of the Chinese-American community.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Wang said, Chinese-Americans used the Internet to
spread word about the Lee case, prompting ``tremendous support
across the country, from coast to coast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
