<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRODIN-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAD BOY SWITCHES TO PUNDITRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Grodin was once notorious as the talk show
guest who zinged the host; the guy with the ironic sidelong look
who would say anything. But as the man whose own cable talk show
got canceled and received some of the most vicious reviews in
television, he's got a thin skin.
</P>
<P>
   He'll joke that he knew the end was near on MSNBC, which
canceled his show last November, when they took away his dressing
room and he found himself changing in the makeup room. He'll say
that he couldn't have been too bad or he wouldn't have the new gig
on ``60 Minutes II,'' as the end-of-show commentator.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to what the critics had to say about Grodin as
a pundit when he tackled such issues as capital punishment, the
homeless and the rights of welfare mothers, ``I don't want to hear
it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This will make discussion difficult.
</P>
<P>
   People say you rant, Mr. Grodin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, I do rant,'' Grodin says. ``But I don't plan how
I'm gonna come off. If I start getting angry it's not neat and
clean and possibly plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Addendum: ``It's not like the airways are filled with people
trying to get people out of prison. If that was all there was all
over the place, you wouldn't need somebody like me to be on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more disappointing than a comic actor who
decides to get serious? It's like hoping for a chocolate souffle
and getting spinach. Not that there's anything wrong with spinach,
but Grodin, 65, had been a man with a dark, original, funny
presence. He made his name with ``The Heartbreak Kid'' and then
played the beleaguered dad in the ``Beethoven'' movies, as co-star
to a St. Bernard.
</P>
<P>
   Grodin, these days, is very serious.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving for a chat at The New York Times, the first thing he
wants to know is where the editorial writers are _ he wants to talk
to them about reforming the stiff penalties of the Rockefeller drug
law. He's still enough of a ham to do riffs in a crowded elevator
and when pressed, he'll talk about the movies, a life he insists he
is done with. Talking movies, he's funny. Asked about the making of
the film ``Ishtar,'' he recalls walking a back street in Marrakesh
with Dustin Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I imagining this, or are a lot more people recognizing you
than are recognizing me?'' Hoffman asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a lot of community theater here,'' Grodin says.
</P>
<P>
   Grodin was also, it turns out, not a guy to underrate himself.
Offered the starring and star-making role in ``The Graduate'' as a
young actor, he turned up his nose at the $500 weekly salary and
lost the role. He had done Broadway by then, and the salary seemed
``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I think something is unfair, I won't do it, even if that
might not be in my interests,'' Grodin says.
</P>
<P>
   What Grodin wants to talk about these days, however, is social
reform; the special he did for Court TV from the Bedford Hills
Maximum Security Prison, which resulted in Christmas pardons last
year for three female prisoners who had been serving long sentences
under the Rockefeller drug law.
</P>
<P>
   How did a comic actor morph into social commentator?
</P>
<P>
   He had always been interested, Grodin says. Growing up in
Pittsburgh, he was the argumentative kid who got thrown out of
class for talking too much, he had considered a career in
journalism. In 1969, he produced a show with friends Paul Simon and
Art Garfunkel which involved the Vietnam War and segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, five years ago, Grodin, who is married and has a young
son, decided he no longer wanted to make movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't leave acting to get involved socially and
politically,'' Grodin says. ``I was not sitting on the set with a
St. Bernard saying, `I've got to get all those people out of
prison.' I left because my son was entering the first grade and I
no longer wanted to travel. Even then, I wasn't hired to do a talk
show on social issues. I was supposed to be dessert, after Geraldo.
Then the O.J. Simpson trial came along and all of a sudden I
shifted back to where I started in 1969.''
</P>
<P>
   If the ratings were not great for his later shows, no matter. No
one could have done well in his last time slot on MSNBC, Grodin
insists: When they put you on at 7 Friday night, they just don't
want you. Anyway, it should not be about ratings.
</P>
<P>
   You want to know what matters, let him tell you about those
three women who were pardoned after he interviewed them and their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the Camus book `The Stranger,' where a guy runs to
help an old lady across the street because of the feeling he gets
when he does it?'' Grodin says. ``That's what this is all about. I
went to a reception in the Village when these people were let out.
A reporter asked, `How do you feel?' I couldn't even answer, it was
so powerful. These were women I'd only seen in prison, now they
were sitting there with their children. It was the most significant
thing I've done in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
