<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLEDPARENT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW WELL DO I KNOW MY KIDS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CATHERINE NEWTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a typical Tuesday night. I was working at the computer
and a 10-year-old child stepped into the room with a pair of white
Hanes underpants on his head. They were puffed up to look like a
beret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doood,'' said the young man with an accent so atrocious that I
felt sure his name must be Gunther or Franc. ``It's a nightcap.''
</P>
<P>
   He went away.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 minutes later, I got up to check the laundry. As I
passed by the half-open bathroom door, I saw the light on and I
peeked in. Same child. This time, his fist was in his mouth and
just as I entered the room, he gave a Venus Williams-style grunt
and yanked out a midsized tooth, spewing a viscous stream of blood
onto the tile floor.
</P>
<P>
   I live with this person. He is my son, Jack. But who the heck is
he?
</P>
<P>
   Like most parents, I think I know my children. We talk a lot
(especially Hadley, who's 6). We read together (two Redwall books
and one Nancy Drew last month) and compete in family games
(favorite: Pretty, Pretty Princess). We all study spelling at one
table every Thursday night, we take naps en masse, and this summer
the three of us crowded on the love seat every Wednesday to root
for our favorite Survivor. We are close. Bonded.
</P>
<P>
   But still, they surprise me.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week alone, without trying, I discovered that:
</P>
<P>
   Despite my efforts to the contrary, not only is Hadley aware of
Britney Spears, but my daughter knows every word to ``Oops! ... I
Did It Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack spends his time at school looking at things like
Turtledance.com. ``And there's fishdance.com and hamsterdance.com
and raccoondance.com and pikachudance.com.,'' he informed me.
``Basically, every animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Hadley aware of The Facts of Life, she has a
favorite character: Natalie.
</P>
<P>
   Hadley can eat a quart of strawberries in one sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Hadley can memorize 15 spelling words and still not be able to
read any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Jack thinks Firestone should pay for the tire recall and not
Ford. ``How did you know about this?'' I asked him. ``Mom,'' he
said. ``Don't you read the paper?''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about all this, I began to doubt that I really knew my
children well. I decided it was time for a test. I pulled out the
``How Well Do You Know Your Child?'' quiz from Sal Severe's book
How to Behave So Your Children Will, Too! I answered each of the 20
questions (My favorite song is ...; Other kids think I am ...; What
I like best about my mother is ..., etc.) the way I thought each of
my children would. And then they answered the questions. And we
compared notes.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the results, in brief.
</P>
<P>
   I know Hadley less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I know she likes grilled cheese. I know she likes pink and the
``Powerpuff Girls.'' I know she thinks her bedtime should be
midnight. I know she wants to write books and illustrate them when
she grows up. I know she likes ``The Parent Trap.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know she feeds her cats at her dad's house. I didn't
know she wishes she could read better. I thought what she would
like best about me is that I am nice, but she says I'm lovable. I
had no idea that she feels like not everyone likes her. Or that she
knew Spanish. ``They like me asi asi,'' she said. ``Do you know
what that means?''
</P>
<P>
   I know Jack less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I know he likes oatmeal. I know he likes blue and ``Gundam
Wing.'' I know he doesn't have a favorite song or video game. I
know that if he had lots of money he would: a) ``give some to my
mom'' (and believe me, I'm a little concerned that we got that
right word for word) and b) help animals. I know he likes ``The
Parent Trap.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know that he thinks other kids think he's cool, his
best subject is math, he likes to chat in his free time, and he
would like to be smarter. I thought what he would write he liked
best about me is that I am nice, but he said, ``She's like a best
friend to me, but better.'' I thought he felt that way; I just
never thought he'd write it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good exercise. And a good surprise. We all ended up
laughing and teary-eyed. And we decided to watch TV. Together.
</P>
<P>
   We put on ``The Parent Trap'' video (my favorite, too). And I
discovered something else: Hadley knows every single word of the
script. Completely, not asi asi.
</P>
<P>
   And I reconfirmed what I already knew: Hadley's exuberant verbal
skills work Jack's last nerve.
</P>
<P>
   He went away.
</P>
<P>
   To do what?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows.
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Newton writes the Frazzled Parent column for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
