u s BC-OLYMPIC-DISPUTE-1250(     09-12 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-DISPUTE-1250(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE EVE OF THE OLYMPICS, THE IOC STRUGGLES WITH ITS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ In the wake of the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal and growing fears that the use of performance-enhancing
drugs is pervasive, the International Olympic Committee has faced a
barrage of new embarrassments this week that raise questions about
its ability and resolve to change significantly.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, which has been struggling to turn attention to the
Summer Games that open on Friday, is trying to convince the world
that it is no longer the autocratic organization that it has been
during the two decades Juan Antonio Samaranch has served as
president.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indonesian government criticized Samaranch Tuesday for
lobbying for the release from jail of an IOC delegate named Mohamad
``Bob'' Hasan so he could attend the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   This followed the Australian government's refusal, on grounds of
national security, to allow entry in recent days to two Olympic
officials: Gafur Rakhimov of Uzbekistan, who is a member of the
international boxing federation, and Carl Ching of China, a member
of the international basketball federation. Each man has been
accused of links to organized crime in published reports, and each
has denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's immigration department also said it was monitoring
the activities of between 20 and 40 Olympic officials for security
reasons during the Games, which run from Friday through Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the IOC's problems, many academics, scientists,
athletes and coaches have criticized as insufficient and
ineffective a new test for the endurance drug known as EPO, which
is believed to be widely used in sports like swimming, distance
running and rowing.
</P>
<P>
   These matters have been reported incessantly by the fiercely
competitive Australian media, sometimes in a mocking tone, each
story magnified by the fact that the 2000 Summer Games are
considered among the most important events in the country's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some IOC members said the skeptical coverage
indicated that an overhaul of Olympic rules and procedures enacted
after the Salt Lake City scandal might not earn broad public trust
until Samaranch steps down as president next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably hard for genuine reform to take place
within the existing structure and with the existing president,''
said Richard Cashman, director of the Center for Olympic Studies at
the University of New South Wales in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis in the Australian media on unsavory characters,
drugs, transportation problems, windy weather and shivering nights
in the athletes' village has clearly exasperated some IOC
delegates, who would prefer that the focus be on performances, new
stadiums and public enthusiasm in a sports-mad country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't we done anything right?'' said Phil Coles, an
Australian IOC delegate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Monday, some livid IOC officials even considered suing the
Salt Lake City committee organizing the 2002 Winter Games over a
disputed document that contains the word geld _ German for money _
next to the names of some current delegates. The delegates thought
their reputations had been besmirched by the suggestion they were
bribed for their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps we should see if we can do something legally to attack
those who continue to call our dignity into question,'' said
Francois Carrard, the IOC's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seemed to fade quickly, given that American courts
might not be sympathetic and that it might look unseemly to pick a
fight with the city that the IOC has chosen to host the next Winter
Games in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   The latest controversy occurred Tuesday when the Indonesian
government criticized Samaranch for a letter he wrote last April
seeking the release of Hasan, the IOC delegate, from jail. A
powerful Asian track and field official, Hasan was also an
associate of the deposed Indonesian president, Suharto. Hasan faces
trial next week on charges of embezzling $87 million in state
money. He has said he is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the letter written by Samaranch to Abdurrahman
Wahid, the Indonesian president, was first reported by the Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazed me that they asked for this,'' the Indonesian
attorney general, Marzuki Darusman, said of the IOC to the
Associated Press in Jakarta. ``The ethics involved are quite odd.
It contravenes the spirit of the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, a vice president of the IOC from Montreal, said it
was the IOC's obligation to defend members who have not been
convicted of a crime. ``When you pick an IOC member in a country,
you don't always get it right,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates are chosen for their commitment to sport and their
ability to influence governments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, he was such a person,'' Pound said of Hasan.
``Whether he is now remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some IOC officials questioned Samaranch's sense of public
relations for pressing the Australian government to allow Rakhimov
and Ching into the country after it became clear they would not be
granted visas. Pound said the IOC simply wanted to know why the two
men were not allowed in, to determine whether it was for a reason
other than politics, race or religion.
</P>
<P>
   But other Olympic officials saw it as the IOC meddling in the
internal affairs of a sovereign government. ``We looked stupid,''
said an IOC official who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``We
should have dropped it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time at the Sydney Games, the IOC will use blood
testing to identify athletes who use performance-enhancing drugs,
which are prohibited. As many as 40 athletes have been removed from
various national Olympic teams for failing blood tests before
leaving home. However, the Olympic committee has said that it was
having trouble locating athletes in Australian locations other than
Sydney to administer the EPO tests.
</P>
<P>
   The test is also flawed, IOC officials admit. Only athletes who
fail both a blood test that detects EPO use over the previous three
weeks and a urine test that detects use over the previous three
days will face punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were going to catch athletes using EPO, they had to
have a test that would catch them weeks after their last dose,''
Peter Larkins, a member of the medical team of the Sydney Olympic
organizing committee, said on Australian television.
</P>
<P>
   Some members have remained defiant in the face of the
unremitting criticism. ``We are like ducks; the rain falls but does
not touch us,'' said Prince Alexandre de Merode, an IOC delegate
from Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerhard Heiberg, a member from Norway, said the criticism
was necessary and welcome. Ed Hula, the editor of an Olympic
newsletter called Around the Rings, said the critical coverage
reflected a heightened level of distrust of the IOC in the media
since the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Sydney Games represent an important crossroads,
said Cashman of the Center of Olympic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Games work out well, the IOC will recover a bit of
ground and Samaranch would go out on a positive note,'' Cashman
said. ``The Olympic movement is fragile now in terms of
credibility. If the Games don't go well, it could be immensely
damaging.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
