<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0699 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ENERGY-CRISIS-NNS &LR;      09-12 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-CRISIS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC ALONE CAN'T SOLVE LOOMING ENERGY PROBLEM, EXPERTS WARN 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Sept. 12, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ART ADVISORY: With graphic showing recent trends in price of crude
oil. For information about purchasing this photo call 202-383-7824.
 By JIM NESBITT  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sudden specter of an energy crisis underscores
the world's reliance on Middle East oil, raises the likelihood that
sharp price increases will spike the American economic expansion,
and revives consumers' nightmares of sky-high winter heating bills,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about a recession here, but we are talking
about a significant shaving of the growth,'' said Donald Ratajczak,
professor emeritus at Georgia State University and author of the
school's economic forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by strong global economic growth and some
supply-and-demand gamesmanship by Middle East producers and Western
middlemen, the price of oil has topped $35 a barrel, up from less
than $15 in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the price of bringing natural gas out of the ground
is projected to hit an all-time high of $3.50 per thousand cubic
feet. And inventories of both heating oil and natural gas are well
below expected winter demand.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to fierce international political pressure, the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries this week boosted
production quotas by 800,000 barrels a day. But spot prices for oil
actually increased in the wake of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Massoud Samii, a former OPEC economist who is now a professor of
international business strategy at New Hampshire College in
Manchester, said the market's contrarian reaction illuminates two
points:
</P>
<P>
   _ The announced quota increase is small _ roughly one percent of
daily world demand. And there is skepticism that it is more than
official endorsement of ``cheating'' _ a reference to the roughly
700,000 barrels a day that OPEC oil producers already pumped above
the previous quota.
</P>
<P>
   _ OPEC is bumping the ceiling of its production capacity,
meaning that the world can't count on the Middle East simply to
open up the crude-oil tap.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, when the Iran-Iraq War drove oil to $40 a barrel, OPEC
ministers wanted to increase production to push prices to a more
economically healthy level, but they lacked the capacity to do so,
Samii said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much at the maximum of what they can produce,''
he said. ``If we have a very cold winter, it's not clear they can
produce much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if OPEC can pump out more crude, American refineries may
not have the additional capacity to produce enough heating oil to
offset low inventories and meet expected winter demand, said John
Felmy, director of policy analysis at the American Petroleum
Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although existing facilities have been modernized, there hasn't
been a new refinery built in America in 25 years, Felmy said _ and
there's been a two-million-barrel-a-day drop in domestic refining
capacity in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the bottleneck is a winter transportation problem.
Most fuel oil is shipped to the Northeast by barge, and ``rivers
freeze when it gets cold,'' Felmy said.
</P>
<P>
   A third factor is at play in the supply of both domestic heating
oil and natural gas: A decade or more of relatively cheap energy
prices has lessened the incentive for domestic oil and gas
exploration and production and increased dependence on cheap
imported crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1999, the number of domestic drilling rigs fell
to an all-time low _ about 500 _ in reaction to worldwide oil glut
that followed the Asian economic crisis of 1997 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the number has risen to around 1,000 as prices
have climbed, said Allen Mesch, director of the Maguire Energy
Institute at Southern Methodist University in Dallas. But it is
still low considering the current price of oil: It matches the
number of domestic drilling rigs at work when the price was about
$22 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you've got almost twice as much price and you still have
the same number of rigs out there,'' Mesch said. ``That tells me
people just aren't believing these high prices. They're cautious
because they got clobbered in '98. If you're just an oil and gas
explorer and producer, when prices go down, you're really hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, this caution reflects a major shift in the domestic
energy game, said Mesch. Throughout the 1990s, major oil companies
sold off much of their domestic property, leaving exploration in
places like the Permian Basin of West Texas to small independents
who lack the financial heft to weather price fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   There's a mirror image of this caution among the OPEC oil
ministers. While they're anxious to keep global economic growth
humming, they want to avoid an oil glut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to kill themselves,'' said Mesch. ``They don't
want $15 oil. They do want to sell more oil at a more modest price.
I think this is the way to go _ bring a little more production on,
a little more production on and see what it takes to bring the
price down.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with prices as high as they are right now, domestic
oil companies and energy wholesalers want to keep inventories as
low as possible in order to maintain a healthy bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   But Mesch said that means a severe shortage of heating oil and
natural gas stock going into the peak demand season, setting the
stage for even more volatile price spikes than last winter's.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas stocks are 15 percent lower than last year, and the
federal government's Energy Information Agency predicts a 27
percent increase in the residential cost of gas this winter _ to
more than $8 per thousand cubic feet. Heating oil stocks are 25
percent lower than last year. That is likely to drive up the cost
to about $1.30 a gallon, up roughly 30 cents from last year.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the high price of natural gas is the changing
nature of natural gas demand.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, cheap natural gas prices and tougher
environmental restrictions on coal and nuclear fuel have encouraged
utilities to build natural gas power plants, resulting in
year-round demand for this fuel. Gone is the roller-coaster demand
that characterized past natural gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Although dire warnings of an energy crisis seem shocking, Mesch
said there has been a steady climb in energy prices over the past
few years, a climb marked by the summer's sharp spike in gasoline
prices.
</P>
<P>
   And the key difference between now and the Arab oil embargo of
1973 is this: Gasoline prices are high, but supplies are still
plentiful, meaning there has been no replay of the long lines at
the pump of almost 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   To date, America's rapidly rising productivity gains and raw
economic growth have more than offset the higher price of energy.
The domestic economy is also more energy efficient and less
dependent on energy as a factor of overall growth.
</P>
<P>
   But warning signs of slowdown are already flashing in the form
of higher prices for airline tickets, trucking rates and the
double-digit increases in electric utility rates imposed on
industrial users in the West and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you have a surcharge on your airline ticket or
utility bill because of fuel, you look for alternatives, you're
more cautious about purchases and that has a ripple effect
throughout the economy,'' said Mesch.
</P>
<P>
   Ratacjzak and other economists say that a longer regime of high
energy prices may trim as much as a third of the growth rate from
the American economy early next year, compounding the cooling
effect of interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve. They say the
more energy-dependent Asian economies are already feeling the
pinch.
</P>
<P>
   Higher energy prices will rejuvenate interest in alternative
sources, from wind and solar to more exotic variations, the experts
say. But the current scare also serves as a reminder of the failure
to stockpile oil and gas reserves and develop alternative energy
sources when crude oil was cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoyed the low prices, but we may pay for it now,'' said
Samii. ``We got complacent in the individual and policy sense,
driving our SUVs, not doing exploration, not conserving oil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0163 </DOCNO>
