<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FARROS-BOSS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-12 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARROS-BOSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUPPORTIVE ENVIRONMENT IN THE WORK PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   Royal Farros is chairman and CEO of I-Print, an online printing
service. This article was written with Geoffrey Brewer.  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ROYAL FARROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having pets has had a profound impact on how I manage. I expect
a lot of out an animal in terms of love and affection, and I give a
lot of love and affection in return. It involves effort but is also
effortless.
</P>
<P>
   Successfully managing a company involves a lot of the same
expectations and feelings.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Laurie, and I had an 8-year-old Doberman named Otis.
Otis was big, about 130 pounds, and brought so much joy into our
lives. What I really loved doing was getting him on the ground and
wrestling. He was a brute, indestructible, but ultimately we both
had an inner sense about when our playing became too rough. We knew
how to keep our play fun and challenging without it being damaging.
My wife, on the other hand, could get him to purr like an overgrown
house cat.
</P>
<P>
   He developed such a wonderful personality, almost as if he knew
how important he was in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   The way people treat pets really tells you a lot about the way
they approach life, whether they're passive or active. Maybe as
important, I've always believed that the way people treat pets when
they're sick tells you a lot about people, too. Otis battled
lymphoma for two years _ the doctors only gave him six months _
before finally passing. We had high expectations of Otis, and he
did his part: he endured debilitating chemotherapy, doctors' visits
and constant poking and prodding. We had high expectations of
ourselves. We made sure he had the best care, the best diet, and
the most love and affection that was humanly possible.
</P>
<P>
   Now, employees aren't pets (though some bite harder than Otis!).
But creating a loving, affectionate home for pets is similar to
fostering an active environment where employees feel important and
influential. Building such a culture for employees is not just
critical to the personality of an organization, but absolutely key
to its livelihood. Pardon the pun, but you have to let employees
sink their teeth into something that they care about, and you have
to have an environment that supports this.
</P>
<P>
   A new employee came into my office some months ago and proposed
that we move into a different area in the e-printing space. He was
almost defiant in his request, somehow anticipating an Otis-style
wrestling match. I told him, ``OK, let's do it _ you bring in the
order, and you've got the support.'' Our average order at the time
was $60, and he pulled in a $70,000 job.
</P>
<P>
   It's beautiful to watch this new area of business grow into
something significant all because an individual, then individuals,
then the whole company believed in it, wanted it to happen. The
environment we have created made this happen.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like ours that are lumped in with the dot-coms of the
world are going through a lot of pain right now, and justifiably.
There are a lot of bad, young businesses out there that aren't, if
you will, housebroken. Like wild animals, a lot of online companies
are full of enthusiasm but lack a sustainable, supportable
environment. Good companies have both, and some even let you bring
your dog into work with you. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
