<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-12 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DSL: A CHRONICLE OF UNEASY ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LISA BELKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last six months, I have been stalled on the entrance
ramp to the information superhighway. Back in February, I signed up
for my very own digital subscriber line, or DSL, an Internet
connection so fast that it leaves last century's must have, the 56K
modem, in the dust. At least that's what the ads say. When and if I
ever get DSL, I hope it's faster than the companies that supply it.
</P>
<P>
   The arc of all technology is from indulgent to indispensable. In
between there is an interminable moment when everyone must have
``it'' but not everyone can get ``it,'' when the potential becomes
bogged down by the infrastructure. That's why we all listened to
endless busy signals on AOL several years ago.. And now that we've
all become more computer savvy _ spoiled by ISDN lines and T-1
lines at the office and impatient to bring that speed home _ many
of us have war stories to tell about the wait for DSL
</P>
<P>
   When I first sent my deposit to Flashcom, my DSL provider, they
told me that because of high demand, my installation would be
scheduled in six to eight weeks. The visit would not be from
Flashcom, but Northpoint, because, in this complicated DSL world,
it takes three separate companies to install any one line. So I
waited two months, only to learn that the wires to my house were
not up to grade.
</P>
<P>
   It seems this happens a lot. On average, 40 percent of would-be
customers, whose computers are within proper range of a
DSL-equipped central telephone office, run into wiring
complications. I learned this from a very nice executive way up the
management ladder at Flashcom who prefers I don't use his name
because the company is _ natch _ in the midst of going public. (He
also directed me to a Web site, www.DSLreports.com, one of a number
of sites that have sprung up for trading gripes about DSL providers
across the country. It made me feel much less alone.)
</P>
<P>
   But I'm getting ahead of my story. Flashcom sent a ``trouble
ticket'' to what, way back then, was still Bell Atlantic. They are
the third company in this dance, because they own the actual wires.
Although I never saw any evidence that Bell Atlantic had been by, I
received an e-mail message weeks later saying that the problem had
been fixed and that I was scheduled for a two-hour appointment _
with Northpoint again _ to install a lot of hardware through my
walls and onto my computer. When the very nice technician was
finished, my desk was decorated with a pretty DSL modem.
Unfortunately, the lights on the modem, which were supposed to turn
green, stayed red and orange instead.
</P>
<P>
   The problem _ surprise! _ was still the outside wires. Another
``trouble ticket'' was sent, and then Flashcom and I spent several
months exchanging e-mail messages. Theirs were upbeat and peppy,
saying that my outside wiring was now complete and it was time for
my inside wiring. Mine were less than upbeat, saying that no, the
inside wiring had already been installed, but the outside wiring
was still a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bell Atlantic became Verizon, went on strike, settled
and bought a 55 percent stake in Northpoint. The only thing they
didn't do was fix my wires. I, on the other hand, decided to give
up, get back my deposit and remain in the Stone Age. But I wouldn't
go out quietly. So I called Verizon and Flashcom and asked them to
comment, for this column, on why it takes more than six months to
get DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies agreed they were having growing pains. The entire
industry is only two years old, explained the Flashcom executive
(who does not have DSL at his own house because he doesn't want to
go to the trouble of getting his sub-par inside wiring replaced.)
Joan Rasmussen of the public relations department at Verizon
compared this to the early days of electricity, when homeowners
kept their gas lamps installed because the newfangled wiring failed
so often.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been coincidence, but within 24 hours of my call
there was a very nice Verizon technician on the pole outside my
house. (A technician, by the way, who had given up on getting DSL
for his own house after waiting three months.) By the end of the
day the lights on my modem had turned green, and it was left to me
to make a few small adjustments to my computer. These didn't make
my DSL work, but it did disable my existing dial-up modem, leaving
me with no Internet connection at all.
</P>
<P>
   As I write this, there is an exceedingly nice technician from
Northpoint in my office, where he has been the last two hours. My
DSL modem works when connected to his laptop, he says, which means
the problem is now my computer, and he suggests I go out and buy a
new Ethernet card. While I'm out, I think I might pick up a gas
lantern, just in case. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0722 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN     09-12 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OPERATING SYSTEM DID `WIN ME' OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   A few months ago, I installed a
beta version of Microsoft's new operating system for home users,
Windows Millennium Edition, on my computer. Microsoft calls it
``Windows Me'' for short.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Struggling with the installation, I called it ``Windows Woe is
Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The operative word in the first sentence of this column is
``beta,'' software industry lingo for work-in-progress.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, the beta version on my computer was replaced
by the final shipping version of Windows Me _ the one that will go
on sale in stores Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Woe begone. This one installed without a hitch, and unlike the
beta version, which froze on startup unless a second computer
connected to the Win Me computer was disconnected from it, the
final version had no problems with the network connection.
</P>
<P>
   Win Me promises faster start-up times, and that, too, has been
the case. Windows 98 used to take almost three minutes to load on
my jam-packed Nimbus 2001. Win Me has cut that loading time to 45
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The new operating system is being offered for $59.95 to users
upgrading from Windows 98 or Windows 98 Second Edition; the
introductory price is good through the middle of January.
</P>
<P>
   To recap some of the other features in Win Me:
</P>
<P>
   New shut-down options offer a sleep mode that powers down a
desktop computer but allows a quick resumption of work. A
hibernation mode saves work in progress to the hard drive, then
drops the system to its lowest power state.
</P>
<P>
   Easier networking. Many homes have two computers. Windows Me
makes the task of linking the two simpler. Both computers need not
be running Windows Me.
</P>
<P>
   Win Me's Movie Maker makes working with video clips much easier.
It can speed the process of creating videos to e-mail to friends
and family. It's also easier to work with digital cameras and
photographs than older Windows versions.
</P>
<P>
   Win Me's Media Player has been revamped, transforming music into
colorful dancing bars and circles. It also provides the useful
feature of creating and indexing high qualilty audio files.
</P>
<P>
   System Restore has been added, allowing users to turn back the
clock and reset the system and its files to a previous point in
time _ usually to a point to before when something stopped working
or a file was accidently erased. The restore program automatically
takes ``snapshots'' of the computer's hard drive and saves them, or
allows users to make them manually. Then, if a virus finds its way
into the machine, the user can back up a day or two before the
virus appeared and get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNET, the Internet arm of computer-magazine publisher Ziff
Davis, predicted in May that Windows Me ``will be a compelling
upgrade for most users.''
</P>
<P>
   It apparently won't have people standing in lines before the
doors open as the release of Windows 98 did. But the first time a
computer starts misbehaving, the System Restore function of Windows
Me may begin to have a magnetic appeal.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
