<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-VA-AGENTORANGE-0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vietnam sergeant was victim of Agent Orange
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Ind. _ When he was 18, Harold Johnson served his
country proudly in Vietnam as an infantry sergeant, only to be
exposed by his own government to a toxic chemical, Agent Orange,
that would kill him some 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Days before his death from lung cancer last week, Johnson, 51,
said he was no longer angry about what had happened to him in
Vietnam, when military personnel sprayed the potent herbicide
around his tent ``like it was Kool-Aid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm bitter, but I don't want to die hating anyone,'' he
said in a whisper. The ballooning tumor in his chest had all but
blocked his air passage. ``Probably I would have felt differently
if my religious beliefs hadn't grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was grateful that the Dayton VA had provided all
his care, free of charge, because his illness was 100 percent
service-connected.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton VA provides a full range of end-of-life services to
eligible veterans, at reduced or no cost, depending on their
eligibility. Its new patient tower includes a homey 36-bed unit for
both hospice and palliative care. Hospice care is for terminally
ill patients with a life expectancy of less than six months, while
palliative care is for patients expected to live more than six
months but less than five years.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before his death, Johnson was free of pain. He was
receiving regular doses of morphine and taking Tylenol laced with
codeine to help him sleep. But like many terminal patients, he was
so weak he couldn't walk or feed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take away the weakness completely, of course. What we
do is encourage patients to eat to the extent they can, and we try
to help them cope with it psychologically,'' said Dr. Geetika
Kumar, medical director of the VA hospice and palliative care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his lung cancer was diagnosed 2 1/2 years ago, one of
Johnson's lungs was removed, and he was treated with chemotherapy
and radiation, but it was too late, he said. More recently, the VA
arranged to send him to Cincinnati for a special laser treatment to
try to burn away the tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten good medical care'' from the VA, Johnson said.
``Ninety percent of the people over there are really dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Each room in the VA hospice unit is equipped with a sofa bed for
family members who want to stay overnight. A family lounge includes
a TV room and kitchen stocked with food items requested by
patients. In addition, there is a hospitality house on the VA
grounds where family members can stay for $5 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Every Thursday afternoon, the unit throws a ``quality of life''
party for patients and their families in the lounge, which is
decorated for holidays and other themed events.
</P>
<P>
   Dying veterans who prefer to return home can receive community
hospice services, coordinated by the Dayton VA program. The VA also
will supply medical equipment to families, including a motorized
scooter for patients to get around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way they can spend their energy doing the things they
want to do'' rather than trying to walk, said Kathy Hayes,
coordinator of the VA hospice and palliative care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had spent eight weeks in the VA hospice unit before
returning home late last month. His two grown daughters, Christina
and Merrily, cared for him in his cozy frame cottage on the
outskirts of town. Behind the home is Johnson's beloved garden,
teeming with corn, squash, tomatoes, beans and pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   A community hospice agency in Richmond provided his nursing care
under Kumar's supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson died last week at his home, surrounded by his two grown
daughters and son. ``He died in his sleep. It was very peaceful,''
Hayes said..
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had counted on returning to the VA unit when his
condition worsened. ``I'm really glad there is a hospice unit. I
can go there if I really get bad,'' he said. ``I think they can
probably make me more comfortable there.''
</P>
<P>
   But by early Friday morning, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had said he was not afraid of dying. He just wanted to
go in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually looking forward to meeting the Lord,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
