<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0728 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DEATHMAINBAR-0913-COX     09-12 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHMAINBAR-0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospice eases burdens for those who fall through government's
support network
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Although she had complained of pain in her
shoulders and back for half a year, Sandi Hughes wasn't diagnosed
with lung cancer until the disease had reached her brain and
paralyzed her legs.
</P>
<P>
   At age 43, and with two adolescent daughters in her sole care,
Hughes suddenly had no job and no family support system at a time
when she was facing a terminal disease.
</P>
<P>
   She called on her unemployed husband, from whom she had been
separated for six years. In May, he moved her from Alabama to his
home in Fairborn, where family members, especially Hughes'
15-year-old daughter, Jennifer, cared for her in a tiny, ramshackle
house.
</P>
<P>
   For hours at a time, Jennifer and her 12-year-old half-sister,
Stephanie, were alone in caring for their mother and, at times, had
no food in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Many poorer families can fall through the cracks of the
government's support network when a loved one is dying. While
Medicare or Medicaid will pay for most end-of-life services, a
physician must first certify that the terminally ill patient is
expected to live less than six months.
</P>
<P>
   Terminally ill patients under the age of 65 with a longer
prognosis must wait two years from the time they become disabled to
qualify for a Medicare card to pay their medical bills. And while
there is no waiting period for coverage through Medicaid _ the
state-federal program that pays the medical bills of the poor _
families who apply for disability coverage can wait weeks and even
months for their benefits to kick in.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it can be a race between the patient's declining
health and the speed of paperwork. In the case of Sandi Hughes,
Medicaid didn't begin paying her bills from Alabama until a day
after she had died.
</P>
<P>
   Doug McGarry, head of the Area Agency on Aging, an advocacy
group for the elderly, said the hardest hit patients are those
younger than 65 who have just enough assets to disqualify them for
Medicaid but who must somehow make ends meet during the two-year
wait for Medicare disability coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a terminal diagnosis,'' he said, ``do you have enough
time to spend down your assets'' to qualify for Medicaid?
</P>
<P>
   Without any home health coverage for her mother, Jennifer became
her primary caregiver for nearly a month this spring. She got her
mother up in the mornings, fed her, got her to the bathroom and
into bed again at night. When her mother would ask for a cigarette
in the middle of the night, Jennifer made sure she didn't burn
herself up in bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She kept saying how sorry she was that she had taken my
childhood away,'' Jennifer said. ``She was just really hard on
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can refer a family to hospice, but only a doctor can
approve their care in the program. In mid-June, Hughes finally was
seen by her husband's physician, who in turn certified her
admission to Hospice of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Hospice programs neither hasten nor postpone death. Their
mission is to keep patients free of pain and their quality of life
as high as possible, without hooking them to machines or isolating
them in hospitals. Hospice services include patient and family
counseling, specialized nursing and home health care and drugs and
supplies for pain relief.
</P>
<P>
   Hospice of Dayton not only took over Hughes' care but the care
of her family as well, making sure there were enough medical
supplies and food in the house. On her first visit, a hospice nurse
took Jennifer and Stephanie out for a rare treat _ a visit to
McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nurse told us it was a reward for helping her out, but we
knew what it was all about,'' Jennifer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Baughman, a Hospice of Dayton social worker, referred the
family to the Emergency Food Bank and gave them a gift certificate
donated by Meijer supermarket. She even found a new home for the
family's dog, which they could no longer afford to take care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing I can say that is good enough'' for the
Hospice of Dayton staff, said Dee Harmeling, Sandi's mother and a
Bellbrook resident. ``They helped us out with anything, everything
we asked, no matter how small it was.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 19, Hughes was moved to the Hospice of Dayton inpatient
facility, where she could be made more comfortable in her final
days.
</P>
<P>
   Hospice of Dayton did not charge the family a penny, but it must
rely on community donations to extend its help. In 1999, the agency
provided $3 million in uncompensated care. Donations from local
businesses and individuals covered those costs. Almost all of the
2,600 patients and their families in the care of Hospice of Dayton
last year received some form of financial aid, since Medicare,
Medicaid and private insurers rarely pay the full cost of services.
</P>
<P>
   Worry over family finances and the fate of those left behind can
keep many dying people from letting go, Baughman said. Amazingly,
with cancer eating away at her brain, Hughes had remained lucid
until the last 10 days of her life. Within hours of her admission
to the hospice inpatient facility, her speech began to fail and
words escaped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a marked change,'' said Pat Selter, a family member
who helped with Sandi's care. ``It was like she had held herself
together for all those months. I think she just needed to get
things settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer remembers the night her mother decided to let go. ``I
was just kind of sitting there watching TV in her room when I heard
her say something. At first she sort of rattled off something _ I
don't know what _ and then she just said, 'Goodbye.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the last lucid things she said,'' Harmeling
said.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Hughes was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman called her ``a fighter who wanted to take care of her
kids. And once she was able to do that, she was able to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: jimdebrosse(at)coxohio.com .
</P>
