<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BOURSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE MANHATTAN SAID TO BEIN TALKS TO ACQUIRE J.P. MORGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated.) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan is in serious talks to acquire J.P Morgan, an
executive close to the deal said Tuesday. The deal, expected to be
worth at least $40 billion, would unite two of the oldest and most
powerful forces in New York finance.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the negotiations were not immediately available,
although the executive said an announcement could come as early as
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction would end the independence of J.P. Morgan, the
most famous name in the history of American finance. For Chase,
which has historically made smaller acquisitions, like its buyout
of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist and Robert Fleming Holdings, the deal would
catapult the bank into the top echelon with Goldman Sachs and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Chase and J.P. Morgan declined to comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is part of a recent wave of consolidation in investment
banking, where size and diversity _ both in business lines and in
geography _ are becoming more and more necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The deal follows other large transactions like the Credit Suisse
Group acquisition last month to pay $13.4 billion in cash and stock
for Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. In July, UBS AG agreed to pay $16
billion for the Paine Webber Group.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan shares were trading $5-3/8 higher Tuesday at
$174-3/8, a 52-week high. The shares climbed to as high as $176
after opening at $169. J.P. Morgan had held talks with Deutsche
Bank, but those talks were abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Peter Hancock, J.P. Morgan's chief financial officer,
resigned abruptly, fueling merger speculation.
</P>
</TEXT>
