<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      09-12 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING THAT KICK BACK INTO SALSA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For decades in this country, the most beloved
condiment was ketchup, bottled ketchup. But the American palate
woke up, and a great national craving for a spicy Mexican sauce
took hold, and ultimately it supplanted ketchup in many homes.
</P>
<P>
   It was salsa. But lately it, too, has come perilously close to
the commonplace _ bottled and consistent and without much variety.
The fact is, though, that even if you limit yourself to Mexico for
inspiration _ and ignore Spain or even Sicily _ the salsas from
Mexico's regions are too numerous to count, bursting with invention
and surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs across the country have continued to take salsa to new
levels, and their ideas are easy to adapt to the home kitchen. By
preparing just a few of these widely different salsas (the Spanish
word simply means sauce), you can get a sense of the breathtaking
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   There's the familiar tomato salsa, with tomato, onion, chile and
cilantro. Less familiar is the salsa verde, with its tomatillo
base. But a great salsa doesn't have to have tomatoes in it, or
even chilies. Some are cooked, some aren't. Some reach for
combinations that you've probably never experienced before, like
black beans and peaches or toasted almonds and fresh herbs. One
thing all salsas have is bite, and they have the remarkable
capacity to breathe life into the simplest grilled fish or meat
dish.
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing: For the most part, they are much easier to
prepare than they seem. To me, salsas are especially appealing when
they are made from uncooked ingredients. The basis of most raw
salsas is a chopped, pounded or nearly pureed vegetable, herb or
fruit, made superflavorful by the addition of some combination of
onion, garlic, lime or lemon juice. Many also incorporate more than
one herb, shallots, spices and, of course, chilies. The best
combinations are quite moist _ so if tomato or a juicy fruit is not
one of the basic ingredients, a great deal of citrus juice usually
makes up for it. Salsas are thin-textured and informal, but they
are fresh, colorful and beautiful on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs understand these things, and are always experimenting:
There are only so many ways you can grill a piece of fish, meat or
chicken, but the salsas you can serve them with are unlimited. In
some ways, asking a chef which salsa to serve with which dish is an
exercise in futility, not unlike asking the short-order cook which
dish to serve with ketchup. (The short answer: Almost anything.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, chefs do tend to serve salsas and other strong sauces
with grilled food, and that's a good guideline: When even a mild
meat or fish is well browned, it gains enough backbone to support a
spicy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Raw salsas retain the strong, bold flavors of their basic
components, especially garlic and chilies. And because these
flavors can sometimes be overpowering, many chefs make salsas with
roasted chilies. ``I hardly do any salsas that are completely
uncooked,'' said Rick Bayless, the chef and owner of Frontera Grill
in Chicago. Roasting tames the heat of many chilies, and brings out
more subtle flavors. But Bayless has his no-cook salsa, too: A
tomato-fruit version that features uncooked habaneros, the fiery,
complex little pepper also known as Scotch bonnet.
</P>
<P>
   Chipotles (smoked jalapenos) also need no roasting, since
they've already been mellowed by smoke. ``And,'' said Mark Miller,
the chef and owner of Coyote Cafe in Santa Fe, N.M., ``if you buy
canned chipotles in adobo, you already have the added flavors of
tomato and vinegar, so you're halfway to making a great-tasting
salsa already.'' Miller combines a puree of chipotle in adobo with
fresh fruit to make a salsa for grilled or roasted pork or
dark-fleshed fish.
</P>
<P>
   Zarela Martinez, the chef and owner of Zarela's in Manhattan,
reminded me that one of the most basic and important salsas, chile
pastor _ a thin sauce that is not unlike a coarse pesto _ is an
uncooked blend of chilies, lime, onions and herbs. Her green sauce
with avocado combines jalapeno, tomatillos and avocado for a kind
of light, spicy guacamole that is a good dip or sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh, raw salsa can, of course, be made with no chilies at all.
A good example of this is one created by Susanne Goin at Lucques in
West Hollywood, Calif. ``I start with a basic chopped salsa
verde,'' she said, ``and add either almonds, which makes it perfect
for grilled fish, or shards of feta, which I like to serve with
chunks of skewered and grilled lamb. You can also add hard-cooked
egg to the sauce and use it for salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing about salsa. Once you get started, there's
almost no limit to what you can put together with no cooking at
all.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN SAUCE WITH AVOCADO
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Zarela Martinez
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 small white onion, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh serrano or jalapeno chilies, or to taste, stemmed,
seeded and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 tomatillos (about { pound), husks removed, and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado
</P>
<P>
   8 to 10 cilantro springs.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a food processor or with mortar and pestle, process or
pound the garlic and salt to a paste. Add onion, chilies and
tomatillos; pulse in processor or pound to make a slightly chunky
paste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Scoop out the avocado flesh. For a smooth machine-finished
puree, add it and the cilantro to the processor and process very
fine. By hand, finely chop the avocado and mash it into the
onion-tomatillo mixture; stir in cilantro leaves. (For a medium
texture, pour the machine-processed onion-tomatillo mixture into a
bowl and mix in the chopped avocado and cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   3. Serve immediately as a dip or a sauce with chips or
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 2{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   SALSA VERDE WITH NUTS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Susanne Goin
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 anchovy, preferably packed in salt, rinsed and cleaned
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh marjoram leaves
</P>
<P>
   \ cup mint, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup parsley leaves, tightly packed
</P>
<P>
   } cup olive oil, more or less
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped or slivered almonds, preferably toasted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a food processor or with a mortar and pestle, pulse or
pound the anchovy and garlic to a paste, then add capers, and then
the herbs until everything is coarsely pureed. Be careful not to
overprocess.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the olive oil a bit at a time until mixture is smooth and
saucy. Taste and add more oil if necessary. Stir in nuts and serve
with fish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO SALSA WITH FRUIT
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Rick Bayless &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups tomatoes, in \-inch dice &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 habanero chili, or to taste, seeded, stemmed and minced
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup chopped cilantro (the stems are OK)
</P>
<P>
   } cup chopped ripe mango, peach, nectarine or pear, in \-inch
dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt as needed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Soak the onion in the lime juice for 20 minutes while you
prepare the other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine the tomato, chili, cilantro and fruit. When the onion
is ready, stir it in, along with some salt. Add more lime juice if
necessary and serve with grilled meats or poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK BEAN AND PEACH SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked black beans, drained (and rinsed, if from a can)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peach, mango or papaya, cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   { red bell pepper, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 small chili (or more), preferably habanero seeded, stemmed,
minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients. Taste and adjust seasoning if necessary.
Let sit 5 minutes or so, and serve with white-flesh fish or
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   HERB AND SHALLOT SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tightly packed chopped herbs like as parsley, cilantro or
mint leaves, alone or in any combination
</P>
<P>
   { cup peeled and chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 small jalapeno or other hot chili (or more to taste), seeded,
stemmed and minced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 limes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine all ingredients and let sit 5 minutes.
If mixture seems thick, thin with a little water, neutral oil (like
canola or corn oil) or additional lime juice. Taste and adjust
seasoning if necessary. Serve with grilled meat, chicken or fish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   FRUIT SALSA WITH CHIPOTLE PUREE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Mark Miller
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus up to 1 hour's resting time
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pineapple, peach or nectarine, cut into \-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   { cup red bell pepper, stemmed, seeded and cut into \-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons pureed canned chipotle chilies in adobo
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine all the ingredients; let rest for at
least 10 minutes and up to 1 hour. Serve with pork or dark-fleshed
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
