<HEADLINE>
DONALD WHYTE, 68, VIOLINIST WITH NEW YORK PHILHARMONIC  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Ohio, Pa., Canada)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donald Whyte, a violinist in the New York
Philharmonic, died on Sunday at Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital in
Manhattan. He was 68 and lived in Pleasantville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications after surgery, said Eric Latzky, a
spokesman for the Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Whyte was born in Rivers, Manitoba, in 1942, and began his
violin studies with his father, Alexander Whyte. He continued his
studies at the University of Saskatchewan and later as a student of
Josef Gingold at Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   Whyte was a member of the Cincinnati Symphony, the Montreal
Symphony and the Pittsburgh Symphony before joining the New York
Philharmonic in 1972. As a member of the orchestra, he was a
representative at the International Conference of Symphony and
Opera Musicians, an organization that monitors everything from
compensation to performance conditions at the major orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a board member of the Music Assistance Fund, which
provides support for young minority musicians. He was chairman of
the Philharmonic's artistic committee, which is involved in the
search for a new music director for the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his work with the Philharmonic, Whyte played
recitals with his wife, Noriko Kitamura, a pianist, and played
chamber music with several ensembles, including the Gofriller
Quartet and the Soho Ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife &UR; , &LR;  and a daughter, Lianne McKenzie,
of Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
