<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0747 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-RATS-COLUMN-NN     09-12 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-RATS-COLUMN-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BETTER A RATTY CAMPAIGN THAN A MOUSY ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Sept. 12, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(AT)nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Every time this dull campaign threatens to get fun, it
gets boring again. Latest outrage: An ad produced for the George
Bush campaign appears to flash the word ``RATS'' when discussing
how bureaucrats would flourish under the Al Gore-Joe Lieberman
health care plan. How ... diabolical. They associate bureaucrats
with RATS, thereby dispelling the warm feeling of love most
Americans have for government functionaries.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably an editing mistake, a stray frame. Too bad. It
should have been intentional. We need crueler ads to liven up the
race. Enough of these earnest, warm-voiced dispatches from the
Blandlands -- this campaign needs a series of ads that open wounds
and dump on the salt. It wouldn't change anyone's mind; it might
not move the polls a jot. But it's part of the modern automated
campaign:
</P>
<P>
   1. Candidates pledge to take the high road. Translation:
puppies-and-flags commercials until Labor Day, and then we accuse
the other guy of decapitating nuns and using their skulls in a
white-power skeet-shooting competition.
</P>
<P>
   2. Half the pundit corps tut-tuts when someone goes negative,
but only if the spots land body blows on their man. Witness the
reaction to Bush's first unspeakably negative ad. The spot plays
Gore's I-begat-the-Internet quote, points out the ethical brouhaha
over the Buddhist Temple fund-raiser, and suggests that you just
can't trust Al. From the reaction of the press, you'd think Bush
had accused Gore of doing and saying WHAT EVERYONE KNOWS HE DID AND
SAID. Has he no shame?
</P>
<P>
   3. The rest of the punditry -- the older, saturnine half that's
seen it all and just hangs on for the expense-account suppers --
will point out that campaigns used to be much, much worse. Why, in
1804, Lucius Zachary Throckstrochen called his Senate race opponent
``a trebly-curs'd Masonic whoretaster,'' prompting his opponent to
reply that Lucius had ``the morals of an vaporous ibex and the low
cunning of a popish rooster. Also, he's gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they could really sling the dirt in those days. No one knew
what they were talking about, but they got the general idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bush needs to vault over the heads of the press; he needs to
learn to spin small truths into big lies, Democrat-style. He needs
some cruel ads that take a two-by-four to Gore's brainpan. A
suggested spot:
</P>
<P>
   Black-and-white footage of a civil rights march. Sonorous, sad
voiceover:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long struggle for equality. But it's not over yet
-- not as long as Al Gore opposes innovation in education. He
doesn't want black children to use vouchers so they can attend the
same schools as his children. He doesn't want Social Security
reform -- and since black men die earlier than whites, this means
most of their contributions stay with the government instead of
going to their children. That's right: Al Gore would take money
from dead black dads and use it to subsidize cotton-farm owners in
the Deep South. But what else would you expect from a man whose own
father voted against civil rights for blacks? Al Gore: Smart guy.
Too bad he wants to keep black people down.''
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine the shouts of outrage. But if the shoe fits in
your opponent's buttocks, start kicking. Gore is the candidate of
the teachers' unions, not the students. He's the candidate of the
government unions -- and when you're more concerned about the
people who hand out the welfare, you're less concerned with the
welfare of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Ad No. 2: The environment. Film of gas lines. Voiceover:
``Remember the days of energy shortages? Cheap, flimsy cars? A
collapse of national strength and will? Al Gore does. And he wants
them back again. Due to his environmental beliefs'' (Cut to film of
naked hippies dancing around a tree) ``we've stopped drilling for
oil in America. Gore wants you out of your safe SUVs and into small
tin cars, because he worships dirt instead of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Outrageous, of course. Unspeakably wrong. But why can the Dems
associate GOP votes with a vote for church-burning -- or, as Gore
has said, equate their water policies with DEATH? This is war; this
is a fight to the end. But of course the soccer-mom demographic
hates it when the two parties fight, so we'll never see good
negative ads. Rats.
</P>
<P>
   Or, rather, medium-level government officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
