<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CAMPAIGN-VOLUNTEERS-N     09-12 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-VOLUNTEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS IN WHITE COLLARS WITH POLITICAL STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ore., Conn., Texas)   By JOBERT E. ABUEVA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every Thursday evening, Marilyn Robinson, executive director of
the Nashville Minority Business Center, drives from her office to
the Gore-Lieberman campaign headquarters and works the phones for
three hours, canvassing voters throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what I do at work is persuading others to fund and
support our various programs. It's no different with potential
voters,'' said Robinson, who also puts in a Saturday morning shift
at Gore headquarters. ``I like that I bring what I do best, selling
and speaking, into the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   And those aren't the only management skills she taps into. She
also enlists help from her network of friends and business
associates, including members of 100 Black Women, a local social
group.
</P>
<P>
   For all the frenzied fund-raising by Democrats and Republicans
this year, candidates for offices from the the White House to the
local school board know one thing is even more important than
money: volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   And while these unpaid armies are made up mostly of students and
retired people, it is business professionals who exhibit the
qualities that political candidates value most: nuts-and-bolts
organizational skills, management savvy and address books crammed
with contacts.
</P>
<P>
   To campaign managers, these executives are golden because they
can get things done. Consider Jose Forquet, a 34-year-old vice
president at Goldman, Sachs in New York, and Joe Bogosian, a
35-year-old lawyer at McGuire Woods Consulting in Washington. A
couple of years ago, Forquet, an independent, and Bogosian, a
Republican, each had a plan to promote George W. Bush for president
by creating advocacy groups _ of Hispanic executives in Forquet's
case, and of young professionals in Bogosian's.
</P>
<P>
   But then the men were introduced to each other in late 1998 by a
mutual friend who knew of their political activism, and before long
they had developed a more ambitious project. Working with a Bush
campaign official, they drafted a proposal for creating an e-mail
database to recruit corporate managers, lawyers and other young
professionals to take part in fund-raisers and other activities for
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, they traveled at their own expense to Bush's
campaign headquarters in Austin, Texas, to seek its official
endorsement. ``The exact same skills required of selling a start-up
firm to venture capitalists applied'' in winning over the Bush camp
to the idea, Bogosian said.
</P>
<P>
   They got the green light, and YP4W.com _ or Young Professionals
for George W. Bush _ was born, along with a national networking
organization of the same name with chapters in 30 cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from our research that there were many people out
there like us,'' Forquet said. ``A market clearly existed.''
</P>
<P>
   The site was so successful, in fact, that the Bush campaign took
it over and now runs it out of Austin as part of a coalition of Web
sites and voter groups. Forquet and Bogosian continue to head the
New York and Washington chapters of the networking organization.
</P>
<P>
   While few managers can boast of such influence on a national
scale, most can have a big impact on the state or local level.
Laura Dambier, a senior strategist for Lincoln Financial Group in
Hartford, Conn., for example, has no doubts that she is making a
difference in the re-election effort of state Rep. Jessie Stratton,
a Democrat. Dambier spent the greater part of Labor Day assigning
volunteers to task forces and revising calendars for the final
stretch of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely draw from a wide repertoire of skills,'' Dambier
said. She has been active in numerous political races in the past,
she said, and the two biggest tasks in almost every case were the
same ones that corporate managers face every day: setting
priorities and motivating people.
</P>
<P>
   `As you enter the final, crucial weeks, volunteers may begin to
lose interest and therefore need to be refocused on the mission of
our campaign beyond simply garnering votes,'' she said. ``In some
cases, you might reassign duties.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing presence of business professionals is not lost on
campaign managers and indeed presents them with something of a
challenge. ``Working volunteers come into a campaign motivated but
are extremely busy people themselves. They want their investment in
time and effort to pay off,'' said Catherine Shaw, the Democratic
mayor of Ashland, Ore., and the author of a how-to book on
conducting local campaigns. ``Campaign managers need to know what
competencies and connections they bring to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate her point, Shaw described how a volunteer, a
manager in the hospitality industry, recently pulled disparate
databases and segmented voters for follow-up direct-marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Even political neophytes have high expectations of themselves if
they have a business background. Rochelle Pachtman, founder of the
public relations firm Pachtman Communications in Manhattan, says
she jumped into the fray just a few weeks ago to lend a hand to the
Gore campaign because the race was so tight and she thought she
might actually make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting for my marching orders,'' Pachtman said. When she
gets them, she says, she believes she will be able to leverage her
communications skills as well as tap into her expertise in the
industries and issues she has researched over time on behalf of her
clients. For example, she says, she could coach campaign volunteers
on how to put their points across when they are making phone calls
or knocking on doors to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteers, especially inexperienced ones, want feedback on
how they are performing,'' Pachtman said, ``to know that they are
doing a good job and find ways to improve on it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
