<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0913-COX     09-12 1961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    D-RATS! SUBLIMINAL MESSAGE RAISES RUCKUS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A GOP TV ad that subtly flashes the word ```RATS'' across the
screen is coming off the air amid allegations the Republicans were
trying to send a subliminal message about Al Gore. George W. Bush
called the notion ``bizarre and weird,'' and his campaign made
light of it all. The Republican admaker, Alex Castellanos, said he
was just trying to make the spot visually interesting. But Gore's
campaign and experts in political advertising said the choice of
words _ as an announcer was denouncing Gore's Medicare plan _ could
hardly have been an accident. ``I've never seen anything like it,''
Gore said Tuesday in Middletown, Ohio. Bush noted that the word
appears only fleetingly _ for a tiny fraction of a second. Played
at full speed, it's barely noticeable, particularly if the viewer
isn't looking for the word.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING FOR SURVIVAL IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, campaigning in Florida _ no longer a sure-win
state for him _ was trying to reassure seniors Tuesday that his
health proposals would expand the choices under Medicare. With his
new, more personal campaign style on display, Bush greeted the
breakfast crowd at a diner in West Palm Beach, telling patrons his
plan would ``leave the Medicare system in place . . . but offer
additional choices for seniors beyond the current system,
additional choices just like federal employees get.'' Later, at
Florida Hospital in Orlando, Bush said Medicare has failed to
sufficiently cover new treatments and to give doctors the options
they need to care for cancer patients. And he promised a cancer
patient that he will expand Medicare coverage for her and millions
of other older Americans suffering from budget-busting illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN GETS MONEY NOD FROM FEC
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission decided that the Reform Party's
disputed $12.6 million in federal campaign money belongs to Pat
Buchanan. The FEC's 5-1 ruling said Buchanan is the rightful
recipient of the money as the party's nominee. But Buchanan, who is
counting on the money to revive his presidential campaign, can't
get the money yet. The commissioners are expected to give their
final approval within days, theoretically freeing the U.S. Treasury
to give Buchanan a check. However, John Hagelin, who contends that
he, not Buchanan, is the party's legitimate nominee, intends to
appeal to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   BUSING ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried that George W. Bush may be making inroads on
the education issue, Al Gore and Joe Lieberman rumbled across
southern Ohio in separate yellow school buses Tuesday, letting
their limos trail behind, to promote the $170 billion they would
pour into education. They conceded there are ``some similarities''
between their education proposals and Bush's, but promoted their
ideas as far more sweeping. ``What we're proposing is a
comprehensive approach that focuses on the classroom,'' Gore told
middle school students in Miamisburg. ``The difference is we start
with accountability; we don't end with accountability.'' Gore and
Lieberman then headed to a Middletown high school.
</P>
<P>
   WELL, THEY LIKED HIM SIX YEARS AGO, DIDN'T THEY?
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware News Journal and Gov. Tom Carper both want Sen.
William Roth (R-Del.) to pull a TV ad featuring an endorsement of
Roth by the newspaper. Roth spokeswoman Jo Anne Barnhart called the
complaints ``ridiculous,'' saying it's common practice to use
articles and editorials in political ads. The only problem is that
campaigns usually use recent endorsements. This one was from 1994,
when Roth was running against state Attorney General Charles
Oberly. This time, Roth is running against Carper, and the
newspaper has made no endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON THE NEW YORKER VOTES FOR WIFE
</P>
<P>
   Putting their political role reversal in high relief, President
Clinton cast his first vote as a New Yorker Tuesday, pronouncing it
``a thrill'' to vote for his wife. Hillary Clinton was facing the
little-known Dr. Mark McMahon in the New York Democratic primary.
``After all these years of her helping me, it was a thrill,''
Clinton said after early morning balloting at an elementary school
in Chappaqua, his newly adopted hometown. The Clintons bought a
home there last year when the first lady began her Senate campaign
in earnest. Her Senate opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, did not face a
primary challenge.
</P>
<P>
   CONTROVERSIAL JEWISH HONOR TO HILLARY CLINTON
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of her first primary election, Hillary Clinton
collected a controversial award from the World Jewish Congress for
setting up a meeting between her husband and Edgar Bronfman, the
head of the organization, and for work on restitution for Holocaust
victims. Some critics have questioned whether the award is
appropriate, given that Bronfman is an adviser to her campaign and
Jews make up a crucial voting bloc in the Senate race. The campaign
of Clinton's opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, has pointed out that he,
too, played a role in restitution efforts by introducing a bill
that extended the life of a presidential commission investigating
what happened to Holocaust victims' assets that came into American
hands.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI CRITICIZES LAZIO ON ARAFAT
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani says it was a mistake for Rick
Lazio to have enthusiastically shaken the hand of Yasser Arafat
during an official visit to the Middle East nearly two years ago.
``I'm a little confounded by it,'' said Giuliani. ``I don't
particularly like to shake hands with murderers.'' But the mayor
also said that Lazio's handshake was ``not a big deal'' and that
maybe he ``doesn't have the background and understanding of Arafat
that I do.'' Giuliani's remarks about his fellow Republican, who
replaced him in the Senate race against Hillary Clinton, were not
well received by Lazio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   LAMBEAU FIELD VOTE AT GOAL LINE
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay's long love affair with the Packers was being tested
in Wisconsin, with tens of thousands of voters going to the polls
to decide whether to increase the county sales tax to help pay to
expand and remodel Lambeau Field. On the eve of the referendum, the
vote was regarded as too close to call _ with backers of the
proposal engaged in what amounted to a football two-minute drill
and opponents playing rugged defense. Voters were deciding whether
to raise the Brown County sales tax a half-percent to repay $160
million in construction loans, the cornerstone of a $295 million
project to renovate Lambeau Field, the city-owned home of the
Packers.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-CONTROLLED ESTATE INVOLVED IN LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   A $48 million estate controlled by Joe Lieberman evicted a woman
from one of its buildings, then reversed course when she sued him
and alleged she lost her job because she was injured when falling
on the property. Monica E. Beach, 58, continues to live rent free
in the building in Stamford, Conn., until the legal dispute is
settled. A trial is slated for February. Beach was evicted by court
order in April 1997 for not paying rent in a multifamily building
owned by the estate of Lieberman's uncle, Bernard Manger, who died
in May 1995. Beach filed a personal injury lawsuit in April 1997
against Lieberman and his co-executor, Harold Bernstein. Instead of
forcing Beach from her apartment, the estate and its insurance
company responded by letting her stay and agreeing to take rent she
owes out of any eventual settlement.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS: FOR NOW, A TOSS-UP
</P>
<P>
   Four new national polls _ those for Time, Fox News, CNN/USA
Today and NBC/Wall Street Journal _ showed little change in the
presidential race since Al Gore closed the gap with George W. Bush
after the Democratic convention. None of the polls has Gore ahead
by more than three points, about the same spread that many surveys
released a week earlier showed. So with about eight weeks until
Election Day, the race appears to be a toss-up _ at least for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUING ROLE FOR GREENS
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader says that he and his Green Party backers will remain
a presence in American politics, no matter what his showing in
November, and he warned Democrats they'll continue to be challenged
from the left ``unless they shape up.'' In an interview with the
Washington Post, Nader warned, ``This party is not going to go
away.'' Nader conceded that Democrats are closer to his views than
Republicans on issues such as taxes and tobacco, but said he
believed neither party was prepared to address the ``real issues of
power'' in this country, largely because both are dependent on
wealthy individuals and corporations for campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN DENIES BOTH REFORM HOPEFULS
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Court of Appeals ruled against allowing either of
the two Reform Party presidential hopefuls to appear on the state's
Nov. 7 ballot. The court ruled 2-1 that Secretary of State Candice
Miller followed the law when she denied both Pat Buchanan and Iowa
physicist John Hagelin ballot slots. Miller said she was unable to
determine the official Reform Party chairman in Michigan. The state
party _ like the national _ has split into two factions, each with
its own chairman. Hagelin supporters said he will appear on the
ballot as the Natural Law Party candidate if he cannot appear under
the Reform Party banner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH DENIES SUGGESTIONS OF DYSLEXIA
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush denied suggestions in a Vanity Fair article that
he has dyslexia. ``No, I'm not dyslexic,'' Bush said on ABC's
``Good Morning America'' today. ``That's all I can tell you.'' Bush
said he hadn't read the article and referred to his spokeswoman
Karen Hughes' characterization: ``In the case of this story,
fiction is stranger than truth,'' she said. The article in the
October issue quotes language experts who say Bush's tendency to
mix up words while speaking is consistent with dyslexia, a
neurological disorder impairing the ability to read and write. The
Bush campaign said the author, Gail Sheehy, may have confused the
candidate with his brother, Neil, who is dyslexic.
</P>
<P>
   HOW FAR REMOVED FROM LIFE-DEATH DECISIONS?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush gets criticized for his hands-off approach to
state executions, but state law leaves little room for governors to
act in these life-and-death decisions. Supporters say Bush allows
the 18-member Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles to do its job
freely by maintaining an arm's-length relationship. ``The governor
leaves it up to each parole board member to make their own
decisions after they review the case. They're an independent
body,'' said Bush spokesman Mike Jones. Others contend that Bush
does direct the board _ through his public statements on executions
and his power to appoint members to their six-year, $80,000-a-year
jobs. Since Bush became governor in 1995, the state has executed
143 people, including 32 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ON SECOND THOUGHT, HE'D LIKE SOME ORANGE JUICE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush tried to woo senior citizens in Florida, but
almost alienated another huge Sunshine State voting bloc: the
orange juice lobby. Joined by his brother, Jeb, the Florida
governor, Bush was promoting his plan for a Medicare prescription
drug benefit in Clearwater when he was offered a glass of orange
juice. Seemingly oblivious to the political ramifications of
refusing the beverage in this state, he declined. Brother Jeb
quickly stepped in. ``You don't want any FLORIDA orange juice?'''
Jeb Bush asked, setting off his brother's political warning lights.
Bush then replied: ``I am orange-juiced out. But if I had orange
juice it would be FLORIDA orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
