u w BC-MILITARY-READINESS-HN     09-12 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-READINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIR FORCE GENERAL SAYS READINESS IS ON THE MEND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (FILED in the ``w'' and ``p'' categories) ,
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Weighing in on a hot-button campaign issue, a
frontline Air Force general said Tuesday that the military
readiness of his crews and equipment is on the mend after several
years of decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are turning the corner,'' said Gen. Gregory Martin,
commander of U.S. Air Force units based in Europe, adding that
readiness in the Air Force hit its nadir in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Martin leads 26,000 active-duty airmen and women at 14 overseas
bases, many of which are the first to be called on in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His picture of military readiness is considerably less bleak
than that of Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush and
Dick Cheney, his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney have accused President Clinton of eroding
military readiness by sending the armed forces abroad too often on
questionable missions and by not replacing older weaponry. As a
result, the GOP candidates argue, the military has low moral,
insufficient training and outdated equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Bush has called the armed forces ``a military in
decline'' and has charged that they have been ``undermined by
back-to-back deployments, poor pay, shortages of spare parts and
equipment, and rapidly declining readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration and Vice President Al Gore, Bush's Democratic
opponent, have conceded that the military needs improvement,
particularly in pay and benefits, but that readiness is not
faltering. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart has said the Army,
Marines and Air Force are more ready for battle today than in 1993,
when Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said Tuesday that in four key measures of military
readiness _ weaponry, training, availability of spare parts and
morale of troops _ the Air Force has shown improvement, especially
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. weaponry is ``excellent,'' he said, adding that his forces
are well trained although the service is ``a little thin'' because
it lacks sufficient numbers of supervisors to help train the crews.
Morale is rising in part because the Air Force is ensuring that its
service members and their families have adequate housing, he said.
Lack of decent housing has been a longtime gripe of many military
families and has been a factor in the inability of the armed forces
to retain personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the availability of spare parts is one area that
needs more improvement. Although the Air Force has ``arrested the
decline'' in such parts, Martin said, ``we're not ahead of the
game.'' Some units have enough and others do not. In battle, some
units likely would have to borrow spare parts from others, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the Air Force would like to have 80 percent to 85
percent of its fighter aircraft available for operations at any
given time. However, because of parts shortages and other factors,
75 percent to 80 percent of the aircraft are currently available,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force also would like to have 70 percent to 75 percent
of its airlifter planes available for duty at any given time, but
only 60 percent to 65 percent of planes are currently available, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Military operations _ such as last year's NATO air war against
Serbia in which the U.S. Air Force shouldered most of the duty and
current missions over Iraq _ have eaten into the U.S. parts
inventory, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
