<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBY-DEE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actresss usrges students to watch their world
 &HT;    By Richard O. Jones
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Ruby Dee says, ``Pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran actress spent a day in Oxford Monday as Miami
University's Cromer/Flory Performing Artist-In-Residence to share
her vast experience with both students and the university
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get older, there's a great temptation to give
advice,'' said the 75-year-old actress to the Hall Auditorium crowd
Monday night, but some of her best advice came earlier in the day
when Dee conducted a master class for acting students.
</P>
<P>
   As an award-winning actress, Dee appeared in films, on Broadway,
and in television productions, including ``Decoration Day,'' for
which she received an Emmy, and ``Roots: The Next Generation.'' She
starred in the original Broadway production and the film version of
Lorraine Hansberry's ``A Raisin in the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   On the dimly lit stage of Studio 88, the black box theater in
the basement of the Center for Performing Arts, Dee told the
assembled students that their greatest tool is their own powers of
observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I stand before you about to speak, I have to first see
you,'' she said, and pointed at various students and pointed out
something about them: Brown sweater, blue scarf, gold earrings. ``I
pay attention to these details and then you will remain in some
region of my consciousness for the rest of my life,'' she said.
``You might have to bring it out under hypnosis, but we are a part
of each other forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something comfortable in that. As actors, you have to
have an affinity for people in the first place. If you pay
attention to the details, you'll always have something to put in
your bag. As an actor, I'll never know when I'll need you.''
</P>
<P>
   During the nearly two-hour session, three students presented
monologues for Dee to critique. She impressed upon them the
purposefulness of action on stage, that characters are coming from
somewhere and have reached the stage because they want something.
Sometimes, an actor can convey more with her body than with the
words she speaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important parts of a scene is what you don't
say,'' she said. ``What you think can be seen and you must have the
courage to think it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dee considers herself a ``word monger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I won a box of jelly beans for a short story I wrote when I
was six years old,'' she said during her public performance Monday
evening. ``It took many years for me to get my thoughts together
enough to write again.''
</P>
<P>
   Her writings for the stage include ``Zora Is My Name,'' a
production based on the works of Harlem Renaissance author Zora
Neale Hurston and the musical revue ``Two Hah Hahs and a Homeboy,''
a collaboration with her husband Ossie Davis and son Guy Davis. She
also adapted for the stage works of other authors for her ``Books
With Legs'' series, which began with ``The Disappearance'' by Rosa
Guy.
</P>
<P>
   With Ossie Davis, she co-wrote ``In This Life Together,'' a
biography of their marriage. Monday night, she read from her other
book, ``My One Good Nerve,'' a compilation of short stories, humor
and poetry, including a selection of poems in which she updated the
Mother Goose nursery rhymes for a modern age.
</P>
<P>
   In her reconception, ``The Old Lady Who Lived in a Shoe'' became
a three-part treatise on birth control and homelessness, ``Jack and
Jill'' an exploration of racism and minority issues, and ``Peter
Peter Pumpkin Eater'' a look at spousal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer period with the audience, she
discussed her appearances in two Spike Lee films and told how she
knew him as a child and how he raised money with $10 and $20
donations to make his first film, ``She's Gotta Have It,'' and how
her son Guy was amazed when Lee paid him back.
</P>
<P>
   Before she left the stage, someone asked her for her best piece
of advice for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing keeps coming to my mind every day,'' she said, ``and
that's to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention to both sounds and silence. Pay attention to the
stories behind the headlines. Pay attention to the divine. We're a
concoction of divine material and were here for something, and we
have to pay attention to what that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention that we don't get bought, that the highest
bidder doesn't rake us in. Pay attention that we don't let our
things drown us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention to our wants, because I know that it's not what
we can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
