<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, notes from wrestling industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love is in the air all around professional wrestling circles.
</P>
<P>
   World Wrestling Federation commentator Jim Ross reports in his
weekly ``Ross Report'' that ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin will marry
Debra McMichael and
</P>
<P>
   Jerry ``The King'' Lawler will marry long-time girlfriend and
WWF valet The Kat this month.
</P>
<P>
   While real wedding bells are ring in the WWF, World Championship
Wrestling has its own wedding gone bad. On Monday ``Nitro,'' David
Flair was set to take Miss Hancock as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who are dating in real life, were set to tie an
imaginary knot when Flair's father Ric, who was making his first
appearance on television since May, was carted off by police for
violating a restraining order. The wedding started again and was
interrupted by Miss Hancock's disclosure that the baby she was
carrying was not David Flair's.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought Triple H and Stephanie had problems.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like Flair's saga will continue after this Sunday's
pay-per-view ``Fall Brawl'' and don't be surprised if Ric Flair is
the father.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last week's second straight pre-empted ``Raw is War'' show
allowed ``Nitro'' to get his highest ratings of the year. Despite
that ``Raw,'' which aired from
</P>
<P>
   11 p.m.-1 a.m. instead of its usual 9-11 p.m. slot because of
the U.S. Open tennis matches, still had a better rating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extreme Championship Wrestling announced that will be hold its
Dec. 3rd pay-per-view ``Massacre on 34th Street'' at the
Hammerstein Ballroom in New
</P>
<P>
   York City. Tickets will be available on Monday, Sept. 18 from
Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call it a case of reverse discrimination. While some women are
still battling for equal treatment, the men of the WCW Power Plant
are crying foul because of the special treatment the women seem to
be getting. WCW has sent most of its women valets and dancers to
the Power Plant to learn wrestling moves and get more involved in
storylines. So after a month at the Power Plant they are making
debuts on ``Nitro'' and ``Thunder.'' Meanwhile, some male wrestlers
will never make television even after years at the WCW training
facility.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just when you didn't think characters could get any lower
comes this. Mideon, who has been looking for a gimmick, may turn up
as ``Naked Man'' soon. Seems
</P>
<P>
   Perry Saturn suggested the gimmick after a backstage competition
between Mideon and Kurt Angle to see who could stay naked the
longest. Mideon won.
</P>
<P>
   _ For those looking for Raven to make his WWF debut, the wait
may end October. Ideas for his debut have been discussed, but no
decision has been made. One interesting move may be to bring him
back with injured Billy Gunn and reunite DX with XPac and Road
Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   _ The war between Paul Heyman of ECW and Rob Black of XFW
continues to escalate. In the October 2000 issue of World of
Wrestling magazine, there is a
</P>
<P>
   paid advertisement ``open letter'' by Black to Heyman addressing
the events at ``Heatwave 2000.'' Here's some of the highlights: ``I
really enjoyed Heatwave
</P>
<P>
   2000 on July 16. I humbly apologize for the events that
transpired. I'm also extremely sorry for using the name XTREME In
reference to our wrestling company. And then there is the apology
due for using Sabu and our allowing him a make a living in the
sport he helped revolutionize. I'm also sorry for all the
mean-spirited epithets hurled in your direction. Finally, if you're
willing to buy all that I've just said, you're more gullible than
everyone at XPW thought you were.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
