<SLUG> BC-NOMURA-MILLENNIUM-DOME-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMURA WITHDRAWS BID TO TAKE OVER LONDON'S TROUBLED MILLENNIUM
DOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As Britain approached the Year 2000, the centerpiece of
its efforts to draw the eyes of the world to a cool Britannia was
the Millennium Dome _ a huge tent beside the Thames River shaped
like an inverted wok and packed with exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Cool is hardly the term for it now.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months since the dome opened at Greenwich in east
London, it has become a sore embarrassment for Prime Minister Tony
Blair's government, depicted less often as a dome than as a
sinkhole for seemingly endless subsidies from the National Lottery
that have pushed its cost to the public beyond $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the cruelest cut came Tuesday when a British
division of Nomura Securities Co. of Japan pulled the plug on a
$157 million bid to take over the ailing edifice at the end of this
year, when New Millennium Experience Co.'s one-year contract to
operate the dome expires.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, primarily, was that despite the hoopla surrounding
its opening at New Year's, Britons and other potential visitors
stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, New Millennium Experience Co., a government-led
agency that runs the Dome, forecast it would be a financial
success, with 12 million visitors in the space of a year.
</P>
<P>
   That forecast was cut to 7 million but, by the end of the summer
vacation season, no more than 4.7 million people had passed its
portals, according to a spokeswoman for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Even those figures are questionable. By some estimates, the
final tally for the whole year will be no more than 4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A Nomura-led consortium called Dome Europe had promised a $1.2
billion investment to turn the dome and its surrounding land into a
leisure and entertainment park.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, it was not low attendance but the dome's
ramshackle finances that caused the problem. Only weeks after the
newest, $74 million injection of lottery money _ the fifth in a
year _ Nomura on Tuesday called into question the dome's financial
management, saying there was ``substantial uncertainty'' about the
assets controlled by New Millennium Experience Co.
</P>
<P>
   But, Nomura said, it had been denied access to full financial
information about its acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult decision to make but in the
circumstances we had no alternative,'' said Guy Hands, Nomura's
financing chief in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Nomura won a bidding competition for the Dome last July, beating
out a rival, Legacy PLC, a consortium that had promised a major
investment to turn the dome into a center for high technology
business start-ups. Legacy said today it was still interested in
buying the dome and government officials said Legacy's bid might be
revived.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For all that, the dome has become an emblem of financial
ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Many Britons complained that Blair's government was more
interested in salvaging hurt pride than spending public money for
the public good. But the government minister responsible for it,
Lord Falconer, has rejected what have become routine calls for his
resignation, saying it is his duty to remain to the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   After the latest injection of lottery money, David James, a new
chairman with a reputation for fixing troubled companies, was
appointed to sort out the dome's financial problems and keep it
open until it could be handed over to Nomura. Shortly after his
appointment, James said he had been shocked to discover that the
dome's operators had not even compiled a register of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier audit by PriceWaterhouseCoopers revealed what Hands
called ``new information about the costs and future liabilities of
the Dome,'' suggesting that its finances had been run in a
haphazard way. The ownership of some of its assets was also
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The dome's operators said Tuesday that the exhibit would remain
open until the end of the year under the same management. Between
2,000 and 3,000 jobs in the depressed area around the dome will be
in jeopardy if it is closed down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
