<HEADER>
A0777 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-SOLE-SURVIVOR-REVI     09-12 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOLE-SURVIVOR-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOLE' SHORT ON THRILLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Wed., Sept. 13.) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dean Koontz's Sole Survivor'' could've been sheared down to
two or, at most, three hours. Virtually nothing happens in
tonight's installment, while way too much goes on in Part 2, as the
characters we've been following to that point turn out to be almost
irrelevant to the real story.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Zane stars as Joe Carpenter, former crack journalist, and
boy oh boy, does this movie go to lengths to establish that he's
tormented by the deaths of his wife and daughter in an airline
tragedy. (Watching video footage of a past birthday party has
become Hollywood's cliched way of evoking soulful suffering.) Said
information takes up the whole of the film's first five minutes (an
adept filmmaker could manage it in two shots) and is revisited with
numbing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course there was more to that flight than meets the
eye, or none of us would be here. Visiting his family's grave site
late one night, Joe encounters a cryptic woman named Rose (Gloria
Reuben), who tells him they need to talk _ but not now (since
clearing everything up in the movie's first 15 minutes doesn't make
for interesting thrillers).
</P>
<P>
   Soon, she _ and he _ are pursued by a bunch of mysterious
official types, led by a breathtakingly ruthless and sardonic guy
named Victor (John C. McGinley). (Who knows if that's his real
name, since at various points in the movie he claims to be from the
CIA, the FBI and the Department of Agriculture.) There's some
nugget of info Vic and his sadistic gang of misfits doesn't want
getting out, and Joe, investigative genius that he is, at numerous
points in the story tries to delay or prevent people from divulging
crucial information to him, information that might keep him alive.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big secret that Victor wants concealed? That
doesn't come out till halfway through Part 2, when Rose returns,
only to dump a ton of exposition on Joe that makes you realize
they've gone about this story completely backward. Turns out the
story's actually about a bunch of other people who only get a few
minutes of screen time apiece. This bit of misdirection might've
seemed cool had we not had to watch so darn much of Zane brooding,
brooding, brooding.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, the big secret _ the one that has Victor chopping digits
off victims and in general doing a Bill-Murray-as-psycho-killer
impersonation to keep quiet _ is that some evil megaconglomerate is
sponsoring a big battle between youthful incarnations of good and
evil. And, that death is not the end of life. Oh.
</P>
<P>
   You know, people don't ask for a lot out of their thrillers, but
they do kind of like it when filmmakers stay on message and don't
go mucking up the place with a bunch of inane New Age mumbo-jumbo.
(The scene in which scientists suggest straight-facedly that the
good, pure child is too dangerous for this world and must be
destroyed is the miniseries' most risibly silly.) But that's what
happens here, as our stars are shunted to the side for some soaring
music and low-rent special effects and shots of imperiled children
looking particularly angelic or martyred.
</P>
<P>
   At least McGinley's on hand, mugging with great abandon as an
unhinged operative who enjoys his job a bit too much, to make this
more entertaining than it otherwise might be. He's this project's
sole survivor. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
``DEAN KOONTZ'S SOLE SURVIVOR'' &QL; 
-What: Miniseries about the paranormal events leading to an air
tragedy and its aftermath. &QL; 
-The stars: Billy Zane, John C. McGinley, Gloria Reuben. &QL; 
-When: 8 tonight and Thursday. &QL; 
-Where: Fox (Channel 11). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
