<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOST': EVIL AND FRAILTY IN A CORSICAN MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Publication notes at end of review)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corsica is the setting for ``Lost,'' a taut and atmospheric
first novel by Lucy Wadham in which the kidnapping of a child gives
a strange and transient meaning to the lives of several island
inhabitants. No kidnapping ever took place on Corsica, the talented
Wadham assures us in an author's note. This book is refreshingly
not ``based on a true story.'' And maybe for that very reason
Wadham seems to have made her imaginary Corsica believable.
</P>
<P>
   It is an austerely beautiful, politically afflicted place, where
officials live in a state of exile from the French center and where
a kind of human driftwood, gangsters and nongangsters alike, has
collected to live out lives of isolated desperation.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, it won't take long for devotees of exotic
adventure to fall under Wadham's spell. Described succinctly on the
dust jacket as a freelance journalist who lives in Paris, Wadham
writes with stylish precision. She makes you think of Graham Greene
in one of his lighter moods as she teases out the emotional
responses to a situation of extreme distress, managing grimness,
terror and suspense like an artist mixing paint, getting the right
tint, the proper degree of shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Why ``Lost''? Almost everybody seems to have some quality to
justify Wadham's evocatively monosyllabic title. The central
character is Alice Aron, a rich young widow, beautiful of course,
whom we first see arriving at the airport with her two young sons
to visit her dead husband's ancestral home. Watching her, waiting
for her, is a small-time hoodlum named Mickey da Cruz, whose
presence, along with a pair of brothers named Scatti waiting in a
car, gives Wadham's story an ominous tone from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   One of Alice's sons, 7-year-old Samuel, the kind of normally
inquisitive boy who asks his mother which runs faster, a scorpion
or a snake, is going to be taken away from her. But not before
Wadham has introduced us to the other dramatis personae.
</P>
<P>
   First there is Antoine Stuart, the disillusioned and unhappy
police commissioner whose career is in such a sad state that he
spends whole days at the beach. He has a lurking intelligence, a
moral incorruptibility that makes him almost outlandish in a place
like Wadham's Corsica. He drives an old brown Datsun because ``the
car cult on the island had always sickened him and so he kept his
own in protest.'' He is not a widower but a man abandoned by the
wife he still longs for, and he knows he has faded into
insignificance on Corsica because the unofficial chief of the
island, the leader of the criminal underworld, doesn't even bother
to keep watch on him any more.
</P>
<P>
   The capo is Coco Santini, who lives with his mistress in a large
villa designed by a Scandinavian architect. He mistreats his wife
and has people he doesn't like killed, including Stuart's most
valuable informant. Santini confidently maneuvers though the
island's Byzantine politics to control the National Liberation
Front, which started out as an independence movement but has become
an entrepreneurial mafia. When young Sam is hustled into a car one
morning by Mickey da Cruz and the Scatti brothers, we are not sure
whether Santini is ultimately behind the kidnapping or not. But we
do know that he is dangerous to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes people sick about you is that you pretend to be a
good man when what you are is a coward,'' Santini tells Stuart as
Wadham's climactic scenes approach and the characters of the two
rivals have been stripped bare. ``There aren't any good men on this
island. They don't survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart replies, ``They don't survive because you kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadham constructs a complicated intrigue after the kidnapping of
Sam, one with lots of the unpredictable motion that occurs when
human volition comes into play. The original kidnappers are
replaced by a second, radical political gang that Santini is using
to keep the liberation front under his control. Sam, whom we
glimpse from time to time in various states of captivity, is slowly
reduced to a mute, curled up ball divorced from the sensory reality
outside himself. But at the moral heart of the story is the rivalry
between the good but, in Alice's eyes, ineffectual Stuart and the
evil but charismatic Santini.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry includes the seduction of Alice, which adds another
savory element of suspense to Wadham's story. Which of the two will
she trust to regain her son? The reader knows whom she should
choose, but one of Wadham's skills is to imagine realistically the
densely clouded mind of a young mother in which the senses of loss,
guilt and desperation are mixed. Danger hovers over Wadham story
like a mist, and the danger comes not only from the evil figures in
her book but from normal human frailty as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost'' in this sense remains true to Wadham's grasp of gritty,
confusing reality right to the end as the chess-like conflict
between Stuart and Santini reaches its conclusion. At one point,
Stuart ruminates on the vanity to which police investigators are
prone, that they will be able to sift the evidence, figure out the
game and win it with guile and intelligence. ``But his job was to
sit still as a lizard in the sun and wait for the fallible
mechanism to spring and perhaps make a catch, perhaps not.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadham's appreciation of the fallible mechanism gives this
darkly entertaining novel its special aura of suspense and of
something more satisfying than suspense: the melancholy feeling
that people being what they are, these events _ based on nothing
but imagination _ could happen exactly the way she describes them.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOST'
</P>
<P>
   By Lucy Wadham
</P>
<P>
   315 pages. Carroll &AMP; Graf. $24.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
