<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers will douse portions of the Northeast Seaboard
early Wednesday as a cold front pushes eastward off the coast.
Behind the front, drier breezes from the northwest will direct
cooler and less humid air into the Great Lakes and interior
Northeast. Sunshine will return to coastal sections of the
Northeast and Middle Atlantic States by the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms will surround a cool front advancing
through the Southeast. Farther south, humid air will fuel isolated
afternoon thunderstorms in Florida, though most places will stay
dry with ample sun.
</P>
<P>
   The searing heat of recent days will end over South Texas as
clouds and numerous showers cover the region. A few of the showers
will be heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be sunny and very warm. An exception will
be across central California, where a disturbance will bring clouds
and spotty showers to the Sierra.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TYPHOON CONNECTION
</P>
<P>
   Typhoon Saomai, which lashed the islands south of Japan on
Tuesday, is a hemisphere away, but the storm may incite a change in
the weather over North America. Weather systems around the
hemisphere are connected by a serpentine high-level wind pattern
called the jet stream. When a strong typhoon leaves the tropics, it
infuses the jet stream in the northern Pacific with abundant
energy. Typically, several days after the typhoon's effects reach
the middle latitudes, eastern North America turns much cooler. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
