u i BC-EUROPE-FUEL13-COX     09-12 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FUEL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FUEL PROTESTS BRING BRITAIN TO THE BRINK OF GRIDLOCK
 &HT;    460&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain slipped toward national gridlock Tuesday as
truckers and others protesting high fuel prices blocked shipments
from refineries across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair said he would not to bend to the
protests and assured Britons that his government would move quickly
to restore order. Shortly afterward,
</P>
<P>
   trucks reportedly began departing some fuel depots.
</P>
<P>
   Across Europe, similar blockades and protests were staged by
truckers, taxi drivers, farmers and others pinched by rising oil
prices and high national fuel taxes. But the crisis here was being
described as the greatest domestic challenge since Blair's
government was elected in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott warned that ``chaos ...
seems to be developing across the country, where emergency services
are being denied to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals canceled ambulance service and non-emergency
procedures. Grocery stores and supermarkets reported a run on
essential items.
</P>
<P>
   Service stations were expected to run out of unleaded gasoline
Wednesday, and the fuel shortage began spreading to other forms of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Some diesel-fueled commuter trains were canceled, and Glasgow's
airport reported late Tuesday that it had only hours worth of fuel
left. Taxis, which have become very popular with people trying to
conserve their own supplies, were on the verge of running out of
gas.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Automobile Club said the fuel crisis was the worst
since the mid-'70s. ``The government has to step in immediately,''
it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after an emergency cabinet meeting, Blair
said, ``I believe that whatever the right or wrongs the arguments
over fuel (taxes), we cannot accept as a government or as a nation
that policy should be dictated by illegal blockades, pickets or
direct action. There can be no excuse whatever for this type of
action, which is hurting our people businesses and emergency
services severely.''
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth and her senior advisers gave Blair the go-ahead
to use force if necessary to provide fuel for essential services.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair, seemingly wary of the political effect of moving
against the economically distressed protesters, told oil companies
that it was up to them to ensure fuel supplies. Oil companies have
refused to send out tankers, claiming they do not want to put
drivers at risk.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of the price of a gallon of gasoline in Britain
is taxes, about twice the rate paid by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Blair conceded that fuel taxes have increased at a faster rate
than inflation for two years. He said this was necessary to
generate the money his government has needed to help fuel the
country's economic recovery. He said the proper way to address high
prices was to pressure the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries into producing more oil.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The already dreadful traffic in and around London was even more
challenging Tuesday as motorists had to contend with lines of cars
waiting in hopes of finding fuel at service stations.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Effingham about 20 miles south of London, a line of
cars stretched Tuesday morning from the Rust Service Station for a
quarter-mile down the busy Guildford Road. Nick Gower said he
arrived at 6:45 a.m. to find a line had already formed to buy
gasoline, selling at the equivalent of about $5 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there would be a queue for petrol, so I drove from
Ashtead (about eight miles) to see if I couldn't find some petrol
out here,'' Gower said after filling the tank of his Ford. ``I
don't like queues, but I also understand why these lads are acting
up. Can anyone explain why we in the UK have to pay more tax on our
fuel than anyone else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are doing it to save their livelihoods,'' said Mike
Salmon of the British Road Haulage Association, which represents
many of the drivers taking part in the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders in Belgium, the Netherlands, France and Germany
vowed Tuesday to increase their demonstrations against high fuel
prices and short supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In the western German city of Saarbrucken near the French
border, more than 200 trucks, buses and taxis drove, honking their
horns through the center of town. Rallying in front of the state
parliament building, the protesters demanded that an energy tax
imposed by the Social Democratic-led government be repealed.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters want their governments to follow France's lead in
granting concessions. The French government, faced with similar
protests, reduced its fuel tax by about 15 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
