   TEXAS AT LARGE-CHAPMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Last weekend, Galveston officially acknowledged the
storm of 1900 that wrecked the community and killed more than 6,000
residents. There were wreaths, statues and marching bands. People
remembered; some cried. For a hundred years, the most famous island
city of Texas has been quiet about the storm. People knew of it,
but the city never really memorialized it _ made it a visible part
of the past. By ART CHAPMAN. Story has moved in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
