<P>
   CHILDREN-DISCIPLINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Sal Severe, Ph.D., is a discipline expert with some
fairly radical advice for parents: Look at things from your kid's
point of view _ and watch your own behavior. Those are the building
blocks of a program that helps parents deal with everything from
tantrums and homework hassles to sibling rivalry and whininess.
It's all outlined in his book ``How to Behave So Your Children
Will, Too.'' Sounds great. But does it work? By CATHERINE NEWTON.
Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRAZZLED PARENT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Like most parents, I think I know my children. We talk
a lot. We read together and compete in family games. We all study
spelling at one table every Thursday night, we take naps en masse,
and this summer the three of us crowded on the love seat every
Wednesday to root for our favorite Survivor. We are close. Bonded.
But still, they surprise me. By CATHERINE NEWTON. Story has moved
in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
