<HEADLINE>
FINDING DEFECT WAS COMPLEX,   FIRESTONE EXECUTIVE TESTIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: This early version will be updated.) 
 By DAVID STOUT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An official from the Bridgestone/Firestone Co. told
a Senate committee Tuesday that discovering the pattern of tire
failures that has been linked to 88 deaths nationwide took longer
than the company would have wished because of the complexity of the
problem and the fact that, statistically, only a tiny number of
tires failed.
</P>
<P>
   John Lampe, a vice president of Bridgestone/Firestone, told the
Senate Commerce Committee that the company wished it could have
discerned the potentially fatal problem sooner. But Lampe said
after the company identified the problem _ that the treads of
underinflated tires could separate at high temperatures _ it moved
as fast as it could to get the defective tires off the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize and we recognize there is a problem, a very
complex problem that must be solved because lives are at stake,''
Lampe said. ``And for too long, we didn't see the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampe said the company has appointed an independent outside
investigator to monitor the company's recall of defective tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make great tire products on which millions of Americans
have driven for billions of safe miles,'' Lampe told the panel,
headed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the deaths linked to Firestone tires have involved Ford
Explorers, and the safety problem has frayed one of the
longest-standing corporate partnerships in America. Tuesday,
officials from the Ford Motor Co. and Firestone each tried to shift
some of the blame for the accidents and deaths on to the other
company.
</P>
<P>
   Lampe's call for more attention to ``the interaction between the
tire and the vehicle'' strongly suggested that the tire company has
not abandoned its stand that part of the safety problems was caused
by what Firestone has said is Ford Explorers' tendency to roll
over.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford has a much different perspective, as its chief
executive, Jacques Nasser, made clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford did not know that there was a defect with the tires until
we virtually pried the claims data from Firestone's hands in late
July, early August, and analyzed it ourselves,'' Nasser said.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks made it unmistakable that the Firestone-Ford
relationship has hit a big bump. ``Firestone failed to share
critical claims data with Ford that might have prompted the recall
of these bad tires sooner,'' Nasser said. ``This is not the candid
and frank dialogue that Ford expects in its business
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with next year's Ford Explorers, Nasser said, Ford
will offer buyers a choice of tires.
</P>
<P>
   While senators of both parties on McCain's committee expressed
anger that Ford had ordered tire recalls overseas many months
before the problems became known in the United States, McCain
promised at the outset that the hearing would not be a forum for
attaching blame to business or government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we all share blame equally when the system
fails,'' McCain said in opening remarks. But he added: ``Serious
questions remain about what Ford and Firestone knew of this problem
and when they knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mounting evidence is making it increasingly difficult to
credibly believe that neither of these companies knew anything of
this problem before this summer,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., called the problem ``a sordid
chapter in the history of two companies that for more than a
century have become household names for the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, dozens of deaths have been linked to traffic
accidents in which Firestone tires were a factor. The National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration said 88 deaths in the United
States might be linked to the tires. More than 6 million tires have
been recalled, and the NHTSA says another 1.4 million might be
dangerous _ a finding that Firestone has not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Firestone also face scrutiny in the House. Rep. Billy
Tauzin, R-La., who heads the House Commerce subcommittee on
telecommunications, trade and consumer protection, said Tuesday he
might subpoena documents from both companies relating to tire tests
if he does not get them by week's end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
