<SLUG> BC-BURGERKING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BURGER KING ACCOUNT IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, Burger King has sought to stimulate flagging sales
of its fast fare with a seductive appeal carrying the theme ``Got
the urge?'' Tuesday, it was Burger King that had the urge _ the
same old urge the company has had so often, to place the creative
duties for its general market advertising account in review.
</P>
<P>
   The review, denied by the top Burger King marketing executive as
recently as a month ago, involves assignments with billings
estimated at $400 million. It began with an unusually frank
dismissal of the recent work produced by the incumbent agency, the
New York office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners Worldwide. Lowe Lintas
and two predecessors have created campaigns for Burger King since
1994 carrying themes like ``Get your burger's worth'' and ``It just
tastes better'' as well as ``Got the urge?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed with the impact our advertising has had in
driving sales,'' said Mikel Durham, the new North American
president for Burger King Corp. in Miami, part of Diageo PLC, ``and
moving the indicators we track on the relationship of the consumer
with the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lowe Lintas is being invited to participate in the review,
she added, the agency would be expected to offer a drastically new
approach to the account.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-food category of the restaurant market ``is intensely
competitive,'' Durham said, adding that it ``becomes harder and
harder to stake out a point of differentiation and a `share of
throat,' if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   The review came as sales at Burger King stores in the United
States open at least a year declined 0.4 percent for the 12 months
ending June 30. That's worrisome to Durham, brought in a month ago
from a sibling, Guinness in London, to help Diageo dress up Burger
King for a planned stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Her perspective on the industry is underscored by recent steps
taken by other chains that compete against Burger King, the world's
second-largest fast feeder. Taco Bell, a unit of Tricon Global
Restaurants, dismissed its agency, the Playa del Rey, Calif.,
office of TBWA/Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of the
Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies for two other fast-food advertisers _ KFC, also
part of Tricon, and McDonald's _ have made substantial changes in
the creative content of their campaigns. At the KFC agency, Young &AMP;
Rubicam Advertising in New York, the creative team was changed,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, comments like those made by Durham mean that the
incumbent stands a slim chance of retaining an account. That is
particularly true for a restless marketer like Burger King, which
has had four creative agencies since 1987 _ six if you count the
two predecessor shops of Lowe Lintas that created ads from 1994 to
1999, Ammirati &AMP; Puris and Ammirati Puris Lintas. Still, Lowe
Lintas intends to take part in the review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the history, we've got the experience and we've
certainly got the creative firepower to help them turn their
business around,'' said Rob Quish, president at the New York office
of Lowe Lintas, part of the Lowe Group unit of Interpublic Group of
Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe Lintas has not been having a good week. On Monday, another
client, Sun Microsystems, left the agency, citing a conflict with
the account of a second high-technology marketer, Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, during the MTV Video Music Awards, the
performer Kid Rock mocked Burger King commercials created by Lowe
Lintas for a promotion featuring the Backstreet Boys by unfavorably
comparing them with a similar promotion pairing a rival boy band,
'N Sync, with McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Asked her opinion of Kid Rock's humorous remarks, Durham was all
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Durham declined to identify the other agencies that are being
asked to take part in the review; speculation has already started
that TBWA/Chiat/Day may be one of them. She also declined to
discuss whether an agency in San Francisco that has worked for two
months on a project for Burger King, Odiorne Wilde Narraway &AMP;
Partners, would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Odiorne Wilde was a strong signal that Burger King
was getting ready to flame-broil Lowe Lintas in addition to its
hamburgers. While the company had been pleased with a campaign that
ran from March 1996 to August 1999, which paired familiar rock and
pop tunes with appetizing footage of Burger King menu items,
subsequent work was less well received.
</P>
<P>
   Durham said that she hoped to complete the review by the end of
the year and have a new campaign soon after. That fast-track
timetable might favor Lowe Lintas because it may prove difficult
for an agency of the size needed by Burger King to handle such a
big assignment to mobilize so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the nature of Burger King's business and the challenges
it is facing as a corporation,'' said Lee Garfinkel, chairman,
chief executive and chief creative officer for the U.S. operations
of Lowe Lintas, ``we understand new management's obligation to
entertain new points of view relative to its advertising and
marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We embrace this opportunity to look at the account from a
fresh perspective,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Three other agencies will continue handling other tasks for
Burger King: MediaVest in New York, part of the Starcom MediaVest
unit of the B Com3 &UR;  &LR;  Group, for media services; Uniworld in New
York, 49 percent owned by the WPP Group, for campaigns aimed at
black consumers; and Bromley, Aguilar &AMP; Associates in San Antonio,
Texas, also part of B Com3, for ads aimed at Spanish-speaking
consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
