<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON'S THE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By   ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Compared with some of California's better-known wine
regions, the Anderson Valley doesn't get much attention, except
when it's mistaken for the Alexander Valley. The Alexander, in
northern Sonoma County, is home to many big wineries like Clos du
Bois and Jordan. Anderson Valley, in Mendocino County, is roughly
the same size as the Alexander but with far fewer grapes planted,
and it is home mostly to small, little-known wineries that deserve
a higher profile.
</P>
<P>
   Pinot noir in particular grows successfully in the Anderson's
cool climate, but the valley may also be California's best area for
Germanic grapes like gewueztraminer and riesling. Chardonnay and
zinfandel also do well.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to work to find Anderson Valley wines. Navarro
Vineyards, perhaps the area's leading winery, doesn't sell its
wines retail. You can often find the wines on good restaurant
lists, though, and you can buy directly from the winery through
www.navarrowine.com, state laws permitting. Navarro makes superb
rieslings and gewuerztraminers, both dry and sweet, and a fine
chardonnay, though I found its 1997 pinot noir to be too lean.
</P>
<P>
   Handley Cellars is a little easier to find in stores than
Navarro. It, too, makes a fine gewuerztraminer, along with a juicy
pinot noir. Edmeades Vineyards, a winery owned by Kendall-Jackson,
makes small lots of wine, including a terrific pinot noir.
</P>
<P>
   Several wineries outside the area buy Anderson Valley grapes to
make excellent wines. Au Bon Climat in Santa Barbara County makes a
fine though pricey pinot noir under its Ici/La-Bas label, while
Littorai, a small winery in Napa Valley, makes several Anderson
Valley wines.
</P>
<P>
   The one giant among the Anderson elves is Roederer Estate, the
California arm of the French Champagne house, which produces one of
America's best sparkling wines. If you get frustrated looking for
the other wines, you can find Roederer Estate at almost any wine
shop. One glass of its brut offers fine solace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDMEADES, PINOT NOIR 1997 $20.
</P>
<P>
   Rich, fruity aroma; smooth and medium-bodied with herbal and
chocolate flavors.
</P>
<P>
   HANDLEY, PINOT NOIR, ESTATE RESERVE 1995 $31.
</P>
<P>
   Big and mouth-filling, with berry, mint and leather flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ICI/LA-BAS, PINOT NOIR, LES REVELES, ELKE VINEYARD 1997 $58.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh, fruity aroma, silky textured, rich and complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTORAI, PINOT NOIR, SAVOY VINEYARD 1997 $35. &QL; 
Sweet, complex and voluptuous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NAVARRO WHITE RIESLING, CLUSTER SELECT, LATE HARVEST, VERY SWEET
1997 $25 (1/2 bottle). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rich, sweet and honeyed, yet spicy and balanced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROEDERER ESTATE, BRUT, NV $19.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus aromas, tangy, bright and delicious. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
