<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-12 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH, GORE BATTLE OVER GOP AD CRITIQUING GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore tangled Tuesday
over a two-week-old Republican Party television ad that flashed the
word ``rats'' during a 30-second critique of the role that
``bureaucrats'' allegedly would play under Gore's plan to cover
prescription drugs under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee withdrew the ad that had
appeared an estimated 4,400 times in 33 television markets
nationwide at a cost of $2.6 million. It was the second time in
three weeks that a Republican party ad on behalf of the GOP nominee
had stirred controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the ad eclipsed efforts by Bush to win support in
Missouri and Florida for his health care proposals for catastrophic
coverage and Gore's bid to win support in Ohio for his proposal to
strengthen public education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed criticism of the latest GOP advertisement, but
said the GOP was withdrawing it. Bush said that subliminal
advertising that flashed a word or image on the screen was ``not
acceptable.'' He said, however, that he was ``convinced'' that the
appearance of the word ``rats'' in large capital letters on one of
900 frames in the ad was ``not intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-term governor of Texas added: ``We don't need to play
games; what we need is a debate on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush communications director Karen Hughes said the ad was being
withdrawn as scheduled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican chairman Jim Nicholson defended the advertisement,
saying that a frame-by-frame review in slow motion and discussions
with the producer, Alex Castellanos, made it ``clear that there was
no attempt to deliberately manipulate anyone here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, joined by running mate Joseph Lieberman aboard separate
school buses in southern Ohio to spotlight their education
initiatives, called the GOP ad a ``disappointing development.''
Gore _ the veteran of 24 years in national politics _ insisted that
he had ``never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a former Connecticut attorney general who has
represented his state in the Senate for 12 years, called the ad
``very disappointing and strange,'' adding: ``I'm sure the public
will be puzzled by it as we are and want an explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   William Schneider, a public opinion specialist at the American
Enterprise Institute, said the ad triggered such a furor because
``it's a deception and voters don't like to be fooled.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission adopted a policy in 1974
that declared subliminal advertising contrary to the public
interest. Officials said the FCC would investigate broadcasters
that aired the ad, if complaints were received.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second ad voiced support for Bush's plan to expand
Medicare to cover part of the cost of prescription drugs and
contended that senior citizens could exercise greater control over
their health care under Bush's 10-year, $158 billion proposal.
</P>
<P>
   As an announcer declared that under ``the Gore prescription
plan, bureaucrats decide,'' segments of same words flashed across
the screen. At one point, the word ``RATS'' in large white capital
letters flashed on a black background as the announcer said that
under the Gore plan, ``bureaucrats decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican ad came to light after the Gore campaign gave a
slow-motion copy of the ad to the New York Times late Monday that
resulted in a story in Tuesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Television journalist Brit Hume mentioned the embedded message
in a report on Fox News on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, the GOP chairman, called the use of flashing words
``a visual drumbeat to capture viewers' attention.'' Nicholson said
three frames in the ad displayed the entire phrase ``bureaucrats
decide'' alternating with three frames that displayed ``fragments
of the phrase in large type.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Holt, spokesman for the GOP's advertising campaign, said
the spot was ``about health care not about rodents,'' adding: ``The
word bureaucrats ends with `rats' just like the word `Democrat.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said the use of the word was
intentional. ``Ad graphics don't pop up out of thin air,'' Hattaway
said. ``Someone sits down at a computer and creates them.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert said voters would have to
decide whether the ad was ``an accident or a dirty trick.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest controversy over an ad recalled an earlier
embarrassment for the Bush campaign caused by his party. Bush and
his Austin-based advisers vetoed a Republican National Committee
attack ad on Gore in late August that drew upon videotaped material
that he said was taken out of context from an earlier television
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The newest controversy erupted as Bush told senior citizens in
Orlando, Fla., that his overhaul of Medicare would ``offer
additional choices for seniors'' including coverage for
catastrophic illness after the first $6,000 in expenses. Bush said
Gore's proposed overhaul of Medicare would force senior citizens to
join ``a government HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore promises to spend $253 billion over 10 years to revamp
Medicare to add prescription drug coverage for senior citizens who
spend more than $4,000 for prescription drugs. Gore's plan does not
include expanded coverage for catastrophic illness.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wrapped up a two-day barnstorming effort in Florida, where
his younger brother Jeb is governor. He later headed to Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman devoted their campaign efforts to persuading
voters in the swing state of Ohio that their proposed $170 billion
education overhaul would encourage both students and teachers to
become more accountable for results.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal calls for local authorities to identify and
implement recovery plans for ``failing schools'' with ``rigorous
peer evaluation of every teacher'' and ``performance report cards''
to help parents select a school for their child. Gore also calls
for performance reviews of teachers and bonuses for performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told an audience in a middle school in Miamisburg that the
Democrats' ``comprehensive approach'' to requiring accountability
from teachers and students is superior to Bush's plan which he said
would only hold authorities accountable for school performance
following statewide tests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett derided the proposal touted
by the Gore-Lieberman campaign. ``If Al Gore's school bus is
anything like his education proposal, it will have four flat
tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, vowing to ``close the achievement gap, set high standards,
promote character education and ensure school safety,'' proposes
that local jurisdictions set performance standards. If schools
cannot meet the standards within three years, according to the Bush
plan, federal education money for that district would be
distributed as vouchers to parents to enable them to send their
children to other public or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Three nationwide public opinion surveys had Gore leading Bush
among likely voters in a four-way race with the Reform Party's Pat
Buchanan and the Green Party's Ralph Nader. Gore's margin ranged
from 1 percentage point in a bipartisan survey for
Voter.com-Battleground to 7 percentage points in a CNN-USA Today
survey to 11 percentage points in survey by International
Communications Research, based in Media, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reform Party nominee Pat Buchanan won the approval of the
Federal Election Commission to receive $12.6 million in campaign
money set aside as a result of the party capturing 8 percent of the
popular vote in 1996. Rival Reform nominee John Hagelin vowed to
challenge the FEC ruling in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Bush campaign distributed an electronic message calling
attention to an Associated Press report recounting Lieberman's role
in winning a 1997 housing court order to evict a woman from a
building in Stamford, Conn., while serving as executor of his
uncle's $48 million estate. The eviction for nonpayment of rent has
not been enforced, pending a trial scheduled in February on a
contention by Monica E. Beach, 58, that she was injured at the
property and lost her job as a result of the injuries.
</P>
