<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MADONNA-MUSIC (Undated) _ The notion of an objective, natural
reality, separate from human intervention, was damaged beyond
repair in the 20th century. It was besieged on all sides by art,
philosophy and technology: by Cubism and post-modernism, by film
and sound recording, by television and synthesizers, by video games
and plastic surgery, by all the gizmos of the computer era. Any
separation between natural and artificial has grown fuzzy and, in
practice, irrelevant. Now, everyone lives on the cusp of the
physical and the virtual. That's the running joke, though some
might call it a subtext, on Madonna's new album, ``Music,'' her
latest foray into electronica. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   MEHTA-MUSIC (New York) _ Zarin Mehta took over as the
orchestra's executive director just after Labor Day, replacing
Deborah Borda, who decamped last December for a similar position
with the Los Angeles Philharmonic. And with the kinds of
difficulties American orchestras face today, Mehta may well prove
the more important catch. At 61, he is considered a star in the
small world of classical-music management. By Peter Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EXORCIST (Undated) _ ``The Exorcist'' is back in a new,
longer version that Warner Bros. is releasing in theaters on Sept.
22. When William Friedkin's ``Exorcist,'' based on William Peter
Blatty's best-selling theological-horror novel, opened, on Dec. 26,
1973, it was not only the movie event of that Christmas season, but
it also became the dominant pop-culture phenomenon of the final
days of Richard Nixon's presidency. One wouldn't want to make too
much of this. By Terrence rafferty.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DANCER (Undated) _ ``Dancer in the Dark,'' the film chosen
to open the New York Film Festival, is a musical about the battle
music wages for the soul's transformation amid the din of life. By
Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ARCAND (Undated) _ When Denys Arcand stepped onto the red
carpet at Toronto's Roy Thomson Hall last week, he had reached the
end of a long road. His first major film in seven years,
``Stardom,'' was the opening-night offering at the Toronto
International Film Festival, and Arcand, a French-Canadian
Montrealer, was enjoying a welcome reserved for native sons. But
the premiere represented more than a jubilant return. By Murray
Whyte.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TV &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-GIRLS (Undated) _ ``Generation O!'' made its debut on Aug. 26
on WB, with ``Molly'' the lead character. Molly arrives during a
season of extraordinary girl power in animation: At least eight
shows having their premieres in 2000 have female leads, radically
altering the entire landscape of television for kids. By Ted Loos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-ARCHITECTURE (Houston) _ Here in Texas, a one-time
Spanish colony, architecture is for all practical purposes a
network of sealed membranes, constructed around air-conditioning
systems and linked together by cars chilled to bone-rattling
discomfort. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMPANY-OF-MEN-DANCE (Undated) _ As Charles Wright sees it, one
of the greatest disparities between men and women has to do with
touch. ``Women have the freedom to touch in public, and men
don't,'' Wright, the artistic director of the Dance Space Center,
says. His solution, In the Company of Men, is a series devoted to
the theme of men. Now in its fifth season, the program is a
celebration of the dynamic of men dancing together, in both joyous
and virtuosic terms. By Gia Kourlas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ A glimpse of vanguard modernism
in photography, which has been studiously neglected and probably
largely unknown by historians, may be caught in the gallery of the
Mexican Cultural Institute in Manhattan , in a quiet and elegant
little show called ``Otras Cosas: Abstract Photography.'' By Vicki
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FISHMAN-ART (Undated) _ in the 1970s, process art, with links to
abstraction and minimalism, called attention to how artists
manipulated their chosen media; sometimes finished objects looked
like specimens from testing labs for industrial materials-which was
exactly their point. In the American painter Louise Fishman's work,
the lessons of those past eras and the challenges that emerged from
the artistic self-awareness they awakened are still discernible. By
Edward M. Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS, PAPERBACKS and BESTSELLERS-CHILDREN have all moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Coded `t') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE-AFTERDARK (Undated) _ Report from New York Times
correspondents on some of the hottest nightspots in Europe this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER (London) _ Want a big theatrical success?
Hire yourself a celebrity, preferably a film star. This blunt
wisdom has recently brought Kevin Spacey, Cate Blanchett, Nicole
Kidman and others to London, and, with Jerry Hall replacing
Kathleen Turner as the seductive Mrs. Robinson, is currently
ensuring that an adaptation of ``The Graduate'' is packing the
Gielgud Theater. And the trend is set to continue this fall. By
Benedict Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM (Undated) _ As Dutch as tulips and considerably
more fun, bicycles _ or fietsen, as they're called in Amsterdam _
are ideally suited to the brick-paved canal streets of the old
central city and to the flat landscape surrounding the urban area.
They're everywhere: chained to bridges, parked by the hundreds
outside Central Station, rolling steadily by (often with one or two
small passengers aboard) as you sit in outdoor cafes. By Judith
Yarnall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE-AIRPORTS (Paris) _ The fatal crash of a supersonic
Concorde northeast of Paris on July 25 has renewed debate over the
construction of a third major airport to serve the French capital.
The fact that the Concorde could easily have come down on top of a
small town, with even more than the four deaths that resulted among
people on the ground, is also raising questions about the safety of
existing airports in or near cities, about their further
development and about the location of future airports elsewhere in
Europe. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Reading the fine print on package
deals. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: One of the world's largest
exhibitions of the work of the jeweler and goldsmith Peter Carl
Faberge has opened at the Riverfront Arts Center in Wilmington,
Del. ``Faberge'' features more than 1,000 works from museums and
private collections, including objects from the State Hermitage
Museum in St. Petersburg and the Moscow Kremlin Museums that have
never been seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Items: By train to the Redwoods; Sailing
in Greece and Turkey; Hiking in Switzerland. By Florence Stickney.
</P>
