</P>
<P>
   MANIPULATIVE-ADS (Undated) _ To the flashes of ``Buy Coke'' that
supposedly had moviegoers stampeding to concession stands and the
word ``SEX'' secretly emblazoned on Ritz cracker ads, we now add
George W. Bush's ``RATS.'' Oddly enough, only the last example, the
latest presidential campaign flap, turns out to be true. By Raja
Mishra. 900 words. (p and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ASTHMA-DRUGS (Undated) _ In what they call a key demonstration
of how genome information is opening a new medical era, scientists
say they have discovered personal DNA differences that predict
which asthma patients will benefit from a certain drug before they
take it. By Richard Saltus. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-HOLE (Undated) _ X-ray telescope discovers the first of a
new type of black hole, midway between the two kinds that were
known to exist. Nobody knows how this thing came to be, but it may
lead to new understanding of black holes in general. By David L.
Chandler. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-SMOKING (Boston) _ Under code names such as ``Project
Stealth,'' cigarette manufacturers have used ingredients that hide
secondhand smoke in a bid to make smoking more socially acceptable
but not necessarily safer, according to a study. By Anne Barnard.
750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Rutherford, N.J.) _ Terry Glenn was one of the
last players in a glum and defeated locker room, looking over the
summary package of the game and shaking his head. By Nick Cafardo.
1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
