<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSCHWITZ-SYNAGOGUE-6     09-12 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSCHWITZ-SYNAGOGUE-690&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNAGOGUE OPENS NEAR HOLOCAUST-ERA DEATH CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSWIECIM, Poland _ For the first time since World War II, a
synagogue opened on Tuesday in the vicinity of the Auschwitz death
camp, and was hailed as a symbol of the healing of the
long-troubled relationship between Poles and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the small synagogue, ransacked by the Nazis and
later used as a carpet warehouse under Poland's post-war communist
government, Jewish leaders, Polish ministers and even a Jordanian
prince gathered to hear messages of reconciliation, including a
call from President Clinton to act with ``principle and purpose''
on the lessons of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   But the atmosphere of goodwill was clouded slightly by the fact
that the synagogue's opening came a few weeks after that of a large
discotheque, located about a mile closer to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations, including the Simon Wiesenthal Center in
Los Angeles, have protested that the discotheque ``in the immediate
vicinity of the largest Jewish graveyard in history'' amounts to an
affront, but local authorities have said that they can do little
because the dance club is on private property, a mile from the
Auschwitz-Birkenau complex.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties appeared to capture the tensions between the
desires of the living, particularly Polish youth, and the shadow of
the dead, including more than a million murdered Jews, in a
provincial Polish town stained forever by what the Nazis did
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better, and normal, that young people go and dance than
that they make trouble,'' said Klaudia Zaor, an 18-year-old
student. ``Sometimes we have the impression that the Jews just want
this town to die.''
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, she watched, with an amused twinkle in her green
eyes, as the ceremony at the synagogue proceeded. Speaker after
speaker referred to a restoration of life. The sun shone with a
late-summer glow on the newly painted cream-yellow walls of the
refurbished building, the only place of Jewish worship not entirely
destroyed by the Nazi onslaught in 1939 on the town of Oswiecim _
the Polish name for Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was this modest southwestern Polish town, whose Jewish
minority numbered 7,000 in 1939, that gave the German version of
its name to the adjacent camp.
</P>
<P>
   Not one Jew now lives in Oswiecim _ the last survivor died in
May. But the synagogue will serve as a place of prayer and
reflection for the many Jewish visitors to the Auschwitz camp. No
rabbi is to be permanently attached to the synagogue, so any formal
services must be organized in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The past, post-Communist, decade has brought a modest Jewish
revival in Poland. Fred Schwartz, the New York businessman who
raised $3 million for the new synagogue, said he backed the
building in part because ``the ashes at the camp communicated
nothing of the life that had been here.''
</P>
<P>
   His initiative was repeatedly applauded by more than 100 people
at a three-hour ceremony on Tuesday. The U.S. ambassador,
Christopher Hill, read a letter from Clinton that said that the
synagogue would serve ``as a place for contemplation where future
generations can reflect on the world they lost.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A letter from Poland's prime minister, Jerzy Buzek, was read by
the chief of the Polish chancellery, Maciej Musial. In notably
stark language, Buzek said that Jews had been ``sentenced to be
burned at the stake by the Nazis,'' but that the attempt at
annihilation had failed and the synagogue showed that ``those who
save traditions save a culture.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Poles and Jews have proved difficult in the
post-war years. They have been clouded by the competitive
victimhood of two peoples that both suffered terribly at the hands
of the Nazis, by the intermittent anti-Semitism of the Polish
communist government, by the sometimes hostile attitude of Poland's
Catholic Church, and by the fact that the epicenter of the Nazi
killing-machine for Jews lay in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   But these difficulties have come a long way toward resolution in
recent years, and the ceremony on Tuesday included an emotional
speech by the local bishop and an equally warm evocation of
Polish-Jewish relations by Marek Siwiec, the national security
adviser to the Polish president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Saying that the dignity of the victims of the Holocaust had
always remained intact but that ``our own dignity needed to be
restored,'' Bishop Tadeusz Rakoczy praised the synagogue as a place
of ``meeting and hope.'' He concluded with a simple greeting:
``Shalom.''
</P>
<P>
   Siwiec said the synagogue, flanked by a cultural center filled
with photographs of the town's pre-war Jewish life, was a ``symbol
of the links between Poles and Jews'' and a sign of a shared
determination ``to close an age of pain and sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But some problems remain. The furor over the disco, situated in
a former tannery where camp inmates worked and died, follows
conflicts over crosses erected outside Auschwitz to commemorate
Catholic victims and over a Carmelite convent. All but one of the
crosses _ the largest _ have now been removed; the convent closed
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The government denounced the disco last week, saying that
``amusement places should not be located at areas marked with the
suffering of the inmates of former death and concentration camps.''
But it also said it could not order the club's closure because
``the disco and the land under it are both private property.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafal Waliczek, the club's owner, has also made this point,
arguing that it lies well beyond the 100-yard-deep zone around the
camp in which all commercial activity is banned and that his
premises are not the original tannery, as most historians contend,
but a factory erected in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Jozef Krawczyk, the town's mayor, met representatives
of the Simon Wiesenthal Center, which has demanded the disco's
immediate closure, and said the town needed money from
international organizations or the government to compensate
Waliczek and buy the building. He said he was confident that the
problem would be solved.
</P>
<P>
   Krawczyk avoided any reference to the controversy in a speech on
Tuesday that focused on reconciliation. He was followed by Prince
El Hassan bin Talal of Jordan, the brother of the late King
Hussein, who made an impassioned plea for people of all religions
to ``make a commitment to our common humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   He was profusely thanked by Shevach Weiss, the chairman of the
Yad Vashem Memorial in Jerusalem, who said the prince's presence
was a moving ``symbol of the continuity of making peace, of
solidarity in its pursuit, and of understanding of what happened
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
