u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-HNS &LR;      09-12 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEC SAYS $12.6 MILLION IN ELECTION MONEY BELONGS TO BUCHANAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Election Commission on Tuesday awarded
Pat Buchanan $12.6 million in disputed federal election funds owed
the Reform Party's presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   However, Buchanan, whose campaign is nearly bankrupt, still
faces more battles over the money with his rival for the party's
nomination, John Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-1 vote, the commission said Hagelin, an Iowa physicist
who is also the presidential candidate for the Natural Law Party,
failed to prove that he was the Reform Party candidate on at least
10 state ballots _ a minimum requirement for claiming that party's
election funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin submitted the requisite documents, but FEC auditors said
he was the nominee of the Natural Law Party, not the Reform Party,
in six of the states he listed. Hagelin attorneys argued that the
Natural Law Party and the Reform Party are the same in those six
states. The auditors disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan submitted documents showing he is on the Reform Party
ballot line in Alaska, Arizona, Delaware, Idaho, Maryland, New
Jersey, New Mexico, South Dakota, Utah and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my vantage point, only one candidate meets our standard:
Pat Buchanan,'' said FEC Vice Chairman Danny Lee MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   The nominee is entitled to the money because Ross Perot, the
party's standard-bearer in 1996, received 8 percent of the
presidential vote, exceeding the commission's 5 percent
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's sister and campaign chairwoman, Bay Buchanan, said
her brother wants to use the money on radio and TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in pretty good shape as long as the money comes in this
week,'' she said. ``I think we'll have a strong opening next
Monday.'' Her brother, whose campaign was interrupted by two gall
bladder operations last month, is scheduled to resume speech-making
Monday in South Carolina, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan announced earlier this week that he had beefed up his
campaign staff and has hired Love Advertising Inc. of Houston to
produce his ads.
</P>
<P>
   But he will likely have to wait for the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin has 15 days to ask the commission to reconsider its
decision, which he has said he would do if the FEC ruled against
him.
</P>
<P>
   If the FEC again favors Buchanan, Hagelin can file an appeal in
federal court, which his spokesman, Robert Roth, said he would do.
``This will only be resolved in the court of appeals,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion over which candidate legitimately represents the
Reform Party began last month when its national convention in Long
Beach, Calif., disintegrated in shoving matches between delegates
with differing loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan won more votes in his convention than Hagelin did at a
rump convention. Hagelin supporters accused Buchanan of massive
vote fraud, but on Tuesday the FEC commissioners agreed not to
investigate the fraud claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the authority or capabilities to conduct a long
investigation into party's rules,'' FEC Chairman Darryl R. Wold
said. ``If Mr. Hagelin chooses to appeal our decision in a court of
law, then this matter could be looked into properly,'' Wold said.
</P>
<P>
   The only dissenting voice came from Commissioner Karl J.
Sandstrom, who objected to what he called the FEC's ``rush to
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan joined the Reform Party last year after bolting from
the Republican Party, which twice denied him its nomination.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
