<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-VARVATOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN VARVATOS REACHES OUT   TO THE MAN IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Gucci men's show in Milan earlier this summer,
Dylan McDermott, the actor who plays a Boston lawyer on ``The
Practice,'' sat in the front row in the kind of attenuated black
suit (Gucci) his character would only wear if he were delivering a
summation to 12 jury members putting together the next Whitney
Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   What came down the runway _ indulgent expressions of a momentary
Bruce Lee fascination _ wasn't for smug lawyers, either. As it
turned out, McDermott had already found some clothes for his
character to wear this season, and they were from a designer named
John Varvatos.
</P>
<P>
   Varvatos, who is showing his second men's collection on Thursday
morning in Bryant Park, where much of Fashion Week will be held, is
everything a new fashion star generally isn't.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is the fact that he designs clothes for men rather
than women. Then there's the matter of his age, which is 45, not
26. Surely that is one reason he is so decidedly averse to the
zanily effete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few men's wear designers understand that regular blokes
do not want to look like hairdressers or skateboarders or street
hustlers,'' said Simon Doonan, creative director at Barneys New
York. Barneys has given Varvatos hundreds of square feet in its
Madison Avenue store, putting him in a league with the Dolce &AMP;
Gabannas, and Doonan is featuring Varvatos' fall clothes
prominently in the store's current advertising campaign. Varvatos
also received a lot of room for a new designer at Bergdorf Goodman
and at Saks Fifth Avenue, which were quick to pick him up after a
first collection that did not go unnoticed by the press.
</P>
<P>
   The designer's clothes seem intended for the kind of guy who has
moved into a salary bracket that no longer confines him to Banana
Republic. Varvatos, who garnered the award for best new designer of
men's wear at the American Fashion Awards in June, creates
masculine clothes. There are bulky knit sweaters, wide-leg pants
and topcoats _ made in Italy, not Taiwan _ with fabrics Varvatos
develops with his manufacturers. For his spring line, the
silhouettes are similar, this time with sweaters made of a
cashmere-linen blend.
</P>
<P>
   A native of suburban Detroit, Varvatos was the head men's wear
designer at both Ralph Lauren and Calvin Klein before going out on
his own with backing from Nautica. Executives from Nautica in fact
called him seven years ago about starting a line, but Varvatos
turned them down. ``I decided my ego wasn't that big,'' he said.
Eventually, though, he started to see a real void in the men's
market, and when Nautica called him two years ago with the same
offer, he said yes. He also oversees Nautica's jeans line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the modern guy who shops at Prada and Gucci and Helmut
Lang,'' Varvatos said. ``And then there's the classic Armani
customer. But there's a guy in the middle and there isn't that much
out there for him.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a point Varvatos likes to make as he travels to stores
to rouse the sales people. ``Please take the time to go through the
collection because you can find great details to talk to the
customer about,'' he said to a group at Bergdorf Goodman a few
weeks ago as he picked up acoat with a built-in cell phone pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a business person as well as a designer,'' Varvatos said
later. ``Sometimes designers are brilliant creatively, but they
lose touch with what's happening at the store. You have to ring the
register.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
