<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Sept. 13 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MORGAN (New York) _ Chase Manhattan is in serious talks to
acquire J.P Morgan &AMP; Co. Inc., an executive close to the deal said
on Tuesday. Details of the negotiations were not immediately
available, although the executive said an announcement could come
as early as Wednesday morning. The transaction would end the
independence of J.P. Morgan, the storied investment bank and the
nation's fifth largest. For Chase, which has historically made
smaller acquisitions like its buyout of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist and
Robert Fleming Holdings, the deal would catapult the bank into the
top echelon with Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. By
Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT31, and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Early version has MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-AVOIDANCE (Undated) _ Treasury officials say that abusive
corporate tax shelters are the government's biggest tax enforcement
problem, costing billions of dollars annually. Now a company called
The Tax People is teaching similarly dubious tax avoidance
techniques to middle class Americans and says it has already signed
up 50,000 of them. The key to the system is to set up a business in
your home. For almost everybody who participates, that business is
to sell the company's ``tax relief'' system to others. Then, almost
any time you leave the house _ whether to commute to your day job,
buy groceries, play golf or go to church _ you deduct the cost of
the trip as a business expense on the ground that everywhere you go
you are doing business recruiting customers. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-SCHOOLS (Ramallah, West Bank) _ As Palestinian
schools open, some grades, for the first time, have a curriculum
written by and for Palestinians. And some Palestinians, as well as
Israelis, don't like it. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FUEL (London) _ Britain slid into chaos on Tuesday as
continuing protests over high fuel prices all but halted gasoline
deliveries across the country, forcing businesses and government
agencies to begin curtailing operations and more than three
quarters of the nation's 13,000 service stations to shut down for
lack of fuel. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Early version has MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ The results of the latest N.Y.
Times/CBS News poll on the presidential campaign. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ An official from the
Bridgestone/Firestone Co. told a Senate committee Tuesday that
discovering the pattern of tire failures that has been linked to 88
deaths nationwide took longer than the company would have wished
because of the complexity of the problem and the fact that,
statistically, only a tiny number of tires failed. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,4.
</P>
<P>
   Early version has MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-RELEASE (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Folo on the Wen Ho Lee
agreement, and some of the finger pointing that has ensued. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
