<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-MILITARY-STRATEGY-NNS     09-12 1939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-STRATEGY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CHENEY WAS ARCHITECT OF DEFENSE STRATEGY HE NOW SCORNS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Sept. 12, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ART ADVISORY: With a photo of U.S. troops landing on a beach in
Somalia in March 1993 (NNS1). For information about purchasing this
photo call 202-383-7824.  
 By DAVID WOOD  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration's national security
strategy, which has drawn cutting scorn from Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush and his running mate, Dick
Cheney, was in fact devised by then-Defense Secretary Cheney eight
years ago and has enjoyed broad bipartisan support in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy, first detailed in a February 1992 report by Cheney
to Congress and endorsed by then-President George Bush and Gen.
Colin Powell, who at the time was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, articulated a rationale for maintaining an ambitious
``forward presence'' of U.S. military forces worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's strategic blueprint, faithfully followed by the Clinton
administration, rested on the conviction that America's safety and
prosperity depend on stability in vast stretches of the globe, from
the Taiwan Straits to the Persian Gulf and Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   His plan mandated not only a frenetic pace of traditional
military operations but also the engagement of U.S. military forces
in peacekeeping, humanitarian and nation-building missions _
missions that candidates Bush and Cheney now say ``squander''
American combat power.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP team charges that the military is ``over-used and
under-resourced,'' and accuses the Clinton administration of
overextending and neglecting U.S. military forces.
</P>
<P>
   But it was budget cuts and base closings begun while Cheney was
defense secretary and deepened under Clinton that left the military
struggling to keep up with the strategy's global demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney today is running against the sorts of things he
endorsed back in the early 1990s,'' said James Lindsay, a senior
foreign policy fellow at the Brookings Institution in Washington.
``But this is really more about slogans than substance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cheney campaign responded Tuesday that even if Cheney's 1992
strategy set the direction for U.S. forces in the 1990s, the
Clinton administration had exceeded what Cheney intended as a
prudent management of military forces and defense budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush administration in 1992 laid out a plan for what it
thought might occur in the future, and that plan would have been
subject to annual revision,'' said Cheney spokeswoman Juleanna
Glover Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the Clinton administration made the mistake of hiking
up deployments to a level unanticipated by Bush's projections,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeanne Kirkpatrick, who was President Reagan's ambassador to
the United Nations from 1981 to 1985, agreed that the Bush and
Clinton administrations shared a strategy of global leadership and
military engagement, ``not constantly engaged in military
operations, but doing so when necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   She said their common strategic approach enshrined the idea of
working in coalition with other countries and with multilateral
organizations such as the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay said the strategy was actually a ``common sense''
approach that steers clear of both isolationism and an ``intervene
everywhere'' policy. ``Most Americans are comfortable with that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the strategy's core is the idea that only the United States,
with its unparalleled military reach and power, can underwrite
world stability.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney drew on that concept as he struggled in 1992 to deal with
the uncertainties and dimly perceived dangers of the post-Cold War
world that was just emerging. He and Bush sought to justify
maintaining much of America's Cold War military force in the face
of popular pressure for deeper cuts and a ``peace dividend.'' But
their strategy was put in place just as they slashed the Cold War
defense budget and military manpower by a third and closed ``more
than 700'' U.S. bases overseas, as Cheney boasted at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1992 report, Cheney said U.S. military forces would
maintain stability by engaging globally in ``peacekeeping, disaster
relief, nation-building assistance, humanitarian assistance'' and
other non-combat functions.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon soon found it difficult to cover all the new
missions Cheney envisioned without the convenience of the foreign
bases he had ordered closed. The result was a significant strain on
warships and aircraft, and longer deployments for troops, sailors
and airmen.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Air Force squadrons that a decade ago could have
flown daily missions over Bosnia from home bases in Europe now must
deploy to Europe for months at a time from home bases in the United
States. That ``time away from family'' has cut deeply into pilot
morale.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush has vowed to ``restore morale.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has curtly dismissed the Clinton administration's use of
the military as ``action without vision, activity without priority
and missions without end _ an approach that squanders American will
and drains American energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, in a speech Aug. 30 at the Southern Center for
International Studies in Atlanta, noted that ``over the last
decade, (military) commitments have gone up 300 percent while our
military forces have been cut by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our military has been overextended, taken for granted and
neglected,'' Cheney charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's needed,'' Bush thundered in a Sept. 7 speech to the
Veterans of Foreign Wars, ``is a strategic plan with a strategic
vision as to how to keep the long-term peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor Cheney has suggested which missions they would
halt, or where they would cut back today's military presence.
</P>
<P>
   But Kirkpatrick, in an interview, suggested that Bush would use
military forces more carefully, under more restrictive conditions,
than Clinton has. What has emerged in the presidential campaign
rhetoric, she said, are ``not huge differences, but more than
nuances.''
</P>
<P>
   While some specific missions within Cheney's strategy have
generated controversy, including the ill-fated U.S. intervention in
Somalia in 1992, the overall concept of global engagement has drawn
remarkably little fire.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as articulated by other politicians, and by successive
defense secretaries who followed Cheney, the strategy reflects an
extraordinary consensus about America's place in the world and the
role of its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the United States should not seek to be the world's
policeman ... but in a world where we are the only remaining
superpower, it is the role of the United States to marshal its
moral and material resources to promote a democratic peace. It is
our responsibility, it is our opportunity to lead. There is no one
else,'' President George Bush said in a speech to West Point cadets
in January 1993 after he was defeated for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen used almost the same language
last year, when he declared: ``We are not the world's policeman.
What we seek is to promote stability and democracy wherever we can
and in whatever capacity we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Condoleezza Rice, the chief national security and foreign policy
adviser to candidate Bush, maintains that the United States ought
to pay less attention to areas of ``questionable'' importance, such
as Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   But in an article in Foreign Affairs magazine earlier this year,
she declared that U.S. military forces need to be decisively
engaged in the Asia-Pacific region, the Middle East, the Persian
Gulf and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is the only guarantor of global peace and
stability,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, annual Pentagon reports and official White House
statements of national security policy have reflected Cheney's
original strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military ``forward presence,'' Cheney wrote in 1992,
``continues to be critical to stability and world confidence in
America's leadership. ... Future peace and stability in the world
will continue to depend in large measure on our willingness to
deploy forces overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. military forces must maintain a forward presence to show
U.S. commitment and lend credibility to our alliances, to deter
aggression, enhance regional stability, promote U.S. influence and
access, and when required, provide an initial crisis response
capability,'' Cheney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, Congress year after year has generously
supported the forces assigned to carry out the strategy, including
aircraft carrier battle groups, expeditionary Air Force squadrons,
and the ground troops that rotate through the Far East and Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, with concern mounting about the wear and tear
on people and machines, Congress has consistently added money to
the defense budget. This summer it appropriated $3.3 billion more
than Clinton requested, for a total of $287.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That money finances a military operating tempo more reminiscent
of Cold War days than today's peacetime environment.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for example, the Navy has 146 warships under way on
routine operations, including two aircraft carriers, 14 submarines
and two amphibious fleets carrying 4,200 Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 20,000 Air Force personnel _ pilots, ground crews and
other support people _ are on temporary missions abroad. The Army
has 21,000 soldiers on temporary missions overseas, and another
124,300 stationed abroad, in South Korea, Germany and 124 other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, almost 20 percent of today's active-duty military _
or some 265,518 people _ are deployed overseas, together with about
188,000 military dependents, according to a Defense Department
report issued in March.
</P>
<P>
   And they are involved in a vast array of missions that reflect
Cheney's 1992 list: peacekeeping in Kosovo and Bosnia, crisis
prevention in Kuwait, disaster relief in Honduras, even a minor
nation-building mission in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, George W. Bush has savaged such missions
as ill-considered.
</P>
<P>
   As president, he would ``order an immediate review'' of all U.S.
commitments and ``replace uncertain missions with well-defined
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   But his father, in his 1993 West Point speech, warned against
adopting such a ``rigid'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that many people would like to find some formula, some
easy formula to apply, to tell us with precision when and where to
intervene with force. Anyone looking for scientific certitude is in
for a disappointment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the complex new world we are entering, there can be no
single or simple set of fixed rules for using force. Inevitably,
the question of military intervention requires judgment,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Some senior military officers privately have chafed at the broad
responsibilities of ``stability operations,'' as many of today's
military missions are known.
</P>
<P>
   But publicly, at least, they seem skeptical that any other
approach can be devised.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as our strategy remains that we will be `forward'
(deployed), I see no way to avoid being out there and doing all
those things,'' Marine Gen. Terrence Dake told reporters last
month. ``And I don't see the world changing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
