<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-VIOLENCE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL PANEL TO HEAR TESTIMONY ON MARKETING OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Sept. 12, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 By J. SCOTT ORR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When critics of the entertainment industry fret
about the marketing of violent material to children, they are no
doubt thinking of artists like rapper Eminem, who screams violently
about ``blood, guts, guns, cuts, knives, lives, wives, nuns,
sluts'' in his song ``Kill You.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem isn't on the witness list for Wednesday's Senate Commerce
Committee hearing on the marketing of violence to children, but
lyrics like his are on the agenda along with the blood-soaked
imagery of many video games and the gratuitous gunplay of some
R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the Federal Trade Commission released its report
charging the entertainment industry with marketing violent music,
movies and video games to children, the industry is set to defend
itself before the Senate on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding politics to the mix, Democratic vice presidential
candidate Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut will testify, as
will Lynne Cheney, wife of Dick Cheney, the Republican vice
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said in its report that the motion picture, recording
and software industries routinely ignore their own rating systems
when devising marketing strategies. The commission found all
samples it examined of music rated for adults were marketed to
children younger than 17, as were 80 percent of R-rated movies and
70 percent of adult-rated video games.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not say which titles the FTC used for its
analysis, but the commission's concerns about marketing to youth
audiences would apply generally to all music that contains warnings
about adult language, all movies with R ratings and all video games
rated for consumers 17 or older.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Examples might include Eminem. His current release, ``The
Marshall Mathers LP,'' contains violent, misogynist and homophobic
lyrics, including ``Kill You,'' a song with lyrics like ``I
invented violence you vile, venomous, vomital bitches. ... Touch
the chainsaw, left his brains all dangling from his neck while his
head barely hangs on.''
</P>
<P>
   And Slayer, for decades the most successful satanic rock band.
Its 1998 album ``Diabolus in Musica'' includes the song ``Death's
Head'' with the lyrics ``Death's pointed at your head, your mind on
the trigger pull it. Bludgeon bodies give up their muted horror
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Among video games, there's ``Soldier of Fortune,'' a
first-person shoot-'em-up game from Activision. On its Web site,
Activision promotes the game, saying: ``Real bullets do real
damage: Shoot someone in the leg and he falls, writhing and
grasping his wound; shoot someone in the head and he falls down
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Redneck Rampage'' from Interplay, an unusual
blend of violence and rank humor that has spawned at least two
sequels. A review of the game linked to the Interplay site says:
``Peek at the industry rating _ mature for animated blood and gore,
strong language, and use of tobacco and alcohol _ and that should
be your first clue that this ... is no `Hee Haw.'''
</P>
<P>
   The movie category is by far the broadest, including everything
from sexploitation flicks and action films to some modern classics:
anything that received an R or NC-17 rating from the Motion Picture
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Among current films that would qualify as violent fare are ``The
Way of the Gun,'' which is rated R for ``strong violence/gore,
language and some sexuality,'' and ``The Art of War,'' which got
its R rating for ``nudity, language, excessive violence.''
</P>
<P>
   But the category also would include ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the
1998 World War II classic, which was rated R for ``strong, intense,
prolonged, realistically graphic sequences of war violence and for
language.''
</P>
<P>
   James T. Hamilton, director of the Duke University Program on
Violence and the Media, said movies like ``Saving Private Ryan''
are the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry likes to talk about `Saving Private Ryan' and
`Schindler's List' as examples of movies that would get an `R' for
violence and also get a four-star rating. But if you look at all
movies, violent four-star movies make up only about 2 percent,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Expected to defend the industries Wednesday against the FTC's
charges of marketing violence to children are a parade of witnesses
representing the movie, recording and software industries.
</P>
<P>
   They are likely to point to the voluntary rating programs that
have been established to help parents take the initiative in
steering their kids away from violent music, movies and video
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents, not the government, have the responsibility for
guiding their children toward music that is appropriate for a
child's age and maturity,'' said Hillary Rosen, president of the
Recording Industry Association, who is slated to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Another scheduled witness, Douglas Lowenstein, president of the
Interactive Digital Software Association, added that ``parents have
the tools and, as importantly, the power and the opportunity to act
responsibly on behalf of their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Parental vigilance, he said, ``is ultimately the best way to
ensure that games that are inappropriate for kids are kept out of
their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman said on Monday that their administration
would give the industry a period of perhaps six months to change
its marketing techniques before seeking regulatory or legislative
means to crack down on them.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Gerstein, a spokesman for Lieberman's Senate office, said
Lieberman will reiterate the campaign's position Wednesday. He
would not say if Lieberman's testimony was drafted by his Senate
office or by the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see him expand on the points that he and the vice
president made yesterday,'' Gerstein said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proper way to think about this is that we're looking at
things the industries themselves say are inappropriate for kids.
And if they are targeting their marketing at kids, then that is
wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Cheney, the author of a 1995 book on the nation's
dysfunctional culture, will issue a similar call on the industry to
police itself. Marguerite Sullivan, a spokeswoman for Cheney, said
Cheney opposes legislative means to crack down on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will be addressing the bigger cultural issues: how the
industry needs to start taking real responsibility for its
products,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, neither Cheney nor Lieberman will be testifying on
behalf of the presidential campaigns, though their appearances on
the witness list seem hardly coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   After Gore and Lieberman made an issue of the FTC report on
Monday, Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said Gore ``deserves an Oscar
award for hypocrisy'' for criticizing Hollywood while accepting
millions of dollars in campaign contributions from the
entertainment industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
