<SLUG> BC-U.N.-WEST-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. INVESTIGATORS OF WEST TIMOR KILLINGS NOT WELCOME, INDONESIA
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Indonesia's defense minister said on Tuesday
that his government would not meet with U.N. representatives when
they visit Indonesia to look into the killings last Wednesday of
three U.N. refugee workers in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Mohammed Mafud, told journalists in Jakarta that
the government Cabinet considered the incident an internal matter
better handled by the Indonesians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will reject the presence of that mission,'' Mafud said,
according to the French news agency Agence France-Presse. ``We will
negotiate on our own, we will settle this on our own,'' the defense
minister said. ``We are a sovereign nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, being sent by the Security Council, was expected
to depart early next week for Indonesia and West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But President Abdurrahman Wahid said that the minister had gone
beyond his instructions, diplomats here reported. They said that
Indonesia's foreign minister, Alwi Shahab, would convey his
government's formal response to the council's president, Moctar
Ouane of Mali, here on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
predicted that the visit would go ahead. ``I can't imagine why it
won't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit's purpose, Holbrooke said, was not to embarrass the
Indonesian government but to offer help by directly expressing the
council's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mission is to support the civilian leadership of
Indonesia,'' Holbrooke said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The three workers for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees _
Carlos Cacere, Samson Aregehegn and Pero Simundza _ were killed in
the West Timorese town of Atambua when a mob led by armed militia
members stormed their office and battered and hacked the three
unarmed men to death. The assailants had been attending a funeral
for a militia leader killed the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, in a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
promised to bring the killers to justice.
</P>
<P>
   The national police chief, Gen. Rusdihardjo, who uses only one
name, reported on Tuesday in Jakarta that five suspects had been
arrested in the investigation into the death of the militia leader,
Olivio Mendosa Moruk. Rusdihardjo said another five suspects were
being sought.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council, in its resolution adopted Friday, called
the killings ``outrageous and contemptible'' and demanded that the
Indonesian government take immediate steps to disarm and disband
the undisciplined militias, which oppose independence for East
Timor and are thought to get support from elements in the
Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   The slain U.N. workers were in West Timor to assist refugees who
had fled militia-led violence in East Timor. The council said that
the U.N. workers, more than 400 of whom were evacuated from West
Timor after the murders, would not return until the government
showed that it could guarantee their security.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Indonesian government initially refused to meet
another delegation from the Security Council, only to back down
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1856EDT &QL; 
