u a BC-MA-SMOKING-BOS &LR;      09-12 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SMOKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO COMPANIES TRIED TO HIDE SECONDHAND SMOKE, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Using code names such as ``Project Stealth'' and
``Project Ambrosia,'' cigarette manufacturers have tested
ingredients that hide secondhand smoke in a bid to make smoking
more socially acceptable but not necessarily safer, the
Massachusetts Department of Public Health alleged in a study
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study was issued just four days after a federal court struck
down Massachusetts' 1996 law requiring tobacco companies to reveal
each brand's ingredients in order from largest to smallest, like
the ingredients printed on soup or cereal packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department is extremely disappointed with the opinion,''
said Dr. Gregory Connolly, head of the Department of Public
Health's Massachusetts Tobacco Control Program and an author of the
study. ``It's denied the department's right to do basic research.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said the new study highlights public health officials'
need to know about ingredients that may be used as a ``marketing
ploy'' to make smoking more palatable to consumers _ particularly
women _ who are concerned about exposing their children to smoking,
or about odors on their hair and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1980s, tobacco companies tested a number of
compounds on people or animals to see if they would lower the
``visibility, aroma, irritancy, or the actual level of secondary
smoke,'' Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big concern is there was little evidence (that) they
tested the product to see if it was reducing risk for disease,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Carnovale, a spokeswoman for Phillip Morris, said that for
every new additive, the company does a ``rigorous assessment to
make sure it doesn't increase the health risks of cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Phillip Morris never masked cigarette odor, and did not
know if it had used additives to reduce the appearance of
secondhand smoke. But she stressed that the DPH study was based on
``past documents,'' adding that the company is ``doing things very
differently today,'' including working to cut down on the actual
effects of secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Public Health study, published Wednesday in
Tobacco Control, a journal of the British Medical Association, was
based on tobacco company documents that were either filed with
patent applications or made public in the massive lawsuit by state
attorneys general against the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The study cited two 1990 Philip Morris describing Project
Stealth, a product with less smoke from the lit end and low odor
aimed at ``helping smokers feel better about smoking in social
situations.'' But after research showed smokers felt the product
did not reduce smoke enough to make them feel better around
non-smokers, the company instead positioned it as ``the first
cigarette that doesn't leave a stale, lingering odor after
smoking,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Phillip Morris spokesman said the company was pleased
with the decision by U.S. District Judge George A. O'Toole Jr., who
ruled that it would be unfair to force companies to disclose
recipes that help create distinctive flavors and brand identity.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators, led by Senator Mark Montigny, are working on
an amendment to address concerns about the 1996 law, the first in
the nation to force the disclosure. One possibility, Connolly said,
is to require disclosure to public health officials but not to the
public, as in a Texas law that has not been challenged in court.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1986 federal law, tobacco companies are required to
provide lists of ingredients to the Department of Health and Human
Services, but the information isn't made public. It does not
specify quantities or indicate which additives are used in which
brands; nor does it include ingredients in wrappers or filters.
</P>
<P>
   Carnovale said Phillip Morris would welcome ``reasonable
regulation'' of ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, smoking kills 10,000 people in Massachusetts and
secondhand smoke kills 3,000 people nationwide, public health
officials estimate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
