<HEADER>
A0892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE13-COX     09-12 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore, Lieberman tour in Ohio
 &HT;    By Thomas Gnau
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Ohio _ Close up, Democratic presidential candidate
Vice President
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore doesn't look larger than life. But the roar of students
that greeted him in the Middletown High School cafeteria Tuesday
was.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and running mate U.S. Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., brought
their campaign to classrooms, hallways, the cafeteria and Paul
Walker Gymnasium surrounded by
</P>
<P>
   school staff, campaign aides, Secret Service agents and - of
course - a lot of students.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was in Middletown as part of his campaign's ``On the Road
to A+ Education'' tour. The focus was Democratic ideas on improving
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good message,'' said Middletown Board of Education member
Katie McNeil. She added, ``Our students need to hear that from more
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore and I love the Middletown High School Middies,''
Lieberman declared
</P>
<P>
   after he and Gore ascended a platform in the gym to the tune of
``Rocky Top,'' performed by an MHS pep band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we take these cheerleaders with us around America?'' the
Connecticut
</P>
<P>
   senator asked, referring to the girls on bleachers behind the
candidates. That ignited shrieks and another roar from 1,700
assembled students.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Middies appeared taken with the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore entered the cafeteria at about 11:30 a.m., cheering
students stood
</P>
<P>
   on tables and chairs to get a glimpse and take photographs.
Students exchanged cameras with other students in an effort to get
better shots. Beaming cafeteria workers waited behind the lunch
serving counter as Gore picked up a tray. He took onion rings, a
bowl of spaghetti and bottled water, and he shook hands with
students and employees as he went.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman, who entered the cafeteria a few moments
later, sat down
</P>
<P>
   with Principal Gary Perkins, social studies teacher Mary Harvey
and four female students.
</P>
<P>
   Gore invited those surrounding his table to ask him questions.
``How's the food?'' junior Josh Estoye, standing a few feet away,
shouted at Gore above the din.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent,'' Gore answered.
</P>
<P>
   Estoye, 17, said a moment later he spoke to Gore ``just to start
up a
</P>
<P>
   conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   The student said he will be old enough to vote on Election Day
Nov. 7. He
</P>
<P>
   said he doesn't know which candidate will get his vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I watch TV and all the political shows, I realize it's
interesting to
</P>
<P>
   know what's going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, Lieberman greeted members of Libby Armentrout's
English class. Before the vice presidential candidate arrived,
Armentrout described her students as ``all seniors, all potential
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the class had missed lunch, and had been holding off
hunger with
</P>
<P>
   ``animal crackers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pretty pumped up since 10 o'clock, so we're very
excited,'' she
</P>
<P>
   said. A few minutes later, Lieberman entered the room with a
slight smile and a
</P>
<P>
   wave. ``Hello, everybody,'' he said. ``How are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We saved you the seat of honor, which is perched at my desk,''
Armentrout
</P>
<P>
   said.
</P>
<P>
   She told Lieberman that the class was starting to study
``Beowulf,'' an Old
</P>
<P>
   English poem written some 1,000 years ago. A first draft of a
paper on the
</P>
<P>
   work was due today, but his visit delayed the assignment due
date, she told
</P>
<P>
   him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So did I give you a break there?'' Lieberman asked the
students. ``Tell your
</P>
<P>
   families to all vote for the Gore-Lieberman campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   When he learned that one student was 18, Lieberman told him:
``Be sure to
</P>
<P>
   register (to vote). I'm serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman learned that striving to write well was an ongoing
concern in the
</P>
<P>
   class. ``It's such an important skill,'' he said. He said when
he was a high school student, ``the time I was expressing myself
most at that time was when I was writing because I was awkward
verbally.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the class that he had about 120 attorneys working for
him when he was
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's attorney general. Some of them, he said, couldn't
write very
</P>
<P>
   well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made them less effective lawyers,'' he said. ``I didn't
expect to give that lecture this morning,'' he added a bit
wistfully a moment later.
</P>
<P>
   When told the students would soon tackle resume and technical
writing,
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman became more serious. He said a poorly-written resume
``closes my
</P>
<P>
   mind to that person, even if that person happens to be capable
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lieberman asked senior Aaron Fay where he wanted to go to
college, Fay shook his head. ``Anywhere but a school in Ohio,'' Fay
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing as you come along is to be educated
today,'' Lieberman said. ``We want to try, Al Gore and I, to make
that a little easier for you.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the students about Gore's plans for a ``$10,000 tax
deduction for tuition'' at a college, trade or technical school as
well as a savings fun in which citizens and their employers could
invest tax-free for education costs.
</P>
<P>
   He talked of friends with whom he graduated from high school in
Stamford, Conn., almost 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their expectation was, so long as they went to work and did
their job, they
</P>
<P>
   could work at their place for 35, 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all changed now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides ushered watching reporters out of the class
before Lieberman
</P>
<P>
   finished his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the candidates arrived, about 11 protesters made their
presence felt
</P>
<P>
   near Manchester Technical Center, just north of the high school
at the
</P>
<P>
   intersection of Breiel Boulevard and Manchester Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not really pose a problem,'' said Middletown Police
Lt. David
</P>
<P>
   VanArsdale. ``They were orderly and complied with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was arrested, he said. He said one of the protesters held
a sign that
</P>
<P>
   said, ``Gore lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
