<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-12 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BOTH GORE, BUSH SHOULD SPARE US DETAILS
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The longer this presidential campaign goes on the more one
wonders if Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush
understand the way our government works.
</P>
<P>
   Or, one wonders, is it possible the two candidates do understand
how our government works but are so sure we don't that they think
they're better off campaigning on governmental details over which
the president has little control?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than letting Gore stampede him into their current contest
of whose tedious legislative specifics are better, Bush should have
stuck to one of his stronger campaign points: His claim he has a
proven record of working well across partisan lines in passing
legislation through a bipartisan Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has stepped off into the deep end of his political
pool by trying to out-wonk one of America's all-time great wonks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore not only genuinely enjoys excruciating details, he, at
least at the moment, is proving himself a far better politician
than GWB.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken almost total control of the presidential campaign
by setting an agenda that has little to do with the presidency.
Indeed, he has steered the campaign into a contest driven by more
legislative specifics than those to which most legislative
candidates should be willing to commit.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for presidential candidates to disagree on the
general form and financing of Medicare _ especially as the plan
deals with prescription drugs. It's quite another to wrangle over
the design of prescription forms and the number each Medicare
doctor must keep.
</P>
<P>
   You think that sounds silly? Listen to some of the Medicare
specifics on which Bush and Gore are campaigning _ and arguing.
</P>
<P>
   And, meanwhile, the voting public _ and, ultimately, the
presidential election _ would be well served if the voters were
paying attention to what is going on in the Congress right now.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pretty fine demonstration of a couple of political
cliches that are cliches because the truth of them has made them
trite:
</P>
<P>
   No. 1) Politics is compromise. As was graphically proven during
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich's Republican reign in the
Congress: The GOPers who won't compromise are likely to be made
politically miserable by a Democratic president who will veto their
purist legislation.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2) When all else fails a president who wants legislation the
Congress doesn't, the president can share his unhappiness with the
veto.
</P>
<P>
   If you will recall, when GWB's father, George Bush the Elder,
was a GOP president, with a Dem Congress, his main legislative fame
was, for a political eternity, the number of his vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   That man vetoed right and, well, right tons of bills.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say a president can't be quite important when it
comes to passing legislation. Bill Clinton, the Democratic
president who outlasted Gingrich and made so many other Republicans
willing to see the merits of pragmatism over purism, is being
important right now.
</P>
<P>
   Lame duck and despised by many GOPers though he may be, Clinton,
who once made Republicans look to be unfeeling jerks to many, is
offering to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   He is not likely to get that opportunity, however. Instead,
legislative deals will be cut and political trades will be made
within the Congress _ and with him, if necessary. But Clinton, as
should be the case with presidents, is not going to waste the
legislative power he has to deal for minor, tedious legislative
details.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gore and Bush, Gore has moved to adopt one of Bush's
strong political points, while Bush has embraced one of Gore's
least realistic and likable traits in a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Al Gore won friends and influenced women voters when he
kissed his wife and joked with Oprah. But, he's winning more
friends and influencing lots more voters the easier he gets in
style. Not so for Bush, who's been suckered into being less a
likable big-philosophical-picture type and more a wonk who has
trouble pronouncing his details.
</P>
<P>
   Our government has three branches: executive, legislative and
judicial. Good political judgment suggests their campaigns would be
better and far more meaningful if Gore and Bush would spend less
time on the legislative and more effort in proving their abilities
to be the leading executive of the Free World. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
