<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    GOP FRIENDLY FIRE: WHO NEEDS ENEMIES?
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republicans' circular firing squad has stood down, but it
could re-form on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   About this time last week, the mau-mauing started. Veteran
Republican whingers knew that several new national polls were about
to hit. They thought George W. Bush was in for more bad numbers
(worse, actually, than they turned out to be) so they elbowed to
the front of the line to get in their usually anonymous licks early
against their beleaguered candidate. An appearance of prescience is
so important.
</P>
<P>
   A modestly seminal story appeared on the front page of The New
York Times. It spoke of Republican disaffection with Bush's
campaign and worry that his Austin handlers weren't up to the
demands of a national effort (which may ultimately prove to be
perfectly true). It quoted Bill Bennett, whose chief virtues are
that he almost always answers his phone and wants to appear to have
some Jesuitical compulsion toward earnest truth-telling. (Bennett
was also hard to avoid on the weekend talk shows.)
</P>
<P>
   As these things happen, the Times piece was read in New York
over coffee by network anchors and producers, and the day's agenda
for political pieces was set. Yes, it's a touch incestuous, but
nevermind.
</P>
<P>
   As could have been expected, Bush did not take the grousing well
and, perhaps remembering his father's 1992 fiasco, told aides that
only when a campaign is in trouble do you ``find out who your
friends really are.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Bush blamed the carping on ``Washington,'' contending
``that's the place where you find people getting ready to jump out
of the foxhole before the first shell is fired.'' (Given Bush's &QL; 
daring service in the Texas Air National Guard, perhaps he should
leave off the battlefield metaphors.)
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the complaining also was coming from around the
country, especially from Republican fat cats who only weeks ago
were measuring for drapes in Washington or some exotic capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bush observed: ``I guess some of my supporters wanted it to be a
run-away.''
</P>
<P>
   Then as last weekend began, the poll numbers started coming out,
showing the race to be a dead heat, the closest post-Labor Day
surveys in 20 years. Slap-dab even or within the margin of error in
almost every national survey.
</P>
<P>
   A new sounding published Tuesday by the historically dead-on
Battleground poll, now an adjunct to Voter.com, also showed a
neck-and-neck race, with Gore at 41 percent and Bush at 40.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasn't rebounding, but he also wasn't in free-fall as some
of the GOP doubters feared. Most worrisome for Bush is what appears
to be a slight trend to Gore in the USA Today-CNN-Gallup tracking
poll. Also, new polls in key states shows a shift to Gore. A
Missouri survey found the vice president leading 45-40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The best possible reading of the new numbers is that Bush has
just been through the worst three weeks of the campaign and hasn't
been knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Democrats believe, however, that Gore has sufficiently
allayed voters' concerns about the vice president's personal
leadership qualities and his relationship with President Clinton to
let the natural effect of ``peace and prosperity'' work through the
undecided electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his team aren't dummies. They were aware of their
problems (it would have been difficult not to be, given three weeks
of slippage and daily media reminders) if not exactly what to do
about them. But alterations were already in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turn on a dime,'' Bush communications director Karen Hughes
observed, in a bit of overstatement, as her candidate left the
lectern and headed for coffee shops and shop floors, the informal
settings that proved salutary after John McCain knocked the Texas
governor's crown off.
</P>
<P>
   Internally, Bush operatives took firmer control of the
Republican National Committee staff (about time) to ensure better
coordination on the RNC's television ad campaign. Bush had
personally scratched the RNC's first attack ad against Gore.
Republican sources said that the RNC ad that eventually aired was
insufficiently market-tested before being slammed into a time buy
costing up to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hopeful Republicans believe that a campaign that rebounded, as
Bush's did, after the nasty surprise in New Hampshire, can retool
effectively. Others in the party believe the Bush effort is still
floundering and has no clear idea of how it can get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Any minute now, the doubters may again circle round and cry,
``Lock and load.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
