<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPACIFIC-SUIT0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Caraustar says G-P dispute brings mill closure
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Recycled-packaging company Caraustar Industries claims
a contract dispute with Georgia-Pacific has forced it to shut a New
Jersey mill.
</P>
<P>
   Austell-based Caraustar also said Tuesday it will fall far short
of earnings estimates for the third quarter, partly because of
reduced orders from Georgia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves a contract that calls for Georgia-Pacific
to use Caraustar's paper products in its gypsum wallboard products.
Gypsum wallboard, made from a layer of gypsum sandwiched between
two sheets of paperboard, is used widely to finish interior walls
in houses and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Caraustar claims Atlanta-based Georgia-Pacific, the country's
No. 2 paper and lumber company, violated the contract when it
started using products from its own mills to make the wallboard. As
a result, Caraustar said Georgia-Pacific's average monthly purchase
dropped by more than 80 percent from 7,000 tons during the first
half of this year. Caraustar also said Georgia-Pacific, its largest
wallboard paper customer, indicated it will further cut back in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
   The cutback in business caused Caraustar to close its mill in
Camden, N.J., where it makes about 50,000 tons of paperboard a
year, the company said. That's about 3.3 percent of Caraustar's
total production of paperboard. The company also makes tubes,
cartons and other products.
</P>
<P>
   Caraustar has filed a lawsuit against Georgia-Pacific in
Superior Court in Charlotte, N.C., seeking damages of more than
$100 million for breach of contract. Georgia-Pacific in turn filed
a separate action in Fulton County, Ga., Superior Court for
judgment seeking to justify its interpretation of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific said the contract doesn't include certain grades
of gypsum-facing paper that it makes itself. The company also said
it was surprised by the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia-Pacific is committed to complying fully with its
contracts. We repeatedly have attempted to negotiate this issue in
good faith and we are disappointed by actions taken by Caraustar
Industries,'' said Pete Correll, chairman and chief executive of
Georgia-Pacific. ``We completely disagree with its interpretation
of the contract and its representation of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Caraustar said the loss of Georgia-Pacific business, plus rising
fiber costs and lower profits in some businesses, will
significantly hurt third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   After one-time charges for the mill closing and other costs,
Caraustar expects third-quarter earnings to be between 21 cents and
24 cents a share, said Chief Financial Officer Lee Thrash.
Caraustar was expected to earn 47 cents in the third quarter,
according to a poll by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
