<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-IXL-ELLIS0913-COX     09-12 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IXL-ELLIS0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long days ahead for iXL chief
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Last week was the worst for Bert Ellis, founder,
chairman and CEO of iXL Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   First, the company announced it would not meet its third quarter
earnings projections, due in part to lengthening sales cycles from
its Global 2000 client base.
</P>
<P>
   That news was followed quickly by a company reorganization that
included the resignation of Bill Nussey, president of iXL Inc., the
company's professional services division. Ellis stepped into
Nussey's job, announced a new management team and began to
streamline iXL's operations that culminated the layoff of 350
employees, about 65 of them in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After what he referred to as one of the worst weeks of his life,
Ellis took time out to talk about what's happened. Ellis remains
confident he can reverse iXL's fortunes by stepping in, working
18-hour days and focusing on bringing in more revenue.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's confident his clients and most of his investors
will stick with him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This is a challenging time for iXL, but you've been through
other rough times in other businesses you've had. Are the problems
the same, or is the Internet economy a totally different business
environment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe, maybe not. What's different is what I'm doing about
it. I've got a nose for the revenue side of the business. When I
get up every morning, I think about what I can do about the
business, how are we doing with our existing business, with our
existing clients, what's in the pipeline and what can we do to
close the deal, and how can I help close the deal, and what else
can I do. Sales, revenue, client service and delivery. That's what
I spend half my time on. With me driving the company, we will focus
on that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The big question most analysts and investors want to know
right now is when will you be able to show some gains on the
revenue side?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've got a 30-day bubble problem. We let some things bite us
in the back that took 30 days out of our pipeline. The closing
cycle takes 30 days longer than it used to.
</P>
<P>
   There's the same amount of business out there. It just takes 30
days longer, and I didn't have enough revenue to fill it.
</P>
<P>
   We used to fill it with the dot-com business, but the dot-com
business is gone. We need six deals in the pipeline to close two.
We used to have a lower ratio.
</P>
<P>
   It's just math. The dilemma before was you had too much business
and you didn't have the people to build it. You used to have to
scramble around to get people. Now you have to scramble to get the
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you characterize your relationship with Wall Street
right now? Do you think they understand, not just iXL but all the
companies in your space, like Razorfish, Sapient, Viant and the
others having the same problems?
</P>
<P>
   A: We are in the penalty box and we have to understand that. We
have friendly cordial relationships with the analysts that cover
us. But we have to re-prove ourselves. Mike Casey (iXL's chief
financial offer) is crackerjack, and he knows how to do this. But
it's going to be one of those ``show me'' things.
</P>
<P>
   This quarter we take our lumps and they'll see what we do next
quarter. I think people will be pretty ... happy with what we do
and they'll look on us more favorably. There's not much point in
trying to win people over until we put another quarter behind us.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to miss our numbers, we've said we're going to miss
our numbers and we're going to use this time to make some strategic
changes that we couldn't make if we were going to hit our numbers.
The changes would have caused us to miss a number or two. Once you
miss a number, it doesn't matter. You miss a number you get thrown
in the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What you're doing is using a quarter you know isn't going to
look good to make key changes in the company that would have had a
negative impact on the third quarter anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A: We're getting out of some business it doesn't make sense for
us to be in.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to reduce the cost of operating this company. It's
going to throw two bad things into our quarters. It's going to
throw a boatload of severance into the quarter and mess with our
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what we say, they're going to say `show me.' We've
already told them what we're going to do this quarter, and they
don't like the story. We gave them expectations, and we didn't meet
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You are one of the most visible Internet executives in
Atlanta and in the Internet community (Ellis serves on 10 corporate
and six nonprofit boards). Now that Bill Nussey has resigned, and
you are stepping into his post, how will you run iXL Enterprises,
iXL Ventures, iXL Inc., and be an active member of the Internet
community without having a heart attack?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer is it's always been my style to hire really good
people, put them in good positions and let them run with it. If
they can't, then I step in. Bill (Nussey) and I decided he couldn't
do the job we needed to get done, and I decided that it would be
me.
</P>
<P>
   I have a great team running AppGenesys, CyberStarts and CFN (iXL
owns a 48 percent interest CFN). They don't need my attention right
now. I have really good managers there. I put iXL Ventures fund on
hold. iXL is my main focus right now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you have to admit you've got a pretty full plate right
now, even with just the business of iXL, given the financial
situation and corporate reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm going 18 hours a day right now, and we've accomplished a
lot. We have accomplished more in one week than we have in nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you be more specific?
</P>
<P>
   A: We reorganized this company. Regrettably, we fired 350
people.
</P>
<P>
   But I feel great about the company, and I was feeling pretty
gloomy some of last week. Firing 350 people is something I never
want to do again.
</P>
<P>
   But our management team is so invigorated. We are making
battlefield promotions, and we are at it full bore. I've had my
team in here all weekend. This is something we can solve, and we
can solve it fast.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Is making quick decisions what iXL needs right now to get back
on track with clients and investors?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ninety percent of it is about management. I've talked to a
lot of our clients. They are disappointed we are having a blip, but
they've seen it in their own businesses, too. They see what we are
doing about it. We haven't had any defections yet.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What are you saying to your investors?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know Atlanta and you know my situation here. There is a
boatload of people in Atlanta who own iXL stock because they know
me and a lot of people wanted to see what we were going to do about
this.
</P>
<P>
   My reputation and everybody I know is affected by this company.
I'm going to get it fixed fast. I gave Bill the ball and I said run
the company. Now, it's time to make a change there's no bigger
change you can make than changing the person at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When we talked with Bill Nussey when he resigned (Sept. 1),
he said he knew this management change was coming. During Bill's
tenure with iXL what positive contributions did he make to iXL? He
was named consultant of the year, after all.
</P>
<P>
   A: He put some structure to the company and we will take
advantage of that. Bill had a different focus at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Bill was with us a during a period when revenue was coming over
the transom, so he could afford to take the focus off the revenue
side. It didn't affect us until this quarter. It won't surprise us
again, now that I've restructured the company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Unlike a lot of new economy executives, this isn't your first
experience running a company or your first experience running into
some roadblocks. You've ridden this roller coaster before. Is this
any different, or is it just a new version of what you've been
through before?
</P>
<P>
   A: The difference with my other companies is they were private
and weren't in the fishbowl. These days if you are a public
company, it's a very confining environment. There are Internet
message boards and chat rooms and many more outlets for all kinds
of information. The market is like an accordion and snapped. Some
companies won't come back up. We're going to come back up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
