<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE LABEL OWNER SUES MP3.COM
</P>
<P>
   Zomba Recording said it had filed a lawsuit against MP3.com, the
online music distributor that only last week was found in violation
of copyright law in a similar suit filed by Universal Music Group.
The lawsuit accuses of MP3.com of willful copyright infringement in
relation to its MyMP3.com site, a service that lets users listen to
the company's CD collection over the Internet. Zomba's Jive label
records some of the biggest pop acts today, including Britney
Spears, the Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync. A sister company, Zomba
Music Publishing, filed a separate suit on the same grounds.
</P>
<P>
   AOL TAKES STAKE IN CYBIKO
</P>
<P>
   America Online has invested in Cybiko, Inc., a Bloomingdale,
Ill.-based maker of Palmlike hand-held devices aimed at teen-age
consumers. The terms of the deal were not disclosed, but Don
Wisniewski, president of Cybiko, said that as a result AOL had
become a ``significant shareholder'' in the company. The two
companies have also agreed to work together to give users of the
Cybiko devices access to AOL features such as Instant Messaging and
other teen-oriented content. The Cybiko hand-held devices, which
were released in April 2000, sell for $129. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIFETIME INVESTS IN WOMEN.COM
</P>
<P>
   In a deal that could lengthen the life span of the beleaguered
Web site Women.com, the company announced Tuesday a joint equity
and promotions agreement with Lifetime Entertainment Services, a
joint venture owned by Hearst and Walt Disney. Lifetime
Entertainment Services said it would purchase a 4.6 percent equity
position in Women.com, while Women.com will purchase $10 million in
advertising and promotion on Lifetime Television over the next
three years. Hearst currently holds a 46 percent stake in
Women.com.
</P>
<P>
   ULCER DRUG WORKS IN TRIALS
</P>
<P>
   Human Genome Sciences said Tuesday that its drug for wound
healing had accelerated the repair of chronic venous ulcers in an
early Phase II clinical trial. The drug, repifermin, is a natural
human protein and is believed to be the first drug discovered using
genomics that has shown effectiveness in a randomized clinical
trial. In a test of 94 patients, 63 percent of patients who
received the high dose and 71 percent who got the low dose achieved
75 percent wound closure after 12 weeks, compared with 45 percent
of the patients who got a placebo. The trial was not long enough to
show a difference in complete wound closure between the drug and
placebo, the company said. Venous ulcers are skin lesions in the
legs of people whose veins cannot remove blood fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   PRI OFFERS EARNINGS WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Shares of PRI Automation plummeted $16.8125, or 39.4 percent, to
$25.875, Tuesday after the semiconductor industry supplier warned
of lower-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings. The company, which
provides automation systems and software for the semiconductor
industry, said it expects its net income for the fourth quarter,
excluding extraordinary items, to be slightly above the breakeven
point. Analysts' consensus estimate had been for earnings of 52
cents. PRI cited manufacturing, capacity and supply chain problems
as reasons for the shortfall.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
