<HEADLINE>
X-RAY TELESCOPE DISCOVERS THIRD TYPE OF BLACK HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black holes, among the most exotic and mysterious objects known
in the depths of space, have just become even more mysterious:
Astronomers reported Tuesday discovering a new type of black hole
whose existence they can't yet explain.
</P>
<P>
   Two types have been known before of these massive objects whose
gravitational fields are so intense that even light cannot escape
from their grip. They were either ``stellar,'' meaning they
contained all the matter of one star, compressed into a region just
a few miles across, or ``supermassive,'' containing the mass of
billions of stars and located in the centers of galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   The new black hole, discovered by the orbiting Chandra X-ray
Observatory, falls in between. Its mass is at least as much as 500
stars, and possibly up to 100,000, and it is located in the
vicinity of a galaxy's center, but well away from it _ 600 light
years, or about 3,600 trillion miles, from the center of the galaxy
M82.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers had previously suspected that there might be an
``intermediate'' black hole in M82, but it took the amazing power
of the Chandra telescope, designed and operated by scientists and
engineers at Harvard University and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, to prove it and to determine its approximate size.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found a black hole that sits right in the middle''
between the known types, said Martin Ward of the University of
Leicester in England, in announcing the new find at National
Aeronautics and Space Administration headquarters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new find has another odd characteristic: Its brightness
varies wildly, with small pulses every 10 minutes and with larger
variations over periods of days. This may be a sign that the black
hole is devouring stars or gas from its immediate neighborhood,
which become so hot that they emit a bright burst of radiation just
before disappearing forever into the bottomless abyss.
</P>
<P>
   Stellar-size black holes are believed to form when normal stars
that are three times the sun's mass or more collapse at the end of
their lives, when they have finished burning up all their nuclear
fuel (smaller stars, like the sun, collapse to become white dwarves
instead). But the mass of this black hole is far greater than any
star could ever be, according to accepted theories of star
formation. Either the theories are drastically wrong, or this black
hole must have formed some other way, the astronomers say _ perhaps
by the merger of a cluster of many smaller black holes.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, nobody really knows how the supermassive black holes
at galaxy centers form, although there are at least five theories
in the running. At this point, there remains a central
chicken-or-egg mystery about them: Nobody knows whether the black
holes formed first, becoming the ``seeds'' around which galaxies
condensed, or whether the galaxies formed first and somehow spawned
the black holes within them.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in the theory of black holes that restricts the
sizes they might have. It's just that nobody has yet figured out a
way to make them of such a size. ``There's no physical reason why
midsize black holes can't exist,'' said Douglas Richstone of the
University of Michigan, another member of the team that made the
new find. But, he said, this is ``the first object in this
intermediate range. It points to what will likely be a series of
discoveries of many of these objects, and that will point us toward
an understanding of the formation mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first big step in what's going to be a very
exciting period of discovery with black holes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While this black hole is away from the center of M82 _ a
relatively small and nearby galaxy _ nobody knows whether there is
also a supermassive black hole at the center of that galaxy, which
is obscured from view by a veil of gas and dust. Many astronomers
have become convinced that most, and possibly all, galaxies contain
such black holes at their cores.
</P>
<P>
   This intermediate black hole, said astronomer Andrea Preswich of
the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics in Cambridge,
Mass., ``most likely formed by a merger of black holes, or by
swallowing other stars or gas.'' On the other hand, if it formed by
the collapse of a star larger than the theories say should exist,
that too would be an exciting finding for astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the theories are wrong,'' said Preswich, ``that's extremely
interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
