<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GLENN, THE FRUSTRATION IS OVERWHELMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The game was over and it was time to get
on the bus that would take the 0-2 Patriots to the airport, where
they would depart for Foxborough in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn was one of the last players in a glum and defeated
locker room, looking over the summary package of the game and
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so frustrating,'' Glenn would say over and over. ``We had
the game won and we let it slip through our hands like this. This
one really hurts. You can't lose games like this, not when you've
beaten them for 3 1/2 quarters like that. It doesn't make any
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the least sense to Glenn was how his team could have
thought the game was over when they had a 19-7 lead in the fourth
quarter. What would give them any right to think that way or play
that way?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think it's over,'' said Glenn. ``We didn't have a
30-point lead. We weren't blowing anyone away. It was a close,
hard-fought game. We were in it from the beginning. But to think we
had it won when there's that much time left and in their home
stadium with their fans behind them? We should never act that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said coach Bill Belichick's postgame theme was that the
Patriots had to play 60 minutes of football, not 50 or 55. It was
the mantra of the evening, reflected in every sad nook and cranny
of the visitors' locker room at the Meadowlands. It was the look on
everyone's faces and the words on the tip of everyone's tongue. The
players didn't have to be told this. They knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should have to tell us that we need to play 60
minutes,'' said Glenn. ``As professional football players we should
know that. You take nothing for granted. It just seems that when we
need to get a first down so we can run out the clock and put the
game away, we can't get it. It's been that way since I've been
here. We have to put the other team away. We can't give them an
opening to get back into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who caught six passes for 81 yards, played well, but he
wished he could have sprung loose for a long gain like the 39-yard
touchdown pass he caught against Tampa Bay in the opener, or that
he could have kept his feet inbounds on the first drive of the
game, deep in Jets territory, so that the Patriots may have gone in
for a touchdown instead of settling for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets know, more than anyone, that to beat the Patriots
you don't let Glenn out of your sights. The Patriots know, more
than anyone, that to beat the Jets you don't let Wayne Chrebet out
of your reach. For 3 1/2 quarters they didn't. Chrebet saw a lot of
Ty Law and a lot of Lawyer Milloy. But when it counted, he
distanced himself from both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense did a good job against us,'' said Glenn. ``They
played a Cover-2 so they don't give up the stuff down the field.
They had Aaron Glenn on me the whole time with some help and they'd
give us the underneath stuff and that's what we took. We were
hoping to be able to get loose and break a long run after the
catch, but their defense didn't allow that. They played very tough
until the end. We had a chance to still win the game after they
took the lead, but we couldn't get the ball off. Their coverage got
tighter and they really pressured Drew (Bledsoe) at the end where
he didn't have time to find one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn made some key grabs. On third and 2 from the New England
39 late in the first quarter, he caught a 5-yard pass for a first
down to keep alive a drive that led to a 35-yard field goal by Adam
Vinatieri. On the same drive, on third and 3, he made his longest
gain of the night, 20 yards, on a throw into the flat, after which
he scooted free from Glenn and was pulled down by free safety Scott
Frost.
</P>
<P>
   He became more of a force in the second half. He had a 15-yard
gain on third and 5 to the Jets' 25, though Vinatieri subsequently
missed a 29-yard attempt. A 17-yard gain to the New England 46 on
third and 9 kept alive the drive that led to the Patriots' only
touchdown, a 6-yard toss to tight end Eric Bjornson for a 19-7 lead
with 9:56 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jets scored on their subsequent drive to pull within 5
points with 6:20 remaining, this was when the Patriots needed to
put the game away. This was where the offense needed to make plays
so the ball wouldn't go back to New York with any appreciable time
left on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our problem the whole game,'' said Glenn. ``We didn't
make any big plays. Our biggest play was _ what? _ 22 yards? They
took that away and we didn't do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets handed them their biggest gain of the night _ a 24-yard
interference call on Ray Mickens on that late drive. That penalty
moved the ball to the Patriots' 47, and a few plays later Bledsoe
kept the drive alive by sneaking for 2 yards on fourth and 1 at the
Jets 44.
</P>
<P>
   By this time the clock was running down to the three-minute
range. This is where victory should have been secured. They had
received life twice on the drive. Just one more first down and the
Patriots might have nailed it down.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 7-yard pass to Troy Brown. Chris Floyd then was
stuffed for a 1-yard loss, and the Jets called time out with 2:48
left. On third down, Bledsoe dropped back to pass, trying to play
ball control through the air, since there was no chance of doing it
on the ground. He was sacked by Shaun Ellis (one of the Jets' four
first-round draft picks this year, incidentally), a huge play at
the wrong time for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had to punt, and the Jets struck quickly for the
go-ahead score. All it took was a 44-yard pass to Dedric Ward, then
a 28-yard touchdown toss to Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis sacked Bledsoe again on second down after the Patriots got
the ball back with 1:48 remaining, and rookie John Abraham finished
the Patriots with a sack on fourth and 16.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the defense that was ultimately red-faced at the
end, but it was the offense that couldn't sustain ball control.
That ultimately comes down to the offensive line, and the running
backs not being able to handle the blitzes the Jets threw at them
late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had a chance to win the game,'' said Glenn. ``We had
plenty of time left, but we didn't make any plays and they did. I
guess they wanted it more than we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
