<HEADLINE>
TV DEBATE TO PIT RODHAM CLINTON, LAZIO FOR FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - The season's hottest Senate battle sees its first
real skirmish Wednesday night, as Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rick
Lazio meet for a televised debate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of public speaking, the First Lady has never
before engaged in this sort of candidates' forum _ a point she has
made several times lately, in a stab at lowering expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, several politicians and analysts say, it is Lazio _ the
four-term congressman from Long Island _ whose performance could
transform the tenor of the race, one way or the other, in a single
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a fairly well-formed opinion of Hillary Clinton,
but Rick Lazio remains a work-in-progress,'' Maurice Carroll, head
of the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazio's job,'' he continued, ``will be to show he can play in
the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   One well-placed Republican agreed: ``If he looks good, shows he
has some presence, shows he can talk in the same room with Hillary
for an hour and not look foolish, then he comes out ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton had a preliminary hurdle to clear Tuesday _ a
Democratic primary against Mark McMahon, an unknown Manhattan
doctor who had collected enough petition-signatures to force a
formal run-off and who hoped to sponge up anti-Hillary
protest-votes from the few who turned out for various,
better-publicized House primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady and her husband voted Tuesday morning at a school
near their new home in suburban Chappaqua. ``After all these years
of her helping me, it was a thrill,'' President Clinton said after
casting the ballot, his first as a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio did not have to contend with a Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Several top Republicans are anxious about the debate _
including, some say, Gov. George Pataki, who hand-picked Lazio to
run for the Senate seat last May after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of disappointment with Lazio,'' said a close
associate of Pataki's, who asked not to be identified. ``He's been
a lazy campaigner. He hasn't made himself a visible force. He
hasn't let people know who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has spent most of his campaign emphasizing who he is not.
One fundraising letter stated, in its entirety: ``It won't take me
six pages to convince you to send me an urgently needed
contribution for my United States Senate campaign in New York. It
will only take six words. I'm running against Hillary Rodham
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   This I'm-not-Hillary tactic catapaulted the previously obscure
Lazio to a neck-and-neck standoff with the Mrs. Clinton just a week
after entering the race. But he has not advanced an inch in the
months since.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not made much progress, either.
</P>
<P>
   Three statewide polls, taken over the past week, all show her
and Lazio essentially tied. In all three, Clinton is ahead, but by
fewer percentage-points than the statistical margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady knows she rankles many people. So, from the
outset of her campaign, she has emphasized key issues _ education,
health care, Social Security _ on which the majority of New Yorkers
agree with her positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the election is decided on the issues,'' Carroll said,
``she wins.''
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, the more genial Lazio has focused on
character. The refrain in one of his most frequently aired TV ads
goes, ``Hillary Clinton _ you just can't trust her.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lazio has watched his own nice-guy image deteriorate in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, a Zogby poll found 55 percent of likely voters had a
positive view of Lazio, while only 15 percent had a negative view.
By last week, the positives were up just slightly, to 59 percent,
but the negatives had doubled to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Mrs. Clinton is viewed positively by 53 percent,
negatively by 43 percent _ about the same as when her campaign
began in the summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Lazio has started emphasizing some issues, too.
Monday, he issued an education-reform proposal that would cost $98
billion over 10 years. Polls show voters consider education as the
most important issue _ and Clinton as better-suited to deal with
it. Lazio's proposal gives him something to tout when the topic
comes up at the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80 percent of likely voters plan to watch the debate,
according to one statewide poll. In New York, it will be broadcast
live from Buffalo at 7-8 p.m. Nationwide, MSNBC will air it from
10-11pm EST.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
