<HEADER>
A0913 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KNIGHT DISCIPLE EXPLAINS HIS FIERCE LOYALTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the late '60s, and Bobby Knight's West Point gang had
just finished a daily ritual. At noon, Knight and the young
assistant coaches from all the sports at Army met for a game of
pickup hoops, which is still remembered on campus today as being
more bloodbath than basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But upon leaving the gym this particular day, the weary group
noticed a young woman jogger huffing and puffing her way up a hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at her,'' Knight said. ``No matter how hard she tries,
she'll never lose that fat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' answered Bill Parcells, ``that's my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor basketball coach Dave Bliss told that story yesterday.
``I realized then,'' said Bliss, laughing, ``that no matter how
special Bob Knight was _ and it was obvious he was going to be
special _ he would be sticking his foot in his mouth at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, of course, Knight's mouth would end up with both
feet, both ankles, both knees, etc., firmly planted. It became part
of the legend. And his legend grew to massive status, which,
speaking of fat, included a hangover gut not so well hidden
underneath a red sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, count me among the media masses who said, ``It's about
time,'' when Indiana University ended the 29-year Knight reign this
week. The Ayatollah of college basketball had been ousted. He would
bully no more athletic department secretaries in Bloomington.
</P>
<P>
   The tough side of Knight was fine. Even commendable. Blasting
away at the media, his bosses, his players _ I've got no problem
with that. But he also picked on people who couldn't fight back _
secretaries, NCAA tournament volunteers, bus drivers, and anyone
else who happened to be in his line of fire on a particular day.
I've got no use for people like that.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there is obviously another side of Knight, the side
that inspires such long-term loyalty and devotion from a wide
variety of people who have crossed paths, and maybe swords, with
Knight over the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Among that group is Knight's old basketball-at-noon West Point
gang. He was head coach of his sport, but this bunch came from all
over campus. Parcells, Al Groh (now the coach of the Jets), Ken
Hatfield, and John Mackovic from the football staff. The late
Arthur Ashe from tennis. Bliss and Bob Weltlich were Knight
assistants in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   When Bliss says, ``Bob Knight is like my older brother, which
means our friendship is unconditional,'' he is sounding an echo
from prominent Knight disciples around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't always agree with Bob or with his actions, but I love
him,'' Bliss said.
</P>
<P>
   Next question: ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss told of a dinner he attended this summer in Indiana that]
was a wrapup for Knight's charity golf tournament. At that dinner
an Army general spoke of his basketball-playing days under Knight
at West Point. Addressing the current Indiana players who were in
attendance, the general said, ``I knew Bobby Knight before he
mellowed,'' a line that brought down the house.
</P>
<P>
   But then he added, ``I left West Point, and went to Vietnam and
I know I saved lives on the battlefield because of the discipline I
learned under Bob Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bliss, that's the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than my parents, Bob had the biggest impact on my life
because he made me realize things about myself that I didn't know,
and would probably have never found out,'' he said. ``Working for
him \Rat both Army and Indiana\S was the hardest thing I've ever
done, and also the best thing I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the ``abuse'' carried over to his assistants. ``Maybe more
so than the players,'' Bliss said. ``But if you accept and learn
from it, you know it's his way of showing tough love. And you also
know you have a fiercely loyal friend for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there a fine line, however, between tough love and someone
who has a problem with anger management? And that is, don't you
think, Knight's problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question it is, and he knows it as well as we know
it,'' Bliss said. ``The day isn't long enough for me to list my
sins, but his anger is Bob's sin. You can't just take some of Bob
Knight, you have to take all of Bob Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed, and he hasn't. I'm not so sure either one
is wrong. There was a time when every coach wanted to be the strict
disciplinarian. Truthfully, every coach wants that right now. But
Bob is from another era and this is a different era, whether we
like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Indiana University found out, defending his decisions and
his actions finally reached a point where that relationship had to
end. Probably, this ending was best for both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   What the future now holds for Knight is uncertain, but a devoted
friend like Bliss doesn't concern himself with where that next
basketball job might be. ``I don't want his story to end with the
image of the last few days,'' Bliss said. ``Bob brought much of
this on himself, but he's also better than this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patton and MacArthur also had their names soiled a bit late in
their Army careers, but over the years, their images have evolved
the right way. I hope Bob's legacy evolves that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, ``General'' Knight would be highly pleased to join
such esteemed company. \Ntagtop:Randy Galloway's ``Sports at Six''
can be heard weeknights, 6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
\Ntagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
