</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSCHWITZ-SYNAGOGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNAGOGUE NEAR INFAMOUS NAZI DEATH CAMP REOPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSWIECIM, Poland -- Elinoar Paleiov was four years old when she
fled Poland just weeks before the outbreak of World War II. This
week, she came back to her hometown, a place known to most of the
world as Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Now an Israeli citizen, Paleiov was one of about 100 Jews who
went to Oswiecim, where the Auschwitz death camp was located, to
attend the rededication of the only synagogue in the city to
survive World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said reopening a synagogue just 1.9 miles from the
infamous Nazi concentration camp was an important step in reviving
Jewish culture in Oswiecim. The city, which once boasted a thriving
Jewish majority, became synonymous with the holocaust, and today
there are no Jews among its 50,000 people. The last Jewish
resident, Eimelech Korneich, died in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a vibrant symbol of life regenerated and of the
angel of death that passed over here,'' said Fred Schwartz,
President of the New York-based Auschwitz Jewish Center Foundation.
The foundation raised $10 million to renovate and reopen the Chevra
Lomdei Mishnayot synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Like Paleiov, several of those at Tuesday's solemn rededication
ceremony were natives of Oswiecim who had been back for more than
60 years. Paleiov, now 65, fled Poland with her brother and father
in August 1939. The family made its way to Israel by way of Russia,
Iran, and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   As she explored her childhood home this week for the first time
in 61 years, she got a pleasant surprise. Tereza Miton was waiting
for her and gave her an envelope filled with prewar photographs of
Paleiov's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother worked as a housekeeper for your family, and
she wanted you to have these,'' Miton, 30, said. ``I have been
saving them for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' Paleiov said, choking back tears.
``You don't know what this means to me. When we left we had no
pictures of our family. And to think that somebody thought to save
these.''
</P>
<P>
   Many said they hoped such small gestures of reconciliation would
become commonplace as the city rediscovers its heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 50 years of communism the Jewish past and present were
forgotten,'' said Tomac Kuncewicz, who will administer the
synagogue and an adjacent Jewish historical center. ``But this is
part of Polish history and we need to understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuncewicz, 28, is a Catholic who earned a masters degree in
Jewish Studies at Brandeis University outside Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue was the only one of 12 in Oswiecim that the
occupying German army didn't level. They defaced it and used it to
store munitions.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue was briefly revived after World War II but was
abandoned when most Jews left communist Poland. Authorities used
the building as a carpet warehouse and it fell into disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Polish government returned the synagogue to the
Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dignitaries on hand was Prince El Hassan bin Talal of
Jordan, brother of the late King Hussein, and representatives of
the United States, Israel, Poland, and the Roman Catholic Church.
Hassan joined Jewish leaders in nailing a traditional mezuza prayer
scroll to the door frame of the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our commitment is the reconciliation between the adherence to
our faith and respect for what's human and sacred in each of us,''
Hassan said.
</P>
<P>
   Polish officials said they hoped the synagogue's renewal would
bring Jews and Poles closer together and help lessen some of the
stigma attached to the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a place that is symbol of our times. It could become
a place of reconciliation,'' said Mayor Jozef Krawczyk. ``World War
II was a tragedy for both Jews and Poles.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 6 million Poles, including 3 million Jews _ 91 percent of
the prewar Jewish population _ died at the hands of the Nazis. At
the Auschwitz death camp alone, some 1.5 million people, most of
them Jews, were systematically murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surviving Jews eventually left for Israel, the US
and other countries, and only about 20,000 live in Poland today.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the synagogue, the Auschwitz Jewish Center also
opened Tuesday with exhibits on prewar Jewish life, a library and
archives, conference rooms, and a kosher cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will serve the needs of Jewish visitors who want to meet,
pray, reflect and feel safe,'' said Nadine Greenfield, a native of
Boston and project manager for the Auschwitz Jewish Center
Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
