<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-AND-FIELD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET JONES' DRIVE FOR FIVE BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Sport: Track and field
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gold medals at stake: 46 (24 men, 22 women) Events: Men will
compete in 100 meters; 200; 400; 800; 1,500; 5,000; 10,000;
marathon; 110 hurdles; 400 hurdles; 4x100 relay; 4x400 relay; high
jump; pole vault; long jump; triple jump; shot put; discus;
javelin; hammer; and decathlon. Women also compete in those events,
except they have 100-meter hurdles instead of 110 and the
heptathlon instead of the decathlon. The men also have the
3,000-meter steeplechase and the 20-kilometer and 50K walks, and
the women have a 10K walk. Venue: Sydney Olympic Stadium
Competition dates: Sept. 22-25, Sept. 27-Oct. 1 Year introduced:
1896 History: The first Olympic event in ancient times, circa 776
B.C., was a footrace. When the Games were revived in 1896, track
and field reassumed its preeminent place on the Olympic card.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's history, in many ways, is the saga of the Olympics.
On the ovals of the world's great Olympic stadiums, legends were
born, through the feats of Jesse Owens, Paavo Nurmi, Carl Lewis,
Florence Griffith Joyner, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful nation in track and field has been the
United States, with 299 gold medals and 694 overall. The former
Soviet Union is a distant second in the gold-medal count with 71
and has 214 medals overall. Third place, interestingly, is Finland
with 48 golds. Past heroes: Where to begin? How's about Carl Lewis,
Jesse Owens, Paavo Nurmi, Bob Beamon, Al Oerter, Emil Zatopek,
Lasse Viren, Jackie Joyner-Kersee, Heike Drechsler, Wilma Rudolph,
Betty Cuthbert, Abebe Bikila, Edwin Moses and many, many others.
1996 medalists: U.S. gold medalists included Michael Johnson, 200
and 400; Allen Johnson, 110 hurdles; Derrick Adkins, 400 hurdles;
men's 4x400 relay; Charles Austin, high jump; Carl Lewis, long
jump; Kenny Harrison, triple jump; Randy Barnes, shot put; Dan
O'Brien, decathlon; Gail Devers, women's 100; and the women's 4x100
and 4x400 relays. It's going to be a tough act to follow. Rule
book: New events for 2000 include the women's hammer throw and the
immensely popular (don't ask why) women's pole vault. Best of the
Yanks: Marion Jones, who will try to capture gold medals in the
women's 100, 200, long jump and both relays; Michael Johnson in the
men's 400; Maurice Greene, men's 100; Charles Austin, men's high
jump; Allen Johnson and Gail Devers in their high hurdles; and
Stacy Dragila, women's pole vault. Rest of the blokes: Australian
Cathy Freeman in the women's 400; Gabriela Szabo, Romania, women's
5,000; Haile Gebrselassie, Ethiopia, men's 10,000; Ivan Pedroso,
Cuba, men's long jump; and Tomas Dvorak, Czech Republic, decathlon.
U.S. medal chances: Without benefit of the adoring home crowd, it's
going to be very, very difficult to match the 13-gold-medal
performance of Atlanta. The Americans won 22 medals overall. In
Sydney, the number could dip below 15. Et cetera: If you want the
name of a possible Marion Jones spoiler, remember Fiona May of
Italy in the long jump. ... TCU ex Jon Drummond will run the 100
and probably the 4x100 relay. ... The pride of Keller, Bubba
Thornton, also known as head coach of the University of Texas men's
track program, is one of Team USA's assistant coaches. ... U.S.
discus thrower Adam Setliff calls California home but graduated
from L.D. Bell High School in Hurst. Setliff has been hot and could
medal in Sydney. ... Certain headline for next week: ``Visiting
track athletes complain about constant winds at Olympic Stadium''
... Californian Adam Nelson is throwing the shot so well this year
_ 72 feet plus _ that Jones' husband, the scowling C.J. Hunter,
injured and scratched from the Games, likely will not be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Let Jones' Drive for Five begin Michael Johnson captured hearts
in Atlanta by dashing to a world record and three gold medals in a
pair of golden slippers.
</P>
<P>
   But how about what Marion Jones is after _ a whole golden
necklace?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this will be an odd Olympics for Johnson, the epicenter
of all things electric and golden four years ago. Having seen his
workload diminished to one individual event, the 400 meters,
Johnson will not be nearly as visible, nor seem as dominating, as
he did in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The torch now passes to Jones, the wonder woman who will attempt
to win gold medals in the 100, 200, long jump and both relays.
</P>
<P>
   Look for her now at your neighborhood grocer checkout stand.
Jones' million-dollar smile radiates from the cover of various
national magazines this week. To a lesser person, this would be
some awfully heavy baggage to tote.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones is so even-tempered, so unflappably confident, she has
shrugged off the pre-Olympic hype about her five-medal quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a dollar for every time someone has asked me about
that,'' Jones sighed at the Olympic trials, ``I'd be a rich person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops. Wrong choice of words, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Mrs. Jones really is rich, even by track and
field's occasionally nouveau riche standards. Her pleasant face
beams back not just from magazine covers, but billboards. The Nike
TV spots showing just part of her, playing the soulful DJ Mrs.
Jones, has been a marketing hit.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones has an Achilles' heel, it could be the long jump. It's
her weakest event. Even Marion admits that. Her problem is one of
technique and timing and, in the long jump's case, maybe even being
too fast for her own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've decided I'm not even going to talk about that anymore,''
Jones said about the relentless media critiquing of her jumping
technique. ``People are going to criticize my jumping even if I win
the gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson four years ago, Jones is in for a busy Olympics.
Her only respite figures to be in the preliminary rounds of the
relays, in which Jones is expected to be spelled by other U.S.
runners.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
