<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: NO RELIEF IN IRISH INFLATION
</P>
<P>
   The inflation rate in Ireland remained at 6.2 percent in August,
the highest in the European Union, according to figures released by
the Central Statistics Office. The government said the rate would
moderate by the end of the year, but Irish economists predicted
that the worldwide increase in oil prices would push inflation up
to 7 percent within the next few months. In response to the
figures, three of Ireland's largest trade unions called for a
renegotiation of the national wage agreement, implemented when
inflation ran at 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   IRISH PILOTS WANT MORE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Pilots in Aer Lingus, the Irish airline, demanded pay increases
that would make their salaries comparable with pilots in other
airlines that belong to the One World Alliance, of which Aer Lingus
is a member. In the case of top-earning pilots, who currently make
87,000 Irish pounds ($95,000) a year, the demands called for a 100
percent increase, to more than 160,000 Irish pounds ($190,000). The
Irish Airline Pilots' Association said that its members share work
with employees of other airlines, and that it had received
complaints that Aer Lingus salaries were lowering the industry
average.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE DEAL FOR INFOSTRADA
</P>
<P>
   The British mobile phone company Vodafone AirTouch is talking to
Wind SpA about buying Infostrada, an Italian fixed-line phone
company that Vodafone inherited as part of its purchase of
Germany's Mannesmann. Wind's bid of 11.5 billion euros, or about
$9.7 billion, exceeded a 9 billion euro offer from Albacom, a
business phone consortium that is 23 percent owned by British
Telecommunications. Specializing in wireless, fixed-line and
Internet operations, Wind is controlled by the Italian state-owned
electricity utility Enel and by France Telecom. Should the sale not
go through, Vodafone could revert to its original plan of selling a
49 percent stake of Infostrada through a share offering.
</P>
<P>
   DE BEERS REASSURES RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Top executives from De Beers, the supplier of half the world's
rough cut diamonds, met with Russian executives and government
officials Tuesday in Moscow to persuade them that its new company
strategy would not harm the diamond trade in Russia, the world's
second-largest producer of diamonds. Russia's monopoly producer,
Alrosa, said it would continue to work with De Beers and expected
to conclude a new contract before the current one expires late next
year. That was is in contrast to comments by Russian government
officials in July that Russia may change its relations with the
South Africa-based producer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL'S INFLATION EASES
</P>
<P>
   The inflation rate in Brazil fell in August, reassuring
investors that a spike in consumer prices the month before had
faded. The benchmark IPCA inflation index rose 1.31 percent in
August, down from a 1.61 percent increase in July, as the effects
of government-regulated increases in electricity, telephone and
gasoline prices dissipated. Gasoline prices made the largest
contribution to August inflation, rising 7.54 percent. For the
first eight months of the year, the Brazilian inflation rate was
4.6 percent. The Brazilian government's goal is to keep the rate
from exceeding 6 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment in China fell nearly 8 percent to $22.79
billion in the first eight months of the year compared with the
same period a year earlier, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation said. But it said new contracts for investment
not yet delivered rose 31.27 percent to $33.25 billion as foreign
companies position themselves for what is expected to be a
friendlier business climate after China joins the World Trade
Organization. The country's WTO membership is expected to be
finalized this year.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA INTERNET MERGER
</P>
<P>
   China's Nasdaq-listed Sohu.com Inc. has reached a preliminary
agreement to acquire rival ChinaRen.com, in what would be the first
major merger of an expected consolidation of China's fledgling
Internet industry. Neither company is making money and Sohu.com's
share price plunged shortly after it sold stock to the public for
$13 a share in July. The company's stock now trades at about half
that price.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION RECALL
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric Corp. said it will recall two defective
color TV models that could overheat and catch fire, a problem the
company has known about for at least eight years. The sets were
marketed only in Japan. The company had not previously recalled the
TVs because the defect is not that serious, officials said. It
decided to do so now because of a recent defect cover-up by the
related Mitsubishi Motors Corp. &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
