<HEADLINE>
BRITISH WRESTLE WITH BLOCKADE-INDUCED FUEL PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Nearly all gasoline pumps in London were dry Tuesday
night, and the rest of Britain could be dry by Thursday as panicky
motorists continued their rush on the nation's petrol stations and
an emboldened group of protesters stepped up their blockades of
British oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The protests, inspired by more militant outbursts in France last
week and reflecting similar unrest spreading across Europe, had
affected all nine of Britain's oil refineries. The resulting panic
emptied most of the nation's 13,000 gas stations by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the biggest crisis since his Labor Party won a landslide
election in May 1997, British Prime Minister Tony Blair vowed not
to lower the fuel tax that makes British gas prices, at nearly $5 a
gallon, the most expensive in Europe. Instead, a defiant Blair
ordered the oil companies to defy the demonstrators at the refinery
gates, and instructed police to make sure there was no intimidation
of drivers ferrying gas to gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legitimate protest is one thing. Trying to bring the country
to a halt is another,'' said Blair, emerging from 10 Downing St.
after daylong meetings to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As darkness fell, some trucks moved out of the refineries.
Facing the most serious challenge to his authority, Blair vowed
that things would be back to normal in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Truck drivers for the oil companies have expressed solidarity
with the demonstrators, many of them truckers and farmers, while
the oil companies had suggested they did not want to risk injury to
their drivers by defying the blockades. Angry British government
officials privately accused the oil companies of not doing enough
to force its drivers to make deliveries, claiming the oil firms had
a financial incentive to let pressure build for a tax cut, as lower
fuel prices would lead to more people buying more gas.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Britain, meanwhile, there were signs of panic, chaos
and what Bill Morris, head of the transporation workers union, who
called for an end to the blockades, described as anarchy.
Increasingly frustrated motorists waited for hours in long lines to
buy gas. The panic even spread to supermarkets, where panicky
shoppers loaded up on groceries, fearing that distributors would
soon run out of gas and be unable to deliver food. Some hospitals
cancelled operations, and the health minister, Alan Milburn, warned
that some people would die unless the crisis was resolved by
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Blair and his Cabinet huddled at 10 Downing St., trying to
forge a strategy to end the crisis, tension mounted among ordinary
Britons. At an Esso station in Highgate, in North London, a
fistfight broke out when one motorist accused another of cutting in
line by approaching on foot to fill a cannister.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy,'' said Mohammed Aziz, an engineer, as he sat in
the long line at the Esso station. ``People are panicking, and now,
you see, some are even fighting over petrol.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said he left work early to fill his tank after hearing news
reports suggest that London would soon be dry. He said he had
sympathy for the demonstrators who were precipitating the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pay more for petrol than anyone in Europe,'' he said. ``The
government should listen to the people and lower the fuel tax.''
</P>
<P>
   But speaking to the annual conference of British trade unions in
Glasgow, Gordon Brown, chancellor of the Exchequer, ruled out any
chance of the government lowering the tax. Sounding like Jimmy
Stewart's banker character George Bailey in ``It's a Wonderful
Life,'' Brown tried to calm those who were making a run, in this
case on gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   He said the money raised through the fuel tax, some $54 billion
last year, is used to pay for the national health service and
education. For some two decades, Britain's income tax rates have
been among the lowest in the 15-member European Union, as the
British treasury has instead relied on indirect taxation, such as
the fuel tax, to raise money for essential services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not make tax policy this afternoon because of
blockades this morning,'' a defiant Brown declared.
</P>
<P>
   But along the picket lines, the demonstrators accused the
government of backing itself into a corner by adopting such a hard
line and by not acknowledging that the fuel tax disproportionately
hurts some industries, such as trucking, which cannot reduce their
use of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the picket line at the Stanlow oil refinery in
Cheshire in northwest England, protest leader Keith Thompson
accused the government of being ``totally out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about a few farmers and truckers looking for
tax relief. This is about a nation being ripped off by Tony Blair's
New Britain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the disruption and fuel shortages were most acute in
Britain, the popular anger over high fuel prices has spread across
Europe. In Germany, the government has taken a hard line similar to
Blair's, saying it will not bargain with demonstrators. In Ireland,
Prime Minister Bertie Ahern was scheduled to meet with the
association representing the nation's trucking industry, who have
vowed to bring the country to a standstill unless the government,
which has registered record surpluses in recent years, cuts the
fuel tax. Gerry McMahon, president of the Irish Road Haulage
Association, said his drivers wanted a 20 percent cut in the tax
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish drivers are threatening similar action, and protests in
Belgium, the Netherlands and Norway have disrupted those countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is most serious here in Britain, where a loose
federation of farmers, truckers and other small business people who
accuse the government of ignoring their concerns has seized upon an
issue that has struck an uncharacteristic chord with a British
population that is traditionally hostile to strikes and the
inconvenience that comes with them.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative government of Margaret Thatcher largely
succeeded in breaking the strength of British labor unions in the
1980s, and there is little British appetite for the sort of street
protests that are a regular feature of life in France, where there
is widespread support for as many as 10,000 strikes and
demonstrations a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
