A0928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-MCNABB13-COX     09-12 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MCNABB13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small school has a big day with Gore
 &HT;    By Rick McCrabb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Ohio _ Blood pressures returned to normal at
Middletown High
</P>
<P>
   School a few minutes before 1 o'clock Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the motorcade carrying Vice President and Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore and his running mate Sen. Joe
Lieberman pulled out of the school parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   For a school that has been in session for less than two weeks,
MHS passed its
</P>
<P>
   biggest test of the year Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big day for Middletown,'' said Principal Gary
Perkins, who credited his assistant principals, faculty and staff
for their extra effort
</P>
<P>
   the last few days. ``There is a certain sense of relief, and at
the same time, a true sense of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief that nothing happened to Gore and Lieberman; pride in the
way the
</P>
<P>
   students responded to the politicians.
</P>
<P>
   School officials learned late last week that Gore and Lieberman
planned to
</P>
<P>
   stop at the high school during their campaign swing - ``On the
Road to an A+
</P>
<P>
   Education'' - through southwestern Ohio. Sandwiched between
visits to
</P>
<P>
   Franklin High School and Cincinnati State Technical and
Community College,
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman spent about two hours at MHS.
</P>
<P>
   While the actual event lasted only a short time, the planning
and the hype
</P>
<P>
   went on for days.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins and the vice president's advance team - a lot of guys
who rarely, if
</P>
<P>
   ever, smile - spent the weekend at the high school, canvassing
the building
</P>
<P>
   for possible trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   They tapped the phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   They gave school officials a bomb threat plan.
</P>
<P>
   They locked the entrance to the roof.
</P>
<P>
   They inspected the drainage area by the nearby practice football
field.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs searched the hallways for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   They changed plans ``minute-by-minute,'' according to Renee
Martin, an office
</P>
<P>
   secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   More Secret Service agents, members of the Dayton SWAT team
perched on the high school roof, all available Middletown police
officers in uniform and
</P>
<P>
   officers from the Ohio Highway Patrol parked at about every
street corner.
</P>
<P>
   All for Gore and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives me a whole new appreciation of the Secret Service
and the police departments,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin described the last few days as ``very interesting and
very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added with a smile: ``I'm glad it's over. I never knew
there were so
</P>
<P>
   many Secret Service agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Martin, who said she worked ``several'' hours of
overtime Monday
</P>
<P>
   and Tuesday preparing for the politicians' visit, never got a
glimpse of Gore. Whenever she thought she was in the perfect
picture-taking or hand-shaking position, Gore went the opposite
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of frustrating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cieara Pope and Amanda Downey, two of the more than 1,700 MHS
students who attended the rally in Paul Walker Gymnasium, said they
were impressed by
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a heck of a guy,'' Pope said of Gore. ``He can get some
good stuff for
</P>
<P>
   us.''
</P>
<P>
   Downey added: ``He really cares about us. I hope he gets it (the
presidency).''
</P>
<P>
   The two freshmen said they were most impressed by two of Gore's
presidential
</P>
<P>
   promises: increasing minimum wage by $1 an hour and hiring more
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
