<SLUG> BC-TUFTS-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUFTS PRESIDENT SAYS HE'LL STEP DOWN BY 2002 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After eight years of aggressively raising money to catch up to
the richer endowments of other colleges, Tufts University president
John DiBiaggio said Tuesday he would step down by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   As an academic leader, DiBiaggio was very much a businessman. He
sought to shore up Tufts' competitive advantage among top colleges
by securing donations to support the university's strengths: Funds
for buildings and programs in medicine, international relations,
and civic education, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived on the Medford, Mass. campus in 1992, Tufts was
dipping into reserves to meet its budget. The endowment stood at
about $180 million _ relatively small for a school that said it
offered a top education and charged a high tuition.
</P>
<P>
   DiBiaggio _ formerly president of Michigan State University,
where he had battled trustees for authority over the sports program
_ took to fundraising with similar gusto.
</P>
<P>
   The school's endowment has tripled to nearly $600 million,
boosted by the fund-raising campaign that DiBiaggio will wrap up
over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   DiBiaggio said Tufts was still behind other colleges that
courted donors more steadily during the last century. But he said
he was satisfied with the pace of fundraising today, though he said
he wished more alumni gave to the school; the current rate stands
at about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to convince people they should give even a modest, small
amount _ even those are important because they develop a habit of
giving,'' DiBiaggio said Tuesday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Under DiBiaggio, Tufts was regularly rated as one of the top 30
universities in the nation, and he tried to develop niches for the
campus to stand out among that field.
</P>
<P>
   His proudest accomplishment, he said Tuesday, was the creation
this year of a College of Citizenship and Public Learning. The
effort is aimed at adding ``an appreciation of the needs of
people'' across the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students shouldn't graduate with just the ability to compete
for jobs, but with the attributes of good citizenship,'' DiBiaggio
said. ``Every student in every course is reminded of their
responsibility to society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
