<HEADER>
A0936 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BISHER-KNIGHT0913-COX     09-12 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHER-KNIGHT0913-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Knight mask his good side, stirringly
</P>
<P>
   ByI'll put it this way to start: I'd like to like Bob Knight,
the basketball coach. I'd like to see in him a person I could
admire, and a percentage of him I can. There is a good side to him.
Trouble is, he masks it so stirringly.
</P>
<P>
   He won't tolerate the kind of miscreant players that other
coaches will play as long as they can keep them out of jail. He
believes in education and graduation. He is high on principle but
low on tolerance. He has a faction of unwavering supporters, an
army of them on the Indiana campus. Other coaches respect him on
the court, but he gives them grounds to want to shut him up.
</P>
<P>
   A coach I talked with the other day said, ``We were friends for
a long time, but I tell you, he can be a maniac.''
</P>
<P>
   Peculiar that he and Woody Hayes should have happened upon the
same campus. Knight was the ``sixth man'' on Fred Taylor's greatest
Ohio State team, of the Jerry Lucas and John Havlicek vintage,
while Woodrow the Great rode high on the football field. Just as
peculiarly, both careers jolted to a similar halt.
</P>
<P>
   There was a difference in response. Hayes was capable of
remorse. Knight, sadly, isn't, as represented by his performance on
television last evening. Hayes accepted his downfall with grace and
was a welcome figure on campus the rest of his life, maintained an
office there within view of the stadium where he had once been king
of all he surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Knight is not content to go quietly. He will fan the flame again
tonight, when he holds an open house with members of the student
body. They have already given him life with a protest march,
directed at the president, Myles Brand, who may rue the day he ever
accepted the chair.
</P>
<P>
   They resurrected an outdated expression of student disdain
usually reserved for football coaches. They burned in effigy the
freshman enrollee who triggered the whole mess, when he hailed The
General with, ``Hey, what's up, Knight?'' I'm certain it was not a
question to which he expected an answer, nor the reaction that he
got. He must surely find another place for his college education,
and I'm not sure the University of Bangkok would be far enough.
</P>
<P>
   How did it come about that the encounter went public? Why was it
three years later that Neil Reed, the disgruntled former player,
decided to level his blast at Knight? How do films of such an
incident get taken and conveniently go on display? It gives a
smithereen of logic to what Alan Henderson, the Hawks forward,
contends, that ``he was set up.''
</P>
<P>
   I offer no defense for Knight, I, one who once wrote I would not
like one of my sons to play for him. My first contact with him
impressed me, although it was by mail. Several seasons ago, I would
receive an annual letter from this young man who coached at West
Point. It was a polite request for the names of basketball
prospects in the state who might have the stuff to make it at the
Military Academy. I don't know that our agents ever helped him, but
we tried.
</P>
<P>
   Knight wants to coach again, but who would take a chance with
him, unless it's an obscure college willing to take the risk to get
attention? He does little to impress future employers by directing
a mass desertion of players he has recruited at Indiana. On the
other hand, he might take the nucleus of a good team with him, if
the attitude of A.J. Moye is widespread, who said, ``I'd travel the
world a million times to play for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
