r f BC-BOBBIN0913-COX     09-12 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOBBIN0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bobbin show focused south of the border
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The theme song of this year's Bobbin Americas trade
show could be ``South of the Border,'' as American apparel and
footwear manufacturers hurry to set up production operations in the
Caribbean and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons for the rush _ a Caribbean trade
partnership act and pending changes in import barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean Basin Trade Partnership Act becomes effective Oct.
1. This law will enable clothing makers to move production offshore
and slash labor and overhead costs while avoiding import fees on
the returning goods, said Roy Bowen, president of the Georgia
Textile Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   But the real task is preparing for changes in World Trade
Organization import barriers that will occur in January 2005. After
that, cheap-labor countries like China will be able to pour apparel
products into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-based companies have four years to find offshore
manufacturing partners and transform into sophisticated,
computer-savvy contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies need new choices, sources and alliances to permit
them to get the product made and back into the U.S. to sell at the
lowest possible cost,'' said Sergio Cruz, an analyst with Kurt
Salmon Associates. . . . At this show, people will look for
manufacturing relationships as much as for new equipment and
software.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a big change for little shops in countries such as
Jamaica and Costa Rica. They've been accustomed to receiving cut
pattern pieces from U.S. companies and simply sewing the cuff to
the sleeve. Now, those companies expect their contractors to
provide a complete package of services _ acquire the fabric, cut
and sew it, trim and zip it, label it and ship it.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica already is geared up to do this _ and to reap the
economic rewards _ said export promoters Irene Gago and Max Garcia,
who represent the country's Foreign Trade Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, fruit and coffee were her country's chief exports
to the United States, she said. Now, it's electronic components and
apparel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we came to the Bobbin show representing six of our
companies (that want U.S. business). This year, we represent 12,''
said Gago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
