<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0940 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEFENSE09     09-12 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEFENSE0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons considering simplifying defense that ranks last in
league
 &HT;    ``We beat a team that wasn't ready to play.'' - - Brian Griese
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Atlanta and Denver won't play again, barring a Super
Bowl rematch. So the Falcons won't be able to turn the words of the
Broncos' young quarterback against him.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons defense, however, might end up owing Brian Griese a
thank you. The way the Broncos dismantled the Falcons 42-14 will
bring about welcome change.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, the Falcons' defense is about to get simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Denver (1-1) gained 407 yards against Atlanta and scored on its
first seven possessions. The Falcons (1-1) are giving up 373 yards
a game, 26th in the league. Injuries to the defensive line and
linebackers have hurt, but the Falcons also have made it worse for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta acquired cornerback Ashley Ambrose in the offseason,
emboldening defensive coordinator Rich Brooks to add blitz
packages, line stunts and coverage changes, because Ambrose and
cornerback Ray Buchanan both would play man coverage. But the
defensive changes appear to be fooling the Falcons more than the
opponents. Ambrose said after the Denver game that everybody on
defense needed to ``get on the same page.'' ``A lot of us are
thinking too much instead of playing,'' free safety Ronnie Bradford
said. ``I think one of the most glaring things is it seems like
we're adjusting a lot to what (offenses) are doing instead of
playing our stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Patrick Kerney is ready for a change: ``You can
say it was only preseason, but when we were going first team
against first team playing mostly straight-up base defenses, I
thought we were whipping guys pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the stunting is opening up holes,'' Kerney said. ``I'd
have no problems going back and simplifying things, just straight
rushes, and playing your gap on the runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks will comply. ``You've got to simplify it,'' he said.
``That means (opposing offensive coordinators) will be able to get
a better bead on you, but at least you don't beat yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe instead of going in (to a game) with three or four
fronts, maybe go in with two. Instead of four or five zone
(blitzes), maybe go in with two _ whatever we can handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves said the temptation to question the team's
talent should be tempered by the rash of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very unfair to judge the defensive line ... when
you have as many things that have happened to it, moving people
around,'' Reeves said. ``I would wait to make an observation.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks will wait no longer to get back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not making plays anywhere,'' he said. ``Therefore ...
I've got to make sure we play better. The disturbing thing is we've
got mistakes being made by players who haven't made them in the
past when we haven't had as many ... packages.''
</P>
<P>
   So there will be fewer packages, and, it is hoped, fewer
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some good players,'' Bradford said. ``I think ... we
just got to go out and play regardless of ... where they're lining
up. Hopefully, when this thing kicks off Sunday at Carolina, we'll
be able to play full speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
