A0944 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-12 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS ROOKIE LOOKS LIKE A SHOVER AND A FIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Stars rookie looks like a shover and a fighter 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ For those wondering if the Stars will be tough
enough this season, I have a name for you.
</P>
<P>
   John Erskine.
</P>
<P>
   Six-foot-four. Just a shade under 220 pounds but still a growing
boy. Nasty as a Texas summer. Fists as gnarly and big as pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   One word jumped out of the scouting report provided by a
high-ranking Stars official yesterday at training camp: ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   My kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if he can just make the team.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has raged almost from the moment Shane Churla dropped
his gloves for the last time and was handed a one-way bus ticket
out of town when the Stars actually started becoming good a few
years ago. Does this team need an enforcer?
</P>
<P>
   Those who say ``no'' point righteously to the final results the
past two years, when the Stars have basically gone without one and
made two trips to the Stanley Cup Finals. Try arguing with that.
</P>
<P>
   Those who say ``yes'' _ me, you, and most everybody else who
doesn't mind a little blood on the ice once in a while as long as
it doesn't belong to us _ still remember Anaheim's Ruslan Salei
running Mike Modano headfirst into the boards early last season and
the one Stars player who went after him in a berserk rage.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   That just won't do.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can the Stars afford for it to be Derian Hatcher, as ably as
the captain might fill that retaliatory role. They can't afford to
have their best defenseman being hit with game misconducts for
fighting unless he has no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody, however, needs to be able to deliver a message _ and
an effective right cross _ when the opposing team insists on taking
repeated and blatant cheap shots at Modano, or Hull, or Joe
Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at what San Jose is doing, bringing in a few more
retards there, that might be a route we have to go,'' agreed former
defenseman Craig Ludwig, an assistant coach for the Stars' top farm
team, the Utah Grizzlies, this season.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock had hoped Dave Manson would return to
provide that kind of physical presence. Manson could also anchor
the third defensive pair. But scratch that plan. The veteran got a
better offer from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the players who finished the season with us and aren't
with us now were some of our more physical players,'' general
manager Bob Gainey conceded. ``Manson, \RScott\S Thornton, even
\RGuy\S Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our preference would be to have a team toughness, a grain of
toughness running through our team so that we don't load it all on
one or two people to carry the burden.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' general philosophy since Hitchcock became coach has
been that if a player can't contribute on the ice as a player,
there's no place for him on the team. That hasn't changed, but I
sense a slight lessening in the rigidity of that position at this
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has moved back to more physical play, and fighting
sometimes comes as a result of the physical play,'' Hitchcock said.
``We're definitely going to have to have a physical sense to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's basically defined the role of his sixth
defenseman as a physical one with hopes that either the 20-year-old
Erskine or 6-5, 225-pound Sami Helenius, obtained from Colorado in
the off-season, can step up and fill it.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock sees a lot of Hatcher in the raw-boned Erskine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some skill that's in line with Derian,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Derian played for us at 19. This guy's 20. He'll play in
eight or nine \Rexhibition\S games, and I suspect that's how many
fights he'll have.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because they don't know him in the NHL yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Ontario Hockey League, where he's played the last
couple of years, no one even comes near him anymore,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year in the OHL, I was trying to make a name for
myself, and I just went out there and fought everyone,'' Erskine
said. ``As time went on, I started to play hockey. I fight when I
have to, but I don't go looking for fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, on the surface he sounds perfectly sane. Don't be fooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he snaps,'' one team scout said, ``you don't want to be
around. He destroyed everybody in that league a couple of years
ago. Now, nobody challenges him.''
</P>
<P>
   Goes to show that kids really are getting smarter these days.
</P>
<P>
   Having established his reputation, Erskine proceeded to settle
down and earn OHL defenseman-of-the-year honors last season. Good
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Erskine is going to wind up playing for the Stars and soon. The
only question is whether he'll break camp with them or get more
seasoning under Ludwig with the Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called enforcers have to play now, too,'' Ludwig
pointed out. ``Used to be, you'd pay somebody a couple of hundred
grand a year, and all they did was fight. Now, they've got to be
able to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe Stars\S play more of a style that if somebody takes a
run at one our guys, our answer to is capitalize on the power play
and put the puck in the net. But we don't back down from anything
either.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when push comes to shove, it's always comforting to
have a guy around who has experience at being the shover, rather
than the shovee. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
