<SLUG> BC-OCTOGENS-WED13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After years of separation, romance blooms at reunion of former
neighbors and leads to octogenarian marriage
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR _ On a beautiful late summer afternoon in Decatur, four
couples are seated in the eighth floor hallway of the DeKalb County
Courthouse, staring at eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Wedding bells are ringing in Associate Magistrate Mary W.
Whiteman's office. Here lovers can vow to be faithful forever, in a
civil ceremony performed with dignity _ and in just under five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The couples chat sparingly, some feeding babies, while
associates ready video cameras. Six of the eight are young, nervous
and hopeful. Hann and Huie, Sam and Sherese, Onofre and Maria _ all
take their turns standing before the DeKalb County seal, to repeat
their vows _ ``en enfermedad y en salud,'' say Maria and Onofre _
and retreat shyly to the elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for Leroy Pinkerson and his betrothed, Lillian
Weaver. His hair is immaculately combed; hers is handsomely curled.
Both are adorned with white rose boutonnieres, his in the lapel of
his powder-blue blazer, hers pinned to her silky blue flowered
dress.
</P>
<P>
   He is 85, retired from the frozen food business; she is 80,
retired from the real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   Even in an age when you can win a bride on a TV game show and
marriage rates continue to fall, people still believe in the
institution _ and apparently, that it's never too late.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, about 60 couples over the age of 80 marry every year in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second marriage for both Leroy and Lillian. Former
neighbors on the same Druid Hills block, their daughters decades
ago became best friends at Fernbank Elementary School. Later, with
their children grown, they fell out of touch, until death and
divorce made them both single again.
</P>
<P>
   Some 35 years after Leroy and Lillian last spoke, her daughter,
Carol Davis, engineered a meeting. ``It was love at first sight,''
says Pinkerson.
</P>
<P>
   They are here on Tuesday to declare their love before God and
DeKalb County. Judge Whiteman addresses the couple. ``Hold hands,''
she says. Then she notices: They are holding hands already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you, Leroy, take this woman, Lillian, to be your lawfully
wedded wife ...''
</P>
<P>
   The groom jumps the gun. ``I do,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on,'' says the judge. ``You've got to promise more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Promises made, rings exchanged, Leroy and Lillian stroll to the
elevator, en route to a Toco Hill restaurant, where they will enjoy
a modest reception. They will settle in his house in Druid Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says this is the fourth-biggest event in his life,'' says
Leroy's daughter, Shelley Hamilton, a Covington schoolteacher.
Those events are: ``marriage to my mother, my birth, catching a big
sailfish in Mexico and marriage to Lil.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about this pantheon of peak moments, Pinkerson
insists that his daughter has the order wrong.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to Lillian, he says, definitely ranks ahead of the
sailfish.
</P>
<P>
   David Milliron contributed to this article
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
