<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ASTHMA-DRUGS-BOS &LR;      09-12 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTS WITH ASTHMA PATIENTS SHOW WAY TO TAILOR-MADE DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what they call a key demonstration of how genetic information
is opening a new medical era, scientists report they have
discovered personal DNA differences that predict which asthma
patients will benefit from a certain drug before they take it.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first example, said the researchers, of ``personalized
medicine'' made possible by the decoding of the human genome. In
the not too distant future, they said, doctors will be able to
match individual patients to different medications, using their DNA
as guidance, to improve the drugs' effectiveness and eliminate
harmful side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Although such tests aren't yet available, the results reported
in the current Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences
indicate that the concept is sound, said Dr. Stephen Liggett,
professor of medicine at the University of Cincinnati College of
Medicine and principal investigator of the study.
</P>
<P>
   In tests on the DNA of 121 asthma patients, the researchers
found four different patterns of DNA in a gene that helps relax
muscles in a person's lungs. Albuterol, a drug that is aimed at
spurring that gene into greater action to treat asthmatic wheezing
worked very well in those with one pattern, not at all in those
with another, and moderately in the other two cases.
</P>
<P>
   Based on this idea, tests for all kinds of diseases and
medications could vastly reduce waste of time and money spent on
drugs that don't help a specific patient, as well as sometimes
produce fatal side effects, they researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, ``there are no guidelines or explanation why one
individual with the same disease as another doesn't respond the
same way,'' said Liggett in a conference call news briefing.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, he said, ``physicians will need to get into their
mindset the notion that genetics will help guide treatment programs
which will result in better health care.'' The new approach signals
the end of a ``one drug fits all'' practice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Liggett worked in collaboration with scientists from Genaissance
Pharmaceuticals Inc., in New Haven, Conn., a biotech company whose
aim is to market an array of gene tests for different diseases.
Genaissance says it has already studies 1,500 genes, looking for
telltale DNA patterns that predict how drugs will affect people.
</P>
<P>
   This is known as ``pharmacogenomics,'' and it's considered
perhaps the most likely spinoff of decoding the human genome to
have practical application in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Conway, president of Millennium Predictive Medicine in
Cambridge, Mass., said the report ``validates what we've been
talking about in the last few years'' _ that pharmacogenomics
underlies a new thrust in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacogenomics is made possible by the fact that one person's
genes differ from those of another person in about 1 of every 1,000
letters of the genetic code that makes up our chromosomes. There
are an estimated 2.3 billion letters of the code in our genome, or
set of all genes.
</P>
<P>
   These tiny differences in genetic code are called SNPs, for
single nucleotide polymorphisms. Some SNPs act like typographical
errors, causing abnormalities in the DNA, while others don't seem
to matter. But there's a great rush among companies to find SNPs
that correspond to differences in the way people respond to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Genaissance team had previously found that a human gene that
the asthma drug works on _ called the B2 adrenergic receptor _
contains 13 of these sites where SNPs are present in the genetic
code. The scientists analyzed all the possible differences people
could have and called each person's pattern a haplotype _ a kind of
genetic marker.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing the DNA of the 121 patients, the scientists found
four common haplotypes, or markers, that predicted how people would
respond to the drug albuterol.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to use this information to devise a test that
could identify which of the four patterns, or haplotypes, an asthma
patient carries, which would then predict whether or not it was
worth trying albuterol. If it wasn't, the doctor could then try
another drug.
</P>
<P>
   Genaissance plans to apply this technology to create tests for
individual differences that predict patients' responses to drugs
for heart disease, mental illness such as schizophrenia, high
cholesterol, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Ruano of Genaissance said that as these tests proliferate,
researchers will find diseases in which no individuals respond very
well to the current drugs. That, said Ruano, will provide feedback
that will focus research on devising better drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
