<SLUG> BC-NETRETAIL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOKWARE: Shopping online for cooking equipment can be
an  adventure  By Lynne Char Bennett 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Next to eating and cooking, most food-lovers enjoy
shopping for items like cookware, tableware and all those must-have
gadgets. Shopping on the Internet is a stress-free way to seek out
the fun, the practical and the unusual.
<P>
   Some cookware sites are slick, with beautiful graphics and
sophisticated search engines. Others are utilitarian and offer a
limited number of items geared to commercial restaurant operations
or the extremely serious home cook. And many sites carry only
specific brands.
</P>
<P>
   We selected five items to shop online _ a 5-quart KitchenAid
stand mixer (325 watts), aluminum half-sheet pan, 8-inch
Wusthof-Trident chef's knife, 8-inch nonstick frying pan and a
large white oval serving platter. We also did comparison shopping
at brick-and-mortar stores. As expected, availability and price
varied but, with the exception of Costco, online shopping prices
were similar to those found at stores, ranging from $493-$615.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dollar Deviations &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Out of three San Francisco stores _ Costco, Macy's and Economy
Restaurant Supply, Economy was the only store that had all five
items. Macy's does not stock large platters until next month, and
Costco only carried the chef's knife as part of a set. The largest
price difference was on the KitchenAid mixer _ $240 at Costco and
$400 at Macy's. Total prices for all items: $492 at Economy, and
$615 at Macy's (substituting a 13-inch platter for a 20- to 21-inch
one). A few weeks later I revisited Costco. Not surprisingly, as
die-hard Costco shoppers might guess, only one item _ the
KitchenAid _ was still available.
</P>
<P>
   The total at  &LR; www.bigtray.com &LR;  was lowest at $497.
</P>
<P>
   And  &LR; www.williams-sonoma.com &LR;  took the top at $614.
</P>
<P>
   We did not escape any sales tax, plus shipping was as high as 11
percent on some orders (Williams-Sonoma) while on others the
shipping would have been free since the order was over $250.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wandering the Web sites &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The best way to find something is to use the site's category
links. However, my hurry-up nature prefers using searches by typing
in an item name whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   Navigating through the category links seemed more organized and
intuitive at  &LR; www.cooking.com &LR;  and it had reasonable response
times, as did the searches. You can also opt to get a larger view
of an item. If you are searching for only a specific, brand-name
item, it often makes sense to go to the manufacturer's Web site, as
I initially did for the KitchenAid mixer. You can usually find an
entire line of products, retail pricing and list of dealers or
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   However, to find all five things on one Web site, we chose some
that have a large presence.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the option of  &LR; www.williams-sonoma.com &LR; , which allowed
searching without having the graphics, beautiful though they were.
This feature would help speed up response time on computers with
slower modems and less memory capacity. It also displayed several
items on a page.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service over e-mail was very responsive for most sites.
 &LR; www.bigtray.com &LR; ,  &LR; www.surlatable.com &LR;  and  &LR; www.cooking.com &LR; 
answered my e-mail questions within one day. Tavolo's link to send
a message did not work after two attempts on different days. And as
of press time, we were still waiting to see whether
Williams-Sonoma.com could find us a couscoussiere (see attached
story below).
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, although the toll-free phone calls were quickly
answered, Cooking.com's and Sur La Table's customer service
representatives couldn't answer my questions about Web merchandise,
and shipping and return policy. The staff seemed focused on taking
catalog phone orders and were not familiar with the Internet side
of the business.
</P>
<P>
   The return policies varied between companies, but most have a
30-day ``unconditional guarantee'' return-refund-exchange policy.
However, the effort and cost of returning things via postal service
as opposed to returning an item to a store made the store-related
sites more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Helpful Hints &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some Web sites that may be useful to help answer a question or
make buying decisions include: &QL; 
 &LR; www.fantes.com &LR;  specializes in cookware but also provides
information on many of the products it sells, including tips on
equipment selection, use and care. &QL; 
 &LR; www.epinions.com &LR;  does not sell items. Instead, members of this
Web site write product reviews and opinions on all sorts of topics,
including cookware, even down to specific brands such as Le
Creuset.
</P>
<P>
   After all the surfing around, would we necessarily use the
Internet to purchase a mandoline for personal use without having
previously held it in hand and thoroughly inspected it? Doubtful.
Search for an obscure piece of equipment? Definitely yes. Joyously
select an All-Clad saute pan for a friend's wedding gift?
Absolutely _ especially when it could be gift wrapped and shipped
with one extra mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COOKWARE SITES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cooking.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.cooking.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses &LR; : Wide range of items, well-organized site and easy to
navigate. Good customer service, free ground shipping for orders of
more than $250.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses &LR; : Some delivery restrictions; no international service.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Williams-Sonoma &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.williams-sonoma.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses &LR; : Polished looking, slick and stylized. Good customer
service, including return policy (may return items to any store or
by mail).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses &LR; : Focus on high-end cookware, so it is harder to find
everyday items. Prices often at full retail. Graphics slow down the
site unless you have a fast computer and high-speed connection. No
delivery to foreign addresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Hunt for a Couscoussiere Becomes a Spelling Lesson &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Lynne Char Bennett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Couscous, a grain-based staple of North Africa, is
showing up on a lot of menus and can be found on most grocery
shelves. What can't be easily located is the traditional North
African cooking vessel for couscous, called a couscoussiere.
</P>
<P>
   The couscoussiere resembles a double boiler with the upper part
having perforations like a flat-bottomed colander. The couscous is
placed in this upper portion and steamed over simmering stew, broth
or, as a last resort, boiling water. Then comes the fun of
intermittently working the swelling grains by hand to keep them
separated and evenly cooked.
</P>
<P>
   So how would the Internet fare for finding this specialty item?
After all, if we're making a wish list, it might as well be a
complete one.
</P>
<P>
   Google.com came up with 373 hits, few of which were in English.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite sites,  &LR; www.cooking.com &LR;  has a 10-quart
aluminum couscoussiere for $129. A smaller (6 quart) version can be
ordered for $49 at  &LR; www.surlatable.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But beware. An innocent spelling error while searching the Web
sites had me convinced such an animal didn't exist. That is, until
a couscous-savvy co-worker checked my spelling. Even then,
different sources differ on the spelling of this pot.
</P>
<P>
   Is it couscousier? Couscousiere? Couscoussier? or Couscoussiere?
</P>
<P>
   All are correct spellings, depending on which reference you use.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a match on the exact spelling each Web site used was
more challenging than I'd expected. I should have typed in the root
word ``couscous,'' which would have located all the spelling
variations.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted from my spelling lesson and not to be outdone, I used
this assignment as an excuse to go shopping at a very fun San
Francisco foodie store, Cookin', where I found two used
couscoussieres: a 4-quart pot for $48 and an 8-quart version for
$80. But for that kind of money, I'd rather buy a new one from the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Does using a couscoussiere improve flavor and texture? I think
I'll try a steamer and pot before clicking that mouse.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cookin', ``Recycled Gourmet Appurtenances,'' 339 Divisadero &LR; 
 &LR; (between Oak and Page streets), San Francisco; (415) 861-1854. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
