<SLUG> BC-NETHEALTH-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 HEALTH: Recommended sites just a starting point  &HT;     By Kim Severson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; There is no shortage of diet and nutrition sites
on the Internet. You can count calories, join the latest fad diet,
e-mail a personal trainer or order any number of health
supplements. Egg safety, diabetic recipes, organic food sources _
the list goes on.
<P>
   It's enough to make you reach for a cheeseburger.
</P>
<P>
   After wading through several sites, talking with nutritionists
and turning to the sites I use when reporting on food news, I came
up with four I can recommend.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the United States Department of Agriculture site
( &LR; www.usda.gov &LR; ). Although it can be difficult to figure out which
arm of the USDA handles which food issue, the site is a wealth of
reliable nutrition information. It features a searchable database
on food safety and links to other government agencies like the
Centers for Disease Control, the Food and Drug Administration and
the Center for Food Safety and Applied Nutrition. You can read the
latest press releases and scan the list of local and national food
recalls. There's even maintain a section that highlights health-
and food-related hoaxes and rumors.
</P>
<P>
   For a fun, easy-to-use site that links to almost every food and
nutrition site imaginable, check out The Blonz Guide
( &LR; www.blonz.com &LR; ). You can surf to CNN's food-and-health site and
the BBC's home page, sustainable agriculture Web sites and
pediatric journals, Irish health-food magazines and almost every
university food and nutrition department in the country. The site
also links to lots of commercial operations, such as Ben&AMP;Jerry's
ice cream and the American Egg Board. It even translates text into
other languages.
</P>
<P>
   The site is part of More.com, which wants to sell you health and
beauty aids, and is named after Ed Blonz, More.com's director of
nutrition and the man in charge of which link gets on the page. You
can e-mail questions to him and he will post answers. He's a decent
writer and a good nutritionist, relying on a Ph.D. in nutrition
from the University of California at Davis and more than 25 years
of experience in the fields of nutrition, foods and health. He's
also a winner of the James Beard Foundation Award for writing on
diet, nutrition and health.
</P>
<P>
   The health and nutrition site at Yahoo.com ( &LR; www.yahoo.com &LR; ) has
a similarly wide range, with the added bonus of live chats on
issues like what you should eat for a healthy liver. The site also
features newsgroups with ongoing discussions about all sorts of
nutrition issues, as well as tools to help determine the health
factor of many common foods. The search feature is easy to use,
which is always a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, if you want specific nutrition information tailored to
you or your family, check out the Tufts University nutrition
navigator ( &LR; navigator.tufts.edu &LR; ). Experts have ranked various
health and nutrition sites on a scale of 1 to 25 and divided them
into categories for women, children and other groups. For example,
if you have special dietary needs, you can find what the academics
think are the very best of the Web on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ONLINE HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; U.S. Department of Agriculture &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  www.usda.gov &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Pluses. &LR;  Sound information on food safety, plus a good way to
stay in touch with public food policy. Lots of links to other
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses. &LR;  It's run by a government agency, with all the
confusing acronyms and bureaucratic language that go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The Blonz Guide &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.blonz.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  An easy-to-navigate, one-stop guide to all sorts of
health, fitness and nutrition sites. Complete, reliable and
screened for overt commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses. &LR;  Doesn't go much beyond offering links to other sites.
The little cartoon cat that marches around on the page is
obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Yahoo.com Health and Nutrition page &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; dir.yahoo.com/Health/Nutrition &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Good, general searchable site. Access to several
nutrition and health experts. Live chat, if you're into that sort
of thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  A little dull and the list of links to health sites
isn't as complete or screened as nicely as the Blonz site.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tufts University Nutrition Navigator &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; navigator.tufts.edu &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  A unique rating system makes it easy to sort through
the junk on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Not much more than a directory, but a cleverly sorted
one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
