<SLUG> BC-NETBEST-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 RECIPES: Top four recipe sites come from reliable sources  &HT;       
 By Tara Duggan 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; When evaluating the best recipe Web sites, I
looked for those with recipes from a reputable source, hopefully
pre-tested. I also sought out sites with enough recipes to provide
a broad range, but not necessarily 100,000 different ones, a number
that one site boasts.
<P>
   I avoided sites that were difficult to use or had too many
flashing ads, which I hate almost as much as having to listen to
someone chat on their cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my list of the top four recipe sites, in no particular
order:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ SOAR _ The Searchable Online Archive of Recipes &LR; .
 &LR; soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/ &LR; . This mammoth site _ at last count,
67,784 recipes _ was created by students at the University of
California at Berkeley and has no ads or links to e-commerce sites.
It also doesn't have bells and whistles such as printer-friendly
versions of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes come from random sources but the broad range,
including 952 for chili alone, makes up for their potentially
dubious origins. Some sophomoric but funny choices like Crudites
with Vomit Vinaigrette (for Halloween) reveal collegiate origins.
</P>
<P>
   The site is celebrated for its variety of ethnic cuisines,
including recipes from Tahiti, Ukraine and Iceland. It's easy to
search for recipes by category, but the site can get overloaded and
slow down if you try to look up specific recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Epicurious.com &LR; . &LR;  www.epicurious.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This site features 11,000 tested recipes from Gourmet and Bon
Appetit magazines, accompanied by ratings from users, photos and
videos. A nice-looking layout makes the site fun to use, even
though you do have to deal with some flashing ads and links to
Williams-Sonoma. There's also a dictionary of culinary terms, and
``boxes'' where you can save your favorite recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ RecipeLand.com &LR; . &LR;  recipes.wenzel.net &LR;  or
 &LR; www.recipeland.com &LR; . Although a commercial site, this one is
similar to SOAR in that it has a pared-down layout and a kind of
populist appeal. The two sites even have some of the same recipes.
Although viewers can't make submissions, the recipes were collected
``from various sites around the world,'' the site states.
</P>
<P>
   There's a disclaimer that some of the recipes have missing
information, and there are an overwhelming 1,000 categories. You
can, however, search quickly by ingredient. And when you get 20,000
recipes for free, who's complaining?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Food Network &LR; .  &LR; www.foodtv.com &LR; . The recipes _ more than
11,000 of them _ on this easy-to-navigate site have been presented
by chefs on the Food Network, so they do come from a reputable
source. Even if you don't want to try the more complicated recipes
at home, they provide fresh ideas and inspiration, and there are
video demos for many of the recipes if the technique sounds too
advanced.
</P>
<P>
   A great part of this site is the ability to search for a wine
match for a specific recipe or style of food, and by price range.
However, the colorful site is littered with some annoying ads and
the home page is overloaded with categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TOP RECIPE SITES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ SOAR &LR;  soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/ &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Huge number of recipes from wide variety of cuisines
and sources; no ads.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses:  &LR; Hard to search for specific recipes.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Epicurious.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.epicurious.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Tested recipes from Gourmet and Bon Appetit, user
ratings, culinary dictionary, a system to collect and store
favorite recipes from the site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses &LR; : Lots of links to e-commerce Web sites; flashing ads.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; RecipeLand.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; recipes.wenzel.net &LR;  or  &LR; www.recipeland.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Lots of recipes _ 20,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Some recipes are incomplete; there are too many
categories.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Food Network &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.foodtv.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Contemporary, often complicated recipes with exotic
ingredients, like Mustard Roasted Pork Tenderloin with Armagnac,
Rutabaga and Golden Beet. Menu planners, wine search engine, video
demos and culinary encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Too many categories, annoying ads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
