<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER IN HOLOCAUST CASES GETS WARNING FROM JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York state judge threatened on Monday to hold a
lawyer involved in the Holocaust-related reparations lawsuits in
criminal contempt for failing to pay court-imposed penalties in a
personal injury case.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Albany state Supreme Court Judge Thomas W. Keegan,
said the lawyer, Edward D. Fagan, had ignored his orders to show
that he had paid $12,500 in court-imposed penalties in the case.
Keegan had warned Fagan in May that if he failed to show proof of
payment he risked being held in contempt of court, court papers
show.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan did not respond to a telephone call for comment on
Tuesday. A lawyer who has represented him, Hal R. Lieberman, said
he did not have any comment on the matter. Keegan ordered Fagan to
explain his actions at a hearing scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, who has been one of the principal lawyers involved in
actions against companies and banks charged with profiting from the
Holocaust, was the subject of an article in Friday's New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   The article, which chronicled complaints against the lawyer, was
prepared under a joint reporting agreement between The Times and
ABC News. It was also broadcast Friday on the ABC program
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   The filing of the order by Keegan did not have a connection with
the appearance of the article.
</P>
<P>
   The order involves a lawsuit filed in 1997 by Fagan on behalf of
Christopher Bombardier and his parents against Christian Brothers
Academy of Albany, a parochial school. In the action, Bombardier
contended that while a student at the school in 1993 he was
assaulted by a classmate and severely injured.
</P>
<P>
   The judge imposed $5,000 in sanctions in 1998 against Fagan
after finding that the case filed in his court was identical to one
brought on Bombardier's behalf in another New York State court. In
August 1999, he ordered Fagan to pay an additional $7,500 to the
defendants in the case to reimburse them for legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare, legal experts said, for a lawyer to be held in
criminal contempt. If such a finding is made against Fagan he could
face a fine of $1,000 or 30 days in jail or both.
</P>
<P>
   One legal expert said Fagan might be able to resolve the matter
by paying the court-ordered penalties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
