<SLUG> BC-NETGROUPS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 NEWSGROUPS: The cybercooking community is ready to chat with you   By Kim Severson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; An interesting slice of the food community can be
found by dipping into the world of newsgroups and listserves.
Newsgroups, and to a lesser degree, listserves, are the places
where communities form on the Internet.
<P>
   Using a newsgroup is basically like reading a bunch of e-mails
about a specific subject and then joining in the debate. With a
newsgroup, you will have to wade through lots of personal
discussions to get to what you want, but there can be some good
nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   When you subscribe to a listserv, you'll get e-mail about a
subject sent directly to your computer. Be careful _ some can
generate so much e-mail that it can be annoying.
</P>
<P>
   By participating in a newsgroup, you'll get a feel for the
cybercooking community, the modern-day recipe swap and coffee
klatch. For example, if you wanted to know why your bread didn't
rise, you could log into a newsgroup, post the question and sit
back and wait for the answer. Or if you're interested in a
particular kind of food, you can find a group of people willing to
chat about it.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial sites sometimes have their own newsgroups, but the
mother of commercial-free newsgroups is Usenet.com, a global,
community bulletin board system that began in 1979. People can log
onto  &LR; www.usenet.com &LR;  and post messages about food-related events
and recipes, or ask the community for cooking help.
</P>
<P>
   Food, of course, isn't the only subject. Usenet is organized
into thousands of separate topic areas that discuss anything from
religion to sports to politics. There are some 20,000 newsgroups,
and fans of Usenet post more than a quarter-million messages a day.
It is a free-wheeling part of the Internet that can be useful and
maddening.
</P>
<P>
   The groups are divided into formal categories. Food science, for
example, is found under  &LR; sci.bio.food-science &LR; . But there are also
unofficial groups, designated with the prefix ``.alt.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does it work? Newsgroup resources are only available if
your Internet service provides access to newsgroups and your
browser is capable of reading them. Some providers give you access
to newsgroups, but many do not subscribe to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in a listserv, consider World Wide Recipes
( &LR; www.wwrecipes.com &LR; ). You can subscribe and receive a recipe a
day. Each morning, a recipe from one of seven categories _
breakfast &AMP; brunch, starters, soups &AMP; salads, entrees, sides,
desserts and extras _ is e-mailed to you. In addition to the
recipe, there's a pen-pal forum, tips forum and recipe request
area.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to get a feel for newsgroups is to search the Usenet
archives using Deja.com or any major search engine. Just be aware
that your food questions will sometimes be answered by real chefs,
sometimes by expert amateurs and sometimes by people who don't have
a clue. Beware, but it can be fun. A few sites to explore:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Deja.com &LR; .  &LR; www.deja.com/usenet &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Get a good, general introduction to newsgroups.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Star Chefs &LR; .  &LR; www.starchefs.com/boardtopic.html &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is a good example of a commercial newsgroup. Note that all
responses become the property of the Web site, preselected topics
can get a little forced and commercial advertising often can creep
in posing as information.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chronicle staff writer Lesli Neilson contributed to this
story. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
