<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-NETTEST-SFCHRON &LR;      09-12 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETTEST-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 TESTING: Internet recipes often have unsuccessful outcomes  &HT;       
 By Lynne Char Bennett  
 and Scott Clapp 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Halibut cheeks _ a surprise find at the Ferry
Plaza Farmers' Market _ led to a trip on the Internet. These
delicate and tender cheeks turn up on local restaurant menus, but
are rarely found at supermarkets. We wanted to see if we could find
good recipes for using them, since none of our cookbooks had any.
<P>
   That search was fruitful _ we dined on wonderful sauteed halibut
cheeks in citrus-brown butter vinaigrette _ but when we tried doing
the same thing for other randomly selected recipes, we were much
less successful.
</P>
<P>
   We chose three common dishes: the ever-popular chocolate chip
cookie, a simple marinara sauce and a stuffed chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   To begin, we logged onto Google ( &LR; www.google.com &LR; ), which has
the ability to search more than a billion Web sites. We typed in
chocolate chip cookie recipe and got a list of 12,400
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The first one was a recipe written specifically for chemists. It
required adding gluten, NaHCO3 and refined halite to a 2-L jacketed
round reactor vessel with constant agitation. Huh? We skipped it.
</P>
<P>
   Even with basic searches we discovered changing just one letter
made a big difference. Adding an ``s'' to ``cookie'' turned up an
additional 3,500 possibilities. Inserting ``spaghetti'' before
``marinara sauce'' turned up restaurant sites and Web pages with
Italian menus.
</P>
<P>
   We randomly chose three recipes for each of the three dishes.
Out of the nine, only one proved a keeper and one was merely
acceptable. Problems with ingredients, instructions and techniques
doomed the others.
</P>
<P>
   One cookie recipe with ``Mrs. Fields'' in the title _ a definite
lure _ called for water. The sticky, shiny batter resulted in thin
rather flavorless cookies. These were not Mrs. Fields'.
</P>
<P>
   One of the marinara recipes was simmered entirely at moderately
low heat and never shed its canned flavor. All three chicken
recipes were terrible. One said to saute the thick, stuffed breasts
over medium-high heat for four minutes per side. After following
these instructions, the breasts were still raw in the thickest
part. We didn't want to serve partially cooked chicken so we stuck
the breasts in the oven to finish.
</P>
<P>
   With most cookbooks, recipes are tested and edited. But anyone
can write a recipe and post it on the Internet. In fact, a few Web
sites solicit recipes from people visiting their pages. Going to an
Internet site associated with a food-oriented company or a cohesive
archiving system (see Tara Duggan's article elsewhere in this
section) may make recipe selection less random and more consistent
with what you'd find in a cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill of choosing an Internet recipe from thousands and
coming up with a success can be as addicting as spinning a roulette
wheel _ and just as risky. There is more to choosing a recipe from
the Internet than just printing one out and using it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RECIPE ROULETTE
</P>
<P>
   Gambling can be fun, but if you want to increase your odds of
picking a good recipe from the Internet, ask these questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Do you have the ingredients on hand or are they easily
obtained?
</P>
<P>
   _ What is the quality of the ingredients?
</P>
<P>
   _ If brand name products are specified, are measured amounts or
acceptable substitutions given? A brand-name instant soup packet
was required for one chicken recipe. We couldn't locate the exact
brand and didn't know how much to use of our substitute brand.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are instructions and techniques clear and concise?
</P>
<P>
   _ Are you familiar with the basic style or type of dish? If you
are, you can readily make necessary adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is the recipe source mentioned? Even if it is, beware. Anyone
posting recipes on the Internet can make any sort of claim. A
marinara sauce we tested titled ``Marinara Sauce (Food&AMP;Wine,
1990)'' probably had no relationship to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does the recipe make sense?
</P>
<P>
   _ If you find a good recipe you might make again sometime,
bookmark it, save it in your cookbook software program or print it
out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Read over the entire recipe before beginning. Recipes are
often not specific about ingredients or any special equipment
needed until you are midway down the instructions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
