<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONORS PLEDGE HELP AS AIDS THREATENS TO RAVAGE CARIBBEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  By   DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados _ With the Caribbean facing the highest
rate of infection with the AIDS virus outside of sub-Saharan
Africa, international donors and banks have pledged at least $120
million to support a regional strategy to combat the disease, they
announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which includes a proposal from the World Bank
for $85 to $100 million in loans, came at the end of a conference
on AIDS in the Caribbean, where many speakers emphasized that the
epidemic threatens to undo the social and economic development in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Official estimates place the number of HIV and AIDS cases at
360,000, but many health experts said that the actual number
exceeds 500,000 because of underreporting.
</P>
<P>
   While the average rate of infection of the total population is
about 2 percent _ compared with 8 percent in sub-Saharan Africa _
it has burdened the region's smaller economies. It has also forced
political leaders to acknowledge the need to act, rather than to
stay quiet because of fears of breaking taboos or scaring off the
tourists that are a mainstay of many Caribbean economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have a choice in the matter _ we must act now,''
said Prime Minister Owen Arthur of Barbados. ``The Caribbean has
never lost a generation of its most talented young people because
of war or natural disaster. It is in danger of doing so because of
the pandemic of AIDS. With it, goes the hope, promise and idealism
of the best educated and most creative minds in the history of the
Caribbean people.''
</P>
<P>
   The spread of the disease has been fueled by tourism, migration
between islands, poverty and religious and cultural resistance to
combating the spread of the disease through the use of condoms and
sex education. Haiti and the Dominican Republic account for the
vast majority of cases _ the infection rate is 12 percent in parts
of Haiti. Growing concern about the virus' spread led the Caribbean
Community to form an AIDS task force in 1998 to develop a regional
plan to track and treat the disease.
</P>
<P>
   More new cases of HIV infection were diagnosed in the region
between 1995 and 1998 than in all the previous years since the
disease was first identified, and as in Africa, it is spread
largely by heterosexual contact. In the English-speaking Caribbean
it has become the leading cause of death for men and women ages 15
to 44.
</P>
<P>
   Current spending is about 10 percent of the estimated $258
million a year needed for effective regional treatment and
prevention. The United States, which has supported anti-AIDS
programs in several of the worst-hit countries in the Caribbean,
did not pledge to a specific amount because of continuing budget
discussions in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   While international aid will help, Arthur underscored the need
for regional efforts to combat the disease. ``There has been stigma
and discrimination,'' he said. ``There has been the usual Caribbean
serendipity that the solution to the problem will be found
elsewhere and applied here.
</P>
<P>
   This week's conference is the latest in a series of recent
events at which AIDS has dominated discussions. In June, during a
meeting of Caribbean finance ministers in Washington, officials
from the World Bank and international health organizations placed
the disease and it threat in sobering context. The cost of
treatment and the loss of life and income, they said, could reduce
gross domestic product in Jamaica and Trinidad and Tobago alone by
6.4 and 4.2 percent, respectively, by 2005. Some Caribbean nations
responded to the epidemic at its beginning in the early 1980s, with
mixed results. The Bahamas, for instance, established comprehensive
and innovative programs that actually have reduced the rate of
infection.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond money, the challenge facing many of the island nations
comes from societal attitudes that often lead to discrimination,
forcing people with HIV to sink further into obscurity rather than
seek help. Phillip Goddard, Barbados' Minister of Health, said that
good leadership could help transform these attitudes. ``The message
has to be sent by demonstrably macho leaders who speak plainly
about human sexuality and the human condition,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
