<SLUG> BC-NETSEARCH-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 SEARCH TIPS: Pointers to help you surf the Net without wiping out  &HT;       
 By Laura Perkins 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; It can be great fun to surf the Web and float from
one hyperlink to another, exploring unexpected treasures along the
way. But if you are looking for information on a specific topic,
surfing can be downright distracting.
<P>
   The millions of Web sites on the Internet are not cataloged like
a library collection, but there are ways to navigate the World Wide
Web and take some of the guesswork out of searching.
</P>
<P>
   Subject indexes are good starting points for general topics.
These Web sites are similar to library catalogs because they list
Web sites by category. The better subject index sites describe and
evaluate each site they list.
</P>
<P>
   The Librarians' Index to the Internet ( &LR; lii.org &LR; ) is a
user-friendly annotated guide to more than 6,600 Internet sources
that have been selected and evaluated for reliability and quality.
For example, a keyword search for ``wine'' using this guide returns
a list of 19 sites divided into several categories, including the
best all-around sites, directories of wineries and searchable
databases. On the other hand, , a keyword search of ``wine'' using
the search engine Google yields more than 4 million records.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a more specific topic in mind or feel ready to
narrow your focus after you have taken a look at a subject index, a
search engine will help locate relevant Web sites. Each search
engine works differently and has its own database of Web sites, so
similar searches will produce different results depending on which
search engine you use.
</P>
<P>
   You can access some of the best search engines by clicking on
``Best Search Tools'` at the Librarians' Index to the Internet
site. Clicking this link will take you to a list of search engines
and metasearch engines, which are sites that search more than one
search engine at a time. Two of the better search engines:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Google &LR; .  &LR; www.google.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is a personal favorite. Though it does not support advanced
searching, it allows you to search for phrases and it returns the
most-relevant sites near the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   If you search for ``chocolate chip cookie recipe'' and enclose
the phrase in quotation marks, Google returns a list of 1,390
sites, with the most relevant sites at the beginning. If you run
the same search without the quotation marks, Google returns a list
of 12,400 sites.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; AltaVista &LR; .  &LR; www.altavista.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Advanced search techniques are allowed, which means that you can
design the search to retrieve only Web pages that contain all the
words in your search, exclude certain words or allow for spelling
variations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you search for ``+chocolate +chip +cookie
+recipe -cake,'' you will retrieve only Web pages that include each
word that has a plus sign in front of it, and none of the pages
retrieved will have the word cake anywhere because of the minus
sign in front of that word.
</P>
<P>
   To check for spelling variations, truncate a search term with an
asterisk: Plugging in cook will retrieve Web pages dealing with
words that begin with the four letters ``cook,'' including cooks,
cooking and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GLOSSARY OF TERMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Boolean Logic: &LR;  There are three logical operators or ways to
combine search terms using Boolean logic. You can use ``or,''
``and'' or ``not'' between terms to refine a search. For example,
if you search for ``restaurant or cafe'' you'll retrieve records
that have either of those terms. If you search for ``chocolate and
chip'' you'll retrieve only records that have both terms. If you
search for ``jalapenos not chipotles'' you'll retrieve records that
mention jalapenos but do not mention chipotles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Browser: &LR;  A browser is a software program that allows you to
access the Internet to view World Wide Web pages. Examples include
Netscape Navigator and Microsoft Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Domain Name: &LR;  This is a name that identifies one or more
Internet addresses. In the URL  &LR; http://www.sfchronicle.com &LR; , the
domain name is sfchronicle.com. Every domain name has a suffix that
indicates a top-level domain. These include .gov, .com, .org and
.net.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ FAQs &LR; : A FAQ is a document that lists answers to Frequently
Asked Questions and is often a hypertext link on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ HTML: &LR;  Hypertext Markup Language is the standardized computer
language behind Web documents. Hypertext documents contain text,
pictures, music, programs and sound that can be creatively linked
to one another. For example, while reading about different
varieties of tomatoes you might click on a word to see an image or
a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Internet: &LR;  The Internet is a global network connecting
millions of computers. The Internet is decentralized by design;
each computer is independent. According to CyberAtlas, over 144
million people have access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Link: &LR;  A link is the URL embedded in another document, so
that if you click on highlighted text or on a button referring to a
link you will go to that Web site address.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Search Engines: &LR;  Search engines are intermediate databases
that give you access to Web sites, which are not indexed according
to a standard vocabulary like a library catalog. Search engines and
meta-search engines (which search more than one search engine at a
time) allow you to enter names or subjects and then give you a list
of Web sites that might be useful.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ URL: &LR;  The Uniform Resource Locator is the unique global
address of individual documents on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Web site: &LR;  A location on the Internet. Each Web site contains
a home page, which is the first document a user sees when entering
the site. The site might also contain additional documents or files
that can be accessed from the home page.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _www: &LR;  The World Wide Web is a system of Internet servers which
supports documents that are formatted in HTML.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-NETGROCER-SFCHRON &LR;      09-12 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETGROCER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 GROCERS: Minus the formalities, Cyber shopping can be
a  time-saver  By Lesli Neilson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; My mission: Rate online grocers serving the Bay
Area. The contenders: Webvan.com and Peapod.com _ the only two in
the area that offer full-service grocery delivery online.
<P>
   Although some view grocery shopping as a chore, I find it a
tactilely pleasing adventure. Still, because I consider myself
Web-savvy, I was up for the challenge. The trick was to design a
dinner menu for two and see how the two sites measured up.
</P>
<P>
   After my first shopping session with Peapod, characterized by
endless waiting for the site to respond, I felt like throwing my
computer out the window, grabbing my keys and heading to the
grocery store. But out of fairness, I tried both sites a second
time, ordering the same 16 products. I was much more satisfied with
the experience, probably because I knew my way around the site and
I didn't have to re-enter my credit card and other information.
</P>
<P>
   This was the menu I chose:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Appetizers. &LR;  Assorted olives and skewers of bocconcini
mozzarella, basil leaves and cherry tomatoes and a bottle of white
wine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Entree. &LR;  Grilled salmon, roasted garlic mashed potatoes, corn
on the cob and a baguette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dessert. &LR;  Vanilla ice cream with fresh nectarines and
blackberries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pre-Delivery &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I logged onto Webvan.com, selected a delivery time and began
shopping, selecting items and placing them in my virtual basket. I
was interrupted and didn't get back to ordering until the next day.
Webvan had remembered my shopping list, even though I had to
forfeit my confirmed delivery time.
</P>
<P>
   At a second shopping session, it took 20 minutes to select the
same 16 items and delivery time. (Webvan allows you to choose a
half-hour delivery window.)
</P>
<P>
   Although I was impressed with the product images and ease of
navigating the site, getting what I wanted was hit and miss. Webvan
has at least 1,200 grocery-related items, including seafood from
Monterey Market, beef from Niman Ranch and produce from Greenleaf.
The selection of several items was vast (at least on the screen),
like nine kinds of cherry tomatoes, 18 varieties of butter and many
organic products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I had to substitute several items from what I'd
originally wanted _ roasted golden beets for corn on the cob, and
fresh figs, mascarpone and pistachios for nectarines, blackberries
and vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Once I completed my order, I was reminded that I could make any
order changes until 8:30 p.m. the day before my scheduled delivery
time. Webvan requires someone to receive the order if there are any
perishable items. Delivery is free for purchases of $50 or more;
otherwise, it is $4.95. Drivers do not accept tips.
</P>
<P>
   I then ordered the same items on Peapod.com. The site wasn't as
user-friendly as Webvan. I had to use several extra mouse clicks to
complete my order, plus the graphics weren't as good.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Webvan, Peapod offered only one kind of cherry tomato but
had 27 kinds of vanilla ice cream (all of Peapod's products are
from Andronico's).
</P>
<P>
   Fresh corn on the cob wasn't available, so I had to purchase
frozen. But gourmet products such as white truffle butter were
available.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the system for sizing and pricing seemed odd. It was
rather daunting to see a 0.67-ounce package of fresh basil listed
at $80.91 per pound (totaling $3.39). It's also necessary to know
your conversions _ Haagen Dazs ice cream is priced at $6.58 per
quart, but comes in pint-sized packages so it costs $3.29 per
package.
</P>
<P>
   On the first visit to Peapod.com, it took me 11/4 hours to order
16 products. Needless to say, I was a little frazzled. On a second
visit shopping for the same products, I was able to finish in 17
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Peapod's delivery window is two hours, and some slots can fill
up quickly. I could, however, select an unattended delivery time,
even though I had ordered perishables. Order changes can be made
until 4 p.m. the day before scheduled delivery time. Peapod charges
customers $4.95 for orders less than $75. Above that, delivery is
free. Tipping Peapod drivers is optional and they do accept
manufacturer coupons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What's in the Bag &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Webvan delivery arrived within the half-hour window. Fred
unloaded all the products for me from a yellow Webvan tote and
included a free jar of salsa. He also asked to see identification
for the bottle of wine purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cherry tomato ``medley'' I'd chosen looked great on
the screen, what arrived were skimpy, beadlike red cherry tomatoes.
A wimpy portion of olive ``cocktail'' arrived, including
reconstituted raw fava beans. I had ordered a three-seed baguette,
but that was unavailable so I received an anemic-looking plain
baguette. The nectarines were rock hard.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the corn ears arrived in the husk and were
fresh and chilled, the salmon fillet was beautiful and the quality
of all the other products was more than acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The Peapod delivery was scheduled between 7 and 9 a.m. It
arrived at 8:25 a.m. The order was left outside the door _ no one
requested identification. A dispatcher did phone to remind me of
the delivery because there were perishables in the order.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 items arrived in eight plastic Andronico's bags. The four
corn ears were frozen, as I was notified when I ordered that they
would be. Only a couple of leaves in the skimpy, browning portion
of basil were usable. The 3/4-pound portion of salmon, the only
size available, would be enough for only two small entrees. The
nectarines arrived rock hard.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the cherry tomatoes were large, perfectly
ripened and sweet tasting. The ice cream arrived rock hard, and the
assortment of olives was great (albeit $5.09 per half-pound). All
the other products were acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Bottom Line &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a fast Internet connection (DSL or cable
connection), ordering groceries online is frustrating. The biggest
consolation is the ability both Web sites offer to create lists
from past shopping sessions, which lessens the time spent on future
visits.
</P>
<P>
   For my order, Webvan cost about $10 less than Peapod. Similar
items at Safeway cost roughly $5 less than Webvan and $15 less than
Peapod. Safeway's salmon, at $6.99 per pound, was much less that
Peapod's or Webvan's, and a bunch of basil was only $1.39. Cherry
tomatoes were middle of the road at $2.49 a pint, as were bamboo
skewers at 99 cents.
</P>
<P>
   I'd probably use online grocers to order food staples and heavy
products such as laundry detergent and 12-packs of soda _ the
delivery services mean I don't have to carry them on a bus, up the
stairs or unload them. However, if you have young children or it is
difficult to get out of the house, shopping online does offers a
great option.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ONLINE GROCERS
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Webvan &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  www.webvan.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses:  &LR; Vast product selection, good product images, ease of
navigation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Products aren't always available; inconsistent
produce quality and selection.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prices:  &LR; Slightly more expensive than Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Delivery charge:  &LR; $4.95 for orders less than $50; otherwise,
free. Tips not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Delivery window:  &LR; 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Peapod &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  www.peapod.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses:  &LR; Gourmet products, produce quality, accepts
manufacturer coupons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses:  &LR; Requires many mouse clicks to complete order; poor
graphics; odd sizing/pricing system; inconsistent produce quality;
restricted to products available at Andronico's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prices:  &LR; More expensive than Webvan and Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Delivery charge:  &LR; $4.95 for orders less than $75; otherwise,
free. Tips optional.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Delivery window:  &LR; Two hours
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
