r d BC-NETWINE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-12 2122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWINE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Wine Potpourri: Gratification Is Slow in Cyberspace  &HT;        By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Ah, the Internet! Just when I was getting used to
wine warehouses and wine clubs, I'm now faced with the opportunity
(challenge?) of buying wine through cyberspace.
<P>
   This new sales approach, which I'm convinced nobody really
understands, is called e-commerce, a techno-term for buying stuff
by pushing an electronic button and then waiting for it to show up
at the door a few days later. But there's the rub, at least so far
as wine is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The delay between selection and fulfillment is tolerable if
you're buying wine to lay down and drink later. But most people
today buy a bottle of wine on the way home from work, or while
grocery shopping, for dinner that night.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the confusion over pricing and selection that I
found, even on the most thorough e-tail site, that's not likely to
happen in a real-time customer-merchant relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sales Climb &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Despite these potential problems, Internet wine sales are
climbing as more people decide they don't have the time to shop at
a wine store. So, I spent some time _ a lot more time than I ever
expected _ looking at wine-sales sites on the Internet, plus a few
others that offer wine information.
</P>
<P>
   Buying wine through cyberspace, inner space, outer space or any
space is not like buying a loaf of bread. There are legal
considerations. In California, you must be 21 years old to purchase
wine. Wine can also be shipped only to certain states (California
is one of them).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Major Sites &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Although there are many small local or regional wine sites, the
following are the major ones. For each site, I sent a question to
its experts to see if I'd get a response, and searched the database
for one of three widely available Chardonnays: 1998 Saintsbury
Carneros Chardonnay, 1999 Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay and 1998
Kendall-Jackson Vintner's Reserve Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Wine.com &LR; .  &LR; www.wine.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is the premier Internet site for ordering wine. It's smart,
sometimes a little cute, staffed with wine-knowledgeable people and
carries an extensive selection of wines from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wine.com ships directly to consumers in states where it is legal
and it works through distributors and retailers in other states. I
liked the wide range of information, wine events and more than
2,000 wine selections. The home page is attractive and inviting,
with no advertisements and plenty of links to other wine-interest
sites. It is easy to read and navigate, and gives you a lot of bang
for the buck, with five price ranges to fit all budgets. The Short
Cuts feature quickly takes you to your wine.
</P>
<P>
   However, when I e-mailed Wine.com a question, I never received a
response. The site did not have the Saintsbury Chardonnay, but
listed Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay for $9.95 (more than both
EVineyard.com (CQ)  &LR; and Drinks.com) and the Kendall-Jackson
Chardonnay for $12.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Drinks.com &LR; .  &LR; www.drinks.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If Wine.com is the best e-commerce site for wines of all
stripes, then Drinks.com is the hands-down top choice for wine,
spirits and beer.
</P>
<P>
   Because it covers all alcoholic beverages, Drinks.com projects
an inventory of more than 14,000 products, including 11,000 wines.
Rather than shipping direct to the customer, Drinks.com works
through established distributors, thus promising delivery in two to
three working days.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the look of the Drinks.com home page. The use of file
tabs (Home Page, Wine, Spirits, Beer) at the top of the page is
convenient and familiar. There are options for Cuisine Complements,
Party Ideas, Drink Recipes, a Drinks Dictionary and commentary by
wine experts such as Anthony Dias Blue and Andrea Immer.
</P>
<P>
   Some e-tail wine buyers wanting to know more about Drinks.com
may find ``About Us'' requires a bit of a search, but the site puts
the products up front and that's what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   Drinks.com never responded to my e-mail question. I had a
difficult time locating Chardonnay through the Super Search and
couldn't price either the Saintsbury or Kendall-Jackson Chardonnay.
I did find the Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay at a very good $7.96.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; WineShopper.com.  &LR; www.wineshopper.com  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Until the merger with Wine.com, WineShopper.com was considered
by wine Web surfers to be Wine.com's major competitor. The site has
an attractive home page, with no advertisements, and all the bells
and whistles it takes to get around a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   I especially liked the Quick Search and Community Favorites
features and the Pro Review, even if I didn't agree with all of the
reviewers' choices. Easy links are available to the Wine Spectator
and WineToday.com for more ratings and wine information. Although
WineShopper.com has plenty of easy links to other wine sites, it
seemed to me that it relies too much on the ratings of associate
sources such as the Wine Spectator. For now, WineShopper.com sends
orders to producers or distributors, which then ship to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A message sent to WineShopper.com brought no response. On the
wine search, I found the Saintsbury Chardonnay at $16.99 and the
Kendall-Jackson Chardonnay at $12.49, but I ran into a curious wall
on the Rosemount wines. Although WineShopper listed five Rosemount
Diamond varietals, the popular Chardonnay was not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; EVineyard.com.  &LR; www.evineyard.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Operating out of offices in Portland, Ore., EVineyard.com ships
to 12 reciprocal states, including California. The thing I most
liked about EVineyard.com is the strong commitment to consumer
education and assistance. When I clicked on Our Cellar, about 200
wines came up to consider, which appears to be less than the other
sites. But EVineyard.com has a lot of other things to like. It's
easy to locate the wine of your choice, plus there is a Teach Me
feature that answers questions about wine in real time. There's
also assistance like Help Me Pick and Wines by Chance, a random
selection of 20 wines, many at special prices.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the sites, EVineyard was the only one to respond to my
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   While EVineyard.com did list the Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay at
$9.19, I found some confusion with the Saintsbury and
Kendall-Jackson wines. Saintsbury 1998 Chardonnay is available only
in the 375 ml bottle, for $9.79, while EVineyard.com lists the
Kendall-Jackson 1998 Vintner's Reserve Chardonnay at $6.99 and
$7.99 and the 750 ml bottle at $11.99. More attention to detail
would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Two Companies Merge Instead of Making War &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In the business world, one way to overcome competition is to
eliminate it. Some dot-com observers say that is what happened when
the wine e-commerce leader, Wine.com, recently merged with its
online competitor, WineShopper.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two competing sites slugging it out for sales,
it creates problems for the sites as well as the wine consumer,''
said Peter Granoff, proprietor of Wine.com.
</P>
<P>
   Granoff said the new company, which will be called Wine.com, is
working out the transition. WineShopper.com will continue as an
e-commerce site through the end of the year, he said, ``Then the
site will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Wine.com and WineShopper.com handle online wine sales using
slightly different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Granoff said ``every single sale (through Wine.com) touches
every tier of the system,'' referring to the traditional three-tier
system of distributor/wholesaler, retailer and consumer.
</P>
<P>
   WineShopper.com is often described as an intermediary that
passes wine-sales orders on to producers or distributors, who in
turn ship the wine to the retailer or directly to the consumer. The
method used depends on state laws.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Gannon, director of public relations and corporate
communications for WineShopper.com, said a lot of things have to be
worked out. ``Basically the deal will not be closed for several
more weeks,'' she said. ``Until the end of the year, both sites
will continue to operate independently.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the new company is working toward launching a
site sometime in the first quarter of 2001 and that it will use
WineShop- &QL; 
per.com's network of distributors and retailers in all 50 states;
Wine.com does not have shipping arrangements in all states.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon disputed speculation in the industry that the merger was
forced by either venture capitalists looking to increase the bottom
line or one competitor seeking to eliminate the other.
</P>
<P>
   She said the merger is simply two companies joining forces to
create a bigger and better company. ``The merger will represent an
enhanced opportunity for the consumer,'' she said. ``It will double
the fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Busman, director of public relations for Drinks.com,
another Internet wine e-tailer, said her company sees things
differently. ``It seems as though this teaming is more about
consolidation to survive rather than a merger of equals to become
the category leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Busman said that, along with all of the expenses the new company
will incur during the merger, ``their new business model will need
to incorporate the three-tier system.''
</P>
<P>
   Busman said Drinks.com has built its business on the traditional
structure that has been in place since Prohibition. ``Other online
counterparts have focused on the possibility of direct shipping (to
the consumer) or reciprocity agreements to succeed and are now
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   She said no online business can hope for a long-term future with
that vision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WINE INFORMATION SITES
</P>
<P>
   These are favorites for general wine information, wine ratings,
wine reviews, wine travel and other wine-related subjects.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ambrosia.com &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; www.ambrosia.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This Napa site specializes in aged Napa Cabernet Sauvignons and
other California wines. It has a direct link to Winetasting.com.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Enews Monitor &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; www.bensonmarketing.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This supplier of free e-commerce news, direct shipping news and
general wine news works directly through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Local Wine Events.com &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.localwineevents.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The new site provides listings of local wine and spirits events,
classes, dinners and other wine-related activities.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; WineAccess.com &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.wineaccess.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This site makes wine recommendations and connects the subscriber
to wine shops in his or her area for specific wine purchases.
WineAccess.com lists 34 ``Wine Access Stores'' nationwide,
including two in San Francisco _ Wine House and Napa Valley Winery
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Winebid.com &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; www.winebid.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This online wine auction house says it sells more than $1
million of rare and fine wine monthly through facilities in the
United States, the United Kingdom and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Wine Fool &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.winefool.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This site is billed an ``Interactive Wine Community,'' which
means wine enthusiasts can search for and share general wine and
wine travel information and tips with others.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Wine Today &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; www.winetoday.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is what is known in Internet circles as an e-zine, or an
electronic magazine. A part of New York Times Digital, Wine Today
has the most current wine news, wine reviews of more than 7,000
wines and a list of wine columnists and reviewers, including Frank
Prial of the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WINE SALES SITES
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Wine.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.wine.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses:  &LR; Knowledgeable staff, wide range of information, more
than 2,000 selections, no ads on home page.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses:  &LR; No response to e-mailed question.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sample prices:  &LR; Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay, $9.95;
Kendall-Jackson Chardonnay, $12.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Drinks.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.drinks.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses:  &LR; Inventory of more than 14,000 products includes 11,000
wines, fast delivery, covers alcoholic beverages other than wine,
easy-to-navigate site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses:  &LR; Some information is buried, no response to e-mailed
question.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sample prices: &LR;  Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay, $7.96.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; WineShopper.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.wineshopper.com  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses:  &LR; Attractive home page with no advertisements, simple to
navigate, easy links to other wine sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses:  &LR; Relies too heavily on ratings from other sources,
didn't respond to e-mailed message.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sample prices: &LR;  Saintsbury Chardonnay, $16.99; Kendall-Jackson
Chardonnay, $12.49.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; EVineyard.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.evineyard.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses:  &LR; Strong emphasis on consumer education and assistance,
searchable database, responded to e-mailed question.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses:  &LR; Limited choices in Our Cellar category.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sample prices: &LR;  Rosemount Diamond Chardonnay, $9.19; Saintsbury
1998 Chardonnay, $9.79 (375 ml bottle); Kendall-Jackson 1998
Vintner's Reserve Chardonnay, $6.99 and $7.99 (375 ml bottle),
$11.99 (750 ml bottle).
</P>
