r d BC-NETREST-SFCHRON &LR;      09-12 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETREST-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Dining Out: The Surfing's Dangerous in Review Land  &HT;       
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; When Jon Wilson wants to find a restaurant, he
doesn't go to the phone book or newspaper. He relies on the
Internet.
<P>
   The 23-year-old information specialist types in the name of a
restaurant and the city in a search engine then clicks on whatever
site it brings him. But how reliable is the information he finds?
</P>
<P>
   Let's say he wanted to find out about Backflip, the trendy
restaurant adjacent to the Phoenix Hotel in the Tenderloin. If he
typed in Backflip in San Francisco on Google, his favorite search
engine, he'd get 17,400 sites. But in the first 10 that come up,
there are two that look the most like what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   First is Citysearch, which shows a photo and gives a brief and
mostly accurate description of the restaurant/nightclub. It also
has a hyperlink to Backflip's Web site. That's good.
</P>
<P>
   The second site is Metroactive, which would tell him that the
restaurant serves dim sum-style cuisine. That's bad _ Backflip
hasn't served that style cuisine since it first opened almost three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Diners relying on the Internet for restaurant reviews,
descriptions or online reservations are in for a mixed bag of
results. Not all of the information on Metroactive.com is outdated,
for example. In fact, the site has a longer list of Silicon Valley
restaurants than just about anyone else. But the reviews are
reposted from other publications, not written for the site itself,
and some of them are more than 3 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Food.com, another popular site, boasts of having 18 restaurant
critics around the country on staff. However, those critics work
for other publications and generally repackage their reviews for
Food.com. The site doesn't pay for them to revisit a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem at Food.com is that the listings are some
of the most inaccurate and outdated we've seen. Elephant Bleu, a
Vietnamese restaurant in the Mission, is categorized as an Italian,
Chinese, barbecue, American/casual and seafood restaurant. On the
Peninsula, 231 Ellsworth, which has been closed for over a year,
and Gibson, which has been closed for two, still come up in
searches.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of our favorite general restaurant Web sites, not
including any from individual restaurants:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Citysearch &LR; .  &LR; www.citysearch.com &LR;  is one of the most
comprehensive sites of restaurants _ and more _ in the Bay Area.
Surfers can search by cuisine or neighborhood, and can find lists
of late-night eats, romantic dining and places that are good for
groups. The site also features brief synopses of new restaurants as
well as restaurant gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The review policy of the site is clear: Citysearch pays for
reviewers to visit the restaurant multiple times before a review is
written. Citysearch is also tied into Zagat.com, but it's
convoluted getting the information from that site. It's better to
just go to Zagat.com directly.
</P>
<P>
   Citysearch also has a relationship with Foodline.com for online
reservations. Unfortunately, Foodline doesn't have many Bay Area
restaurants in its stable.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information is accurate, though occasionally we ran
across a chef who was no longer at a certain restaurant, such as
Ken Rosselot, who is no longer at Backflip.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; SFGate &LR; .  &LR; www.sfgate.com/food. &LR;  This site, currently composed
of information from The Chronicle, the San Francisco Examiner and
KRON-TV, requires you to go to the food page to see the latest
restaurant reviews or search for a restaurant. But once you're
there, it's pretty easy. Surfers can search by cuisine or
neighborhood, or look at presorted lists of late-night dining,
four-star dining or cheap eats.
</P>
<P>
   However, searches can be frustrating. Any restaurant with an
apostrophe in the name seems to wreak havoc on the results. (The
trick is to leave the apostrophe off.)
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Zagat.com &LR; .  &LR; www.zagat.com &LR; . If you're more interested in
diners' comments rather than professional reviews, Zagat.com is the
site for you. This site is an online version of the paperback
guides that many people swear by when it comes to finding a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Zagat.com can also handle online reservations. Once the surfer
finds a restaurant he likes, he can make reservations through
OpenTable or Foodline. The caveat? Only restaurants currently using
one of those online reservation systems can be used.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit is the ability to search. If you're browsing and
find a restaurant you like, you can search for restaurants that are
similar, either in food, decor or for things as specific as
fireplaces and views.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; OpenTable &LR; .  &LR; www.opentable.com &LR; . For online reservations in
the Bay Area, OpenTable is the current leader. Foodline is trying
to make inroads, but OpenTable has the most restaurants on board.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is easy: Customers can either decide where they want
to eat, then see what reservations the restaurant has available, or
they can choose a date and time and see what restaurants have
reservations available at the requested time. Searches usually take
only a few seconds, and reservations can be confirmed online.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that customers are restricted to those
restaurants that are signed up with OpenTable. That's limiting,
especially on the Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; The Low-Down on Take-Out Food &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Take-out food hasn't been left out of the Internet food
explosion, but options are limited. In fact, there's only one site
we liked.
</P>
<P>
   Waiters on Wheels, the popular company that delivers meals from
restaurants to customer's homes, can be accessed through
 &LR; www.waitersonwheels.com &LR; . The site is easy to navigate and offers
food from a number of restaurants, although the vast majority are
neighborhood pizza, pasta and Chinese places.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few negatives. First, you can't search, and have to
scroll through lists of restaurants. Second, you can only order
food when the restaurant is open. And finally, while the restaurant
has a decent selection of San Francisco and Peninsula/South Bay
restaurants, there is no service in the East Bay or Marin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RESTAURANTS ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Citysearch &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.citysearch.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Comprehensive list of restaurants; can search by
category; independent reviews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Some inaccurate information; online reservations
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; SFGate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Information compiled from The Chronicle, the San
Francisco Examiner and KRON-TV; comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Searches can be frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Zagat &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.zagat.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Listings include diners' comments. Once you find a
restaurant, you can search for similar ones by style of decor,
views, hours and more; can reserve online.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  No professional reviews.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; OpenTable &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; www.opentable.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Largest reservation service for Bay Area restaurants;
searches are quick; reservations confirmed online.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  The number of participating restaurants are limited,
especially on the Peninsula.
</P>
