</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-POE-HNS &LR;      09-12 2747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-POE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Friendship gives Poe shot at taekwondo gold
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID BARRON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kay Poe and Esther Kim were nose to nose, lost in their own
world, which was nothing unusual.
</P>
<P>
   And they were crying, which was.
</P>
<P>
   It was the afternoon of May 20, and Poe and Kim were huddled
next to the bleachers in an out-of-the way corner of the Olympic
Training Center gymnasium in Colorado Springs, Colo. They were
minutes away from their match that would decide the U.S. Olympic
team berth in the women's taekwondo flyweight division.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't hard to imagine the problem faced by these two
distraught young women. Best friends since childhood, they clearly
were upset at the prospect of having to kick and punch each other's
Olympic dream into submission. They talked, then cried some more,
then hugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that,'' said a bystander. ``They really don't want to
fight each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That had to be it. That much was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Then Poe and Kim turned to walk toward the competition floor and
suddenly things weren't so clear after all.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you know the story that emerged from the confusion of
May 20. Poe had suffered a dislocated kneecap in a preliminary
match and couldn't walk without leaning on Kim for support. Rather
than fight her injured friend, Kim elected to forfeit, assuring
that Poe, the No. 1-ranked competitor in the world in her weight
class, would advance to the Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting furor was considerable. Poe and Kim became
standard fodder for most big magazines and every major network. Kim
and her father, Jin Won Kim, who coaches both women, were offered
an expenses-paid trip to Sydney by Juan Antonio Samaranch,
president of the International Olympic Committee. Esther Kim threw
out the first pitch at an Astros game and visited Washington, D.C.,
to receive a national sportsmanship award.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, along with assorted television tapings, they have
been together in Korea, for a tour by the U.S. Olympic team, and in
Colorado Springs, where Kim won a berth on the U.S. team for the
Pan American championships while Poe cheered from the sidelines,
and in San Antonio, site of the U.S. Taekwondo Union's Junior
Olympics, and back in Colorado Springs, where Poe spent several
weeks training with Kim and members of the national team.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Olympics drew near, Poe was alone. Kim and her father
left in early August for another training trip to Korea. And as she
trained, the very act that gave Kay Poe her ticket to the Olympics
was the very thing that stood in her way.
</P>
<P>
   The grim resolve, the virtual imperviousness to pain and the
focused vision that have made a Poe a favorite to win the gold
medal in Sydney represent a stark contrast to the childlike
qualities that got her into the sport at age 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Umm, I was kind of a mischievous child,'' she said, almost
apologetically. ``My parents wanted something for me to do. I tried
other sports, but I always got bored.''
</P>
<P>
   So what sort of things would a bored 7-year-old do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just things I wasn't supposed to do,'' she said. ``I'd go
outside and do things and get into things, and my parents would be
upset. Nothing big. I didn't rob houses at 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob, no. Paint, yes. Poe's father, Ken, who works with wife
Linda for a Houston insurance agency, is the unofficial historian
of his daughter's mischievous period. It is a role he fills with
relish. He doesn't quite have Dennis Miller's sense of comic
timing, but he's working on it.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of the white brick house and the Krylon
spray-paint can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kay was maybe 5, 6 years old and just learning to read,'' Ken
Poe said. ``I came home one afternoon and found that someone had
taken Krylon spray paint and sprayed it across the back of my white
brick house.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I asked the girls to come outside. The oldest one (Kerri,
who is four years older than Kay) said, `I don't know anything
about it.' So I said, `Kay, do you know anything about this?' And
she says, `Yep.' And I said, `Kay, did you do this?' And she said,
`Yep.' I said, `Kay, ' and she blurts out, `It's not my fault.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I say, `Kay, please explain to Daddy why it's not your
fault.' And Daddy's ears are turning red and his blood pressure is
going up. And she grabs the Krylon spray and points to where it
says `clear' (as in ``shake can to clear nozzle``) and says, `Look,
it says right here that it's clear.' So I said, `Kay, just go into
the house and let Daddy stand outside for a few minutes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We had those kinds of experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 911 call,'' said Linda Poe. ``That was a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time that Kay had an argument with the family
housekeeper. She was too young to read, but she managed to riffle
through the Yellow Pages, used pictures to find the listings for
maid services and tried to hire a new maid.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the trip to Chicago. When radio problems
delayed the airplane's departure, Poe allowed his fidgeting
daughter to leave her seat to use the rest room. Ten or so minutes
went by. Kay didn't return to her seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Kay has gone into the doggone terminal,'' Ken Poe
said. ``So I go into the terminal, frantically looking for the
child. I send a lady into the women's rest room to find her. No
Kay. They make the announcement that the plane is about to leave. I
go back and tell the stewardess that I have to stay because I can't
find Kay.
</P>
<P>
   And then I see the door cracked to the cockpit. That's what she
did. She went to the bathroom, saw the door open, waltzed into the
cockpit and just started talking to the pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Poe, of course, has explanations for everything. She was
just being friendly. The housekeeper was working too hard. Cartoon
shows encouraged kids to become familiar with 911. The paint can
said ``clear,'' and, besides, she was spray painting nice things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to write `I love God,''' she said. ``But I had trouble
with my d's and b's. So it came out `I love Gob.'''
</P>
<P>
   However his name is spelled, the Poes could have used some help
from the Almighty in dealing with their younger daughter. They
tried gymnastics. They tried dance. ``They didn't dance like she
did,'' Ken Poe said. They tried softball. And then, when Kay was 7,
they tried the Korean martial art of taekwondo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have imagined,'' Ken Poe said, ``that a contact
sport would be something that would hit her hot button. There
aren't too many contact sports that a woman can get involved in
that are considered respectable. And she was so little.''
</P>
<P>
   She still is. At age 18, Poe stands only 5-1 and weighs 101
pounds. But she can break boards and bricks with her hands, and she
can cave in a grown man's side with one swift kick.
</P>
<P>
   The Poes enrolled Kay in a taekwondo school on Houston's
northwest side owned by Master Jin Won Kim, a Korean-born American
citizen who opened his first Houston school in 1978. She quickly
fell under the spell of Simona Hradil, an older student who would
go on to win 11 gold medals in national and international
competition. And she quickly became friends with Kim's daughter,
Esther, who is two years older.
</P>
<P>
   At one particular Halloween party, Esther came dressed as a
pirate and was assigned by her father to keep watch over Kay, who
was dressed in a black ninja outfit. The two grabbed hands and, in
some ways, they've never let go.
</P>
<P>
   Just as easily as they seem to invite stereotypes, Esther Kim
and Kay Poe take equal delight in smashing them and then, on
occasion, building them back up.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Olympic committee workers were circulating her smiling
mug shot with the girlish flip hairstyle, Poe showed up in San
Antonio this summer, a few weeks after the Olympic team trials,
with a closely cropped, spiked haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Things had gotten boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when I was little. You see what happens when I get
bored,'' she said. ``I went with a friend who was getting his hair
done, and I was flipping through a book and wondering if this would
look good on me. I asked the hairdresser, and she said I had the
face for it. So I cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks good,'' Kim said. ``You don't even have the baby
bangs anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the messy look, but I never had the guts to do it,''
Poe replied. ``It was blonde in January and February, then red, and
now it's going back to brown. Nothing extreme. I just want it to
look natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as they can behave for the camera, Poe and Kim can be
boisterous when the lights are off. When Poe expressed some
confusion about their upcoming schedule, Kim shook her head and
said, ``When they cut off her hair, they must have cut off her
brain, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a little chat between friends
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of it is inside stuff,'' Kim said, ``things only we can
know and joke about. In a way, we're in our own little bubble. If
we let people in, they wouldn't understand the way we can
understand each other. We don't have to say things. We know what
the other is thinking. We can make conversation with eye contact.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to paint either or both as stereotypes, and
several have tried. A week after the Olympic trials, University of
Minnesota sports psychologist Mary Jo Kane hypothesized to the New
York Times that the Poe-Kim encounter could indicate that women
were not as competitive as men and reinforced stereotypes that
women don't care as much about winning as men do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She needs to go back and take some more classes,'' Kim said,
scowling. ``She put a big shame on women. This isn't about gender.
It's about being an athlete. She put shame on women, and she should
be ashamed of herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wanted to comment on something, she should know what
she's talking about. She had no knowledge of what taekwondo is. She
should read some books, takes some notes and find out what she's
talking about before she says anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The nature of taekwondo, as a sport or as a martial art, has
been something of a player in the ongoing story of Poe and Kim.
</P>
<P>
   The young women were not above laughing raucously after one
conference call at the earnest question from a reporter for a
taekwondo magazine. The woman asked Kim which tenet of taekwondo
(courtesy, integrity, perseverance, self-control or indomitable
spirit) was on her mind when she forfeited the match to Poe.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, in her own way, Poe talks about the
importance of each.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of life to me,'' she said. ``It teaches about
morals, how you should act, respect and discipline. It always
challenged me. It challenged my physical ability. I didn't know
anything about the sport when I was little. It was just challenging
physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get older, people can get bored with something that
challenges just one part of them. But as I started to grow, it
challenged me mentally, too. And now, I find it in my heart and
soul to do it. There are so many things about it that I love.''
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of years at Jin Kim's studio, Kay announced to
her father that she wanted to be like her friend Simona, the future
national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Kay, if that's what you have on your mind, you need
to tell Master Kim,''' Ken Poe said. `Now, at the time, talking to
Master Kim was like talking to God. But I took her to the school
and said, `There's the man's office. There he is.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So she timidly goes in there and he says, `What do you want?'
She tells him, and he said, `OK, I can't promise you anything. But
if you'll be a good student, I'll be a good teacher.'''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, at age 13, she was a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always a competitor,'' said Jin Kim. ``It's the speed.
She goes at 100 miles an hour, and nobody can stop that. She gives
everything. That is what I do with my students. I tell them the
more time you put in, the better you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming a great taekwondo practitioner is like any sport. If
you want to be a good swimmer, go play in the water. If you want to
be good at taekwondo, come to school more often. I don't believe in
other methods. People ride bikes to strengthen their legs. I say if
you want stronger legs, come to school. I don't do any fancy
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The old ways seemed to work for Jin Kim's new student. She won a
silver medal at the Pan American championships in 1996, the first
year since 1984 that taekwondo had not made the Olympic Games as a
demonstration sport. She won international events in Denmark and
Mexico in 1997, taking bronze at the world championships. And in
1999, she began a backbreaking schedule of competition that
established her as the Olympic favorite for 2000, the first year
that taekwondo would be a full medal sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was an athlete in the world who took on
the schedule that child did (in 1999), and I thought she was
nuts,'' Ken Poe said. ``She fought at the Pan Am championships in
December 1998 in Peru, February at the U.S. Open, March at the Pan
Am Games trials, the national championships in April, the national
team trials in May, the worlds in June, the world Olympic
qualifying event in July, and in August she went to Korea to train.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see this little bitty ordinary kid. The only thing she may
have done differently from any other kid is that she had the
courage to set her goals pretty high and the good sense to tell
other people about it. And then she just went out there and did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She had come a long way from the little girl in the ninja
costume. But with one blow to the knee May 20 in a preliminary
match against Mandy Meloon of Sugar Land, she almost lost it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell it was a nasty bruise,'' Ken Poe said. ``But
after the match, when she's walking to the holding area, I can see
it might be a little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kay has a huge tolerance for pain, and this is the second time
I've seen it. She probably was about 9 when she broke her arm. She
came home from practice and, typical knothead Kay Poe, she runs off
to play with her friends and trips and breaks both the radius and
ulna in the arm. There wasn't a tear until they had to cut off her
taekwondo uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ken Poe joined Esther Kim and his daughter in the
basement of the Olympic Training Center gym, Kay's left knee was
swollen with blood and fluid. Esther asked Ken Poe to find her
father. ``That's when I thought there was a good chance that Kay
wouldn't be able to return to fight,'' Ken Poe said.
</P>
<P>
   The final conversation that led to Esther Kim's withdrawal came
after the women had the holding area to themselves. It was not a
gentle discourse between two old friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still arguing about it,'' Ken Poe said.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Kim, however, prevailed. She and her father helped Kay to
her feet, and the two friends made it back upstairs for one last
conversation near the gymnasium bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure you want to do this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I told you. We can't turn back now. I know this is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   And then they hugged, and then they turned, and then they walked
toward the mat, toward the judges, toward the cameras, toward the
moment that Bud Greenspan, the filmmaker who has chronicled the
Olympic movement for more than 40 years, describes as the very
essence of sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic oath says that we will take part for the honor of
our team and the glory of sport,'' Greenspan said. ``That
expression about the glory of sport seems to be an outmoded one at
times. But what those two kids did brought it back to life.''
</P>
<P>
   One task remains in Sydney. But even though Kay Poe will have
made it to the ring with the help of her parents, her coach and her
best friend, she steps into the ring alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideal answer would be yes, I want to go to Australia and
win it for Esther,'' she said. ``But to be honest, right now it's
back to being all about me. Every time I think about what happened
in Colorado Springs, I think about the stadium filled with people,
but it was her and me alone. There are so many emotions, I can't
express them. It was too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now, I have to focus on fighting. If I have any doubts or
any other thoughts, it affects me. Even when I talk about what
happened at trials, it has to be in the third person kind of view.
I can't keep reliving the moment. If I keep doing it, I'll start to
doubt myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when this is over I'll be able to reflect on it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
