<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0994 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-JUAREZ-HNS &LR;      09-12 2201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JUAREZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Juarez hasn't forgotten where he comes from
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID BARRON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Rocky Juarez, as befitting a world champion boxer who
was named after Rocky Marciano, is a student of the fight game.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of 140 amateur fights with only 16 losses, Juarez sits
into the night in front of his family's big-screen television,
playing tapes of his fights over and over again until he can recite
the exact series of punches before they unfold.
</P>
<P>
   He studies other fighters as well. He knows all the stories
about Oscar De La Hoya and George Foreman and Ray Leonard, and that
their Olympic gold medals laid the foundation not only for a
professional career but financial success as well.
</P>
<P>
   And he knows what is on the line as he prepares to leave for the
Olympics as the defending world champion in the featherweight
division, the favorite to bring home a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always thinking ahead,'' he said. ``But at the same time,
I know I have to take it day by day. So the first thing in mind is
the Olympics, concentrating on the Olympics. I can't predict what
will happen. I can only hope that I win that gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way. Anybody who wins a gold medal
skyrockets in the pros. The promoters want you. It's a business.''
</P>
<P>
   The businessman, however, also is the baby of the family _ the
youngest of Pedro and Emelinda Juarez's six children. And while he
dreams of medals and championships, his goals for life outside the
ring extend no further than the street where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky (or Rocky, the names are used interchangeably by friends
and family) had little choice but to become a boxer. There was the
name, of course. Actually, his father wanted to name his youngest
child Rocky Marciano Juarez before he compromised on Ricardo Rocky
Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Juarez, 88, grew up in Mexico in the years before World
War II as a fight fan _ and, for one bout in the 1940s, a fighter
in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped the other guy in the first round,'' said the
younger Pedro Juarez, translating from Spanish for his father.
``But when he went to be paid, the promoter said there wasn't
enough action and paid him only 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said they cut off his two arms, humiliated him, by treating
him that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Juarez left Mexico in November 1944, moving to Houston
to work as a carpenter, a trade he passed on to his son. He also
passed on the love of boxing to the younger Pedro, his only son
among seven children, staying up with him on Friday nights at the
family home in the Silverdale neighborhood just north of downtown
Houston, watching the Gillette Cavalcade of Sports on television
and taking him to fight cards across the city.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Juarez never followed his father into the ring. But when
Ricardo came along in April 1980, his grandfather was ready to
spread the word to a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father would stick out his hands and say, `Throw punches,
throw punches,' but none of the other kids would listen, just
him,'' Pedro Juarez said. ``He would start throwing punches at my
father's hand, and almost from the beginning he would use his left
hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like the way he threw the hook. He threw it real
nice. And one day I said, `Son, you have to throw that left hook
more often. It looks like a gift that God gave you.'''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a gift for baseball, as well as something of a flair
for the dramatic. A pitcher for his neighborhood Little League team
at Lindale Park, he led his team to a local championship and was
nicknamed ``Babe'' for his habit of calling his shots at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   When Juarez turned 13, it was apparent he wouldn't be big enough
to consider a career in baseball. So Pedro took his son to Ray
Ontiveros, proprietor of Ray's Boxing Gym on Freeman Street, a
couple of blocks west of North Main.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw in the gym how he was throwing punches, and people
who were there asked me how long he had been boxing,'' Pedro Juarez
said. ``I said he just started today, and nobody believed me. The
way he threw punches, they thought Ricky had been fighting for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he had been working there for two or three days, he
wanted to go into the ring. So Ray put him in to spar with a
friend, and Ricky caught him with an uppercut and made him cry.
That's when Ray came to me and said he wanted to enter Ricky in a
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Juarez likes the symmetry of having taken up the game at 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali started at 13,'' he said. ``It's a good age because it
gives a kid a chance to decide what they want to do. If you start
him too early, they don't know what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The first six months in the ring weren't easy. Juarez had to get
used to getting beaten up every day by the same sparring partner,
Juan Campion, who later went on to the professional ranks. But from
the beginning, Juarez knew this was what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just a feeling about it,'' he said. ``When you step
into the ring with the guy in front of you, it's just him and you,
and there's no better feeling than to come out victorious. After I
won the first one, I said, `This is a good feeling. I want to do it
again. I want to win again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Juarez won his first fight at Chapas Boxing Gym in Houston, then
traveled to Fort Stockton to compete for a state championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a camera to tape his first fight, and Ricky beat him
in the first round just by using body shots,'' Pedro Juarez said.
``That's when I knew the kid had something. He was a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the tape recording of the first fight didn't
survive. Pedro Juarez was so nervous that he hit the rewind button
and accidentally erased the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Juarez won a state Junior Olympics title in 1994, his second
year in the ring, and was national Junior Olympic champion in 1996.
He finished third in the 1997 national championships, won the Ali
Cup Invitational and made the world championship team, losing to
the eventual champion at 119 pounds, Cruni Otteanu of Romania.
</P>
<P>
   But that first trip to worlds, in Budapest, Hungary, and a 1997
dual meet against the Russian team at the George R. Brown
Convention Center where Juarez lost 16-6 convinced Ontiveros that
Juarez would have to change his strategy to succeed on an
international level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. boxers have beautiful legs and movement but no upper
body strength,'' Ontiveros said. ``The Russians and Cubans, that's
all they have is upper body strength. They use it to push people
around, and they're good at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when we came back, we decided in December (1997) that for
the next two years that we were going to work on upper body
strength, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ontiveros' last Olympic boxer, Raul Marquez in 1992, also
learned the hard way about the often strange ways of amateur
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the computer scoring system, to be honest with
you,'' Marquez said. ``It favors the European countries because
they fight straight up and don't throw body shots. In the Olympics,
you've got to throw straight shots that are accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember in my first Olympic bout, I fought a 6-foot-4
Nigerian. Well, what are you gonna do with a tall guy? You hit him
in the body. But none of those shots counted (with the judges). I
won 7-6.''
</P>
<P>
   While Juarez adjusted to the demands of the amateur scoring
system, he didn't lose the characteristics that could make him a
successful pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. fighters are more technicians. They fight better, they're
smoother, faster. That's our style,'' he said. ``Foreign boxers are
more straight up, stronger, not too much head movement. Not a lot
of them make it the pros because of the way they fight, straight
up. But a couple have been world champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked on my upper body, but I still punch to the body a
lot. The coaches say judges don't count body shots, but I go to the
body and stick with it. That's how I've gotten a lot of my
knockouts, from body shots.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1999, Juarez had remade his body and his game. He won his
first national championship, advancing to the world championships
before a home crowd at George R. Brown. He beat fighters from
Kazakhstan, Germany, Scotland and Turkey, then beat Tulkunbay
Turgunov of Uzbekistan by decision for the world championship.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he was becoming an internationally successful
boxer, Rocky Juarez tried hard to be one of the guys at Davis High
School. He generally avoided trouble from classmates who might be
tempted to test his skills, in part because of his deceptively
slight build, in part because of a loyal cadre of protective
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are proud of me on the north side,'' he said. `I can
walk around _ say to a club or something, and people might say,
`Hey, Rocky, do you want a beer?' and somebody will say, `Are you
crazy? This boy doesn't drink. He's going to be a world champion.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I like about my neighborhood. People protect me.
And I think I'm a good person. I never let things go to my head. If
you think too highly of yourself, there are people out there who
don't care who you are and can take everything away from you, and
your whole career is down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to respect everybody, and I try to reduce things from
happening. Say I go to a dance and I'm with friends. It may be
crowded and I tap a guy on the shoulder and say `excuse me' rather
than trying to push by him and bragging that I'm an Olympian.''
</P>
<P>
   Juarez is proud of having graduated from Davis High School, and
Davis is proud of him, too; a mural at the school includes a
painting of Juarez with the Olympic rings in the background. His
success in the ring, however, complicated things in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to miss a month of school at a time (for
competitions and training),'' he said. ``That was the hard part.
But when I was in school, I made the grades, did my homework.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Davis in December but made a return trip to
Houston from the team's training base in Colorado Springs this
spring so he could go through graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't give up,'' he said. ``My dream has always been to
become a world champion, and I was thinking more about boxing. But
I was trying to do my best because I would have been the only one
in my family not to graduate. I'm glad to have the diploma. It
shows that I'm not a quitter and that I didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Juarez in the classroom is a lot like Rocky Juarez in the
ring _ troublesome start, successful finishes. He has never been
knocked off his feet in 156 fights, even though he is anything but
a quick starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who sees me knows that Rocky always loses the first
round, always,'' he said. ``I'm patient. I try to make the guy show
me everything he has in the first round. In a way I'm getting beat
in the first round, but I know what he's going to do the whole
fight. I make the other guy commit.''
</P>
<P>
   Juarez's road to the Olympics got off to a slow start, too.
After qualifying for Sydney earlier this year, he suffered a cut
while sparring and had to sit out dual meets against Mexico and
Ukraine. He's had a lot of time to think, and what he usually
thinks about his life after the Olympics and the beginning of his
professional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``My amateur career is about to end,'' he said. ``Then I'll have
to take another step and have to prove myself on the next level,
the professional level. I think about what happens if I don't
fulfill that dream and people say, `Oh, he was only a good
amateur,' that I stopped at that one spot and didn't keep going
step after step. I think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it becomes a money thing,'' he said. ``The
promoters promise so much if you win a bronze, then it goes up with
a silver medal, and with a gold you can almost name your price.''
</P>
<P>
   No Houston fighter has won a gold medal at the Olympic Games
since Foreman in 1968. But Ontivaros and Marquez think Juarez has
the potential to bring it home.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make a mistake with Rocky,'' Ontivaros said. ``They see
him shorter (5-4) and so the guys go right to him, and that's a
mistake. He tears at their body and then goes to the head. He's a
good boxer, a good hitter. That's what we teach here. None of that
moving and playing around.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether he wins a medal, Juarez's thoughts in
Australia will never be far from his home on Silverdale, where he
lives on the same street with his grandparents, an uncle and a
sister, and from the lessons his grandfather taught him so long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he prepares for the longest trip of his life, and then
the professional journey to follow, he hopes to remain the guy just
up the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go well, I'll come back,'' Juarez said. ``I don't
even want to move from Houston. I don't even want to move from my
neighborhood. That's how happy I am there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say I was a millionaire and things go well for me. I'll still
live in my neighborhood and get the response of being who I am and
live a happy life. I want to make Houston a fighting city again.
Las Vegas, MGM Grand? I want people to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
