<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Purveyors Gear Up to Offer Ingredients Online But
Hard-to-Find  Products Can Still be Hard to Find   _ Salad: Perishable products are fairly scarce 
 &HT;       
 By Lesli Neilson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Cyber-hunting for a specific recipe ingredient is
like trying to find a needle in a haystack _ especially if it's
perishable. To see how well the Internet worked for finding
specialty ingredients, we took a green salad recipe and went
surfing.
<P>
   We were able to find a variety of sites which offer upscale
ingredients which led to some gourmet finds with expensive totals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dean &AMP; Deluca. &LR;  If you want to splurge,
 &LR; www.deananddeluca.com &LR;  (or  &LR; www.deandeluca.com) &LR; , the site from
the gourmet retail grocer, is just for you. This sharp-looking site
has four categories: marketplace, recipes, articles and wine. Crisp
product images and colorful styled recipes signal that this is no
amateur site. General food information taken from the Dean &AMP; Deluca
Cookbook is also helpful.
</P>
<P>
   I purchased upscale olive oil and vinegar for the recipe. With
descriptions like, ``More tart than sweet, with a true raspberry
taste, this is a vinegar destined to dress the most delicate
salads. Serve with young lettuces or goat cheese on cro &LR; u &LR; tes,''
how could you not select French Champs Champagne Vinegar with
Raspberry for $8.25 for 16.9-ounce bottle? For a traditional red
wine vinegar, there was domestic Delouis Aged Red Wine Vinegar for
$5 for a 500-ml bottle.
</P>
<P>
   I also chose a bottle of California Bariani extra virgin olive
oil for $24 (33.8-ounce bottle). In addition, there are three other
California olive oils and 14 Mediterranean olive oils.
</P>
<P>
   Customer assistance provides all sorts of useful information
like Frequently Asked Questions, shipping information and company
history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ World of Cheese &LR; .  &LR; www.worldofcheese.com &LR;  is a no-frills site
that offers cheese from 12 countries. A search for goat cheese led
to nearly a dozen choices, many from Bay Area cheese artisans like
Cypress Grove Humbolt Fog. But after selecting a 7-ounce round of
Sea Stars Monet goat cheese for $11 and proceeding to check out,
the delivery charge ended up costing an additional $16.95. You're
better off ordering several cheeses to make up for such a hefty
shipping fee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Webvan. &LR;  After endless searching,  &LR; www.webvan.com &LR;  was one of
the only sites I found for mixed greens. The popular mix includes
baby lettuce leaves, frisee, radicchio, mizuna, arugula, baby red
chard and baby spinach. A 4-ounce bag sells for $3.37. With seven
kinds of goat cheese _ the most expensive for $5.38 _ this
easy-to-navigate site simplifies shopping. English shallots were
available for $1.87 a pound. Diamond Kosher salt was $3.06 for a
3-pound box. Webvan charges $4.95 for deliveries under $50 and
offers a 30-minute delivery window.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Monterey Bay Spice Co. &LR;  This Santa Cruz company seems to
carry every herb and spice imaginable. Clicking to  &LR; www.herbco.com &LR; 
will bring you to a fairly rudimentary site but the immediate
response while searching for products is refreshing. A search for
black peppercorns revealed nine kinds. Spices are available by the
quarter-pound or in bulk. A $3 processing fee is added to orders
less than $20. Orders are shipped via UPS for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SALAD OF WILD &AMP; CULTIVATED GREENS
</P>
<P>
   Include a well-balanced selection of assertive and mild greens
for this salad from Georgeanne Brennan. Choose from dandelion,
chicory, borage, watercress, mache, purslane, spinach, arugula,
radicchio, chervil, frisee, escarole, sorrel and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups mixed young tender greens (see above)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine or other vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 ounces fresh goat cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Rinse and clean all the greens carefully, discarding any old or
bruised leaves. Tear any large leaves into bite-size pieces. Dry
the greens well in a salad spinner or with a towel and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the olive oil into a large salad bowl. Add the shallots,
vinegar, salt and pepper and stir with a fork to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Put the greens in the salad bowl and gently toss in the dressing
until they are well coated. Let the salad stand for about 10
minutes to soften the taste of the greens and to blend the flavors.
Top with the goat cheese and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 128 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate,
12 &LR;   &LR; g fat (3 g saturated), 7 mg cholesterol, 413 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _ Couscous: Search yields few hits, lots of misses &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Lesli Neilson &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; It was quite a task coming up with reliable Web
sites to purchase ingredients for Marlena Spieler's recipe for
Vegetable Couscous, especially the fresh produce required.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ethnic Grocer. &LR;  Trying to shop _ more than once _ on
 &LR; www.ethnicgrocer.com &LR;  was a negative experience each time. I was
able to purchase some spices for my recipe and the number of
products available was impressive. A search for olive oil brought
up 53 choices. But the product images were too small and amateurish
to determine the brand name and it wasn't immediately apparent
where to select the product if you wanted to purchase it.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for paprika (nine kinds were found) turned up an
informative little blurb at the bottom of the page telling all
about the pepper.
</P>
<P>
   However, all the bells and whistles made it tough to move around
the site. Each step of searching and selecting items seemed
endless. Although shipping is free for orders of $30 or more, it
would take forever to acquire that sum in products. Otherwise,
shipping costs $5.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ethnic Superstore &LR; .  &LR; www.ethnicsuperstore.com &LR;  is divided
into five categories: products, recipes, festivals, recipe contest
and promotions/sales. The product category is divided into tea and
coffee, Middle Eastern and Mediterranean and Indian Subcontinent.
We were able to find canned and dried chickpeas. However, a search
for ``chickpea'' came up with nothing. Typing in ``chick pea'' came
up with 10 results. Shipping is by UPS and costs $4.50 for orders
up to $35.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; San Francisco Herb Co &LR; . Neil Hanscomb has been in the herb
and spice business for over 25 years. In addition to a
brick-and-mortar outlet at 250 14th St., San Francisco (10 a.m.-4
p.m. Monday-Saturday), he sells more than 450 items at
 &LR; www.sfherb.com &LR; , including dried herbs and spices, spice blends,
teas, baking items, nuts, seeds and potpourris. There is a minimum
order of $30, and shipping is through UPS.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Eco-Organics USA &LR; . Based in New Jersey,
 &LR; www.eco-organics.com &LR;  was simple in design but had several
ingredients I needed, including onions, garlic, carrots, sweet
potatoes, cabbage, green beans, zucchini, tomatoes and vegetable
broth. In addition, the site offers a variety of other products,
including hemp goods, groceries and juicers. Ground shipping is
available for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; American Spice Co &LR; .  &LR; www.americanspice.com &LR;  is a virtual
pantry filled with all sorts of spices, sauces, seasonings and
more. Although the site is rather bare bones (no product images or
other useful information), I was able to find many of the
ingredients _ olive oil, paprika, cumin, turmeric, coriander,
ginger, curry powder, cloves, cinnamon, salt and pepper. There is a
fee for ground shipping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COUSCOUS ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ethnic Grocer &LR; .  &LR; www.ethnicgrocer.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Wide variety of products; minimal shipping charge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Hard to read; slow to respond and difficult to move
around the site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Ethnic Superstore &LR; .  &LR; www.ethnicsuperstore.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Lots of products and categories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses &LR; : Hard to find individual items.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ San Francisco Herb Co &LR; .  &LR; www.sfherb.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Terrific variety of products from a local retailer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Requires a minimum order.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Eco-Organics USA &LR; .  &LR; www.eco-organics.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Good variety of organic produce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Simple in design.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ American Spice Co &LR; .  &LR; www.americanspice.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Wide variety.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Barebones appearance. Delivery charge.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; VEGETABLE COUSCOUS
</P>
<P>
   Recipe from Marlena Spieler.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Stew
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow or white onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ras el hanout or curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 sweet potato, peeled and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 turnip, peeled and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 head cabbage, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound green beans
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   11/2 to 2 quarts broth of choice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked chickpeas
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 to 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Couscous
</P>
<P>
   2 cups couscous grains (traditional or quick-cooking)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 2/3 cup dark or golden raisins, or chopped dried
apricots, figs or dates
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Harissa sauce
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; To make the stew:  &LR; Saute the onion and half of the garlic
in the olive oil for 5 to 10 minutes, or until the onion softens.
Add the paprika, cumin, turmeric, coriander, ginger, ras al hanout,
cloves and cinnamon. Let cook for a few moments, then add the
remaining garlic, the vegetables, tomatoes and broth. Simmer for
about 40 minutes, or until the vegetables are tender. Add the
chickpeas and cook until heated through. Season with salt, pepper
and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make traditional couscous:  &LR; Rinse traditional couscous
grains in cold water. Spread in a baking pan and set aside for 15
minutes. Rake through the grains with your fingertips, breaking up
the lumps. Line a steamer or top of a couscousiere with
cheesecloth. Place the grains inside; cover and steam over
simmering water for 15 minutes. Spread the grains in the baking
pan, sprinkle with cool water and rake through them again.
</P>
<P>
   To finish: Just before serving, add the raisins and return the
couscous to the cloth-lined steamer. Cook over simmering water for
15 to 20 minutes. Toss with the butter and cinnamon. Heap onto a
platter and top with the stew. Pass harissa at the table.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make quick-cooking couscous:  &LR; Combine the quick-cooking
couscous with an equal amount of cold water. Cover and set aside
for 15 minutes, until the water has been absorbed. Transfer to a
baking dish. Add the raisins, cover tightly, and bake in a 425
degrees oven for 20 minutes, or until hot. Remove from the oven,
fluff with a fork, then toss with the butter and cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 715 calories, &LR;   &LR; 23 g protein, 122 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 18 g fat (7 g saturated), 25 mg cholesterol, 77 mg
sodium, 11 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _ Mole: Latino food sites dot the Net &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Lesli Neilson &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Cooking an authentic Oaxacan mole might be
challenging for a Northern Californian but could the Internet be
used to bridge the gap between us and our Southern neighbors? With
South to North columnist Jacqueline Higuera McMahan's mole recipe
in hand, we went to the Net to get some of the ingredients and came
up with the following finds:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; CMC Co. &LR;   &LR; www.thecmccompany.com/mexico.htm &LR;  offers many
Mexican products. Dried ancho chiles were $6 for 6 ounces and
guajillo chiles were $7 for 6 ounces. Ibarra Mexican chocolate
costs $3.75 for 18 ounces and Mexican cinnamon,  &LR; canela &LR; , is $2.50
for six 5-inch sticks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the extensive Mexican category, the site covers
ingredients for Thai, Japanese, Chinese, Indian and Jamaican
cuisines. Clicking on a product name will bring up a helpful
description. The site is easy to navigate and response is quick.
Simple but effective graphics are a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The site does have a major flaw _ the capability to select items
and place them in a cyber shopping basket is not yet available. It
is necessary to fill out an order form and e-mail it, print it out
and send it by snail mail or fax, or call in your order. But this
is scheduled to change next month. Delivery is through UPS, and
charge is based on weight of the order.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Buchanan Hollow Nut Co. &LR;  Located off Highway 99 near Merced,
the little town of Le Grand is home to this Northern California nut
company. Rudimentary in design, the Web site  &LR; www.bhnc.com &LR;  does
carry a handful of products, including the almonds and dark raisins
we were looking for. It is necessary to print out the order form to
make purchases. Shipping costs are determined by weight and is
through UPS.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Latin Grocer. &LR;  Although I wasn't able to find fresh plantains
on  &LR; www.latingrocer.com &LR; , I did find ancho and guajillo dried
chiles, sesame seeds and oregano. Set up like a grocery store, this
Miami-based Web site has colorful graphics with quick response
time. Among its offerings: Latin food and music, vitamins, beauty
products, housewares and electronics. Simply place purchases in the
shopping cart and check out.
</P>
<P>
   UPS ground shipping is free for non-perishable items (which are
sent next-day for a fee).
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cuban Food Market &LR; . We were very excited to find
 &LR; www.cubanfoodmarket.com &LR;  _ this site had the fresh plantains our
recipe called for. Unfortunately, due to California's regulations
regarding accepting exotic fruit and vegetables, we were unable to
purchase them.
</P>
<P>
   The site is divided into categories: groceries &AMP; produce,
kitchen &AMP; accessories, gifts &AMP; baskets, clothing &AMP; accessories,
books &AMP; videos and memorabilia &AMP; music. The design of the Web site
is pretty simplistic and the colors are gaudy. A search for
plaintains led us to a quick 22 results. But switching between
categories can be slow. Ground shipping is free for orders of
$17.99 or more. Otherwise, charges are $4.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MOLE INGREDIENTS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ CMC Co. &LR;   &LR; www.thecmccompany.com/mexico.htm &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Wide range of chiles, Mexican and other ethnic
ingredients; site easy to get around; good graphics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  No cyber shopping basket system yet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Buchanan Hollow Nut Co. &LR;   &LR; www.bhnc.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Good selection of nuts and dried fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Cannot order on the site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Latin Grocer &LR; .  &LR; www.latingrocer.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Good assortment of dried chiles and spices, as well as
other Latin products like music tapes. Colorful graphics; quick
response time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  No fresh ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cuban Food Market &LR; .  &LR; www.cubanfoodmarket.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Carries fresh produce, but can't be shipped to
California. But the non-fresh products can, and there are lots of
those, including non-food items.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Web site looks simplistic, and can be difficult to
switch between categories.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MOLE COLORADITO OAXAQUENO
</P>
<P>
   Serve this red chile sauce from Jacqueline McMahan over roasted
or poached chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ancho chiles
</P>
<P>
   4 guajillo chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 large tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 yellow or white onion
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whole blanched almonds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 plantain, or 1/4 banana
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2-inch piece canela (Mexican cinnamon)
</P>
<P>
   1 piece pan dulce, or 1 slice French bread, toasted
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Ibarra Mexican chocolate (1/2 round), broken into small
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Toast the ancho and guajillo chiles in a dry skillet over
medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes. Transfer the chiles to a bowl
and cover with boiling water. Cover and let steep for 45 minutes,
pushing the chiles down into the liquid from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the tomatoes, onion and garlic in a 400 oven for 25
minutes. At the same time, put the almonds and sesame seeds in
separate pie tins, place in the oven and toast for 5 minutes. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the plantain and slice in long diagonal pieces. Fry the
pieces in 1 tablespoon of the oil in a nonstick skillet until
golden. (If you use a banana, peel it but do not fry.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove the stems and seeds from the soaked chiles. Place the
chiles in a blender (do not use a food processor), add the
tomatoes, onion, garlic and 1 cup water. Puree (do this in batches,
if necessary).
</P>
<P>
   Combine the toasted sesame seeds, almonds, raisins, cloves and
cinnamon in a spice grinder or electric coffee mill reserved for
spices; grind to a fine powder. Add to the chile-tomato mixture in
the blender. Process to blend. Add the sauteed plantain, the bread,
oregano, pepper and salt. Process until pureed.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 1 tablespoon oil in a heavy pot; add the
pureed ingredients, the chocolate and 1 cup of the chicken broth
(use more, if necessary, to thin the mole). Simmer for 30 minutes,
stirring frequently (be sure to stir down to bottom of pot). Be
cautious, as mole tends to splatter.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 quart mole; enough to serve 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 165 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 18 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 10 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 168 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; _ Sambar: Indian recipe calls for unusual spices &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mildred Fernandes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Like other make-or-break ingredients, there's
something about fresh curry leaves that defies explanation. Purists
of Southern Indian cuisine swear by this leaf, homesick Indians
worship it, and there's nothing quite like the smell of it
overpowering golden-fried onions freckled with mustard seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, trying to source curry leaves online was like
trying to get a tan in a San Francisco summer: time-consuming and
often unsuccessful. This unique spice grows well in tropical climes
and is, sadly, quite perishable, which means it can survive for
only three days outside the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   These difficulties mean that only a smidgen of online retailers
offer fresh curry leaves, and in varying doses. Since this was the
hardest spice to find, it quickly became my benchmark for
evaluating Indian grocery Web sites. Most sites offer dried curry
leaves, which I recommend avoiding at all costs. It's far too easy
for them to leave an acrid aftertaste that no amount of pleading
and tweaking will diminish.
</P>
<P>
   The following sites are my recommendations, listed in order of
preference:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Namaste. &LR;   &LR; www.namaste.com. &LR;  The guru of all online Indian
grocery stores, Namaste.com offers just about everything Indian. A
search for turmeric, for example, yielded turmeric powder in a
variety of packages, as well as turmeric skin cream, a popular
herbal cleanser.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the two places that stocks fresh curry leaves,
which they will ship via two-day special freight. The downside is
that they're only available by the pound and a pound costs a hefty
$31.99. Ideal if you're running a South Indian restaurant, but an
expensive and overwhelming stash otherwise. There's also free
shipping for orders over $30, but without the curry leaves, you'd
need to buy a whole lot to take advantage of that.
</P>
<P>
   The blurbs that accompany every ingredient are a perfect touch.
A site as extensive as this can be a little time-heavy to navigate,
and Namaste.com scores again with a handy database. I popped in
every individual ingredient I was looking for and it gave me the
option to buy any of the ones it found. Other little things I
liked: 1) leaving your name and information for future shopping is
an option, which was perfect for a test driver like me, and 2) they
had pomegranate seeds.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Patel Brothers. &LR;   &LR; www.patelbrothersusa.com. &LR;  A no-frills
little site that's a good example of the legendary Gujrati knack
for business. This was my second favorite site because they include
a number you can call to place an order for fresh curry leaves ($1
per ounce, plus a two-day shipping fee _ since this company is
located in New York). A slow server and clunky design restrain this
site, as does its lack of bells and whistles (like pictures of
ingredients), but it is a spunky little site with a lot of promise.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mahabazaar. &LR;   &LR; www.mahabazaar.com. &LR;  Ace customer service,
prompt replies to e-mail queries. Lots of background information
about the owners, which was reassuring. No pictures and the actual
order form can get annoying, but there's a lot of potential here.
Easy to navigate, thoughtfully put together: the checklist offers a
``quantities'' column and an ``add-to-cart'' column.
</P>
<P>
   However, no fresh curry leaves, and they tragically tried to
convince me that the dried would do just fine. Saving grace: They
offer fresh mangoes.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; India Plaza. &LR;   &LR; www.indiaplaza.com. &LR;  Offers the options of
shopping in the United States, Britain or India, which is a pretty
tall order for a single site. There's a lot of stuff here and it
takes awhile to get down to the actual grocery shopping. The sheer
volume of goods means they list groceries by alphabetical order,
which can get crazy if you're not sure whether ``curry leaves'' is
spelled ``kari leaves.'' Patience is a must.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Caveats: &LR;  All the online Indian supermarkets I found listed
different brands for individual spices: You could choose between
MTR, Shan, Rajah, MDH or Badshah versions of garam masala, for
example. Even the prices vary, so unless you've used a particular
brand before or can view or take a whiff of its contents to guess
its authenticity, this is definitely one of the downsides of online
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Specialty spices. &LR;  If you're buying saffron, curry leaves or
fresh mangoes, seeing really is believing. If it's expensive,
perishable or if there's a particular type of mango you're looking
for, then it's almost impossible to be satisfied online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INDIAN INGREDIENTS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ India Plaza &LR; .  &LR; www.indiaplaza.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Offers a large assortment of products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  Groceries listed in alphabetical order, which is a
deterrent if you're not sure of the spelling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mahabazaar &LR; .  &LR; www.mahabazaar.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Ace customer service; easy to navigate; thoughtfully
put together; prompt replies to e-mail queries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  No pictures; the order form can get annoying.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Namaste &LR; .  &LR; www.namaste.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  Offers just about everything Indian. Easy to navigate,
with detailed product descriptions (including pictures) and easy
search functions. Free shipping on orders over $30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  This is a huge site. It takes a little time to
navigate, but that can be half the fun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Patel Brothers &LR; .  &LR; www.patelbrothersusa.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pluses: &LR;  A no-frills site, but it includes a number to call if
you have questions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Minuses: &LR;  A slow server and clunky design. Bare-bones product
information.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; INDIAN SAMBAR
</P>
<P>
   This recipe from Laxmi Hiremath is kind of a cross between soup
and stew.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup toovar dal, or dried yellow split peas
</P>
<P>
   31/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped tomato
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cauliflower, in 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sliced carrots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup green beans, cut into 1/2-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon tamarind concentrate, dissolved in 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sambar powder, homemade or store-bought
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro + chopped cilantro for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   15 fresh kari leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 dried red chiles, stemmed, broken into pieces
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the dal and water in a large saucepan. Bring to a boil,
reduce the heat to medium and cook until the dal is soft, about 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomato, cauliflower, carrots and beans. Simmer, covered,
until the vegetables are tender, about 10 minutes. Add the tamarind
liquid, sambar powder, cayenne, salt, sugar and cilantro. Cover and
simmer for 10 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a large tureen, cover and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a small frying pan over medium-high heat. Add
the mustard and cumin seeds. When the seeds pop, immediately add
the turmeric, kari leaves and chiles. Stir for half a minute, then
pour over the sambar. Ladle into bowls; garnish with a sprinkling
of cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 119 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 19 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 230 mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
