<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETMAGS-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 MAGAZINES: Online versions of publications vary widely  &HT;       
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Read it online! Get recipes online!
<P>
   Your favorite food magazine may be touted as offering these
tempting options, but don't cancel your subscription just yet.
There is valuable information you can get with a few clicks of your
mouse _ including some recipes _ but it's far from complete and, in
some instances, barely more than a teaser.
</P>
<P>
   Print magazines are not in the business of putting themselves
out of business. So in many instances, the magazine's Web site is
filled mostly with information on how to subscribe to the
paper-and-ink product rather and on purchasing special merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   We checked out a sampling of some of the best-known food
magazines and found that their online offerings vary widely. All
give you subscription information, sometimes with promotional
discounts; most offer one or two free sample issues; all let you
bookmark what free recipes they carry or send them to a third
party; and several offer weekly e-mail newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what's available is free, but some sites charge. Some
give you listings of recipes that ran in past issues, but you'll
have to order those issues _ and pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bon Appetit &LR;  and  &UR; Gourmet &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.epicurious.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The two Conde Nast publications, which you can find on
Epicurious, were the most user friendly of the sites we perused,
with lots of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   You don't get the whole magazine, but you can find a great deal
_ enough, if nothing else, to whet your appetite for the whole
product, which might just be the idea behind the Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cooking Light &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.cookinglight.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the more frustrating sites. It has some
interesting features _ an explanation of test kitchen procedures
and a virtual tour of the kitchens _ and you can call up some 2,000
recipes. But the indexed list of year-to-year recipes seems
pointless; it's just a list.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Fine Cooking &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.finecooking.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fine Cooking has extensive listings but few recipes online, and
it is complicated to search. The main thrust here seems to be to
sell back issues _ at $5.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Food &AMP; Wine &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; www.foodandwine.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FoodandWine.com gives you a recipe of the day the moment you
sign on but not much more in the way of recipes. There is an
easy-to-use wine search that lets you find, say, a Sonoma County
Chardonnay in a price and quality range you determine. Once you
have found that wine, you can also click for foods that would be a
good match _ sans recipes.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cuisine &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.cuisinemagazine.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cuisine magazine has a good number of free recipes done in
cooking-class style: Ingredients are listed on the left third or so
of the screen, with step-by-step pictures to the right. This is a
helpful approach, especially when dealing with unfamiliar
ingredients or techniques.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cook's Illustrated &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.cooksillustrated.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This site has a limited number of articles and recipes, plus a
free newsletter, but if you want the full content of the magazine,
you have to subscribe to the Web site: $19.95 a year if you also
subscribe to the print magazine; $24.95 if you don't, or $3.95 for
one month. This is not unreasonable, since Cook's Illustrated
operates on principles similar to Consumer Reports: No advertising
or other promotional revenue. This policy assures a high degree of
independence _ and it means that online or in print, you are not
assaulted by a clutter of advertising and special promotions.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Atlantic Monthly &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.atlanticmonthly.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Monthly is not the first magazine you think of when you
are interested in food, but the excellent, frequently amusing food
articles and cookbook reviews make for good reading. They can be
found at the magazine's online site, Atlantic Unbound.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Vegetarian Times &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; www.vegetariantimes.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This site offers few free recipes, but you can order articles
and/or recipes for $3 each and back issues for $6.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Saveur &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The very literary magazine disdains going on the Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
