<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-PICKLES-NYT &LR;      09-12 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICKLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MYSTERY OF THE PICKLE JAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DULCIE LEIMBACH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wilfred Kean is famous for his dill pickles, but on one
particular day last fall, he couldn't make them by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Wilfred, 86, is my neighbor at our weekend place in Equinunk, a
fleck of a town overlooking the Delaware River in the northeastern
corner of Pennsylvania. He had called me over, so I followed him
into his comfortable kitchen, with its flowered linoleum floor,
sparkling white stove and porcelain sink, all of which his wife,
Grace, keeps immaculate. Grace is also mindful of her pantry,
stocking it with so many sugary items that my daughter always
manages a visit, even though Wilfred's gravelly voice and teasing
manner scare the daylights out of her.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, Wilfred stood stooped at the sink, his arthritic
hands as gnarled as ginger root, his body not cooperating, leaving
him unable to stand for too long. ``Hold them like this, Delsey,''
he instructed, mispronouncing my name, as he has for 12 years, as
he showed me how to scrub the small black warts off one of his
Kirby cucumbers, of which, I noticed, there were a bucketful.
Inwardly I sighed, aware that the many tasks on my own to-do list
were about to be slighted in this venture. Still, I was drawn to
the job. I had rinsed many cucumbers, but never scrubbed. I was
curious, too, about the makings of these pickles.
</P>
<P>
   He handed me a small plastic brush, and I picked up the first
cucumber and whisked away, removing every black knob. Then I looked
down at the bucket and realized I had to pace myself better if I
was to last at the sink.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wilfred sat down at the kitchen table and mumbled
through a monologue about how no one helped him pick the cucumbers
in his garden but how everyone wanted his pickles, about the bald
eagles he'd seen nesting on the Delaware last winter and about the
virtues of sweet pickles, which he makes occasionally. ``Can't
write the recipe down,'' he said. ``A recipe ain't worth the
woof.''
</P>
<P>
   Although I was swamped with cukes, Wilfred's dill pickles were
worth it: Crunchy on the outside, firm on the inside and snappy
with garlic, they lived far beyond the pale of any other pickles I
had ever known.
</P>
<P>
   With the cucumbers washed and Wilfred pleased with my efforts,
we prepared the brine: Water, cider vinegar, sugar and canning
salt, all boiled in a big pot. I looked at the recipe written in
Grace's girlish cursive on notepaper, thinking I would be able to
recall it by memory when I got back to the city, but it drifted out
of my head, just as my grandmother's recipe for lemon cake with
lemon icing had died with her 25 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The brine heating up, we started to pack two gallon-size jars.
At the bottom Wilfred dropped a handful of dill, and then threw in
a bunch of chopped white onions as I sliced a garlic pod on top.
Next came the cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start with the smallest ones,'' Wilfred said. ``Then put the
ones that look pregnant in the next layer. You can slice the ones
that are too big _ just put them face down. Put the curve side
against the jar. Don't leave any gaps. Fill the middle with the
tiny ones. There you go.''
</P>
<P>
   The jar was now two-thirds full _ time to insert more dill,
onions and garlic. It was hard for Wilfred to stick his hand in the
jar, so I put the dill in for him, though he managed the onions,
dropping some on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   As time ticked away, I fleetingly wondered what was happening
across the lawn in my own house. It had been ages since I had
lingered in any kitchen, and though this had felt self-indulgent at
first, it now felt totally right. Wasn't I old enough to dawdle?
How long did I have to wait? My 80s? The last time I had spent so
many hours in a kitchen was probably the summer of 1963, when as a
young girl I stayed with my grandmother in her bungalow in New
Jersey. Day after day, I'd watch as she stirred her cake batters,
popped the pans in the oven and sat down to a good, hot cup of tea
despite an indoor temperature of 90.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get any more cucumbers in here,'' I complained to
Wilfred, slightly annoyed that he expected me to find space where
there was none.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, come on, there's plenty of room,'' he grumbled as I
searched for possible victims. ``Pack them in. You don't want a jar
of floating cucumbers, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   The brine had been boiling a few minutes. I asked Wilfred again
how he made sweet pickles. ``By guess and by God,'' he said, waving
his hand but elaborating. ``You use four times as much sugar than
in dill pickles. You got to go with your taste. The brine must be
sweet but still quite sour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who gave you these recipes?'' I prodded some more. I knew
Wilfred had grown up on a farm, had even worked his own a few years
before he switched to construction and ended up on a state road
crew. ``Delsey, you know these recipes are from a hundred years
ago,'' Wilfred chastised, putting an end to my query.
</P>
<P>
   We put the packed jars in a plastic basin and ladled the hot
brine in, sure to fill every cranny. We then threw in a teaspoon of
mustard seed _ to keep the pickles fresh longer _ and let the
pickles set before topping them off with more brine. The pickles
would need to stay refrigerated over the months it took to eat
them.
</P>
<P>
   The last steps _ leaving the jars out until they cooled down
before refrigerating them _ I left to Wilfred. The afternoon had
nearly vanished, and I could see my husband approaching Wilfred's
house, a weary look in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   We made the pickles with Wilfred another time. Grace helped, and
my husband prepared the brine. ``He was afraid you wouldn't do it
right,'' Wilfred said jokingly, trying to catch me off guard. As we
took a noontime break, my daughter and I sat with Wilfred under his
carport, as he hand-fed a chipmunk.
</P>
<P>
   He told a story about the white swans that swam in the Delaware
within view of our houses, how a mother had laid her tail down flat
and her babies walked right up it onto her back and they all
floated away. How nice, I mused _ much like a day making pickles.
</P>
<P>
   DILL PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Wilfred Kean
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus 24 hours' marinating and refrigerating
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup noniodized salt or canning salt
</P>
<P>
   { cup (packed) fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   3 white onions, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3{ to 4 pounds small Kirby cucumbers, well scrubbed (to fill
1-gallon jar)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon mustard or celery seed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Sterilize 1-gallon glass jar and lid by immersing in boiling
water for 10 minutes. Remove from water, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In large enameled, glass or other nonreactive saucepan,
combine 6 cups water with the cider vinegar, sugar and salt. Bring
to boil, reduce heat to low and then simmer mixture while
proceeding with recipe.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place a third of the dill in bottom of jar. Top with a third
each of the onion and garlic. Starting with smallest cucumbers,
pack 1 layer horizontally over garlic. Place another layer
crosswise over first. Continue until jar is two-thirds full,
packing jar tightly and filling gaps with cucumbers halved
lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add another third of the dill, followed by another third each
of onion and garlic. Top with cucumbers, packing tightly. Top with
remaining dill, onion and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   5. Place jar in large plastic basin and carefully pour hot
vinegar mixture (brine) into jar to fill it completely. Using a
long wooden skewer, gently nudge the pickles deep in the jar to
dislodge any air bubbles. Add more brine, if necessary, and allow
to sit 5 minutes. Add more brine to fill the jar to the brim, and
top with mustard seed. If using glass lid, place lid directly on
jar. If using metal lid, to prevent corrosion place large piece of
wax paper over top of jar before fastening lid.
</P>
<P>
   6. Let mixture cool to room temperature. Remove jar from basin,
and wipe clean with damp sponge. Refrigerate jar at least 24 hours
before eating. The pickles may be refrigerated for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 20 to 25 pickles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
