<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFOOD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 It's a Weird Wired World for Cooks Who Surf the Net   By Kim Severson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Fran Goss, 55, runs a bed and breakfast near
Yosemite. She considers herself a kitchen sophisticate and a darn
fine baker.
<P>
   Sue Kim, 22, pumps software for Bluemartini.com in San Mateo.
She lives in San Francisco and doesn't cook much. She can, however,
name a dozen of the city's best chefs.
</P>
<P>
   As cooks, they are worlds apart. Yet they both recently sat at
their computers searching for solutions to culinary dilemmas.
Gross' peach trees were weighed down with fruit; Kim had become
obsessed with some five-pound bags of catfish she had seen at
Costco.
</P>
<P>
   Their common experience demonstrates the tentative, early
courtship between two pursuits dear to the Bay Area _ food and
cyberspace. Yet, although the Internet has promised to
revolutionize how we live, the wonders of the Web have yet to make
it into the kitchen. Online grocery shopping sales remain flat,
cooking Web sites battle to be recognized and diners and
restaurateurs still rely on the telephone to handle reservations.
</P>
<P>
   How long will it be until the Internet invades America's
stomach? Experts are divided. Some say food is a latecomer to the
cyber revolution because of the nature of eating _ a tactile
experience built on smell and taste that the Internet can never
replicate. Others say demographics are to blame _ many accomplished
cooks with a honed knowledge of food and wine tend to be older than
the generation that takes the Internet for granted.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, food and the Internet are mixing like, well, oil
and water. Among sizzling e-commerce categories like computers, CDs
and books, food is barely a blip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monumental challenge,'' says Bill Wallace, culinary
director of Tavolo, a Web site that mixes specialty food and
equipment sales with recipes and content from food magazines, ``is
to express on the Internet the wonderful sensual quality of food
and the art of cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Food made up less than 1 percent of the $440 billion in online
sales last year, according to Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   _ No food site was among the 50 most visited, according to a
July report by Media Matrix, which tracks Internet activity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Foodtv.com, a companion site to a popular cooking network,
generated the most traffic of any food site. But even that site's
1.147 million monthly ``visitors'' pale next to the 6.2 million
visitors logged each month by sites like Freelotto.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are not yet ready to transfer this care-giving
function (buying food) to a detached process like online
shopping,'' said Mary Brett Whitfield, an analyst with
PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people who have their feet in both worlds predict the Web
stands to revolutionize how Americans _ especially those in Middle
America _ eat. Cyber-analyst International Data Corp. predicts that
online grocery shopping, which accounted for about $200 million in
sales in 1999, will reach $8.8 billion by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But food on the Internet is not just about buying groceries. The
Web is dramatically impacting politics and consumer issues like
food safety.
</P>
<P>
   When the Department of Agriculture recently proposed changes in
rules regarding irradiation and egg processing, tens of thousands
of responses to the changes were logged by e-mail. And
organizations focusing on hot-button issues like organic
regulations and genetically altered food use the Internet to drive
the public debate. With e-mail and Web sites, Berkeley's
Frankenfood protesters, for example, can be instantly linked with
their European counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   And the most recent results of an annual food safety study
conducted by CMF &AMP; Z Communications shows that last year 23 percent
of those surveyed used the Internet to learn about the issue. This
year, that number jumped to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area restaurateurs are cautiously optimistic about how the
Web will affect their future. Reservations and restaurant reviews
can increasingly be found online, and chefs in Bay Area kitchens
are using the Internet to order food and handle reservations and
patron preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wilson, a 23-year-old information specialist in San
Francisco, eats out five to seven times week at restaurants he
often picks from the Internet, checking hours and sometimes making
reservations _ if the restaurant is as wired as he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do it at work very quickly since I'm on the Internet
anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But industry watchers point out that it's still early in the
game. Carolyn Everson of Zagat.com likens the online reservation
revolution to the cyber travel industry. Only about 10 percent of
all travel reservations are expected to be made online by 2003, she
said. And restaurant industry is far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see 20 or 30 percent of the population making online
restaurant reservations in the next two years,'' she said.
``Consumers need time to trust it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chefs also fear the personal touch might be lost in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that it never goes completely Internet,'' says Doug
Washington, general manager at Jardiniere in San Francisco about
restaurant reservations. While he's happy with OpenTable.com, he
talks about a woman who called him one day, explaining she had
forgotten to make reservations for that night for her husband's
birthday. The restaurant was booked, but Washington was able to fit
her in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she'd tried to make reservations online, she would have
seen the restaurant was full and she would have gone somewhere
else,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Those chefs who have turned to the Internet to order ingredients
praise its efficiency, but worry about losing personal contact with
their purveyors _ the people who provide the raw ingredients that
can make or break a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Obranovich, executive chef at Left Bank in Larkspur,
orders about 70 percent of his food through the Internet, but he
still goes to the farmers' market twice a week. ``You need to be in
touch with local growers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the Internet is going to affect the Bay Area food
scene has yet to be revealed, maintains Wallace of Tavolo.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, a pioneer in the food specialty ingredient industry,
believes food fanatics in San Francisco will use the Internet for
recipe ideas, to learn about food from other cultures and to keep
up on the region's artisan food producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet will provide access, but many people in San
Francisco don't need that kind of access,'' he said. ``Where I live
now I can walk a half a block or two to Clement Street and find
almost any ingredient from around the world. But people who live in
Missoula or Davenport, Iowa, can't.''
</P>
<P>
   As America continues to get more sophisticated about food,
people in less populated, less food-driven environs will want to be
able to order Filipino spices, Chinese noodles or even artisan goat
cheese from Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all over the country are attuned to wonderful food but
they're just not enough people in many places to support a store
that carries 75-year-old balsamic vinegar,'' he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet certainly has enhanced bed and breakfast owner Fran
Goss' culinary life. She lives in the mountains, and the closest
grocery store in Mariposa isn't exactly the multicultural culinary
wonderland of Berkeley Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great. If I do want to buy something I don't have to go
to Fresno or the coast,'' she said. ``It has really revolutionized
my cooking. I don't feel so isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also changed life for Sue Kim, the San Francisco
dot-commer. A year ago, she organized a dining club using an online
bulletin board to find people who wanted to eat at the same
restaurants she did. And when she decides to cook she turns to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the office until 7 or 8 p.m. some nights,'' she said.
``So I've got the laser printing going and I print a couple recipes
out really quick and maybe hit the Trader's Joe's on the way
home.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chronicle staff writer Robin Davis contributed to this story. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
