<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODINTRO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Dot-com Food: A user's guide to recipes, ingredients,
equipment,  restaurants, wine and more   By The Chronicle Food Staff  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For the adventurous cook, the Internet seems like
a dream.
 &HT;    Want to make Laotian catfish stew or a vegetable Moroccan
couscous? A wired cook need merely download a recipe, check in with
a few other online cooks for tips on technique and then click over
to order the ingredients and the pots to cook it in.
 &HT;    But reality has a way of smashing dreams. Type ``couscous'' into
a popular search engine and you get 15,500 entries. It's like
trying to get a drink of water from a fire hose.
 &HT;    When it comes to reading about restaurants online, most
restaurant Web sites are fine for hours and menus, but even the
most popular portals have out-of-date information.
 &HT;    In this week's special Food issue, we've devoted ourselves to
helping Bay Area cooks find their way around the brave new world
that blends food and technology. We've cooked recipes we pulled off
``the Net.'' We've sent our best cooks surfing to find their top
recipe sites. We've researched how to order ethnic ingredients and
compared shopping for equipment online versus what can be found in
stores.
 &HT;    As we've rated sites and picked our favorites, we've tried to
keep in mind the practical needs of cooks with average computer
equipment. Using the Internet is a lot like cooking _ if you don't
have good equipment, both pursuits can become difficult And, we've
researched with an eye toward people who might not have much skill
navigating the Web. So whether you think a search engine is stored
in a garage or you surf Google daily, you'll find something here to
help you use the Internet to enhance your kitchen.
 &HT;     By Kim Severson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
