<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-HANOVER-GERMANY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANOVER OPENS WINDOWS ON PAST AND FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material, the seventh destination
column in the MICHELIN ON TRAVEL feature from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by MICHELIN clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos and a map of Hanover are available on Newscom
or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREW ROSENBAUM &QL; 
 &UR; c.2000 by Michelin. &QL; 
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people come to Hanover each year, but most of them
never see the city.
</P>
<P>
   The two great exhibitions, this year's world's fair, EXPO 2000,
and the world's largest information technology show, CeBIT, each
hosted in a 2-million-foot space outside the city, attract all
their attention. But those who do take the time to see Hanover find
a jewel box of history and art.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this important German port was destroyed in World War
II, but there are still beautiful public buildings and gardens plus
several notable collections of modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors arriving at Hanover's main railroad station are greeted
by a red arrow which leads them along a three-mile walk past the
city's principal treasures. Although the walk takes less than three
hours to complete, it spans medieval to modern times.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up the red thread at the Hanover Tourist Information booth
at Ernst-Augustplatz not far from the station.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to bypass the first stop on the tour, Galerie
Luise, the high-roofed shopping gallery with a selection of
international stores _ (come back later to shop at your leisure) _
and head straight for the old Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Originally built between 1845 and 1852, this three-tiered
neo-Palladian gem gives viewers their first taste of the classic
architecture favored by the Hanoverian princes. The Opera House
burned down during the war, but was rebuilt in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   When you pick up the red trail again, it will lead you to
Georgstrasse, Hanover's main thoroughfare. Here you will find
19th-century cafes and some monumental sculpture. Don't miss the
four stone statues of famous Hanover burghers, who, these days,
ogle the traffic below.
</P>
<P>
   Breeze past the one-time headquarters of Europe's largest bank,
Deutsche Bank, and head straight for the haunting Aegidienkirche.
In 1347, pious Hanoverians began to build a Gothic church to
replace a 12th-century Romanesque basilica on this site. This
church was destroyed on October 9, 1943 by Allied bombs. Today,
only the walls remain. Inside the bombed-out church is a peace bell
presented by another war-torn city, Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   As you proceed down the red trail, you will go from the historic
to the post-modern at the Kubus Galerie, which regularly hosts
shows by well-known contemporary artists. Hanover has a thriving
gallery scene of which Kubus is only one example.
</P>
<P>
   After this, move on to Hanover's best-known cultural monument,
the Rathaus (City Hall), which dominates the lake in front of it.
With its carved stone walls and its copper-roofed turrets, it looks
far older than it is. It took 12 years to build and opened in June
1913.
</P>
<P>
   Skip the tour of the interior _ the outside is much more
interesting _ but take a few minutes to ascend the tower and get a
panoramic view of the entire city.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to pause at the Kestner Museum after that. The
building itself with its 5000 windows, is unusual. The collection
includes ancient coins, antiquities from Egypt and Rome and
European decorative art.
</P>
<P>
   Another important museum, the Sprengel, is just a short distance
away from the Rathaus. Bernhard Sprengel, a chocolate manufacturer
in Hanover, began collecting modern art in 1937 to preserve it from
Nazi destruction. He has left a thrilling collection of art from
the greatest masters of the 20th century including Paul Klee, Max
Beckmann, Pablo Picasso and Hanoverian-born Kurt Schwitters.
</P>
<P>
   When you leave the Sprengel, retrace your steps to a bridge that
crosses the Leine River. (The name ``Hannover'' as it is spelled in
German, comes from ``hohen ufer,'' referring to the high banks of
the Leine river.) On the far side are some of the most outrageous
monumental sculptures in the world _ Niki de Saint-Phalle's buxom,
curvaceous and colorful ``Nana's'' who cavort with decidedly
un-Germanic abandon. When they were first installed on this site in
1974, petitions were circulated to have them removed. However, they
stayed and are now much loved fixtures in the Hanoverian landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The path will now lead you into the ``Altstadt,'' a quarter that
dates back to medieval times. Here you can see some half-timbered
houses from the 13th and 14th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Move a bit faster here, but don't miss the ``Leineschloss,'' a
13th-century cloister with carefully sculpted columns.
</P>
<P>
   You will also want to see the old Rathaus, some of which dates
from the 15th century. It was nearly torn down in 1844, but was
saved and rebuilt in the Gothic style of 1500.
</P>
<P>
   The red trail now takes you back into the modern city, where it
ends. But there are more treasures to be savored in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   You should not miss the Herrenhausen Gardens, a 17th-century
masterpiece adorned with sculpture from Roman to Renaissance. An
avenue of lime trees connects four gardens with a 270-foot-tall
fountain in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Are you convinced? Will you leave the software of the world's
largest information technology show or the reconstructed landscapes
of EXPO 2000 for a look at this varied and marvelous city?
</P>
<P>
   Those who do will enjoy a rare day out. The rest will be able to
take advantage of two of the most unusual events anywhere in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   CeBIT, which takes place in March, is the world's largest
information technology exposition. Experts don't miss it _ they
routinely spend at least three days examining everything from the
latest in semiconductors to massive supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   And this year's world's fair _ EXPO 2000, which runs from June 1
to October 31 _ has 180 countries hosting pavilions, offering
visitors everything from fine art to fine cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the fair this year is
``Humankind-Nature-Technology'' _ that is, showing how all these
interact. A cable car carries visitors to the site and, as it is
395 acres in size (designed by Japanese architect Shigeru Ban), the
visitor should allow a few days to get a good look at it.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
 &UR; SERVICE BOX &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Follow your phone company's international dialing instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RECOMMENDED HOTELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Splurge &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maritim Grand Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Friedrichswall 11 30159
</P>
<P>
   Tel: (0511) 3 67 70
</P>
<P>
   Fax: (0511) 32 51 95
