<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TAX-AVOIDANCE-2TAKES-     09-12 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-AVOIDANCE-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP INSTRUCTS INDIVIDUALS ON CORPORATE-STYLE TAX-AVOIDANCE
SCHEMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Mo., Texas, Calif., N.Y.)   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treasury officials say that abusive corporate tax shelters are
the government's biggest tax enforcement problem, costing billions
of dollars annually. Now a company called the Tax People is
teaching similarly dubious tax avoidance techniques to middle-class
Americans and says it has already signed up 50,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   At Tax People's national convention last month, 3,500 people
hollered with delight as the group's president told them that not
only would they cut their own tax bills but they would also grow
rich by selling the same tax-advice system to other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the system, which Tax People has been selling since
late 1997, is to set up a home business. For almost everyone who
participates, that business is to sell the ``tax relief'' system to
others. Then, almost any time the taxpayer leaves the house _
whether to commute to a day job, buy groceries, play golf or go to
church _ he deducts the cost of the trip as a business expense on
the ground that everywhere he goes he is doing business recruiting
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf, hunting, fishing and even vacations with your family''
can become tax deductible expenses, asserts a brochure from the Tax
People. Learn it all for $300 down and $100 a month _ costs that
are themselves deductible.
</P>
<P>
   It does not stop there. Hire the children to clean your home
office and then provide them with a fringe benefit _ their college
education _ and deduct the cost as a business expense.
</P>
<P>
   Tax People's president, Michael Cooper, 46, of Topeka, Kan.,
said he was marketing ``a way for people to legally, ethically and
morally reduce their taxes to the absolute legal minimum so they
can get out of debt and enjoy the lifestyle they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   But a variety of seasoned tax experts who have examined the Tax
People system said they did not share Tax People's views on the
legitimacy of the techniques. ``This is very clever,'' said
Professor Charles Davenport, a Rutgers Law School tax professor,
when asked to examine the system. ``They have created a system to
cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax People is just one example of the vulnerability of the
income tax system to questionable operations in an era when
Congress has sharply reduced the resources to hunt for tax cheats
and has imposed new rules that make it difficult for IRS agents to
pursue cases.
</P>
<P>
   Tax People advertises that a family of four with $60,000 of
wages can take $33,560 in federal income tax deductions if they
have a home-based business with just $1,000 of revenue. Those
deductions would slash their federal tax bill 81 percent, to
$1,384.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, tax law requires that a business report a taxable profit
at least two of every five years, or those deductions will be
disallowed. That is no problem, said Jesse Cota, a former IRS
district director and head of Tax People's ``tax dream team.'' He
said one need only switch to a different money-losing business
every three or four years to take these deductions for life.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tax People has ardent supporters. At the San Diego convention,
Cooper introduced the Rev. Terry Thomas, a retired Army sergeant
who leads an independent congregation on the Japanese island of
Okinawa, and his wife, Phyllis, noting that their trip was a
tax-deductible expense.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said they were thrilled with the system and that
since joining in July they had signed up 33 other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tax People teaches people to be debt free, and by selling
this system we can help people do that,'' Terry Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Thomas said persons who embrace the system ``tend to be
visionary and business-oriented people.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Thomas said the integrity of Tax People was critical to
his involvement. ``We are in the business of helping people, and we
feel this is a way to help people achieve financial freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Independent tax experts say that Tax People is advertising
techniques that can be legal only in unusual circumstances and is
glossing over limits on who can use them. For example, the rule
allowing a deduction for commuting expenses applies only when one's
wage job and home business are in the same line of work and the
taxpayer can show a bona fide expense.
</P>
<P>
   As another example, the Tax People teach that the owner of a
home-based business can deduct $5,250 for each child in education
benefits if they employ the child in the business. But among the
many complex rules to qualify for this tax break, is one requiring
that the business first give the same benefit to at least 19
nonfamily employees at a cost of $99,750.
</P>
<P>
   The tax experts warned that while many of the techniques the Tax
People teach may have a patina of legality, they would not survive
an audit because they ignore complex tax rules.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the techniques are similar to some used by big companies
that have been criticized as abusive by Treasury officials, in that
they have no purpose except tax avoidance, as opposed to a
legitimate business purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But even if adherents of the Tax People abuse the rules, they
might get away with it, tax experts say. Congress has cut the
budget for auditing tax returns to historically low levels. For
those who file the kind of tax return that Tax People recommends,
there was only a one in 77 chance of being audited last year, down
from one in 31 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And if a taxpayer is audited, the IRS is more likely to pursue
further the cases of people who do not keep good business records.
Because Tax People teaches members to keep exhaustively detailed
records, even dubious deductions might make it past the IRS simply
because the deductions appear to be documented.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sheldon Cohen, the IRS commissioner during the Johnson
administration, said the IRS has the power to shut down Tax People,
but he doubted it would act.
</P>
<P>
   After examining Tax People literature, Cohen said that if Tax
People had come along in his day ``I would have issued a summons
for the names of everyone who has paid for the system and then we
would have mailed each of them a letter saying that this is not
legitimate, but if you file an amended return, then that will be
the end of it, with no penalties, but if you do not, then we will
come after you.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Charles O. Rossotti, the current tax
commissioner, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Tax People is under scrutiny by state officials in Kansas and
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, in an interview, confirmed the investigations and said
that state officials suspect, wrongly, that he is running a pyramid
scheme in which an expanding base of recruits pay fees that are
funneled up to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Stovall, the Kansas attorney general, said company records
show that virtually all of those buying the system are trying to
make money selling it to others.
</P>
<P>
   She said her attention was drawn to the company in part because
of complaints by people who said they were lured into paying four
enrollment fees with a promise that doing so would bolster their
earnings as independent marketing associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is illogical for people to buy four or more tax
relief systems unless it is to expand the pyramid,'' Stovall said.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the last six years Kansas authorities have moved
against Cooper and his marketing companies with accusations of
fraudulent and deceptive practices. He twice signed consent
decrees.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when Cooper had discovered tax avoidance as a product,
he told marketing associates that he would give each of them 1,000
shares of stock in his company, which he valued at $40 a share now
and a fortune in the near future. Kansas securities regulators
valued the shares at one five-hundredth of a penny each.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was recorded telling the associates that the stock gift
was ``double secret stuff'' that ``cannot be discussed publicly''
and expressing concern about violating securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, in an interview, said he thought his gifts of the stock
were legal. ``I had legal advisers, and I thought it was all
appropriate,'' he said. ``I paid a $10,000 fine, and I am still
giving the stock away.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who join Tax People get a slim booklet and audio tapes
that explain complex tax avoidance strategies in very simple
language.
</P>
<P>
   W. Bradford Murray, a businessman in San Rafael, Calif., is
suing Cooper and Tax People in federal court in Kansas City. Mo.,
for copyright infringement, saying much of the best tax advice in
the Tax People manual was taken verbatim from Murray's work. The
company says it acquired the rights legally through an
intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   Recruits to Tax People can also listen in on daily conference
calls with tax preparers and accountants who are affiliated with
the organization and, at the end, can ask questions about their own
tax concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In the event a return is audited, Tax People promises that its
``tax dream team'' of tax experts will represent the taxpayer. The
Tax People says it has a 100 percent success rate in audits and
that in 60 percent of the cases the IRS approves additional
reductions in the taxpayer's bill.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting in San Diego of 3,500 of what the company calls
independent marketing associates, Tax People's speakers repeatedly
characterized the ``tax dream team'' as having such prowess that
when the IRS learns who is representing the taxpayer, it quickly
``wilts.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Keith, the senior IRS spokesman, said that ``we decide
cases on the basics of facts and law, not who represents the
taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has not disclosed any documentation of his company's
claim of 100 percent success in audits and getting an increased
refund in 60 percent of cases.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has not set aside any reserves to cover the cost
of future audits. He said in an interview that if the IRS were to
make targets of his clients the company might not have the
resources to fulfill its audit representation promise. ``That's a
risk you take with any business, that they might not be there to
honor the guarantee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit guarantee itself is limited. Not only must the
marketing associate have done exactly as instructed by the Tax
People manual, meticulous records must also have been kept.
</P>
<P>
   The audit representation guarantee ends if the individual stops
paying the $100 monthly fee. Typically, IRS audits begin 18 months
or more after a tax return is filed. Thus an individual who paid
Cooper's company $6,300 over five years and then retired and
stopped paying would have no right to audit representation if his
tax returns were selected later for audit.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Siddons, a San Diego woman who bought audit protection
from Cooper's company, said she could not persuade the company to
represent her last year until she went to the Tax People sales
meetings and loudly declared that the company was not delivering on
its promises. She said Cooper eventually hired someone to represent
her but that she lost her deductions. Other clients say they were
well represented, though one said he had to pay additional taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say Tax People's Web sites make grossly inflated
promises. Many, for example, guarantee $5,000 in tax savings, when
the company actually promises only $5,000 in tax deductions.
``That's a huge difference,'' said Mike Wellman, a Texas tax
accountant who is one of a half-dozen tax professionals who have
sought in an Internet news group to debunk Tax People's statements.
``No one at the company seems to be correcting the false claims by
the marketing agents, but then what incentive does the company have
to police its sales force?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Zehr of Watertown, N.Y., said he paid $1,200 for four
subscriptions because he was told this would make him eligible for
bonus payments if he sold the system to others.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that after contacting the Better Business Bureau in
Kansas he had questions about the company and began calling its
customer-service number to stop further charges on his credit card.
``I could never get through,'' he said, so he canceled his credit
card number to stop further charges.
</P>
<P>
   Zehr said he regarded the Tax People as ``unethical, dishonest
and fraudulent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nelson of Wichita, Kan., said he, too, could not get the
company to stop charging his credit card $100 a month and the
customer-service line was answered with a recording saying that the
company was so busy processing new orders it did not have anyone
available to process cancellations. Tuesday night, he said, his
money was finally refunded, though his calls were never answered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
