<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1013 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-NUDES0913-COX     09-12 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NUDES0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Body beautiful stripped down as athletes pose for risque photos
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would you pose nearly nude?
</P>
<P>
   The question swished through the brain of swimmer Jenny Thompson
in May. The answer: a qualified no.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human body is a beautiful thing,'' said Thompson, owner of
five Olympic gold medals, with more expected to come in Sydney.
``If it's done right ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson cited a teammate who would ``do it in a heartbeat.''
Then she drew a personal line: ``I wouldn't mind posing for the
swimsuit edition'' of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   SI's Aug. 14 edition is far removed from the knockoff of a
Victoria's Secret catalog that SI sends out in the dead of winter.
But there on page 52 is Thompson wearing red boots and a
form-fitting bottom patterned after the American flag, with her
hands covering her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Her apparent change of heart touched off a debate on whether
athletes should flash excessive American skin.
</P>
<P>
   Olympians can be found in various stages of undress all over the
newsstands. Others grin and bare it on calendars that generate
charitable contributions along with either admiration or
titillation, depending on your take.
</P>
<P>
   America is downright prudish next to Australia, the Olympic host
with the most athletes au natural. Some female soccer players went
the whole nine meters with full-frontal nudity. One magazine
unveiled 29 athletes; another 20 turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just a bare-naked ladies show. The Aussie magazine
co-featured males, as did a Canadian periodical with nine jocks and
jockettes. Such gender equity is rare in the U.S., a notable
exception being cyclist Lance Armstrong, who doffed it all in
Vanity Fair last year while sufficiently obscured by his bike.
</P>
<P>
   The guys tend to be dismissed as harmless exhibitionists, if
that. Women have been accused of playing into the hands of media
inclined to present them as sexual objects.
</P>
<P>
   Some athletes said they agree to photo shoots with no cheesecake
poses in mind. They show up decently clothed. And when the camera
keeps clicking, well, stuff happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media has to be just as responsible (as the athletes),''
said Brandi Chastain, 32, soccer's poster and pin-up girl. ``Jenny
posed for more than two hours, but look at the picture they chose
to run. The same went for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there have been no loud complaints from the subjects about
any finished products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't giving a seductive look,'' Thompson, 27, said. ``I'm
a strong female athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Thompson is a finely toned athlete proud to display
pictorial evidence of her diligent work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the Jenny Thompson photo,'' Chastain said, ``my
first thought was, 'My God, where did she get those thighs?' ``
</P>
<P>
   It was not Chastain's nudity but her underwear that brought the
topic to America's radar screen. When she struck the winning goal
in last year's World Cup finals, she pulled off her jersey to
expose a sports bra that was hardly risque. But some people branded
her as a shameless showgirl.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain offered no apologies, not for her televised
pseudo-striptease or her spread in Gear magazine, where she removed
everything else and replaced it with a few well-situated soccer
balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all must make decisions for ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also defended her counterparts Down Under doing a female
full monty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Australian team did was absolutely acceptable, a very
gutsy decision,'' Chastain said. ``You can't knock them for that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Chastain acknowledged concerns that the photos
could send mixed messages to impressionable youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is not a one-timer. She teams in a more discreet shot
with Dara Torres, Amy Van Dyken and Georgian Angel Martino, who
failed to qualify for the Games, in Women's Sports &AMP; Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   High jumper Amy Acuff has appeared in Rolling Stone, Maxim,
Esquire and Glamour showing different amounts of flesh. Acuff
organized a calendar of track-and-field Olympians she is Miss July
that includes former Atlanta schoolteacher Tisha Waller, a
high-jumper who did not make the 2000 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a calendar of bimbos,'' Acuff said. ``I think it's
pretty sexist to assume that a woman can't show her body without it
being sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   The skin-is-in movement is explained easily:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most Olympic sports participants need money, and such exposure
can bring another type to companies with available endorsement and
sponsor funds.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic activities tend to attract or produce better bodies than
the more widely appreciated sports. A magazine editor might see an
athlete in the same context as an actor or a musician.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Magazines, which seem to be multiplying like rabbits, are in
an race of sorts. Nakedness generates some buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Once athletes qualify for the U.S. team, they must abide by a
code of conduct. USOC spokesman Mike Moran said: ``No one at this
point considers (posing nude) a violation. It's a personal choice
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the trend coincides with a Games in which some
competitors are covering up for their activity. Many swimmers have
exchanged their skimpy Speedos for full bodysuits designed to
propel them faster through the water. Some extend below the knee,
others all the way to the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   And female beach volleyballers got permission to bend federation
rules, which require a two-piece bikini with low-cut tops and
narrow straps on their hips. In a concession to possible cold
weather in Sydney, players can slip on shorts, one-piece suits,
even leggings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
