<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.13.00
 &HT;    Securities giants team up on new site
 &HT;    Amazon hits 2 million in U.K.
 &HT;    Wireless may reach 1.3 billion in 2004
 &HT;    IXL settles into new digs
 &HT;    Clarus launches e-conferences
 &HT;    Bass Hotels reaches out to Chinese
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVE TIME ONLINE: All stories and URLs in this column are one
click away on ajc.com/enews
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH GIANTS UNITE: Goldman Sachs, Merrill Lynch and five
other securities firms are joining forces to create a Web site to
provide their institutional customers with research and other
financial information. The site, dubbed TheMarkets.com, is set to
launch during the fourth quarter. Other firms that signed on
include Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Salomon Smith Barney, Credit
Suisse First Boston, Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown and UBS Warburg.
Multex.com, which provides securities research over the Internet,
will host and maintain the site.
</P>
<P>
   2 MILLION BRITISH ON AMAZON: Amazon.com's site in England has
reached 2 million customers, doubling its users in less than eight
months. The site has added about 125,000 new customers each month.
Amazon said it's the first European e-commerce site to reach 2
million customers.
</P>
<P>
   www.amazon.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   STAMPEDE OF WIRELESS: Every day, it seems, there's a new
partnership to bring the Internet to mobile phones. And with good
reason. The wireless data market, including handsets, personal
digital assistants and Internet appliances, is projected to grow
from about 170 million subscribers now to more than 1.3 billion in
2004, according to research firm Cahners In-Stat Group. The firm
estimates that number of wireless messages sent per month will
balloon from 3 billion a month to 244 billion by the end of 2004.
In the United States, there are more than 100 million wireless
phones now, Cahners said.
</P>
<P>
   WORKOUT AND CAFFEINE FOR iXL: Despite iXL's current financial
straits, employees are now in the process of settling in at the new
offices on Peachtree Street overlooking I-85. In addition to the
Starbucks stations on every floor and the fully equipped gym, the
building also houses a colorful collection of jukeboxes and vintage
TVs. The latter two are passions of founder Bert Ellis, who began
his collection when he ran the TV station group Ellis
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   E-CONNECTIONS BY CLARUS: Biz-to-biz fans can log on to a series
of chats this fall hosted by Clarus Corp. The Atlanta-based B2B
company is hosting Web-based conferences, including presentations
by research firms Gartner Group, Forrester Research, Yankee Group
and Giga Information Group. Clarus wants listeners to register in
advance on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   www.claruscorp.com/connections
</P>
<P>
   BASS HOTELS GOES CHINESE: Atlanta-based Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts
has beefed up its online reach with a new site for Chinese-speaking
travelers. The site has the usual info about amenities and
reservations, and it's updated with news in China. Bass, which owns
the Holiday Inn, Staybridge Suites and Inter-Continental brands,
said it's considering adding sites in other languages. Bass has 31
hotels in China.
</P>
<P>
   www.China.Basshotels.com
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   The United States far outspent the rest of the world last year
on e-commerce and information technology, according to a new report
by research firm IDC. U.S. spending on e-commerce accounted for
more than 60 percent of the $130.5 billion spent worldwide,
according to IDC. The U.S. tab for information technology reached
$385 billion, nearly half the worldwide spending on IT last year.
Japan ranked second, with about $90 billion.
</P>
<P>
   HOT/COLD NET STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Netergy Networks (NTRG), up 21 percent at $11.69. AT&AMP;T's AT&AMP;T
Labs will test Netergy's wireless home networking service.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick (DCLK), up 12 percent at $37.81. Analysts reiterated
``buy'' and ``strong buy'' ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Network Access Solutions (NASC), down 10 percent at $7.19. Fell
in wake of Monday's deal between SBC Communications and Covad
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   NetCreation (NTCR), down 43 percent to $12. Cut third-quarter
earnings estimates.
</P>
