   DRESDNER-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ On reports that Dresdner Bank
AG, Germany's third-largest bank, is in talks to buy the U.S.
investment bank Wasserstein Perella Co. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   other business stories of interest:
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-AUTOS (Seoul) _ In the wake of the financial crisis that
shook the South Korean economy almost three years ago, foreign
manufacturers _ Renault, Ford Motor and General Motors among them _
are snapping up factories and whole car companies, making direct
investments in a nation that has long turned its nose up at their
products. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-SERVER (Undated) _ Hewlett-Packard, taken to task by
investors for coming up short against Sun Microsystems in the
server market, announces a new server line and brings Carly Fiorina
to New York to explain how H-P is reinventing itself. By Barnaby J.
Feder.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ The London Stock Exchange has
abandoned its merger plan with Frankfurt, at least temporarily, in
order to defend itself against a hostile bid from OM Gruppen, the
operator of the Stockholm stock exchange. By Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
<P>
   NOMURA-MILLENNIUM-DOME (London) _ Nomura Securities, which in
recent years has been on a buying spree for particular British
institutions _ chains of pubs and betting shops _ has drawn the
line at the Millennium Dome, the Labor government's celebration of
national pride. Nomura says it is withdrawing its bid because it
was not given enough financial information. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
