<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EXECUTIONS13-COX     09-12 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTIONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RENO 'TROUBLED' BY PATTERN OF FEDERAL DEATH CASES
 &HT;    Attn: Texas papers.
 &HT;    By BRUCE HIGHT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Tuesday she is
``sorely troubled'' by a Justice Department study that shows that
blacks and Hispanics are ``overrepresented'' in federal death
penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that U.S. attorneys in a few states,
including Texas, seem to produce a high number of death penalty
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The survey today finds that minorities are overrepresented in
the federal death penatly system, as both victims and defendants,
relative to the general population,'' Reno said at a news
conference. ``Sadly, the same is true of the entire criminal
justice system, both state and federal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reno rejected calls for a moratorium on federal death
penalty cases. She said that minorities were also over-represented
among the victims and cited ``social ills and harsh conditions''
that have had a disproportionate effect on minorities.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he would consult with Reno on the study,
but acknowledged that the data raised questions because ``we're
supposed to have a uniform law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a system begun in 1995, all U.S. attorneys must submit
cases in which the defendant is eligible for the death penalty to
Reno for her review. Of 682 such cases since 1995, U.S. attorneys
recommended in 183 that she actually seek the death penalty, and
she gave approval in 159 cases.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that of the 183 recommendations to seek the
death penalty, 26 percent involved white defendants, 44 percent
blacks and 21 percent Hispanics. The rest were of some other group.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that about half of those 183 cases came
from just five states, including Texas, plus Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to concerns about the disproportionate number of
minority group members, critics noted that many of the death
penalty recommendations were coming from U.S. attorneys in
relatively few states.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 183 cases, the study showed, the four U.S. attorney's
offices in Texas recommended seeking the death penalty in 14 cases.
Of these, two defendants were white, nine were black and three were
Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. attorneys in Virginia during the same period recommended
seeking the death penalty for 25 defendants, while those in Puerto
Rico and New York each submitted 14 cases. U.S. attorneys in
Missouri had 13 such recommendations, and Tennessee had 10.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that while she is concerned about the figures, she had
not detected any bias and saw no reason to call a moratorium on
federal death penalty cases. She said the guilt of those sentenced
was not in question, and that minority group members also were
disproportionately represented among the victims of those sentenced
to death.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, there were 590 victims in the 183 cases
in which the U.S. attorney recommended the death penalty. Of those
victims, 34 percent were white, 58 percent were black and 5 percent
were Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   The number includes the 168 who died in the bombing of the
federal building at Oklahoma City. Timothy McVeigh, who is white,
has been sentenced to die in that case.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that of the 19 defendants sentenced to die
by a federal jury, six _ five black and one Hispanic _ were Texas
cases. The federal government has not actually executed anyone
since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it were chance that so many on federal death row were
from Texas, Reno said she would ``have to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the state of Texas has 445 convicted defendants
on its death row, according to the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice. Of those 445, 36 percent are white and 64 percent are
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she has asked the National Institute of Justice to
solicit research proposals on the question of why murder cases get
diverted from a state to the federal system and ``the factors
accounting for the present geographic pattern of submissions by the
U.S. attorney's offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, speaking at the same news
conference, resisted a suggestion that the study indicates the
federal system is arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can draw the conclusion that you have that
the system is arbitrary based on the numbers that we've seen so
far,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight's e-mail address is bruceh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
