<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DRESDNER-MARKETPLACE-     09-12 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRESDNER-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROPOSED MERGER SIGNALS PASSING OF SWASHBUCKLING ERA ON WALL
STREET
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.)  (Skedded earlier as DRESDNER-WASSERSTEIN) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As J.P. Morgan and Chase Manhattan Bank captured the
spotlight on Tuesday, a smaller proposed union signaled the passing
of another era on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co. is in advanced talks to be acquired by
Dresdner Bank of Germany, a person close to those discussions said.
If the two can come to terms on price _ said to be $1.2 billion to
$1.5 billion _ a deal could be announced in three to five days, the
person said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an agreement would end the reknowned firm that embodied the
swashbuckling style of dealmaking celebrated in the 1980s. It was
then that Wall Street bankers were storied media stars, reveling in
a media world captivated by the rough-and-tumble business of
hostile takeovers. Bruce Wasserstein, along with his then partner,
Joseph Perella, made their names at First Boston, which was later
acquired by Credit Suisse. It seemed that there was almost no deal
without them, including Texaco's takeover of Getty Oil and the sale
of Beatrice Cos.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the two took a core of talented bankers with them and
set up shop as Wasserstein Perella. From the start it was a dynamic
team. Wasserstein, colleagues say, is a numbers whiz with the
ability to map out the maneuvers of a hostile takeover from memory.
He is a gruff, intimidating negotiator who earned the nickname
``Bid 'em Up Bruce'' for his ability to extract the highest price
from a suitor. But his reputation suffered after the hostile
takeover of RJR Nabisco by Kohlberg Kravis, a deal in which he was
said in the book ``Barbarians at the Gate'' to have leaked
sensitive information to the press.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Wasserstein hoped to fashion himself after Felix
Rohatyn, the Lazard Freres dealmaker who went on to become the U.S.
ambassador to France, said one person who asked not to be named.
Not surprisingly, Wasserstein talked with Lazard in the past about
acquiring the firm, but those talks faltered over price, said
people involved in those talks. Wasserstein did not return calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Perella, say colleagues, was always the more affable, a
charismatic leader, liked by chief executives and the staff. But
the partnership, which was so successful at First Boston, grew
strained at Wasserstein Perella. In particular, the two clashed
over the direction their investment boutique would take and what
private investments it would make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marriage is a complex one,'' Perella told The Boston Globe
in 1990. ``Sometimes you hate your wife. Sometimes you love her.
The differences are often reconcilable.'` In this case, they were
not.
</P>
<P>
   Perella left Wasserstein in 1993 for Morgan Stanley, where he
became managing director in the investment banking department and
was later named head of that division. Despite Perella's protests,
former colleagues said, Wasserstein kept the Perella name on the
door. Perella has thrived at Morgan, spending hours with clients
and mentoring younger bankers there, leaving the day-to-day
operations to a colleague, Terry Meguid.
</P>
<P>
   But Wasserstein thrived, too. And indeed if Wasserstein's firm
gets the astounding price being discussed for the investment
advisory business, he could net as much as $750 million because he
owns more than 50 percent of the company, said a person close to
the discussions. The investment boutique is in a good place to
negotiate, particularly because bankers there are very familiar
with Dresdner's business. Wasserstein Perella helped advise
Commerzbank of Germany on its failed merger with Dresdner. This is
Dresdner's third try at a deal this year, having failed to close a
planned merger with Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   If Dresdner's talks with Wasserstein _ talks reported on Tuesday
by The Wall Street Journal _ bear fruit, the German bank will get
the long sought presence in the United States it needs to compete
on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not just about mergers,'' said Richard Strauss, a
Goldman Sachs analyst. ``It is any business generated from those
transactions to help them grow,'' such as initial public offerings
of stock and bond deals.
</P>
<P>
   One person involved in the transaction said Wasserstein would
probably be named a vice chairman of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson,
while Frank Biondi, who is the chief executive of Wasserstein and
who has been there since the beginning, would probably become
co-head of investment banking with a Dresdner official.
</P>
</TEXT>
