<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FCC0913-COX     09-12 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FCC chair pokes fun at Baby Bell maneuvers
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - In a speech to a trade conference Tuesday, the
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission criticized
regional phone companies like BellSouth, and then went off to meet
with the company's top executive.
</P>
<P>
   At the Voice on the Net conference, Chairman William Kennard
poked fun at what he said was the legal-centric way the regional
Bells had responded to demands that they open their local networks
to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this behavior `regulatory capitalism,''' Kennard said.
``Regulatory capitalism is when companies invest in lawyers,
lobbyists and politicians, instead of plant, people and customer
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard left after the speech to meet with BellSouth Chairman
and Chief Executive F. Duane Ackerman to be briefed on BellSouth's
preparations for its long-delayed request to enter the
long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've met in the past, and it's not unusual when they are in
the same city for them to have lunch,'' said BellSouth spokesman
Jeff Battcher.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has failed in both Louisiana and South Carolina to
transform local endorsement into FCC approval. In the meantime,
Verizon _ the former Bell Atlantic _ has been granted the right to
offer long-distance in New York, and SBC has won the right in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, BellSouth and various rivals have slogged through
years of hearings before the state Public Service Commission since
the Telecommunications Act of 1996 set the rules for entering the
market. BellSouth's application in Georgia repeatedly has been
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the request will come in mid-November at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Local phone companies are required to ``unbundle'' the pieces of
their network, leasing portions of the system to rivals at
reasonable prices. But Kennard said it had been jokingly suggested
to him that ``instead of unbundling monopoly networks for
competitors, we should unbundle some lawyers for them. You know,
there may be something to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard, praised as ``a good friend'' by conference organizer
Jeff Pulver, said he opposes unnecessary Internet regulation,
including the trend toward using it for phone calls. ``I will
practice the high-tech Hippocratic Oath: First, do no harm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Voice on the Net trade show and conference continues through
Thursday at the Cobb Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Arbogast, a Microsoft vice president, told the several
thousand attendees that the world is only starting to move into the
mobile era. He said that while there are phones, various digital
assistants and desktop computers, as well as a host of different
features from messaging to e-mail to conversation, ``The challenge
is to integrate all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
