 PERSONALS: Many Ways to Make a Buck 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Douglas &LR;  and  &UR; Catherine Zeta-Jones &LR;  have sold the rights to
pictures of their new baby to the British magazine OK! British
newspapers reported that the couple will be paid $1.2 million, but
a spokesman for the new family told the New York Daily News that
the amount was wrong. He confirmed the deal but wouldn't say how
big the payment is.
</P>
<P>
   _ When another guest at the Emmy ceremonies wished  &UR; Lara Flynn &LR; 
 &UR; Boyle &LR;  a ``great evening,'' the actress _ who was there without
boyfriend  &UR; Jack Nicholson &LR;  _ responded, ``Have a great evening,
right. Well, you know, I'm not here for free. It's wonderful. I'm
paid to come to a great party.'' She said she intended to stay for
only 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC representative told MSNBC that she'd never heard of
anyone being paid to attend an Emmy ceremony. Boyle's
representative didn't return MSNBC's calls.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pegi Allardyce &LR;  found it in The San Francisco Chronicle: An
ad for a `` `Survivor' Tour of the Falkland Islands. . . .
Participants will fly to Stanley, the islands' capital, before
being flown to a remote island, where they will stay and `vote' one
another off, one at a time.'' Lest consumers worry about their
vacations being cut off, the exiled will stay on another island,
waiting for the losers to join them, one by one. The cost is $1,500
plus airfare to the Falklands. ``Now people can pay for the chance
to get voted off,'' writes Allardyce. ``Oh boy, sign me up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Picture the long, gloomy face of  &UR; Virginia Woolf &LR; , and what
actress immediately comes to mind to play her? Rumor has it that
 &UR; Nicole Kidman &LR;  is negotiating to play the author in a film
adaptation of  &UR; Michael Cunningham &LR; 's novel ``The Hours.''  &UR; Meryl &LR; 
 &UR; Streep &LR;  and  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR;  are also said to be talking about
playing other roles in the film.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PRESIDENT HAS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SOME TRAVEL FUN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In New York over the weekend after the U.N. summit,  &UR; President &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR;  ate, drank and made merry. On Saturday, Sept. 9, although
Secret Service men had been waiting for hours, a planned visit to
the Carnegie Deli was thwarted when deli lovers waiting in line
refused to give up their places.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customers weren't moving,'' said owner  &UR; Sandy Levin &LR; .
``They didn't care who he was. So he switched to Plan B.'' So
Clinton,  &UR; Madeleine Albright &LR;  and  &UR; Sandy Berger &LR;  in tow, went to
the rival Stage Deli, where he ate a pastrami and tongue sandwich,
chocolate marble cheesecake and a Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Open, someone gave the president a copy of Hamptons
magazine with  &UR; Donald Trump &LR; 's girlfriend,  &UR; Melania &LR; 
 &UR; Knauss &LR; , on the cover. Spotting Trump in the stands, Clinton waved
the cover at him and gave him what the New York Post reported was
``a big thumbs-up sign.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BERRY RECOVERING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Actress  &UR; Halle Berry &LR; , who pleaded no contest this year to
charges stemming from a hit-and-run car accident, is McCall's cover
girl this month, with a story about ``how I bounced back from the
toughest year of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think that one of the most beautiful women in the world
would be a little intimidating, a little haughty,'' writes
 &UR; Martha Southgate &LR;  in a profile that could be called fawning, if
that weren't an understatement. ``You'd expect some touchiness
about how she looks.'' (How dare you call me one of the most
beautiful women in the world?)
</P>
<P>
   ``She is even more beautiful in person than in photographs,''
writes Southgate. And what's more, according to the producer of
``X-Men,'' in which Berry starred, ``although she's small, she has
a lot of internal strength and calm.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Joan Kennedy &LR; , who said in a July interview that she hadn't
had a drink in nine years, was arrested in Cape Cod on Sunday
night, Sept. 10, for driving while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Actor  &UR; Joe Mantegna &LR;  will be special guest Sept. 23 when the
Grand Lodge of California of the Sons of Italy in America
celebrates its 75th anniversary at the Palace Hotel. Mantegna's
connection: The lodge will present a check to him for the National
Alliance for Autism Research. He has an autistic son.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Like Elvis and Lassie and Oprah, I have one-name &LR; 
 &UR; recognition.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Geraldo Rivera &LR;  on his possible candidacy for mayor of New
York, in Us Weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I feel insecure every five minutes.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Madonna &LR;  in Rolling Stone magazine.
</P>
