<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-NIERENBERG-NYT     09-12 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NIERENBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM A. NIERENBERG, 81, PHYSICIST AND MILITARY POLICY ADVISER
</HEADLINE>
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. William A. Nierenberg, a physicist with a passion for the
ocean who spent five decades striving to mesh science, technology
and policy as an adviser to presidents, military agencies and NATO,
died on Sept. 10 at his home in San Diego. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, according to a statement from the Scripps
Institution of Oceanography in San Diego, of which Nierenberg was
the director from 1965 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1950s until shortly before his death, he served on
dozens of National Academy of Sciences committees, presidential
commissions and panels examining issues such as what to do about
acid rain and where to hide ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg's mingling of science and politics and his
rapid-fire, straight-talking manner, sometimes put him at odds with
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But any differences of opinion did not erode lifelong
friendships, said Dr. Walter H. Munk, a research oceanographer at
Scripps who knew Nierenberg for 40 years and debated him on issues
like global warming, a theory that Nierenberg long held posed
little immediate threat to human affairs.
</P>
<P>
   When Nierenberg was appointed to run Scripps, Munk recalled,
``there was some concern as to whether a nonoceanographer would do
this job well.'' But, Munk added, ``he fought hard for the
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   While Nierenberg was director, Scripps pioneered several
research projects, including drilling surveys of the sea floor,
which revealed much about the history of the oceans and the
dynamics of the earth's crust, and studies of the interactions of
the oceans and the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   William Aaron Nierenberg was born in New York City on Feb. 13,
1919. According to the National Academy of Sciences, to which he
was elected in 1971, he received three degrees in physics _ his
bachelor's degree from City College of New York in 1939 and his
master's and doctorate from Columbia University in 1942 and 1947.
At Columbia, he studied under I.I. Rabi, winner of the 1944 Nobel
Prize in Physics. While pursuing his degrees, Nierenberg served as
a section leader on the Manhattan Project.
</P>
<P>
   He taught briefly at the University of Michigan, then at the the
University of California at Berkeley beginning in 1950, where he
established his credentials in experimental physics. While there,
he formed the Atomic Beam Laboratory and, from 1950 to 1965, his
work resulted in more than 100 academic papers.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s, he took a break from physics and developed
expertise in sonar and antisubmarine warfare, which he put to use
advising government and military agencies on scientific questions
related to national security.
</P>
<P>
   From 1960 to 1962, he served as assistant secretary-general for
scientific affairs of NATO and from 1962 into the 1980s he was a
member of Jason, a group of scientists advising the Pentagon and
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg is survived by his wife, Edith; a son, Nicolas, of
San Diego; a daughter, Victoria Nierenberg Tschinkel, of
Tallahassee, Fla.; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-EU-AUSTRIA-ART-625&AMP;AD     09-12 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-AUSTRIA-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION LIFTS SANCTIONS ON AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The European Union lifted its sanctions against Austria
on Tuesday, seven months after hurriedly imposing a diplomatic
freeze on Vienna for bringing a rightist party into its ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But the Europeans said they remained deeply concerned about the
Freedom Party's role in the government and vowed to maintain a
``special vigilance.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to end the sanctions came four days after a panel of
experts issued a report on human rights and political life in
Austria, recommending an end to the sanctions, which had
increasingly become an embarrassment to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian officials quickly welcomed the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great success for Austria resulting from our
patience and firmness,'' Austria's chancellor, Wolfgang Schuessel,
said on national television soon after the sanctions were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel said there had been efforts behind the scenes to
suspend the measures rather than lift them and to keep them in
place for a longer time or to set up a monitoring mechanism.
Ultimately, all those efforts were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sanctions were adopted unanimously by Austria's 14
European Union partners, enthusiasm for them waned quickly as they
threatened to strengthen opposition to the group and to a common
European currency, particularly in a crucial referendum on the euro
in Denmark this month.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions _ which included a boycott of cultural exchange
programs and military exercises _ did not amount to much more than
a crimp in the social life of Austria's ambassadors. But critics
said the sanctions went too far: they represented an unparalleled
intrusion into the internal affairs of a member country and they
infuriated the Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions that the boycott would affect tourism or the
Austrian economy never came to pass. But early on, the sanctions
did cause some awkward diplomatic moments as various officials did
their best to avoid their Austrian counterparts. At a summit
meeting of the European Union in Portugal, for instance, the usual
group picture was done away with because various leaders _
including France's president, Jacques Chirac _ did not want to be
seen standing next to Schuessel.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Tuesday, a State Department official said that the
United States was examining the European Union report but would
maintain the modest diplomatic sanctions that it imposed in
February to ``limit'' contacts with Austrian officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy has not changed,'' the official said. ``We remain
concerned about the Freedom Party's participation in the Austrian
government.''
</P>
<P>
   ((Canada followed the Europeans' lead and on Tuesday lifted
sanctions it had imposed against Austria on the ground that it no
longer feared Vienna would adopt policies that infringed on human
rights.))
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weekend, it seemed clear that many European Union
members were eager for the sanctions to be lifted immediately. But
France _ which had led the move to impose the freeze and which now
holds the group's rotating presidency _ refused to be rushed. Its
officials hinted that a monitoring system was still needed.
</P>
<P>
   But France was apparently forced to settle for the vague promise
of ``vigilance.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In lifting the sanctions, the 14 members issued a joint
statement in Paris Tuesday evening. ``The measures taken by the 14
were useful,'' the statement said. ``They can now be lifted.'' But
the statement added: ``The nature of the Freedom Party and its
uncertain evolution remains cause for serious worry. The 14
consider that a particular vigilance should be exercised with
regard to this party and the influence it exerts on the government
it is a part of.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the sanctions continued month after month, it became clear
that some of the smaller European member countries felt threatened
by what was happening to Austria. In Denmark, for instance, some
experts believe that lifting the sanctions could help make sure
that Danes vote to adopt the euro when the issue goes to a
referendum on Sept. 28. Even before the joint-statement was issued
Tuesday evening, Danish officials were promising that the sanctions
would be gone by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of summer, signs of a thaw were apparent. On
Bastille Day, July 14, the Austrian ambassador was among the
dignitaries sharing a reviewing stand with Chirac. The Belgium
extended a similar invitation to its Austrian ambassador.
Meanwhile, European Union officials _ trying to build a face-saving
way to wriggle out of the sanctions _ appointed a three-member
panel to assess human rights and political life in Austria before
making a recommendation on the lifting the freeze.
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued last Friday and found that the sanctions
had served a useful purpose by focusing attention on common values
in the European Union and increasing the Austrian government's
self-awareness. But the report said that prolonging the sanctions
would be counterproductive by creating ill-will from Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   The three experts _ Prof. Jochen Frowein, the director of the
Max Planck Institute in Germany; Martti Ahtisaari, the former
president of Finland; and Marcelino Oreja, a former Spanish
government minister _ also gave the Schuessel government high marks
for taking concrete steps to fight racism, xenophobia and
anti-semitism.
</P>
<P>
   But they called the Freedom Party, which was led by the
controversial Joerg Haider until he stepped aside in February, ``a
right-wing populist party with radical elements.'' Some of its
members continued to use xenophobic, even racist language and were
not reproached in any way, they said. Haider's party became part of
the current Austrian government when Schuessel and his People's
Party decided that a coalition was the only way to end months of a
political stalemate after the October elections.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sanctions were imposed, Haider has several times
lashed out at Chirac. This weekend, Haider stepped up his attacks,
calling Chirac ``a pocket-sized Napoleon'' who had just met his
Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac has not spoken on the issue, though other French
officials have scoffed at the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever decision is made by the 14, it is not a question of
giving absolution'' to the Freedom Party, said the French affairs
minister, Pierre Moscovi on Monday. ``I don't see how the party can
be exonerated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
