<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Insurrection At `Big Brother'
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Big Brother'' continues to drive the show's
producers batty. Last week, an effort to bribe one of the six
remaining contestants to leave the camera-filled house where they
have been confined for two months failed because they decided they
would present a united front to thwart the producers' main goal of
inserting a new participant.
</P>
<P>
   Then over the weekend the houseguests, as they are called,
became so inflamed by the notion that they were being trifled with
that they announced they would stage a mass walkout of the house
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That revolt was short-lived. By Sunday the six had seen the
light. If they walked out no one would receive the $500,000 grand
prize.
</P>
<P>
   With the houseguests now apparently locked in for the long haul,
the producers went into this week still wishing they could find a
way to squeeze their new hope, a straightforward and outspoken
attractive young woman named Beth, into the house for the show's
last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One idea was to let one house member out into the world for one
night for a taste of the real word. So Curtis, a lawyer from
California, won a contest to leave the house and go to the Emmy
Awards show on Sunday in Los Angeles. He said he decided to go back
into the house, however, partly because he was cheered by fans at
the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   That left the producers pondering further moves for Wednesday
night. Paul Romer, the executive producer, said Tuesday that the
show had all but resolved to offer a $50,000 prize again to anyone
who wanted to leave the show, an offer that would be made just
before the audience vote is revealed Thursday night, determining
which houseguest is banished. Cassandra, Curtis and Eddie have been
nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said he would still love to add Beth to the group, ``to
add that new impulse.'' And he admitted that the resistance to
taking the money baffled the producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same amount as the third prize, $50,000. Three of the
people left are going to walk away with no money.''
</P>
<P>
   -BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Producers Walk Out
</P>
<P>
   After not developing any new comedy hits last year, NBC is still
struggling with the genre it rode to prominence in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with ``The Michael Richards Show,'' named for a former
``Seinfeld'' star, were reported this summer, when the pilot
episode for NBC was retooled.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bad news for the network came when Nat Bernstein and
Mitchel Katlin, executive producers and creators of ``Cursed'' _
one of four half-hour sitcoms that are to make their debuts on NBC
this fall _ left their posts on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said Tuesday that they hoped to complete a deal with
Adam Chase, a former co-executive producer of ``Friends,'' to take
over the executive producer duties on ``Cursed.''
</P>
<P>
   Network executives said they expected ``Cursed'' to make its
debut on Oct. 12, as expected, in the prime Thursday night time
slot at 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   Both the network and the former producers say they could not
agree on the show's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cursed'' is based on the misadventures of an advertising
executive, played by Steven Weber, whose life is turned upside down
after a curse is laid on him during a blind date with a woman who
practices black magic.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said he and Katlin were getting mixed signals from
network executives, who questioned the name of the show and at one
point even suggested doing away with the premise of the curse
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response was, `We love the pilot; maybe we should get rid
of the curse,''' he said. ``The fact of the matter is that from the
very, very beginning, there were many opinions and many cooks, and
there were many things that people would have liked to have seen.
It was a very difficult process.''
</P>
<P>
   Network executives said that they were not happy with the
scripts they were receiving from the producers but that they
expected to keep the main premise.
</P>
<P>
   News of trouble with the program was first reported in the
Hollywood trade papers ``Variety'' and the ``Hollywood Reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   -JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   A `Survivor' on MIR
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most daring reality show of all now looks as if it
will become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has bought the rights to a new show from Mark Burnett, the
producer of ``Survivor,'' who plans to take a group of American
contestants to Moscow to take part in a training program for a
rocket trip to the Russian space station MIR.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives said they paid more than $35 million for the
show, which will run 15 to 17 hours in the fall of 2001. It will,
like ``Survivor'' be a weekly elimination duel, but with MIR
officials making the weekly choice of who will be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, the winner will be launched into space.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives expressed confidence in Burnett, who besides
``Survivor'' has also produced the series ``Eco-Challenge'' on
cable television.
</P>
<P>
   -BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A Prize for the Emmys
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy Awards struck back this week against all those who have
denigrated the award as all but meaningless: with 21.8 million
viewers, the broadcast Sunday on ABC was the most watched Emmy
Awards show since the Nielsen company started using the
people-meter ratings system in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The show also added significant numbers of younger viewers,
bringing in the most young adult women since 1994 and the most
young adult men since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Many television executives said the big increase in ratings was
proof that television was having a revival of sorts with the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally the biggest evidence of that revival has been the
enormous number of people watching first ``Who Wants to be A
Millionaire'' on ABC and then ``Survivor'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But neither show was up for any Emmy Awards, though the show did
open with an elaborate comedy sketch based on ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   One difference this year was a change in the voting system,
which broke away from the blue-ribbon panels that previously
selected winners after watching nominees over one day in one room.
This year the winners were picked by a much broader group of voters
who watched tapes at home.
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable result was more Emmys for the shows
considered the hottest favorites of the season: five for ``The West
Wing'' and three for ``Will and Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The voting system was changed because last season's hot show,
``The Sopranos,'' was shortchanged under the old voting system,
winning only two awards. This year ``The Sopranos,'' not quite as
hot as it was last year, won only one award, for James Gandolfini
as best actor.
</P>
<P>
   -BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
