<SLUG> BC-TIRE-AKRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AKRON, THE TALK IS ABOUT TREADS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ When the International Tire Exhibition and
Conference opened here Tuesday, more than 2,500 people gathered in
small meeting rooms to listen to scientists deliver papers on
``Metallic Coagents for Bonding Rubber to Metal and Synthetic
Fibers'' or ``Tire Shearography.''
</P>
<P>
   But try as they might to focus on such topics, they couldn't
help talking about the Firestone controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Though scientists and industry officials are gathering for this
three-day conference to deliver papers that deal with tire failures
and ``tread separation,'' which is at the heart of the massive
recall, few will speculate about what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said they were legally advised not to speak
about Bridgestone/Firestone and even to delete the term ``tread
separation'' from presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they had noticed a growing interest in X-ray and
laser equipment that might be used to detect problems.
</P>
<P>
   Several executives said tire makers use such equipment in plants
only sporadically because it is too expensive to test every tire.
But that may be changing, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truck industry X-rays 100 percent of their tires, but the
margins aren't in passenger tires to be able to X-ray each one,''
said Ted Neuhaus, a tire consultant at Laser Technology Inc. in
Norristown, Pa. ``Now, though, the fear is that if it happened to
one company, it could also happen to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference organizers held a news briefing this afternoon
calling for the creation of a commission made up of government and
industry officials to gather information about tire safety.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Simmons, publisher of Rubber &AMP; Plastics News, which
organized the conference with its parent company, Crain
Communications, said that creating such a commission would prevent
the need for greater government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that if the tire industry does not take quick,
responsible action, someone else will do it for us,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Many here said the Firestone brand name has been irreparably
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are talking about sooner or later this name will
disappear,'' said John Choi, who sells tire-making machinery in
Korea. ``People don't want tires made by Firestone.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested the problem could be poor maintenance of the
tires and the discrepancy between the inflation levels recommended
by Firestone and Ford, which equipped its Explorers with the tires.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry officials stressed how complicated the tire-making
process was and how sophisticated tires had become.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition hall, industry officials talked about how far
the industry has come from the days when a man named Charles
Goodyear invented the vulcanization process, which helped transform
Akron into the industry's birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have doubled the life of the tire and provided all-weather
traction,'' a Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber spokesman told a television
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Many at the conference _ not naming names _ pointed the finger
at automakers, which have pushed to keep tire prices low, and a
public unwilling to pay top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here buy tires that are cheaper than sneakers and then
drive 70 miles per hour on them,'' said Jorg Jetter, who manned the
exhibition booth of Jet Lasersysteme, which makes equipment for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Truck tires, many delegates said, are much more expensive and
largely better made because of the liabilities associated with the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Few, though, were willing to point too harshly at Firestone, at
least publicly. Several meetings, after all, were held in the
Harvey S. Firestone room, and the loudspeaker announced at noon
that a complimentary luncheon was sponsored by
Bridgestone/Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   After delivering a paper on the bonding of steel cords to rubber
_ the issue many investigators said may be the problem _ William J.
van Ooij, a professor at the University of Cincinnati and an expert
in rubber adhesion in tires, said he would not speculate about the
cause of tread separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's theoretically possible, but I think it's highly unlikely
that it was a design problem,'' he said. ``I know Firestone and it
wouldn't be design.''
</P>
<P>
   Suresh Sethi, an executive at Modi, a tire equipment company in
India, said that auto and tire makers around the world were overly
concerned about price and market share. Not enough thought had been
given to safety, he said. ``You buy a $30,000 vehicle,'' he said,
``and what does the tire cost? The companies were trying to save $1
per tire because $1 per tire adds up to a lot. That is responsible
for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunter Maass, an executive at Erhardt &AMP; Leimer, a tire equipment
company in Germany, said the recall is about technology. He said
this would not happen in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I understand, this is not the first time,'' he said,
referring to a 1978 Firestone recall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
