<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: REPUBLICANS ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE AND EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mich.)   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee began broadcasting a new
commercial, ``Let's See/Education,'' in Michigan and Pennsylvania
on Monday. The spot takes aim at the investigation into
fund-raising excesses by the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996 and then
offers a critical assessment of Vice President Al Gore's education
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Cold Harbor Films &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The 30-second commercial, like other Republican
spots, uses a small television screen on a kitchen counter to show
flickering images of Gore. The vice president is seen speaking to a
crowd, answering questions behind the lectern in the White House
briefing room (it appears to be his ``no controlling legal
authority'' news conference) and addressing the Democratic National
Convention last month. Text superimposed over the images cites the
number of people indicted and convicted and who took the Fifth
Amendment or fled the country in the fund-raising investigation. On
education, the text reads ``No real testing'' and ``No Testing No
Accountability.'' The final text refers viewers to the Republican
National Committee Web site, gorewillsayanything.com.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: A female announcer: ``Al Gore is promising campaign
finance reform. Can I believe him? Because of Gore's last
fund-raising campaign, 22 people have been indicted, 12 convicted,
70 took the Fifth Amendment and 18 witnesses fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Al Gore is promising more accountability in our schools.
And that sounds good. Until you find out he doesn't require any
real testing. And no testing means no accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just more politics, from Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: The numbers of people cited in the campaign finance
investigation were taken from a television news broadcast and are
probably lower than the real figures, congressional officials say.
</P>
<P>
   On education, the advertisement is accurate in stating that Gore
would not require mandatory nationwide standardized testing for
students. But Gore does propose voluntary national tests for
fourth-grade reading and eighth-grade math, and he encourages
states to participate in the National Assessment of Educational
Progress, an exam administered nationally to a sample of students.
Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, would
require states to participate in the national test and would demand
that they impose mandatory reading and math tests in third- through
eighth-grades.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The spot tries to use the 1996 campaign finance
scandal to undercut Gore's credibility on a wholly unrelated issue,
education reform. The mixed message leaves little time for a
meaningful contrast of the two candidates' positions on school
testing, an important policy difference that Bush hopes will
attract female voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0333 </DOCNO>
