<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLL WAS CONDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CAMPAIGN-POLL) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll is based on telephone
interviews conducted Saturday through Monday with 1,050 adults
throughout the United States. Of these, 843 said they were
registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The sample of telephone exchanges called was randomly selected
by a computer from a complete list of more than 42,000 active
residential exchanges across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Within each exchange, random digits were added to form a
complete telephone number, thus permitting access to both listed
and unlisted numbers. Within each household, one adult was
designated by a random procedure to be the respondent for the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been weighted to take account of household size
and number of telephone lines into the residence and to adjust for
variations in the sample relating to geographic region, sex, race,
age and education.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20 the results based on such
samples will differ by no more than 3 percentage points in either
direction from what would have been obtained by seeking out all
American adults.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller subgroups, the margin of sampling error is larger.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sampling error, the practical difficulties of
conducting any survey of public opinion may introduce other sources
of error into the poll. Variations in the wording and order of
questions, for example, may lead to somewhat different results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-BANKS-HISTORY-N     09-12 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-BANKS-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN DEAL IS CLIMAX OF DECADES OF CONCENTRATION IN BANK
INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (with CHASE-MORGAN, CHASE-MORGAN-HISTORY)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A generation ago, six major commercial banks
dominated the financial world in New York, which itself was the
financial capital of the world's largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   Now J.P. Morgan _ the last of those six to stay independent _ is
about to be bought, in the latest example of a trend toward
financial concentration. If the planned takeover by Chase Manhattan
is completed, it will bring together four of the six biggest banks
in New York, circa 1980. And yet the combination reflects weakness
as much as strength, as both institutions seek growth in areas
where their previous efforts have not been especially successful.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, the commercial banks were dominant because they
were the major financial intermediaries for both individuals and
companies. Investment banks and insurance companies had their own
niches, some quite profitable, but none of them seemed to be in a
position to challenge the big banks as financial powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Beginning in the 1970s, the commercial banks saw
the dominance of their franchise diminish as corporations
discovered they could save money by issuing securities rather than
borrowing from banks. As the stock market boomed for years,
investors' money flowed out of banks and into stocks and mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   And the commercial banks were hobbled by a series of loan
debacles that damaged some severely and hurt all to some extent,
whether in real estate or loans to Third World countries. It took
years for the banks to recover from those problems, and by then,
their competitors were ahead of them in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Depression-era laws aimed at protecting banks
from possible losses in securities made it difficult for them to
move into other financial products. By the time those laws were
largely repealed, it was the investment banks that were dominant.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of trading Tuesday, Chase Manhattan _ a company
that includes the former Chemical New York and Manufacturers
Hanover banks _ had a market capitalization of $66 billion, and
J.P. Morgan had shares valued at $29 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the investment banking
company descended from J.P. Morgan, had a market capitalization of
$121 billion. Morgan Stanley was split from Morgan after the
Glass-Steagall Act of 1933 required the separation of investment
banks and commercial banks. For decades, no one doubted that J.P.
Morgan itself had made the right decision by sticking to commercial
banking. Now it will be subsumed, while Morgan Stanley is a
dominant company.
</P>
<P>
   The trend of financial consolidation can be traced, said H.
Rodgin Cohen, a partner in Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell and a lawyer
involved in many bank mergers _ but not in the Chase-Morgan talks _
can be traced largely to three factors: ``convergence,
globalization and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   By convergence, he refers to the fact that many financial
institutions can now offer similar products, in contrast to the old
days of protected turf. Globalization has put a premium on gaining
strength in markets around the world, and the heavy costs of
installing new technology have made it much more difficult for
small players to compete.
</P>
<P>
   There are many areas where Chase and Morgan would seem to
complement each other. ``They can fill in each other's gaps,'' said
Ronald Mandle, an analyst for Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. Chase's
strongest position in equity securities is in technology stocks,
thanks to its acquisition of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. Morgan has a
broader equity business, but is not strong in technology. ``Morgan
is stronger in Europe and Chase is a leader in syndicating U.S.
loans.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the largest New York-based bank was Citibank. It still
holds that position, but it is now part of Citigroup, which was
formed by the merger of Citicorp, Citibank's parent, and Travelers,
the large insurance and investment banking company run by Sanford
I. Weill. While the Citi name survived, the bank is now part of a
much larger company mainly run by executives who came from outside.
</P>
<P>
   Chase ranked second among New York banks in 1980, followed by
Manufacturers Hanover, Morgan, Chemical and Bankers Trust. Chemical
and Manufacturers Hanover merged in 1991, and then acquired Chase
(and its name) in a 1995 deal. Bankers Trust was sold to Deutsche
Bank, a German institution, in a deal announced in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The two non-New York banks in the top eight, as compiled by
American Banker, a trade publication, in 1980, have not fared much
better. Bank of America, then No. 1, and Continental Illinois, then
No. 7, have joined and both been taken over by what was then known
as North Carolina National Bank, which ranked 26th in the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEF-NYT &LR;      09-12 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN TO JOIN HILLARY CLINTON  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the day last month that Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut was selected as the Democratic vice-presidential
candidate, Hillary Rodham Clinton has said she would like to
campaign with him as she runs for a Senate seat in New York. On
Friday, she will get her chance. Lieberman will campaign with
Clinton in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   His aides say the events have not been determined, but this much
is known: Clinton and her strategists have said they hope that some
of Lieberman's popularity will rub off on her, particularly with
Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have Clinton, who is in a tight race with Rep. Rick Lazio,
leading among Jewish voters by a margin smaller than New York
Democrats usually need to win statewide races. But those same
surveys show Vice President Al Gore, helped by Lieberman, the first
Jewish candidate for national office from a major party, leading
Gov. George W. Bush by 20 points or more in New York. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Monroe, Wash.; Long Beach, Westminster and
Irvine, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY: Montague and Grand Rapids, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Lewiston, Maine; Boston and Manchester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH LIEBERMAN: Washington; Boston and Brookline, Mass.; and
Flushing, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   PAT BUCHANAN: No appearances scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER: Long Beach, Calif., and Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
