<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-RATS-HNS &LR;      09-12 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush TV spot has Democrats yelling `RATS'
 &HT;    Experts say they doubt use of word in ad unintentional
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ALAN BERNSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word ``Republican'' contains the letters that spell
``pubic.'' The word ``experts'' contains the letters that spell
``sex.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts commenting on the controversy about a Republican
campaign commercial say that embedded words, subliminal advertising
or flashed messages have virtually no power to change how voters
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't work, and if they don't work why fool around
with it?'' advertising expert Jack Haberstroh of San Diego, Calif.,
said Tuesday. His 1994 book, ``Ice Cube Sex,'' aimed to debunk the
idea that subliminal advertising is used widely and has the desired
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the intrigue surrounding the use of the word ``RATS'' in a
Republican National Committee television commercial that promotes
Gov. George W. Bush's presidential candidacy and criticizes
opponent Al Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which was discontinued Tuesday after a two-week, $2.5
million run in 33 cities across the nation (none in Texas), said
that under Gore's plan to add prescription drugs benefits for
Medicare recipients, ``bureaucrats decide'' about health care for
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   As an announcer pronounced the phrase, the word ``RATS,'' a
fragment from ``bureaucrats,'' appeared on the screen for a
fraction of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party operatives alerted The New York Times, whose
Tuesday article about the commercial started a rat-a-tat-tat
between the candidates for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the suggestion that ``RATS'' was used to disparage
Gore is ``bizarre and weird.'' He said the appearance of the word
in the 30-second ad was unintentional. Alex Castellanos, who
produced the commercial, said the phrase was highlighted to make
letters on the screen visually captivating and that the use of
``rats'' was coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called the ad ``disappointing and strange'' and his running
mate, U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman, said the Democrats want an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on advertising and business procedures doubted that
``RATS'' was an unintended feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying it was accidental? Oh my God, I find that hard
to believe,'' said Haberstroh, who taught college courses about
advertising for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   He said the word was not a subliminal message, because
``subliminal'' means below the line of conscious perception and
``RATS'' appears long enough to be seen and read by the conscious
mind.
</P>
<P>
   And because the word appears long enough to be perceived, its
inclusion had to be planned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Klein, a marketing professor at Rice University's Jones
Graduate School of Administration, said someone on the Republican
side must have been made aware of ``RATS'' before the ad ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody that runs a national ad will do it without testing it''
on sample viewers, she said. ``It would have shown up on research
they did to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the message is subliminal or another kind of suggestion,
it can backfire, according to Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who are against Republicans or against `that kind'
of campaigning, this can have a negative effect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For viewers supportive of Republican causes, the commercial can
introduce the idea that bureaucrats are rats, but not necessarily
inspire them to despise Democrats as rodents, Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   A professor of management and psychology at the Jones School,
Steven Currall, said he was surprised to hear Republicans say they
did not deploy ``RATS'' on purpose. Considering that such
commercials are pieced together rigorously, ``it is surprising that
something would slip by,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Haberstroh said that regardless of whether ``RATS'' was
accidental, it will dent Bush's image as a candidate who promised
to run a civil campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine the people who put this commercial together
thinking it was going to produce some positive results for George
Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Haberstroh pointed out, subliminal advertising can get
TV stations in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the Federal Communications Commission declared that
subliminal advertising is against the public interest and therefore
in possible violation of the license agreements that stations make
to broadcast on the public airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The title and content of Haberstroh's ``Ice Cube Sex'' made fun
of the notion that subliminal advertising is used widely on
television or in newspapers and magazines, which are beyond the
reach of government regulations. Unless advertising addresses the
public plainly and directly it is doomed, according to Haberstroh.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite view has come from author Wilson Bryan Key, whose
1970s book, ``Subliminal Seduction,'' said that advertisers were
using sexual images and words on the subconscious level to sell
food products and other items.
</P>
<P>
   Key's work fed the idea that the populace is manipulated by
money-hungry media, and Bush chose in his comments about the ad
Tuesday to discuss conspiracy theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``One frame out of 900 hardly in my judgment makes a
conspiracy,'' Bush said. ``I am convinced this is not intentional.
You don't need to play, you know, cute politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Subliminal advertising first got attention in 1957, when New
York market researcher James Vicary claimed that he increased
popcorn and cola sales at a movie theater by flashing promotional
messages at 1/60,000th of a second during a film. His research was
later discredited, but not before the National Association of
Broadcasters in 1958 adopted a self-imposed ban on such ads.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
