<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-1STLD-W     09-12 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL RACE IS TIGHTEST IN 20 YEARS, POLL FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs lede to recast, make one sentence.) 
(With CAMPAIGN-POLL-METHOD) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE with JANET ELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has shaken the persistent sense that he
is not particularly likable and is now as highly regarded as Gov.
George W. Bush on matters of character, leadership and overall
personal popularity, the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   Now that public opinion has settled somewhat since the
Democratic convention nearly four weeks ago, and voters say they
are far more interested in the race, the survey makes clear that
Gore's enhanced fortunes are deeper and more sustained than a
post-convention afterglow.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has achieved substantial gains among women, independent
voters and those from middle income groups. While Bush's support
has diminished somewhat overall, he still retains the overwhelming
support of men, Midwesterners and Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   The poll shows that the presidential race is neck-and-neck, and
that Bush and Gore are facing off in the tightest competition just
after Labor Day in 20 years. If the election were held today, 42
percent of registered voters said they would back Gore and 39
percent said they would vote for Bush. Four percent said they would
back Ralph Nader, the Green party nominee, and 2 percent would
favor Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has gained on Bush in recent weeks, but not to a degree
that is statistically significant. The nationwide telephone poll,
conducted Saturday through Monday with 843 registered voters, has a
margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   And there was some encouraging news for Bush in the numbers.
Forty-seven percent of Gore's supporters said they had reservations
about him; only 38 percent of Bush's backers registered concerns
about their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most pronounced shift in the survey is the marked
improvement in the public's perceptions of Gore. For months,
Americans said they found Gore's positions on a various issues more
appealing than Bush's, but the vice president's most persistent
problem was that voters said they had significant misgivings about
him on issues of character.
</P>
<P>
   Now, while Bush has held his own in retaining impressive
favorability ratings, Gore's favorability ratings have increased
substantially _ to the point where the two men are now equally
popular. Forty-four percent of voters say they have a favorable
view of Gore, while 29 percent have an unfavorable view. Gore has
not done that well by this measure for years. In recent months, the
public either had more negative views of Gore than positive ones,
or, more recently, given him positive ratings that equaled his
negatives.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking example of how perceptions have transformed,
voters no longer view Bush as the runaway winner in the November
election. They are now split on whether Gore or Bush will make it
to the White House. As recently as two months ago, Bush led Gore on
this question by more than 20 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are also more confident in Gore's ability to deal wisely
with an international crisis. Forty-nine percent said they were
confident in Gore, a gain from 43 percent in a Times/CBS poll in
July. Bush's standing on that issue has remained steady at 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While 63 percent of the public thinks Gore cares about the needs
and problems of ordinary people _ a figure that has not changed
since July _ Bush has shown some slippage. Forty-nine percent say
that of Bush cares about ordinary people, a decline from 55 percent
in July.
</P>
<P>
   It is not altogether clear what has prompted the more kindly
feelings toward Gore. But in follow-up interviews Tuesday, many
voters who now back Gore said they were impressed by what they saw
at the Democratic convention. Repeatedly, they said, Gore seemed to
be coming into his own _ and moving out of President Clinton's
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the convention, he did a better job of concealing anything
that was negative, if he had anything to begin with,'' said Wilma
Akins, 69, a retired office manager in Statesboro, Ga. ``He made me
feel hopeful and optimistic about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Taylor, 46, a grocery store manager in Philadelphia, said,
``He's become stronger and seems to be speaking out more since the
convention. He's becoming his own man now, and he's not as stiff as
he once was.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is still not a single overwhelming issue that
defines the race _ as the economy has in the past _ the survey
found that the closest contender this year was health care, and the
related matter of Medicare. Nearly two-thirds of voters said the
high cost of prescription drugs for the elderly was quite important
to them personally.
</P>
<P>
   Voters said they thought the government _ not insurance
companies _ would do a better job of providing coverage to the
elderly for prescription drugs. Gore was seen as more likely than
Bush to succeed in reducing the cost of prescription drugs for the
elderly. Bush has proposed allowing private insurance companies to
compete for Medicare clients, while Gore has proposed adding a
subsidy for prescription drug coverage to the current Medicare
plan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has recently accused the administration of presiding
over a weakening of the military, the issue did not register much
with voters. And many seemed confused about the state of the
nation's missile defense capability.
</P>
<P>
   Half the voters agreed with Bush's assertion that the military
has weakened under Clinton, and just under half said it had either
strengthened or stayed the same over the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But half the voters said they thought that the United States had
a missile defense system, although it does not; only 28 percent
knew that the country does not one. One explanation may be that
nearly seven in 10 respondents said they had not heard or read much
about the debate over proposals for a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, four in 10 voters said it was important that the United
States try to build a missile defense system; two-thirds said they
favored such an effort even though the government has already spent
$60 billion trying to develop one.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has repeatedly called upon Gore to elevate the
discourse and not sink to harsh commercials, voters gave the vice
president higher marks for his advertising campaign. Two thirds of
voters said Gore was spending more time explaining what he would do
as president than he was spending attacking Bush; half said the
same of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of voters have seen advertisements for Bush,
and they are divided over whether they mostly explain things about
Bush or attack Gore. About a third have seen advertisements for
Gore. But those viewers, decisively, say Gore's commercials explain
things about Gore rather than attack Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the voter interviews, many said Gore's selection of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut spiced up the ticket, especially
when Lieberman was compared with Dick Cheney, who even many
Republicans say has not been as beneficial to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The move to choose Lieberman took a lot of guts and was
brilliant,'' said Nati Gottlieb, 53, an insurance salesman in
Philadelphia. ``That move stopped Bush dead in his tracks and
started his current momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such comments, the poll reinforced the accepted wisdom
that running mate choices do not matter much. Cheney and Lieberman
are each well liked _ and each are about twice as likely to be
viewed favorably as unfavorably. But most people still have no
opinion of them. And more than half of voters said the selections
did not make them any more, or less, inclined to vote for Bush or
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Voters did not sound exercised about the frequent references
that Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, has made to his faith. Voters said
it was perfectly appropriate for candidates to discuss their
religious beliefs, and a majority said none of the Democratic or
Republican candidates had used their religion improperly.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of televised debates, a subject that has dominated
much of the campaign news in recent weeks, 49 percent said they
believed Gore and Bush want to debate; 21 percent said only Gore
wanted to debate and 10 percent said only Bush wanted to take part.
Eighty-six percent said the bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates should hold the events; the Bush campaign had earlier
sought other sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This is only the third time in 40 years that a presidential
contest has been this close immediately after Labor Day, and that
may be why more voters _ 53 percent _ now say the race is
interesting; 39 percent say it is dull.
</P>
<P>
   A continuation of such interest could spur turnout in the range
of 50 percent to 55 percent, slightly higher than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the contest between Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan was
a dead heat at this point, with Reagan pulling ahead only over the
final weekend. In 1960, the match-up between Richard M. Nixon and
John F. Kennedy was equally tight at this stage, and stayed that
way until Kennedy's narrow victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of the best horse races we've had in the
country since Kennedy and Nixon,'' said Sen. Peter Fitzgerald,
R-Ill. ``The Bush campaign is going to have to do most everything
right between now and November to win. And it will not be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Maslin, a Democratic pollster, put it this way: ``This race
is shaping up to be more like Kennedy-Nixon than anything else,
mostly because of the closeness but also because of the dynamics of
an incumbent hanging on with the country in pretty good shape but
against a tough challenger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
