<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART     09-12 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE MONEY IS SOMEWHERE OVER GUAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Where is everybody?
</P>
<P>
   That is the feeling in Sydney right now. No chanting crowds. No
swarming hordes. No obvious rush of fresh money, newly arrived from
overseas. Just peaceful streets, comfortable trains, empty
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   This tranquillity is far preferable to the steamy days and tacky
nights of Atlanta 1996, when you couldn't walk on Peachtree Street
because of the glut of tourists having a block party. The Sydney
organizers looked at that unkempt scene and sniffed, ``Don't sweat
it, mate, this won't happen in Sydney.'' Up to now, this looks like
the anti-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Games are only two days away, but the feeling has not
reached critical mass. The Olympic Stadium will surely be jammed
with 110,000 people, watching the Olympic flame during the opening
ceremony on Friday night. Eighty percent of all tickets have been
sold, within a couple of percentage points of the great
record-setting glut in Atlanta four years ago. So far, Sydney is
calm. Too calm for some.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Luongo is getting antsy. He comes from Turin, owns the
Siena restaurant on Glebe Point Road, does a good business in
normal times. Right now he is hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see people from overseas,'' Luongo was saying Tuesday.
``The city is dead, and that is not just my opinion. We are
struggling. I have no idea what is the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   My source in the city reported Tuesday that the Meadowbank Ferry
was nearly empty and that the panoramic film of Sydney at the Imax
had maybe a dozen spectators.
</P>
<P>
   What Luongo and other merchants are discovering is normal for
every Summer Games or World Cup of soccer. People who go to sports
events do not necessarily patronize good restaurants or purchase
artifacts or visit museums. Many of them buy a T-shirt and a beer,
root and go home.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but sports hordes also scare away the locals. In
Los Angeles before the 1984 Summer Games, there was so much gloom
and doom that everybody who could vanished to Hawaii or Mammoth
Lake or London. The freeways have never been so easy to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome in 1990 for the World Cup, we rented an apartment in
Piazza Sforza Cesarini, just across the river from the Vatican. My
wife was regularly regaled with sad tales of deprivation by the
owners of trattorias and specialty shops: ``Signora, tell your
husband the reporter that there is nobody here. The soccer fans
come in, they look at St. Peter's and they go to the game. They
don't even buy a penne a la vodka or an insalata tricolore.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Monday night after the World Cup ended, every seat was
taken in our favorite trattoria. The locals had returned from
California or Greece or deep in the countryside where no soccer fan
could find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have beautiful customers,'' Luongo was saying Tuesday.
``Maybe they have taken their kids on holiday. Every day we have
two, four, six customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities will say that hotel rooms are booked, that
tickets are selling, but there have been empty seats on everybody's
flights into town. Tomorrow is supposed to be the biggest influx
for the Games _ perhaps 100,000 tourists from international
flights. Then we will find out if the trains will really deliver
the crowds to the new Olympic Park station. Some people are
dubious.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the ghost-town feeling is a good reminder for all
cities that tinker with the idea of playing host to the Summer
Games. There are even rumors from New York that some naifs are
agitating for the city to be the host of a set of Summer Games
somewhat later in this century. A Summer Games spread all over that
fractious and balkanized region of bridges and tunnels? That will
be the year when everybody goes to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the cost for all this largesse. The Sydney Olympic
Park looks lovely at dusk, as the lights go on. Handsome new
stadiums sprawl all over the former dumping grounds at Homebush Bay
_ the Superdome, the Olympic Stadium, the Hockey Center, the Tennis
Center, the Aquatic Center, the Dome and Pavilions, the Baseball
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When the crowds arrive _ and they will arrive _ it will all look
good on NBC, two-thirds of a day later. But what is the cost for
the privilege of providing a studio audience for worldwide
television?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't wind up like poor Montreal,'' said one
Australian taxpayer Tuesday, referring to the city that is still
stuck with the bills from a party it gave 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mario Luongo has a table for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
