</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-WHALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED STATES TO MOVE AGAINST JAPAN OVER WHALING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House plans to declare on Wednesday that
Japan has violated international whaling rules by expanding its
whale hunt this year, and will start a process that could lead to
economic sanctions against Japanese imports within two months,
administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting in New York on Monday between Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Japan's foreign minister, Yohei Kono, failed
to head off the start of the sanctions process, these officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Japan began hunting small numbers of Bryde's and sperm
whales in the North Pacific, saying the whales would be harpooned
for scientific research. Both species are protected under U.S. law,
but scientific whaling _ as opposed to commercial _ is permitted
under International Whaling Commission rules.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two months, the expanded hunt has turned into one
of the largest confrontations between Tokyo and Washington since
the trade disputes that marked President Clinton's first term.
Clinton has complained about the whaling in letters to Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori, and the United States has boycotted a U.N.
meeting in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials charge that the move toward sanctions in
Washington has been politically driven, reflecting an effort by
Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate, to
rebuild strained relations with environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   But standing up to the United States on whaling is good politics
in Japan as well. Whale-meat is still a delicacy at small
restaurants dotting Tokyo's back streets, often marinated with talk
of how the United States is attempting to force Japan to adopt
Western environmental rules without regard to local tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is betting that Japan will back down
rather than risk sanctions in the midst of a presidential election.
It is already drawing up lists of goods that could be banned,
including many types of seafood. The hope is that publishing the
list will result in enough panic among Japan's food exporters that
whaling will be called off.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials say that if the United States proceeds to the
next step, the imposition of sanctions, it will take the case to
the World Trade Organization in Geneva. Trade lawyers say the
Japanese government might win the case, because the United States
imports no Japanese whale meat _ and thus may not be able, under
trade agreements, to impose sanctions for actions that take place
beyond U.S. borders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0343 </DOCNO>
