<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT &LR;      09-12 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY SENTENCED TO HOUSE ARREST FOR PROBATION VIOLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry was at home in Tampa, Fla., Tuesday, which is
where he must remain for most of the next two years after being
sentenced to house arrest for violating his probation by admittedly
driving under the influence of medication and then leaving the
scene of an accident on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who is fighting colon cancer and whose career has
been marred by substance abuse suspensions, illnesses and criminal
charges, was driving to see his probation officer on Monday. But
Strawberry said that he blacked out from prescription medication
and hit a road sign, and then slammed into another vehicle.
Strawberry apologized for his behavior when Judge Florence Foster
sentenced him in court Tuesday in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used the wrong judgment taking medication because I didn't
feel well,'' Strawberry said in the courtroom. ``I just blacked
out. I didn't know if I hurt anybody. I feel really bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's wife, Charisse, who was teary-eyed outside the
courthouse, said her husband was in a lot of pain because of his
ongoing battle with cancer and the removal of his kidney last
month. She added that he was relieved that the other driver was not
injured. In a telephone interview after the Strawberrys returned
home, Charisse Strawberry said that her husband is trying to cope
with his latest ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to pick himself up from this and go on,'' she said.
``Hopefully, there will be a light under this dark cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of house arrest, Strawberry can leave the house
only for doctor's appointments or to go to work. If Strawberry ever
wanted to return to baseball, said Robin Fuson, the assistant state
attorney, he would need the court's permission. Fuson added that
the 38-year-old Strawberry still faces misdemeanor charges for
driving under the influence and leaving the scene of an accident,
and he could receive additional punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years of house arrest is no day at the beach,'' Fuson told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Yankees seemed bewildered by the latest twist in
Strawberry's life. Dwight Gooden thought for about 30 seconds
before saying that he would not know what to say to Strawberry.
Derek Jeter, who plans to call Strawberry soon, likened the
developments of his friend's life to a soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you to say to him,'' Jeter said. ``I don't
have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams said it was ``obviously sad'' to see Strawberry
arrested and said how Strawberry's failure to ``maximize his
talent'' was sad for baseball. Williams spoke thoughtfully and
eloquently about Strawberry's uncertain future, a future that was
already clouded by a recurrence of his cancer and a one-year
suspension from baseball starting in April for drug and
solicitation charges and will now include two years of house
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a fairly young person,'' Williams said. ``Maybe, if
it's not baseball, he'll find his calling in society in some other
aspect of life. I wish him the best. He's one of those warriors who
won't give up. Hopefully, he'll be all right in those two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, who had prostate cancer and who declined to discuss
Strawberry on Monday, did not know of Strawberry's sentencing until
reporters told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sad,'' Torre said. ``You know he's not normal
because he's got all this stuff going on, chemically, in his body.
Unless we've experienced it, it's really tough to pass judgment.
It's unfortunate that he keeps running into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charisse Strawberry had told reporters at the courthouse that
her husband was experiencing ``mental difficulties'' but refused to
elaborate. During the phone interview, she explained that she
simply meant that her husband has not been himself because of the
pain from dealing with cancer and the derailing of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just really tough to not be able to continue his
career and then to have his second fight with cancer,'' Charisse
Strawberry said. ``At 38, to have his second bout with cancer,
that's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who tested negative for alcohol in his system,
volunteered a urine sample that will be tested for any
nonprescription drugs in his system. He was fined $265 and his case
will be reviewed in four months. If Strawberry abides by the
conditions of his house arrest for a year, law enforcement
officials said there is a chance the second year could be lessened
to probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is, it's like what one of the reporters at court
said to me today,'' Charisse Strawberry said. ``It was like Darryl
was trying to do the right thing and it went bad.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
