A1085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-HNS &LR;      09-12 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush sees his most `bizarre' day in campaign yet
</P>
<P>
   By CLAY ROBISON
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ George W. Bush said it was ``bizarre'' and
``weird,'' and he wasn't even talking about Al Gore's health care
plan or his Democratic rival's association with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking instead about his own campaign day, one of the
strangest the Republican nominee has yet encountered in his race
for the presidency. It was enough to make a weaker candidate cry,
``Rats!``
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Tuesday tried mightily to stick to the message he wanted
to emphasize _ his plan to give the elderly new options for health
care and prescription drug coverage under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But he also found himself answering distractions about an
alleged subliminal message in a Republican television ad and
whether he suffers from a learning disorder.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles began with two published articles, which set back,
at least for a few hours, the governor's efforts to regain momentum
against his Democratic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   A story on the front page of the New York Times reported that
the word ``RATS'' flashed across the screen in one frame of a
30-second Republican television spot on health care. It was too
fast for most viewers to see clearly, but provided grist,
nevertheless, for political speculation because the commercial
attacked Gore's health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that it obtained a copy of the
slowed-down version of the ad from the Gore campaign, which had
been alerted to it by a Democrat in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The second article, published in Vanity Fair, suggested that the
Texas governor sometimes jumbles or mispronounces words because he
is dyslexic. The condition can impede to various degrees the
ability to read, write or speak.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he is not dyslexic.
</P>
<P>
   And he denied the ``RATS'' ad was intended as a subliminal
characterization of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But the questions rained on his day, beginning with an
early-morning national television interview conducted before
millions of Americans had even crawled out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times article was one of the first pieces of news
to greet the governor on Tuesday morning as he prepared for a 7:05
a.m. live interview from his Palm Beach, Fla., hotel on ABC-TV's
Good Morning America.
</P>
<P>
   Although his campaign had learned of the article the previous
night and his chief media consultant, Mark McKinnon, had commented
on it, Bush wasn't informed until after he awoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first I heard of it is sitting here this morning,'' Bush
told interviewer Diane Sawyer. ``You know, campaigns take bizarre
twists. This has got to be one of the more bizarre accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm telling you I don't think there's a plot to try
to put subliminal messages in the people's minds. The most
important thing is to point up the differences between what I
believe and what the vice president believes when it comes to
important issues like prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the dyslexia question came up later in the interview,
Bush grinned self-consciously and replied: ``I'm not dyslexic.
That's all I can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had to answer similar questions a couple of hours later at
a brief airport news conference in Orlando, where he went to tour
the Walt Disney Memorial Cancer Institute at Florida Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He said the commercial, which was sponsored by the Republican
National Committee, was scheduled to be pulled on Tuesday anyway
and replaced by another GOP ad.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox News Network reported on the ``RATS'' blip two weeks
ago, but that report didn't receive much attention. And Bush
spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor hadn't known about the
Fox report.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters he saw the ad displayed on a computer once
several weeks ago and did not notice the flashing word.
</P>
<P>
   At one point on Tuesday, Hughes passed a cheese tray around for
reporters on Bush's plane, explaining that she was ``just poking a
little fun at the story of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, Bush campaigned in St. Louis before flying
cross-country to Washington state for campaign appearances there
and in California today. (WEDNESDAY)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
