<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DISNEY-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY TO RESTRICT ADS FOR R-RATED FILMS ON ABC 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. announced Tuesday that it would no longer accept
advertising for R-rated movies on any programs on its ABC
television network that are broadcast before 9 p.m., Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in response to a report this week from the
Federal Trade Commission that criticized the entertainment industry
for marketing films with violent and sexual content to children.
</P>
<P>
   Movie advertising is one of the most lucrative sources of
revenue for television networks. According to figures from
Competitive Media Reports, which tracks television advertising,
movie studios spent $668 million on the four big broadcast networks
last year. For the first half of 2000, the figure has grown to $418
million. For ABC, the figures were $148 million from movie
advertising in 1999 and $115 million for the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Disney released comprehensive guidelines for the company in
regard to its marketing practices, many of which were restatements
of existing policies, said John Dreyer, the company's corporate
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on commercials for R-rated movies on the Disney-owned
ABC network is an extension of an existing policy, Dreyer said,
``but previously there had been exceptions.'' He added, ``From now
on, there will be no exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not expect the prohibition to result in a very
significant loss of revenue for the network.
</P>
<P>
   No other network has a prohibition tied to the first hour of
prime time, an hour that was once formally designated by the
networks as a ``family-viewing hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Fox network has an existing policy that prohibits
commercials for R-rated films in any show considered to be family
programming, a Fox spokesman, Jeff DeRome, said. Among that shows
included in that category are ``The Simpsons,'' ``Malcolm in the
Middle'' and ``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives declined to comment on that network's formal
policies, but in recent years CBS has had virtually no programs
with significant numbers of children watching. That changed
somewhat this summer when ``Survivor'' became a hit with almost
every age group, and not coincidentally, CBS began taking in far
more money from movie studios thanks to that program.
</P>
<P>
   NBC ties its own policy to the composition of its audience,
saying that it will not accept commercials for R-rated films in any
show whose audience is made up of more that 30 percent children.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalyn Weinman, a senior vice president of NBC, said that no
show on NBC reached that threshold last season. In recent years,
NBC has taken in more movie money than any other network largely on
the strength of its lineup of Thursday programs, one of which,
``Friends,'' is on at 8 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-WASH-HOUSE-NYT     09-12 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL RACE IN WASHINGTON STATE HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ Democrats held the congressional seat here in
northwest Washington for 30 years until the Republican tide of 1994
brought in Jack Metcalf, a former high school history teacher and
state legislator who finally made it to the House of
Representatives some 26 years after his first attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Metcalf sticking to a pledge to leave Congress after
three terms, and with Democrats believing the vacancy offers a
prime opportunity to pick up a seat in the battle for control of
the House, the 2nd Congressional District race shows signs of
becoming one of the most tightly fought contests in the nation this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   And, though each major party candidate downplays the notion that
presidential coattails will be a major factor in their campaign,
some of the emerging themes in the race are strikingly similar to
those in the race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate, John Koster, a state representative
and third-generation dairy farmer, puts it simply in promising to
push for a big federal tax cut: ``Taxes are the first thing people
are talking about to me.''
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic foe, Rick Larsen, a Snohomish County councilman,
says he will push for paying down the national debt and shoring up
Social Security and Medicare first. ``What I hear from people in
this district is, they're more concerned about using the surplus to
pay down the debt. They want government to get its fiscal house in
order. They want schools to be safe, they want to be sure seniors
can get prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   While drawing considerable attention because it involves the
only open district in the state, the race here is one of at least
three congressional contests that are considered competitive this
fall in Washington, a state that proved to be an interesting
electoral bellwether last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Washington voters broadly backed Bill Clinton and congressional
Democrats in 1992, then turned with a fury to Republicans in 1994,
giving them a 7-2 margin in the House delegation and even throwing
out the speaker of the House, Thomas Foley, a Spokane Democrat. In
1996, they came back to Clinton and over the next two election
cycles, Democrats regained a 5-4 edge.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Democrats are hoping to win the seat in this
district, which stretches from the Seattle suburbs northward to the
Canadian border, and possibly even oust George Nethercutt, the
Republican who unseated Foley six years ago and is now reneging on
a term-limits pledge he made at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are hoping to hold on to both of those seats and
even regain an edge by knocking off the incumbent Democrat in the
neighboring 1st District, Jay Inslee, who holds a seat that has
already switched hands three times over the last 10 years.
(Overall, Republicans hold 222 seats in the House of
Representatives and Democrats 210, and two are held by
independents. That means that Democrats could regain control by
picking up seven additional seats in November.)
</P>
<P>
   The district here was once reliably, even staunchly Democratic.
It was represented in the 1940s by Henry M. Jackson of Everett, who
went on to become a Senator and a national political figure, and in
the years afterward, as the Boeing Co. became the ever more
dominant employer in the region, its thousands of union workers
tended to vote the Democratic line.
</P>
<P>
   Everett and surrounding Snohomish County still account for about
half the district's voters but, as Koster noted in an interview,
many of the suburban areas have leaned Republican in recent years,
and the more agricultural areas to the north also tend to vote
Republican. Both he and Larsen agreed that in very rough terms, the
district's electorate now is probably about one-third Democratic,
one-third Republican and one-third independent.
</P>
<P>
   In many important ways, the race here has yet to catch fire, but
will undoubtedly do so as Election Day grows nearer. The two
candidates have debated face-to-face only once so far, in a
relatively polite exchange in July at the Marysville Rotary. But
they have clashed more recently over each other's records in
office, and are expected to debate in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Both do not expect to run television advertising until next
month, because much of it must be done on Seattle stations, which
is expensive. And while next Tuesday's primary is critically
important in some races _ it will determine, for instance, whether
former Rep. Maria Cantwell or State Insurance Commissioner Deborah
Senn will earn the Democratic nomination to take on the incumbent
U.S. senator, Slade Gorton, a Republican _ it is not central to
this race. Both men are running unopposed for their party's
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, neither currently reports having a huge amount of cash
on hand _ $176,00 for Koster as of Aug. 31, compared to $212,000
for Larsen. But national leaders in both parties have said they
expect to pour significant amounts into the race.
</P>
<P>
   If moderate ``swing'' voters are the key to the election, Larsen
may have some advantages. He often casts himself as a ``fiscal
moderate,'' while Koster is an unabashed conservative. He said at
the July debate that he was proud to have voted against every state
budget since 1994, and he is staunchly anti-abortion, having
suggested in one fund-raising letter earlier this year that he
would ``support all efforts to defund the abortion industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with voters in the district suggested that many are
only beginning to focus on the race. Several said the tax
reductions advocated by Koster and other Republicans did not hold a
lot of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tax cut, that's not as important as knowing your Medicare
coverage will be there, knowing Social Security is sound,'' said
Sherry Andrews, 51, a human resources administrator at Boeing here
in Everett.
</P>
<P>
   But Kate Stannard, 63, a former schoolteacher from Mukilteo, a
town just south of here, echoed many voters who brought up cultural
issues that they said made them lean toward the Republicans and
could energize the turnout for Koster. ``I think children are being
brought up in an amoral world,'' she said. ``We need to teach
values in the schools. That's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor at play is Vice President Al Gore's rising
standing in some statewide polls, which, if it holds here, could
give Koster less of a bounce than some analysts were predicting
earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I've heard a lot of theories on this,'' said Koster.
``Of course, when Bush's numbers were much higher, everyone
expected there'd be coattails. But we're running this campaign like
it all depends on us. If there are coattails, that's fine and
dandy, but I'm not counting on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2057EDT &QL; 
