A1089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-WOMENWORK13-COX     09-12 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENWORK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making jobs work for women
 &HT;    By Stephanie Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At Cross Country TravCorps, a Boca Raton
medical staffing company, a woman not only heads the largest
division but works four days a week. Job sharing isn't limited by
geography _ women who live as far apart as Florida and Connecticut
split work.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Commission on the Status of Women named Cross
Country the state's top large employer for women during a news
conference Tuesday at the Colony Hotel in Palm Beach. The
commission also announced top employers in the small and government
employer categories as part of its seventh annual Best Florida
Employers for Working Women competition.
</P>
<P>
   Large employers include companies with more than 50 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Winners were culled from 92 entries by industrial psychologist
Deborah Johnson, who as a pregnant mother of two, works from home.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second accolade Cross Country has received this month.
</P>
<P>
   The October issue of Working Mother magazine picked the company
as one of the top 100 employers nationally for moms. Cross Country
employs about 500, of which 80 percent are women.
</P>
<P>
   Cross Country's Chief Executive Joseph A. Boshart said strong
financial results and a family-friendly work environment have gone
hand-in-hand. Revenue has grown 25 percent a year, reaching $400
million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cross Country has offered employees flexible
work hours, six months' maternity leave, on-site personal trainers
and yoga classes and lactation rooms for nursing mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The measures also build employee loyalty. When he joined Cross
Country in 1993, turnover reached as high as 80 percent. Now, it's
about 10 percent, Boshart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of employers are reluctant to give employees
flexibility ... but our experience is people work harder to make it
work,'' Boshart said.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Anenberg, who works four days a week, heads a division
that pulls in 80 percent of the company's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Boshart said he would pit her productivity against any manager
who works a full work week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she said she wanted to work two days a week, I'd give it to
her because she'll just become that much more efficient,'' Boshart
said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also recognized 13 other Florida companies and
governmental agencies lauded for providing benefits that include
on-site schools and even an on-site day care staffed with nurses
for sick children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many companies out there doing the right thing by
women,'' said commission member Patricia Clements.
</P>
<P>
   stephaniesmith(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
