<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS COSTS SOAR, BUSINESS TRAVEL DEPARTMENTS REVISE POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication notice: also sent with `t' code)  
 By JOE SHARKEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lately, dealing with my corporate travel department is like
being pecked to death by a duck,'' said a senior executive I know
who travels more than 100,000 miles a year on business and feels
that he is being increasingly second-guessed by the bean counters
when he tries to exercise some personal choice in his airline and
hotel arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint is a common one. As business-travel costs soar,
many travel departments are revamping existing travel policies or
drafting new ones and insisting on more strict adherence to them.
The importance of compliance to these policies has increased
significantly, according to American Express Co.'s latest annual
survey on business travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   What used to be a simple matter of buying an airplane ticket or
booking a hotel room has become a complicated algorithm requiring
the manipulation of prices, discounts, rebates, supplies,
technologies, schedules, demands, preferences, procedures and
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   By necessity, travel departments are becoming increasingly
aggressive and creative in keeping costs under control, said Rusty
Carpenter, the vice president for American Express Consulting
Services, a unit of American Express Co. that helps corporations
manage travel and purchasing expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At many companies, travel departments now more than ever are
dictating who you fly, what you drive, when you leave, where you
stay and why you need to adhere to the rules.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to hear from readers describing their experiences n
good or bad n with new company travel policies. Meanwhile, let's
give the travel departments their due and look at what they're
facing.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in the United States spent about $185 billion on
business travel last year, according to the Institute of Business
Travel Management. That compares with $70 billion in 1982, when
such costs were first tracked. World-wide, about $396 billion is
spent annually on business travel, according to Marianne McInerney,
the executive director of the National Business Travel Association.
</P>
<P>
   The American Express survey, Trends and Forecasts for the
Business Travel Industry: Preview 2001, estimates that business air
fares, hotel rates and car rentals are all expected to rise by at
least 5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   Business air fares, which American Express said rose 8 percent
in the second quarter compared with the same period last year, are
volatile. So it's difficult to predict that 5 percent is all they
will rise. Major carriers recently hiked fares, blaming fuel costs.
The survey noted that proposed and potential mergers among carriers
here and abroad can radically alter the competitive landscape of
the airline industry, possibly leading to even higher fares.
</P>
<P>
   The average booked price for hotels also rose 8 percent in the
second quarter and is expected to increase 6 percent next year
domestically (and 3 percent internationally), American Express
said. But prices are increasing more in high-demand business
cities. In the first quarter of this year, for example, average
room-rates booked in New York, Boston and Houston rose about 10
percent. In Miami, the rate hike was over 15 percent. In Europe,
increases averaged over 20 percent in cities such as Florence,
Paris, Rome and Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0350 </DOCNO>
