<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SUBLIMINAL-AD13-COX     09-12 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBLIMINAL-AD13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Subliminal debate out in the open again
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millions of Americans smoke Camel cigarettes. It has little to
do with nicotine, flavor _ or even the Joe Camel character, claims
Wilson Bryan Key.
</P>
<P>
   It has everything to do with a little man hidden in the shadows
of the picture of a camel on the pack of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a phallic symbol,'' Key maintains. ``And that's why Camel
has sold millions of cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Key, one of a handful of gurus in the field, is talking about
subliminal advertising. It's advertising you can't consciously
detect _ a word flashed too quickly to see, an image hidden within
another image, an imperceptible sound _ and it supposedly holds a
powerful sway over human behavior. And it's illegal on broadcast
TV, even though it's never been proven to work.
</P>
<P>
   Believers say it makes people smoke. It may even make them vote
Republican, judging by the furor that erupted Tuesday when it was
revealed that an anti-Gore campaign ad contains the word ``rats''
shown for a fraction of a second.
</P>
<P>
   The adman who created the commercial, Alex Castellanos, called
the insertion of the word ``purely accidental.'' Democratic
strategists howled that was not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the suggestion that the GOP was trying to plant a
secret message harks back to the Red Scare of the 1950s, when
so-called subliminal advertising was first perceived as a public
menace.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``subliminal advertising'' entered the language in
1957 when adman James Vicary was profiled in Vance Packard's expose
``The Hidden Persuaders,'' which darkly portrayed the motives of
Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Vicary supposedly had designed a ``subliminal projection
machine'' and successfully tested it at a movie theater in Fort
Lee, N.J. During a six-week period, Vicary claimed, he blipped the
words ``Hungry? Eat Popcorn'' and ``Drink Coca-Cola'' on the screen
every five minutes during the showing of the film ``Picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   The words flashed so quickly the audience didn't realize they
were there. Meantime, Coke sales jumped 18 percent and popcorn
sales 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a national sensation,'' says Texas professor John
Murphy, who has studied the history and effectiveness of subliminal
advertising. ``Unfortunately, it was all a hoax. Vicary recanted
his story years later. He made it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Vicary, a Maine TV station tested a subliminal
message _ ``If you have seen this message, write WTWO'' _ but
abandoned it after a few weeks when there was no increase in mail.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Congress got into the act, led by Rep. William Dawson, a
Utah Republican, who asked the Federal Communications Commission to
ban the advertising from TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contemplate, if you will,'' warned Dawson, ``the effect of an
invisible but effective appeal to `drink more beer' being poured
into the subconscious of teenage television viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC resisted a ban, saying it wasn't sure it had the
authority. Evidence continued to mount that subliminal ads didn't
work anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian broadcasters flashed the hidden message ``telephone
now'' 352 times during a half-hour show. Of 500 viewers surveyed
afterward, only one reported the urge to make a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, the issue flared again when an announcer on the CBS
show ``To Tell The Truth'' joked that audience was being fed
subliminal ads during the program credits. In 1973, after
complaints of a TV station that inserted the subliminal message
``Get It'' at the end of a commercial, the FCC finally did make
subliminal broadcast advertising illegal _ ``whether effective or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was mainly Key who kept the issue alive in the
public mind, authoring five books on the subject. His best known,
now out of print, is ``Subliminal Seduction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff works with a vengeance,'' Key said Tuesday in a
telephone interview from his home near Reno, Nev. ``The only
mistake Castellanos made was he made it too obvious. You shouldn't
be able to see it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Key claims that advertisers still use the technique, inserting
images imperceptibly using digital technology. But he can't cite a
specific ad. ``I don't watch much TV,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of subliminal advertising is well enough known that
everybody got the joke when ``Saturday Night Live'' featured a
regular character, Subliminal Man, who uttered ``hot sex'' and
other come-ons under his breath while carrying on outwardly
innocent conversations.
</P>
<P>
   And earler this year, English advertising agency Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi was accused of inserting Satanic images into the
backgrounds of a Toyota commercial that aired in France. The agency
denied anything intentional, but edited the images out of the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer psychologist Carol Moog, who does work for Nabisco and
Lever Brothers, says people already feel so manipulated by
advertising, especially political advertising, they want to believe
there are subliminal ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get asked about it all the time, as if it's a current
strategy in advertising,'' she says. ``They believe it exists
because it validates their worries about not being in control of
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Murphy says subliminal advertising is an ``urban
myth'' that won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that Vicary, the supposed originator of the
practice, disappeared long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's sure where Vicary is now,'' jokes Murphy. ``Maybe
he's working for the Republican National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
