<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dresdner Bank in Talks to Buy Wasserstein Perella
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein Perella is in advanced talks to be acquired by
Dresdner Bank of Germany and, if the two can come to terms on
price, a deal could be announced in three to five days, a person
close to the talks said. If an agreement is reached, it would be
the symbolic end of the swachbuckling style of deal-making
celebrated in the 1980's, which has been replaced by a blander type
of investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Company Teaches Tax Avoidance
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials say that abusive corporate tax shelters are
the government's biggest tax enforcement problem, costing billions
of dollars annually. Now a company called the Tax People is
teaching similar tax avoidance techniques to middle-class Americans
and says it has already signed up 50,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett Rolls Out New Computer
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard rolled out the powerful computer it is counting
on to lift sales to companies that need systems capable of handling
huge amounts of data around the clock. Carly S. Fiorina,
Hewlett-Packard's chief executive, hailed the new computer, called
Superdome, as a symbol of the company's claim that it has been
``reinvented'' as a more customer-oriented vendor selling solutions
rather than products. Fiorina did not mention the company's talks
to acquire the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, but
analysts said that such a deal would be consistent with the vision
involved in Superdome. Shares of Hewlett-Packard fell $2.19, to
$112.56.
</P>
<P>
   Merger of Exchanges Abandoned
</P>
<P>
   The London Stock Exchange scrapped its proposal to merge with
the Frankfurt stock exchange, abandoning for now an effort to
create the first pan-European stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King Puts Account in Review
</P>
<P>
   Burger King placed the creative duties for its general market
advertising account, involving assignments with billings estimated
at $400 million, in review. The incumbent agency, the New York
office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners Worldwide, is being invited to
participate in the review, but the company said it would be
expected to offer a drastically new approach to the account.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Declines, but Dow Edges Up
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks declined, but blue chips rose modestly, driven
by the surging shares of J.P. Morgan. The Nasdaq composite index
fell 46.84 points, or 1.2 percent, to 3,849.51. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 37.74 points, or 0.3 percent, to 11,233.23.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was down 7.27 points, or 0.5
percent, to 1,481.99.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a Supportive Atmosphere
</P>
<P>
   Royal Farros, the chief executive of iPrint.com, an online
printing service, says managing a company involves a lot of the
same expectations and feelings as having pets. Creating a loving,
affectionate home for pets is similar to fostering an active
environment where employees feel important and influential.
Building such a culture is not just critical to the personality of
an organization, he says, but absolutely key to its livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Political Volunteers in White Collars
</P>
<P>
   For all the fund raising by Democrats and Republicans this year,
candidates for offices from the the White House to the local school
board know one thing is even more important than money: volunteers.
And while these unpaid armies are made up mostly of students and
retired people, it is business professionals who exhibit the
qualities that political candidates value most: nuts-and-bolts
organizational skills, management savvy and address books filled
with contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Departments Toughen Limits
</P>
<P>
   With estimates that business air fares, hotel rates and car
rentals will rise by at least 5 percent next year, many travel
departments are revamping travel policies or drafting new ones _
and insisting on more strict adherence to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
