<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TIRE-SAFETY-HNS &LR;      09-12 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-SAFETY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Transportation secretary seeks more power from Senate panel,
while Ford, Firestone point fingers
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JENNIFER HOYT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater asked
lawmakers Tuesday to expand his agency's authority to investigate
and penalize companies for violating vehicle and tire safety rules
as officials from Ford and Firestone tried to blame the other for a
series of fatal car crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like tying two cats by the tail and throwing them over
the clothesline and letting them claw each other,'' Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., said about the Ford and Firestone feud that was
aired during a hearing before Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate panel was the third in less than a week to summon
Transportation officials and executives from Firestone/Bridgestone
and Ford Motor Corp. to discuss the recall last month of 6.5
million Firestone tires. The recall was issued in the wake of
vehicle crashes in which 88 people have been killed and another 250
injured in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to fend off criticism that his agency was slow to
order the recall, Slater said the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration needs broader investigative authority to detect and
avoid hazards similar to the Firestone tire case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of no clearer case in which this message must be
heard,'' Slater said. ``We must look to the future and guard
against any repetition of tragedies caused by defective vehicles or
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, chairman of the Commerce Committee, said the
case points up the need to strengthen the transportation agency's
authority. ``Currently, NHTSA plays the role of a toothless and
declawed cat in a game of cat and mouse with automakers,'' said
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Slater wants Congress to increase civil penalties for defective
products, require manufactures to provide free remedies to
consumers for a longer period of time, and require manufactures to
test their products as part of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation secretary also wants the agency to have the
authority to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Require companies to alert U.S. officials to defects in their
vehicles or equipment overseas if that information relates to
vehicles or equipment here.
</P>
<P>
   -- Collect from foreign governments and organizations
information relating to defective products that could be present
here.
</P>
<P>
   -- Get claims, warranty and adjustment data from manufacturers
and companies that produce original equipment, as well as claims
information from insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Slater also encouraged lawmakers to allow the agency to devise a
system for providing consumers with guidance on the possibility of
vehicle rollovers. The Senate's version of the transportation
spending bill for 2001 would bar the agency from developing a
rollover rating system.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's hearing, Ford President and CEO Jacques Nasser
blasted Bridgestone/Firestone for not sharing information about
tire defects sooner. Nasser said he was surprised last week when
Firestone officials testified that they had been aware of tread
separation problems two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the candid and frank dialogue that Ford expects in
its business relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bridgestone/Firestone Executive Vice President John Lampe
said tire and vehicle problems should be investigated together. He
suggested that Ford's recommended tire pressure of 26 pounds per
square inch may have led to the tire failure. Bridgestone/Firestone
recommends tire pressure of 30 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take full responsibility, senators, when a tire fails
because of a defect,'' Lampe said. ``We firmly believe, however,
that the tire is only part of the overall safety problem shown by
these tragic accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA Administrator Sue Bailey said she thought the problem was
with tires, but that the agency was still investigating the
vehicle-tire interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Senators Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Herb
Kohl, D-Wis., announced they would introduce a bill to increase
civil penalties for withholding information from NHTSA. Their bill
also would set criminal penalties for companies that knowingly
allow defective vehicles or parts to be distributed if death or
injury results.
</P>
<P>
   The Feinstein-Kohl bill would increase civil penalties for
withholding information from NHTSA and for failing to recall
defective vehicles or parts from $1,000 per violation to $10,000
per violation. It also would eliminate the maximum penalty, now set
at $925,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When consumer health and safety are at issue, there cannot be
any question that the American public deserves full, open and
complete disclosure,'' Kohl said. ``Anything less endangers each
and every one of us, and our measure _ with its tough penalties _
will take defective products off the market.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bridgestone/Firestone, 2 million of the 6.5 million
P235/75R15-size ATX, ATX II and similarly sized Wilderness AT tires
recalled on Aug. 9 have been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
