<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore, Lieberman ride school bus through Ohio talking about
education
</P>
<P>
   By PATTY REINERT
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore took a
campaign swing through southwestern Ohio on a yellow school bus
Tuesday to draw attention to his $170 billion education plan.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.,
Gore greeted students arriving for classes at Anna K. Wantz Middle
School in Miamisburg Tuesday morning. The vice president told them
that he and Republican opponent George W. Bush agree that decisions
involving schools should be made at the local level, and both
believe in making schools more accountable for their performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is the plan that Joe Lieberman and I are
putting out starts with accountability but doesn't end there,''
Gore said. ``What we're proposing is a comprehensive approach that
focuses first of all on the classroom,'' he said, rattling off his
proposals for recruiting 100,000 new teachers and paying and
training them better, reducing class sizes, fixing dilapidated
schools and hooking them to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan, which would cost more than $170 billion over the
next decade, also calls for universal preschool for all 3- and
4-year-olds, making college tuition tax-deductible and providing
lifelong skills training to help workers keep up with rapidly
changing technology.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would increase spending by $48 billion, focusing primarily
on literacy programs, scholarships and grants. He proposes stiffer
standards for accountability than Gore does. And he would offer
parents more flexibility in choosing schools _ including vouchers
for students of poor parents in failing schools, an idea Gore
rejects as harmful to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president noted that he is not proposing as extensive a
tax cut as Bush _ a cut Gore says benefits mostly the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one reason we will not go along with that is that it would
take away the chance we have now to use our prosperity to help lift
up the schools,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman then loaded a group of students, teachers and
parents onto a bus motorcade and held a rolling discussion on
school violence, class size and teacher salaries during the
50-minute ride to a high school in Middletown.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they stopped to greet a marching band and other
supporters in Franklin, ate lunch with high schoolers in Middletown
and attended a rainy rally at a technical and community college in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Gore gave only slight mention to the day's big campaign flap,
over a Republican National Committee television ad in which the
word ``RATS'' flashes briefly in front of text on the screen
criticizing Gore's prescription drug plan for those on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a disappointing development,'' Gore said during a
quick stop along his route. ``I've never seen anything like it. I
think the ad speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the ad's producers denied any effort to send a
subliminal message.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Gore flew to Philadelphia for a fund-raising
concert featuring entertainers Cher and Michael Bolton, which was
expected to raise more than $800,000 for the Democratic National
Committee. Today, (WEDNESDAY) he will continue his education
campaign tour in Maine before attending a fund-raising concert by
singer James Taylor in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch in Middletown, Gore and Lieberman moved to the high
school's gymnasium where they were greeted by a band and a crowd of
students, faculty and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing Gore, Lieberman told the students that the election
``is not about us or our opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about you and your future _ what's good for you,''
Lieberman said. He gave Gore a hug as the crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all of you to be able to reach your full potential by
having access to the best education possible,'' Gore told the
students.
</P>
<P>
   He also gave his standard stump speech on prescription drugs,
health care, environment and balancing the budget, and he asked
students to ``think long and hard about what it means to be an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody here tells you it doesn't make any difference what
happens in elections, if anybody tells you that politics is
something you should stay way away from, don't listen to that,'' he
said, ``because for all the problems in government and politics, it
is what we make it, and it is going to be what you make it.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
