<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ADOPTS STRONGER RULES GOVERNING PIPELINES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By NEIL STRASSMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first in a series of tough new rules to protect Texans from
natural gas and hazardous liquid pipeline disasters were adopted
Tuesday by state officials.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, approved by the Texas Railroad Commission, cover
plastic pipes used to transport natural gas _ the type of pipe that
ruptured in January, killing three people in the Dallas suburb of
Garland.
</P>
<P>
   More frequent and thorough inspections of intrastate lines and
stiffer penalties for failing to call the state for pipeline
locations before digging,
</P>
<P>
   are proposals expected to come before the commission later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   An Abilene police detective died Friday, one day after a
bulldozer ruptured a 12-inch steel pipeline sending a propane cloud
across a highway. Jay Hatcher, 42, suffered fatal burns after the
cloud ignited. A woman at a home destroyed by a wall of flames
barely escaped by diving into a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety must be our number one priority,'' Railroad Commission
Chairman Michael Williams said of the state's 250,000 miles of
pipelines. ``In light of what we found in Garland, we need an
inventory of information and materials so that we can direct
removal and replacement if there is a danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules adopted by the commission, natural gas
pipeline operators must:
</P>
<P>
   _ Note each failure of plastic pipe in an annual report to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disclose in a new construction report the type of pipe,
operating pressure and route, at least 30 days before building five
miles or more of pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inventory by 2005, the amount, type and location of all
plastic pipe being used to transport natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction with one type of pipe,''
Commissioner Tony Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   More than two-thirds of pipeline fatalities and injuries are
caused by breaks in natural gas lines, which make up 90 percent of
the nation's 2.2 million miles of pipeline, according to government
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the natural gas and propane explosions of the past 30
years have been traced to problems with cracking in early versions
of polyethylene pipe introduced in the late 1960s. As the pipe
ages, it becomes brittle and susceptible to damage from extreme
temperature changes and adjacent rocks.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, the crack-prone plastic pipe was banned,
replaced by more pliable, longer-lasting pipe made from modern
plastic resins, said Rich Gottwald, executive director of the
Plastics Pipe Institute, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the gas companies now use plastic,'' he said, adding
that some larger diameter high-pressure pipe is steel.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a 30-inch diameter steel natural gas pipeline owned
by the Houston-based El Paso Natural Gas Co. ruptured at the Pecos
River in rural southeastern New Mexico, killing 12 people in three
related families camping nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators discovered corrosion in the pipeline that
exploded and federal records show that the company has had 30
corrosion- related accidents since 1970, two of which claimed four
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The commission expects to adopt a ``risk-based'' testing program
of pipelines, Garza said. Pipeline age, accident records and
proximity to aquifers and population centers are factors that would
determine testing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply because a pipe is old doesn't mean it is a threat,''
Garza said. ``Let's just test them more thoroughly and more
often.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Explorer Pipeline carrying gasoline from Louisiana
to Chicago ruptured near Greenville in Northeast Texas, spilling
500,000 gallons into Lake Tawakoni, causing Dallas to lose
one-third of its water supply for six months. Federal investigators
have said outside damage was not a factor in the break.
</P>
<P>
   New rules may also require setbacks and easements to put a fixed
distance between pipelines and existing structures, and stiffer
penalties for ignoring the state's call-before-you dig ``One-call
System,'' that can help keep people from digging into pipelines,
the most frequent cause of pipeline accidents in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators of the Abilene accident have said that there are
no indications that the bulldozer company called for pipeline
locations before digging.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas fine of $50 for failing to make a call is among the
lowest in the nation, said Garza, who wants the penalty increased
to $1,000 for first-time offenders and from $2,500 to $10,000 for
repeat offenders, but that would require Legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Garza said pipeline issues would probably come
before the Legislature in the session that begins in January.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the U.S. Senate approved a bill to improve pipeline
safety, largely for interstate pipelines governed by the Department
of Transportation's Office of Pipeline Safety. The bill, which
awaits consideration in the House, calls for larger fines,
increased state oversight and greater disclosure of information by
pipeline operators.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2114EDT &QL; 
