<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-OHIO13-COX     09-12 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OHIO13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore kisses babies, talks education
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMISBURG, Ohio _ Vice President Al Gore Tuesday promised to
make the plight of the nation's schools his No. 1 priority, as he
visited three Miami Valley schools with a rolling caravan of school
buses and an entourage of students, teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee, and his vice
presidential running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., boarded
a yellow school bus in the early morning hours in downtown Dayton
and rode to Miamisburg's Wantz Middle School, where they greeted
hundreds of cheering students before classes started, then met in a
classroom with a small group of teachers, students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   From Miamisburg, the candidates made a brief stop at Franklin
High School, then went to Middletown High, where Gore and Lieberman
again met with students in classrooms and ate lunch at the school
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they were interviewed on the bus by student
journalists from around the state. They finished the day with a
rally in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   At every stop, Gore said the nation's schools needed ``dramatic
and revolutionary change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The same kind of debate you've been having in Dayton is going
on all over the United States,'' Gore told a group of 15 Wantz
students. ``It's hard to come up with the funding for all the new
students and to modernize schools that were built a long time ago
and to build new schools so you don't have to cover up playgrounds
with portable classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his school proposals are similar to those of his
Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, in that they both
want to hold schools and teachers more accountable for student
performance. Gore said his plan is pledging $170 billion over 10
years on education while the Bush proposals would not be able to
afford that because Republicans are proposing income tax cuts
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered that Gore has had eight years as vice
president to address the ills of the nation's schools and has
failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago the vice president promised to close the
achievement gap in education between disadvantaged students and
their peers, but he hasn't delivered,'' said Lisa Graham Keegan, a
Republican and Arizona's superintendent of public instruction who
visited a Middletown elementary school Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's education proposals include money to help school
districts recruit 100,000 new teachers, including $10,000 signing
bonuses to attract teachers to some high-demand districts, and a
$10,000 annual tax deduction for college tuition expenses.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposes national proficiency tests for new teachers,
continued support for charter schools, and a national program in
which consistently poor-performing public schools are shuttered and
reopened under new staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said both he and Bush ``believe there should be new
accountability to encourage better performance. The difference is
the plan Joe Lieberman and I are putting out starts with
accountability but it doesn't end there.''
</P>
<P>
   A wave of teacher hiring would allow average class sizes to
shrink to 18 to 20 students, Gore claimed. He is also proposing $50
billion to make pre-school available for all 4-year-olds, $20
billion in special education spending, and $8 billion in school
construction bond subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it a national priority to help local
communities modernize and improve their schools,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign defended its positions and said its proposal
to spend $47.6 billion over 10 years on everything from Head Start
to college assistance would do more for learning than Gore's $170
billion plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear from some of the proposals Al Gore is laying out
now that he wants to be the national superintendent,'' said Bush
spokesman Bob Hopkins. ``It's probably worse than the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, however, said a Gore-Lieberman administration would
support leaving control of schools at the local level.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with aging school buildings were in evidence during
the Democrats' tour. Gore and Lieberman had to dodge a trash can
set in a hallway at Middletown High School to catch dripping
rainwater. At Wantz Middle School, with nearly 800 students, Gore
sweated through his shirt during his morning speech because the
sweltering classroom where he spoke was not air conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   During the bus ride from Miamisburg to Middletown, Lieberman _
making his first visit to the area as a national candidate _ held
court with a dozen high school journalism students and teachers
from around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Mississiniwa Valley High School senior Misty Moehl asked
Lieberman how his Jewish faith might effect the U.S.'s role in the
Middle East peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman praised Moehl for asking a good question and said his
first responsibility as vice president would be upholding U.S. laws
and policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's peace in the Middle East, it is good for the
United States,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   The caravan caused near chaos wherever it went. At a brief visit
to the front of Franklin High School, a stop just scheduled on
Sunday, Lieberman marched up the front lawn of neighboring homes
and high-fived 3-year-old Cory Aleksin and spoke briefly with
Cory's mother, Linda.
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, Gore and Lieberman spoke to about 2,000 people at
a rally at the Cincinnati State Technical and Community College.
There, Gore left the education theme and ran through his
traditional stump speech, pledging to act on prescription drug
coverage in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I won't be the most exciting politician, but I will
work hard for you everyday,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jim Bebbington at e-mail him at
jimbebbington(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
