<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-NYT &LR;      09-12 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN'S CLAIM TO $12.6 MILLION IS RECOGNIZED BY ELECTION
COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Offering a moral victory but no immediate cash, the
Federal Election Commission on Tuesday upheld Pat Buchanan's claim
to $12.6 million in disputed federal campaign funds earmarked for
the Reform Party's presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In an ``initial determination'' of a heated Reform Party
dispute, the commission voted 5-1 that Buchanan is the legitimate
nominee and entitled to the money. But the actual awarding of the
funds from the treasury must await the commission's final
determination at some later date, with a federal court fight
threatened after that.
</P>
<P>
   The commission rejected the rival claim of John Hagelin, an Iowa
physicist who was nominated by a Reform faction that staged a
walkout at the party convention last month rather than take part in
Buchanan's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan camp hailed the decision by the commission and
signaled Buchanan's emphatic return to the national hustings after
a month's recuperation for gall bladder surgery. He is to deliver
an address on Monday at Bob Jones University in Greenville, S.C.
The Bob Jones campus became an issue for the Republicans during the
primaries when Gov. George W. Bush of Texas spoke there, despite
critics' complaints that the university banned interracial dating
and had a history of anti-Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in pretty good shape, as long as the money comes in this
week,'' said Bay Buchanan, the sister and campaign strategist of
the candidate, who bolted the Republican Party last October when
his presidential quest flagged.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, the fiery conservative polemicist whose standing has
plummeted to 1 percent in recent national opinion polls, has been
bedeviled by the challenge of the Hagelin faction. Hagelin has
already said he will try to continue the challenge to Buchanan's
legitimacy beyond the commission with a federal court suit.
</P>
<P>
   In the remaining eight weeks of the campaign, Buchanan has said
his goal is to tap into the federal financing to begin television
ads and to win his own court fight to gain entry into the televised
presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which meets again on Thursday, set no date for
its final determination, said Ian Stirton, a spokesman. A petition
from an anti-Buchanan faction in New York remains to be dealt with
before the final determination.
</P>
<P>
   The petition includes an affidavit from Ross Perot, the founder
of the Reform Party, siding with Hagelin as ``the only proper
candidate to receive public funding, based on the votes I received
in the 1996 election.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission majority found otherwise in its initial
determination, after investigating the extent of the rivals'
support in state Reform organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt here that Buchanan is the party's nominee,
and there is no reason to delay the certification,'' Bradley Smith,
a commission member, said.
</P>
<P>
   The one dissenting commissioner, Karl Sandstrom, insisted that
the decision was hasty and should be left for the courts to settle.
``The law requires more of us than of officials at a track meet,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's final determination, which could be made within
days, then would be followed by its certification to the treasury
that the money can flow to the Buchanan campaign's cash-starved
coffers. Whether Hagelin can block this through the courts remains
an open question.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has been sorely counting on the federal funds, which
come from taxpayers' nonpartisan voluntary check-off on federal
income tax returns. The amount of money is calculated using the 8
percent share of the vote won by Perot in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now move forward with our campaign and go after Al Gore
and George W. Bush and take our issues to the American public,''
declared Tim Haley, Buchanan's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan contends that the drawn-out challenge to his
candidacy's legitimacy, which includes continuing ballot challenges
in state courts, is ultimately being financed by Perot. But Russell
Varney, a Perot associate, declared, ``That is not true, and
Buchanan knows it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
