u i BC-EUROPE-FUEL-1STLD-WRI     09-12 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FUEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-760&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS OVER FUEL PRICES HOBBLE BRITAIN, PARTS OF CONTINENTAL
EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete writethru to update and include new details;
also adds info on protests in Continental Europe; adds art note) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Spreading protests over high fuel prices all but halted
gasoline deliveries across Britain on Tuesday, forcing most service
stations to close for lack of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   As panicked motorists set out on frantic, often fruitless, hunts
for gasoline, ambulance companies and fire departments began
cutting back services. Many hospitals canceled all but essential
procedures, and some scheduled diesel trains were canceled
altogether. The Royal Mail said many of its delivery trucks had
just a day's worth of fuel left.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair struggled to contain his worst
domestic crisis as similar protests continued to spread through
Western Europe, where truck drivers, farmers and small businessmen
have formed impromptu coalitions to protest cripplingly high fuel
prices. In Belgium, truck drivers kept traffic at a standstill in
Brussels for the third day in a row and blockaded three fuel depots
in the south. In the Netherlands, protesters blocked two major
tunnels on roads near Amsterdam and Rotterdam at the height of the
rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, a convoy of 100 buses, trucks and taxicabs drove
from the French border to the state Parliament Building in
Saarbruecken to demand that the government lower fuel prices.
Farmers and truck drivers in Ireland, Italy, Poland and Spain
threatened to mount actions within the week if their price-cutting
demands were not met.
</P>
<P>
   But as discontent spread around the Continent, Britain held the
dubious honor of being the country most flattened by the protests.
Although its refineries and storage depots are full of fuel,
blockades have prevented the fuel from being delivered to service
stations.
</P>
<P>
   People waited for hours Tuesday to buy gasoline, and those
unable to buy it said they might have to stay home from work on
Wednesday. The shortages struck so quickly because people rushed to
the pumps in an effort to refuel before it was too late. Around the
country, there were scattered reports of people stealing fuel from
parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In South Wales, the Spar supermarket chain said there had been a
300 percent increase in purchases of staples like bread, milk and
canned goods by people worried that supplies would run out or that
they would be unable to drive to the store.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Petrol Retailers' Association, Roy Holloway,
warned that there might be no fuel left for sale anywhere by
Wednesday. ``In the next 24 hours,'' Holloway said, ``it is
unlikely that we will see any retail fuel sales in the UK.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Blair sought to appease an increasingly restive electorate by
promising that essential services would continue and saying that he
expected deliveries of fuel to start again ``in the next 24
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   He also firmly ruled out capitulating to the protesters' demands
that he lower the 76.2 percent fuel tax, the highest in Europe and
the main reason that gasoline in Britain costs $4.37 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Queen Elizabeth II met a representative of the
Privy Council _ a panel of senior politicians, judges and church
leaders _ and granted the government ``exceptional powers'' under a
law from 1976 to force oil companies to provide fuel to services
like hospitals and schools. It was unclear whether the government
would move to invoke such powers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After emergency meetings with his Cabinet and with Britain's
largest oil companies Tuesday, Blair said that the companies had
pledged to do all that they could to start deliveries moving from
their blockaded depots and refineries, provided that their drivers
were guaranteed police protection. But though there were signs that
small numbers of oil trucks were carrying fuel from depots late
Tuesday night, and though there has been no violence, many
companies seemed reluctant to order drivers to cross the
protesters' informal picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the issue has always been the safety of our drivers,''
a spokesman for Shell Oil said. ``They have said they don't feel
comfortable, that they don't feel safe.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The protesters are a mixture of truck, bus and taxicab drivers,
farmers and small-business owners, all of whom say the increasing
cost of fuel threatens their livelihoods. Not organized by a union
or any one group, they have joined together out of a common
desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll come down every day if I have to, until I run out of fuel
myself,'' Derek Wood, a hauling contractor who was protesting at
the gasoline depot for the Total oil company in Leeds, told the
BBC. ``Our lads have nothing to lose.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Public opinion about the protesters, their tactics and the
government's responsibility to resolve the problem is sharply
polarized. Many Britons appear inclined to agree with William
Hague, the leader of the Conservative opposition, who said he did
not think that Blair ``has got a grip on the situation or
understands how angry people are about taxes being loaded on and on
to fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the unhappy mood, The Mirror published an enormous
photograph of the prime minister as he passed a line of cars at a
service station on Monday on his way to a meeting under the
headline, ``I'm All Right Jag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Blair glides past petrol-starved drivers in his Jaguar,''
the newspaper said, noting that the prime minister ``will always
have a full tank,'' no matter who else is waiting for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's car was pummeled by protesters later, the paper noted
with some glee, and a blockade by trucks, trailers and taxicabs
prevented him from attending a dinner on Monday night for his
deputy, John Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   Such images resonate with people like Colin Palmer, a taxicab
driver in London who said that fuel was prohibitively expensive and
that it was the government's fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``This job is getting unviable,'' Palmer, 45, said. ``If Blair
doesn't listen to people protesting about the price of fuel, we're
going to be worse off than we were under the Conservative
government.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blair made clear Tuesday _ as did Germany and the
Netherlands _ that Britain would not capitulate to protesters'
demands that it lower gasoline taxes. Last week, after widespread
protests in France, the government there agreed to lower its fuel
tax 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that whatever the rights and wrongs of the argument
over fuel duty, we cannot accept as a government or as a nation
that policy should be dictated by illegal blockades, pickets or
direct action,'' Blair told a news conference late Tuesday
afternoon. ``Whatever the strength of the feeling, there can be no
excuse whatever for this type of action, which is hurting our
people, businesses and emergency services severely.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers agreed, saying they supported the protesters'
goals, but could not countenance their methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, people are queuing for a half-hour to get
fuel,'' said Brian Shapiro, another London cabdriver, who said he
had enough fuel to keep running through Wednesday. ``Tomorrow,''
Shapiro said, ``when there's no fuel, when people are struggling to
get to work, to get their kids to school, you'll see how quickly
public opinion shifts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
