<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1138 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-GIRLS-$ADV17-985(2     09-12 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GIRLS-$ADV17-985(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING THROUGH ANIMATION'S BOY BARRIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
Ted Loos is a Manhattan-based free-lance writer specializing in
film and the visual arts. 
 By TED LOOS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Hale was developing an animated television show that
looked as if it had potential. ``Generation O!,'' about an
8-year-old who just happened to be an international rock star, had
a funny concept, catchy music and a punchy visual style.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem: The 8-year-old star was a girl named
Molly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were banging our heads against a wall,'' Hale recalled of
the meetings he and his partners, Jim Proimos and Tim Newman, had
with the networks. ``It was the old cliche: Girls will watch boys,
but boys don't watch girls. We had many people tell us, `If you
turn this character into a boy, this is a hit show.'''
</P>
<P>
   They stuck by their idea, and five years after their initial
brainstorm, ``Generation O!'' made its debut, on Aug. 26 on WB,
with the lead character intact. ``To us, it's a girl empowerment
show,'' Hale said. ``And being a rock star is a thing that every
kid aspires to.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly arrives during a season of extraordinary girl power in
animation: At least eight shows having their premieres in 2000 have
female leads, radically altering the landscape of television for
children. ABC is even turning a popular live star into a younger
animated version in ``Sabrina, the Animated Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The new programs range from two of Nickolodeon's programs for
preschoolers _ ``Maggie and the Ferocious Beast'' and ``Dora the
Explorer,'' both featuring little girls who navigate unknown lands
while imparting lessons about life _ to three fantasy-adventure
imports from the realm of Japanese-style anime.
</P>
<P>
   One of these, Fox's ``CyberSix,'' puts the most unusual twist on
gender. The lead is a female cyber-mutant who wears a tight black
cat suit and stiletto heels at night, but disguises herself as a
male literature teacher by day.
</P>
<P>
   These new shows fortify the ranks of those that have broken the
animated ``boy barrier'' in the past few seasons, ``Pepper Ann,''
``Daria'' and ``The Wild Thornberrys'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   The change couldn't be more stark. ``Ten years ago, it was
pretty much unheard of to have a female lead in an animation
show,'' said Linda Simensky, president of original animation for
the Cartoon Network. ``There was a great enlightenment in the early
'90s, spurred by `The Simpsons.' Lisa Simpson was such a good
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she wasn't the lead, Lisa _ an ironic teen-age
commentator on the world who's a good bit smarter than those around
her _ set the mold for one type of brainy cartoon girl, epitomized
by the sarcastic lead of ``Daria.''
</P>
<P>
   Simensky, who started her career at Nickelodeon, now presides
over the year-old ``Mike, Lu &AMP; Og,'' whose main character is a girl
named Mike, and ``The Powerpuff Girls,'' now in its third season,
which has been an unqualified hit for the Cartoon Network.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Powerpuff' is great because we never said, `OK, now give
them three best friends who are boys,''' Simensky said. ``If we
were concentrating on our jobs, we might have said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bubbles, Buttercup and Blossom are ``the world's cutest
superheroes,'' three bug-eyed, pint-size sisters who battle
assorted mutant villains in their native Townsville. The program's
action sequences entice children, while adults are attracted by its
superhero satire: The girls were created when their dad, Professor
Utonium, mistakenly mixed sugar, spice and everything nice with the
mysterious and potent Chemical X.
</P>
<P>
   Craig McCracken, who created ``The Powerpuff Girls'' when he was
still an animation student at the California Institute of the Arts,
suspected that the knowing humor would attract some older viewers,
and he was right: The show has become a pop phenomenon, with
licensed merchandise appearing everywhere and a feature film in the
works. What he didn't expect was that in a TV landscape with
relatively few options, young viewers would see the Powerpuff Girls
as role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a lot of girls saying that they look up to them,'' said
McCracken, who professes surprise at the reaction to his show. ``It
developed into a whole subculture. There are girls who say, `My
best friend's a Buttercup, but I'm a Bubbles.' They identify with
the different personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Powerpuff Girls'' and ``Generation O!'' are part of a trend
within the trend _ many of the new shows were created exclusively
by men. ``The real story is how three old guys have created the
hottest girls' property,'' joked Hale, 49, a musician and former
advertising executive. The character of Molly O! was inspired by
his daughter, Isabel, who is now 10.
</P>
<P>
   Historical precedent partly explains the initial resistance to
``Generation O!'' and other shows that struggled to get airtime. In
the heyday of the Warner Brothers cartoons, there were almost no
female animators and hence few female characters; Bugs Bunny in
drag was as girlish as it got.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the years went on, cartoon girls were eye candy or
dispensable plot points; exceptions like ``Josie and the
Pussycats'' were rare. And despite the recent influx, they're still
heavily outnumbered by boy-oriented shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracted us to having a strong female character like
Daria is that back in '97, we hadn't seen it before on
television,'' said Abby Terkuhle, president of MTV animation and
executive producer of ``Daria.''
</P>
<P>
   The character Daria Morgendorffer, an expressionless high
schooler with big black glasses, was spun off from MTV's ``Beavis
and Butthead.'' Now entering her fourth season of dispensing wry
witticisms, she has solidified her appeal with viewers enough to
merit her own TV movie, which was broadcast in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started in this business, there were few women in
animation at all,'' said Chuck Swenson, co-creator and executive
producer of ``Mike, Lu &AMP; Og.'' ``Now it's getting closer to equal
proportions. And as more women are coming to the fore on the
network side, you'll see even more girls in the shows.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
