<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    NASA extends Atlantis shuttle mission from 11 to 12 days
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MARK CARREAU
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after astronauts from the shuttle Atlantis swung open
the hatches to the international space station on Tuesday, NASA
extended their flight.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching the mission from 11 to 12 days will give the
shuttle's five American astronauts and two Russian cosmonauts more
time to equip the orbital outpost for the arrival of its first
resident crew in November, the space agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven fliers began their difficult housework chores late
Tuesday. They planned to move more than 3 tons of equipment and
supplies into the station, including hardware to generate and
recycle breathing air, a toilet, exercise equipment and a laptop
computer network. Most will be installed in the station's latest
addition, the Zvezda crew module.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out by planning 11 days of activity, but we had a
shopping list of tasks that exceeded what we could do in 11 days by
quite a large margin,'' said NASA's Phil Engelhauf, the mission's
lead flight director. ``(Now) we think we will complete all the
tasks on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they had hoped for the longer mission all along, managers
could not count on Atlantis having enough electrical power and fuel
until Tuesday's decision. The shuttle will remain linked to the
station until Sunday night and return to Earth early Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The July arrival of the station's Zvezda module rendered the
orbital outpost habitable for the first time, providing living and
working space for a resident crew of three. But with a mass of
42,000 pounds, Zvezda was too heavy to be launched fully equipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew reached the station early Sunday. With
Atlantis skipper Terry Wilcutt leading the way, the shuttle crew
began boarding the station late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the astronauts and cosmonauts worked ahead of schedule,
the boarding activities stretched well into the next day as the
fliers made their way through a dozen airtight hatches.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the outpost consists of a 143-foot-long collection of
three large modules and a temporarily docked Russian Progress cargo
capsule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome aboard,'' greeted mission control as Wilcutt and his
colleagues flipped on the lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge station right now, having all that space, up to
150 feet, it's really amazing,'' said Atlantis pilot Scott Altman,
pleased to leave the much less spacious shuttle behind.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors donned surgical masks and safety glasses as they
entered each of the modules for the first time, a precaution to
protect them from dust and small debris suspended in the station's
weightless confines.
</P>
<P>
   Their final destination was Zvezda. Delayed more than two years
by Russian economic problems, Zvezda's arrival promises to greatly
accelerate the pace of the station's assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely beautiful,'' said Wilcutt as he and cosmonaut
Yuri Malenchenko became the first to inspect the Russian-crafted
module from orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Experiencing no ill effects, the visiting astronauts soon
discarded the masks and protective eye ware.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlantis is docked to the station, the shuttle's
life-support system will recycle and cool the breathing air
throughout the outpost. The shuttle crew strung long flexible
ventilation ducts and portable air circulation fans as they made
their way through the station, where temperatures were in the upper
70s and the humidity low.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, shuttle astronauts focused their efforts on the
installation of five large power storage batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The batteries are charged by the station's solar power arrays.
They discharge electricity when the station circles regions of the
Earth that are in darkness.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
