<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ALFONSECA13-COX     09-12 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ALFONSECA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alfonseca gets saves, raves as Marlins closer
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best closer in the National League is hardly a strikeout
artist and gives up nearly a .300 batting average. Only eighteen
months ago, he was riding a career to nowhere, just a set-up man
for the worst team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   He fought a weight problem. All people wanted to know was
whether having 12 fingers made it harder to pitch. This was not the
Goose Gossage way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens sometimes,'' Antonio Alfonseca said.
``Sometimes they give you the job and you just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the synopsis. On July 9, 1999, the Florida Marlins traded
closer Matt Mantei to Arizona, declared the closer job would go to
a committee and then gave Alfonseca, a 28-year-old Dominican, the
first try. That committee was never convened.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonseca went into the Braves series having converted 60 of the
66 save opportunities he's had since Mantei left. His 39 saves this
season, which are tied for the NL lead with San Diego's Trevor
Hoffman, are more than 23 of the 29 major-league teams. He leads
the league's Rolaids Relief Man standings by three points over New
York's Armando Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really started to take himself extremely seriously,''
Florida manager John Boles said. ``It was like when he was named
the closer, he was a whole different guy.''
</P>
<P>
   That process had actually begun before the 1999 season, when
Alfonseca dropped 35 pounds to his current 235. Always owning an
outstanding fastball that tops out at 97 mph, he needed a second
pitch and began to develop a wicked two-seam fastball with a hard
sinking motion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those improvements, he remains hittable: 76 hits in 62
1/3 innings with a 4.48 ERA, while striking out just 44. Alfonseca
offsets that vulnerability with ground balls off his two-seamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a strikeout pitcher,'' Boles said. ``He'll throw it
over the plate and he has tremendous action on his fastball. It can
really get in on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonseca has gotten on some people's nerves lately because of
the gyrations he goes through on the mound after a strikeout.
Sunday in Miami, he and Arizona's Greg Colbrunn, a former teammate,
exchanged obscenities and had to be restrained after Alfonseca's
demonstration for striking out Colbrunn.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Will Clark also mocked him after driving in a
go-ahead run Aug. 30. Anfonseca's defense: Benitez and Houston's
Jose Lima do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why me?'' he asked. ``Why can't I do it?''
</P>
<P>
   This might also be a residual of a changed demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, it was hard when he was a set-up guy and didn't have a
lot of pride in that role,'' Boles said. ``And when we gave him a
chance to be closer, it opened up a whole new attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins will take that. Alfonseca is a critical component to
a young pitching staff that Florida believes will make the team a
contender as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy right now with what I'm doing,'' he said. ``I'm
happy for the team, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
