<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-GIRLS-$ADV17-2NDTA     09-12 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GIRLS-$ADV17-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the shows.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Swenson has worked in the business for 30 years, most recently
overseeing ``Rugrats,'' the popular Nickelodeon program whose
toughest character is the fearsome cousin Angelica, who bosses
around a motley crew of toddlers. For ``Mike, Lu &AMP; Og,'' he
developed the tomboy character of Mike with her two Russian
creators, Mikhail Aldashin and Mikhail Shindel.
</P>
<P>
   On the show, the 11-year-old Mike _ short for Michelanne _ is a
girl from the Bronx who interacts with a strange bunch of natives
on a desert island where she has chosen to live as an exchange
student.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's smart, one of those kids who's got it all together in
her own mind,'' said Swenson, who joins Hale in crediting his
daughters as models for his animated creation. ``But she's thrown
up against people who seem like they're from another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   As the series took shape, however, Swenson realized that a
critical perspective was missing. ``Once the show was sold, I
consciously sought out female writers,'' he said. ``There really is
a difference in their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited an episode in which Mike changes her friendly
allegiances from one girl to another. ``The male writers made jokes
about their separation and hurt feelings, but the women in the room
stopped us cold,'' Swenson said. ``They told us very pointedly that
that kind of situation was really serious for a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the episodes center on the rivalry between Mike, a
tomboy, and Lu, a more traditionally girly girl. That basic
conflict also animates one of the most successful programs
introduced last year, Fox's ``Angela Anaconda.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela, a third-grader at Tapwater Springs Elementary, isn't
really a brainiac or a tomboy _ she just wants to enjoy herself, a
goal constantly foiled by the poodle-toting rich girl Nanette
Manoir. (It's also the rare cartoon that dares to tackle issues of
class, though it does so in a lighthearted way.) Much of the show
is devoted to Angela's fantasy life, in which she wreaks revenge on
Nanette.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the other characters, Angela comes from the
imagination of two women. ``That's the kind of kid I was,'' said
Joanna Ferrone, the co-creator of the show. ``I was really a
dreamer. I couldn't help but observe that although we're all told
that everybody is created equal and has an equal shot at things,
that wasn't really how life was.''
</P>
<P>
   Angela resembles ``Pepper Ann,'' which is now in its fourth
season on ABC, because the leads don't always master every
situation, as a superhero girl might. ``In both shows, sometimes
the main character does the wrong thing,'' said Sue Rose, who
created both characters. ``That's a much more valuable way to teach
a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rose hears reactions to ``Angela,'' one theme stands out.
``The most frequent feedback we get is from parents of boys,'' she
said. ``They say: `My boys watch it and they love it. I never
thought they would.' These are not just girls' shows, they're kids
shows. And whether you're a girl or a boy, you're going to exhibit
many of these same feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of its popularity undoubtedly comes from the humor that
leavens the show's message _ which is, as Rose puts it, ``You are
what you are, and it's cool to be you.'' Angela often ends up in
comic situations that Lucy Ricardo might have found familiar, as
when she enters a pogo contest despite not knowing how to pogo. The
look of the show _ a two-dimensional, cut-and-paste collage with
black-and-white faces _ enhances the feeling of retro comedy.
</P>
<P>
   According to Simensky of the Cartoon Network, even as the tide
turned for girl characters, a certain amount of political
correctness kept them from being the butt of jokes _ and laughs are
still the most prized currency in a cartoon. ``You can roll over a
male character with a steamroller,'' she said, ``but if you do that
to a girl or a minority character, people might get up in arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny or not, animated characters tend to attract an unusual
devotion from their creators, since they spring whole from the mind
and are not diluted by casting. Rose, who may have the record for
successful girl-led cartoons, even lends her own voice for the
character of Angela Anaconda.
</P>
<P>
   But she also faces a year of separation anxiety. This is the
last season of new episodes for the groundbreaking ``Pepper Ann,''
and the shows are already completed. (The 12-year-old-girl-angst
slot may be taken over by Nickelodeon's ``As Told to Ginger,''
which makes its debut in October.)
</P>
<P>
   Though animated characters never get any older, they do move
into syndication. ``I miss Pepper Ann, I really do,'' Rose said
with a maternal sigh. ``I want to know more about what's going on
with her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
