<HEADER>
A1142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-AUBURN-RUDI0913-C     09-12 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-RUDI0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson a tiger in Auburn's backfield in the backfield
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Auburn's offensive coordinator Noel Mazzone went to Kansas
looking for a quarterback. He came back with a running back who
could become a late entry into the Heisman Trophy race.
</P>
<P>
   While Mazzone was recruiting former Harrison High quarterback
Daniel Cobb, he also noticed running back Rudi Johnson, a bruising
runner from Ettrick, Va. Both players were enrolled at Butler
County (Kan.) Community College, which won the past two junior
college national championships.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Cobb, Mazzone persuaded Johnson to enroll at
Auburn in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auburn was looking at Daniel before they started recruiting
me,'' Johnson said. ``I was looking at Colorado, but I was keeping
my options open. Auburn showed up late, but from Day One they told
me I'd get an opportunity to play immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers desperately needed a running back after they ranked
last in the SEC _ and 112th out of 114 teams nationally _ in
rushing last season. Auburn averaged only 68 rushing yards per game
in 1999, and the school hasn't had a 1,000-yard rusher since
Stephen Davis gained 1,068 yards five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 5 feet 10, 228 pounds, should change that this year. He
had more rushing yards as a sophomore _ 2,224 on 306 carries _ than
Auburn had the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the JUCO championship Johnson rushed for 375 yards and scored
seven touchdowns in Butler's 49-35 victory over Dixie College of
Utah. In comparison, Auburn's leading rusher last season, fullback
Heath Evans, had 330 yards in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody coming out of junior college wants to go somewhere
where you can make an immediate impact,'' Johnson said. ``Auburn's
coaches told me I was going to play as soon as I got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been as good as advertised in the Tigers' first two
games. In victories over Wyoming and Mississippi, he rushed for 339
yards and five touchdowns. In last week's 35-27 victory over the
Rebels, Auburn had 261 rushing yards, its highest total since
gaining 292 yards in a 62-0 victory over Fresno State in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you how far the running game's come, I'm getting all
kinds of e-mails now from alumni and fans (asking), `What's
happening to our passing game?''' Auburn coach Tommy Tuberville
said. ``It's a whole different attitude from everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's emergence couldn't have come at a better time for the
Tigers. Quarterback Ben Leard has struggled in throwing downfield
and has two touchdown passes. Receiver Ronney Daniels, who had 56
catches as a freshman, has three in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Tigers scored 70 points in those two games, and
they're ranked No. 24 going into Saturday's home game against LSU.
It's the first time Auburn has been ranked since Sept. 3, 1998, a
span of 723 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudi Johnson gave us a lot of trouble,'' Mississippi coach
David Cutcliffe said, after Johnson gained 165 yards against the
Rebels. ``I have a feeling he's going to give a lot of teams
fits.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
