u s BC-FBC-TENN-QB0913-CoX     09-12 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-QB0913-CoX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suggs moves in as Tennessee's starting quarterback
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Those who know A.J. Suggs best aren't
surprised he will be the starting quarterback for Tennessee in
Saturday's big SEC game against Florida. More than anything, Aaron
Joseph Suggs is a survivor.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of five, Suggs nearly was killed in an accident on
his grandfather's farm. He fell from a moving truck and a trailer
fully loaded with hay ran over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wheel (of the trailer) ran right over my stomach,'' said
Suggs. ``If it's a few inches higher and goes over my chest, I'm
probably dead.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 14, Suggs was a baby-faced freshman at Cobb
County's McEachern High School who had the audacity to compete for
the starting quarterback's job. The job seemingly belonged to
senior Chris Caldwell, who had won 12 games the season before.
Suggs' friends told him he had no shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as soon as he walked on the field, there was just
something special about him,'' McEachern coach Jimmy Dorsey said.
``The coaches would get together after practice, and we'd sort of
look at each other and say, `Is this really happening? Is this kid
really that good?' Then one day, I told them that A.J. was our guy.
I just had a gut instinct that he was special.''
</P>
<P>
   When McEachern opened the 1995 season, freshman A.J. Suggs was
the starting quarterback. Four years later, he left with a 46-7
record as a starter, including a 14-1 mark in 1998, when he led the
Indians to the state AAAA championship game against Valdosta.
</P>
<P>
   Suggs was 17 when when he verbally committed to play at
Tennessee. When Chris Simms, the nation's No. 1 high school
quarterback, also said he would sign with the Vols, Suggs' friends
warned him that he'd never play in Knoxville. Suggs never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought it was no big deal,'' Dorsey said. ``He figured if
he went to a place like Tennessee, he'd have to beat out somebody
pretty good to play. He just said `Fine. Bring it on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Simms never showed in Knoxville; he changed his mind and signed
with Texas. As a freshman in 1999, Suggs roomed with UT senior Tee
Martin on the road and learned the ropes of being a college
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in October, Suggs suddenly began to feel severe stomach
pains. He lost 20 pounds in less than a month and began to feel an
arthritic-type pain in his throwing hand.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis was Crohn's Disease, an inflammation of the lower
intestine. Some people suggested that his college football career
might be over. Instead, Suggs finally got the proper medication,
and the symptoms subsided. He regained the weight but by then, the
decision was made to redshirt him.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Suggs again was written off as a college
quarterback. Sophomore Joey Mathews was the heir apparent to
Martin, and Tennessee had just signed two of the nation's top high
school quarterbacks Casey Clausen and John Rattay. Both would
enroll in time for spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first game of the season, against Southern Miss, it
was Suggs who came off the bench to spell a struggling Mathews.
Clausen couldn't play because of a sore shoulder, but Suggs
performed solidly and completed four of nine passes, including a
51-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   So, last week, with Mathews (knee) and Clausen (shoulder) still
dealing with aches and pains, Tennessee head coach Phillip Fulmer
announced that Suggs would get his first college career start
against the No. 6 Gators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt it was important for A.J. to know and for the guys
to be able to rally around him,'' Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   They have.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.J. is cool. Nothing bothers him,'' wide receiver Cedric
Wilson said. ``He's not going to be intimidated by his
surroundings. That's what you want from a quarterback.'' ``When I
told A.J. last week that he was going to start against Florida, he
just said, 'OK, cool,' '' said Randy Sanders, Tennessee's offensive
coordinator. ``Nothing really fazes him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little shocked that they would announce it so early,
but I was excited because it gave me a chance to work a lot with
the first team,'' Suggs said. ``I guess I've just kept plugging and
hanging around, and now I'm going to get my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey will be watching Saturday's Tennessee-Florida game from
Athens, Ohio, where his son, Andy, will be punting for Tennessee
Tech against Ohio University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he's going to do, but I do know this: He's
not going to do anything to get his team beat,'' Dorsey said about
Suggs. ``He is just a solid guy, real down to earth. You see the
same kid every single day, and that is a great personality trait.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim, Suggs' older brother who lives with him in Knoxville and
maintains a Web site (ajsuggs.com) of his football exploits,
certainly will be at Neyland Stadium on Saturday. His parents, Mike
and Judy, have a problem because Suggs' little brother, Andrew, 12,
has a junior-high game in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may try to do both,'' A.J. Suggs said. ``I wish I could
see Andrew play, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people here think that Suggs' reign as Tennessee's
starting quarterback will be short. They think that, when Clausen's
arm is well, he will be Tennessee's quarterback of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive A.J. Suggs if he doesn't worry about it. He has heard it
all before.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've ever wanted was an opportunity and now it's up to me
to take advantage of it,'' Suggs said. ``I've been through a lot, I
know. But, hey, I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
