u w BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS13-CO     09-12 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, HILL LEADERS FAR APART ON BUDGET DETAILS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican congressional leaders challenged
President Clinton on Tuesday to set aside 90 percent of next year's
budget surplus to reduce the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to take at least 90 percent of the non-Social
Security and Medicare surplus and lock it away and make sure that
we pay down the debt with it,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., told reporters as Clinton opened a meeting in the White
House Cabinet Room with congressional leaders from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters after
the meeting, though, that the commitment did not extend beyond the
2001 budget year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a one-year deal,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the GOP proposals on debt reduction contradicted
their insistence on tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really makes me wonder, from where will the money come?''
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told reporters after
the meeting. ``What tax cuts come off the table?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Daschle, ``We smell a rat.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting set the stage for a contentious partisan
battle in the weeks remaining until the clock runs out on
congressional debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for a fair middle ground,'' Lott told reporters
after the session. ``I think it was a positive meeting, and he
indicated he would get back to us on a number of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cast the meeting in far gloomier terms, saying
compromise appeared unlikely in a number of key areas.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress aiming to adjourn by Oct. 6, leaders from both
parties said hopes had dimmed for a number of Clinton's
high-priority initiatives, including a so-called patients bill of
rights or a prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come away from the meeting with a lot of confidence
that we're going to be able to find an agreement that will be
effective'' in those two areas, said House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is projected to take in roughly $2
trillion more than it spends over the coming decade, not counting
payments made into the Social Security or Medicare systems.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have passed or proposed tax cuts, heavily weighted
in favor of upper-income earners, that White House analysts contend
would eat up most of the projected surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed $360 billion worth of tax cuts _ mostly
targeted toward lower-income or middle-class workers _ over the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also called for $460 billion in spending hikes,
mostly to add a prescription drug benefit to Medicare and to extend
health care coverage to low-income workers. He has said another
$500 billion should be set aside as a hedge against unmet
expectations. His Republicans regard that, though, as a potential
bank for funding Democratic priorities, such as hiring additional
teachers and police and repairing worn-out schools.
</P>
<P>
   Time for compromise is fast running out.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal 2001 begins Oct. 1. Congress has so far sent Clinton only
two of the 13 massive appropriations bills that direct some $600
billion in so-called discretionary spending, about one-third of the
total federal budget for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is mandatory spending, including Social Security and
Medicare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The White House projects that next year's surplus not including
Social Security and Medicare _ will be $49 billion. Clinton has
proposed using $31 billion of that for debt reduction, $3 billion
for prescription drug benefits and another $1 billion to extend
health care coverage to low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders signaled that another measure Clinton has
fought for _ strengthening federal hate crimes legislation _ was
dead for this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton scheduled an event Wednesday to press for passage in
the House of a hate crimes bill already approved in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed'' over the House posture, Daschle told
reporters. ``We've got to see if we can find a way to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appeal for a dollar-an-hour hike in the minimum wage _
it's $5.15 an hour now _ also seemed a long shot, though neither
party shut the door on further talks.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point was Republican insistence that any such
increase be accompanied by a tax cut for small businesses amounting
to $76 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do that,'' said Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made clear at the outset of the White House meeting,
though, that he remained hopeful for ``a minimum wage agreement
that will have some small business tax relief in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton told reporters his aim was a budget
compromise resting ``on the basis of good policy, not politics or
partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
