<SLUG> BC-RAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    After 73 days, rain falls in North Texas
 &HT;    Despite thunderstorms, dry conditions continue
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JIM HENDERSON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Thunderstorms swirled across North Texas on Tuesday,
dumping 2 to 4 inches of rain on some counties and setting off
warnings of large hail and flash floods, but officially the drought
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Through one of those atmospheric quirks for which the region is
legendary, no precipitation touched Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, where the National Weather Service gauges are located.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officially, the dry streak stretches to 74 days,'' said Gary
Woodall, a meteorologist in Fort Worth, who spoke as a heavy rain
pounded downtown Dallas, 16 miles from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the heaviest rains fell west and northwest of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Copeland at the Wise County office of the Texas
Agricultural Extension Service in Decatur, said that area's dry
spell was broken by nearly three hours of rainfall that deposited
as much as 2 inches in some locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so wonderful,'' she said. ``It was great. People were
running outside and celebrating.''
</P>
<P>
   As rains were falling to the west, dark clouds, the likes of
which had not been seen here since June 30, gathered over Dallas.
At 12:43 p.m., lightning split the sky and a loud thunderclap shook
the windows of St. Pete's Dancing Marlin cafe in Deep Ellum.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd broke out in cheers and applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that thunder?'' a woman asked her luncheon companion.
``I'd forgotten what it sounds like.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later the rains began and continued for about 20
minutes _ just enough to slake the thirst of the city's lawns and
slicken the oil-stained streets that have not been bathed for 2-1/2
months.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Dallas police warned motorists that when the rains
finally came, hazardous driving conditions would be the first
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon Tuesday, that prediction had come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we're pretty busy right now,'' said Sgt.
Jerry Sanchez of the police department's traffic division.
</P>
<P>
   While city and suburban dwellers have suffered through a summer
of brittle lawns and soaring water bills, the surrounding farms
have taken the biggest hit from the longest dry spell in North
Texas history (the previous streak was 58 days in 1934 and 1950).
</P>
<P>
   Gary Clayton, the Wise County extension agent, said that while
some areas west of Dallas/Fort Worth received generous rainfall
Tuesday, the storms were spotty and skimpy for some farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not enough to really do any good,'' he said. ``It cools
us off and makes us feel good, but as far as agriculture production
goes, it was just enough to make you mad. We've still got a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, drought conditions in Texas have cost farmers and
ranchers more than $5 billion in lost production.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's storms brought cooling relief, but farmers will have
to wait for full deliverance.
</P>
<P>
   Skies cleared late in the afternoon and, according to forecasts,
will remain clear at least through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
