u s BC-OLY-SOCCER13-COX     09-12 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCCER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. men to kick off coverage
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canberra, Australia _ Members of the men's soccer team will be
the first U.S. athletes Americans can see compete in the 2000
Olympic Games today.
</P>
<P>
   But when the U.S. men headed Down Under, they had not been sure
where they would be playing their first match.
</P>
<P>
   An embarrassed Sydney organizing committee had to order the new
playing surface at Bruce Stadium torn up last week because it did
not meet FIFA specifications after failing to take hold.
Unseasonably cold winter weather in the Australian capital city was
to blame.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight's match between the United States and the Czech
Republic, and the women's opener between Australia and Germany
before it, will go as scheduled after FIFA approved the second
resodding job Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven matches will be played, including the United States'
second Saturday against Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to play this thing on a parking lot, then we'll
play it on a parking lot,'' U.S. coach Clive Charles said before
leaving for Australia. ``I've just learned not to worry about
controlling things I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a wise approach for his Olympic
preparations. Unlike the women's team, which has played 33 times
this year, Charles' men have been together only twice, the last
time on Sept. 4 in a 2-0 victory over the San Diego Flash of the
A-League. Landon Donovan, the 19-year-old scoring phenom, had both
goals after coming from Bayer Leverkusen, his German Bundesliga
club.
</P>
<P>
   With 14 players on the 18-man roster busy during the peak of the
Major League Soccer season this summer, Charles conducted
mini-camps when possible and traveled to MLS games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every camp I've had, we've seen a majority of the people
we're taking to Australia,'' Charles said. ``We have a pretty good
idea what they can do. They're professionals. They haven't
forgotten how to play soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles coaches the men's and women's teams at the University of
Portland, where he was responsible for grooming U.S. national team
fixtures Kasey Keller for the men and Tiffeny Milbrett and Shannon
MacMillan.
</P>
<P>
   A week before leaving for the Olympics, he was in the Midwest,
where his Portland men upset preseason No. 1 Indiana on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The men's Olympic objective is to nurture a professional team _
only Charles' current star forward at Portland, Conor Casey, is an
amateur _ as the next generation of U.S. national team members. The
other objective is to accomplish something no American men's
Olympic team has done: advance out of group play.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan; Atlanta's Josh Wolff, who plays for the Chicago Fire;
Ajax Amsterdam midfielder John O'Brien; and D.C. United flankman
Ben Olsen are among those young talents viewing the Olympics as
something of a finishing school. But Charles has taken advantage of
the limit of three over-23 players to give his defensive-oriented
unit some World Cup experience.
</P>
<P>
   Keller's national-team backup, Brad Friedel, was added late
after starting Olympic keeper Adin Brown suffered a leg injury. So
were defenders Jeff Agoos, at 32 one of the oldest players in the
tournament, and Frankie Hejduk, recently out of favor with the
senior team.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Brazil have been tipped as the gold-medal favorites,
with defending Olympic champion Nigeria and Spain also contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Even the teams the U.S. will face have players with world-class
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite happy with the way this team has formed,'' Charles
said. ``We may be sending our strongest (Olympic) team ever this
time, but we're still playing against some pretty big
professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
