<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IRELAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MULLING TRIP TO IRELAND AFTER ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is eyeing a post-election visit
to Ireland, taking a ``victory lap'' trip to bask in the new, if
uneasy peace in Belfast, someone familiar with the negotiaions told
the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government is already preparing for a December visit
by Clinton, the source close to the Irish Embassy who asked not to
be identified said, and the two governments are still working out
the dates. It would be Clinton's third visit to Ireland as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern invited Clinton to visit when
the two men were in New York last week for the United Nations
Millennium Summit, and the US president very much wants to go, a
senior White House official said. But the White House, concerned
about what developments could occur between now and December, is
not likely to announce a travel date for at least a month, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will meet Wednesday with the two men who head Northern
Ireland's new, power-sharing government, Protestant First Minister
David Trimble and Roman Catholic Deputy First Minister Seamus
Mallon. The two are expected to thank Clinton for his work toward
peace in Ireland and reiterate the invitation to visit.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will mark Trimble's and Mallon's first joint visit
to the White House since Northern Ireland gained home rule last
November.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential trip would be complicated, since it would
demand diplomatically that Clinton visit both Ireland and Northern
Ireland, perhaps with a side trip to see Clinton friend Tony Blair,
the British prime minister. That's a lot to arrange, even for a
globe-trotter like the president, in the last days of the Clinton
presidency, the White House official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-NYT     09-12 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT FAULTS FEDERAL WEB SITES ON PRIVACY
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most federal Web sites do not meet the commercial
standards for Internet privacy set by the Federal Trade Commission,
including the commission's own site, a new government report has
found.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers, led by Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House
majority leader, and Rep. Billy Tauzin, the Louisiana Republican
who is the chairman of the House Commerce Subcommittee on Consumer
Protection, requested that the General Accounting Office assess the
privacy standards of government Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The study released on Tuesday by the accounting office, the
investigative agency of Congress, found that virtually all of the
federal sites, including those of the Internal Revenue Service,
Postal Service and every cabinet-level agency, failed to meet the
four major privacy standards set by the government. Only 3 percent
of the sites met the four standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration rejected the study's findings. Sally
Katzen, the deputy director for management at the White House
Office of Management and Budget, called the report ``seriously
misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies, Katzen wrote in a letter to investigators
dated Sept. 7, had been directed to follow the Privacy Act of 1974
and internal rules on Web site policies rather than the
commission's standards.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a ``longstanding practice,'' Katzen wrote in a
letter that was released with the report, ``to tailor privacy laws
and policies to the needs of the particular sector.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office measured the government Web sites
against each of the four federal standards for privacy on the
Internet: that a site disclose its information practices before
personal information is collected from consumers; that sites allow
consumers to decide if their personal information may be used for
secondary purposes, like having their names placed on marketing
lists; that consumers have access to personal information, with the
option to change the data if it is incorrect or incomplete, and
that the site protects against unauthorized access to personal
information.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said that government agencies like the Internal Revenue
Service and the Department of Health and Human Services, which
``has access to many of your personal medical records,'' should be
held to clear and strict standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are required to give this information to the government _
you have no choice,'' Armey said. ``You don't have to use a
commercial Web site if you feel it has a bad privacy policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted in July and August, found that 85 percent
of federal sites posted a privacy notice of some kind and tha 69
percent of the sites provided enough information about how personal
data is used to meet the federal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But in the other categories, the report found, the government
Web sites lacked rigid privacy and security standards. Forty-five
percent of the sites met the commission's criteria for providing
consumers with the option to block outside use of their personal
information; 24 percent provided ample protection against
unauthorized access; and 17 percent permitted consumers to view and
change data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
