<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-MORGAN-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL LIKELY TO ELIMINATE FEW JOBS AND FREE UP TIGHT OFFICE SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHASE-MORGAN, CHASE-BANKS-HISTORY, CHASE-MORGAN-HISTORY) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A union between Chase Manhattan and J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
would likely mean the elimination of only a few jobs and free
much-needed real estate space, industry observers contend.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ending the independence of J.P. Morgan, a storied New
York firm that has built a strong reputation as an investment bank.
It would also likely mean the elimination of the jobs of some
employees in similar positions at both companies.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to government officials in New York who had
limited knowledge of the plans, the impact would be minimal, and
the acquisition was likely to have a positive impact on New York's
already tight real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the consolidation will be at the higher levels, and
that banking talent will be redeployed, because those people are
quite resilient and skilled,'' said Mitchell Moss, a business
professor at New York University, echoing the sentiments of
government officials. ``And it will be very good for the New York
real estate market, because it will open up space in a very tight
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said that they were publicly taking a
wait-and-see approach to the mergers of the two New York companies.
But, privately, they said it would help strengthen the financial
services industry in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Moss said that the two companies have ``complimentary
strengths'' that will help a new company at a time when ``the
financial services industry is increasingly one that is becoming
more integrated'' and the lines between ``investment banks, retail
banks and other banks'' were slowly being eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Moss added that, in the end, New York will ``benefit from being
home of the merged banks.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall impacts of any acquisition on the economy, job
market and the real estate industry are still unclear, but local
leaders seem to be taking a positive attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Weisbrod, the president of the Downtown Alliance of New
York, a group that represents businesses in the Wall Street area,
said that the strength of a combined bank would help Manhattan
solidify its international dominance in the financial services
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidation in today's economic climate does not have as
much of an impact as it would have several years ago,'' Weisbrod
said. ``In a way, anything that is going to strengthen New York's
role as the financial capital of the world is going to be
encouraged, especially in this era of globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisbrod said that the areas of Manhattan where both companies
have their offices are in dire need of available commercial real
estate and that any job loses would be offset quickly in this
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1980s, the consolidation of commercial banking
did have an impact on occupancy rates on commercial real estate
space and did contribute to the depression on Wall Street,'' he
said. ``But Lower Manhattan's economy is going extremely well,
people can find jobs, the growth of Silicon Alley has really
diversified things.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, the NYU business professor, said that while some may worry
about losing their jobs, few will be in a position where they have
to truly worry about finding employment. ``The important thing is
that no matter what happens in any merger, New York is going to be
the home of one of the largest banks in the world,'' Moss said.
``There will be a stronger, better bank in New York, as opposed to
having two weaker ones.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
