<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-(500&AMP;TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN, BY GORE'S SIDE, LIGHTENS THE CAMPAIGN LOAD 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Before Vice President Al Gore set foot on the stage
Tuesday afternoon before a raucous crowd of 2,000 supporters at
Cincinnati Technical and Community College, there came The
Testimonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been a friend of mine for almost 15 years, and
he's a man of family and faith,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman told the
already enthusiastic mass. ``Al Gore is a man of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   This scene has quickly become a chestnut for the Democrats'
national ticket, repeated with slight variations from city to city
and likely to be heard again Wednesday when the two men travel to
Boston. More than any other presidential and vice-presidential
nominee in recent memory _ with the possible exception of Gore and
President Clinton in 1992 _ Gore and Lieberman have made a habit of
appearing in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   The practice defies the conventional wisdom that running mates
should split up to cover as many bases as possible. But campaign
officials say it will continue through November, reflecting the
benefits they believe Lieberman has brought to the ticket, benefits
that Gore aides say have exceeded their hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats see tactical advantages in joint campaigning, but
the most compelling factor may be the one Gore aides are least
comfortable addressing openly: It is clear, they agree, that
Lieberman loosens up the famously stiff vice president, making him
a more effective candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good friends, and campaigning is a stressful
experience that's easier when it's shared with someone,'' said Tad
Devine, a senior strategist for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brazile, Gore's campaign manager, said, ``They just enjoy
each other. You may even see some foursomes out there, with the
spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   His aides say that Gore may not be adept at whipping up a crowd,
but that he performs best before groups that are already
enthusiastic. Lieberman, they say, effectively gets audiences ready
for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's easy manner and constant joking leaven Gore's
tendency toward seriousness, and the vice president, like others on
the campaign, has not escaped his teasing. At a recent forum in
Portland, Ore., Gore, noting his wife's training as a psychologist,
said that in recent years, ``Her psychology practice is almost
entirely devoted to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For which she is not adequately reimbursed, I might add,''
Lieberman shot back.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the candidates rolled merrily through Ohio aboard a
pair of yellow school buses to highlight their plans for improving
education in this critical swing state. The day was largely
dedicated to stagecraft, as the candidates visited schools and took
questions from students, basked in the adulation of cheerleaders
and band members, and spoke at a rally here. They were followed by
the campaign's own television crew, filming them together for
possible use in future television ads.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Democratic convention last month, Lieberman has made
campaign appearances on 19 days. On 12 of those days, including the
four-day boat tour he and Gore took down the Mississippi River, he
has made at least one appearance with the vice president, and often
two or three per day. By contrast, in the same period, Dick Cheney,
the Republican vice presidential nominee, has campaigned with Gov.
George W. Bush on four days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``A lot of people still have this feeling that Gore isn't quite
sincere, that he's too serious,'' said Theodore J. Lowi, a
professor of political science at Cornell University. ``Lieberman
brings that Hubert Humphrey-like joy to the experience of
campaigning, and he sounds like he really believes what he's
saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's a living reminder to people that Gore can make a very
bold, very well-received move,'' Lowi said. ``That is, picking
Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's main role in their joint appearances has been to
introduce the vice president with boasts about his accomplishments.
And he is performing an important service for a a presidential
candidate whose own bragging _ like his claim to having a hand in
creating the Internet _ has sometimes been clumsy and, however
accurate, widely mocked. Lieberman reminds audiences that Gore
volunteered for service in Vietnam, that he supported an overhaul
of welfare, that he voted for United States entry into the Persian
Gulf war, and that he helped preside over a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody who is fair would disagree with this
comment,'' Lieberman said on Tuesday, ``that Al Gore has been the
most effective and successful vice president in the history of the
United States of America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
