<SLUG> BC-SELMA-VOTE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Selma elects first black mayor
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. _ In the fertile crescent of the civil rights
movement, where a white mayor named Joe T. Smitherman has held
power for 36 years despite a former life as a segregationist, the
slogan echoed through the summer: Joe Gotta Go!
</P>
<P>
   Well, Joe's gone.
</P>
<P>
   Forced into his first runoff in 10 mayoral elections, the
70-year-old Smitherman lost Tuesday night to computer consultant
James Perkins, who becomes Selma's first black mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Just 26 minutes after the polls closed, word spread on radio and
quickly to the streets that Perkins _ twice before a loser to
Smitherman _ had won 57 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Horns blared from an impromptu parade of cars up and down the
main street, just blocks from the Edmund Pettus Bridge, a symbol of
the fight for black voting rights from the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the world. We've been blessed,'' said Brenda Carter,
a 50-year-old black woman who baby-sits for white families in town.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins' winning percentage nearly matches the black percentage
of the population of the city, which had 300 black voters to 10,000
white ones when Smitherman first won election in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In conceding the election at his headquarters, where workers had
just started dining on fried chicken, fluffy biscuits and potato
salad yellow from egg yolks, Smitherman praised Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the new mayor, the mayor-elect, I offer my
congratulations,'' Smitherman said. ``I love Selma. I'm sure he
loves it. And anything I can do to help him, he can ask for it. I
won't interfere.'' Perkins supporters canvassed the polls
throughout the day Tuesday. The 47-year-old Selma native worked
hard to ensure the vote was strong enough to neutralize the
controversial absentee ballots that Smitherman has used to win past
elections.
</P>
<P>
   At the polls, some locations reported nearly an 80 percent
turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
