<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-WOODS-KNIGHT0913-COX     09-12 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODS-KNIGHT0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You can bet Knight will surface again, because he wins
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - So, do you want Bobby Knight coaching at
your school?
</P>
<P>
   During an hourlong ESPN interview Tuesday night, Knight said he
wants to coach again. Even said he would start tomorrow if the
situation were right. So this morning, this is the question: Would
you hire him?
</P>
<P>
   Before you answer, know this: Someone will.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, don't be surprised if schools end up fighting over him,
tossing out reasons why their situation would indeed be right.
Aerodynamic chairs! Shatterproof vases! Instant expulsion for any
student who doesn't put the ``Mister'' before ``Knight''!
</P>
<P>
   Because for all the flaws, Knight can do two things that every
athletic director craves. Win games. Fill seats.
</P>
<P>
   OK, he also has been known to toss the latter. But someone is
going to overlook that and every other incident during 29 years at
Indiana University. Someone is going to hire him. And until they
do, every other athletic director with an opening is going to face
The Bobby Question.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine he wasn't fired Sunday. Imagine IU president Myles Brand
went ahead and did it back in May a few weeks before Leonard
Hamilton told the University of Miami he was headed to the NBA, a
couple months before UM hired Tulane's Perry Clark.
</P>
<P>
   You're UM athletic director Paul Dee. You're looking for someone
who can make sure your rising basketball program doesn't suddenly
disappear from the national spotlight. Someone who can win. Someone
who can sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Do you call Knight?
</P>
<P>
   Or suppose you're Tom Cargill, athletic director at Florida
Atlantic University. Your basketball team isn't just coming off a
2-28 season. It lost every non-conference game by at least 18
points. It finished at the bottom of the RPI ratings for Division I
schools.
</P>
<P>
   You've already gone the big-name route in football, hiring
Howard Schnellenberger.
</P>
<P>
   Would you be interested in Knight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already been asked that,'' Cargill said Tuesday, adding
with a chuckle. ``Several people have called me to talk about him.
The wheels are turning.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't elaborate on who these people are. But he makes it
clear that it's a moot point, that he and FAU are quite happy with
second-year coach Sidney Green.
</P>
<P>
   But if he were in the market for a coach ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule Bobby Knight out,'' he said. ``He's a proven
winner. He graduates athletes. And he would most definitely bring
attention to any program. ... That attention is important as long
as it's positive.''
</P>
<P>
   With Knight, it won't always be.
</P>
<P>
   The past 29 years proved that. The past four months emphasized
it and, in the process, vividly illustrated why you shouldn't want
Knight at your school.
</P>
<P>
   It would be one thing if you got a sense that at age 59, he
might change. Or, perhaps more important, a sense that he thinks he
should change. Maybe then you could cling to all that is good about
Knight and, yes, there is plenty of that.
</P>
<P>
   But from the moment in May when he gave a written apology that
included one wonderfully telling sentence ``I've always been too
confrontational, especially when I know I'm right'' it has been
clear Knight believes that if you have a problem with anything he
has done, well, then that's your problem.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in a world of twisted logic a place where a man who has
berated an elderly secretary, choked players and used soiled toilet
paper as a coaching tool, can hold a press conference and, in all
seriousness, point to a 19-year-old not calling him ``Mister''
Knight or ``Coach'' Knight as an example of the decline of civility
in today's society.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. Bobby Knight on manners. What's next, Jerry
Springer lamenting all this violence in wrestling?
</P>
<P>
   That absurd press conference should have been his odd, but
fitting farewell. But it won't be. Isiah Thomas already has said he
would offer his former coach a chance to be an assistant with the
Indiana Pacers. Not that Knight would ever go for that scenario.
He's not the boss? He's surrounded by a dozen millionaire NBA
players, their cell phones, agents and entourages?
</P>
<P>
   No, he will wait for a college to offer ``the right situation.''
And you can bet one will.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of zero-tolerance? Check out our hero-tolerance policy!
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
