<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1175 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS &LR;      09-12 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Reno says unfair society to blame for ethnic disparity in
federal death cases
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By STEVE LASH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying ``our society is not fair,'' Attorney
General Janet Reno on Tuesday blamed poverty and drugs for an
overwhelming ethnic disparity in the percentage of federal
defendants on trial for crimes punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   Reno added that the criminal justice system is ill-equipped to
fight these societal ills and called for the public's help. The
attorney general downplayed accusations that racially biased
prosecutors are to blame for racial inequities in death-penalty
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime is often the product of social ills and harsh
conditions, such as poverty, drug abuse and lack of opportunity
that disproportionately affect minorities,'' Reno said. ``The
federal criminal justice system is not designed to remedy these
systemic problems by itself. We must ensure, however, that all
defendants who come into our system are treated in a fair and just
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's comments followed the release Tuesday of a Justice
Department report that showed minorities accounted for 80.4 percent
of the 682 federal criminal defendants accused of committing a
capital crime between 1995 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The study, however, also showed that federal prosecutors were
ultimately more likely to seek the death penalty against a
defendant who is white than one of another race.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Justice Department sought the death penalty in
38.3 percent of the cases involving a white defendant but in only
24.7 percent of the cases involving a black defendant and 20
percent of the cases involving a Hispanic defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she was ``sorely troubled'' but not surprised by the
racial disparity among criminal defendants on trial in potential
death-penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minorities are overrepresented in the federal death penalty
system as both victims and defendants, relative to the general
population,'' she said. ``Sadly, the same is true of the entire
criminal justice system, both state and federal. This should be of
concern to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen people are on federal death row, including 13 blacks,
four whites, one Hispanic and one from an unspecified ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted South Texas killer Juan Raul Garza, whose execution is
scheduled for Dec. 12, would be the first federal prisoner put to
death since 1963 and the first since Congress reinstated the death
penalty in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, a former leader of a drug ring who killed three
associates to further his illegal business, is urging President
Clinton to grant him clemency that would reduce his sentence to
life in prison without a chance for parole. &UR;  &LR; Garza's attorney, Greg
Wiercioch of Houston, has said he might press Clinton to approve
clemency based on the racial disparity argument. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Clinton, who has yet to act on Garza's clemency plea, declined
to comment specifically on the Justice Department report but said a
defendant's race should be irrelevant when prosecutors seek the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone like me, who supports capital punishment and has
actually presided over executions, I think, has an extra strong
responsibility to make sure there's nothing wrong with the
process,'' Clinton said, recalling his tenure as Arkansas governor.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 400-page study racially classifies criminal
defendants as white, black, Hispanic or ``other,'' which is defined
as Asian, Pacific Islander, Native American, Aleut, Indian or
unknown. The report, a statistical compilation, makes no
recommendations on ending the disparity.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, in discussing the data, said further studies must be
performed to examine more specific questions addressing racial
inequities in criminal justice. These questions must address not
only inequities at trial but at all stages of the criminal justice
system from the time a police officer decides to stop a suspect,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department began its study shortly after Illinois
Gov. George Ryan issued a moratorium on capital punishment in his
state in January. Ryan put a temporary end to executions after
discovering that 13 death-row inmates had been exonerated in his
state since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, however, said no need exists for a similar federal
moratorium because the system, though imperfect, has procedural
``safeguards'' to ensure innocent people are not executed.
</P>
<P>
   These federal protections include the requirement that criminal
defendants on trial for their lives be represented by an attorney
experienced in capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also allows death-row inmates, like
Garza, to seek presidential clemency, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Justice Department's internal guidelines also
reduce the possibility that a defendant's race plays any role in
whether the death penalty is sought, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under agency rules, U.S. attorneys must notify the department's
death-penalty review committee whenever a defendant faces trial for
a capital crime. The committee, which is not told the defendant's
race, then reviews the case and makes its recommendation to the
attorney general, who ultimately decides.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general is not apprised by subordinates of the race
of the defendant. However, Reno conceded that she can readily
determine the defendant's race in some cases by his or her name.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., called these protections
insufficient and urged Clinton to call for a halt to executions
pending an independent evaluation of the federal criminal justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the right thing to do given the troubling racial ...
disparities in the administration of the federal death penalty,''
Feingold said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
