<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-NYT &LR;      09-12 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED HOUSE BILL RENEWS   PUSH FOR PATIENT'S RIGHTS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Mich., Wash., Mo., Mont., Ga., Iowa)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional supporters of a patient's bill of
rights said Tuesday that they had revised the legislation passed by
the House last year, in a bid to win the votes of a few more Senate
Republicans needed to enact the measure this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The House and the Senate have passed different versions of the
bill to define patients' rights, but efforts to negotiate a
compromise have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation said they had given up on trying
to reach an agreement with Senate Republican leaders. Instead, they
are trying to revise the House-passed legislation to address the
concerns of individual Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Four Republican senators have previously voted with Democrats on
patients' rights. The 46 Senate Democrats hope they can pick up the
votes of a few more Republicans in view of the fact that Vice
President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee, and
Democratic candidates for Congress hammer the issue almost every
day.
</P>
<P>
   The new effort is being led by three House champions of
patients' rights _ Charlie Norwood, R-Ga.; John D. Dingell,
D-Mich., and Greg Ganske, R-Iowa _ and by a leading Senate critic
of managed care, Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise is supported by the American Medical Association,
whose members complain that their professional judgments are often
overridden by health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The four lawmakers and the doctors' association are trying to
woo Republican senators running for re-election, including Sens.
Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, Spencer Abraham of Michigan, Slade
Gorton of Washington, John Ashcroft of Missouri, and Conrad Burns
of Montana. Democrats reckon that they have picked up a vote with
the arrival of a Democrat, Zell Miller, to replace Sen. Paul
Coverdell of Georgia, a Republican who died in July.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill would set standards for all private health
insurance, protecting at least 160 million Americans, or more than
three times as many as would be covered by the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise measure tries to address the concerns of Senate
Republicans who want to protect states' rights _ notably, the right
of states to regulate health insurance. If a state could show that
its insurance laws were ``at least substantially equivalent'' to
the new federal standards, the state law would remain in effect,
and state officials could enforce the patient protections of state
law.
</P>
<P>
   On another issue, the compromise bill would allow some lawsuits
to be filed against health plans in state court, but would require
others to be filed in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   This would codify the emerging consensus of many judges, who
have suggested in decisions over the past five years that injured
patients can sue HMOs in state court in disputes over the quality
of medical care _ traditional malpractice cases.
</P>
<P>
   Under the compromise bill, a patient could sue in state court if
a health plan denied a claim for benefits on the ground that a
service was not medically necessary or that a treatment was
experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Patients would have to sue in federal court if they wanted to
challenge an administrative decision to deny benefits _ a decision
involving no question of medical judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the compromise bill seeks to allay Republican concerns
that employers might be saddled with immense new costs if patients
could sue them for damages arising from care provided through an
employer-sponsored health plan.
</P>
<P>
   The revised legislation says employers may not be held liable
unless they directly participated in a decision to deny benefits,
as a result of which a patient was injured or killed.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, defendants could not be required to pay punitive
damages unless they showed ``willful or wanton disregard for the
rights or safety'' of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. D. Ted Lewers, chairman of the American Medical Association,
said: ``The AMA strongly supports the revised version of the
bipartisan patient's bill of rights. It covers all Americans and
holds health plans accountable for actions that harm patients.''
</P>
<P>
   John E. Stone, a spokesman for Norwood, said the congressman had
presented the proposed compromise to the speaker, J. Dennis
Hastert, to the White House and to ``a number of Republicans'' in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to hold together the coalition we have in favor of the
Norwood-Dingell bill, while doing what we can to bring in some
reluctant Senate supporters,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill includes several tax incentives to make
health insurance more available and affordable. To win Republican
votes, Democrats said they would consider allowing an expansion of
a pilot program that lets people set aside money for medical
expenses in tax-sheltered accounts known as medical savings
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, the Texas Republican who is chairman of the
Ways and Means Committee, said the encouragement of such accounts
was one of his top legislative priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a Republican version of the patient's bill of
rights in July 1999, and the House passed the Norwood-Dingell bill,
with bipartisan support, in October 1999. Negotiators from the two
chambers met for the first time on March 2 and later reached
agreement on a few issues.
</P>
<P>
   In drafting the new compromise bill, lawmakers borrowed language
developed in the conference committee, headed by Sen. Don Nickles
of Oklahoma, the assistant Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   They accepted language suggested by Nickles to establish an
administrative appeals process for patients denied benefits by
HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise also adopts legislative language similar to that
proposed by Republicans to ensure that patients have timely access
to medical specialists and that doctors can prescribe ``medically
necessary'' drugs, regardless of restrictions imposed by HMOs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
