<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1184 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-ERVIN-LADN     09-12 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ERVIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERVIN STEPS INTO BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ A few days after Anthony Ervin stunned the
U.S. swimming community, he walked to a 25-yard community pool
across the street from his family's Valencia, Calif., home and swam
lap after uninterrupted lap.
</P>
<P>
   If the lifeguard on duty knew he was eyeballing the
second-swiftest swimmer in U.S. history, he hid his awe well.
Indeed, none of the pool's patrons gave the slightest indication
they were aware the Kobe Bryant of freestyle sprinting _ ie: The
Future _ was in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   For that, Ervin was enormously grateful. He found it a relief to
be regarded as just another lanky teen-ager trying to escape the
Santa Clarita Valley heat.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight has been beating down on Ervin, 19, since he
earned an Olympic berth at the U.S. Trials in Indianapolis in
August. The pride of Hart High will have his first chance to make
America proud Saturday when he swims a leg of the 400-meter
freestyle relay on the opening session of the swimming competition
at the International Aquatic Centre.
</P>
<P>
   The relay race is loaded with enough symbolism to sink an
oversized island. The principal players figure to be the U.S.,
which has never lost the sprint freestyle relay in the Olympics,
and the Australians, who are desperate to turn the swimming
competition into a backyard pool party.
</P>
<P>
   Aussies ruled the pool the last time the Olympics was held in
their swimming-crazed country, in 1956. They won 14 medals in
Melbourne, eight of them gold, to the United States' two golds,
four silvers and five bronzes. In 1960 the tide started to turn in
favor of the U.S. and the Aussies have been chasing the Americans
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The host country has been gearing its top swimmers for this week
since the U.S. won 24 Olympic medals to Australia's 12 in Atlanta
in 1996. Not so Ervin, who never dreamed until this spring that he
might be drafted this summer to fight for U.S. swimming supremacy
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the summer of 1999 selling men's clothing at a local
department store instead of honing his swimming skills. So when
Ervin made the U.S. team in the relay and then clocked the
third-fastest time in history in the 50-meter freestyle to earn an
individual Olympic berth, he caught more than the Australians off
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin's father is three-quarters African American, which made
Ervin the first U.S. Olympic swimmer of African-American heritage
and reduced him to a flash point in the smoldering brushfire that
is race in this country. In a matter of seconds, he found himself
U.S. Swimming's answer to Australia's star runner Cathy Freeman,
the standard bearer for her country's Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   Squirming in his seat during a recent media session, Ervin
acknowledged he is ``sort of baffled'' by the intense interest in
his ancestry. ``My dream since I was a little kid was to make the
Olympic team,'' Ervin said. ``In my own mind, I never felt like
there was anything stopping me.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no stopping Ervin since he enrolled at Cal as a
freshman last fall and resumed training after taking most of the
summer off to work in the men's casual-clothing department at
Robinsons-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my last summer to be with my friends,'' said Ervin, a
two-time CIF champion in 1999. ``I didn't want to put that much
time into swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time Ervin had balked at the commitment
swimming demands of its suitors. When he was in junior high, he
told his parents Jack and Sherry he wanted to quit the sport and
take up archery. His parents discouraged the idea and so Ervin
stuck it out.
</P>
<P>
   When Ervin got to high school and came under the influence of
Hart coach Steve Neale, his swimming career took off like an arrow
shot from a bow. It's no wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   The way he glides through the water, one's first inclination is
to check him for gills. Ervin is as comfortable in the water as a
dolphin (as playful, too).
</P>
<P>
   He is comfortable in the classroom, too, which afforded him his
pick of colleges. Ervin chose Berkeley after bonding with the
Bears' sprint coach, Mike Bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Cal was where Matt Biondi developed into the swimmer who set the
world standard of excellence in the sprints in the 1980s. It is a
perennial powerhouse, attracting top swimmers from around the
world. In Ervin's tightknit circle, there was some concern how he
would fit in at such a melting pot of a place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I thought it would be the best thing for him to go
out and experience that kind of competition,'' Neale said. ``You
can get stale being the big fish in a small fishbowl. But another
part of me worried that the intensity of a program like Cal's would
be too much for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin went in with his eyes wide open. ``I knew it'd be
different being in college, that my best times before weren't going
to cut it,'' he said. ``I wouldn't say it was intimidating. It was
just a lot more intense than high school swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Ervin long to adjust. At the spring NCAA
Championships, he won the 50 and 100 freestyles in a 25-meter pool.
He set a world record for the short-course 50 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Biondi had gotten out of the blocks that quickly in
college, begging the question: Can Ervin afford to stick around to
finish what he has started?
</P>
<P>
   Ervin trained this summer in Phoenix alongside America's top
sprinter, Gary Hall Jr., who dropped out of college so he could
accept money for racing. Hall, 25, has been trying to drum up
interest in a series of cash match races that would pit him against
another sprinter. Ervin, his closest competitor stateside in the
one-lap race, looms as the most logical opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is Ervin cannot chase Hall for money and more
NCAA titles, too. His parents are adamant about him getting his
college degree and Ervin doesn't disagree with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary and I've talked about it a little bit,'' Ervin said.
``It's just kind of in the brainstorming phase. Until it's
finalized, I'm not going to take it seriously, especially not until
I'm done with school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have to be vast, vast sums of money for me to give
up my college education. Getting my degree is foremost in my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not entirely true. For the next two weeks, getting an
Olympic medal is uppermost in Ervin's thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a medal would be a huge accomplishment,'' he said.
``Winning a gold medal would be a climax.''
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful, way-out truth? It could be just the beginning. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column will appear every day during the Olympics.
She can be reached at dnlasportsaol.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
