OLY-SYDNEY-SCENE-2-- Simone Polly, far left, a tour guide and climb
leader shows Sydney landmarks to Tom Moody and a group of tourists
while scaling the Sydney Harbor Bridge, Tuesday. The bridge along
with the Sydney Opera House are the two most identifiable images in
Sydney. The 2000 Summer Olympics begin September 15th. About
111,000 visitors from abroad will be in town for the Games. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times) Floater Photo2
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 12, 2000 --
OLY-SYDNEY-SCENE-1 --A view of the Sydney Opera House shot from the
Sydney Harbor Bridge, Tuesday. The 2000 Summer Olympics begin
September 15th. About 111,000 visitors from abroad will be in town
for the Games. That figure includes 14,000 athletes and officials,
80,000 spectators and 17,000 media. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times) Floater Photo
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WOODSIDE, Calif. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- FARROS-BOSS --
Royal Farros, chairman and chief executive officer of I-Print, an
online printing service, says having pets has had a profound impact
on how he manages. Farros with his dobermans, Foxy and Mandy at his
home in Woodside last week. (Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MIAMISBURG, Ohio -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- GORE-4 -- Vice
President Gore greets students at the Anna Wantz Middle School,
Tuesday. Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joe Lieberman, visited
schools in the region Tuesday to highlight their education
proposals. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. -- Sept. 12, 2000 --
NY-PRIMARY-CLINTON-3 -- President Clinton waits for his wife
Hillary Rodham Clinton, running for the U.S. Senate, to leave the
voting booth so he could cast his ballot at the polling station in
their new home town of Chappaqua, Tuesday. Putting their political
role reversal in high relief, Clinton cast his first vote as a New
Yorker Tuesday, pronouncing it ``a thrill'' to vote for his wife.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- GRODIN-PROFILE -- Charles
Grodin was once notorious as the talk show guest who zinged the
host; the guy with the ironic sidelong look who would say anything.
But as the man whose own cable talk show got canceled and received
some of the most vicious reviews in television, he's got a thin
skin. Grodin during an interview last week. (Suzanne DeChillo/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MIDDLETOWN, Ohio -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- GORE-3 -- Gore
accepts some onion rings in the cafeteria at Middletown High
School, Tuesday. Gore joined students for lunch during a campaign
swing in the area designed to call attention to his education
proposals. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MIDDLETOWN, Ohio -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- GORE-2 -- Al Gore
and Joe Lieberman let their limos trail behind as they boarded
bright yellow school buses Tuesday to persuade voters their $170
billion education package tops presidential rival George W. Bush's
ideas for schools. Aboard a bus, Gore talks about his education
plans with Kitty Blattner, left, and Crystal Parker, 15. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MIDDLETOWN, Ohio -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- GORE-1 -- Al Gore
and Joe Lieberman let their limos trail behind as they boarded
bright yellow school buses Tuesday to persuade voters their $170
billion education package tops presidential rival George W. Bush's
ideas for schools. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. -- Sept. 12, 2000 --
NY-PRIMARY-CLINTON-2 -- President Clinton stands inside the voting
booth as his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton, right, running for the
U.S. Senate, speaks to people at a polling station set up in the
Douglas Grafflin Elementary School in their new home town of
Chappaqua, Tuesday. Putting their political role reversal in high
relief, Clinton cast his first vote as a New Yorker Tuesday,
pronouncing it ``a thrill'' to vote for his wife in the state
Democratic primary. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- NY-PRIMARY-CLINTON
-- President Clinton passes his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton,
running for the U.S. Senate at the polling station in their new
home town of Chappaqua, Tuesday. Putting their political role
reversal in high relief, Clinton cast his first vote as a New
Yorker Tuesday, pronouncing it ``a thrill'' to vote for his wife.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SUDBURY, Mass. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- CONCORD-REVIEW-BOS
-- Maverick publisher that he is, Will Fitzhugh has both fans and
detractors of the radical work he does in his little office above a
consignment shop, down the road from the historic Wayside Inn.
Fitzhugh saves thank-you notes from authors and rejection letters
from foundations in his office in Sudbury where he publishes the
concord Review, a quarterly collection of exemplary history essays
by high school students. (Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Sept. 12, 2000 --
TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS -- People are talking about ABC's ``Monday
Night Football'' again, and that is a good thing, at least
according to Don Ohlmeyer, the show's executive producer. Miller on
Monday with a ball from the Hall of Fame preseason game between the
Patriots and the 49ers, his first telecast with the network, which
he brought with him so that Patriots' owner Bob Kraft could
autograph it. (Jim Davis/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- MEDSCHOOLS-RACE-BOS -- In the
eyes of the Association of American Medical Colleges, Grace Lopez
is not a minority. Even though she is Salvadoran-American and has
the broad face and caramel-colored skin of a Mayan, to most medical
school administrators, she's essentially white. Lopez, who grew up
poor in Los Angeles, is one of thousands of minority students who
face a tougher time getting into medical school because the
association excludes them from affirmative action programs that
could boost their chances. (John Tlumacki/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NORTH ANDOVER, Mass. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- TECH-LUCENT-BOS
-- Over the last year, as Lucent Technologies stock has plunged
roughly 50 percent, the gallows-humor line has been that Lucent's
famed red swirl logo symbolized its lifeblood going down the drain.
But the world's largest telecommunications company is fighting its
way back, jettisoning its slow-growing office network installation
business and taking other steps to sharpen its focus on advanced
communications gear, especially optical devices. Brent
Searle-Spratt works on a Lambda Router at Lucent which contains
tiny mirrored devices that redirect Internet traffic from one
fiber-optic strand to another. (John Blanding/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SHARON, Mass. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- MANAGING-MONEY-BOS --
In the beginning, there was the Husband/CFO. As Every family's
chief financial officer, he earned the money, paid the bills, and
doled out spending money as he saw fit. What's since changed is
almost everything about American families and money. Susan Silver,
who discovered her aptitude for household accounting only after her
divorce, reviews some family bills with her daughter, Debbie, 19.
(Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- MFS-OUTLOOK-BOS -- Chief
equity officer Kevin Parke, left, chief executive Jeff Shames, and
president and chief investment officer John Ballen, right, at MFS
Investment Management. As young stock analysts in the late 1980s,
they dreamed of running the company. (David L. Ryan/The Boston
Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- TIRE-CONGRESS-1 -- Jac
Nasser, Ford Motor Company's chief executive officer, right, speaks
with Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and Sue Bailey,
administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, on Capitol Hill, Tuesday, prior to hearings before
the Senate Commerce Committee. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman
of the committee, called the hearings to examine the Aug. 9 recall
of 6.5 million Firestone tires which are used on Ford trucks and
SUVs, particularly the popular Ford Explorer. (Susana Raab/The New
York Times) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- TIRE-CONGRESS-1 -- Jac
Nasser, Ford Motor Company's chief executive officer listens to
testimony from Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, left, and
Sue Bailey, administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, on Capitol Hill, Tuesday, before the Senate
Commerce Committee. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the
committee, called the hearings to examine the Aug. 9 recall of 6.5
million Firestone tires which are used on Ford trucks and SUVs,
particularly the popular Ford Explorer. (Susana Raab/The New York
Times) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) JEROME, Ariz. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- TRAV-JEROME-2-LADN --
It was the dot-com of its day, a speculative enterprise that
soared, stalled, soared again, then plunged precipitously and
ultimately flickered out. The byproduct was Jerome, an Arizona
frontier town that perches on a steep hillside in the Mazatzal
Mountains, a 110-mile drive north of Phoenix. (Eric Noland/LA Daily
News) - LA OUT - MAGS OUT -
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JEROME, Ariz. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- TRAV-JEROME-1-LADN --
It was the dot-com of its day, a speculative enterprise that
soared, stalled, soared again, then plunged precipitously and
ultimately flickered out. The byproduct was Jerome, an Arizona
frontier town that perches on a steep hillside in the Mazatzal
Mountains, a 110-mile drive north of Phoenix. Several of the
lodgings in Jerome have a medical history, including the Surgeon's
House, a former physcian's residence, now an inn. (Eric Noland/LA
Daily News) - LA OUT - MAGS OUT -
</P>
