<P>
   The following photos have been sent as part of tonight's New
York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 09/12/00.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive our photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) UNDATED -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- OBIT-NIERENBERG -- Dr.
William A. Nierenberg, a physicist with a passion for the ocean who
spent five decades striving to mesh science, technology and policy
as an adviser to presidents, military agencies and NATO, died on
Sept. 10 at his home in San Diego. He was 81. The cause was cancer,
according to a statement from the Scripps Institution of
Oceanography in San Diego, of which Nierenberg was the director
from 1965 to 1986. (Scripps Institution of Oceanography/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) UNDATED -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- OBIT-FRIEDMAN -- Dr.
Herbert Friedman, a pioneer in X-ray astronomy who received some of
the country's top scientific honors over a 60-year career, died on
Saturday. He was 84 and lived in Arlington, Va. A prolific
scientist who published some 300 papers, Dr. Friedman conducted his
earliest research after World War II, putting experiments aboard
V-2 rockets sent into the upper atmosphere, where instruments could
record X-rays and other radiation emanating from the sun. (U.S.
Navy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- CAMPAIGN-VOLUNTEERS -- For
all the frenzied fund-raising by Democrats and Republicans this
year, candidates for offices from the the White House to the local
school board know one thing is even more important than money:
volunteers. Jose Forquet, 34, of Goldman, Sachs is a co-founder of
a database used by the Republican Party to recruit corporate
managers, lawyers and other young professionals to take part in
fund-raisers and other activities for the Republican Party. The
volunteer services of white-collar workers like Forquet have become
highly prized by political campaigns. (Ruby Washington/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) KITTY HAWK, N.C. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- WRIGHT-FLYER-COX-2
-- A good measure of what the Wright brothers accomplished with the
world's first powered flight is how difficult it's proving to
duplicate their feat a century later. A coalition of aviation
organizations and government agencies will spend more than a
million dollars, use NASA research facilities, and tap the talents
of historians and engineers in an effort to build and fly a replica
of the Wright Flyer on Dec. 17, 2003, the 100th anniversary of
powered flight. Orville Wright is at the controls of the ``Wright
Flyer'' as his brother Wilbur looks on during the plane's first
flight at Kitty Hawk, N.C., in this Dec. 17, 1903 file photo. (Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- WRIGHT-FLYER-COX-1 --
Tom Poberezny, president of the Experimental Aircraft Association,
stands under the Wright Flyer at the National Air and Space museum
in Washington, D.C., where plans were announced Tuesday for a
celebration of the 100th anniversary of powered flight by the
Wright Brothers. The showpiece of the celebration will be the
construction and flight on Dec. 17th, 2003 of an accurate Wright
Flyer reproduction in Kill Devil Hills, N.C. (Rick McKay/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) DAYTON, Ohio -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- DEATHMAINBAR-COX --
Many poorer families can fall through the cracks of the
government's support network when a loved one is dying. Dee
Harmeling, left, and her granddaughter Jennifer Arnold, 15, are
thankful for the Hospice of Dayton. When Harmeling's daughter
Sandra Lee Hughes, Jennifer's mother, was dying from cancer,
Hospice of Dayton not only took over Hughes' care -- and did not
charge the family a penny -- but the care of her family as well,
making sure there were enough medical supplies and food in the
house. (Lisa Powell/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- CHASE-MORGAN-2 -- Chase
Manhattan is in serious talks to acquire J.P Morgan, an executive
close to the deal said Tuesday. The deal, expected to be worth at
least $40 billion, would unite two of the oldest and most powerful
forces in New York finance. William B. Harrison Jr., chairman and
chief executive officer of Chase, in a March, 1999 file photo.
(Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- CHASE-MORGAN-B&AMP;W -- Chase
Manhattan is in serious talks to acquire J.P Morgan, an executive
close to the deal said Tuesday. The deal, expected to be worth at
least $40 billion, would unite two of the oldest and most powerful
forces in New York finance. The deal would end the independence of
J.P. Morgan, the most famous name in the history of American
finance. Morgan in an undated photo. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- CONGRESS-CLINTON --
President Clinton, flanked by House Speaker Dennis Hastert, right,
and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, third from right, during a
meeting in the Cabinet Room of the White House, Tuesday. At left is
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle. Clinton met congressional
leaders from both parties at the White House Tuesday to discuss
priorities for the remainder of the legislative session and to try
to resolve budget differences. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) MT. LEBANON, Pa. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY --
Dick Cheney, the Republican vice presidential candidate, talks with
Marie Bluestone, 79, during a campaign stop at Baptist Homes,
Tuesday. Cheney visited the seniors residence to talk about the
Bush-Cheney campaign proposals for a prescription drug plan.
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- BUSH-2 --
Gov. George W. Bush poses for a snapshop with diners at Howley's
restaurant in West Palm Beach, Tuesday. Bush dropped by for coffee
before leaving for a campaign stop in Orlando. Bush was campaigning
here and in Missouri on Tuesday to promote the portion of his $158
billion, 10-year Medicare plan that would provide
catastrophic-illness coverage to seniors after their first $6,000
in expenses. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BAY SHORE, N.Y. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- NY-PRIMARY-LAZIO --
Rep. Rick Lazio, R-NY, the leading Republican candidate for the
U.S. Senate, after voting in the state's primary, Tuesday. Lazio
will probably face first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in the
November election. (Vic De Lucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ORLANDO, Fla. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- BUSH-1 -- Gov. George
W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, speaks with Jack
Talton at the Walt Disney Memorial Cancer Institute, Tuesday.
Trying to put a human face on his public policies, the Republican
presidential nominee visited the Florida hospital Tuesday to hear
an emotional plea from Kay Talton, an ovarian cancer patient whose
private insurance is set to lapse. Her husband, Jack, is being
treated for malignant melanoma at the same hospital. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) VUCITRN, Yugloslavia -- Sept. 12, 2000 --
YUGO-JOURNALIST-SLAIN-2 -- As violent crime continues to plague
post-war Kosovo, Shefki Popova, a journalist, was killed in the
town of Vucitrn late Sunday. The body of Popova, a 49-year-old
Albanian journalist who worked for the Rilindja newspaper is
carried for burial Tuesday, as friends and family look on. Popova
was murdered by unknown assailants who shot him as he entered his
flat in the town of Vucitrn. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) VUCITRN, Yugloslavia -- Sept. 12, 2000 --
YUGO-JOURNALIST-SLAIN-1 -- As violent crime continues to plague
post-war Kosovo, Shefki Popova, a journalist, was killed in the
town of Vucitrn late Sunday. The body of Popova, a 49-year-old
Albanian journalist who worked for the Rilindja newspaper is
prepared for burial, Tuesday. Popova was murdered by unknown
assailants who shot him as he entered his flat in the town of
Vucitrn. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) IN FLIGHT -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- BUSH-MEDIA -- The
presidential race may be neck and neck, but there is one place Gov.
George W. Bush has curtailed campaigning. The back of his own
plane. Bush's aides found that the networks preferred informal
chats in the campaign plane to moments at staged events. And
reporters, in turn, began to object when the campaign insisted the
governor's chats at 30,000 feet had to be entirely off the record.
Bush on his plane in June. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN
-- The 2000 Summer Games are about to start, but where are all the
people? Sydney isn't exactly bustling with the opening ceremonies
set for Friday night. Mario Luongo, owner and chef of Siena
restaurant in Syndey, awaits customers Tuesday night. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
