It was the dot-com of its day, a speculative enterprise that
soared, stalled, soared again, then plunged precipitously and
ultimately flickered out. The byproduct was Jerome, an Arizona
frontier town that perches on a steep hillside in the Mazatzal
Mountains, a 110-mile drive north of Phoenix. (Eric Noland/LA Daily
News) - LA OUT - MAGS OUT -
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JEROME, Ariz. -- Sept. 12, 2000 -- TRAV-JEROME-1-LADN --
It was the dot-com of its day, a speculative enterprise that
soared, stalled, soared again, then plunged precipitously and
ultimately flickered out. The byproduct was Jerome, an Arizona
frontier town that perches on a steep hillside in the Mazatzal
Mountains, a 110-mile drive north of Phoenix. Several of the
lodgings in Jerome have a medical history, including the Surgeon's
House, a former physcian's residence, now an inn. (Eric Noland/LA
Daily News) - LA OUT - MAGS OUT -
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
