<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR SWISS TO PAY NAZI VICTIMS IS PROPOSED 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a significant step for thousands of Holocaust victims who
have fought for decades to recover their savings from Swiss banks,
a special master appointed by a federal judge overseeing a class
action lawsuit submitted a complex plan on Tuesday for distributing
$1.25 billion in settlement payments from the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, $800 million from the settlement would be set
aside to repay Holocaust survivors or heirs who can show that they
held accounts in Swiss banks during the World War II era.
</P>
<P>
   Where account balances can be proven, the money would be
refunded in full with interest and adjusted for inflation. Where
balances are not known, victims or their heirs would get at least
35 percent of amounts recommended case-by-case by an independent
tribunal in Zurich. To date, 26,000 Swiss accounts have been
identified as probably belonging to victims of Nazi persecution.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $450 million would be divided among survivors _
but not their heirs _ from four other classes of Holocaust victims.
An estimated 200,000 slave laborers who worked for German companies
and a smaller number who worked for Swiss companies would be paid
up to $1,000 each. About 17,000 refugees who were denied entrance
to Switzerland during the war would get up to $2,500 each, while
3,000 refugees detained in Switzerland under abusive conditions
would be entitled to $500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Another $100 million would be set aside to help compensate those
whose assets were looted by the Nazis and then deposited in Swiss
accounts. But rather than distribute it to individual survivors,
most of the money would be given to organizations that provide aid
to elderly and destitute Holocaust survivors in the former Soviet
Union. A final $10 million would be used to compile a list of all
who were the target of persecution under the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Edward R. Korman, who is overseeing the
case, will hold a public hearing on the proposal on Nov. 20. He
could adopt the proposal, reject it or modify it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
