<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIRE-CONGRESS-1STLD-W     09-12 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSE OF RANCOR GROWING   BETWEEN FORD AND FIRESTONE 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Updates and rewrites throughout; no pickup; note byline
change.) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ford and Firestone, partners for a century, fell
into bitter sniping before a Senate committee Tuesday, with top
executives trading accusations about how the companies should
divide responsibility for the dozens of deaths in roll-over crashes
involving Ford Explorers and Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was ``like tying two cats by the tail and throwing
them over the clothesline and letting them claw each other,'' said
Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Each company has been seeking to put blame upon the other since
early August, when Firestone recalled 6.5 million tires because of
deadly failures on some sport utility vehicles, mostly Explorers.
But Tuesday's hearing before the Senate Commerce Committee showed
how profound the rift between the two automotive pioneers had
become.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief executive, faulted the way John
Lampe, a Firestone vice president, and others had handled warranty
claims and other evidence of a problem. Nasser said that when he
attended a House subcommittee hearing last Wednesday on tires: ``I
listened in disbelief as senior Firestone executives not only
acknowledged that Firestone had analyzed its claims data, but also
identified significant patterns of tread separations as early as
1998. Yet Firestone said nothing to anyone, including Ford Motor
Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was also unhappy with Firestone's estimate that it would
take well into next year to replace all the tires being recalled,
Nasser said. ``We went berserk when we heard that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the American subsidiary of the Japanese-owned tire
company, Masatoshi Ono, made a brief opening statement, saying he
took ``full and personal responsibility'' for the events that led
to the hearing. But he also said his limited command of English had
reduced the company's ability to get its points across.
</P>
<P>
   Lampe, however, sought to focus attention on the design of the
Explorer. He said that there had been 16,000 Explorer roll-overs
and that ``tire failure was involved in only a very, very small
portion'' of them. His written testimony put it at less than 10
percent. In remarks to reporters later, he said that the stability
of the Explorer would have to be analyzed as ``part of the puzzle''
of the crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Lampe also said that the company might have found the source of
the flaw that made some of its tires throw off their treads. The
company now believes that the problem involves a ``unique design
specification'' of the tires, combined with human error and machine
problems at the company's Decatur, Ill., factory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to reporters after the hearing, Lampe said he
would not be specific because the problem involved a trade secret,
saying only that the bad tires had resulted from ``an aspect of the
design combined with a process variability.'' The design feature
involved a belt, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone is bringing in an expert from the University of
California at Berkeley to evaluate the hypothesis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the testimony Tuesday focused on the federal highway
safety agency and what even top transportation officials
acknowledge is its ineffectiveness in spotting and monitoring
safety problems like the tire flaw. The secretary of transportation
and his subordinate, the head of the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, asked for powers to compel tire and auto
companies to turn over data on quality.
</P>
<P>
   But they acknowledged that they lacked the ability to pick up
safety trends from the varied sources of information they already
had. For example, they receive complaints from consumers, reports
on fatal accidents and information from insurers, but have trouble
linking them to expose serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   The safety official, Sue Bailey, dodged a question from Sen.
Bill Frist, R-Tenn., who asked how her agency would evaluate
information ``qualitatively,'' looking at the significance of
reports of problems rather than their number. Bailey, a doctor of
osteopathy, referred to Frist, who is a surgeon, as a ``fellow
scientist'' and said that a mathematical system was needed to
determine when an issue reached a threshold at which investigation
was required.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the committee repeatedly asked if the highway agency
needed more money to analyze safety trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never once has any of you come to me and said, `look, we've
got to increase this budget, be our advocate here,''' the committee
chairman, John McCain, R-Ariz., said pointedly to Bailey and
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater. The two witnesses agreed
with him, but said they were planning to take $1.8 million from
other safety programs and spend it on investigating Firestone
tires. They did not specify what programs would be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said his department wanted the authority to require auto
makers and related companies to report on foreign recalls. But he
acknowledged under questioning that the information could also be
obtained from foreign governments, though the United States does
not normally trade information with highway safety regulators in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he said, is a lack of a protocol by which
governments could swap proprietary information without fear of
public release.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings expressed surprise that commercial attaches in American
embassies in Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Malaysia, three countries
where Ford replaced Firestone tires on Explorers, had not informed
the highway safety agency. Bailey said that if her office had known
of those actions, combined with the reports of problems in the
United States, it would have triggered an investigation sooner.
Instead, the tip-off for the federal government came from consumer
complaints generated by news reports from a Houston television
station, KHOU, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members voiced enthusiasm for giving the
highway agency greater powers to demand information, including data
on services provided under warranty, which is the type of data that
Ford eventually used to expose the problem with Firestone tires.
Several also called for enacting criminal penalties for companies
that failed to report safety problems, a position even Ford and
Firestone endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   Lampe, of Firestone, said that in hindsight his company had not
looked at its own data properly. He added that the root of the
problem might be Ford's recommendation to inflate the tires on
Explorers to a relatively low range of 26 to 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone approved that range when the large, heavy vehicle
first went on the market a decade ago. But looking back, he said,
Firestone should probably have considered that more carefully,
because under-inflated tires heat up rapidly and heat can cause
damage. Consumers also often run their tires at pressures lower
than what is recommended, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members also favored raising or eliminating
the ceiling on fines to companies for failing to turn over
information. Joan Claybrook, a former administrator of the highway
safety agency and now president of Public Citizen, the consumer
advocacy organization founded by Ralph Nader, derided the existing
limits as ``a joke.'' The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration is one of the few such federal agencies with no
criminal statutes to back it up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-CLINTON-ART-     09-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS' REQUEST TO REDUCE DEBT SURPRISES DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the demise of their large-scale tax cut,
Republican leaders in Congress met Tuesday with President Clinton
at the White House to discuss unfinished legislation and request
that he set aside 90 percent of this year's surplus to pay down the
debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're down here to find a fair middle ground and try
to start to have some productivity and finish up the season,'' said
House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic leaders who attended the meeting quickly seized
on the Republican request to set aside 90 percent of the surplus
for this year, saying they were puzzled by the last-minute
proposal. For two years, Republicans have made tax cuts their
showcase issue, although they have often mentioned debt reduction
and protecting Social Security and Medicare in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vetoed their two most popular tax-cutting bills in
August as too expensive and too skewed toward the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans spent their entire two years trying to pass these
tax cuts and now they say they really want to pay down the debt,''
said House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt. ``It's either a gimmick
designed to get them out of town or a break from where they have
been in the past, if you play it out over 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Republicans he viewed paying down the debt as a
priority, but said he was not sure it could be done in the 2001
fiscal budget, which is set to kick in on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Spending requests are also piling up, Clinton said. The
government must send emergency money to states recovering from
wildfires in the West, and lawmakers want increases for military
spending and to help farmers. ``Whether we can do it this year or
not depends upon what the various spending commitments are,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   As the discussion veered off to other matters, Clinton said he
hoped Congress would pass bills to overhaul managed care and
classify violence against gays as hate crimes, an issue the House
is expected to take up on Wednesday. Clinton said he hoped to reach
a compromise on raising the minimum wage and providing some tax
relief to small businesses, which Republicans want to see linked in
the same bill.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Tuesday's discussion revolved around the Republican
proposal to reduce the debt.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the shift in emphasis away from tax cuts and
toward reducing the debt is an effort to take the money off the
table, rein in spending and protect them from Clinton's attacks on
their tax cuts. It is also a move to put Clinton in an awkward
position, since he and Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
presidential nominee, both support paying down the debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lock in the debt reduction, you don't spend it,'' said
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said a proposal to set aside 90 percent of the
surplus for only one year would do nothing to pay down the debt. As
it stands, they said, that figure is not so different from what
already exists in the budget requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's budget more than meets the 90 percent
marker,'' said Gene Sperling, Clinton's top economic policy
adviser. ``But the real test is not a potentially artificial
one-year number but whether or not there is a 10-year commitment to
debt reduction and paying off the debt over exploding tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats portrayed the request as an effort to jump on a more
popular bandwagon and as a split from the direction Gov. George W.
Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, is headed in with his
large tax-cut package.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates that the surplus next
year will total $268 billion. By setting aside 90 percent, nearly
$30 billion would be available for extra spending and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We smell a rat,'' said Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle.
``If it's a one-year plan, it's a gimmick. If it's a 12-year plan,
they're divorcing themselves from their presidential candidate,
George Bush, because George Bush has committed all of that surplus
to a tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's press secretary, Ari Fleisher, said the Bush plan would
eliminate the debt by 2016. The Gore plan would eliminate it by
2012.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said their proposal was no gimmick, simply a
bid to make Clinton choose between increasing spending or reducing
the debt. Michele Davis, press secretary for House Majority Leader
Dick Armey, said: ``It's saying, `OK, Mr. President, you vetoed the
marriage penalty. Fine. That money is going to debt reduction. You
vetoed the death tax. That money goes to debt reduction and you
don't get to spend it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, said the meeting was
most productive in that Republicans established a direct line to
Clinton, without interference from Democratic leaders, to discuss
issues that would come up in the waning weeks of the session. ``We
were straightforward with him,'' DeLay said. ``We didn't pull any
punches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
