<HEADER>
A1218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-COLUMN-JETS-PATS-     09-12 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-JETS-PATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: PATRIOTS GET A LESSON ON HOW TO GET IT DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides the muddled rivalry, the verbal war, the mutual respect
mixed with envy that color nearly every facet of the Jets-Patriots
relationship, their meeting Monday night was more about which team
would gain the jump on its new course.
</P>
<P>
   With new head coaches, new coordinators, new assistants, new
schemes and new players on both sides, the Jets and the Patriots
are in the same boat: to produce while learning on the run, to curb
the learning process. To coalesce. To act as one even though the
identity and chemistry are still being created.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage Jets. So far they are better at putting this thing
together than the Patriots are.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Jets can brag.
</P>
<P>
   In a rivalry like this one, the winner realizes it has gained a
quicker track toward the ultimate goals: a divisional championship,
a playoff berth and Super Bowl possibilities. The loser is
confronted with the nagging notion that the other guys are better
at pulling the package together. Better at the free-agent game, the
draft, the preparation, the desire, the performance. Better at the
entire game.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2-0 Jets, it is an exhilarating feeling. For the
Patriots (0-2), it hurts. It is exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of Monday night's game _ Jets 20, Patriots 19, a
thriller, a shocker, a high-strung victory _ can be lasting. The
Jets now enjoy a wonderful opportunity to propel themselves toward
something great. Their confidence is soaring. The Patriots,
however, are full of questions and doubt and are forced to shake a
mountain of the wrong momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are in excellent shape to continue their trend, playing
at home against Buffalo next and then traveling to Tampa Bay where,
against Keyshawn Johnson, they can stare down another old ghost and
prepare for a remarkable ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots _ at home next against Minnesota followed by road
games at Miami and Denver and then home again against Indianapolis
_ have all of the makings for an 0-6 start before seeing the Jets
again Oct. 15. Losing this game that they should have won could
very well spiral the Patriots into a mental and physical funk.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and the Patriots are two franchises that scrutinize and
compare each others' every move. Let's make some comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   THE COACHES: Al Groh's start is as good as two opening victories
get. Close victories. Fourth-quarter victories. They indicate
resolve in adversity and that his message and leadership are clear.
</P>
<P>
   Groh talks a good game. His handling of questions regarding the
Bill Parcells-Bill Belichick relationship before the Patriots game
was smooth. He complimented them both and kept the focus on the
opportunity for his team and for himself. In two games he and his
staff have made enough of the right moves _ especially in the
waning moments _ to begin to distinguish Groh.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Belichick saw his team fight itself as much as Tampa Bay in
an opening loss at home and then lose a 19-7 fourth-quarter lead
Monday night. After playing much of the game in press coverage and
throwing the Jets' offense out of sync, the Patriots' defense could
not keep pace when the Jets opted for an empty backfield and for
running back Richie Anderson spread wide as a receiver. That
exposed the Patriots' weakness of too few cover guys at linebacker,
and the Patriots failed to respond with a solution such as a safety
covering Anderson instead of linebackers. Of the Jets' touchdown
drives of 85 yards and 72 yards, the latter one was comical: a
two-play drive.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has to be alarmed that the strength of his team and
his game _ defense _ did not win versus the Jets when called upon.
When your team's strength becomes its liability, you are in
trouble. Belichick has plenty to correct, but how he handles the
mental state of his team right now will determine the Patriots'
season.
</P>
<P>
   THE QUARTERBACKS: Vinny Testaverde is 14-2 as the Jets' starter.
He struggled all night against the Patriots but then when they
backed off, he took control. He showed experience and
determination. To make the kind of game-ending throws he did under
that kind of pressure shows that Testaverde is not only back from a
season lost because of injury but that he remains one of the game's
top five quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe has been sacked 12 times in two games (six sacks in
each game). On his last play of the game against the Jets, he was
sacked. His team traveled six times inside the Jets' 20-yard line
and gained only one touchdown. His mobility is being questioned,
but the bottom line with Bledsoe is pass protection. With it, he
can flourish. Without it, he cannot improvise.
</P>
<P>
   THE RECEIVERS: With no pass protection, Patriots receiver Terry
Glenn, so talented, is becoming a nonentity.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne Chrebet and Dedric Ward in two games are on their way
to answering the Keyshawn question. Do the Jets have a go-to
receiver without Keyshawn? Chrebet and Ward are answering yes and
yes. Their plays in the winning touchdown drives were far from
routine. Ward's one-handed, 44-yard catch and Chrebet's two scoring
catches that showed athleticism and concentration were Pro
Bowl-like plays.
</P>
<P>
   Neither receiver has grabbed a microphone or pounded his chest
and proclaimed why he could take over for Johnson. Both, instead,
took the high road, walked and spoke softly, and let performance
speak loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis nationally and locally about both players crept toward
them (too small, too little, not good enough even as a duo to
replace Keyshawn). Both used the Monday night football platform to
give America and their peers a response. That is impressive in
production, personality and style.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots look toward the long haul. They know that the
coming, rugged divisional games for both teams could change
everything. They know that the season is a 16-game foray determined
by what you have, what you do with it and with how much heart.
Their stories are unfolding. But two games in, the Jets have
barrels more of what the Patriots desire.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence. Promise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
