<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUSH-SUBLIMINAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SUBLIMINAL HEADACHE FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Sept. 13:
</P>
<P>
   Memo to the Bush campaign team: Can you spell backfire?
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, at least, it is spelled RATS, and Gov. George W.
Bush must be seething despite his labored attempt to shrug off
``conspiracy theories'' about his campaign's latest fiasco. That,
of course, was the insertion of the word RATS in capital letters
into a television ad attacking Vice President Al Gore over the
issue of prescription drugs for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   News of the ad, coming after Bush's embarrassing problems with
an open microphone 10 days ago, launched a new round of jokes and
questions about his technologically challenged campaign. Even a
studiously somber Vice President Al Gore expressed puzzlement over
the strangeness of the episode. Other Democrats were predictably
gleeful, and Paul Begala, a party strategist, questioned whether an
organization that cannot handle the rewind button can be entrusted
with the nuclear button.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Republicans know that, all kidding aside, this is a
fraught moment for the Bush campaign. The governor's malapropisms
are becoming standard comic fare. Tuesday he referred four times to
``subliminable'' techniques. Meanwhile, a conservative publication,
The Weekly Standard, features on its cover a worried-looking Bush
beside the slightly panicky-sounding headline ``How Bush Can Win.''
Being an object of doubt and ridicule can quickly become a serious
problem for a presidential candidate. Just ask Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Forceful damage control would be Bush's smartest move. He has
already removed the ad. But since subliminal messages are regarded
as unethical by the ad industry and unfairly deceptive by the
Federal Communications Commission, Bush should go further. He needs
to find out how it got on the air in the first place, especially
since Alex Castellanos, who produced the commercial for the
Republican National Committee, has not kept his story straight.
</P>
<P>
   Castellanos originally told Richard Berke of The New York Times
that the use of the word was ``purely accidental.'' Tuesday he said
he was using a ``visual drumbeat designed to make you look at the
word bureaucrats.'' That sounds to us like a declaration of intent
to use subliminal techniques by Castellanos, who is known as a
creator of attack ads. If Bush really means that such techniques
are not acceptable to his campaign, perhaps he should sever his
connection with Castellanos.
</P>
<P>
   When a presidential campaign has the stumbles, such decisive
action by the nominee can be a step toward getting back on message,
a place Bush has hardly visited in the last two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
