r s BC-OLY-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN     09-12 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIRST IMPRESSION OF SYDNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Think Seattle with more sun. ... Or Los
Angeles with more water. And 4 million or so people friendlier than
either place.
</P>
<P>
   They really do call each other ``mate,'' here. Such as the bus
driver who said of an upcoming trip, ``It's not far, mate, but it's
not fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney may not be quite ready for prime time, but it's bloody
cheery in the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Lines for buses. Lines for security screenings. Lines for
accommodations. An airport nearly overwhelmed by traffic. A traffic
grid thoroughly overwhelmed by traffic. Nothing is far, mate, but
absolutely nothing is fast.
</P>
<P>
   Our first glimpse of Sydney was off the left side of an Air New
Zealand 767, and as initial impressions go, it had the gut-level
impact of wandering into Yosemite.
</P>
<P>
   Miles of green peninsulas lined with white-sand beaches. Deep
bays reaching far into the interior, creating enough waterfront
property to shame Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The air approach to Sydney takes you right over the city, and
then back around it in a spiraling descent. Not quite the intimate
perspective of a helicopter ride, but almost.
</P>
<P>
   Even the dullest tourist can pick out the Sydney Opera House
from the air. And that must be Harbour Bridge. The skyscrapers
downtown. And enormous swaths of green open space and athletic
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, spectacular views do not an Olympics make (or we'd be
doing this at Niagara Falls every fourth year), and the Aussies
seem to be having a rough go of the rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   They have owned up to the fact they fibbed _ OK, lied like dogs
_ about how long it takes to get around town. The national
newspaper ``The Australian,'' conceded in Wednesday's editions,
``The timetables in the (Olympic) bid document read like science
fiction, or a manual for weekend drag racers. They assume no
traffic lights and no traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   A particular trip, from downtown Sydney to Darling Harbour,
advertised as a 180-second jaunt, is now known as ``the myth of the
three-minute cab ride.'' It's more like a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   At times Tuesday, the transport system was so spotty it almost
made a bloke nostalgic for Atlanta. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sydney has attributes Atlanta can never match. Great
weather being high on the list. It is the tail end of winter in the
Southern Hemisphere, and it's 70 degrees most days. Like March in
the Inland Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney really is rather like SoCal, which Sydneysiders concede
with a mixture of enthusiasm and terror.
</P>
<P>
   Climate and commuter horror stories are just part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The newest housing could be plucked right out of tracts going up
in Santa Clarita, south Orange County or Calimesa. Split-level
homes with multicar garages marching into the distance on hills
that were grass and scrub a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The older housing stock, squat square little single-family
bungalows, could be Long Beach's east side, or El Monte, or San
Bernardino north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the people, increasingly diverse and world-wise,
just like SoCal.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century ago, Sydney was an outpost of the British Empire,
with High Tea and scones and English reserve overlaying Celtic
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   As we open the new millennium, Sydney is multi-ethnic and
multilingual. It is Thai food, Chinese immigrants and a leading
role in Southeast Asian and Polynesian affairs. Overlaying a Celtic
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, we begin to discover how well Sydney, and Australia,
have prepared for the real thing, with soccer matches in Melbourne
and Canberra two days ahead of Opening Ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Getting crabby journalists from Point A to Point B (and into
their village, a former insane asylum) four days before competition
is one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Getting athletes to the venues and fans into the stands, and
back home at a reasonable time, are the real tests.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney will give this its best shot, but even if it comes to
logistical meltdown, it's hard to imagine all those eager Aussies
crying in their Foster's lager.
</P>
<P>
   Regret is for other blokes, mate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
