<HEADLINE>
POSTCARD FROM SYDNEY: ONE OF A KIND LODGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Staying at the Olympic Media Village, I feel
like I've died and gone to summer camp. There are 5,883 reporters
ensconced in 664 buildings, 21 of which once housed a psychiatric
facility. Call me crazy but I feel sorry for the other 10,000
credentialed media who are scattered in hotels in downtown Sydney.
Like the athletes who chose to stay outside the Athletes' Village,
they're missing out on the quintessential Olympic experience.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't trade a harbor view for the chance to crack onto
(Aussie slang for chat up) journalists from all over the world.
Reporters like the distinguished gentleman from Luxembourg who
proudly ticked off the names and sports of the eight athletes from
his country who are competing here.
</P>
<P>
   And the man with the bored look on the shuttle bus who turned
out to be from Perth. He grew slightly more animated as he
explained that western Australia isn't happy as a dog with two
tails to have the Olympics in its country because it is, after all,
taking place on the _ ahem _ other coast. Apparently the West
Coast-East Coast rivalry is not as pronounced as is it in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   It's also pretty cool to be greeted every morning at the Media
Village entrance by curious kangaroos and wallabies. Alas, an
electric fence keeps our contact with them to a minimum. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
