u s BC-BKC-INDIANA-KNIGHT-NY     09-12 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-INDIANA-KNIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT DEFENDS BEHAVIOR AS INDIANA NAMES COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indiana University tried to look to the future Tuesday, naming
Mike Davis as the interim head basketball coach of the Hoosiers.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis accepted his ascension from assistant to Bob Knight
to successor to the controversial coach, it was clear from the
remarks at Davis' news conference and from a nationally televised
interview with Knight, that it will take a while to chip away at
the Knight legacy in Bloomington.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who was fired on Sunday after 28 years as head coach at
Indiana, spoke on ESPN Tuesday night, defending his behavior at the
school, particularly since the administration put him on ``zero
tolerance'' notice on May 15, and admitting that he had overstayed
his welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would stay here and coach until I was done
coaching, which I'm certainly not now,'' Knight said in the
interview. ``I'm not done coaching. But in recent years things have
changed, the administration changed, the athletic department
changed. For some people that may be good. For me, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``As recently as July I gave serious consideration to another
job, and have in the last couple of years. I don't think that my
thinking about another job quite overrode the feeling that I had
for Indiana University and the kids we had here, the kids we had
coming, what we had built. I wanted more than anything to see us
get back. We've never been mediocre, always been really good or
pretty good. I wanted to see us get back to really good. I kind of
hung onto that thought for four or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight added: ``Probably I should have gone somewhere else.
There's someone who's a better fit for these people and
administration as a basketball coach. And there would be a place
somewhere that's a better fit for me as a basketball coach than
Indiana is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not embarrassed to leave Indiana the way he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Knight insisted. ``What I am is proud, proud of
what our basketball program turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight denied committing any of the violations that were
detailed on Sunday by the university's president, Myles Brand.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would definitely coach somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent all summer with an offensive set in my mind while I'm
fishing or traveling, thinking who's going to be here or there,''
he said. ``Now I won't be able to do that with these kids. But I'm
looking for kids that I can do it with. I haven't retired. I'm an
unemployed teacher now, looking for a place to teach. There are too
many things I have yet to explore about game of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had already received calls inquiring about his
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was an assistant to Knight for three seasons, serving as
the lead recruiter for this year's prize class and the man who
recruited most of the players he inherits. He now steps into the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   While Knight no longer holds the entire state of Indiana in sway
as he once did, he still had enough stature to prompt protests on
campus and a threatened walkout by nearly the entire team if Davis
were not named as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 39, who played at Alabama, then professionally in Europe
and in the Continental Basketball Association, was named as interim
head coach while another assistant, John Treloar, was named as
interim associate head coach. The team stood behind Davis on the
podium and expressed satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Knight is the reason I'm here, but Indiana basketball is
bigger than anyone,'' Davis said. ``The players stood up for Coach
Treloar and myself. I discussed the situation with their parents,
and my son yesterday when I was leaving said, `I hope you get the
job.' I've gone to these kids' homes and recruited them, convinced
them to come here. They stood up for me, so there's no way I could
turn it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The junior Dane Fife, who on Monday had said he had already
decided to leave, said Tuesday: ``We definitely have something to
prove. We've been through a lot, and we have to come out and beat
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Knight, Fife said: ``We owe it to him. This is his
team. We're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said: ``I don't think there was pressure from the players.
For Mike Davis to be head coach at Indiana University is a miracle.
If it wasn't September, this program could go out and get a
big-time coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
