<SLUG> BC-OLD-MURDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TEST LEADS TO ARREST IN 1985 TEXAS DOUBLE-SLAYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HANSON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSENBERG, Texas _ Because of new DNA testing on old evidence, a
suspect was charged Tuesday in connection with the vicious slayings
of a young woman and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 15 years, detectives have been chasing down leads
in the deaths of Cathy Keith, 20, and Peggie Keith 44, who were
found slain in their apartment on the morning of Jan. 11, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, authorities collected DNA evidence. But it was
only recently that their patience and persistence paid off.
</P>
<P>
   New DNA testing was able to link the evidence to a Florida man
who had been a suspect since the early days of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Charles Tonn, 36, a grocery store meat-cutter, was
arrested by Rosenberg police and charged with murder in Cathy
Keith's death. He is being held in the Fort Bend County Jail,
southeast of Houston, in lieu of $100,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Although the DNA evidence only connected him to the younger
victim's death, authorities believe he acted alone and is also
responsible for the mother's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the killings, Tonn was married to Cathy Keith's
older sister, Susan. He worked as a maintenance man and lived in
the same apartment complex as the victims. The younger woman was a
clerk at a construction company.
</P>
<P>
   The savagery of the killings shocked police.
</P>
<P>
   The younger woman's throat was so severely slashed that she was
nearly decapitated. She had also been dealt a strong blow to the
face, said Rosenberg police Lt. Brad Rollins.
</P>
<P>
   He said her clothing was removed and her body was draped over a
bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   Police theorize that her mother, who worked at a snack-food
plant in Rosenberg, arrived home about half an hour later. She was
attacked in the living room and stabbed numerous times. Her
clothing was also removed and she was left in a bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Neither woman was sexually assaulted, but detectives found their
bodies had been positioned in sexual poses after death.
</P>
<P>
   There was no forced entry at the apartment and Tonn quickly
became the main focus of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not eliminate him as a suspect. He was right there at
the top of our list, '' Rollins said. ``His alibi was horrendous.
And he fit to a T the FBI profile of the killer.''
</P>
<P>
   That profile, he said, included such details as the killer
probably having a military background and the likelihood he would
go on a heavy drug binge after the crime. He said Tonn did indeed
serve in the military and was known to use drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Police found one of Tonn's fingerprints in the apartment, but it
was considered useless as evidence because he worked there and, as
an in-law of both victims, he had also visited them at the
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Purses belonging to the women were missing, as was a pistol, but
police did not believe robbery was the motive behind the killings.
</P>
<P>
   There was one piece of evidence that police recovered that they
hoped would one day lead them to the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Some saliva was found on Cathy Keith's body, and detectives
carefully collected and froze it _ the practice of the time for
processing bodily fluids to be analyzed in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was January 1985, and the first DNA court case was in
England that year,'' Rollins noted. ``We weren't even conducting
DNA testing in the United States. We didn't have any knowledge of
DNA at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   DNA testing began in this country about two years later, and
police submitted the sample to a laboratory for testing. However,
they were told it had degraded because of being frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said the slide was sent back, but police were advised to
hold on to it because, the lab said, ``As technology grows, we may
be able to do something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a little less than a year ago, Rosenberg Detective Jeff
Johnson asked if he could submit the sample again for DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that was an excellent idea, and we did,'' Rollins said.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago, police were told the saliva taken from
Cathy Keith's body matched a blood sample from Tonn.
</P>
<P>
   Police began working to locate witnesses and Tonn himself.
</P>
<P>
   They learned that he and his wife had been divorced about a year
ago and that he had been working recently in Destin, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were already seeking him for failure to make
child-support payments. He and his former wife had two children.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ex-wife who suggested to detectives that they should
go to Enterprise, Ala., because Tonn's mother had died and he might
show up for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Tonn was arrested there after the services. He waived
extradition and was brought back to Rosenberg early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He has told detectives nothing about the killings, Rollins said.
Police do not really have a firm idea of why the women were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have to ask behavioral scientists. This is beyond my
comprehension,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins was with Rosenberg police at the time of the killings
but did not become involved in the case until a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels good, but it feels scary because we have a lot of
work still to do,'' he said of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Keith, the father of Cathy and former husband of Peggie,
said Tuesday that he was stunned to learn of Tonn's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing I felt was relief that this finally
happened,'' Keith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go like the normal justice system goes, we may have
another 10 years of this garbage to go through,'' Keith added.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said that because items were stolen from the apartment,
it is possible that the murder charge could be upgraded to capital
murder, which carries a penalty of life in prison or death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
