A1251 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FEDEXFRANCE0913-COX     09-12 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDEXFRANCE0913-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FedEx works out partnership with French post office
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - FedEx and the French post office announced an alliance
Tuesday in which FedEx will transport French international
shipments in its aircraft, and the French postal service will
deliver FedEx packages across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is similar to an arrangement that FedEx and the U.S.
Postal Service are negotiating domestically.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx's new strategy of forming partnerships with national
postal services is designed to instantly give the Memphis-based air
cargo carrier broad ground delivery capabilities. It also
intensifies competition with Sandy Springs-based United Parcel
Service Inc., which uses its own people, airplanes and trucks to
perform almost all of its 13 million daily deliveries around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumers and markets will ultimately tell us which
strategy they prefer,'' said Michael L. Ducker, FedEx executive
vice president for international operations. ``We feel very
strongly that the synergies between our international air network
and the (French postal service's) ground network will benefit our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance between FedEx and Chronopost Internationale, a
subsidiary of the French post office that handles international
shipments, is scheduled to begin Jan. 1. Terms of the deal were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   UPS officials said Tuesday they will wait to learn details of
the proposed alliance before deciding whether to challenge it in
court. UPS successfully sued the German post office in 1994,
claiming it used its monopoly on first-class mail to illegally
subsidize competition against private carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But John Flick, a UPS spokesman in Atlanta, said FedEx's sudden
willingness to enter far-reaching partnerships shows desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``FedEx is rushing to imitate the integrated air/ground network
we already have in place in Europe,'' Flick said. ``We've always
taken a long-term approach _ not a quick hit.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS began deliveries in Germany in 1976, and the company has
steadily expanded across Europe. UPS now has more than 23,000
workers there.
</P>
<P>
   The company's international operations were consistent money
losers until 1998 when the company recorded its first international
profit. Since then, profits have grown steadily as e-commerce and
globalization have led to a surge in premium-priced, cross-border
shipments.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx made its first foray into Europe in the late 1980s when it
tried to duplicate its U.S. overnight delivery system there. The
effort was doomed, however, by cumbersome regulations, high costs
and competition from efficient road and rail networks. FedEx pulled
out of the intra-European delivery market in 1992 but maintained
intercontinental cargo flights among Europe, North America and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx has 6,000 employees in Europe and 198 weekly flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been driving toward a comprehensive global network for
years,'' said FedEx's Ducker. ``This alliance advances that goal by
leveraging two powerful networks for the benefit of our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   FedEx shares on the New York Stock Exchange closed Tuesday at
$39.36, up 66 cents. UPS shares finished the day at $53.56, up
$1.19.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
