<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, SEPT. 12 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: These corrections appeared in The New York Times on
Wednesday, Sept. 13. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GORE-NYT (moved Monday, September 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
11 about Oprah Winfrey's interview with Al Gore used a misspelled
pen name and a nonexistent given name for the author of ``The Red
and the Black,'' which Gore described as his favorite book. The pen
name is Stendhal, not Stendahl; Robert is not part of it.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT (moved Monday, September 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
11 about Representative Rick A. Lazio's plan for new education
spending if he is elected senator misstated the total for new
spending on education proposed by his opponent, Hillary Rodham
Clinton. Clinton's proposals, taken together, would cost $129.6
billion over 10 years, not $123 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-HARRIS-NYT (moved Friday, September 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Friday, September
8 of Rebert H. Harris, lead singer of the Soul Stirrers,
characterized their music incorrectly. They were gospel singers,
not soul singers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the obituary also omitted the given
name and background of a producer. He is Anthony Heilbut, a gospel
historian and Harris' former producer.
</P>
<P>
   The obituary also misspelled the surnames of two members of the
Soul Stirrers. They were Thomas Breuster (not Brewster) and Roy
Crain (not Crane).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
