<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     09-12 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GAZE WILL CARRY FLAG AND HOPES OF AUSTRALIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Tuesday evening, in the heart of the Olympic
Village, a thousand well-wishers stood in the grand lobby of the
Super Dome for an emotional send-off for the Australian Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   This was an evening drenched in history: Australia was one of
only five countries to play host to at least two Games, and the
athletes were part of the largest team Australia (628) has ever
fielded.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes, wearing smart olive green blazers, stood with team
officials and family members as John Coates, president of the
Australian Olympic Committee, talked about the continent's unbroken
history of Olympic participation. They watched as previous
flagbearers were introduced and came down a steep escalator. They
watched a film of the country's flagbearers, from 1924 to 1996,
making the famous walk around Olympic stadiums. Coates reminded the
audience that athletes were the soul of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the moment that everyone was waiting for: who would
carry the Australian flag?
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Gaze.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupted in cheers, his basketball teammates slapped
him on the back. Finally, after nearly three minutes of applause,
Gaze, the captain of the basketball team, leaped onto the podium,
hugging and kissing everyone on the dais.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very humbling experience,'' Gaze said. ``When
you walk around and see all the volunteers and you see the flag
raised, you see what it means to them and see how passionate they
are and how revved they are just to see you and say, `G'day.' That
makes you feel very welcome and very proud to be an Australian.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaze may have clinched the honor three days earlier during
Australia's warm-up game against the heavily favored United States,
when he got into a scuffle with Vince Carter, the young American
superstar. Officials would chastise both players, but the truth is
that the audience at Melbourne Park indoor stadium for the game
against the Americans appreciated Gaze's show of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Gaze's life is a basketball life, representing a combination of
team, country, family and a sense of national pride that is
difficult to understand in the United States, where profit consumes
and defines right and wrong, loyalty and motivation.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, Gaze, a five-time Olympian, is a national
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, he has a different image.
</P>
<P>
   For many critics in 1989, Gaze became a symbol of a
win-at-all-costs hypocrisy that defines big-time collegiate sports.
He went to Seton Hall University in October 1988, after having
played for Australia in the Seoul Olympics. He averaged 13.6 points
for the Pirates, who lost the national championship game to
Michigan, 80-79, in overtime. Four days later, Gaze left Seton Hall
to return to Australia, prompting critics _ I was one of them _ to
call him and Seton Hall partners in a mercenary alliance to win a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   His short stay and the circumstances of his participation in an
Australian professional league raised questions about amateur and
professional distinctions and the recruitment of top international
talent by major American universities.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gaze said he had decided to leave school when he
learned he would be ineligible at Seton Hall if he played another
season for the Melbourne Tigers, the team coached by his father,
Lindsey.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, no one in the States understood _ or particularly
cared _ about Melbourne. Last night, as Gaze emotionally accepted
the honor, talked to teammates about responsibility, playing hard
and working hard, the deep roots of loyalty became much clearer.
</P>
<P>
   After he left Seton Hall, Gaze went home, joined the Australian
national league season and resumed his career with Melbourne. He
averaged 34 points for the Tigers in 1989. Then his life took a
sharp turn, which in many ways led to yesterday's emotional honor.
Nearly 10 years to the day, Sept. 11, 1990, Gaze became seriously
ill and was hospitalized with a blood clot in his right shoulder
just before the finals of the 1990 Australian season. He missed a
tryout with the Portland Trail Blazers and missed his league's
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Gaze began to rearrange his priorities. Winning
and losing was not the motivation; he no longer felt the need to
prove himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are lying in bed wondering what is going to happen,''
Gaze said, ``you rethink things. Yes, basketball is very, very
important, but it's a game. The world is not going to fall in, and
you are not going to die tomorrow if you don't win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gaze earned more than $130,000 in Italy. But he turned
down a lucrative offer to return to Australia to play for
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   His father coached the Tigers for nothing, he had always played
for or coached the club. Andrew was a Tiger since he could dribble
a ball. Loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   He explained to journalists that playing for more money in Italy
would have meant missing the last half of the Tigers' National
Basketball League campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, as Gaze, age 35, accepted the Australian flag, he
smiled, held back tears and dedicated the honor to the blood of his
country, the blood of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a bit of an imposter up here,'' Gaze said. ``My
dad played in the 1960, '64, '68 Olympics and coached in the '72,
'76, '80 and '84 Olympics. If anyone deserves an honor like this,
it would be him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaze stopped, composed himself and blushed. ``I'll certainly be
carrying this flag for my dad,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
