<SLUG> BC-ECON-OUTLOOK-LADN </SLUG>
 
ECONOMIC FORECASTERS EXPECT CONTINUED EXPANSION &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOSEPH GIORDONO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   VENTURA COUNTY - Ventura County's agricultural business will
continue to enjoy the longest peacetime economic expansion in
history - just not at the same high rate of growth, a leading
economic forecaster said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we expect? We expect a soft landing,'' said Bill
Watkins, director of the University of California, Santa Barbara
Economic Forecast Project, speaking at a meeting of the Pacific
Agribusiness Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A soft landing is when the rate of growth of the economy slows
down. It still keeps on growing. People aren't being laid off, jobs
are still being created - it just goes up at a slower rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said he was more concerned about risks a few months ago
``when the (Federal Reserve Board of Governors) was going on a
rampage changing interest rates every time they got together.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they have now started taking some time to see what is
happening with the economy before they make their rate decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, previously an economist for the Federal Reserve
System's Banking Analysis Section, spoke about the county's
economic forecast before a few dozen participants of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Among other topics, Watkins addressed concerns about the effect
of slow- growth SOAR initiatives on Ventura County's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Though his staff has not yet done a comprehensive report on the
subject - they plan to begin one in December - he said the effects
of the Save Open Space and Agricultural Resources initiatives
passed by voters in 1998 were smaller than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you were supposed to have was a direct wealth transfer
from the people who own ag land to the people who own already
developed land. We did not see it,'' Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Projections of a drop in prices for agricultural land deemed off
limits under SOAR and an increase in prices for existing
developments within SOAR boundaries did not come true, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins speculated that the existence of a large supply of new
housing has kept price pressures down and led people to view the
growth control measures as something far down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe nobody believes the growth controls,'' he said. ``Times
are good, everybody is doing well, so you pass a law protecting
parks and farms. Maybe when there's a recession and you've lost a
job, you're going to change your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
