<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT     09-12 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FINDS A MINUS TO COZINESS WITH REPORTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The presidential race may be neck and neck, but
there is one place Gov. George W. Bush has cut back on his
campaigning. The rear of his own plane.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few days ago, the Republican nominee would stroll the
aisle of the campaign's chartered Boeing 757 to chat with reporters
traveling with him. But the visits became fewer and farther between
after Bush's aides found that the networks preferred those informal
moments to the staged events of the day. And reporters, in turn,
began to object when the campaign insisted that the governor's
conversations at 30,000 feet had to be off the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discovered they were using shots from the plane on the
evening news,'' said Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications
director. ``And because Gore wasn't doing `avails' like that, the
networks were using shots from his events.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of romancing the media, the Bush campaign is
learning about the downside of courtship. Unlike the campaign of
Vice President Al Gore, which has strictly limited the candidate's
access, Bush and his advisers have provided a steady diet of the
kind of ``availabilities'' that reporters crave.
</P>
<P>
   Even on days when he can anticipate tough encounters _ as on the
morning last week when articles appeared quoting prominent
Republicans expressing worries about the state of the Bush campaign
_ the governor met with reporters. ``He took questions for 20
minutes,'' said Walter Shapiro, a columnist for USA Today, ``and
the consensus of the reporters I talked to was that this was a
gutsy performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In providing the access, Bush's aides have also learned how
piercing the double-edged sword can be, for making the governor
available almost every day has given reporters and camera crews a
greater degree of autonomy within the highly controlled confines of
a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, was for weeks this summer virtually
unavailable for daily questions from reporters, a practice that may
have irritated the reporters but certainly gave him tighter control
over the ideas and images the campaign sought to convey.
</P>
<P>
   As the experience of the photo opportunities on the Bush plane
demonstrated, access does not guarantee cooperative coverage. In
fact, Bush appears at times to grant the news media license to
knock him completely off his message.
</P>
<P>
   When, for instance, Bush surprised reporters last month with an
admission aboard the campaign plane that he had to do a better job
of making clear his plan for a tax cut, some reporters used his
candor as the foundation for stories about a campaign in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern continued on Tuesday, as Bush appeared on the tarmac
of Orlando International Airport and faced several questions about
a report in The New York Times that the word ``rats'' shows up for
a split second in an anti-Gore commercial by the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   CNN led its midafternoon newscast today with its follow-up to
the report. ``No detail is too small or too fleeting to cause a
controversy,'' a CNN anchor noted. In its piece about Bush's tarmac
appearance, the network also pointed out that Bush mispronounced
``subliminal'' four times.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Warfield, who was Bob Dole's press secretary during the
1996 presidential campaign, said: ``Another day of message lost for
a guy in a neck-and-neck race. The Bush campaign is a highly
disciplined operation, and I think they are convinced their message
will penetrate. He doesn't want to become a bumbler and he isn't
yet. But this is not a helpful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In what sometimes can sound like an echo of his former rival,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the governor often speaks of his
respect for reporters as if he genuinely likes them. In a
question-and-answer session Bush held with workers at a
high-technology company in Warrendale, Pa., on Friday, the first
two questioners were critical of what they saw as the way the press
distorted Bush's campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an interesting relationship between me and the
media,'' Bush told the employees at the company, Marconi
Communications. ``I need them to get my message out, and sometimes
it comes out fairly and sometimes, frankly, I don't care for the
coverage. But that's OK. Sometimes I answer the question, they
think it's OK. sometimes I answer the questions, they don't like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, it was Bush and his staff who did not like the
questions. As the plane headed to St. Louis, Hughes served
reporters cubes of cheese as she called the article about the rats
reference ``the cheesiest story'' she had ever read.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since his loss in the New Hampshire primary,
Bush has had to endure a sustained period of bad news, reported by
many of the people he says he respects. The recent events range in
significance from his failed effort to impose his own plan for
debates to smaller gaffes and strategic miscues that have become
frequent distractions.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign and the reporters who follow it say there has been
no perceptible deterioration in their relationship. Indeed, some in
the traveling press corps report a kind of admiration for Bush's
resilience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can get pummeled by reporters,'' said David Gregory, a
correspondent for NBC News assigned to the campaign. ``And 10
minutes later, he'll come back and shake hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some political professionals wonder whether the trouble
Bush has faced recently will force a shift in the relationship
between the governor and the journalists.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The press is the most jealous mistress of all,'' Warfield
said. ``And Bush has been very smart in recognizing the demands of
the care and feeding of the press. The question is how he continues
that, now that he's hit a rough patch.''
</P>
<P>
   Warfield said that Dole, who as a senator was known for his
quick wit, found the tenor of the coverage in the presidential race
frustrating. ``He enjoyed bantering with reporters, but his dry
sense of humor didn't always translate into ink,'' Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, Warfield recalled that Dole was asked the
fairly innocuous question, ``What was the one thing he wanted
Americans to know about him?'' ``Senator Dole sort of scratched his
head and said `Beats me,' in a funny way.'' The resulting story?
``Dole can't come up with a single thing he wants America to know
about him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There came a certain reluctance to step on your message of the
day by taking the high risk of shooting the breeze with
reporters,'' Warfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters following Bush say that on some days, the themes
and issues the campaign emphasizes _ especially health care and
education _ are retreads that force them to pursue other story
lines. And ever more often, the story of the day is what the latest
polls are saying.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision to visit this state, previously thought to be
safely in his column, itself became the dominant story on Monday,
when the governor was in Clearwater and West Palm Beach, talking
about health care. For example, the lead paragraph in The Palm
Beach Post's front page story on Bush's noted that Bush's campaign
here was ``nowhere near the sure thing he hoped it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether all the ``avails'' are to any avail may be incalculable.
Much of what happens is beyond the control of a campaign, anyway,
said Shapiro of USA Today, who traveled with the campaign last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A drop in the polls is something that nothing can cushion,''
he said. ``An embarrassing admission is something that nothing can
cushion. So all these things are at the margins.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mr. Shapiro said he thought the campaign and the press had
reached an acceptable equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not chummy `We're all in this together' nor is it `You're
all part of an evil media conspiracy,' '' Shapiro said. ``It's much
more `You have your job to do, and we'll help you.' Anything
closer, you'd get suspicious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      09-12 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Republicans say they'll concede big tax cuts, if Democrats put
surplus toward debt relief
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By KAREN MASTERSON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans offered to back down Tuesday on their
demand for major tax cuts if Democrats would agree to use the
budget surplus for debt relief, not for more spending on government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to take 90 percent of our surplus ... and pay down the
debt,'' House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said yesterday
after a late afternoon meeting with President Clinton and
Democratic congressional leaders at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good discussion'' and found ``a fair middle ground''
on some issues, Hastert said. Among them was a likely compromise to
increase the $5.15 hourly minimum wage by $1 in exchange for
limited tax breaks for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Having all but lost the battle over the repeal of the estate tax
and marriage penalty tax, Republicans switched strategies. Instead,
they want to prevent Democrats from significantly increasing
spending on domestic programs by proposing to put most of the
estimated $264 billion surplus in fiscal year 2001 in a ``locked
box'' for debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Republican efforts to override the president's veto
of the estate tax failed. Today the House is scheduled to vote on
an override of the president's veto of the marriage penalty tax
repeal. That vote is expected to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats called the GOP's debt-reduction proposal a
``gimmick,`` indicating that the two parties remain far apart on
spending issues. Meanwhile, the clock is running out for lawmakers
to reach an agreement before the fiscal year ends Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We smell a rat,'' said Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle of
South Dakota. Following Tuesday's White House meeting, Daschle and
other Democrats said they want to see more money go toward debt
reduction, but not as prescribed by the Republicans. Instead of
putting nearly all of this year's surplus toward the national debt,
Democrats want to spread the debt-reduction payments over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also agreed generally about the need for a
prescription drug plan for the elderly and a patients' bill of
rights. But on details, the two sides remained too far apart to
predict the passage of any new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come away from the meeting with confidence'' on these
two issues, Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, both sides will have to compromise on
fundamental differences over government spending. Only two of 13
spending bills needed to keep the government running into the next
fiscal year have been signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the spending bills have cleared at least the House and
some have been approved by the Senate. But Clinton has threatened
to veto several of them because he said they fall short of funding
important programs, like school construction, by roughly $25
billion.
</P>
<P>
   If the two sides fail to reach an agreement, few options remain.
The government could shut down, although that proved to be
political suicide for Republicans when they challenged the
president in 1995, forcing a partial shutdown of government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   With continued control over the House at stake, Republicans are
more likely to bend so they can get home to campaign, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are now talking about passing a temporary spending
bill that would keep the government running beyond Oct. 1 and,
possibly, keep them in Washington later than they want.
</P>
<P>
   Holding out for a series of modest tax reductions is House
Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land.
</P>
<P>
   What DeLay and others want are tax cuts and other concessions
that would cost roughly $16 billion in 2001 and would include an
increases in the amount of tax-free contributions to retirement
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Also being pushed is an increase in the amount taxpayers can
contributed to their individual retirement accounts, a proposal by
Rep. Bill Archer, R-Houston, that would cost between $4 billion and
$5 billion. That proposal is expected to be included in a budget
reconciliation bill, which the Ways and Means Committee _ chaired
by Archer _ is scheduled to finish on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also want to increase Medicare reimbursements to
hospitals, nursing homes and other Medicare providers, at a cost of
roughly $4 billion; provide roughly $4 billion in tax cuts to small
businesses to offset the cost of raising the minimum wage; and
repeal the federal telephone excise tax, at a cost of roughly $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates a $264 billion surplus
for next year, about $200 billion from taxes collected on Social
Security and Medicare in excess of what is paid out.
</P>
<P>
   Of the non-Social Security and Medicare funds available for
discretionary programs _ about $64 billion _ Republicans say there
is about $10 billion available for additional spending on programs
favored by Clinton, which is about $15 billion short.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats conceded that yesterday's meeting at
the White House brought them closer to understanding what the other
side wants, but not much closer on what each side is willing to
give.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans this year have pushed for hundreds of billions in
tax reductions after Clinton a year ago vetoed a $792 billion tax
package. Instead of funding all the tax measures into one bill, GOP
lawmakers repackage their tax-cut proposals in a series of separate
bills hoping to make it more difficult for Democrats and the White
House to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
