<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-ANDERSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' ANDERSON TURNING THINGS AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This could have gone a couple of very different
ways. Everyone admits that. And its last chapter is still far from
written.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no denying the direction in which Marques Anderson
is now headed. The UCLA junior strong safety is off to an
impressive start to the Bruins' 2000 campaign, quickly emerging as
an impact player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a chance, if he continues to grow, to play in that
league on Sundays,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``He's that
talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinions have changed since last year, when Anderson was forced
not only to sit out the season for disciplinary reasons, but was
suspended from UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a player who had always had things come easily was
banished from his team and school. He spent last fall taking
courses at Compton College. He spent it re-evaluating where he was
going with his career, and his life.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson already had been in serious trouble with the dean of
students when he was discovered as one of the Bruins involved in
the handicapped-parking-placard scandal. Others missed games, but
for Anderson, it was one mistake too many. He was out.
</P>
<P>
   His previous mistakes have been kept confidential. He attributes
them to immaturity, saying he did ``stupid things'' and was
``taking shortcuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe things came a little too easily for Anderson early. The
latest talented defensive back out of Long Beach Poly High, he
started five games as a freshman at cornerback. He had three
interceptions. He seemed headed for football greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you start taking things for granted,'' Anderson
said. ``Then you kind of forget what got you there, and that's hard
work and dedication.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that suspension, it kind of put everything into
perspective. It was a real humbling experience. Since I came back
to school, I just dedicated myself to working hard and devoting my
time to football.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no certainty he would even come back to UCLA. While
attending Compton, he could have spurned the Bruins and headed to
another campus. But before he left, he spoke with Toledo, who
assured him if he got his life together, a scholarship would be
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to go anywhere else,'' he said. ``I love my
Bruin family.''
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo also told Anderson one other thing: There was no room
for even one more mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him if he did something wrong, he was going to be
gone,'' Toledo said. ``He's on probation. The next major mistake he
makes, he won't be with us anymore. He knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson returned during the winter quarter, having
rededicated himself to his sport and to getting things done the
right way.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA cornerback Jason Bell, who also missed most of last season
with a heel injury and is his closest friend on the team, said it
was obvious early something good had developed out of a bad
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sitting out was probably the best thing that could
ever have happened to him,'' Bell said. ``He realized how much he
loved the sport and how much he missed not playing it. When he came
back, he worked harder than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could just tell he was taking the game seriously. Usually
Marques is kind of passive. He's so talented he's kind of like,
`Let's go. Whatever, whatever.' But this time he was a different
person about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely saw that things aren't going to work out for you
just because you're Marques Anderson. He kind of realized he had to
take care of his business and do things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he trained harder than ever. Already one of the
strongest players on the team despite his 6-foot, 208-pound frame,
he increased his bench press to 350 pounds. Anderson said he
improved his time in the 40-yard dash to 4.31 seconds, a remarkable
improvement from his previous best of 4.5.
</P>
<P>
   Others noticed his new attitude. Anderson had been away for only
one quarter, but had returned a seemingly different young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big maturing process,'' Toledo said. ``He played as a
true freshman and he had a lot of success. All of a sudden he
thought, `This is pretty easy.' And it wasn't that easy. He became
a little lackadaisical, he became a little lazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when his problem hit, he realized how badly he missed it
and how important it was to be out there performing. I think he
reassessed what he had done and his goals. Now he's living up to
those goals.''
</P>
<P>
   When the college football world last saw Anderson, it was in the
two final losses of the 1998 season _ the infamous poor-tackling
games against Miami and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I most definitely was one of the guilty parties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a year away, he had been moved to a new position to
open against third-ranked Alabama. Knowing how he had prepared,
Anderson said he felt nothing but confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year away there was a lot of built-up tension,'' he said.
``It was a lot of mixed feelings. Sadness that I couldn't be with
the team. Frustration. All these things that kind of built up
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 20 months away from football, I was ready. The excitement
was building up. All of these things I was thinking for such a long
time were just ready to explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and an unexpectedly strong secondary helped to give
Alabama fits in the 35-24 upset. Against Fresno State last week,
Anderson was again all over the field _ recovering the fumbled snap
in the closing minutes to preserve the 24-21 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Through two games, he is tied for second in tackles (nine) and
for first in passes defensed (four), and he has a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's just beginning to reach his full potential,''
Bell said. ``I think free safety is his natural position. He's an
outstanding player this year, but we haven't seen the best he's
going to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
