<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-VISA-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSATIONS OF MISCONDUCT IN TWO JUSTICE DEPARTMENT PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Top Justice Department officials responsible for
teaching foreigners about American-style justice and democracy
engaged in ``egregious misconduct,'' including a visa-fraud scheme
to slip Russian girlfriends into the United States, according to a
report by the department's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released to Congress on Tuesday, the inspector
general recommended discipline against several managers of the
overseas training programs for abuse of visa procedures,
mishandling classified documents, traveling by business class
without authorization and practicing favoritism in hiring and
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations span several years of the mid-1990s at the two
programs: the International Criminal Investigative Training
Assistance Program, which trains foreign police agencies in newly
democratic nations, and the Office of Overseas Prosecutorial
Development, Assistance and Training, which instructs foreign
prosecutors and judges.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs are part of the Justice Department's criminal
division, though they are financed through the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who has pressed Attorney General
Janet Reno to crack down on the police training program, called the
report ``merely the latest example of how the Justice Department is
a real mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Myron Marlin, a Justice Department spokesman, declined to say
what action, if any, would be taken against the managers criticized
by the inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the accusations involve Robert K. Bratt, a senior
Justice Department official who enjoyed the confidence of Reno to
the extent that she subsequently tapped him to help overhaul the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bratt, who served in various management roles over the two
training programs beginning in 1992, made four trips to Russia in
1996 and 1997, the report said. During those visits, he met two
women, one or both of whom became his ``Russian girlfriends,'' the
inspector general said.
</P>
<P>
   The report asserted that Bratt and an associate, Joseph R. Lake
Jr., who retired in 1997, used Bratt's authority to bypass the
normal procedures to get U.S. visas for the women. They were
granted visas in April 1997, through a process reserved for special
humanitarian cases or those involving an American government
interest, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Bratt issued a statement Tuesday denying any abuse of his
position. He portrayed himself as the target of an inspector
general, whom he called ``out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The report recommended several current Justice Department
managers for discipline, including Joseph Trincellito, the
associate director of the police training program, for mishandling
classified documents; Janice Stromsem, a former director of the
program, for violating security regulations and personnel rules;
and Cary Hoover, a special assistant, for sharing classified
material with uncleared parties.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the inspector general would have recommended
``significant discipline'' for Bratt including ``possible
termination,'' but noted that he retired last month. Senator
Grassley insisted that Bratt should face criminal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
