<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAT-AD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE MAN SPOTS ``RATS'' IN GOP TELEVISION AD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On Tuesday, Gary Greenup was America's man in the
news. Today, he's on his way to becoming history's footnote.
</P>
<P>
   All because Greenup, a Seattle technical writer and college
instructor, can't just smell a rat. He can spot one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Greenup created the political hubbub du jour after identifying,
then recording, the word ``RATS'' in a Republican television
advertisement praising George W. Bush's plan for prescription drugs
and belittling Vice President Al Gore's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The multiple-rodent identifier flashes by most viewers too
quickly to notice _ in one-thirtieth of a second. But Tuesday,
Greenup's find became news fit to print and the focus of the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent much of his day answering questions about the
advertisement after The New York Times told all on Page One. The
Republican National Committee canceled the ad. The man responsible
for it said it was all a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats enjoyed their opponent's embarrassment and spoke
darkly of subliminal advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Back at his Ballard home, Greenup fielded at least a dozen
interviews, including a spot on CNN. So great was the media crush
that the state Democratic Party dispatched a staff member to help
Greenup cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can rest on my laurels now. I've made it in The New York
Times,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I didn't set out to be the avenging angel. I just
thought it might be something interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   For Greenup, it all started around Labor Day when he noticed the
Republican ad that blasted Gore's plan to provide senior citizens
with prescription-drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The 64-year-old Greenup may understand the way the candidates
and their parties communicate better than most citizens.
</P>
<P>
   He is a retired technical writer for Boeing who writes on a
variety of subjects. He also teaches business communications and
English at community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Greenup follows politics with a passing interest. A Democrat, he
regularly gives a small amount to the national party.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, he worked on Democrat Mike Lowry's campaign for
governor. But he said his campaign work didn't amount to much more
than ``sweeping out the office at night.''
</P>
<P>
   When Greenup first saw the Bush ad, he thought he spotted
something. He watched it a second time. The third time the ad ran,
he had his VCR ready. He watched the commercial frame by frame, and
sure enough, ``RATS'' appears in capital letters. Then the ad
states: ``The Gore prescription plan: Bureaucrats decide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just kind of intrigued by what I saw. It's pretty
interesting that they are taking a risk to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He called King County Democrats, who shuffled him to the state
party. Greenup left a voice-mail message for Paul Berendt, party
chairman. But Berendt didn't exactly leap to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, when I heard the message, I didn't think there would
be anything to this,'' Berendt said Tuesday. ``I just didn't think
subliminal advertising was in the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Berendt and his wife, Beth, saw the ad as they
were having breakfast. There was a quick flash on the screen that
made him suspicious. He sent a staff member to Greenup's home, who
watched the ad frame by frame in the writer's living room.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Berendt's wife recorded the ad, did her own analysis
and came up with the same conclusion as Greenup.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the ad was soon on its way to Gore headquarters
in Nashville, then to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Greenup hopes the controversy he sparked does some good. Just
maybe, he said, people who create political ads ``will be more
responsive to the good sense of the electorate'' the next time they
try to win votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making too much out of this,'' he said of his sudden
fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be in, then I'll be out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
