<HEADER>
A1455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-GREY-NYT &LR;      09-12 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GREY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA GREY, 54, PUBLISHER WHO LED BALLANTINE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Linda Grey, a top publishing executive who rose from
editorial assistant to president and publisher of Ballantine
Publishing Group, died on Aug. 30. She was 54 and lived in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from lung cancer, said Alun Davies,
a friend of Grey's.
</P>
<P>
   Grey resigned from her position at Ballantine last February
during a reorganization of the company that came more than a year
after the media conglomerate Bertelsmann moved to acquire
Ballantine's parent, Random House.
</P>
<P>
   She got her start in publishing in 1970 as an editorial
assistant at Coward McCann &AMP; Geoghegan. Later she rose to become
managing editor there and then took executive positions at Dell
Publishing Co., where she was its editor in chief. In 1981 she
moved to Bantam Books as an editorial director and became its
publisher and editor in chief in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   She left that position in 1992 to start her own short-lived
imprint for the company, Linda Grey Books, which published just one
book, ``It Doesn't Take a Hero: The Autobiography of General Norman
H. Schwarzkopf.'' The imprint was dissolved the same year after the
announcement that Grey was resigning to become president and
publisher of Ballantine Publishing Group.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her career Grey worked with best-selling authors like
Schwarzkopf, Lee Iacocca, , Shirley MacLaine, Judith Krantz and
Robert Ludlum and the suspense writers Michael Palmer and John
Saul. Alberto Vitale, her longtime boss as the chief executive at
Bantam Doubleday Dell and later Random House, often described Grey
as a ``tremendously good editor.''
</P>
<P>
   After her resignation from Ballantine Publishing Group, Grey,
who was unmarried, essentially retired from the publishing
industry, although she continued to counsel authors who were her
close friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
