<HEADLINE>
SUPERDOME UNIX SERVERS CRUCIAL TO HP 
 &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Hoping to expand its share of the lucrative and
fast-growing market for e-business hardware, Hewlett-Packard rolled
out a new line of high-end Unix servers Tuesday that it says
leapfrogs the best available from rivals like Sun Microsystems and
IBM.
<P>
   Known as the HP 9000 Superdome series, the new machines are
designed for large dot-com businesses and service providers, as
well as conventional corporate data processing.
</P>
<P>
   The new models won't come cheap: Prices start at $1 million, not
counting the software packages HP, and its partners will offer for
such applications as e-commerce, billing and ``customer
relationship management.''
</P>
<P>
   But HP, calling Superdome, without qualification, ``the fastest
server in the Unix market,'' said it will be a bargain compared
with the mainframes customers would previously have needed to get
equivalent performance, reliability and flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The first Superdome systems will run HP's version of the Unix
operating system, HP-UX, on the PA-RISC 8600, the latest in its
line of proprietary processors for servers and workstations.
Initial configurations, offering twice the performance of HP's
previous high-end servers, will have 32 of the high-performance
chips; a 64-chip version will be offered later.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's 4-year-old E10000 line doesn't deliver the performance
that many of today's e-business customers would like, said Lee
Kroon, an analyst for the Andrews Consulting Group of Cheshire,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Kroon said IBM's S80, a high-end server series introduced last
year, did ``incredibly well,'' with sales topping 1,000 systems
during the first 90 days after the introduction. ``I expect a
similar experience with Superdome,'' Kroon said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kurt King, an analyst at Banc of America Securities in San
Francisco, was less impressed with HP's performance claims. ``It
would be shocking if a major server vendor introduced new products
that didn't outperform their competitors' old products. Everybody
always outperforms everybody else when they set the standard of
measurement.''
</P>
<P>
   HP is generally ranked second in revenues from Unix servers,
after Sun and ahead of IBM. New models from Sun have been delayed
pending release of the UltraSPARC III, the company's
next-generation processor, which is nearly a year behind schedule.
But the new chip is expected to appear in low-end and midrange
servers this fall and in new high-end models early next year.
</P>
<P>
   During the second half of 2002, HP will offer Superdome users
the option of switching to Intel's impending ``IA-64'' or Itanium
processors, which HP helped design. The timetable implies that HP
will pass on the first IA-64 chip, known by the code name Merced,
and wait for its successor, code-named McKinley, which according to
Intel will deliver higher performance.
</P>
<P>
   By switching to IA-64, users will get additional
operating-system options. Superdome machines with the new Intel
chips will support Windows and Linux as well as HP-UX _ or even all
three simultaneously, via mainframe-style schemes that enable users
to partition the machine into separate hardware and software
environments.
</P>
<P>
   King, however, called the IA-64 option ``more an insurance
policy for their customers than anything else.'' There has been
concern among many HP server customers, he said, that the company
will eventually ``pull the plug'' on its proprietary RISC chips.
</P>
<P>
   Kroon also warned that switching processors ``won't be a walk in
the park'' for customers, even though HP says IA-64 chips will be
compatible with many applications written for the older HP chip
family. ``There's a lot of marketing hype in these claims,'' he
said. ``Whenever you change CPUs, there are always a lot of caveats
and considerations. If I were an HP customer, I'd be asking some
very pointed questions about how this transition is supposed to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Banc of America's King last month lowered his rating on HP
shares from ``strong buy'' to ``buy,'' primarily, he said, because
of the ``lack of momentum'' in the company's Unix sales.
</P>
<P>
   HP disputes that assessment of its current market position, but
it is clearly counting on Superdome to erase all doubts. In
addition to the new machines' performance, the Palo Alto giant is
emphasizing its commitment to service and support, including
assignment of an HP ``solution manager'' to each Superdome
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded coolly to HP's announcement: The company's
shares were off $1.44 to close at $112.56.
</P>
<P>
   HP will also offer ``utilitylike'' pricing plans, under which
customers will pay only for the computing capacity they actually
use. That option, according to analyst Kroon, ``will have very
significant appeal to anyone in e-business, because capacity needs
are very unpredictable for businesses that are open to the world
7/24.''
</P>
<P>
   King agreed that ``HP is doing the things that customers in the
e-business market want to see,'' but added that ``the bad news is
that there's not a lot here that competitors can't easily
replicate.'' Both Sun and IBM have already promised similarly
flexible pricing plans.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
