<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUEGOLD--FLEET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRY FIRM, STATE ATTORNEY GENERAL AGREE ON COMPLAINT SETTLEMENT  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The California attorney general Tuesday disclosed
the settlement of an antitrust and unfair-competition complaint
against the Blue &AMP; Gold Fleet.
<P>
   The San Francisco cruise and ferry service was charged in San
Francisco Superior Court with allegedly tying the sale of popular
tickets to Alcatraz Island to purchases of other San Francisco Bay
cruises operated by the company.
</P>
<P>
   Blue &AMP; Gold denied any wrongdoing, saying it never engaged in
the alleged activities. However, it agreed to a permanent
injunction against so-called ``unlawful tie-in sales'' and will
offer specific training to sales staff to avoid future problems.
</P>
<P>
   Blue &AMP; Gold also agreed to send a copy of the complaint and
judgment to its tour operator customers and pay $10,000 to the
state Department of Justice to cover the attorney general's
investigation and attorney fees.
</P>
<P>
   After the settlement, Blue &AMP; Gold President Ron Duckhorn said
the allegations were off-base. ``This has never been our practice
or policy nor have we operated our business in any inappropriate
way.'' He added that the goal of settling this suit ``quickly and
efficiently'' was to ``put to rest these questions'' and to get on
with business.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BLUEGOLD () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Deputy Attorney General John Donhoff Jr. had a different take on
the settlement. ``We have evidence that firms that wanted good
blocks of tickets for resale to Alcatraz were required to buy
(other) bay cruises from Blue &AMP; Gold, or things would change for
them in an adverse way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that the state attorney general's
office has acted to preserve competition on the bay. Three years
ago, it objected when Crowley Maritime Corp. decided to sell its 11
Red &AMP; White tour boats, ferry service license, bay cruise routes,
Alcatraz service contract and packaged-bus-tour business to Blue &AMP;
Gold.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a consent decree to prevent a monopoly, Blue &AMP; Gold
agreed to sell the Red &AMP; White name and three of its ferryboats to
Tom Escher, grandson of the Crowley Maritime founder.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in the latest dispute are high. Each year, Alcatraz
attracts more than 1 million visitors. Because walk-up sales for
same-day departures to the former federal prison are often
impossible to obtain, visitors frequently pay three or more times
the $12.25 fixed price of the Alcatraz trip and self-guided audio
tour to companies who package the Alcatraz visit with other tours.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of BLUEGOLD () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Despite the attorney general's latest action, Blue &AMP; Gold's legal
troubles involving access to Alcatraz are not finished. Two small
Fisherman's Wharf tour operators last year accused Blue &AMP; Gold of
violating equal-access provisions of its park service contract by
giving more-favorable treatment to big tour companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Sears' A American Tours and Elric Leano's San Francisco
Magical Mystery Tours charge that Blue &AMP; Gold repeatedly gave
preferential treatment to their biggest wholesale customers,
including advance ticket allocations, the most-popular departure
times and, in the case of Tower Tours, exclusive permission to
return unsold tickets. A mediation meeting is set for Nov. 6 with a
trial scheduled for Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Blue &AMP; Gold competitor Red &AMP; White Fleet was pleased
with Tuesday's legal action. ``The judgment speaks for itself,''
said Red &AMP; White President Tom Escher. ``All we're looking for is a
level playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
