<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER--PLAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PG&AMP;E CHIEF WANTS RATE INCREASES 
 &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In an invitation-only meeting with Wall Street analysts, the chief
executive of PG&AMP;E Corp. said he wants to raise electricity rates as
quickly as possible to pass along billions of dollars in extra
power costs to ratepayers, participants told The Chronicle.
<P>
   It was the most explicit declaration to date of the company's
intentions as California lawmakers, regulators and utility
customers grapple with the increasingly murky outlook for
deregulation of the state's energy market.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E Chief Executive Officer Robert Glynn told analysts in New
York on Monday that the company will attempt to pass along more
than $2 billion in unforeseen costs when a current freeze on
electricity rates is lifted in early 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While PG&AMP;E's meeting with financial analysts was intended to
focus on a wide range of issues, recent developments in California
prompted Glynn to devote almost an hour to explaining his company's
goals for the state.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's PG&AMP;E Corp. is the parent company of Pacific Gas
and Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glynn said the company is entitled to recover all the money it
spent buying power for customers,'' said Peggy Jones, an analyst at
Prudential Securities who attended the briefing. ``He said it would
be best to raise electricity rates and to do so very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   A rate increase is precisely what California utility customers
were told would not happen as a result of a deregulated power
market. Increased competition, it was said, would result in rate
cuts for most customers.
</P>
<P>
   But surging wholesale electricity prices have caused utilities
like PG&AMP;E to swallow hundreds of millions of dollars in expenses by
not being able to pass along their costs to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The one California utility that has had its rate freeze lifted,
San Diego Gas &AMP; Electric, was the target of widespread protests
after average customer bills more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to calls for relief from San Diego politicians and
ratepayers, the state Public Utilities Commission last week
approved an emergency rate cap for the city, effectively halting
deregulation in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, PG&AMP;E officials told The Chronicle that their
costs under the rate freeze continue to grow by about $700 million
a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glynn's position is that he would favor raising rates as
quickly as possible, above where they are today,'' Jones said.
``The message I heard is that the company intends to strike the
best deal it can to recover costs from customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer activists were dismayed to learn that PG&AMP;E's top
executive has come out so strongly on the issue of passing along
costs to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Jacobson, consumer program director for the California
Public Interest Research Group in Sacramento, noted that PG&AMP;E was
one of the prime architects of the state's deregulation blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be PG&AMP;E that eats the costs because they made the
initial promise that rates would go down,'' he said. ``Consumers
are being ripped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Spatt, a spokeswoman for The Utility Reform Network in San
Francisco, agreed that PG&AMP;E took its chances with deregulation and
should not be allowed to subsequently stick customers with the tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loaded the dice and, unfortunately, it didn't work,'' she
said. ``But it's not consumers' fault it didn't work. It's not
consumers' responsibility to bail them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn's trip to New York was intended in large part to reassure
heavyweight institutional investors that PG&AMP;E will not be left
holding the bag for the more than $2 billion in unforeseen
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which slipped 69 cents Tuesday to $30.94,
is hovering near its 52-week high. Glynn wants to prevent investors
from growing nervous about PG&AMP;E's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``His message to Wall Street was that they've got $2 billion to
recover and they're going to recover it, which was the right thing
to say to investors,'' said Greg Gordon, an analyst with Goldman
Sachs who also attended Monday's briefing.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts still expect PG&AMP;E to seek a compromise whereby
it would share its financial burden with customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to persuade shareholders and customers that they
will come up with a middle-of-the-road solution that will be good
for everyone,'' said Danielle Seitz, an analyst with UBS Warburg.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Greg Pruett said Glynn hinted to the analysts
that such a settlement could be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reiterated that the main thing we're focused on is working
with regulators to find a solution that's fair to all parties,''
Pruett said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Glynn had been scheduled to speak today at an
energy-industry conference in New York sponsored by Merrill Lynch,
Pruett said the PG&AMP;E chief decided to skip the event and fly back
to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He said Glynn had returned to work on the deregulation issue,
but could not say whether any meetings are scheduled for this week
with regulators or legislators.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; dlazarus(AT)sfchronicle.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
