<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EATING--OUT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT RESTAURANT EXODUS 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The dot-com revolution is drawing hordes of new
office workers to San Francisco's Financial District _ but where
are they going to eat?
<P>
   Several big-name restaurants in the neighborhood have either
shut down or are about to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason: A space squeeze caused in large part by
cash-rich dot-com companies competing for elbowroom in one of the
tightest real-estate markets in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues, a lot of dot-com millionaires could be
forced to prepare brown-bag lunches each morning before leaving
their luxury penthouses on Nob Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the popular, flourishing Financial District restaurants
that have closed or soon will:
</P>
<P>
   _ Occidental Grill, which occupies the first floor of a building
at 453 Pine St. and is being evicted next month by the owner,
Shorenstein Co. The building _ along with others on the block _ is
being torn down and will be replaced by an office tower.
</P>
<P>
   _ Murphy's Exchange, which occupies the second floor of the
building housing the Occidental Grill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barcelona, at 7 Spring St., which couldn't afford a huge rent
increase. It is closing its doors forever at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jack's, at 615 Sacramento St. Owner John Konstin succumbed to
an exorbitant $5 million offer from a real-estate developer for the
three-story building. The restaurant will close during December.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Post, owner of the 113-seat Occidental Grill, which has
occupied the Pine Street location for seven years, says he has a
deal in the works to reopen at an undisclosed site in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He had been paying a relatively modest $7,000 monthly rent for
the 2,400-square-foot premises, but he won't disclose his rent on
the new place.
</P>
<P>
   Post is bitter about his eviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter Shorenstein simply doesn't have enough money,'' he
exclaimed sarcastically. ``This has to do with greed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Shorenstein Co. said the company bought the
building early this year, and that both the Occidental Grill and
Murphy's Exchange had provisions in their leases allowing a new
owner to terminate the leases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has allowed them some slack, given them time to
wind up their affairs,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of the 5-year-old, 245-seat Barcelona is ``sad _ we
put so much energy into the place,'' said the flamboyant owner,
Giovanni, who doesn't use his last name. ``I am known as Giovanni
the Margarita King,'' he said, ``even on my driver's license.''
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni said the restaurant is a magnet for celebrities _
notably rock-and-roller Bruce Springsteen and basketball immortal
Magic Johnson. It is ``so well known that you can't get a
reservation for Friday and Saturday nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni said Calfox, managing agent for the owners of the
building _ reportedly the Cahill family _ offered to renew the
lease, but at several times the current rent. (Giovanni declined to
disclose either figure.)
</P>
<P>
   Rather than open a restaurant elsewhere, Giovanni plans to start
a new business, marketing his patented margarita and tequila
recipes to other restaurants and to supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Aljoe, chief operating officer of Calfox, said that the
landlord's relationship with the Barcelona was very good, and that
the rent increase was ``strictly an economic decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial office space commands higher rents than retail space,
Aljoe said, so the restaurant probably will be converted to an
office. Several prospective tenants have expressed interest, he
remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Another restaurant in the area, the 300-seat Scott's Seafood
Grill and Bar, at 3 Embarcadero Center, almost had to pull up
stakes. But that tale has a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lease was up, and the new rent was so high we were going
to move to a site South of Market,'' said owner Paul Albert. But
some other major restaurants already had vacated the Embarcadero
complex, and ``the owner, Boston Properties, wanted us to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties negotiated a rent lower than the first offer, and
Scott's signed a new lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lucky,'' Albert says.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur Louis at  &LR; alouis(AT)sfchronicle.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
