<SLUG> BC-MONGO--MUSIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT GETS MONGOMUSIC 
 &HT;     BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Moving to bolster its reach into Internet music,
software giant Microsoft is buying MongoMusic Inc., a Redwood City
company that has developed music search and recommendation
technologies.
<P>
   In a deal that will be formally announced Wednesday, Microsoft
plans to make MongoMusic part of an evolving strategy to infuse
more music and digital entertainment content into sites like
MSN.com and WindowsMedia.com., said Bob Visse of MSN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Visse would not comment on
published reports that Microsoft is paying $65 million in stock for
the year-old MongoMusic.
</P>
<P>
   MongoMusic will move to Microsoft's headquarters in Redmond,
Wash., and all 65 employees have agreed to move with the company,
said spokeswoman Colleen Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Using programs like RadioMongo and the IntuitiveMusicSearch
System, MongoMusic users can find and listen to new music that fits
their taste.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Aram Sinnreich of Jupiter Communications Inc. said music
search and recommendation technology such as MongoMusic's is
becoming more valuable as the market for Internet music continues
to grow to a projected $1.5 billion by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft would very much like to have a major role as a
digital music service provider,'' Sinnreich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``MongoMusic has some very interesting technologies that can be
used as part of the backbone for an online music initiative,'' he
said. ``Typically, when Microsoft encounters technology like this
in a market that's growing, they buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bevangelista(AT)ssfchronicle.com. &LR;
</P>
