<HEADER>
A1462 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DAILY--BREAD-SFCHRON &LR;      09-12 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAILY--BREAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA'S ARTISAN BREAD RISING ACROSS THE NATION  &HT;     BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The Bay Area is rolling in artisan breads _ those
crusty, European-style loaves preferred by consumers who would
rather go hungry than eat presliced bread from a plastic bag.
<P>
   But not all Americans are so fortunate in their access to
crusty, paper-wrapped loaves. Even in large markets such as Los
Angeles, there are often only three or so artisan bakers, compared
with about a dozen in greater San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, even the most ambitious bakers have been confined to
trade areas no larger than 100 miles. That's because artisan breads
are too temperamental to travel far afield; after 24 hours or so,
the crust becomes overly chewy and the spongy interior begins to
dry out.
</P>
<P>
   But all that is changing, thanks to new applications of old
technologies (ovens and freezers) and an increasingly sophisticated
American palate that has boosted demand for good bread.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of artisan bakers around the country, including Bay
Area market leader Grace Baking, have begun shipping frozen,
slightly undercooked loaves to faraway restaurants and
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the line, these ``parbaked'' loaves are thawed and
``baked off'' for 10 to 15 minutes, producing loaves that even
purists admit can rival local breads in taste and texture.
</P>
<P>
   All this has sparked a hot debate in the insular and
serious-minded world of artisan bakers, many of whom consider
themselves more artists than businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, parbaking has created a vast market for
entrepreneurial bakers like Grace, which has recently begun
shipping frozen, parbaked bread to Monterey, Mendocino and
Sacramento as well as Reno and  &LR;   &LR; Hawaii. Grace will enter Los
Angeles later this month and is scouting out Portland, Ore.
(Grace's breads and pastries sold in the Bay Area are still baked
and delivered fresh daily.)
</P>
<P>
   A couple of ambitious artisan bakeries, including Los Angeles'
La Brea Baking, which pioneered parbaking, are shipping frozen
loaves across the country. La Brea's parbaked sourdough baguette
won a Chronicle Food section taste test three years ago against
five local competitors, including Grace, whose bread was fresh
baked.  &LR;   &LR; Brave New World
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brave new world that we're into now,'' said Peter
Franklin, owner of PeterBread Consulting in Marblehead, Mass.
``There's a market out there (for parbaked bread) and a very viable
business model as well. But will it replace the corner bakery? For
the fabric of the country, I hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace's foray into parbaking began about two years ago, when it
started selling its  &LR; pugliese &LR; , a rustic, Italian-style loaf, to
Sacramento's Corti Bros. grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   While most retailers buy a steady amount of fresh bread every
day, Corti was picking up huge shipments twice a month. An inquiry
by Grace revealed that Corti was freezing the pugliese, reheating
it in the store and selling the bread warm to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't work with most bread, but pugliese (which is
particularly durable) does fine,'' says Fred Doar, Grace's chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the opportunities in far-flung markets, Grace's
founder and head baker, Glenn Mitchell, developed a technique for
parbaking and freezing his breads. In April, Grace moved from its
small Albany headquarters into a mammoth new Richmond facility,
where it is gearing up for major expansion into parbaked goods.
</P>
<P>
   Doar, who worked for Nestle SA and Andersen Consulting earlier
in his career, expects Grace's sales to jump from $10 million in
1999 to more than $11 million this year and $30 million in 2005 as
the company spreads across the country.
</P>
<P>
   According to Doar's forecast, parbaked product will account for
60 &UR;  &LR; percent of Grace's total in five years. Today, parbaked goods
represent only 1 percent of Grace's sales, with 69 percent coming
from fresh-baked wholesale to retailers such as Whole Foods, Trader
Joe's and Costco, and 30 percent generated at four retail locations
in Albany, Corte Madera, Oakland and San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Grace is also experimenting with parbaked breads that can be
sold directly to consumers from supermarket freezer sections,
without being baked by retailers first.
</P>
<P>
   The company is even contemplating a step previously unheard of
in artisan baking: a public stock offering. If Grace continues to
meet its growth forecasts, Doar foresees an IPO in two years.
</P>
<P>
   While traditionalists argue that parbaked breads lack the
specialness of their fresh counterparts, Mitchell contends that
parbaked quality can actually exceed that of fresh goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're baking better breads than ever before,'' said Mitchell,
a former pastry chef at San Francisco's Hotel Meridien who founded
Grace in Oakland's Rockridge district in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   That's because parbaked goods are sold in large orders that can
be made with high-capacity, automated equipment. While it may seem
counterintuitive, Mitchell, Franklin and others agree that
state-of-the-art automation can be gentler and more reliable than
human bakers, resulting in lighter and more-consistent loaves.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Better-Shaped Loaves
</P>
<P>
   Grace, for example, uses an 80-foot-long Italian oven for its
parbaked products. As many as 3,000 loaves at a time sit on a
conveyor belt and move through compartments where baking and
steaming times are programmed (steam helps produce a nice crust).
</P>
<P>
   The automated oven largely eliminates over- and undercooking, a
danger when humans are responsible for pulling the bread out at
just the right time, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Grace also uses a dough-shaping machine to turn out same-size
loaves
</P>
<P>
   but maintain the irregular appearance prized by lovers of
artisan bread. The machine was imported from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get 10 people to hand roll 10 baguettes exactly the
same,'' said Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's expansion has helped make the entrepreneurial bakery a
better business partner, said Adriano Paganini, who sells Grace's
pugliese at his 14 local Pasta Pomodoro restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be difficult to deal with because they were
small,'' said Paganini. ``You had to order well in advance and they
couldn't always fill orders. Now it's totally different,'' with
Grace even developing a special pugliese for Pasta Pomodoro to use
as sandwich bread.
</P>
<P>
   Paganini, a native of Italy, said he may ship Grace's parbaked
pugliese to restaurants in other markets as Pasta Pomodoro expands
beyond the Bay Area. ``To me, it's one of the best (artisan breads)
around,'' he said. ``I eat it at home all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Paganini dismissed criticism that progressive ideas such as
expansion and parbaking can take the magic out of artisan bread. He
has heard the same doubts as he moves Pasta Pomodoro toward a
national expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is to identify the values that allowed you
to be successful in the first place and be able to preserve
those,'' Paganini said.
</P>
<P>
   But to traditionalists, parbaking is, if not sacrilege, at least
something of a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, (parbaking) departs conceptually from the notion of
somebody who is devoted to his or her craft expressing, to the best
of his or her ability, the results of that craft,'' said Steve
Sullivan, co-founder of Berkeley's Acme Bread Co.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan acknowledges that parbaked breads can be very good and
in some cases may even taste fresher than fresh-baked bread. For
example, fresh bread is typically baked during the middle of the
night, many hours before it is served, whereas parbaked bread can
be thawed and reheated at a restaurant just in time for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But parbaking has its drawbacks, including bread drying out more
quickly than bread that hasn't been frozen and reheated, Sullivan
said. Also, if a shipment winds up thawing on a loading dock and is
later refrozen, the quality suffers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tasted (La Brea's) parbaked lines at trade shows,'' said
Sullivan. ``With Nancy (founder Nancy Silverton) standing there and
taking the bread out of the oven at just the right moment, it can
be wonderful. But that's not going to happen in every
circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Opportunities are Rising
</P>
<P>
   Doar acknowledged that Grace has experienced some
disappointments, such as supermarket customers overcooking the
parbaked breads. But all in all, the quality is quite good, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities for growth-oriented artisan bakers are rising
every day, said Ed Lee, editor of Modern Baking magazine.
</P>
<P>
   While there are too many small bakeries to make an accurate
tally of sales for the sector, crusty breads are believed to be the
fastest-growing category of baked goods, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, particularly those who are well traveled, are
increasingly interested in European-style bread, he said. ``And
certainly more discretionary income over the last 15 years hasn't
hurt, either. People are willing to spend $2.50 to $5 for a loaf of
bread.''
</P>
<P>
   One question on the minds of bread bakers is whether the new
breed of artisan bakers like Grace will put smaller local guys out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, whose bakery generated about $8 million in sales last
year, doesn't think so. He sees parallels with another alleged
threat to bakers back in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out in 1983 and bread machines came out the next
year,'' Sullivan said. ``I thought, `Oh great, we just spent all
this money and people are going to be doing their own.' But that
just didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfchronicle.com. &LR;
</P>
