<SLUG> BC-GROW-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITY BEGINS ON THE NET 
 &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Charity has been in the headlines lately.
<P>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney got some heat
for giving just 1 percent of his $20.7 million income over the past
decade to charity. Conversely, the graduate business program of the
University of California at Berkeley got kudos for saying it would
offer an innovative class on ``Contemporary Philanthropy'' to MBA
students this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans are naturally more intent on earning money and
investing it than on giving it away.
</P>
<P>
   But many experts say entrepreneurs and others can well afford to
pay more attention to philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, several new tools and Web services can help you
assess how much you can afford to give and make the process
simpler.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's NewTithing Group unveiled its online
philanthropic budgeting tool last week at a ``Sharing the Wealth''
summit in St. Paul, Minn., organized by Minnesota Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Using NewTitheCalc, users can securely and quickly enter
financial data such as investment income, investment assets, earned
income and living expenses and quickly explore affordable giving
levels and check how changes in their finances can affect their
giving wherewithal. (For information on the conference and the
interactive calculator, visit  &LR; access.mpr.org/civicj/giving &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   ``This tool can change the way people think about affordable
giving by helping them budget for charity each year instead of
simply reacting to solicitations,'' says former money manager
Claude Rosenberg, who founded the nonprofit NewTithing Group to
inspire Americans to think more, and differently, about
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Many people consider giving based on their income. Some churches
ask members to tithe a fixed percentage, sometimes 10 percent, of
their annual income. But Rosenberg argues that excluding asset
wealth from investments and inheritance is ``outdated, outmoded and
basically unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley alone, approximately 64 new millionaires are
created every business day. If each of them gave 1 percent of that
wealth to charity, there would be $3.2 million going into
philanthropic endeavors each week. Rosenberg figures that Americans
can afford to be far more generous if they base their giving on
their wealth rather than their income.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, total giving by individuals in the United States was
more than $143 billion a year. But NewTithing estimates the total
could go up additional $244 billion, with all but $27 billion of
that coming from individuals in the three highest tax brackets who
receive more than $200,000 in annual income.
</P>
<P>
   NewTithing Executive Vice President Tim Stone says that the 1.4
million American tax filers with income of $200,000 to $499,000 who
now donate an average of $7,251 a year could afford to give an
average of $30,500 without deviating from their financial goals or
lowering living standards.
</P>
<P>
   If appreciated assets are involved, he notes the net cost could
be as little as $13,630, given the benefits of deducting charitable
contributions from state and federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market is worth $13 trillion or more,'' says
Rosenberg, ``and high-net-worth individuals own a great deal of
that.'' Indeed, the approximately 110,000 Americans who earn more
than $800,000 a year have average investment assets of about $21
million.
</P>
<P>
   GIVING THROUGH WORK: San Francisco's CoreMatter, formerly called
AllCharities, is on the verge of announcing the first four Fortune
1,000 companies that will offer Internet-based ``e-Giving'' service
to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some employee-giving programs, CoreMatter guarantees that
100 percent of donated funds reach the designated charities, and
its online service lets employees choose from 670,000 nonprofit
organizations. Donors can contribute appreciated securities as well
as cash. They can also use their credit cards to make onetime or
regular donations or set up a contributions plan through payroll
deductions.
</P>
<P>
   David Scholtz, founder and CEO of the year-old startup, says
American households give an average of about $1,200, or 1.8 percent
of income, to charities each year. The goal of CoreMatter
 &LR; (www.all &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; charities.com &LR; ) is to make it easier for employees of large
organizations to contribute and expand their choices and payment
options. It also lets companies and employees track matching
contributions and time spent on volunteer activities.
</P>
<P>
   CoreMatter's clients, including high-tech, consumer product and
financial service companies, will pay for these new employee
services.
</P>
<P>
   Other online charitable-giving sites include  &LR; charitableway.com &LR; 
and  &LR; www.matchgift.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Grow a Business appears every Wednesday in The Chronicle. Send
small-business tips, comments and questions to
 &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfchronicle.com,  &LR; or to Peter Sinton, Grow a
Business column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
