<DOCNO> NYT20000912.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-HUGHES-NYT     09-12 0179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HUGHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALCOLM. K. HUGHES, 66, NEWS AGENCY EDITOR, 66  
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Malcolm K. Hughes, a former editor in chief of United Press
International, died on Monday in Arlington, Va. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, known as Mike, had stomach cancer, UPI reported.
</P>
<P>
   Born of British parents in India, he served in the Royal Air
Force and was hired by what is now UPI in London as a teletype
operator in 1956. He rose through the agency's ranks as a sports
writer and editor, becoming executive sports editor in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes went to Washington as vice president and general manager
of UPI's international division. He was executive vice president
and editor in chief from 1984 to 1986, when he resigned in a
dispute with UPI's owners over administration of the financially
troubled agency.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes became an associate director of the American Press
Institute in Reston, Va., and retired in 1992 because of ill
health.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Morfydd, known as Nicky; a daughter,
Christine Dian of London; a brother; and a sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
