<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINPRECHT HELPING KINGS EARLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Steven Reinprecht was a finalist last
spring for the Hobey Baker Award, which is given to the top player
in college hockey. In his first NHL training camp, that gets him a
lot more hip checks than handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   What has gotten the attention of the Kings has been his work on
a line of Nelson Emerson and Jason Blake during the first five days
of camp. As a center on a team without its best center, Jozef
Stumpel, who is holding out in a contract dispute, that is a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a situation where a key player is missing, it is
critical to have the young guys perform right away,'' coach Andy
Murray said. ``You want the team to keep moving forward and don't
have time for a kid to make the transition from the college game.
Reinprecht has given us that.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray is particularly impressed with Reinprecht's speed and
instincts, but durability and consistency will be the ingredients
that help him make the team. Reinprecht will not replace Stumpel on
the first unit, but there is room in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, moving up another level, you have to push yourself
really hard,'' said Reinprecht, signed as a free agent last March
from the University of Wisconsin. ``They are bigger, stronger,
faster than in college. We worked hard there, but there wasn't as
much skating or weight training as here. I'll be in that weight
room a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinprecht, 24, did not reach the NHL in the conventional way.
He was scheduled to be drafted in 1996 but broke his right leg that
year. He wasn't drafted and played four years for Wisconsin before
coming to terms with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it worked out better for me this way,'' Reinprecht
said. ``Guys get drafted and often they aren't a good fit with
their new team. I had the chance to pick and choose where I wanted
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 26 goals and 66 points in 37 games for the Badgers
last year, Reinprecht played one game for the Kings. His real
education about the rigors ahead began with a two-month
conditioning camp here from late May to late July.
</P>
<P>
   In August, he and teammates Brad Chartrand, Joe Corvo and Joe
Rullier were sent to Prague in the Czech Republic to work out with
one of the top teams. For a kid who grew up in Edmonton watching
the great Oilers teams of Wayne Gretzky and Mark Messier, it was a
different experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of speed and skill over there was incredible,''
Reinprecht said. ``Petr Nedved and Jan Hlavat (New York Rangers)
were there. They were very quick with great puck movement. We got
to skate hard for a couple of weeks and now we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinprecht knows there are no guarantees. Last year, when
Mattias Norstrom missed all of camp in a holdout, Jaroslav Modry
stepped in and was arguably the Kings' best defenseman. But
Norstrom signed the day before the regular season began and Modry
rarely played again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my status is,'' Reinprecht said. ``All I can
do is keep working hard and see what happens.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
