<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COL-CUNNINGHAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDALL HAS HANDLE ON WHAT BACKUP SHOULD BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randall Cunningham has received as much praise this week for his
handling of the so-called quarterback controversy as he has for his
stellar play against the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 37, has gone to great lengths to explain that he
knows that he has no chance to supplant Troy Aikman, no matter how
well he plays. Furthermore, he understands and accepts the role he
agreed to when he joined the Cowboys last June.
</P>
<P>
   So he's being lauded for his selfless attitude, which he credits
to maturity and a spiritual rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been different during my egotistical days,''
Cunningham said. ``I've matured. And I've learned to humble myself
unto the Lord. If you humble yourself, you will be lifted up.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit also should go to the Golden Rule: Do unto others as you
would have them do unto you. Cunningham has been in Aikman's
position on more than one occasion during a 15-year career dotted
with a healthy share of high highs and low lows.
</P>
<P>
   Three times during his 11-year stay in Philadelphia, Cunningham
had former starters as primary backups. Jim McMahon, Rodney Peete
and Bubby Brister all came in knowing that Cunningham was the
starter, yet all openly pursued his job.
</P>
<P>
   And this was before Mr. Congeniality (Jeff George) went from
Cunningham's backup to his replacement in Minnesota last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said he learned a lot from those experiences. He said
divisiveness can tear up the team, while fostering an unhealthy
quarterback environment that prevents both starter and backup from
reaching their full potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of respect for Troy and what he's done in
the past,'' Cunningham said. ``We can work together. There have
been teams I've been on when the backup guy is a tough guy to deal
with. That's tough on the quarterbacks. You can't say the wrong
things at the wrong time. Whenever you are a starter, you've got to
have a good relationship with the guys around you. But it takes
time to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say the two quarterbacks just got a little closer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only Cunningham can take back that rub-it-in touchdown
pass he threw after faking a kneel-down in the waning moments of
the Eagles' 37-20 victory against the Cowboys in 1987. \Nsubheds:No
contest, right? All sides are right to roundly dismiss any hint of
a quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   This is Troy Aikman's team. And it should remain Aikman's team
until Aikman decides to walk away. With three Super Bowl titles
under his belt, he has earned that right.
</P>
<P>
   And while Aikman's long-term health _ considering his concussion
history _ may be better served with Cunningham starting, there's no
concrete evidence that the Cowboys would be better served with
Cunningham at quarterback. Until there is, Aikman haters, please
pipe down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to the blindly loyal Aikman backers who see a quarterback
controversy as a joke because they believe Cunningham is a far
inferior quarterback, their career numbers heading into the 2000
season suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Entering his 12th season, Aikman had a 90-64 record as a
starter. His quarterback rating was 82.6. He had thrown 158
touchdown passes and 127 interceptions. Aikman has been to the Pro
Bowl six times.
</P>
<P>
   Entering his 15th season, Cunningham had a 79-50-1 record as a
starter. His quarterback rating was 81.4. He had thrown 198
touchdown passes and 128 interceptions. Cunningham had four Pro
Bowl appearances and two league MVP awards.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's review: In 24 fewer starts, Cunningham had 11 fewer
victories and 14 fewer losses. He had thrown 40 more touchdown
passes and only one more interception. His quarterback rating is
just a shade off of the supposedly more accurate and consistent
Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's big edge is playoff results. He is 11-4 as a starter in
the postseason, including three Super Bowl titles. Cunningham is
3-6 with no Super Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are those who wonder how good Cunningham could
have been in the playoffs if former Eagles coach Buddy Ryan would
have put any emphasis on the offense or Minnesota Vikings coach
Denny Green would have cared something about defense in 1998.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
