<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-12 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1487 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MEHTA-MUSIC-$ADV17-AR     09-12 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEHTA-MUSIC-$ADV17-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONE THAT DIDN'T GET AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You and I will not be having this discussion after
Labor Day,'' Paul B. Guenther, the chairman of the New York
Philharmonic, bravely declared last April. ``Either that or you'll
be talking to my successor here.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Guenther was promising that the orchestra would have
named its next music director by now.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   But who's keeping track? Probably no one on the Philharmonic's
board; who would want to take over Guenther's position and its
problems just now?)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Guenther could hardly be blamed for feeling euphoric at the
time; he had cast two lures, and a big fish was nibbling at each.
In the end, the bigger one, Riccardo Muti, got away as music
director. But Guenther landed the other one: Zarin Mehta took over
as the orchestra's executive director just after Labor Day,
replacing Deborah Borda, who decamped last December for a similar
position with the Los Angeles Philharmonic. With the kinds of
difficulties American orchestras face today, Mehta may well prove
the more important catch.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, he is considered a star in the small world of
classical-music management. Guenther has said that every other
candidate interviewed for the position suggested that Mehta would
be the ideal choice if he were available but that the Philharmonic
would never get him. Mehta, who was the managing director of the
Montreal Symphony Orchestra from 1981 to 1991, when he became
executive director of the Ravinia Festival in Highland Park, Ill.,
the summer home of the Chicago Symphony, had just signed another
five-year contract with Ravinia when the Philharmonic came calling.
</P>
<P>
   Even before arriving in New York, Mehta took a hand in the
search for a new music director to replace Kurt Masur in 2002. In
addition, Mehta seems to have wasted little time in papering over
the Philharmonic's shattered relationship with Masur, who opens his
10th season on Wednesday at Avery Fisher Hall. Masur said in May
that he had no dates scheduled with the orchestra after the end of
his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to guest conduct,'' Zarin Mehta said on Sept. 5,
his first day on the job, looking instantly at home, sitting at a
conference table before an outsize bust of Mahler in his spacious
office at Avery Fisher Hall. ``He has three weeks already for the
2002-3 season. He and I go back many years, and I'm looking forward
to working on his last two seasons with us and making sure that
things are done properly for him. I'd like to do something special
in his final summer, 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the stalled search for Masur's successor, now more than
two years old, Mehta said that it would go forward as soon as the
orchestra returned from its vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the eggs were in one basket,'' he said of the Muti
courtship.
</P>
<P>
   Word of a short list of candidates leaked from the Philharmonic
last spring. Along with Muti, who broke off negotiations in July,
the list named two people Mehta would probably find congenial:
Mariss Jansons, the music director of the Pittsburgh Symphony and
the associate principal conductor of the St. Petersburg
Philharmonic in Russia, whose work Mehta is said to admire; and
Christoph Eschenbach, until recently the music director of the
Houston Symphony, whom Mehta hired to succeed James Levine as music
director at Ravinia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta is also said to have discussed the Philharmonic vacancy in
at least vague terms with Daniel Barenboim, the music director of
the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and of the Deutsche Staatsoper
Berlin. Mehta would not be drawn into a discussion of individual
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the `short list' of candidates people talk about,
and it has names that could not possibly be involved with the
Philharmonic for a variety of reasons,'' Mehta said. ``It wasn't a
short list so much as a wish list. So we have to be practical, and
you will find that I'm a very practical person.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the search is starting again from scratch. Mehta,
undaunted by failed predictions like Guenther's, said he hopes to
have a music director in place by the end of the year. Nor does
Guenther himself hesitate to crawl out on another limb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unreasonable to think that it could happen by the end
of the year,'' Guenther echoed last week, citing Mehta's very
presence and involvement as factors attractive to potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Time is of the essence for Mehta. ``Even if the new conductor is
not available for more than two weeks or six weeks or whatever in
2002-3, it is important that the person be named as music director
between now and then,'' he said. ``I have no pretension of being
music director. None at all. I'm a very opinionated person, but I
keep my opinions to myself. I want to work with somebody. I've
already started planning that season in terms of conductors,
general layout, when a tour can take place. But soon I have to jump
in with both feet.''
</P>
<P>
   To help develop a cohesive season with interesting programming,
Mehta is trying to hire fewer guest conductors than usual, for
periods longer than single weeks, a practice he would like to see
continue when a music director arrives. The conductors he mentions
for 2002-3 are unsurprising: Muti, Charles Dutoit and Sir Colin
Davis in addition to Masur. (It would hardly be surprising or amiss
if Zubin Mehta, Zarin's older brother, who was music director
before Masur, were represented as well, though Zarin Mehta seems to
go out of his way to avoid any appearance of favoritism.) Mehta is
also brainstorming with established maestros like Pierre Boulez,
Zubin Mehta's predecessor as music director of the Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his protestations of avoiding artistic interference,
Zarin Mehta makes it clear that he will take a stronger hand in
artistic administration than some of his peers, who delegate much
of the responsibility. Welz Kauffman, the orchestra's last artistic
administrator, followed Borda to Los Angeles in May and recently
replaced Mehta at Ravinia, starting that job the same day Mehta
began his. Mehta has just hired the less-experienced Jeremy Geffen
from the Aspen Music Festival as artistic administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be my right hand,'' Mehta said. ``But the only reason
I'm in this business is because I like music. The thought of not
being involved in the creation of what happens _ every cancellation
to me is a challenge. As I say, I've sat down and looked at 2002-3.
I have looked at the summers of 2001 and 2002, and Masur and I have
already talked about a couple of ideas. I don't want anyone else to
do that. If I was going to administer just anything, I would have
taken a commercial job somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehta began his working life in a commercial position, with the
accounting firm of Coopers &AMP; Lybrand in Montreal. Unlike Zubin
Mehta, Zarin never had aspirations as a performer, though he
developed a broad familiarity with music early. He was born in
Bombay in 1938, a son of Mehli Mehta, a violinist and conductor who
founded the Bombay Symphony in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's osmosis,'' Zarin Mehta said. ``No, actually, it's
more than that. We have four children, and they grew up in music
even before I went to the Montreal Symphony in 1981. My wife is a
singer. There was music in the house, because of teaching.
Musicians were always there. But none of my children had the same
interest in classical music that Zubin and I did from listening to
music on 78s in India.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehta is married to Carmen Lasky Mehta and the father of two of
her children, who are now in their 30s. The other two he calls his
own were Lasky's from a previous marriage, to Zubin Mehta
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bejun Mehta, who first made his name as a boy soprano and has
recently established himself in New York as a countertenor, is a
cousin of the Mehta brothers.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The business of music is something quite different,'' Zarin
Mehta said. ``That comes kind of naturally. My father ran his own
concerts and chamber concerts, so it became kind of a business, and
it was talked about at the dinner table. Zubin and I both went into
nonmusical directions for a time. At that stage there was never any
thought of our going into the profession, because in Bombay there
really wasn't a profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubin Mehta eventually went to Vienna to join a cousin who was
studying piano, and the rest is musical history. Zarin Mehta, still
in his teens, went to study accounting in London, where he attended
concerts often, usually in standing room. In 1962, he took up his
job in Canada with his lively interest in music in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Symphony's administration fell into disarray in the
1970s, when no suitable executive could be found (fluency in French
being the major hurdle). From his position on the board, Mehta
played a major role in the hiring of Dutoit as music director in
1976. Finally, with no end of the fruitless search for an executive
in sight, Mehta took over the management of the orchestra himself,
guiding it into an era of international acclaim that lasts to this
day.  &QL; 
MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   At Ravinia, he established a similar run of successes. In 1995,
the year Eschenbach took over as music director, the festival also
unveiled a $12 million renovation of its facilities. Mehta formed
the Ravinia Festival Orchestra and instituted programs in jazz and
contemporary music as well as opportunities for young performers.
To those who knew him, he seemed as content with his situation as
the board was with him, and it may never have occurred to either
party that the new five-year contract signed last fall would be a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was difficult,'' Mehta said of his premature
departure. ``They were extremely disappointed. They tried to talk
me out of it. At the same time, I think they realized that this was
an opportunity that was right for me. That's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   He professes to find New York irresistibly appealing; and hardly
less so, the sheer prospect of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something so different from what I've been doing, and
it's nice to have fresh air every so often. Without ever planning
it, it's just worked out that every 10 years I have a natural
change of direction. I certainly didn't plan this. And in the last
three months I've said: `Well why? I'm in a very comfortable
position in a lovely city. Why am I doing this?' But I think it's
to wake up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakeup calls are sure to come, not only in Mehta's dealings with
the Philharmonic players, though their reputation for
obstreperousness seems happily to have faded in recent years, but
also in his dealings with the unwieldy bureaucracy of Lincoln
Center. Extensive renovation lies ahead at Avery Fisher Hall as at
most of the other buildings in the center, and Mehta does not yet
know exactly what to expect or when it may happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'd like to see Avery Fisher Hall sound better,'' he
said. ``And look better.''
</P>
<P>
   Also problematic is the Lincoln Center Festival, in which the
Philharmonic has served honorably over five years to relatively
little reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the festival is extremely avant-garde,'' Mehta
said. ``But we're the only constituent group that's performing
regularly. I think it's wrong for the Philharmonic to play to
one-third houses. I like to think we have a certain self-respect,
and we shouldn't be doing that sort of thing.'' The Philharmonic
will not participate next year for other reasons, and any future
involvement, Mehta said, will hinge on programmatic interest, like,
perhaps, that Masur tribute in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta is clearly not a man to trifle with, a quality that should
serve him well in New York, at Lincoln Center and with the feisty
Philharmonic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-00 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
