<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PRACTICE-PLAYER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME DAY FOR COWBOYS' PRACTICE-SQUAD WIDE RECEIVER IS IN FRONT OF A
TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Damon Hodge isn't going to jump out of his chair
screaming and yelling. Well, maybe he will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe. If it comes down to the fourth quarter, and we need a
score to win,'' Hodge says.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter is a few hours away. While his teammates are
preparing to play the Arizona Cardinals on Sunday night, the
Cowboys practice-squad wide receiver prepares his spaghetti and
meat sauce at his apartment near Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   This is how he watches his team play a road game. Not on the
sidelines, but at home with a remote control by his side and a
glass of juice in his hand. He is an arm-chair receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's identical to being redshirted,'' Hodge says.
``It's tough. Injured guys have something to strive to get back to.
No matter what I do, it depends on what someone else does. Yeah, I
still get butterflies, but I don't get nervous like it's fear. I
want to get contact, so it will get it out of the way to get back
into rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Only he can't take a hit in his new bachelor pad, which is
furnished with a big couch, a big chair, a big bed, a Sony
PlayStation, a Sega Dreamcast and one of thoseJumboTron-size TVs
where you can smell Joe Theismann's cologne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how some of these commentators talk. They don't
know what they're talking about,'' Hodge says. ``They just talk. Of
course, Theismann knows what he's talking about. But Dennis
Miller?''
</P>
<P>
   With his left leg slung over the side of his big chair, Hodge
watches the Cardinals move down the field on their opening drive,
assisted by Cowboys cornerback Kareem Larrimore's 37-yard pass
interference penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, c'mon, Kareem,'' Hodge says. ``He \RLarrimore\S is
physical, but he's more of a speed guy. The toughest thing about
going against \Rthe Cowboys cornerbacks\S is aggression. They
gamble, but Kareem and Ryan \RMcNeil\S catch up more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodge sits with his arms at his side, never getting too up or
too down. This is part of his job as one of the team's five
practice-squad players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely wasn't a Cowboys fan growing up,'' says Hodge,
who lived the first 12 years of his life in the Bronx, N.Y. ``I was
a Giants fan. I still follow them a little bit, but I'm a Cowboy
now. I grew up hating the Cowboys and the Eagles, but I loved
Randall Cunningham and Troy Aikman.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyhood idol Cunningham is on the screen tearing up the
Cardinals. His 47-yard touchdown pass to James McKnight gives
Dallas a 14-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play is called `Speed Bomb,' '' Hodge says. ``Randall's
arm is a little different. Troy is more of a touch guy. He throws a
very catchable ball. Randall, his passes have more steam on them.
It's catchable, but you have to be ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a knock at the door. It's Cowboys practice-squad tight
end James Whalen. This apartment complex has become a
home-away-from home for some Cowboys. Punter Micah Knorr and kicker
Tim Seder live here, as do a few other players.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen makes himself at home, dishing out some spaghetti before
sitting down in front of the TV. Third-string quarterback Clint
Stoerner's face appears briefly on the screen. He has become one of
Hodge's closest friends, and a champion of the practice-squad
players after being elevated to the 53-player active roster last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see you Clint Stoerner!'' Whalen shouts. ``He's my boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The score ticker comes across the screen, showing the Giants'
33-18 victory against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whalen, man, the Eagles didn't look anything like they did
last week,'' Hodge says.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are beginning to look nothing as they did in last
week's 21-16 loss to the Giants. Arizona trails the Cowboys, 31-26,
in the fourth quarter when Cardinals receiver David Boston catches
a 63-yard pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran that play all week in practice,'' says Hodge, who runs
the opponent's offense in practice. ``I scored three touchdowns on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen seconds later, Frank Sanders catches a 17-yard touchdown
pass and Arizona takes a 32-31 lead. The Cowboys have 1:54
remaining to win. This should be the time for Hodge to scream and
shout like a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of time,'' Hodge says calmly. ``We'll come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys move to the Arizona 43 before four consecutive
incompletions send Dallas to 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hodge smacks his hands together. It's the loudest he has been
all game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to swallow a loss like this,'' Hodge says. ``We did
such a great job of establishing ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for a practice player who never boards the plane or puts on
the pads, screaming or yelling isn't necessary. Losing hurts either
way.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
