<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-RESTRICTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATHS AT NEW HAMPSHIRE TRACK FORCE NASCAR CHANGE, BUT IS IT THE
RIGHT ONE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Armed with an interim fix and intriguing new questions, the
NASCAR Winston Cup Series is loading up for a somber return to New
Hampshire International Speedway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty and Kenny Irwin Jr. were killed in separate crashes
during practice this season in Turn 3 of the 1.058-mile oval in
Loudon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Under fire from drivers to institute some sort of
energy-absorbing ``soft wall'' technology before Sunday's Dura Lube
300, NASCAR officials announced Saturday that Cup and NASCAR Busch
North Series cars will be required to compete with a one-inch
carburetor restrictor plate during practices, qualifying and the
races at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's decision is unprecedented, as it marks the first time
the horsepower-reducing plates will be used other than at the
2.5-mile Daytona International Speedway and the 2.66-mile Talladega
Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought with regards to the restrictor plate is obvious,''
said Mike Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief
operating officer. ``The track has not changed, but the cars are
faster; this will slow them down. That's \Rrestrictor plates\S a
common denominator that everyone in the garage area knows and
understands.''
</P>
<P>
   And some even loathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the same things about restrictor plates I've always
thought about restrictor plates. It's not racing,'' said seven-time
Cup champion Dale Earnhardt, driver of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench
Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I applaud NASCAR for doing something, but
they're doing this because everybody is hollering. They should be
hollering at every racetrack, not just one. I think it's the wrong
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-inch-by-5-inch plate fits between the V-8 engine's
four-barrel carburetor and intake manifold. The plate restricts the
amount of air that flows between those components, reducing the
amount of horsepower an engine can generate.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, Winston Cup Series director and a former series
crew chief, estimated the plate will cut horsepower output from 750
to approximately 490 or 500 at NHIS. Nelson also said NASCAR data
showed teams can expect a reduction of approximately 10 mph at top
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Although NASCAR has been unable to offer substantive proof, hung
throttles are believed to have carried both Petty, a regular in the
NASCAR Busch Grand National Series, and Irwin, a former Winston Cup
rookie of the year, into the concrete wall before they could react.
Petty, 19 and the first fourth-generation athlete in any sport, was
killed on May 12. Irwin, 30, was killed on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Benson, driver of the No. 10 Aaron's Pontiac Grand Prix,
said even with the use of computers, speeds this weekend will
remain open to conjecture until the first practice laps are turned
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we're not going to be taking a different line,'' said
Benson, referring to the preferred groove around the track. ``If
the throttle's stuck and you're doing 140 mph as opposed to 150
mph, you might be able to get around the corner a little bit
further, which may change the angle of impact. But we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield, who suffered a concussion Aug. 3 after a crash
during practice at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, does not see
the plate as a long-term solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``But NASCAR was under a lot of pressure to do something
quickly, something that would at least answer New Hampshire,'' said
Mayfield, driver of the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus. ``This
addresses the speed issue; how fast you go into these corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sit there saying, `Do something, do something,' and
then, after they do something, step back and say, `Hey, we didn't
mean ``that''.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis, NASCAR has
mandated use of a throttle-stop on all Cup cars and an ignition
``kill switch'' button on the steering wheel, within easy reach of
the driver. However, native Texan and current Cup points leader
Bobby Labonte did not have time to hit the switch on his steering
wheel during a crash in practice at Darlington Raceway on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace, who set the NHIS qualifying record at 132.089 mph
on July 7, said the plate will change driving styles around the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could look at it as what may resemble another first-time
race there,'' said Wallace, a four-time winner this season in the
No. 2 Miller Lite Ford. ``But say what they like and do what they
will, I personally would have still liked to have seen the
Styrofoam walls all the way around the place.''
</P>
<P>
   James Ince, Benson's crew chief, said that fortunately for Cup
teams, racing remains a ``reaction business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure of the aerodynamic package, spring and shock
package, the gearing ... everything down to tailpipes and
headers,'' Ince said. ``We're happy that NASCAR did do something,
but it will be a pretty busy weekend for all of us.''
nn
</P>
